window.BOOK6_COURSE=[
null,
{
 n:1,
 title:'Amino Acids and Protein Structure',
 subtitle:'The molecular vocabulary of biochemistry: twenty building blocks, four levels of architecture, and the physical logic that drives folding',
 tag:'Molecular Toolkit',
 foundational:'Every protein disease, every enzyme mechanism, every structural defect in medicine traces back to amino acid chemistry and protein folding logic. Master this chapter and every later chapter becomes readable.',
 buildsOn:'Orgo Ch 12-13, amino acids are amines; Gen Chem acid-base.',
 setsUp:'Ch 2, enzymes are folded proteins.',
 objectives:['Identify and classify all twenty standard amino acids by side chain chemistry, charge at physiological pH, and MCAT-high-yield properties','Apply Henderson-Hasselbalch reasoning to calculate net charge and isoelectric point of amino acids and small peptides','Explain the chemical basis for peptide bond planarity, the trans preference, and the restrictions shown on a Ramachandran plot','Describe the hydrogen-bonding geometry of the alpha helix and both forms of the beta sheet, and identify which residues disrupt each structure','Explain why hydrophobic collapse is the dominant thermodynamic driving force for tertiary folding and identify the other stabilizing interactions','Analyze quaternary structure cooperativity in hemoglobin, including the T/R state model, the Bohr effect, and the role of 2,3-BPG','Connect protein misfolding to clinical disease for sickle cell anemia, osteogenesis imperfecta, alpha-1 antitrypsin deficiency, prion diseases, and amyloidoses','Interpret SDS-PAGE, native PAGE, isoelectric focusing, and Western blot data in the context of protein separation and identification'],
 opener:'Everything a protein can do, catalyze a reaction, carry oxygen, transmit a signal, resist mechanical force, recognize a pathogen, emerges from a specific three-dimensional shape built from just twenty amino acid building blocks. That shape is not random: it is the thermodynamically most stable arrangement of a particular sequence of side chains in aqueous solution.\n\nTo understand protein function is to understand why that shape is stable, what chemical interactions maintain it, and how disrupting even a single residue can cascade into disease. This chapter builds the full molecular vocabulary from the ground up: the geometry and acid-base chemistry of individual amino acids, the rigid planarity of the peptide bond, the hydrogen-bond logic of secondary structure, the hydrophobic driving force for tertiary folding, and the cooperative elegance of quaternary assemblies.\n\nEvery protein disease you will encounter on the MCAT and Step 1, sickle cell anemia, osteogenesis imperfecta, alpha-1 antitrypsin deficiency, prion diseases, amyloidoses, is a story told at the level of amino acid chemistry. Learn the vocabulary here, and every later chapter becomes readable.',
 pinnedDisc:{t:'PRIMARY vs TERTIARY STRUCTURE',x:'Primary structure is the amino acid sequence (covalent peptide bonds, cannot be broken without denaturation of this level). Tertiary structure is the 3D fold stabilized by non-covalent interactions (mainly hydrophobic effect). A mutation that changes one amino acid changes primary structure; this can disrupt tertiary structure if that residue is in the hydrophobic core.'},
 sections:[{id:'1.1',num:'1.1',title:'1.1 The Twenty Amino Acids: Structure, Stereochemistry, and Classification',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Every standard amino acid shares the same backbone architecture. A central alpha-carbon (the C-alpha) carries four substituents: an amino group (-NH2, pKa approximately 9.0 to 10.5 in the free amino acid), a carboxyl group (-COOH, pKa approximately 1.8 to 2.4), a hydrogen atom, and the side chain (the R group). It is the R group alone that distinguishes one amino acid from the next, and it is the chemical identity of that R group that determines everything: the amino acid\'s charge at physiological pH, its role in catalysis, its capacity for post-translational modification, and its preference for hydrophobic or hydrophilic environments.'},{t:'p',x:'At physiological pH (approximately 7.4), the free amino acid exists as a zwitterion: the amino group is fully protonated (exists as -NH3+, because the pH is far below its pKa of ~9 to 10.5) and the carboxyl group is fully deprotonated (exists as -COO-, because the pH is far above its pKa of ~1.8 to 2.4). Both groups are ionized simultaneously, producing a molecule with no net charge from the backbone, but the side chain may add charge of its own depending on its pKa and the ambient pH.'},{t:'box',kind:'why',label:'WHY AMINO ACIDS EXIST AS ZWITTERIONS AT PHYSIOLOGICAL pH',x:'The pKa of the carboxyl group of a free amino acid is roughly 2.0 to 2.4. At pH 7.4, which is approximately 5 pH units above that pKa, the ratio of deprotonated to protonated carboxyl is 10^5 to 1: essentially complete deprotonation. The pKa of the backbone amino group is roughly 9.0 to 10.5, meaning that at pH 7.4 the ratio of protonated to deprotonated amino is 30:1 to 1000:1, essentially complete protonation. Both groups are therefore in their ionized forms simultaneously at physiological pH.'},{t:'p',x:'The alpha-carbon of every amino acid except glycine is a chiral center. All twenty proteinogenic amino acids are of the L-configuration. In the Cahn-Ingold-Prelog system, L-amino acids correspond to the S configuration for nineteen of the twenty standard amino acids. The single exception is cysteine, whose side chain contains a sulfur atom. Sulfur has a higher atomic number than the oxygen in the carboxyl group, which alters the priority ranking and makes L-cysteine formally an R configuration. L-cysteine is R: this is a CIP priority consequence, not a contradiction. Glycine has no chiral center because both substituents on the alpha-carbon beyond the backbone are hydrogen atoms.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'NONPOLAR ALIPHATIC AMINO ACIDS',x:'Seven members: glycine, alanine, valine, leucine, isoleucine, methionine, and proline. Side chains are primarily carbon and hydrogen, with no permanent dipole, driven into hydrophobic cores by the hydrophobic effect. Glycine (Gly, G): smallest, achiral, only amino acid in collagen triple helix interior. Alanine (Ala, A): methyl side chain, most common in alpha-helices statistically. Valine (Val, V), Leucine (Leu, L), Isoleucine (Ile, I): branched-chain amino acids (BCAAs), catabolized in muscle not liver, relevant in maple syrup urine disease. Methionine (Met, M): thioether linkage, universal eukaryotic initiator (AUG start codon), precursor to S-adenosylmethionine (SAM). Proline (Pro, P): imino acid, cyclic ring bonds to backbone nitrogen, breaks alpha-helices and beta-sheets, forces cis peptide bond, enriched in turns and collagen Gly-X-Y repeats.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'AROMATIC AMINO ACIDS',x:'Three members: phenylalanine, tyrosine, and tryptophan. Phenylalanine (Phe, F): unsubstituted benzyl ring, most hydrophobic aromatic, buried deep in protein cores, substrate for phenylalanine hydroxylase (PAH); PAH deficiency causes PKU. Tyrosine (Tyr, Y): hydroxyl group on benzyl ring, pKa approximately 10.5, phosphorylation site for receptor tyrosine kinases, precursor to dopamine, norepinephrine, epinephrine, thyroid hormones, and melanin. Tryptophan (Trp, W): largest standard amino acid, bicyclic indole ring system, only amino acid absorbing UV light strongly at 280 nm, precursor to serotonin, melatonin, and niacin.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'WHICH AMINO ACID ABSORBS AT 280 nm AND WHY',x:'Proteins absorb UV at 280 nm primarily because of tryptophan and, to a lesser extent, tyrosine. Tryptophan\'s indole ring has an extended pi-conjugated system with a large extinction coefficient at 280 nm (approximately 5,500 M-1 cm-1 per Trp residue). Tyrosine contributes roughly 1,490 M-1 cm-1 per residue. Phenylalanine has minimal absorption at 280 nm. On the MCAT, if asked why a pure protein is detected at A280, the answer is tryptophan (and tyrosine). Nucleic acids absorb maximally at 260 nm (nucleobases); the A260/A280 ratio near 1.8 indicates pure DNA, and a lower ratio suggests protein contamination.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'POLAR UNCHARGED AMINO ACIDS',x:'Five members: serine, threonine, cysteine, asparagine, and glutamine (methionine is sometimes included). Serine (Ser, S) and threonine (Thr, T): hydroxyl groups (-OH), primary sites of serine/threonine phosphorylation by PKA, PKC, CaMKII; serine is the active-site nucleophile in serine proteases (trypsin, chymotrypsin, elastase, thrombin, plasmin). Cysteine (Cys, C): thiol group (-SH), pKa approximately 8.3, soft nucleophile, forms disulfide bonds (-S-S-) in oxidizing environments (ER lumen, extracellular space); cytoplasmic proteins are generally reduced (maintained by glutathione). L-cysteine is R by CIP priority rules. Asparagine (Asn, N): amide side chain, N-linked glycosylation site (Asn-X-Ser/Thr motif, occurs in ER lumen). Glutamine (Gln, Q): amide side chain, nitrogen carrier between tissues, substrate for glutaminase.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'POSITIVELY CHARGED (BASIC) AMINO ACIDS AT PHYSIOLOGICAL pH',x:'Three members: lysine, arginine, and histidine. Lysine (Lys, K): epsilon-amino group, pKa approximately 10.5, essentially always +1 at pH 7.4; ubiquitination, acetylation, methylation, SUMOylation targets; collagen crosslinking substrate via lysyl oxidase. Arginine (Arg, R): guanidinium group, pKa approximately 12.5, strongest base among standard amino acids, resonance-delocalized positive charge across three nitrogens, essentially always +1 at pH 7.4; substrate for nitric oxide synthase. Histidine (His, H): imidazole side chain, pKa approximately 6.0, the ONLY ionizable side chain among the twenty standard amino acids that falls near physiological pH; approximately half-protonated and half-deprotonated at pH 7.4; found in enzyme active sites as a proton shuttle, in hemoglobin participating in the Bohr effect.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'NEGATIVELY CHARGED (ACIDIC) AMINO ACIDS AT PHYSIOLOGICAL pH',x:'Two members: aspartate and glutamate. Aspartate (Asp, D): beta-carboxyl side chain, pKa approximately 3.9, essentially fully deprotonated at pH 7.4 (net charge -1); participant in the urea cycle and malate-aspartate shuttle; active-site acid-base catalyst. Glutamate (Glu, E): gamma-carboxyl side chain, pKa approximately 4.1, essentially fully deprotonated at pH 7.4 (net charge -1); primary excitatory neurotransmitter; GABA precursor; glutamate dehydrogenase substrate.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'HIGH-YIELD AMINO ACID PROPERTIES',x:'Hydroxyl-containing side chains (Ser, Thr, Tyr) = phosphorylation sites for kinases. Thiol-containing side chain (Cys) = disulfide bond formation and nucleophilic catalysis. Imidazole (His, pKa ~6.0) = only side chain that buffers near physiological pH. Guanidinium (Arg, pKa ~12.5) = strongest base, essentially always positive at pH 7.4. Indole (Trp) = absorbs UV at 280 nm; precursor to serotonin, melatonin, niacin. Proline = imino acid, no backbone N-H, cyclic ring: breaks helices, forces turns, found in collagen. Glycine = smallest, achiral, only residue in collagen triple helix interior. Methionine = start codon (AUG) product; SAM precursor; thioether (NOT thiol, does NOT make disulfide bonds). Branched-chain AAs (Val, Leu, Ile) = catabolized in muscle not liver; relevant in MSUD.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'Which amino acid is the ONLY one that can occupy the interior of the collagen triple helix?',choices:['A) Alanine','B) Glycine','C) Proline','D) Valine'],answer:1,why:'Glycine has only a single hydrogen atom as its R group, making it the smallest amino acid. Every third position in the Gly-X-Y collagen repeat must be glycine because only glycine is small enough to fit in the sterically crowded interior of the triple helix. Any other residue at that position disrupts triple helix formation, as seen in osteogenesis imperfecta.'}]},{id:'1.2',num:'1.2',title:'1.2 Acid-Base Chemistry of Amino Acids',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Amino acids are polyprotic acids: they possess multiple ionizable groups, each with its own pKa, and the titration of an amino acid involves sequential loss of protons as pH increases. The Henderson-Hasselbalch equation, pH = pKa + log([A-]/[HA]), is the indispensable tool. [A-] is the concentration of the deprotonated form and [HA] is the concentration of the protonated form.'},{t:'p',x:'Consider glycine, the simplest amino acid. In strongly acidic solution (pH near 0 to 1), glycine exists fully protonated: +H3N-CH2-COOH (charge +1, the cationic form). As pH is raised through pKa1 = 2.34, the carboxyl group is progressively deprotonated. At exactly pH 2.34, half the molecules are in the +1 form and half in the zwitterion (+H3N-CH2-COO-, charge 0). Above pH 2.34, the zwitterion predominates. This zwitterion has net charge of zero at the isoelectric point (pI). As pH is raised further through pKa2 = 9.60, the amino group is progressively deprotonated. At exactly pH 9.60, half the molecules are in the zwitterion and half in the anionic form H2N-CH2-COO-. Above pH 9.60, the fully deprotonated anion (charge -1) predominates.'},{t:'p',x:'The isoelectric point (pI) of glycine is the pH at which it carries no net charge: pI = (pKa1 + pKa2) / 2 = (2.34 + 9.60) / 2 = 5.97. The logic: the pI is the midpoint between the two pKa values that flank the neutral (zwitterion) species. For basic amino acids (Lys, Arg, His), the neutral species is flanked by pKa2 (backbone amino) and pKa3 (side chain), so pI = (pKa2 + pKa3) / 2. For lysine: pI = (9.18 + 10.53) / 2 = approximately 9.9. For acidic amino acids (Asp, Glu), the neutral species is flanked by pKa1 (backbone carboxyl) and pKa2 (side chain carboxyl), so pI = (pKa1 + pKa2) / 2. For aspartate: pI = (2.09 + 3.86) / 2 = approximately 2.98.'},{t:'box',kind:'why',label:'WHY pI = AVERAGE OF THE TWO FLANKING pKa VALUES',x:'The isoelectric point is defined as the pH at which net charge is zero. At the pI, the concentrations of the +1 and -1 species must be exactly equal so that average charge is zero. By the Henderson-Hasselbalch equation, at the pI: pH - pKa1 = -(pH - pKa2), which rearranges to 2 x pH = pKa1 + pKa2, giving pH = (pKa1 + pKa2) / 2. For amino acids with three ionizable groups, the same principle applies: identify the two pKa values that bracket the neutral (uncharged) species, and average them.'},{t:'p',x:'Electrophoresis of amino acids exploits this charge logic directly. If the pH of the electrophoresis buffer is above the pI of an amino acid, the amino acid carries net negative charge and migrates toward the anode (positive electrode). If pH is below the pI, the amino acid is net positive and migrates toward the cathode (negative electrode). At pH equal to the pI, the amino acid does not migrate. Isoelectric focusing (IEF) establishes a stable pH gradient across a gel, allowing proteins to migrate until they reach the position where the gel pH equals their pI, at which point they stop moving because they carry no net charge.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'HISTIDINE AS THE PHYSIOLOGICAL BUFFER',x:'Of all ionizable amino acid side chains, only histidine\'s imidazole (pKa ~6.0) falls within physiologically relevant range. Histidine has been selected by evolution because its buffering capacity near neutral pH is uniquely valuable. In hemoglobin, histidine residues (particularly His146 of the beta chain) accept protons released by carbonic acid at the venous end (CO2 + H2O forms H2CO3, then H+ + HCO3-; H+ taken up by His) and release them in the lungs: this is the molecular mechanism of the Bohr effect. In enzyme active sites, histidine acts as a proton shuttle. When studying enzyme active sites, histidine as a proton shuttle is almost always the right answer.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'An amino acid has pKa values of 2.1 (alpha-carboxyl), 4.0 (side chain carboxyl), and 9.2 (alpha-amino). What is its approximate isoelectric point?',choices:['A) 3.05','B) 5.60','C) 6.60','D) 9.20'],answer:0,why:'This is an acidic amino acid (it has a side chain carboxyl). The neutral (uncharged) species is flanked by pKa1 (2.1, alpha-carboxyl) and pKa2 (4.0, side chain carboxyl). Therefore pI = (2.1 + 4.0) / 2 = 3.05. The pKa3 of 9.2 is not used in the pI calculation for an acidic amino acid because it does not flank the neutral species.'}]},{id:'1.3',num:'1.3',title:'1.3 Primary Structure: The Peptide Bond',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'The primary structure of a protein is the linear sequence of amino acids linked by peptide bonds. A peptide bond forms by a condensation reaction: the alpha-amino group of one amino acid reacts with the alpha-carboxyl group of another, expelling water and forming the amide linkage -CO-NH-. In the ribosome, this reaction is catalyzed by peptidyl transferase, which is the catalytic activity of the 23S rRNA (in prokaryotes) or 28S rRNA (in eukaryotes): an RNA enzyme, or ribozyme, not a protein enzyme. The convention is N-terminus at the left (free amino group) and C-terminus at the right (free carboxyl group). Synthesis on the ribosome proceeds N to C: new amino acids are added to the C-terminal end of the growing chain.'},{t:'p',x:'The most important physical property of the peptide bond is its partial double bond character. The nitrogen lone pair is delocalized into the adjacent carbonyl pi bond, creating a C-N bond with roughly 40% double bond character. This delocalization has two major structural consequences. First, the peptide bond is rigid and planar: the six atoms of the peptide unit (C-alpha, C=O, N, H, and the two flanking C-alpha atoms) all lie in the same plane because rotation around the partial C-N double bond requires overcoming a rotational barrier of approximately 20 kcal/mol. Second, the trans configuration (where the two C-alpha atoms are on opposite sides of the C-N bond) is enormously favored over cis because the cis configuration places the two large R groups and backbone atoms in steric clash. More than 99.9% of all peptide bonds in real proteins are trans. The one exception is the peptide bond preceding proline, where the cyclic ring reduces the steric penalty of cis sufficiently that approximately 5 to 6% of X-Pro bonds are cis.'},{t:'p',x:'Because the peptide bond is planar and rigid, the only backbone angles that can rotate are the phi angle (rotation around the N-C-alpha bond) and the psi angle (rotation around the C-alpha-C bond). The Ramachandran plot is a two-dimensional map of all possible (phi, psi) combinations for a given residue, identifying which combinations are sterically allowed and which are forbidden. The vast majority of (phi, psi) space is sterically forbidden; only a few clustered regions are allowed. The alpha-helix occupies phi approximately -57 degrees and psi approximately -47 degrees. The beta-sheet region occupies phi approximately -120 degrees and psi approximately +115 degrees. Glycine, lacking a beta-carbon, is allowed in all four quadrants of the Ramachandran plot. Proline is restricted to a small region and cannot adopt the psi angle required for a normal alpha helix.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'WHAT RESTRICTS BACKBONE FLEXIBILITY',x:'PEPTIDE BOND (omega angle): rigid and planar due to resonance delocalization; cannot rotate freely; essentially always trans (>99.9%); the C-N bond has ~40% double bond character. PHI ANGLE (N-C-alpha bond): can rotate, but restricted by steric clash between the carbonyl oxygen of the preceding residue and the R group of the current residue. PSI ANGLE (C-alpha-C bond): can rotate, but restricted by steric clash between the amino group of the following residue and the R group of the current residue. GLYCINE: phi and psi essentially unrestricted because the side chain is only H; can adopt left-handed helical conformations and unusual turns unavailable to other residues; appears as the only residue allowed in all four quadrants of the Ramachandran plot. PROLINE: phi is fixed at approximately -60 degrees by ring geometry; cannot donate N-H bond; breaks secondary structure; forces turns.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'Which bond in the peptide backbone is rigid and planar due to resonance delocalization?',choices:['A) The phi angle (N-C-alpha bond)','B) The psi angle (C-alpha-C bond)','C) The peptide bond (C-N amide bond)','D) The C-alpha to beta-carbon bond'],answer:2,why:'The peptide bond (the C-N amide bond) has approximately 40% double bond character because the nitrogen lone pair is delocalized into the adjacent carbonyl pi bond. This resonance delocalization creates a rotational barrier of approximately 20 kcal/mol, making the bond rigid and planar. The phi and psi angles can rotate (subject to steric restrictions), but the omega angle of the peptide bond cannot freely rotate.'}]},{id:'1.4',num:'1.4',title:'1.4 Secondary Structure: Local Folding Patterns',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Secondary structure refers to regular, repeating local folding patterns stabilized exclusively by hydrogen bonds between backbone carbonyl oxygen (C=O) and backbone amide nitrogen-hydrogen (N-H) groups. Side chains are NOT involved in secondary structure hydrogen bonds. This is a critical distinction for the MCAT: secondary structure is stabilized only by backbone hydrogen bonds; side chain chemistry drives tertiary and quaternary structure.'},{t:'p',x:'The alpha helix is the most common secondary structure in proteins. It is a right-handed helical coil with 3.6 residues per complete turn, a rise of 1.5 angstroms per residue along the helix axis, and a pitch (distance per turn) of 5.4 angstroms. The hallmark of the alpha helix is its intramolecular hydrogen bonding pattern: the backbone carbonyl oxygen of residue i donates a hydrogen bond to the backbone amide N-H of residue i+4. This means every backbone carbonyl and every backbone N-H is engaged in a hydrogen bond (except the four residues at each end of the helix), providing a powerful stabilizing force distributed uniformly along the helix. Side chains project outward from the helix axis.'},{t:'p',x:'Several residue types break or destabilize alpha helices. Proline lacks a backbone N-H for hydrogen bonding (the nitrogen is tertiary) and imposes a fixed phi angle of approximately -60 degrees that is incompatible with the ideal helical phi of -57 degrees; proline is found at helix-breaking positions and at the beginning of helix kinks in membrane proteins. Glycine is too flexible and does not lock the phi/psi angles needed for a stable helix. Clusters of residues with like charges at the same face of the helix destabilize it by electrostatic repulsion. Bulky beta-branched residues (Ile, Thr, Val) can destabilize helices when present in runs.'},{t:'p',x:'Amphipathic helices have one hydrophobic face and one hydrophilic face. Because an alpha helix repeats every 3.6 residues, placing hydrophobic residues at positions 1, 5, 8, 12 (every ~3.5 residues) generates a helix that presents all hydrophobic side chains on the same face. Such helices are common in membrane lipoproteins (the hydrophobic face inserts into the lipid bilayer), in coiled-coil proteins (the hydrophobic face forms the protein-protein interface), and in antimicrobial peptides (the hydrophobic face inserts into bacterial membranes).'},{t:'p',x:'Beta sheets form when two or more extended beta strands align side by side, forming hydrogen bonds between backbone carbonyls and amide groups of adjacent strands. Each residue in a beta strand contributes approximately 3.5 angstroms to the chain length, and side chains alternate above and below the plane of the sheet. Antiparallel beta sheets form when adjacent strands run in opposite N-to-C directions. In antiparallel sheets, the hydrogen bonds between strands are nearly perpendicular to the strand direction and are linear (the N-H group and the C=O group point directly at each other with a bond angle close to 180 degrees). Linear hydrogen bonds are stronger than bent ones, making antiparallel sheets more stable. Parallel beta sheets form when adjacent strands run in the same N-to-C direction; the H-bonds are angled and bent, resulting in slightly less stable sheets.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'ALPHA HELIX vs BETA SHEET HYDROGEN BONDING',x:'ALPHA HELIX: hydrogen bonds are within a single polypeptide chain; they run along the helix axis between the backbone C=O of residue i and the backbone N-H of residue i+4; every backbone group (except termini) participates; side chains are NOT involved; the helix is stabilized purely by intramolecular backbone-backbone H-bonds. BETA SHEET: hydrogen bonds are between backbone groups of separate strands (which may be far apart in the primary sequence or even from different chains); in antiparallel sheets the H-bonds are linear and strong; in parallel sheets they are bent and weaker; side chains alternate above and below the sheet plane and contribute to burial of hydrophobic patches but do NOT directly form the H-bond network. KEY DISTINCTION FOR THE MCAT: both secondary structures are stabilized ONLY by backbone hydrogen bonds, never side chain hydrogen bonds. Side chain chemistry drives tertiary and quaternary structure, not secondary structure.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'An alpha helix has hydrogen bonds between residue i and residue i+?',choices:['A) i+1','B) i+2','C) i+3','D) i+4'],answer:3,why:'The defining hydrogen bonding pattern of the alpha helix is between the backbone carbonyl oxygen of residue i and the backbone amide N-H of residue i+4. This i to i+4 pattern is a direct consequence of the helical geometry (3.6 residues per turn, phi approximately -57, psi approximately -47 degrees). Every backbone group except those at the very ends of the helix is engaged in such a hydrogen bond.'}]},{id:'1.5',num:'1.5',title:'1.5 Tertiary Structure: The Folded Domain',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Tertiary structure is the three-dimensional arrangement of all atoms in a single polypeptide chain, including the full three-dimensional path of the backbone and all side chain positions. It is at the tertiary level that the protein acquires its functional shape: the active site cleft of an enzyme, the oxygen-binding pocket of myoglobin, the antigen-binding surface of an antibody.'},{t:'p',x:'The dominant thermodynamic driving force for protein folding is the hydrophobic effect: the tendency of nonpolar groups to minimize their exposure to water. When a nonpolar residue is exposed to water, the surrounding water molecules must adopt ordered cage-like arrangements (clathrate structures) around the nonpolar surface, dramatically decreasing their conformational entropy. Burying nonpolar residues in the protein interior releases these constrained water molecules back into bulk solution, producing a large increase in solvent entropy (a favorable T*deltaS term). This entropy-driven burial of hydrophobic residues is the primary reason proteins fold; it is NOT primarily driven by the enthalpy of burying hydrophobic contacts (which is actually unfavorable on enthalpic grounds). The phrase "hydrophobic collapse" describes the rapid initial collapse of the unfolded chain driven by hydrophobic burial, which precedes the refinement of specific contacts.'},{t:'box',kind:'why',label:'WHY HYDROPHOBIC COLLAPSE IS ENTROPY-DRIVEN, NOT ENTHALPY-DRIVEN',x:'A common misconception is that hydrophobic residues cluster together because they "like" each other. The van der Waals interactions between two hydrocarbon chains are only marginally stronger than between a hydrocarbon chain and water, and the actual enthalpy change of bringing nonpolar groups together in water is near zero or even slightly unfavorable. The real driving force is the entropy of the surrounding water. When a nonpolar surface is exposed to water, the water molecules adjacent to that surface lose rotational and translational degrees of freedom as they adopt ordered arrangements to hydrogen-bond around the nonpolar group. When nonpolar groups cluster together, the total nonpolar surface area exposed to water decreases, releasing the previously ordered water back into bulk solution with a large gain in entropy (positive deltaS for the system). This favorable entropy gain, not any attraction between nonpolar groups themselves, is what drives hydrophobic collapse. The free energy is G = H - T*S, and for hydrophobic burial, deltaS (positive) dominates, making deltaG negative and folding spontaneous.'},{t:'p',x:'Once the hydrophobic core has collapsed, tertiary structure is further stabilized by several additional interactions. Disulfide bonds are covalent S-S crosslinks between two cysteine side chains; they require an oxidizing environment and contribute 20 to 40 kcal/mol of stability each. They are found in secreted proteins and extracellular domains, not in cytoplasmic proteins (cytosol is reducing due to glutathione). The disulfide bonds in immunoglobulins, insulin, and ribonuclease A are classic examples. Salt bridges are electrostatic attractions between oppositely charged side chains (Asp/Glu with Lys/Arg/His); they contribute less to stability than disulfide bonds but help define the spatial arrangement of charged patches on the protein surface. Hydrogen bonds between polar side chains and between polar residues and the backbone also contribute to tertiary stability, as do van der Waals contacts between closely packed atoms in the protein interior.'},{t:'p',x:'The classical experiment demonstrating that tertiary structure is encoded in the primary sequence is Anfinsen\'s ribonuclease A refolding experiment. When RNase A was fully denatured with urea and reduced with mercaptoethanol (breaking all four disulfide bonds), then the denaturant and reductant were removed by dialysis, the protein spontaneously refolded to its native state with full enzymatic activity and correct disulfide bonds. This demonstrated that all information necessary to specify the native tertiary structure is contained in the amino acid sequence: the thermodynamic hypothesis states that the native state is the thermodynamically most stable conformation of the polypeptide in physiological conditions, and folding to it is spontaneous.'},{t:'p',x:'Molecular chaperones are proteins that assist in vivo folding by preventing premature aggregation of newly synthesized or stress-denatured polypeptides. Hsp70 (BiP in the ER): binds exposed hydrophobic patches on nascent and partially folded proteins using an ATP-dependent cycle of binding and release, preventing aggregation while allowing productive folding. Hsp90: assists folding of specific client proteins including steroid hormone receptors and signaling kinases. GroEL-GroES (Hsp60-Hsp10 in bacteria, CCT/TRiC in eukaryotes): provides an enclosed chamber (the Anfinsen cage) where a polypeptide can fold in isolation away from other unfolded chains, using ATP cycling. Critical point: chaperones do NOT specify the final fold or add information to the folding process. They prevent misfolding and aggregation, but the final native state is determined entirely by the amino acid sequence.'},{t:'p',x:'Proteins are organized into domains, compact independently folding units typically 100 to 300 residues in length, connected by flexible linker segments. Structural motifs are supersecondary structure elements that appear repeatedly in different proteins. The helix-turn-helix motif (two alpha helices connected by a short turn) is found in many DNA-binding proteins. The zinc finger motif coordinates a zinc ion between cysteine and histidine residues, stabilizing a small domain that contacts DNA; it appears in hundreds of human transcription factors. The leucine zipper is a coiled-coil of two amphipathic helices from two protein chains, held together by hydrophobic interactions between leucine and other nonpolar residues spaced seven residues apart on each helix; leucine zippers mediate dimerization of transcription factors like c-Fos and c-Jun (AP-1 complex).'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'Protein folding is primarily driven thermodynamically by which of the following?',choices:['A) Favorable enthalpy of hydrophobic contacts between nonpolar residues','B) Gain in entropy of water molecules released from nonpolar surfaces','C) Formation of disulfide bonds between cysteine residues','D) Hydrogen bond formation between polar side chains'],answer:1,why:'The hydrophobic effect is the dominant driving force for tertiary folding, and it is entropy-driven, not enthalpy-driven. When nonpolar residues are buried in the protein core, water molecules that were previously ordered around those surfaces are released into bulk solution, gaining translational and rotational freedom. This large positive deltaS for water is the thermodynamic engine of hydrophobic collapse. The enthalpy of hydrophobic contacts is near zero or slightly unfavorable. Disulfide bonds and hydrogen bonds contribute to stability but are not the dominant driving force for the initial folding event.'}]},{id:'1.6',num:'1.6',title:'1.6 Quaternary Structure: Multi-subunit Assemblies',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Quaternary structure describes the arrangement of multiple polypeptide chains (subunits) into a functional multi-chain complex. Not all proteins have quaternary structure: monomers like myoglobin do not. Subunits in a quaternary complex are held together by the same noncovalent forces that stabilize tertiary structure: hydrophobic contacts at subunit interfaces, hydrogen bonds, and salt bridges. Disulfide bonds between subunits occur in some cases (immunoglobulin chains are linked by interchain disulfide bonds). A homodimer contains two identical subunits; a heterodimer contains two different subunits. Hemoglobin is a heterotetramer of two alpha chains and two beta chains (alpha2-beta2). Quaternary structure allows properties impossible for monomers: cooperativity, allostery, and communication between distant active sites.'},{t:'p',x:'Hemoglobin is the textbook example of cooperative ligand binding in a quaternary assembly. The oxygen-binding curve of hemoglobin is sigmoidal, in contrast to the hyperbolic curve of myoglobin. The sigmoidal shape indicates positive cooperativity: binding of the first oxygen molecule to one subunit makes subsequent oxygen binding to the other subunits easier. The Hill coefficient (n) for hemoglobin is approximately 2.8, reflecting strong cooperativity (n = 1 for non-cooperative binding; n approaching 4 for full cooperativity in a tetramer). The molecular mechanism of cooperativity is conformational: hemoglobin exists in two states, the T-state (tense, deoxy, low oxygen affinity) and the R-state (relaxed, oxy, high oxygen affinity). In the T-state, ion pairs (salt bridges) between subunits constrain the quaternary structure in a low-affinity conformation. When one subunit binds oxygen, the porphyrin ring and iron move slightly, pulling a histidine residue (the proximal His) toward the iron, which shifts the position of the helix F, disrupting T-state salt bridges and triggering a global quaternary conformational change toward the R-state.'},{t:'p',x:'The P50 is the partial pressure of oxygen at which hemoglobin is 50% saturated. The normal P50 of hemoglobin is approximately 26 to 27 mmHg; myoglobin\'s P50 is approximately 1 to 2 mmHg. The low P50 of myoglobin means that it is already nearly fully saturated at the oxygen pressures found in resting muscle (20 to 40 mmHg), making it an efficient intracellular oxygen store rather than a transporter. Hemoglobin\'s higher P50 allows it to deliver oxygen to tissues: it is approximately 97% saturated at the high PO2 of the lungs (~100 mmHg) and falls to about 75% saturated at the intermediate PO2 of resting venous blood (~40 mmHg), releasing 20 to 25% of its oxygen load per passage through the systemic circulation. In exercising muscle (PO2 as low as 20 mmHg), hemoglobin releases even more oxygen.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'MYOGLOBIN vs HEMOGLOBIN',x:'MYOGLOBIN: monomer (single polypeptide chain); no quaternary structure; no cooperativity; hyperbolic oxygen binding curve; Hill coefficient n = 1; P50 approximately 1 to 2 mmHg; located in muscle; RECEIVES oxygen from hemoglobin; stores oxygen for mitochondrial use; acts as oxygen buffer during muscle activity. HEMOGLOBIN: tetramer (alpha2-beta2); quaternary structure essential; positive cooperativity; sigmoidal oxygen binding curve; Hill coefficient n approximately 2.8; P50 approximately 26 to 27 mmHg; located in red blood cells; DELIVERS oxygen from lungs to tissues; allosteric regulation by 2,3-BPG, CO2, H+. The key MCAT trap: students confuse which protein has the higher P50 and which RECEIVES oxygen. Myoglobin has the LOWER P50 (higher affinity), which is WHY it can accept oxygen from hemoglobin at the oxygen pressures found in muscle tissue.'},{t:'p',x:'Allosteric effectors modulate hemoglobin\'s oxygen affinity by stabilizing either the T-state or the R-state. 2,3-Bisphosphoglycerate (2,3-BPG) is produced by red blood cells from 1,3-BPG (a glycolytic intermediate, shunted through the Rapoport-Luebering shunt). 2,3-BPG binds in a central cavity of deoxyhemoglobin (T-state) between the two beta chains, forming ionic interactions with positively charged residues (Lys, His, Arg, Val1 N-terminus of each beta chain). By preferentially binding the T-state, 2,3-BPG shifts the equilibrium away from the R-state, decreasing oxygen affinity and right-shifting the oxygen binding curve. At high altitude, red blood cells increase 2,3-BPG synthesis, partially compensating for the reduced driving force for oxygen loading in the lungs. Fetal hemoglobin (HbF, alpha2-gamma2) has gamma chains that interact less strongly with 2,3-BPG than adult beta chains, resulting in higher oxygen affinity of HbF, essential for the fetus to extract oxygen from maternal hemoglobin across the placenta.'},{t:'p',x:'The Bohr effect describes the decrease in hemoglobin oxygen affinity with increasing CO2 and decreasing pH. At metabolically active tissues, CO2 is produced and H+ is generated (from CO2 + H2O forming H2CO3, then H+ + HCO3-). These H+ ions protonate specific histidine residues in hemoglobin (particularly His146 of the beta chain), stabilizing salt bridges that hold hemoglobin in the T-state and thereby reducing oxygen affinity. The result: hemoglobin releases more oxygen precisely at tissues with high metabolic activity. CO2 also binds directly to the N-terminal amino groups of hemoglobin chains (forming carbaminohemoglobin), further stabilizing the T-state and facilitating CO2 transport back to the lungs.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'CARBON MONOXIDE POISONING AND THE LEFT SHIFT',x:'Carbon monoxide (CO) binds hemoglobin at the iron center of the heme group with an affinity approximately 250 times greater than oxygen. CO-bound hemoglobin (carboxyhemoglobin, HbCO) not only removes those subunits from oxygen transport but also shifts the oxygen binding curve of the remaining unoccupied subunits to the left, increasing their affinity for oxygen and making them less willing to release oxygen in the tissues. This is why CO poisoning causes cellular hypoxia even when the patient has a normal or high arterial PO2: hemoglobin cannot release what little oxygen it carries. Treatment is 100% oxygen (to outcompete CO by mass action) or hyperbaric oxygen. The pulse oximeter falsely reads HbCO as HbO2 (both have similar absorbance at the wavelengths used), so a normal SpO2 does NOT rule out CO poisoning: arterial co-oximetry or directly measured carboxyhemoglobin is required.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'2,3-BPG decreases hemoglobin\'s oxygen affinity by which mechanism?',choices:['A) Binding the R-state to stabilize it and prevent oxygen release','B) Binding the T-state to stabilize the low-affinity conformation','C) Directly blocking the oxygen-binding iron center of heme','D) Protonating histidine residues to destabilize the T-state'],answer:1,why:'2,3-BPG binds in the central cavity of deoxyhemoglobin, which is the T-state (tense, low-affinity conformation). By forming ionic interactions with positively charged residues (Lys, His, Arg, Val1 N-terminus) on the two beta chains, 2,3-BPG preferentially stabilizes the T-state. This shifts the T-R equilibrium away from the R-state (high affinity), decreasing oxygen affinity and right-shifting the oxygen-binding curve (higher P50, more oxygen released to tissues).'}]},{id:'1.7',num:'1.7',title:'1.7 Protein Denaturation and Stability',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Denaturation is the disruption of the native three-dimensional structure of a protein while leaving the primary covalent structure (the peptide bonds and sequence) intact. Denaturation abolishes biological activity because enzymatic activity, binding specificity, and structural function all depend on specific three-dimensional geometry. Denaturation may be reversible (if the sequence thermodynamically specifies the native fold and the conditions are returned to native-like conditions) or irreversible (if the protein aggregates, undergoes hydrolysis, or forms incorrect crosslinks during renaturation). Boiling an egg is an irreversible denaturation: the egg white albumin denatures and aggregates rapidly, forming a stable amorphous solid that will not refold.'},{t:'p',x:'The major denaturing agents and their mechanisms: Heat increases the amplitude of molecular vibrations, breaking hydrogen bonds and, counterintuitively at high temperatures, actually weakening the hydrophobic effect because the entropic penalty of ordering water around nonpolar groups is less pronounced at very high temperatures. The melting temperature (Tm) is the temperature at the midpoint of the thermal denaturation transition, where half the protein is folded and half is unfolded. Urea and guanidinium chloride are chaotropic agents that disrupt both hydrogen bonds and the hydrophobic effect by competing for hydrogen bond donors and acceptors and by altering water structure. They are used in the laboratory to completely unfold proteins at concentrations of 6 to 8 M. Detergents such as sodium dodecyl sulfate (SDS) are amphipathic molecules that coat protein surfaces, disrupting tertiary and quaternary structure by replacing protein-protein hydrophobic contacts with protein-detergent contacts; SDS gives each protein chain a uniform negative charge proportional to its length. Reducing agents such as dithiothreitol (DTT) and beta-mercaptoethanol break disulfide bonds by reducing the S-S bond back to two free thiols; they are essential when using SDS-PAGE to fully denature disulfide-bonded proteins.'},{t:'p',x:'Protein misfolding leads to accumulation of proteins with exposed hydrophobic patches that would normally be buried in the native core. These patches can mediate intermolecular hydrophobic contacts, causing molecules to associate and aggregate. Amyloid fibrils are ordered beta-sheet aggregates formed when misfolded proteins template the misfolding of additional molecules, recruiting them into cross-beta-sheet structures that grow into long insoluble fibers. The cross-beta architecture (beta strands running perpendicular to the fibril axis with the hydrogen bond direction parallel to the fibril axis) is characteristic of amyloid and can be detected by Congo red staining (apple-green birefringence under polarized light) or thioflavin T fluorescence. Amyloid diseases include Alzheimer disease (amyloid-beta peptide from proteolytic cleavage of APP), Parkinson disease (alpha-synuclein in Lewy bodies), Type 2 diabetes (IAPP/amylin in islet cells), and systemic amyloidoses (AL amyloidosis from immunoglobulin light chains, AA amyloidosis from serum amyloid A in chronic inflammation, transthyretin amyloidosis in the heart and nerves).'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'HIGH-YIELD DENATURATION FACTS',x:'Denaturation disrupts secondary/tertiary/quaternary structure; PRIMARY structure (peptide bonds) remains intact. Heat, urea, guanidinium, SDS = denaturing agents; reducing agents (DTT, beta-ME) specifically break disulfide bonds. Anfinsen experiment: primary sequence alone encodes the native fold (thermodynamic hypothesis). Chaperones (Hsp70, GroEL) prevent aggregation but do NOT encode or specify the final fold. Amyloid = ordered cross-beta sheet aggregates; Congo red staining with apple-green birefringence under polarized light. Alzheimer: A-beta plaques (beta/gamma secretase cleavage of APP) + tau tangles; Parkinson: alpha-synuclein Lewy bodies. Prion diseases: PrPsc is beta-sheet rich, proteinase K resistant, insoluble, and templates conversion of PrPc.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'SDS-PAGE separates proteins primarily by which property?',choices:['A) Isoelectric point (pI)','B) Native charge and shape','C) Molecular weight','D) Number of disulfide bonds'],answer:2,why:'SDS (sodium dodecyl sulfate) is an anionic detergent that coats protein surfaces and gives each polypeptide chain a uniform negative charge proportional to its length (and thus proportional to its molecular weight). Because all proteins receive the same charge-to-mass ratio from SDS, migration through the polyacrylamide gel depends only on molecular weight: smaller proteins migrate farther toward the anode. This is why SDS-PAGE is used to determine the number and sizes of polypeptide chains. Native PAGE separates by charge and shape, not purely by molecular weight.'}]},{id:'1.8',num:'1.8',title:'1.8 Special Topics: Collagen, Fibrous Proteins, and Prions',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Collagen is not a single protein but a family of more than 28 related fibrous proteins, of which type I (found in bone, skin, tendons, and most connective tissue), type II (cartilage), type III (reticulin fibers, blood vessels), type IV (basement membranes), and type VII (anchoring fibrils at epithelial basement membranes) are most clinically relevant. All collagens share a characteristic structural motif: the triple helix, formed by three left-handed polyproline II-type helices coiling around each other in a right-handed superhelix. The triple helix is stabilized by interchain hydrogen bonds between the backbone N-H of glycine in one chain and the backbone C=O of the X-position residue in an adjacent chain.'},{t:'p',x:'The repeating sequence of collagen is (Gly-X-Y)n, where X is frequently proline and Y is frequently 4-hydroxyproline. Every third residue must be glycine because glycine is the only amino acid small enough to fit in the interior of the triple helix. The X-position proline and Y-position hydroxyproline adopt constrained conformations (polyproline II geometry) that pre-organize each chain for triple helix formation. 4-Hydroxyproline is produced post-translationally by prolyl-4-hydroxylase, which requires molecular oxygen, alpha-ketoglutarate, iron (Fe2+), and ascorbate (vitamin C) as cofactors. 5-Hydroxylysine is produced by lysyl hydroxylase with the same cofactor requirements. The hydroxyl groups of hydroxyproline and hydroxylysine make critical intrachain and interchain hydrogen bonds that stabilize the triple helix and serve as sites for O-linked glycosylation.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'SCURVY AND COLLAGEN INSTABILITY',x:'Vitamin C (ascorbate) is an essential cofactor for prolyl-4-hydroxylase and lysyl hydroxylase. When vitamin C is deficient (as in sailors on long voyages without fresh fruit, or today in alcoholics and elderly individuals with poor diets), these enzymes cannot complete their reaction cycle. Without 4-hydroxyproline, newly synthesized procollagen chains cannot form stable triple helices (Tm drops below body temperature), and the unstable collagen misfolds and is degraded in the ER. The consequences are systemic connective tissue failure: bleeding gums, perifollicular hemorrhage (bleeding around hair follicles, a classic exam finding), poor wound healing, corkscrew hairs, and in severe cases, internal bleeding and death. The biochemical basis is elegant: ascorbate is consumed (oxidized) in each catalytic cycle of the hydroxylases, and without ascorbate, the iron in the active site becomes oxidized to Fe3+ and the enzyme is inactivated. Ascorbate regenerates the active Fe2+ form.'},{t:'p',x:'Disease relevance of collagen: Osteogenesis imperfecta (brittle bone disease) is caused by mutations in type I collagen genes (COL1A1 or COL1A2) that substitute the critical glycine residue with a larger amino acid. Because every third position must be glycine, even a single Gly to Ala or Gly to Cys substitution disrupts triple helix formation at that site and propagates a structural defect down the entire triple helix from C-terminus to N-terminus (the zipper model). Osteogenesis imperfecta follows autosomal dominant inheritance because the mutant alpha chain acts as a dominant negative: it is incorporated into triple helices along with normal chains, poisoning 75% of all assembled triple helices in a heterozygous individual (three chains per helix; at least one mutant chain in 3 out of 4 helices if the mutant is incorporated randomly). Ehlers-Danlos syndrome is a heterogeneous group of connective tissue disorders; the most common forms result from defective collagen crosslinking (lysyl hydroxylase deficiency, procollagen peptidase deficiency, or mutations in collagen fibril assembly cofactors), producing hyperelastic skin, hypermobile joints, and vascular fragility.'},{t:'p',x:'Prions are the most conceptually unusual infectious agents in medicine: they are proteins that propagate without any nucleic acid genome. The prion protein (PrP) is a GPI-anchored cell surface glycoprotein of normal function in neurons, encoded by the PRNP gene on chromosome 20. The cellular form, PrPc (c for cellular), is predominantly alpha-helical in secondary structure, soluble, proteinase K-sensitive, and non-infectious. The disease-associated form, PrPsc (sc for scrapie), has the same primary amino acid sequence as PrPc but adopts a dramatically different conformation: predominantly beta-sheet-rich, insoluble, proteinase K-resistant (a key diagnostic feature), and infectious. PrPsc propagates by acting as a template that catalyzes the conformational conversion of PrPc molecules to the PrPsc form: a protein misfolding chain reaction. Because no nucleic acid is required, prion diseases are uniquely resistant to all standard decontamination procedures that destroy nucleic acid-based pathogens; PrPsc survives autoclaving and is resistant to UV irradiation, formalin fixation, and most disinfectants.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'PRION vs TYPICAL INFECTIOUS AGENT',x:'TYPICAL INFECTIOUS AGENT (virus, bacterium, fungus, parasite): requires nucleic acid (DNA or RNA) to encode its own proteins; can be killed by methods that destroy nucleic acids (UV irradiation, nucleases, heat that hydrolyzes nucleic acids); treatment with standard autoclaving (121 C, 15 psi, 20 min) inactivates conventional pathogens. PRION: protein only, NO nucleic acid; identical primary sequence to the normal host protein (PrPc and PrPsc are the same gene product); the infectious agent IS the misfolded protein conformation; cannot be inactivated by UV, standard autoclaving, or most disinfectants; inactivated by extended autoclaving (134 C for 18 min) or NaOH treatment; the prion protein uses the host\'s own translation machinery to produce more PrP substrate, which is then converted by the existing PrPsc; disease progression is driven by protein misfolding and aggregation, not by replication in the microbiological sense.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'Osteogenesis imperfecta is most commonly caused by which molecular mechanism?',choices:['A) Deficiency of vitamin C leading to impaired collagen hydroxylation','B) Substitution of a mandatory glycine in the Gly-X-Y collagen triplet by a larger amino acid','C) Defective lysyl oxidase preventing collagen crosslinking','D) Loss-of-function mutation in both COL1A1 alleles (autosomal recessive)'],answer:1,why:'Osteogenesis imperfecta is caused by glycine substitutions in the Gly-X-Y collagen repeating unit of type I collagen. Every third position must be glycine because it is the only amino acid small enough to fit in the interior of the triple helix. A substitution at a glycine position disrupts triple helix formation at that site and propagates a structural defect from C-terminus to N-terminus (the zipper model). The disease is autosomal dominant because the mutant chain acts as a dominant negative, poisoning 75% of assembled triple helices in a heterozygous individual.'}]},{id:'1.9',num:'1.9',title:'1.9 Protein Identification, Sequencing, and Proteomics',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Edman degradation is the classic method for determining the N-terminal sequence of a protein one residue at a time. The reagent phenyl isothiocyanate (PITC) reacts with the free alpha-amino group of the N-terminal residue under mildly alkaline conditions, forming a phenylthiocarbamoyl (PTC) derivative. Treatment with anhydrous acid then cleaves the N-terminal PTC-amino acid as a thiazolinone derivative without hydrolyzing the rest of the peptide chain. The thiazolinone is converted to the stable phenylthiohydantoin (PTH) derivative and identified by chromatography. Automated Edman sequencers can determine sequences of up to approximately 50 residues; longer proteins must be chemically or enzymatically fragmented first.'},{t:'p',x:'Mass spectrometry (MS) has largely superseded Edman degradation for protein identification in proteomics. In a typical workflow, a protein mixture is digested with trypsin, which cleaves peptide bonds on the C-terminal side of lysine and arginine residues (trypsin\'s active site has an Asp residue at the bottom of the binding pocket that specifically coordinates the positive charges of Lys and Arg side chains). The resulting tryptic peptides are separated by liquid chromatography and analyzed by electrospray ionization tandem mass spectrometry (LC-ESI-MS/MS). The first MS stage measures the mass-to-charge ratio (m/z) of intact peptide ions; the second MS stage fragments selected peptide ions along the backbone (generating b-ions and y-ions) and records the fragment masses, allowing the amino acid sequence to be read from the mass differences between adjacent fragments.'},{t:'p',x:'Protein electrophoresis separates proteins by exploiting differences in charge, size, or both. SDS-PAGE (sodium dodecyl sulfate polyacrylamide gel electrophoresis) first denatures and unfolds all proteins with SDS and heat, coating them with a uniform negative charge proportional to their length. Reducing agent (DTT or beta-mercaptoethanol) breaks disulfide bonds to fully dissociate multi-subunit proteins into individual chains. Migration through the polyacrylamide gel then depends only on molecular weight. Native PAGE (non-denaturing PAGE) separates proteins in their native, folded state by a combination of charge and shape; the results cannot be interpreted as pure molecular weight separations. Isoelectric focusing (IEF) separates proteins by isoelectric point. Two-dimensional PAGE (2-DE) combines IEF (first dimension, separation by pI) with SDS-PAGE (second dimension, separation by molecular weight), allowing the simultaneous visualization and comparison of thousands of proteins from a cell lysate.'},{t:'p',x:'Western blotting (immunoblotting) couples the size separation of SDS-PAGE with highly specific antibody-based detection. After SDS-PAGE, proteins are transferred (electroblotted) from the gel to a nitrocellulose or PVDF membrane. The membrane is blocked with BSA or non-fat milk to prevent non-specific antibody binding, then incubated with a primary antibody specific to the protein of interest. A secondary antibody (anti-species IgG conjugated to horseradish peroxidase or alkaline phosphatase) binds the primary antibody and generates a detectable signal (chemiluminescence, colorimetric, or fluorescent). Western blotting is used in HIV diagnosis (as a confirmatory test after a positive ELISA), in identifying protein expression levels in research, and in diagnosing Lyme disease (confirmatory Western blot after ELISA).'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'READING GEL RESULTS IN CLINICAL DIAGNOSTICS',x:'SDS-PAGE of a patient serum sample showing an additional band at an unexpected molecular weight suggests the presence of an abnormal protein: an M-spike on serum protein electrophoresis points toward a monoclonal gammopathy (multiple myeloma, MGUS, Waldenstrom macroglobulinemia). Isoelectric focusing of hemoglobin lysates distinguishes hemoglobin variants by their pI: HbA (normal), HbS (sickle, pI shifted because Val replaces the acidic Glu), HbC (pI shifted further because Lys replaces Glu), and HbF (fetal) all migrate to distinct positions. Western blotting for HIV: a positive HIV ELISA (high sensitivity screening) is confirmed by Western blot, where the patient antibodies are tested against a membrane containing HIV proteins separated by SDS-PAGE; positivity requires bands at specific HIV protein positions (gp120, gp41, p24).'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'On SDS-PAGE with a reducing agent, a disulfide-bonded dimer protein will appear as:',choices:['A) A single band at twice the monomer molecular weight','B) Two separate bands, each at the monomer molecular weight','C) No band, because SDS denatures all proteins completely','D) A broad smear, because the disulfide bonds cause heterogeneous migration'],answer:1,why:'SDS-PAGE with a reducing agent (DTT or beta-mercaptoethanol) both denatures the protein with SDS and breaks all disulfide bonds with the reducing agent. The disulfide bond holding the dimer together is cleaved, so the two polypeptide chains separate. Each chain runs as an individual SDS-coated polypeptide, migrating based on its molecular weight alone. If both subunits are identical monomers, a single band at the monomer molecular weight is seen. In native PAGE (without SDS or reducing agent), the intact dimer would migrate as a single species with a position determined by both its charge and its hydrodynamic radius.'}]},{id:'1.10',num:'1.10',title:'1.10 Step 1 Clinical Correlations: Diseases of Protein Structure',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'The following clinical diseases are understood through the mechanism: what amino acid or protein is affected, what the structural defect is, and how the biochemical defect produces the clinical phenotype. Memorizing the presentation without the mechanism is insufficient for Step 1, which requires you to reason from mechanism to presentation or from presentation back to mechanism.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'SICKLE CELL ANEMIA: THE SINGLE AMINO ACID MODEL',x:'Sickle cell anemia (HbSS) results from a single nucleotide change in the HBB gene: codon 6 changes from GAG (Glu) to GTG (Val). Glutamate (Glu6) is negatively charged at physiological pH; valine (Val6) is hydrophobic and nonpolar. In the deoxy state, Val6 on the beta-globin surface fits into a hydrophobic pocket on an adjacent beta-globin subunit, forming a hydrophobic contact that drives polymerization of HbS molecules into long rigid fibers. These fibers distort red blood cells into sickle shapes, obstruct capillaries, destroy cells, and produce the recognized clinical syndrome: vaso-occlusive pain crises, dactylitis, splenic sequestration, autosplenectomy (Howell-Jolly bodies), hemolytic anemia, stroke, acute chest syndrome. Hemoglobin electrophoresis shows HbS band (pI shifted because neutral Val replaces acidic Glu). The fibers dissolve on reoxygenation (reversible), but repeated sickling damages the membrane (irreversible). HbC disease (Glu6Lys): Lys6 is positively charged; HbC forms crystals (not fibers) in RBCs; milder polymerization than HbS.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'PHENYLKETONURIA (PKU): AMINO ACID ACCUMULATION',x:'PKU results from loss-of-function mutations in phenylalanine hydroxylase (PAH), the enzyme that converts phenylalanine (Phe) to tyrosine (Tyr) using the cofactor tetrahydrobiopterin (BH4). When PAH is deficient, Phe cannot be converted to Tyr; Phe accumulates to high levels. High Phe competes with other large neutral amino acids (Trp, Tyr, Met, Leu) for transport across the blood-brain barrier via the LAT1 transporter, depleting the brain of these amino acids and their neurotransmitter products (serotonin, dopamine). Untreated PKU causes intellectual disability, musty body odor from phenylacetate, fair skin and hair (from reduced melanin production, which requires Tyr), and eczema. Screened on newborn screening (Guthrie test or tandem MS). Treated with Phe-restricted diet and/or sapropterin (BH4 supplementation for BH4-responsive variants).'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'ALPHA-1 ANTITRYPSIN DEFICIENCY: PROTEIN MISFOLDING AND RETENTION',x:'Alpha-1 antitrypsin (A1AT) is a serine protease inhibitor (serpin) synthesized by hepatocytes and secreted into the blood to inhibit neutrophil elastase in the lung. The most common pathogenic variant is the Z mutation (Glu342Lys). The Z-A1AT protein misfolds in the hepatocyte ER and polymerizes into chains that are retained as PAS-positive, diastase-resistant inclusion bodies in hepatocytes. The retained protein is toxic to hepatocytes (gain-of-toxic-aggregation), causing cirrhosis and hepatocellular carcinoma. The absence of secreted A1AT in the lung means neutrophil elastase (released during pulmonary inflammation) is uninhibited and destroys alveolar walls, causing panacinar emphysema with basal predominance (especially severe in smokers). TWO ORGANS: liver (gain-of-toxic-aggregation) and lung (loss of antiprotease). Serum A1AT levels are low. The key discriminator from cystic fibrosis: A1AT primarily causes emphysema + liver disease; CF primarily causes obstructive lung disease + exocrine pancreatic insufficiency.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'Why does sickle cell anemia result from a Glu to Val substitution at position 6 of beta-globin, rather than the reverse (Val to Glu)?',choices:['A) Valine is positively charged, creating electrostatic repulsion at the molecular surface','B) Valine is hydrophobic and fits into a complementary hydrophobic pocket on an adjacent deoxy-HbS molecule, driving polymerization','C) Glutamate forms covalent crosslinks between beta-globin subunits','D) Valine prevents oxygen binding to the adjacent heme iron'],answer:1,why:'The Glu6Val substitution replaces a charged, hydrophilic residue with a hydrophobic, nonpolar residue on the beta-globin surface. In the deoxy conformation, Val6 fits precisely into a hydrophobic pocket on an adjacent deoxy-HbS molecule. This intermolecular hydrophobic contact drives polymerization of HbS into long rigid fibers. The fibers form only when hemoglobin is deoxygenated (the hydrophobic pocket is not accessible in the oxy R-state), which is why sickling occurs at low oxygen tensions. Glutamate at position 6 (normal HbA) is negatively charged and hydrophilic, so it cannot form this hydrophobic contact; it electrostatically repels adjacent molecules rather than promoting polymerization.'}]}],
 bottomLine:'Amino acids are the alphabet of protein biochemistry: twenty letters, each with a distinct R group that determines charge, reactivity, and structural preference. At physiological pH all amino acids exist as zwitterions with the backbone both protonated and deprotonated; side chain ionization follows Henderson-Hasselbalch from each side chain pKa, and the isoelectric point is the average of the two pKa values flanking the neutral species. The peptide bond is planar and rigid due to resonance delocalization, essentially always trans, and constrains folding to the phi/psi angles mapped by the Ramachandran plot. Secondary structure (alpha helix: i to i+4 backbone H-bonds; beta sheet: inter-strand backbone H-bonds) is broken by proline and glycine. Hydrophobic collapse, entropy-driven burial of nonpolar side chains, is the dominant force for tertiary folding; disulfide bonds, salt bridges, H-bonds, and van der Waals interactions provide additional stability. Quaternary structure enables cooperativity: hemoglobin\'s sigmoidal curve and T/R states allow efficient oxygen loading in the lungs and oxygen delivery in tissues, modulated by 2,3-BPG, H+, CO2, and CO. Protein misfolding drives disease: sickle cell anemia (hydrophobic Val polymerizes HbS), osteogenesis imperfecta (Gly substitution in collagen triple helix), alpha-1 antitrypsin deficiency (retained Z-A1AT damages liver, absent A1AT leaves lung unprotected), and prion diseases (PrPc to PrPsc conformational conversion propagates without nucleic acid). Master the twenty amino acids and the four levels of structure, and every protein disease becomes a mechanistic story rather than a list of facts.',
 nextHint:'Chapter 2, Enzyme Kinetics and Mechanisms, where the folded protein becomes a catalyst: the Michaelis-Menten framework, enzyme inhibition, allosteric regulation, and the mechanisms of the serine proteases and other canonical enzyme families. The amino acid chemistry installed in this chapter is the vocabulary; Chapter 2 shows how that vocabulary builds enzymatic function.',
},
{
 n:2,
 title:'Enzyme Kinetics and Regulation',
 subtitle:'From activation energy to allosteric switches: the quantitative, mechanistic, and clinical language of enzyme function',
 tag:'Molecular Toolkit',
 foundational:'Enzymes are the molecular machines that make biochemistry possible. Without them, most reactions essential to life would proceed at rates too slow to sustain a cell. This chapter builds the complete framework for understanding how enzymes work: the thermodynamic logic of catalysis, the quantitative kinetics of Michaelis-Menten, the pharmacological and toxicological consequences of enzyme inhibition, the regulatory sophistication of allosteric control, the covalent modifications and cascades that amplify hormonal signals, the systematic classification of enzyme types, and the clinical use of serum enzymes as diagnostic windows into organ function.',
 buildsOn:'Ch 1, protein structure; Gen Chem kinetics and equilibria.',
 setsUp:'All metabolic chapters depend on enzyme regulation.',
 objectives:['Explain how enzymes lower activation energy without changing reaction equilibrium','Distinguish transition-state stabilization from substrate binding as the key catalytic principle','Define Km, Vmax, kcat, and catalytic efficiency; interpret each quantitatively','Derive the Michaelis-Menten equation from the steady-state assumption and interpret the hyperbolic curve','Construct and interpret a Lineweaver-Burk double-reciprocal plot','Distinguish competitive, uncompetitive, and noncompetitive inhibition by mechanism, kinetic parameters, and Lineweaver-Burk appearance','Explain irreversible inhibition and suicide inhibition with clinical examples','Describe allosteric regulation, cooperativity, and the Hill equation','Explain feedback inhibition as a metabolic control strategy','Describe phosphorylation, zymogen activation, and signal amplification cascades','Name the six enzyme classes and assign clinically important enzymes to their correct class','Interpret serum enzyme panels for myocardial infarction, liver disease, and pancreatitis','Explain the catalytic triad mechanism of serine proteases at the step level'],
 opener:'Enzymes are the molecular machines that make biochemistry possible. Without them, most reactions essential to life would proceed at rates too slow to sustain a cell. The decarboxylation of a simple amino acid like ornithine proceeds with a half-life measured in millions of years at physiological temperature. The same reaction, catalyzed by ornithine decarboxylase, occurs in milliseconds. Rate enhancements of 10^10 to 10^23-fold are documented for various enzymes relative to their uncatalyzed counterparts.\n\nThis is not merely a quantitative improvement: it is the difference between life and no life. The cell\'s entire metabolic program depends on being able to run thermodynamically favorable reactions at rates compatible with millisecond-to-second physiological processes. Equally important is the regulatory dimension: because each enzyme has a specific active site that recognizes specific substrates, the cell can turn individual reactions on and off independently. This is what allows the 2,000 or more enzymatic reactions of human intermediary metabolism to proceed simultaneously in the same cytoplasm without chaotic cross-reactions.\n\nEvery concept introduced here recurs throughout the remaining chapters of Book 6, wherever a specific enzyme is regulated, inhibited by a drug, or disrupted by disease. Understanding this chapter is not optional for MCAT or Step 1: it is the foundation on which every pathway in this book rests.',
 pinnedDisc:{t:'COMPETITIVE vs UNCOMPETITIVE vs NONCOMPETITIVE',x:'Competitive: competes with substrate at active site. Overcome with more substrate. Km increases, Vmax unchanged. Uncompetitive: binds only to ES complex. Cannot be overcome. Both Km and Vmax decrease (same factor). Noncompetitive: binds E or ES at allosteric site. Vmax decreases, Km unchanged. Statins (competitive), organophosphates (irreversible covalent).'},
 sections:[{id:'2.1',num:'2.1',title:'2.1 What Enzymes Do: Catalysis Without Changing Equilibrium',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Every spontaneous chemical reaction proceeds in the direction of lower free energy: the direction dictated by the sign of delta-G. Thermodynamics determines whether a reaction can occur; it says nothing about how fast. A highly exergonic reaction can be essentially frozen at room temperature if the activation energy barrier is large. Activation energy (Ea) is the energy that reactants must acquire to reach the transition state: the highest-energy, most unstable configuration along the reaction coordinate. Only molecules that have acquired sufficient thermal energy to cross this barrier can proceed to products. At body temperature, the fraction of molecules with enough energy to cross a high barrier is vanishingly small, which is why glucose sitting in a beaker does not spontaneously combust in air despite the reaction being thermodynamically overwhelmingly favorable.'},{t:'p',x:'An enzyme lowers the activation energy barrier, dramatically increasing the fraction of substrate molecules that can cross it per unit time. The critical thermodynamic point, one of the most frequently tested in the entire MCAT biochemistry curriculum, is that an enzyme changes the rate of reaction but does NOT change the equilibrium constant (Keq) or the overall free-energy change (delta-G) of the reaction. The enzyme lowers Ea equally for the forward and reverse reactions, so it speeds up the approach to equilibrium but does not alter where that equilibrium lies.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'ENZYME EFFECT ON Ea vs delta-G vs Keq',x:'An enzyme LOWERS the activation energy (Ea) for both the forward and reverse reactions equally. It does NOT change: (1) the standard free-energy change (delta-G°) of the reaction: whether the reaction is exergonic or endergonic is determined by the thermodynamics of substrates and products, not by the enzyme; (2) the equilibrium constant (Keq): the ratio of products to reactants at equilibrium is unchanged; (3) the concentrations of substrates and products at equilibrium. What the enzyme DOES change: the rate at which equilibrium is approached, by lowering the energy barrier that molecules must cross. MCAT trap: if a question states that adding an enzyme shifts the equilibrium toward products, that is wrong. A coupled reaction or a product sink (e.g., subsequent pathway steps) can shift equilibrium by Le Chatelier\'s principle, but the enzyme itself cannot.'},{t:'p',x:'The mechanism by which enzymes lower activation energy is transition-state stabilization. This is the central insight of modern enzyme chemistry. The transition state is the highest-energy species along the reaction coordinate: not a stable intermediate but a fleeting configuration in which old bonds are partially broken and new bonds are partially formed. An enzyme\'s active site is shaped and chemically complementary not primarily to the substrate in its ground state, but to the transition state of the reaction. By binding the transition state more tightly than it binds either substrate or product, the enzyme preferentially stabilizes the transition state, lowering its energy relative to the uncatalyzed pathway. This is why transition-state analog inhibitors, molecules that mimic the shape and charge distribution of the transition state without actually reacting, are among the most potent enzyme inhibitors known. Statins, for example, are transition-state analogs of HMG-CoA at the HMG-CoA reductase active site, which is why they bind so tightly and inhibit so effectively.'},{t:'p',x:'Enzyme specificity extends beyond geometry to stereospecificity. Enzymes are exquisitely chiral catalysts: most enzymes that act on amino acids are specific for the L-configuration, and most enzymes that act on sugars are specific for the D-configuration. This is a direct consequence of the chiral environment of the active site, itself built from L-amino acids, which discriminates between enantiomers through multiple simultaneous contact points. Beyond stereochemistry, enzyme specificity is classified as absolute (the enzyme acts on only one substrate), group specificity (acts on a class of substrates sharing a chemical group), bond specificity (acts on a type of bond regardless of the molecules around it), and stereospecificity (acts on only one stereoisomer). Hexokinase has relatively broad group specificity (phosphorylates several hexoses) while glucokinase (hexokinase IV) has narrower specificity and different kinetic properties.'},{t:'p',x:'Many enzymes require non-protein components to be catalytically active. A cofactor is any non-protein molecule required for enzyme activity. Metal ion cofactors (zinc, iron, copper, magnesium) are tightly bound and participate directly in catalysis by stabilizing charge, acting as Lewis acids, or facilitating electron transfer. Organic cofactors derived from vitamins are called coenzymes when they bind loosely and act as co-substrates (transiently changed during the reaction and regenerated by a separate reaction elsewhere), or prosthetic groups when they are permanently covalently attached. The complete, catalytically active enzyme including its cofactor is the holoenzyme; the protein component alone, without its cofactor, is the apoenzyme. The apoenzyme is catalytically inactive. Any vitamin deficiency that depletes a coenzyme pool converts holoenzymes to inactive apoenzymes, disrupting all metabolic pathways that depend on them.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'Adding a catalyst to an exergonic reaction will:',choices:['A) Increase the equilibrium constant (Keq) for the reaction','B) Decrease the activation energy (Ea) for both forward and reverse reactions equally','C) Change the standard free-energy change (delta-G°) of the reaction','D) Shift the equilibrium toward products by stabilizing the transition state'],answer:1,why:'A catalyst (including an enzyme) lowers the activation energy barrier for both the forward and reverse reactions equally. It does not change Keq, delta-G°, or the equilibrium concentrations of substrates and products. It only increases the rate at which equilibrium is approached. Answer A is wrong: Keq is a thermodynamic quantity determined by delta-G° and temperature, not by catalyst presence. Answer C is wrong for the same reason. Answer D is wrong: stabilizing the transition state speeds the reaction but does not shift where equilibrium lies.'}]},{id:'2.2',num:'2.2',title:'2.2 Michaelis-Menten Kinetics',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'The Michaelis-Menten model is the cornerstone quantitative framework of enzyme kinetics, and understanding it at the level of both derivation and intuition is essential for the MCAT. The model describes a simple one-substrate reaction: enzyme E combines with substrate S to form an enzyme-substrate complex ES, which then either dissociates back to E and S or proceeds forward to release product P and regenerate free enzyme E. The reaction scheme is: E + S forms ES (rate constant k1 for formation, k-1 for dissociation back to E + S), then ES converts to E + P (rate constant k2, also called kcat). The fundamental assumption of the Michaelis-Menten derivation is the steady-state assumption: after an initial transient period, the concentration of ES reaches a steady state at which its rate of formation equals its rate of breakdown. A second assumption is that the total substrate concentration [S] greatly exceeds the total enzyme concentration [E], so that substrate depletion by binding to enzyme is negligible and [S] can be treated as approximately constant at its initial value.'},{t:'formula',x:'v = Vmax x [S] / (Km + [S])'},{t:'p',x:'Vmax is the maximal reaction velocity, reached when all enzyme molecules in the reaction mixture are saturated with substrate: that is, when every enzyme active site is occupied by a substrate molecule at every instant. Vmax is directly proportional to the total enzyme concentration [E]total: doubling the amount of enzyme doubles Vmax. It is reached asymptotically as [S] increases toward infinity; in practice, experimentally measuring true Vmax requires extrapolation. Km, the Michaelis constant, is defined as the substrate concentration at which the reaction velocity equals exactly one-half of Vmax. Substituting v = Vmax/2 into the Michaelis-Menten equation and solving for [S] yields [S] = Km, confirming this definition. The physical meaning of Km is frequently misunderstood: Km approximates the dissociation constant (Kd) of the ES complex, a measure of substrate binding affinity, only in the special case where k2 is much smaller than k-1 (i.e., when product formation is the slow step). In the general case, Km = (k-1 + kcat) / k1. Regardless, a lower Km always means the enzyme reaches half-maximal velocity at a lower substrate concentration, which is operationally equivalent to saying the enzyme has a higher apparent affinity for its substrate.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'Km vs Kd vs SUBSTRATE AFFINITY',x:'Km is the substrate concentration at which v = Vmax/2. It is NOT the same as Kd (the true dissociation constant of the ES complex) unless kcat is much less than k-1. In the general steady-state model: Km = (k-1 + kcat) / k1. If kcat is large relative to k-1, Km > Kd, meaning the enzyme has higher true affinity than Km implies. HOWEVER, for comparing enzyme affinity across substrates or conditions, the rule always holds: LOWER Km = enzyme achieves half-maximal velocity at lower [S] = higher apparent affinity for substrate. HIGHER Km = lower apparent affinity. MCAT questions often say "which enzyme has a higher affinity for substrate?" and the answer is always the one with lower Km. Do NOT confuse Km with Kd on a mechanistic question; DO use Km as a proxy for affinity on a kinetic question. Vmax depends on [E]total and kcat; Km is (ideally) independent of [E]total and reflects the relationship between substrate and the active site.'},{t:'p',x:'The catalytic constant kcat (also called the turnover number) is the rate constant for the conversion of ES to E + P. Its units are inverse seconds (s-1). Physically, kcat is the maximum number of substrate molecules that one enzyme molecule can convert to product per second when the enzyme is fully saturated. Carbonic anhydrase, the fastest known enzyme, has a kcat of approximately 10^6 s-1. Lysozyme, by contrast, has a kcat of roughly 0.5 s-1. The relationship between Vmax and kcat is: Vmax = kcat x [E]total. Catalytic efficiency combines kcat and Km into a single parameter: the specificity constant kcat/Km, with units of M-1 s-1. This ratio measures how efficiently an enzyme converts substrate to product at low substrate concentrations, where the enzyme is far from saturation. The upper theoretical limit of kcat/Km is approximately 10^8 to 10^9 M-1 s-1, set by the diffusion limit: the rate at which enzyme and substrate can encounter each other in solution. Enzymes that approach this limit are called "catalytically perfect" or diffusion-limited; triose phosphate isomerase is the canonical example, with kcat/Km near 10^8 M-1 s-1.'},{t:'p',x:'Reading Km and Vmax from a hyperbolic curve directly is difficult because the asymptote is never actually reached. The Lineweaver-Burk plot (double-reciprocal plot) transforms the Michaelis-Menten equation into a linear form by taking the reciprocal of both sides: 1/v = (Km/Vmax)(1/[S]) + 1/Vmax. On a graph of 1/v versus 1/[S], this is a straight line with slope = Km/Vmax, y-intercept = 1/Vmax, and x-intercept = -1/Km. All three kinetic parameters can be read directly from the intercepts and slope. This graphical tool is essential for the MCAT, particularly for distinguishing inhibitor types, and must be internalized to the point of automatic recall.'},{t:'formula',x:'1/v = (Km/Vmax)(1/[S]) + 1/Vmax   [Lineweaver-Burk: slope = Km/Vmax; y-int = 1/Vmax; x-int = -1/Km]'},{t:'box',kind:'why',label:'WHY THE LINEWEAVER-BURK PLOT HAS REAL LIMITATIONS',x:'The Lineweaver-Burk plot is mathematically elegant and conceptually useful, but it has a serious statistical weakness: it heavily distorts experimental error. At low substrate concentrations (large values of 1/[S], far to the right on the x-axis), the corresponding velocities are small. Small velocities measured with any experimental noise produce large errors in 1/v (because taking the reciprocal of a small, noisy number amplifies the noise). The Vmax intercept (at 1/[S] = 0) is extrapolated far from the data, where the error is greatest. The Km intercept is similarly extrapolated. Modern enzyme kinetics uses nonlinear regression fitting of the untransformed Michaelis-Menten equation, which handles the error correctly. For the MCAT, however, the Lineweaver-Burk plot remains the primary graphical tool for distinguishing inhibition types: its visual patterns (parallel lines for uncompetitive inhibition, intersecting lines at the y-axis for competitive inhibition) are the standard teaching representation.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'On a Lineweaver-Burk plot, the x-intercept equals:',choices:['A) 1/Vmax','B) Km/Vmax','C) -1/Km','D) Vmax/Km'],answer:2,why:'The Lineweaver-Burk equation is 1/v = (Km/Vmax)(1/[S]) + 1/Vmax. At the x-intercept, 1/v = 0. Setting 0 = (Km/Vmax)(1/[S]) + 1/Vmax and solving: -1/Vmax = (Km/Vmax)(1/[S]), so 1/[S] = -1/Km. The x-intercept is therefore -1/Km. The y-intercept (where 1/[S] = 0) is 1/Vmax. The slope of the line is Km/Vmax. These three values must be recalled automatically.'}]},{id:'2.3',num:'2.3',title:'2.3 Enzyme Inhibition',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Enzyme inhibitors reduce catalytic activity by a variety of mechanisms that differ in their reversibility, their site of action on the enzyme, and their kinetic consequences. Understanding these mechanisms is not an academic exercise: the majority of drugs in clinical use work by inhibiting specific enzymes, and the type of inhibition determines how the drug behaves in the body, whether it can be overcome by substrate excess, and how its potency should be quantified. Reversible inhibitors form non-covalent complexes with the enzyme and dissociate when the inhibitor concentration falls; they are characterized by an inhibition constant Ki, which is the dissociation constant of the enzyme-inhibitor complex. There are three classical types of reversible inhibition: competitive, uncompetitive, and noncompetitive (including its pure and mixed subtypes), each with a distinct mechanism and a distinct kinetic signature.'},{t:'p',x:'Competitive inhibition is the most common and most clinically important type. The inhibitor is structurally similar to the substrate and binds the active site of the free enzyme, directly competing with substrate for the same binding site. Because inhibitor and substrate compete for the same site, increasing substrate concentration can displace the inhibitor and overcome the inhibition: given enough substrate, the enzyme can achieve its full Vmax. This is the defining kinetic feature: Vmax is unchanged. However, the apparent Km increases in the presence of a competitive inhibitor, because more substrate is required to achieve half-maximal velocity when some of the active sites are occupied by inhibitor. Quantitatively, the apparent Km in the presence of competitive inhibitor is Km x (1 + [I]/Ki), where [I] is the inhibitor concentration and Ki is the inhibitor dissociation constant. On a Lineweaver-Burk plot, competitive inhibition produces a family of lines with the same y-intercept (1/Vmax unchanged) but different slopes and different x-intercepts: the lines rotate around the y-intercept. Classic examples: statins (competitive with HMG-CoA at HMG-CoA reductase), methotrexate (competitive with dihydrofolate at dihydrofolate reductase), sulfonamides (competitive with para-aminobenzoic acid at dihydropteroate synthase in bacteria).'},{t:'p',x:'Uncompetitive inhibition is mechanistically distinct: the inhibitor binds only to the enzyme-substrate complex (ES), not to the free enzyme. This means the inhibitor does not compete with substrate for the active site: the inhibitor cannot bind until substrate has already bound and formed the ES complex. The kinetic consequence is counterintuitive: both apparent Km and Vmax decrease by the same factor (1 + [I]/Ki). The decrease in apparent Km might seem to suggest that the inhibitor improves substrate binding, but the actual mechanism is that by locking substrate in the ES complex without allowing product release, the inhibitor effectively removes free enzyme from the system, depleting the enzyme concentration available for new substrate binding while simultaneously trapping substrate. On a Lineweaver-Burk plot, uncompetitive inhibition produces lines that are parallel to the uninhibited line but displaced upward (higher y-intercept, representing lower Vmax): the slope (Km/Vmax) is unchanged because both Km and Vmax decrease by the same factor.'},{t:'p',x:'Noncompetitive inhibition occurs when the inhibitor binds to a site on the enzyme other than the active site, an allosteric site, and binds with equal affinity to both the free enzyme and the ES complex. Because the inhibitor does not block substrate binding, Km is unchanged. However, the inhibitor changes the conformation of the enzyme such that the rate of product formation (kcat) decreases, reducing Vmax. In pure noncompetitive inhibition, the inhibitor binds E and ES with exactly equal affinity (Ki = Ki\'), giving unchanged Km and reduced Vmax. In mixed inhibition, the inhibitor binds with different affinities to E and ES (Ki not equal to Ki\'), and both Km and Vmax change. On a Lineweaver-Burk plot, pure noncompetitive inhibition produces lines that intersect on the x-axis: same x-intercept (same -1/Km), but different y-intercepts (different 1/Vmax) and different slopes. Mixed inhibition lines intersect at a point somewhere in the second or third quadrant, not on either axis. The key clinical point about noncompetitive inhibition: it cannot be overcome by increasing substrate concentration, because the inhibitor does not compete with substrate.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'COMPETITIVE vs UNCOMPETITIVE vs NONCOMPETITIVE INHIBITION',x:'COMPETITIVE: binds FREE enzyme at active site; apparent Km increases, Vmax unchanged; Lineweaver-Burk: same y-intercept (1/Vmax), different slope/x-intercept; lines rotate around the y-axis; OVERCOME by high [S]. Example: statins vs HMG-CoA; methotrexate vs dihydrofolate reductase. UNCOMPETITIVE: binds ES complex only (NOT free enzyme); both apparent Km and apparent Vmax decrease by same factor; Lineweaver-Burk: PARALLEL lines (same slope, higher y-intercept); NOT overcome by high [S]. Rare clinically but testable. NONCOMPETITIVE (pure): binds E and ES equally; apparent Km unchanged, Vmax decreases; Lineweaver-Burk: lines intersect ON x-axis; NOT overcome by high [S]. MIXED: binds E and ES unequally; both Km and Vmax change; lines intersect off-axis. THE ONE QUESTION THAT ALWAYS APPEARS: which type can be overcome by increasing [S]? ONLY competitive, because it\'s the only type where inhibitor and substrate physically compete for the same site. High [S] outcompetes the inhibitor.'},{t:'p',x:'Irreversible inhibition differs fundamentally from reversible inhibition: the inhibitor forms a covalent bond with the enzyme\'s active site, permanently inactivating it. Unlike reversible inhibitors, which reach equilibrium with the enzyme, irreversible inhibitors react with the enzyme in a time-dependent manner: the longer the exposure, the more enzyme is inactivated. Recovery from irreversible inhibition requires the cell to synthesize new enzyme molecules. The kinetic consequence of irreversible inhibition is a decrease in the effective enzyme concentration: Vmax decreases (because fewer functional enzyme molecules are present), while Km is unchanged for the remaining active enzyme. The most toxicologically and pharmacologically important irreversible inhibitors target the active-site serine of serine proteases. Organophosphate nerve agents (sarin, soman, VX) and organophosphate insecticides (malathion, parathion) react with the active-site serine of acetylcholinesterase (AChE), covalently phosphorylating it and preventing the hydrolysis of acetylcholine at synapses. The resulting excess acetylcholine produces the cholinergic toxidrome: muscarinic effects (miosis, bradycardia, bronchospasm, lacrimation, urination, defecation, salivation: the SLUDGE or DUMBELS mnemonics), and nicotinic effects (muscle fasciculations, then paralysis). Aspirin irreversibly acetylates the active-site serine of both cyclooxygenase-1 and cyclooxygenase-2, permanently inhibiting prostaglandin synthesis. Because platelets lack nuclei and cannot synthesize new protein, aspirin\'s antiplatelet effect lasts the entire platelet lifespan (approximately 10 days). Penicillin and related beta-lactam antibiotics irreversibly acylate the active-site serine of bacterial transpeptidases (penicillin-binding proteins), preventing crosslinking of peptidoglycan and causing cell wall failure.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'ORGANOPHOSPHATE POISONING: MECHANISM AND TREATMENT',x:'Organophosphate compounds irreversibly phosphorylate the active-site serine of acetylcholinesterase (AChE), preventing it from hydrolyzing acetylcholine (ACh). ACh accumulates at both muscarinic (parasympathetic, CNS) and nicotinic (neuromuscular junction, autonomic ganglia) synapses. Clinical presentation: SLUDGE (Salivation, Lacrimation, Urination, Defecation, GI distress, Emesis) plus miosis, bronchospasm, bradycardia (muscarinic), and fasciculations progressing to flaccid paralysis (nicotinic). Death is from respiratory failure (bronchospasm + diaphragm paralysis). Treatment has two components: (1) ATROPINE: a muscarinic antagonist that blocks the muscarinic effects of excess ACh; large doses are given to reverse bronchospasm, excessive secretions, and bradycardia. Atropine does NOT reverse the nicotinic (neuromuscular) effects. (2) PRALIDOXIME (2-PAM): an oxime that can regenerate active AChE by displacing the phosphate group from the active-site serine, restoring enzymatic activity. Pralidoxime must be given EARLY, before "aging" (a time-dependent tightening of the phosphate-enzyme bond making the adduct irreversible). After aging, pralidoxime is ineffective.'},{t:'p',x:'Suicide inhibition, also called mechanism-based inhibition, represents a sophisticated class of irreversible inhibitor in which the compound is initially a substrate analog and is processed by the enzyme\'s normal catalytic mechanism. During the catalytic cycle, the enzyme converts the suicide inhibitor into a highly reactive intermediate that then covalently and irreversibly modifies the enzyme, killing it. The inhibitor is a "Trojan horse": it gains access to the active site as a substrate mimic, then destroys the enzyme from within. Because suicide inhibitors require the enzyme\'s own catalytic machinery to activate them, they are exquisitely selective for their target enzyme. Fluorouracil (5-FU), an anticancer drug, is converted inside cells to fluorodeoxyuridine monophosphate (FdUMP). FdUMP mimics the normal substrate of thymidylate synthase and forms a stable, covalent ternary complex with the enzyme and the cofactor methylenetetrahydrofolate, permanently inactivating the enzyme and blocking the synthesis of thymidine, thereby halting DNA replication preferentially in rapidly dividing cancer cells. Allopurinol, used to treat gout, is a structural analog of hypoxanthine. It is oxidized by xanthine oxidase to alloxanthine (oxypurinol), which then binds tightly to the reduced form of xanthine oxidase and inhibits it, blocking the conversion of hypoxanthine and xanthine to uric acid and reducing urate levels.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A drug increases the apparent Km of an enzyme without changing Vmax. Adding excess substrate fully restores enzyme velocity to Vmax. This drug is a:',choices:['A) Noncompetitive inhibitor','B) Uncompetitive inhibitor','C) Competitive inhibitor','D) Irreversible inhibitor'],answer:2,why:'The key features are: apparent Km increases (enzyme appears to have lower affinity for substrate), Vmax unchanged, and the inhibition can be overcome by adding excess substrate. These are the three defining characteristics of competitive inhibition. The inhibitor competes with substrate for the active site. At sufficiently high [S], substrate outcompetes the inhibitor, and the enzyme achieves its full Vmax. Noncompetitive inhibition: Km unchanged, Vmax decreases. Uncompetitive inhibition: both Km and Vmax decrease. Irreversible inhibition: Vmax decreases permanently and cannot be restored by adding more substrate.'}]},{id:'2.4',num:'2.4',title:'2.4 Allosteric Regulation and Cooperativity',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Allosteric regulation is the most powerful and most elegant mechanism by which cells modulate enzyme activity in response to their metabolic state. An allosteric enzyme has at least two distinct binding sites: the active site where the substrate binds and catalysis occurs, and one or more regulatory (allosteric) sites that are physically separate from the active site. Binding of a ligand to the allosteric site induces a conformational change that propagates through the protein structure to alter the geometry or chemistry of the active site. Allosteric activators typically shift the protein toward its high-activity (R-state or relaxed-state) conformation; allosteric inhibitors shift it toward the low-activity (T-state or tense-state) conformation. The profound advantage of allosteric regulation over simple substrate-product kinetics is that the regulatory ligand need not be the substrate: any metabolite anywhere in the cell\'s metabolic network can serve as an allosteric regulator if there is a binding site for it, allowing information about the cell\'s overall metabolic status to be integrated at any individual enzyme.'},{t:'p',x:'Many allosteric enzymes are oligomeric and exhibit cooperativity: the binding of one substrate molecule to one subunit changes the affinity of the remaining subunits for subsequent substrate molecules. Positive cooperativity, the most common form, means that binding of the first substrate makes the enzyme more likely to bind additional substrate molecules. The result is a sigmoidal (S-shaped) velocity-versus-substrate-concentration curve rather than the hyperbolic curve of a Michaelis-Menten enzyme. The sigmoidal curve has an important functional consequence: the enzyme is relatively insensitive to substrate at low concentrations (the flat lower portion of the sigmoid) but switches sharply to high activity over a narrow range of substrate concentrations (the steep middle region). This creates a switch-like response rather than a graded one: exactly what is needed at a committed regulatory step. The degree of cooperativity is quantified by the Hill coefficient (n): n = 1 is a non-cooperative (hyperbolic) enzyme; n > 1 is positive cooperativity; n < 1 is negative cooperativity (rare, seen in some multi-substrate enzymes).'},{t:'formula',x:'Hill equation: v = Vmax x [S]^n / (K0.5^n + [S]^n)   [n > 1: positive cooperativity; K0.5 = [S] at half-Vmax for cooperative enzyme]'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'HYPERBOLIC vs SIGMOIDAL KINETICS',x:'HYPERBOLIC v vs [S] curve: characteristic of MICHAELIS-MENTEN (non-allosteric) enzymes; Hill coefficient n = 1; Km is well-defined as the [S] at half-Vmax; the curve is asymptotically smooth. SIGMOIDAL v vs [S] curve: characteristic of ALLOSTERIC, COOPERATIVE enzymes; Hill coefficient n > 1; K0.5 replaces Km; the curve has a threshold region where the enzyme is inactive, then a steep activation region, then saturation. KEY DISTINCTION: ALLOSTERIC ACTIVATORS shift the sigmoidal curve LEFT (lower K0.5, enzyme active at lower [S]); ALLOSTERIC INHIBITORS shift it RIGHT (higher K0.5, enzyme needs more [S] to achieve half-maximal activity). MCAT trap: competitive inhibitors act on hyperbolic (Michaelis-Menten) enzymes and do not shift Vmax: do not confuse with allosteric inhibition, which acts on sigmoidal enzymes and shifts the K0.5 right while potentially also reducing the maximum achievable velocity. On a Lineweaver-Burk plot, allosteric enzymes are NOT linear and the plot should not be applied to them in the same way.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'COOPERATIVITY AND OXYGEN TRANSPORT: HEMOGLOBIN AS A MODEL',x:'Hemoglobin is not an enzyme, but its cooperative oxygen binding is the most clinically important example of the allosteric cooperativity principle in human physiology. Hemoglobin is a tetrameric protein (alpha2-beta2) with four heme-iron oxygen binding sites. The sigmoidal oxygen-hemoglobin dissociation curve results from positive cooperativity: when one subunit binds O2, conformational changes propagate to the other subunits, increasing their O2 affinity (T-state to R-state transition). The Hill coefficient for hemoglobin is approximately 2.8. Allosteric modulators shift the oxygen-dissociation curve: 2,3-bisphosphoglycerate (2,3-BPG), H+ (Bohr effect), CO2, and temperature all decrease O2 affinity and shift the curve right (Rightward shift = Release of O2 to tissues). Alkalosis, decreased 2,3-BPG (as occurs in stored blood), and CO poisoning shift the curve left, increasing O2 affinity and impairing O2 delivery to tissues. Fetal hemoglobin (HbF, alpha2-gamma2) has lower affinity for 2,3-BPG than adult HbA and therefore higher O2 affinity: essential for extracting O2 from maternal blood across the placenta.'},{t:'p',x:'Feedback inhibition is a ubiquitous regulatory strategy in which the end product of a biosynthetic pathway allosterically inhibits an enzyme early in the same pathway, typically the first committed step. The logic is compelling: if the cell has made enough of the end product, it should stop producing it, and the most efficient way to signal this is to let the end product itself act as the inhibitor. This prevents wasting biosynthetic precursors and energy on products that are not needed. The canonical textbook example is the biosynthesis of isoleucine in bacteria: the end product isoleucine allosterically inhibits threonine deaminase (threonine dehydratase), the first committed step of the isoleucine synthesis pathway. In human metabolism, the same principle applies: accumulated citrate allosterically inhibits phosphofructokinase-1 (PFK-1) in glycolysis, signaling that the cell has sufficient energy. CTP, the end product of pyrimidine synthesis, inhibits ATCase, the committed step of pyrimidine synthesis. ATP, the end product of energy metabolism, inhibits multiple enzymes including PFK-1, while AMP activates it: an elegant system that responds to the cell\'s energy charge.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'An allosteric inhibitor of a cooperative enzyme shifts the sigmoidal v vs [S] curve in which direction?',choices:['A) Left, decreasing K0.5 (enzyme is active at lower [S])','B) Right, increasing K0.5 (enzyme requires more [S] to reach half-maximal activity)','C) The Vmax increases because the inhibitor stabilizes the R-state','D) The Hill coefficient increases, making the curve more sigmoidal'],answer:1,why:'Allosteric inhibitors shift the sigmoidal curve to the RIGHT, increasing K0.5. This means the enzyme requires a higher substrate concentration to achieve half-maximal velocity: effectively it becomes less responsive to substrate at normal cellular concentrations. Allosteric activators shift the curve LEFT, decreasing K0.5 (enzyme is active at lower [S]). Answer A describes an allosteric activator, not an inhibitor. Answer C is wrong: allosteric inhibitors do not increase Vmax. Answer D is wrong: the Hill coefficient reflects the degree of cooperativity in the enzyme structure, not the direction of allosteric regulation.'}]},{id:'2.5',num:'2.5',title:'2.5 Covalent Modification and Enzyme Cascades',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Allosteric regulation operates through non-covalent conformational changes. A second major class of regulatory mechanism involves covalent modification of the enzyme itself: adding or removing a chemical group that changes the enzyme\'s activity. Unlike allosteric regulation, covalent modification is not immediately reversible by ligand dissociation; reversing it requires a separate enzymatic reaction. Phosphorylation by protein kinases is by far the most common and physiologically most important form of reversible covalent modification. Serine/threonine kinases (including protein kinase A, protein kinase C, and AMP-activated protein kinase) phosphorylate the hydroxyl groups of serine or threonine residues; tyrosine kinases phosphorylate tyrosine residues. The phosphate group adds a large, negatively charged moiety that changes the local electrostatic environment of the protein, inducing conformational changes that can either activate or inhibit the enzyme depending on the specific protein. Phosphatases remove the phosphate group and reverse the modification.'},{t:'p',x:'Protein kinase A (PKA) is the primary cAMP-dependent kinase in the cell; it is composed of two regulatory subunits (R) and two catalytic subunits (C). In the absence of cAMP, the R subunits hold the C subunits in an inactive conformation. When cAMP binds the R subunits, they release the C subunits, which are then free to phosphorylate serine and threonine residues on downstream target enzymes. AMP-activated protein kinase (AMPK) is an entirely different energy-sensing kinase that is activated when the cellular AMP:ATP ratio rises (indicating energy depletion). AMPK phosphorylates and inactivates enzymes of anabolic pathways (acetyl-CoA carboxylase, HMG-CoA reductase) while activating catabolic pathways, thereby restoring energy balance. Metformin, the first-line drug for type 2 diabetes, activates AMPK by inhibiting Complex I of the electron transport chain (reducing ATP production and raising AMP:ATP), making AMPK activation central to its mechanism of action.'},{t:'p',x:'Glycogen metabolism provides the most instructive example of reciprocal regulation by phosphorylation. During fasting or stress, glucagon (in the liver) and epinephrine (in both liver and muscle) activate adenylyl cyclase through G-protein-coupled receptors, raising cAMP concentration. Elevated cAMP activates PKA. PKA then phosphorylates two downstream targets with opposite effects: phosphorylation of phosphorylase kinase activates it, and active phosphorylase kinase phosphorylates and activates glycogen phosphorylase, increasing glycogen breakdown. Simultaneously, PKA phosphorylates glycogen synthase and thereby inhibits it, decreasing glycogen synthesis. The net result of a single hormonal signal acting through a cAMP-PKA cascade is that glycogen is degraded and not synthesized: a coherent metabolic response to the need for glucose. The cascade structure (hormone to receptor to G-protein to adenylyl cyclase to cAMP to PKA to phosphorylase kinase to glycogen phosphorylase) amplifies the original hormonal signal at each step, so that a tiny concentration of hormone can mobilize a large amount of glycogen. This signal amplification is a fundamental property of enzyme cascades.'},{t:'p',x:'Zymogen activation is a one-way biological switch: inactive enzyme precursors (zymogens or proenzymes) require proteolytic cleavage to become active. The pancreas synthesizes many digestive enzymes as zymogens precisely because active proteases and lipases inside the pancreatic cell would be catastrophic: they would digest the cell itself. Trypsinogen is activated to trypsin by enteropeptidase (enterokinase) on the luminal surface of the duodenum; once formed, trypsin can autocatalytically activate more trypsinogen and also activates chymotrypsinogen (to chymotrypsin), proelastase (to elastase), and prolipase (to lipase). Zymogen activation is irreversible: once a zymogen is cleaved and activated, the process cannot be reversed under physiological conditions. The coagulation cascade is one of the most elaborate zymogen activation cascades in biology: Factor XII to Factor XIIa, which activates Factor XI, and so on through multiple steps to thrombin, which cleaves fibrinogen to fibrin.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'ZYMOGEN ACTIVATION AND PANCREATITIS',x:'Zymogens are inactive enzyme precursors that require proteolytic cleavage to become active. The pancreas synthesizes digestive enzymes as zymogens precisely because active proteases and lipases inside the pancreatic cell would autodigest the cell itself. In acute pancreatitis, this activation cascade occurs prematurely WITHIN the pancreatic tissue: the zymogens are activated inside the acinar cells or pancreatic ducts before they reach the duodenum. The resulting active proteases and lipases autodigest the pancreatic parenchyma, causing the severe epigastric pain, elevated amylase and lipase levels, and potentially life-threatening systemic inflammation seen in pancreatitis. Common triggers include gallstones (obstructing the pancreatic duct) and alcohol (directly toxic to acinar cells). Lipase is more specific for pancreatic injury than amylase and remains elevated for a longer period after the onset of acute pancreatitis, making it the preferred diagnostic marker.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'PHOSPHORYLATION vs ALLOSTERIC REGULATION vs ZYMOGEN ACTIVATION',x:'Three regulatory mechanisms differ fundamentally in speed, reversibility, and type of conformational change. ALLOSTERIC REGULATION: non-covalent; nearly instantaneous (ligand binding/release in milliseconds); fully reversible on the timescale of ligand dissociation; mediates moment-to-moment metabolic fine-tuning. Examples: AMP activates PFK-1; citrate inhibits PFK-1; CTP inhibits ATCase. PHOSPHORYLATION: covalent addition of a phosphate group by a kinase; requires a separate phosphatase to reverse; timescale of seconds to minutes; allows hormonal signals (glucagon, PKA) to produce sustained metabolic shifts. Examples: glycogen phosphorylase (phospho = active), glycogen synthase (phospho = inactive). ZYMOGEN ACTIVATION: covalent, irreversible proteolytic cleavage; one-way switch; seconds to minutes; used where a committed, irreversible activation is needed. Examples: trypsinogen to trypsin; prothrombin to thrombin. MCAT trap: all three produce conformational changes that alter enzyme activity, but they differ in their reversibility. "Covalent and irreversible" = zymogen activation or irreversible inhibition; "covalent and reversible" = phosphorylation; "non-covalent" = allosteric regulation.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'Epinephrine activates glycogen phosphorylase through a cascade. Which statement correctly describes the reversibility of each step in this cascade?',choices:['A) Epinephrine binding to its receptor is irreversible; all downstream steps are reversible','B) All steps including PKA phosphorylation are irreversible once initiated','C) Epinephrine binding and cAMP generation are reversible; PKA phosphorylation of target enzymes is reversible (reversed by phosphatases)','D) The final step, glycogen phosphorylase activation, is irreversible by proteolytic cleavage'],answer:2,why:'The entire hormonal signaling cascade through cAMP and PKA is reversible. Epinephrine binding to its G-protein-coupled receptor is a non-covalent, reversible interaction. cAMP is synthesized by adenylyl cyclase but is rapidly degraded by phosphodiesterase enzymes (hence why caffeine and theophylline, which inhibit phosphodiesterase, prolong the cAMP signal). PKA phosphorylation of target enzymes (including phosphorylase kinase and glycogen synthase) is covalent but reversible: protein phosphatases remove the phosphate group and reverse the modification. This distinguishes phosphorylation-based regulation from zymogen activation (which is irreversible proteolytic cleavage).'}]},{id:'2.6',num:'2.6',title:'2.6 Enzyme Classes and Nomenclature',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'The International Union of Biochemistry and Molecular Biology (IUBMB) classifies all enzymes into six major classes based on the type of chemical reaction they catalyze. Each class is identified by an EC (Enzyme Commission) number. This classification system is not arbitrary: it reflects genuine mechanistic and chemical distinctions that help predict what cofactors an enzyme uses, what type of reaction it catalyzes, and where it fits in a metabolic pathway. Understanding the six classes at a level sufficient to assign an enzyme to its class is testable on both the MCAT and Step 1.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'THE SIX ENZYME CLASSES',x:'EC 1 OXIDOREDUCTASES: catalyze oxidation-reduction reactions; require redox cofactors (NAD+/NADH, FAD/FADH2, NADP+/NADPH, or molecular oxygen); examples: LDH, ALT, AST, alcohol dehydrogenase, cytochrome P450 enzymes, ETC complexes. The presence of "dehydrogenase," "reductase," or "oxidase" in the name is a reliable indicator of EC 1. EC 2 TRANSFERASES: catalyze transfer of a functional group (amino, phosphate, methyl, acyl) from one molecule (donor) to another (acceptor); cofactors often PLP (transamination), ATP, S-adenosylmethionine; examples: ALT, AST (aminotransferases), hexokinase, creatine kinase, methyltransferases. EC 3 HYDROLASES: catalyze bond cleavage using water (no redox); often no cofactor; examples: trypsin, chymotrypsin, lipase, amylase, alkaline phosphatase, AChE, pepsin. Most numerous class in lysosomes. EC 4 LYASES: catalyze addition or removal of groups to create or break double bonds (C=C, C=O, C=N) without water and without redox; examples: aldolase, pyruvate decarboxylase, adenylyl cyclase, carbonic anhydrase. EC 5 ISOMERASES: catalyze intramolecular rearrangements; same molecular formula, different structure; examples: phosphoglucose isomerase, triose phosphate isomerase, mutases, racemases. EC 6 LIGASES: catalyze joining of two molecules using energy of ATP hydrolysis; name often includes "synthetase" or "carboxylase"; examples: acetyl-CoA carboxylase, DNA ligase, aminoacyl-tRNA synthetases. KEY DISCRIMINATOR: a synthase may or may not use ATP; a synthetase specifically uses ATP hydrolysis.'},{t:'p',x:'Several enzyme classification traps appear repeatedly on both the MCAT and Step 1. Adenylyl cyclase (also called adenylate cyclase): the enzyme that converts ATP to cyclic AMP is a LYASE (EC 4), not a ligase, because it breaks the phosphoanhydride bond of ATP to form the cyclic 3\',5\'-phosphodiester linkage of cAMP, creating a new intramolecular bond rather than joining two separate molecules. Phospholipase C is a HYDROLASE (EC 3) that cleaves the phosphate ester bond of phosphatidylinositol-4,5-bisphosphate (PIP2) to release inositol trisphosphate (IP3) and diacylglycerol (DAG). Reverse transcriptase is a TRANSFERASE (EC 2, specifically an RNA-directed DNA polymerase). Topoisomerases are ISOMERASES (EC 5) that change the topological state of DNA by transiently cleaving and rejoining the phosphodiester backbone.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'SYNTHASE vs SYNTHETASE vs KINASE vs PHOSPHATASE',x:'SYNTHASE: an enzyme that catalyzes synthesis, often using the energy of an already-formed high-energy intermediate; NOT necessarily ATP-dependent. Examples: ATP synthase (uses proton gradient), fatty acid synthase (uses malonyl-ACP), citrate synthase. Class: often lyase or transferase. SYNTHETASE: specifically uses ATP hydrolysis to drive synthesis; the name implies ATP coupling. Examples: acetyl-CoA carboxylase (uses ATP + biotin), aminoacyl-tRNA synthetases. Class: ligase (EC 6). KINASE: a transferase (EC 2) that transfers a phosphate group from ATP to a substrate, phosphorylating it. Examples: hexokinase, protein kinase A, creatine kinase. PHOSPHATASE: a hydrolase (EC 3) that removes a phosphate group by hydrolysis, releasing inorganic phosphate. Examples: protein phosphatase 1 (opposes PKA), alkaline phosphatase. MCAT trap: do not confuse kinase (adds phosphate, uses ATP) with phosphatase (removes phosphate, releases Pi). PKA phosphorylates and activates glycogen phosphorylase; protein phosphatase 1 dephosphorylates and inactivates it. The names describe opposite functions, but both regulate the same enzyme at the same serine residue.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'Which enzyme class does lactate dehydrogenase (LDH) belong to?',choices:['A) Transferase (EC 2)','B) Hydrolase (EC 3)','C) Oxidoreductase (EC 1)','D) Lyase (EC 4)'],answer:2,why:'Lactate dehydrogenase (LDH) catalyzes the interconversion of lactate and pyruvate, using NAD+ as an electron acceptor (or NADH as an electron donor). This is an oxidation-reduction reaction (NAD+ is reduced to NADH, or NADH is oxidized to NAD+), which places LDH in EC class 1, the oxidoreductases. The presence of "dehydrogenase" in the enzyme name is a reliable indicator of EC 1. LDH exists as five isoforms (LDH1 through LDH5) composed of combinations of two subunit types (H and M), providing tissue-specific diagnostic information.'}]},{id:'2.7',num:'2.7',title:'2.7 Enzyme Kinetics in Clinical Context',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Serum enzyme levels are among the most widely used laboratory tests in clinical medicine, and interpreting them requires understanding not just what each enzyme does but why its serum concentration rises in specific diseases. Normally, intracellular enzymes are present in serum at very low concentrations. Serum enzyme elevation occurs through three broad mechanisms: cell lysis releasing intracellular contents (as in myocardial infarction, hepatocellular necrosis, and hemolysis); increased enzyme synthesis and secretion (as in bone disease, where osteoblasts produce alkaline phosphatase, or in prostate cancer); and decreased clearance (relevant for some enzymes in renal failure or biliary obstruction).'},{t:'p',x:'The diagnostic utility of a serum enzyme depends on its tissue distribution. An enzyme found predominantly in one organ is highly specific for disease in that organ. For this reason, clinical laboratories measure isoforms (isozymes): structurally distinct forms of the same enzyme with the same catalytic activity but different tissue distributions, separated by electrophoresis or immunoassay. Lactate dehydrogenase and creatine kinase both exist as tissue-specific isoforms that provide organ-specific diagnostic information beyond the total enzyme level. The LDH isoforms illustrate both the biochemical and clinical utility of isoform analysis: because LDH1 and LDH2 are enriched in cardiac muscle and red blood cells (reflecting the H subunit\'s kinetic preference for pyruvate substrate in aerobic tissues), their elevated ratio in serum after MI was historically diagnostic before high-sensitivity troponin assays became available.'},{t:'p',x:'The liver enzyme panel exemplifies how pattern recognition among serum enzymes guides clinical diagnosis. Alanine aminotransferase (ALT) and aspartate aminotransferase (AST) are both transferases (EC 2) that catalyze the transfer of an amino group using PLP as a cofactor. ALT is found predominantly in the liver; it is therefore highly specific for hepatocellular injury. AST is found in both the liver and cardiac muscle (as well as skeletal muscle and other tissues), making it less specific. In viral hepatitis and non-alcoholic fatty liver disease (NAFLD), hepatocellular damage is the predominant process, releasing large amounts of ALT and AST with ALT typically exceeding AST (ALT > AST ratio). In alcoholic hepatitis, mitochondrial injury preferentially releases mitochondrial AST, and the AST:ALT ratio is characteristically greater than 2:1. Alkaline phosphatase (ALP) is elevated in both hepatic and bone disease. Gamma-glutamyl transferase (GGT) is sensitive for biliary disease and inducible by alcohol and certain drugs; elevated GGT with elevated ALP suggests biliary or hepatic origin rather than bone.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'LIVER ENZYME PATTERNS IN DISEASE',x:'HEPATOCELLULAR PATTERN (ALT and AST markedly elevated, often >10x normal): seen in acute viral hepatitis (A, B, C), ischemic hepatitis ("shock liver"), acetaminophen toxicity, and autoimmune hepatitis. ALT is at least as high as AST in most hepatocellular causes. ALCOHOLIC HEPATITIS: AST:ALT > 2:1 is characteristic; values rarely exceed 300 U/L (contrast with viral hepatitis where values may reach thousands). GGT often elevated. CHOLESTATIC PATTERN (ALP markedly elevated, transaminases mildly elevated): seen in primary biliary cholangitis (PBC), primary sclerosing cholangitis (PSC), biliary obstruction by gallstones or pancreatic cancer, and drug-induced cholestasis. GGT elevation alongside ALP confirms biliary/hepatic source (not bone). INFILTRATIVE DISEASE (ALP elevated, transaminases mildly elevated, normal bilirubin): seen with hepatic granulomas (sarcoidosis, TB) and liver metastases. KEY Step 1 rule: if ALP is elevated and you need to know if it\'s liver or bone, check GGT. GGT elevated means liver/biliary source. GGT normal means bone source (osteoblastic).'},{t:'p',x:'Cardiac enzyme markers are the cornerstone of myocardial infarction diagnosis. Troponin I and Troponin T are structural proteins of the cardiac myofibril that are released into the circulation when cardiomyocytes are irreversibly injured. High-sensitivity troponin assays can detect myocardial injury within 1 to 3 hours of symptom onset; troponin remains elevated for up to 10 to 14 days, making it useful for diagnosing MI in patients who present late. Creatine kinase (CK) is a transferase (EC 2) that catalyzes the reversible transfer of a phosphate group from phosphocreatine to ADP, regenerating ATP in muscle. The CK-MB isoform (containing one M and one B subunit) is more specific for cardiac muscle, though it has largely been supplanted by troponin in modern clinical practice. Serum amylase and lipase elevation indicates pancreatitis: lipase is more specific for pancreatic injury than amylase (amylase is also produced by the salivary glands and may be elevated in non-pancreatic conditions) and remains elevated for a longer period after the onset of acute pancreatitis.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A patient presents with jaundice. Lab values show: ALP markedly elevated, ALT and AST mildly elevated, GGT elevated. This pattern is most consistent with:',choices:['A) Acute viral hepatitis','B) Alcoholic hepatitis with AST:ALT > 2:1','C) Cholestatic liver disease (biliary obstruction)','D) Bone disease with osteoblastic activity'],answer:2,why:'The cholestatic pattern is characterized by markedly elevated ALP with only mildly elevated transaminases (ALT, AST). The elevated GGT alongside ALP confirms that the ALP elevation is of hepatic/biliary origin rather than bone origin (bone disease elevates ALP but does not elevate GGT). Biliary obstruction, whether from gallstones, pancreatic cancer, or primary biliary cholangitis, produces this pattern because bile duct epithelium produces both ALP and GGT in response to bile acid exposure. Answer A (acute viral hepatitis) would show markedly elevated ALT and AST with ALP less prominently elevated. Answer B requires an AST:ALT ratio > 2:1. Answer D would elevate ALP (osteoblastic ALP) but NOT elevate GGT, which is the key distinguishing feature.'}]},{id:'2.8',num:'2.8',title:'2.8 Enzyme Mechanisms: The Serine Protease Catalytic Triad',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'The serine proteases, trypsin, chymotrypsin, elastase, and thrombin, are the best-studied class of proteolytic enzymes and provide the prototype mechanism for covalent catalysis. Despite having different substrate specificities, all serine proteases share a conserved catalytic triad in their active sites: a serine residue (the nucleophile), a histidine residue (the general acid-base catalyst), and an aspartate residue (which positions and stabilizes the histidine through hydrogen bonding). Substrate specificity is determined by the S1 binding pocket: trypsin\'s S1 pocket contains a negatively charged aspartate residue at its base that hydrogen-bonds to the positively charged side chains of arginine or lysine in the substrate, explaining trypsin\'s specificity for cleavage after Arg/Lys. Chymotrypsin\'s S1 pocket is larger and more hydrophobic, accommodating bulky aromatic side chains (Phe, Tyr, Trp). Elastase\'s S1 pocket has two bulky valine residues that restrict access to small, uncharged side chains like alanine and glycine.'},{t:'p',x:'The catalytic mechanism of serine proteases proceeds through two chemical stages separated by a covalent intermediate. In the acylation stage, the active-site serine hydroxyl acts as a nucleophile and attacks the carbonyl carbon of the substrate\'s peptide bond. The histidine acts as a general base, abstracting the proton from the serine hydroxyl to make it a better nucleophile. The aspartate stabilizes the positively charged histidine through a hydrogen bond. The serine oxygen forms a tetrahedral carbon intermediate (the oxyanion hole, formed by backbone amide N-H groups, stabilizes the developing negative charge on the carbonyl oxygen). The tetrahedral intermediate collapses: the N-terminal fragment of the peptide is released as the leaving group (the amine is protonated by histidine acting now as a general acid), and the C-terminal fragment remains covalently attached to the enzyme serine as an acyl-enzyme intermediate. In the deacylation stage, water enters the active site and acts as the nucleophile. Histidine again acts as a general base, activating the water molecule. The water oxygen attacks the carbonyl of the acyl-enzyme intermediate, forming a second tetrahedral intermediate that collapses to release the C-terminal peptide fragment and regenerate the free enzyme with its active-site serine hydroxyl restored.'},{t:'p',x:'The four mechanistic strategies used by all enzymes to achieve catalysis can be summarized as: (1) acid-base catalysis: active-site residues donate or accept protons to facilitate bond formation or breakage; the histidine residue of the catalytic triad in serine proteases exemplifies general acid-base catalysis because its pKa of approximately 6 is near physiological pH, allowing it to function as either acid or base depending on the step of the mechanism. (2) Covalent catalysis: the enzyme forms a transient covalent bond with the substrate, creating a more reactive intermediate; the acyl-enzyme intermediate of serine proteases and the Schiff base intermediates formed by PLP-dependent enzymes (such as the aminotransferases) are examples. (3) Metal ion catalysis: a bound metal ion stabilizes charge, facilitates redox, or positions a nucleophilic water molecule, as in carbonic anhydrase (Zn2+), carboxypeptidase (Zn2+), and the cytochrome enzymes (Fe or Cu). (4) Electrostatic transition-state stabilization: partial charges that develop in the transition state are stabilized by complementary charges in the active site; the oxyanion hole of serine proteases, which stabilizes the negatively charged oxygen of the tetrahedral intermediate through hydrogen bonding from backbone N-H groups, is the prototype.'},{t:'box',kind:'why',label:'WHY pH AND TEMPERATURE AFFECT ENZYME ACTIVITY',x:'Enzyme activity follows a bell-shaped curve as a function of pH, with a maximum at the optimal pH and steep drops on either side. The optimal pH reflects the ionization state required for the active-site residues to perform their catalytic roles. Pepsin, which operates in the highly acidic stomach (pH ~2), has an optimal pH around 2 and its active-site aspartates must be in the appropriate protonation state for this acid environment. Trypsin and chymotrypsin, acting in the slightly alkaline duodenum (pH ~8), have optima around pH 7.5 to 8. The catalytic triad histidine of serine proteases must be unprotonated (basic) to abstract the proton from the active-site serine; at very low pH it becomes protonated and can no longer act as a base, inactivating the enzyme. Temperature effects also produce a bell-shaped curve: activity increases with temperature (Arrhenius kinetics: more molecules have enough energy to reach the transition state), but above the optimal temperature, the enzyme begins to denature (tertiary structure unfolds, the active site is disrupted, and activity falls precipitously). Human enzymes are generally optimized for 37°C.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'In the serine protease catalytic mechanism, the histidine residue of the catalytic triad functions as:',choices:['A) The nucleophile that directly attacks the substrate peptide bond','B) A general acid-base catalyst that activates the serine nucleophile and then the water molecule','C) An electrostatic stabilizer of the positively charged tetrahedral intermediate','D) A metal ion coordinator that lowers the pKa of the catalytic serine'],answer:1,why:'In the serine protease mechanism, histidine acts as a general acid-base catalyst. In the acylation stage, histidine acts as a general BASE: it abstracts the proton from the serine hydroxyl (-OH) to generate the serine alkoxide (-O-), which is a far better nucleophile for attacking the carbonyl carbon of the substrate. In the deacylation stage, histidine acts as a general BASE again to activate the incoming water molecule, making it a better nucleophile to attack the acyl-enzyme intermediate. The aspartate residue of the triad positions and stabilizes the positively charged imidazolium form of histidine through a hydrogen bond, but it is histidine that does the proton shuttling. The serine (not histidine) is the actual nucleophile.'}]}],
 bottomLine:'Enzymes lower activation energy without changing equilibrium: they do not change Keq or delta-G, only the rate at which equilibrium is approached. The mechanism is transition-state stabilization, not lock-and-key substrate complementarity. Michaelis-Menten kinetics give us Km (the [S] at half-Vmax, a proxy for substrate affinity), Vmax (proportional to [E]total x kcat), and kcat (the turnover number). The Lineweaver-Burk plot linearizes the data: y-intercept = 1/Vmax, x-intercept = -1/Km, slope = Km/Vmax. Competitive inhibition (binds free enzyme, Km increases, Vmax unchanged, overcome by high [S]) differs mechanistically from uncompetitive inhibition (binds ES complex, both Km and Vmax decrease by same factor, parallel lines in L-B) and noncompetitive inhibition (binds E or ES equally, Vmax decreases, Km unchanged, lines intersect on x-axis in L-B). Irreversible inhibitors form covalent bonds (organophosphates on AChE, aspirin on COX, penicillin on transpeptidase) and require new enzyme synthesis for recovery. Allosteric enzymes show sigmoidal kinetics (Hill coefficient n > 1) and are regulated by effectors that shift the K0.5 left (activators) or right (inhibitors). Covalent modification by phosphorylation (reversible via phosphatases) and zymogen activation (irreversible proteolytic cleavage) provide additional regulatory layers with distinct timescales. The six enzyme classes (oxidoreductases, transferases, hydrolases, lyases, isomerases, ligases) allow mechanistic prediction of cofactor requirements and reaction chemistry. Serum enzymes are clinical windows into organ function: ALT/AST for hepatocellular injury, ALP/GGT for cholestasis, troponin/CK-MB for MI, lipase for pancreatitis. Master these frameworks and every enzyme you encounter in later chapters becomes a mechanistically predictable entity rather than a name to memorize.',
 nextHint:'Chapter 3, Carbohydrates, Glycolysis, and the TCA Cycle: every regulatory enzyme in glycolysis and the TCA cycle is an allosteric enzyme with the kinetic logic installed in this chapter. PFK-1, pyruvate kinase, isocitrate dehydrogenase: their regulation is the enzyme kinetics of Chapter 2 applied to specific molecular contexts.',
},
{
 n:3,
 title:'Carbohydrates, Glycolysis, and the TCA Cycle',
 subtitle:'From sugar to NADH: the central catabolic engine',
 tag:'Energy Metabolism',
 foundational:'Glucose is the cell\'s primary fuel. Glycolysis breaks it into pyruvate (net 2 ATP + 2 NADH); the TCA cycle oxidizes the acetyl group to CO2 harvesting 3 NADH + 1 FADH2 + 1 GTP per turn. The reduced coenzymes carry electrons to the ETC.',
 buildsOn:'Ch 2, enzyme regulation explains control of PFK-1 and PDC.',
 setsUp:'Ch 4, NADH and FADH2 feed the ETC.',
 objectives:['Classify monosaccharides by chain length, carbonyl type, and stereochemistry; identify reducing sugars and glycosidic bonds.','Trace all 10 steps of glycolysis, naming enzymes, substrates, products, and cofactors; calculate net ATP yield.','Explain allosteric and hormonal regulation of hexokinase/glucokinase, PFK-1/PFK-2, and pyruvate kinase.','Describe the pyruvate dehydrogenase complex: 5 cofactors, regulation, and clinical consequences of deficiency.','Trace all 8 steps of the TCA cycle; calculate yield per acetyl-CoA; identify rate-limiting and irreversible steps.','Define anaplerosis and give four examples of TCA intermediates used as biosynthetic precursors.','Connect thiamine deficiency to three enzyme complexes and two clinical syndromes.','Apply knowledge of pyruvate kinase deficiency, G6PD deficiency, and arsenic poisoning to clinical vignettes.'],
 opener:'Every sprint, every heartbeat, every thought depends on ATP produced from glucose. Glycolysis is the universal first step: 10 enzyme-catalyzed reactions that convert one glucose to two pyruvate, generating a net of 2 ATP and 2 NADH. No oxygen required. But glycolysis alone is a trickle; the real torrent comes from feeding pyruvate into the mitochondrion.\n\nOnce inside, pyruvate dehydrogenase strips the carboxyl group as CO2 and hands the two-carbon acetyl group to CoA. Acetyl-CoA enters the TCA cycle, where eight reactions spin off two CO2, one GTP, three NADH, and one FADH2 per turn. The cycle runs twice per glucose. The NADH and FADH2 produced here are not the end product, they are electron carriers destined for the respiratory chain. Understanding how the cell harvests and controls that electron flow is the foundation of bioenergetics.',
 pinnedDisc:{t:'SUBSTRATE-LEVEL vs OXIDATIVE PHOSPHORYLATION',x:'Substrate-level phosphorylation: direct transfer of phosphate from a high-energy substrate to ADP (phosphoglycerate kinase and pyruvate kinase in glycolysis; succinyl-CoA synthetase in TCA). Does not require oxygen or a membrane. Oxidative phosphorylation: ATP synthase uses the proton gradient generated by the ETC. Requires oxygen as the terminal electron acceptor. Roughly 90% of aerobic ATP comes from oxidative phosphorylation.'},
 sections:[{id:'3.1',num:'3.1',title:'3.1 Monosaccharide Structure and Stereochemistry',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Carbohydrates follow the formula (CH2O)n. A monosaccharide with an aldehyde carbonyl is an aldose; one with a ketone is a ketose. Chain length matters: trioses (3C), pentoses (5C), hexoses (6C). Glucose is an aldohexose; fructose is a ketohexose; ribose is an aldopentose.'},{t:'p',x:'Stereochemistry: the D/L designation is determined by the orientation of the OH on the highest-numbered chiral carbon (C5 in hexoses). In D-glucose the C5-OH points right in the Fischer projection. Nearly all biological sugars are D-configuration.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'Anomers vs Epimers',x:'Anomers differ only at the anomeric carbon (C1 of aldoses, C2 of fructose) formed when the ring closes: alpha-OH is axial (down in Haworth for glucose), beta-OH is equatorial (up). Beta-D-glucose is the dominant form in solution (~64%) and the form released by glycogen phosphorylase.\n\nEpimers differ at a single non-anomeric carbon. Galactose is the C4-epimer of glucose (changes C4-OH from equatorial to axial). Mannose is the C2-epimer of glucose.'},{t:'p',x:'Ring closure creates a hemiacetal (aldoses) or hemiketal (ketoses). The anomeric carbon is electrophilic. A free anomeric carbon makes the sugar a reducing sugar: it can reduce Cu2+ (Benedict\'s, Fehling\'s) because the ring can open to expose the aldehyde. Glucose, galactose, fructose, maltose, and lactose are reducing sugars. Sucrose is not: both anomeric carbons are locked in the glycosidic bond.'},{t:'box',kind:'why',label:'Why the anomeric carbon matters clinically',x:'Glycosidic bond type (alpha vs beta) determines digestibility. Humans have alpha-amylase and alpha-glucosidases for starch (alpha-1,4 and alpha-1,6 linkages). We lack beta-glucosidase for cellulose (beta-1,4 linkages). Lactase deficiency (loss of beta-galactosidase) leaves lactose undigested, causing osmotic diarrhea and fermentation gas.'},{t:'p',x:'Disaccharides: maltose = alpha-1,4 (glucose-glucose, from starch digestion), sucrose = alpha-1,2 (glucose-fructose, from plants, non-reducing), lactose = beta-1,4 (galactose-glucose, from milk).\n\nPolysaccharides: glycogen (animal energy storage) has alpha-1,4 backbone with alpha-1,6 branches every 8-12 residues. Starch has two forms: amylose (alpha-1,4 only) and amylopectin (alpha-1,4 with alpha-1,6 branches, less frequent than glycogen). Cellulose has beta-1,4 linkages forming straight hydrogen-bonded sheets for structural rigidity.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'MCAT Shortcut: Reducing Sugar Test',x:'Reducing sugar = free anomeric carbon = open-chain aldehyde or ketone can form. Sucrose fails because BOTH anomeric carbons are tied up. On the MCAT: "non-reducing disaccharide" almost always = sucrose.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'Galactose is best described as the _____ of glucose.',choices:['A) C4 epimer','B) C1 anomer','C) L-isomer','D) C2 epimer'],answer:0,why:'Galactose differs from glucose only at C4 (axial vs equatorial OH). That is the definition of a C4 epimer. Anomers differ only at the anomeric carbon (C1), not C4.'},{stem:'Which disaccharide is non-reducing?',choices:['A) Maltose','B) Lactose','C) Sucrose','D) Cellobiose'],answer:2,why:'Sucrose links glucose C1 (alpha) to fructose C2 (beta), locking both anomeric carbons. No free anomeric carbon, so sucrose cannot open to an aldehyde or reduce Cu2+.'}]},{id:'3.2',num:'3.2',title:'3.2 Glycolysis: Investment Phase (Steps 1-5)',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Glycolysis occurs entirely in the cytoplasm. Net equation: glucose + 2 NAD+ + 2 ADP + 2 Pi -> 2 pyruvate + 2 NADH + 2 ATP + 2 H2O.\n\nThe investment phase spends 2 ATP to trap glucose as fructose-1,6-bisphosphate and split it into two triose phosphates.'},{t:'formula',x:'Step 1: Glucose + ATP -> Glucose-6-phosphate + ADP  [Hexokinase / Glucokinase, irreversible]'},{t:'formula',x:'Step 2: Glucose-6-phosphate <-> Fructose-6-phosphate  [Phosphoglucose isomerase, reversible]'},{t:'formula',x:'Step 3: Fructose-6-phosphate + ATP -> Fructose-1,6-bisphosphate + ADP  [PFK-1, irreversible, RATE-LIMITING]'},{t:'formula',x:'Step 4: Fructose-1,6-bisphosphate <-> DHAP + Glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate  [Aldolase, reversible]'},{t:'formula',x:'Step 5: DHAP <-> Glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate  [Triose phosphate isomerase, reversible]'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'Hexokinase vs Glucokinase',x:'Hexokinase (Types I-III): Km ~0.1 mM (high affinity), inhibited by its product G6P (product inhibition), Vmax is low, present in all tissues. Keeps glycolysis running at low glucose.\n\nGlucokinase (Hexokinase IV): Km ~10 mM (low affinity), sigmoidal kinetics (cooperative), NOT inhibited by G6P, high Vmax, found only in liver and pancreatic beta-cells. Acts as a glucose sensor: only active when blood glucose is elevated, enabling the liver to clear the post-meal glucose surge and the beta-cell to trigger insulin secretion.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'PFK-1 Allosteric Regulation (The Master Switch)',x:'PFK-1 is the committed, rate-limiting step of glycolysis. Activated by: AMP (energy low), ADP (energy low), fructose-2,6-bisphosphate (F-2,6-BP, the most potent activator). Inhibited by: ATP (high energy, binds allosteric site, not active site), citrate (TCA is full), H+ (acidosis signals anaerobic overload).\n\nF-2,6-BP is produced by PFK-2 (the kinase activity of the bifunctional enzyme PFK-2/FBPase-2). Insulin dephosphorylates PFK-2, activating the kinase domain, raising F-2,6-BP, activating PFK-1 (glycolysis up). Glucagon phosphorylates PFK-2, activating FBPase-2, lowering F-2,6-BP, inhibiting PFK-1 (glycolysis down). Remember: F-2,6-BP is purely regulatory and is NOT a glycolytic intermediate; it does not become F-1,6-BP.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'PFK-1 vs PFK-2: a critical distinction',x:'PFK-1 (phosphofructokinase-1): the actual glycolytic enzyme that converts F-6-P to F-1,6-BP using ATP. This is step 3.\n\nPFK-2 (phosphofructokinase-2): the kinase half of the bifunctional PFK-2/FBPase-2 enzyme. It makes F-2,6-BP from F-6-P. F-2,6-BP is an allosteric activator of PFK-1, not a substrate for it. Do not confuse the two enzymes or the two bisphosphates on the MCAT.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A patient is fasted. Glucagon is elevated. What happens to F-2,6-BP levels in the liver?',choices:['A) Increases, stimulating glycolysis','B) Decreases, inhibiting glycolysis','C) Increases, stimulating gluconeogenesis','D) Decreases, inhibiting gluconeogenesis'],answer:1,why:'Glucagon phosphorylates PFK-2/FBPase-2, activating the FBPase-2 domain and inactivating the PFK-2 domain. F-2,6-BP levels fall. Since F-2,6-BP is the main activator of PFK-1, glycolysis is inhibited and gluconeogenesis is favored.'},{stem:'Which property uniquely distinguishes glucokinase from hexokinase?',choices:['A) Glucokinase is inhibited by glucose-6-phosphate','B) Glucokinase has a lower Km for glucose','C) Glucokinase shows cooperative (sigmoidal) kinetics and is not inhibited by G6P','D) Glucokinase is found in all tissues'],answer:2,why:'Glucokinase (HK IV) has a high Km (~10 mM), sigmoidal kinetics, and is not product-inhibited by G6P. Hexokinase I-III have low Km, hyperbolic kinetics, and are inhibited by G6P.'}]},{id:'3.3',num:'3.3',title:'3.3 Glycolysis: Payoff Phase (Steps 6-10)',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'The payoff phase starts with two molecules of glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate (G3P). Each goes through steps 6-10, so every yield number is doubled per original glucose.'},{t:'formula',x:'Step 6: G3P + NAD+ + Pi -> 1,3-bisphosphoglycerate (1,3-BPG) + NADH  [Glyceraldehyde-3-P dehydrogenase, requires NAD+]'},{t:'formula',x:'Step 7: 1,3-BPG + ADP -> 3-phosphoglycerate (3-PG) + ATP  [Phosphoglycerate kinase, substrate-level phosphorylation, reversible]'},{t:'formula',x:'Step 8: 3-PG <-> 2-phosphoglycerate (2-PG)  [Phosphoglycerate mutase, reversible]'},{t:'formula',x:'Step 9: 2-PG <-> Phosphoenolpyruvate (PEP) + H2O  [Enolase, requires Mg2+, inhibited by fluoride]'},{t:'formula',x:'Step 10: PEP + ADP -> Pyruvate + ATP  [Pyruvate kinase, irreversible, substrate-level phosphorylation]'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'Three Irreversible Steps of Glycolysis',x:'1. Hexokinase/Glucokinase (Step 1): traps glucose in the cell. Bypassed in gluconeogenesis by glucose-6-phosphatase (ER, liver/kidney only).\n2. PFK-1 (Step 3): committed, rate-limiting step. Bypassed by fructose-1,6-bisphosphatase (FBPase-1) in gluconeogenesis.\n3. Pyruvate Kinase (Step 10): generates ATP from PEP. Bypassed in gluconeogenesis by two steps: pyruvate carboxylase (pyruvate -> OAA) then PEPCK (OAA -> PEP).\n\nThese three steps are the regulatory checkpoints. All three are bypassed in gluconeogenesis.'},{t:'p',x:'Pyruvate kinase regulation: activated by fructose-1,6-bisphosphate (feedforward activation, meaning when PFK-1 is active the next committed step is pre-activated). Inhibited by ATP, alanine (signals amino acid abundance), and glucagon-mediated phosphorylation (liver PK only).'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'2,3-BPG: A Glycolytic Side Branch',x:'2,3-bisphosphoglycerate is made in red blood cells from 1,3-BPG by bisphosphoglycerate mutase (Rapoport-Luebering shunt). It stabilizes deoxyhemoglobin, right-shifting the O2 dissociation curve (decreases O2 affinity). Important: this shunt bypasses step 7 (PGK), so no ATP is generated for that molecule of 1,3-BPG.\n\nPyruvate kinase deficiency elevates 2,3-BPG (compensatory) and actually REDUCES symptoms of anemia somewhat by improving O2 delivery to tissues.'},{t:'p',x:'Net yield per glucose in glycolysis: -2 ATP (steps 1 and 3) + 4 ATP (steps 7 and 10, each x2) = net 2 ATP. Also 2 NADH produced at step 6 (x2). The fate of cytoplasmic NADH depends on oxygen availability.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'Which enzyme catalyzes substrate-level phosphorylation immediately after the dehydrogenase step in glycolysis?',choices:['A) Pyruvate kinase','B) Phosphoglycerate kinase','C) Phosphoglycerate mutase','D) Enolase'],answer:1,why:'Glyceraldehyde-3-P dehydrogenase (step 6) makes 1,3-BPG. Phosphoglycerate kinase (step 7) transfers the acyl-phosphate to ADP, generating ATP by substrate-level phosphorylation. Pyruvate kinase does the same at step 10.'},{stem:'Fluoride inhibits enolase (step 9). Which substrate would accumulate?',choices:['A) Fructose-1,6-bisphosphate','B) Phosphoenolpyruvate','C) 2-phosphoglycerate','D) 1,3-bisphosphoglycerate'],answer:2,why:'Enolase converts 2-phosphoglycerate to PEP. Blocking enolase causes 2-phosphoglycerate to accumulate immediately upstream. This is why fluoride (NaF) is added to blood collection tubes to inhibit glycolysis and preserve glucose.'}]},{id:'3.4',num:'3.4',title:'3.4 Pyruvate Fate: Aerobic Entry and Anaerobic Fermentation',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Pyruvate sits at a metabolic crossroads. Under aerobic conditions it enters the mitochondrion and is oxidatively decarboxylated by the pyruvate dehydrogenase complex (PDC). Under anaerobic conditions it accepts electrons from NADH and is reduced to lactate by lactate dehydrogenase (LDH).'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'Pyruvate Dehydrogenase Complex: 5 Cofactors',x:'PDC contains three catalytic subunits (E1, E2, E3) and two regulatory subunits (PDK and PDP).\n\nCofactors, in reaction order:\n1. E1 (pyruvate decarboxylase): TPP (thiamine pyrophosphate, from vitamin B1). Decarboxylates pyruvate, transfers hydroxyethyl group.\n2. E2 (dihydrolipoyl transacetylase): Lipoic acid (covalent, swinging arm). Transfers acetyl group; then CoA joins to release acetyl-CoA.\n3. E2: CoA-SH. Accepts the acetyl group to form acetyl-CoA.\n4. E3 (dihydrolipoyl dehydrogenase): FAD. Reoxidizes lipoic acid.\n5. E3: NAD+. Final electron acceptor, generating NADH.\n\nMnemonic: "Tender Loving Care For Nancy" = TPP, Lipoate, CoA, FAD, NAD+.\n\nOverall: pyruvate + CoA + NAD+ -> acetyl-CoA + CO2 + NADH.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'PDC Regulation',x:'Inhibited (products and high-energy signal): acetyl-CoA, NADH, ATP. These activate PDK, which phosphorylates and inactivates E1.\n\nActivated (substrates and low-energy signal): CoA, NAD+, ADP, pyruvate, Ca2+. Ca2+ activates PDP (phosphatase), dephosphorylating E1 back to active form.\n\nDephosphorylated E1 = ACTIVE. Phosphorylated E1 = INACTIVE.\n\nClinical pearl: insulin activates PDC (via PDP). Fasting/glucagon inactivates it.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'PDC Deficiency (PDHA1 Mutation)',x:'X-linked dominant (PDHA1 gene on Xp22.3). Pyruvate cannot be converted to acetyl-CoA, so it is diverted to lactate (by LDH) and alanine (by ALT). Lab findings: elevated lactate AND pyruvate (L/P ratio normal or mildly elevated, ~15-20), elevated alanine, metabolic acidosis.\n\nKey imaging: agenesis or hypoplasia of the corpus callosum (the brain cannot make myelin because of acetyl-CoA shortage for fatty acid synthesis).\n\nTreatment: ketogenic diet (provides ketone bodies as an alternative acetyl-CoA source for the brain, bypassing the PDC block).\n\nDistinguish from: pyruvate carboxylase deficiency (L/P ratio markedly elevated, >25, OAA deficiency, hyperammonemia).'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'Thiamine (B1) Deficiency: Three Enzymes Blocked',x:'Thiamine pyrophosphate (TPP) is required by three mitochondrial enzyme complexes:\n1. Pyruvate dehydrogenase complex (PDC): pyruvate -> acetyl-CoA\n2. Alpha-ketoglutarate dehydrogenase (alpha-KG DH): alpha-KG -> succinyl-CoA (TCA step 4)\n3. Branched-chain alpha-keto acid dehydrogenase (BCKDH): catabolism of Val, Leu, Ile\n\nAll three share the same E1/E2/E3 architecture with TPP at E1.\n\nClinical syndromes:\nWernicke encephalopathy (acute): ophthalmoplegia (CN VI palsy), ataxia (cerebellar), confusion. Classic triad. MRI: symmetric signal in mammillary bodies, medial thalami, periaqueductal gray.\nKorsakoff syndrome (chronic): anterograde amnesia (cannot form new memories), confabulation, retrograde amnesia.\n\nCRITICAL: Give thiamine BEFORE glucose. Giving glucose first to a thiamine-deficient patient can precipitate Wernicke by consuming the last of the thiamine reserves.'},{t:'p',x:'Anaerobic fate of pyruvate: Lactate dehydrogenase (LDH) reduces pyruvate to lactate using NADH, regenerating NAD+. This NAD+ regeneration is the whole point: without it, glycolysis stops because step 6 (G3P dehydrogenase) requires NAD+.\n\nNet anaerobic yield per glucose: 2 ATP only. No net NADH (consumed by LDH). Lactate is not a waste product. The liver reconverts lactate to glucose (Cori cycle, gluconeogenesis), at a cost of 6 ATP per glucose regenerated. Net energy debt: 6 ATP spent by liver to rescue 2 ATP made by muscle = net 4 ATP cost.'},{t:'box',kind:'why',label:'Cori Cycle: Interorgan Cooperation',x:'Exercising muscle lacks sufficient O2, so it runs anaerobic glycolysis and exports lactate into the blood. The liver takes up that lactate, uses 6 ATP (from beta-oxidation of fatty acids) to run gluconeogenesis, and exports fresh glucose back to muscle. The muscle gets glucose, the liver handles the lactate debt. This cycle keeps muscle glycolysis going beyond what O2 permits.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A patient with PDC deficiency presents with lactic acidosis. Which vitamin is most closely implicated in PDC function?',choices:['A) Niacin (B3)','B) Riboflavin (B2)','C) Thiamine (B1)','D) Pyridoxine (B6)'],answer:2,why:'E1 of PDC requires TPP (thiamine pyrophosphate, from B1). While PDC deficiency is usually genetic (PDHA1), thiamine deficiency also blocks PDC by depriving E1 of its cofactor. B3 (NAD+) and B2 (FAD) are also PDC cofactors but the classic test association is B1.'},{stem:'A malnourished patient is given IV dextrose before thiamine replacement. Which clinical event is most likely to be precipitated?',choices:['A) Korsakoff amnesia','B) Wernicke encephalopathy','C) Pellagra','D) Megaloblastic anemia'],answer:1,why:'Giving glucose to a thiamine-deficient patient rapidly consumes the remaining TPP stores (for PDC and alpha-KG DH). This precipitates acute Wernicke encephalopathy: ophthalmoplegia, ataxia, confusion, with mammillary body lesions on MRI. Thiamine must always precede glucose (the "Banana Bag" protocol).'}]},{id:'3.5',num:'3.5',title:'3.5 TCA Cycle: Steps 1-4 (Entry and First Oxidations)',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'The TCA cycle (tricarboxylic acid cycle, Krebs cycle, citric acid cycle) is the central hub of aerobic metabolism. Acetyl-CoA (2C) condenses with oxaloacetate (4C) to form citrate (6C). Two rounds of oxidative decarboxylation release 2 CO2, regenerating the 4C acceptor OAA. Per turn: 3 NADH, 1 FADH2, 1 GTP, 2 CO2.'},{t:'formula',x:'Net TCA equation (per acetyl-CoA): Acetyl-CoA + 3 NAD+ + FAD + GDP + Pi + 2 H2O -> 2 CO2 + 3 NADH + FADH2 + GTP + CoA'},{t:'formula',x:'Step 1: Acetyl-CoA + OAA -> Citrate + CoA  [Citrate synthase, irreversible, inhibited by ATP/NADH/citrate, activated by ADP]'},{t:'formula',x:'Step 2: Citrate <-> Isocitrate  [Aconitase, reversible, requires Fe-S, inhibited by fluorocitrate/aconitase poison fluoroacetate]'},{t:'formula',x:'Step 3: Isocitrate + NAD+ -> Alpha-ketoglutarate + CO2 + NADH  [Isocitrate dehydrogenase, irreversible, RATE-LIMITING, inhibited by ATP/NADH, activated by ADP/NAD+/Ca2+]'},{t:'formula',x:'Step 4: Alpha-ketoglutarate + NAD+ + CoA -> Succinyl-CoA + CO2 + NADH  [Alpha-KG dehydrogenase, irreversible, same 5 cofactors as PDC: TPP/lipoate/CoA/FAD/NAD+, inhibited by succinyl-CoA/NADH]'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'Citrate Synthase: Gatekeeper of the TCA Cycle',x:'Citrate synthase is strongly inhibited by ATP, NADH, and citrate (product). When the cell is energy-rich and the cycle is full, entry of acetyl-CoA is throttled. ADP activates it. This ensures the TCA cycle runs in proportion to the cell\'s energy needs.\n\nCitrate that accumulates under high-energy conditions is exported to the cytoplasm through the citrate shuttle (tricarboxylate transporter), where ATP-citrate lyase cleaves it back to OAA and acetyl-CoA for fatty acid synthesis. This is how excess carbohydrate carbon is directed to fat.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'Alpha-KG Dehydrogenase: The Thiamine-Dependent TCA Step',x:'Alpha-KG DH has the exact same cofactor and subunit architecture as PDC (E1-TPP, E2-lipoate, E3-FAD/NAD+). Thiamine deficiency blocks both PDC and alpha-KG DH simultaneously, reducing acetyl-CoA entry and blocking the cycle at step 4.\n\nAlso blocked by arsenic: arsenite inactivates the lipoic acid prosthetic group (forms a stable complex with the two sulfhydryl groups of reduced lipoate). This blocks both alpha-KG DH and PDC. Clinical features of arsenic poisoning: lactic acidosis (PDC block), peripheral neuropathy, Mees\' lines on fingernails (transverse white bands), GI symptoms, garlic odor. Treatment: dimercaprol (BAL) chelates arsenite, freeing lipoic acid.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'Which TCA cycle enzyme is rate-limiting and most analogous in structure to the pyruvate dehydrogenase complex?',choices:['A) Citrate synthase','B) Isocitrate dehydrogenase','C) Alpha-ketoglutarate dehydrogenase','D) Succinate dehydrogenase'],answer:1,why:'Isocitrate dehydrogenase (step 3) is the rate-limiting step of the TCA cycle. Alpha-KG DH (step 4) is the enzyme structurally analogous to PDC (same E1/E2/E3 architecture, same 5 cofactors), but it is not rate-limiting. Rate-limiting = isocitrate DH.'},{stem:'Arsenic poisoning selectively inactivates lipoic acid-containing complexes. Which two enzyme complexes are directly impaired?',choices:['A) PDC and alpha-KG dehydrogenase','B) PDC and succinate dehydrogenase','C) Isocitrate DH and citrate synthase','D) Alpha-KG DH and citrate synthase'],answer:0,why:'Arsenite binds the dithiol of reduced lipoic acid (the E2 swinging arm). Both PDC (E2: dihydrolipoyl transacetylase) and alpha-KG DH (E2: dihydrolipoyl transsuccinylase) use lipoic acid. Succinate DH uses FAD and FeS, not lipoic acid.'}]},{id:'3.6',num:'3.6',title:'3.6 TCA Cycle: Steps 5-8 (Substrate-Level Phosphorylation and Regeneration of OAA)',blocks:[{t:'formula',x:'Step 5: Succinyl-CoA + GDP + Pi -> Succinate + GTP + CoA  [Succinyl-CoA synthetase, reversible, SUBSTRATE-LEVEL PHOSPHORYLATION; in heart uses ADP -> ATP directly]'},{t:'formula',x:'Step 6: Succinate + FAD -> Fumarate + FADH2  [Succinate dehydrogenase (SDH), anchored in inner mitochondrial membrane as Complex II of ETC, inhibited by malonate (competitive)]'},{t:'formula',x:'Step 7: Fumarate + H2O -> Malate  [Fumarase (fumarate hydratase), reversible, mutations cause HLRCC and SDH-negative paraganglioma, stereospecific: produces only L-malate]'},{t:'formula',x:'Step 8: Malate + NAD+ -> OAA + NADH  [Malate dehydrogenase, thermodynamically unfavorable (Keq favors malate), driven forward by citrate synthase consuming OAA in step 1]'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'Succinate Dehydrogenase: The Bridge Between TCA and ETC',x:'SDH is the only TCA enzyme embedded in the inner mitochondrial membrane and also functions as Complex II of the electron transport chain. It oxidizes succinate to fumarate using FAD (not NAD+), and passes the electrons to CoQ (ubiquinone).\n\nBecause FADH2 enters at CoQ (bypassing Complex I), it generates less ATP per oxidation than NADH (1.5 ATP vs 2.5 ATP).\n\nSDH is inhibited competitively by malonate (a succinate analog), a classic biochemistry teaching example of competitive inhibition.\n\nSDH is a tumor suppressor: loss-of-function mutations in SDH subunits (SDHA, B, C, D) cause accumulation of succinate, which inhibits alpha-KG-dependent dioxygenases (HIF prolyl hydroxylases, TETs, KDMs), leading to hypermethylation and HIF activation. Clinical: hereditary paraganglioma-pheochromocytoma (SDH mutations) and Carney-Stratakis syndrome (SDHA mutations).'},{t:'box',kind:'why',label:'Why Step 8 (Malate DH) Is Thermodynamically Unfavorable',x:'The standard free energy of malate -> OAA is positive (about +29 kJ/mol). Thermodynamically the reaction favors malate. Yet the cycle runs continuously. This is because OAA is immediately consumed by citrate synthase (step 1, highly exergonic, about -32 kJ/mol). Le Chatelier\'s principle: removing the product pulls the equilibrium forward. This coupling is a beautiful example of how irreversible reactions can drive otherwise unfavorable ones.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'TCA Cycle Yield Summary',x:'Per acetyl-CoA (one turn):\n- Step 3: 1 NADH (isocitrate DH)\n- Step 4: 1 NADH (alpha-KG DH)\n- Step 5: 1 GTP (succinyl-CoA synthetase)\n- Step 6: 1 FADH2 (SDH)\n- Step 8: 1 NADH (malate DH)\nTotal: 3 NADH + 1 FADH2 + 1 GTP + 2 CO2\n\nPer glucose (2 acetyl-CoA, 2 turns): 6 NADH + 2 FADH2 + 2 GTP + 4 CO2\n\nNote: the 2 NADH from PDC (pyruvate -> acetyl-CoA) are not TCA but are often counted with the mitochondrial total.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A researcher adds malonate to isolated mitochondria. Which substrate will accumulate?',choices:['A) Fumarate','B) Succinyl-CoA','C) Succinate','D) Malate'],answer:2,why:'Malonate is a competitive inhibitor of succinate dehydrogenase. Blocking SDH prevents oxidation of succinate to fumarate, so succinate accumulates. This is the classic experiment demonstrating competitive inhibition (adding excess succinate reverses the malonate block).'},{stem:'Which step of the TCA cycle produces GTP by substrate-level phosphorylation?',choices:['A) Step 3 (Isocitrate DH)','B) Step 5 (Succinyl-CoA synthetase)','C) Step 6 (Succinate DH)','D) Step 8 (Malate DH)'],answer:1,why:'Succinyl-CoA synthetase (step 5) cleaves the thioester bond of succinyl-CoA, releasing enough energy to directly phosphorylate GDP to GTP (substrate-level phosphorylation). In cardiac muscle, the ATP-forming isoform is dominant.'}]},{id:'3.7',num:'3.7',title:'3.7 Anaplerosis and TCA Intermediates as Biosynthetic Precursors',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'The TCA cycle is not only catabolic: it donates intermediates for biosynthesis. When intermediates leave the cycle (cataplerosis), they must be replenished to keep the cycle running. Reactions that replenish TCA intermediates are called anaplerotic ("filling up").'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'Four Key Anaplerotic/Cataplerotic Routes',x:'1. Pyruvate carboxylase: pyruvate + CO2 + ATP -> OAA. Biotin-dependent. Activated by acetyl-CoA. Located in mitochondria (liver, kidney, brain). Purpose: replenishes OAA when the cycle is depleted. Also the first step of gluconeogenesis from pyruvate. High acetyl-CoA (fasting, beta-oxidation) signals the need to ramp up OAA.\n\n2. OAA -> Aspartate (transamination): OAA accepts the amino group from glutamate via aspartate aminotransferase (AST). Aspartate donates nitrogen in the urea cycle (step 2) and purine synthesis.\n\n3. Alpha-ketoglutarate <-> Glutamate: glutamate dehydrogenase or transaminases interconvert these. Excess nitrogen enters the cycle as glutamate; excess carbon can exit as alpha-KG.\n\n4. Succinyl-CoA from odd-chain fatty acids and branched-chain amino acids: propionyl-CoA -> methylmalonyl-CoA -> succinyl-CoA (requires B12). Also: succinyl-CoA is the starting material for heme synthesis (ALAS enzyme).'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'Biosynthetic Precursors from TCA Intermediates',x:'Citrate: exported to cytoplasm via the citrate shuttle. ATP-citrate lyase cleaves it to OAA + acetyl-CoA. Cytoplasmic acetyl-CoA is the building block for fatty acid synthesis and cholesterol synthesis. This explains why excess dietary carbohydrate leads to fat accumulation.\n\nAlpha-ketoglutarate: transaminated to glutamate (and then to glutamine, proline, arginine). Glutamate is the major donor in most transamination reactions.\n\nSuccinyl-CoA: substrate for ALA synthase (ALAS), the committed step of heme biosynthesis. Lead poisoning and isoniazid (pyridoxine depletion) block heme synthesis downstream.\n\nOAA: can become glucose (gluconeogenesis via PEPCK) or aspartate (transamination). The liver uses OAA flux to sense the ratio of gluconeogenic substrate to TCA demand.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'Pyruvate Carboxylase Deficiency vs PDC Deficiency',x:'Both present with lactic acidosis in infancy. Key distinction:\n\nPDC deficiency: L/P ratio normal or low (~15-20). Pyruvate accumulates and is converted to both lactate and alanine. Alanine elevated. Corpus callosum hypoplasia. X-linked.\n\nPyruvate carboxylase (PC) deficiency: L/P ratio markedly elevated (>25). Pyruvate cannot enter gluconeogenesis (no OAA), accumulates and floods into lactate. OAA shortage also impairs the malate-aspartate shuttle and the urea cycle (aspartate shortage). Hyperammonemia is a distinguishing feature.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A high-fat diet (elevated acetyl-CoA, depleted OAA) activates which anaplerotic enzyme to replenish the TCA cycle?',choices:['A) Pyruvate kinase','B) Pyruvate carboxylase','C) Citrate synthase','D) Isocitrate dehydrogenase'],answer:1,why:'Pyruvate carboxylase is allosterically activated by acetyl-CoA. When beta-oxidation is high (high acetyl-CoA), this enzyme is switched on to convert pyruvate to OAA, replenishing the TCA cycle acceptor so acetyl-CoA can enter. This is the classic anaplerotic response to fasting/fat oxidation.'},{stem:'Heme synthesis begins with which TCA intermediate and requires which vitamin-derived cofactor at the ALAS step?',choices:['A) Succinyl-CoA; pyridoxal phosphate (B6)','B) Alpha-KG; thiamine (B1)','C) Citrate; biotin','D) OAA; pyridoxal phosphate (B6)'],answer:0,why:'ALA synthase (ALAS) condenses succinyl-CoA with glycine to form delta-aminolevulinate (ALA), the committed step of heme biosynthesis. ALAS requires pyridoxal phosphate (PLP, from B6) as cofactor. Lead and isoniazid interfere downstream.'}]},{id:'3.8',num:'3.8',title:'3.8 Clinical Correlations: PK Deficiency, G6PD Deficiency, and Warburg Effect',blocks:[{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'Pyruvate Kinase (PK) Deficiency',x:'Inheritance: autosomal recessive (PKLR gene, chromosome 1). Affects RBCs only (other tissues use PKM2).\n\nPathophysiology: step 10 of glycolysis blocked. ATP production fails. RBCs depend entirely on glycolysis for ATP (no mitochondria). ATP depletion causes loss of ion pump function, cell swelling, and hemolysis.\n\nBlood smear: echinocytes (crenated, spiculated RBCs). NOT spherocytes (that is hereditary spherocytosis or ABO mismatch).\n\n2,3-BPG: markedly elevated (1,3-BPG accumulates upstream of the PK block and is shunted to 2,3-BPG by bisphosphoglycerate mutase). Elevated 2,3-BPG right-shifts the O2 dissociation curve, reducing hemoglobin O2 affinity and actually IMPROVING tissue O2 delivery. This partially offsets the anemia.\n\nLabs: hemolytic anemia, elevated indirect bilirubin, elevated LDH, reticulocytosis. Coombs negative (non-immune hemolysis).'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'G6PD Deficiency: Glycolysis-Adjacent, ETC-Relevant',x:'Inheritance: X-linked recessive. Most common enzyme deficiency worldwide (~400 million affected). Highest prevalence in malaria-endemic regions (confers protection against P. falciparum).\n\nPathophysiology: G6PD catalyzes the first step of the pentose phosphate pathway (PPP): glucose-6-phosphate + NADP+ -> 6-phosphogluconolactone + NADPH. RBCs require NADPH to regenerate reduced glutathione (GSH), which neutralizes oxidative stress (H2O2). Without G6PD, oxidative stress oxidizes hemoglobin to methemoglobin and then to denatured Heinz bodies. Splenic macrophages chew out Heinz bodies, creating bite cells (blister cells).\n\nTriggers: infections, oxidant drugs (dapsone, primaquine, nitrofurantoin, rasburicase), fava beans. Neonatal jaundice in severely deficient neonates.\n\nBlood smear: Heinz bodies (supravital stain required: crystal violet), bite cells.\n\nDistinguish from PK deficiency: G6PD = Heinz bodies + bite cells; PK = echinocytes.'},{t:'box',kind:'why',label:'Warburg Effect: Cancer and Aerobic Glycolysis',x:'Otto Warburg (1924): cancer cells preferentially use glycolysis even in the presence of oxygen ("aerobic glycolysis"). They produce 18x more lactate than normal cells under aerobic conditions.\n\nWhy? Not because of mitochondrial dysfunction (most cancer mitochondria work). Rather, aerobic glycolysis provides: (1) rapid ATP, (2) biosynthetic precursors (ribose-5-P via PPP, acetyl-CoA for lipids, amino acids from alpha-KG), (3) NAD+ regeneration via LDH.\n\nClinical application: PET scanning. Tumors take up 18F-labeled fluorodeoxyglucose (18F-FDG) avidly because glucose transporters (GLUT1) and hexokinase are upregulated. FDG is phosphorylated by hexokinase but cannot proceed through glycolysis (no 2-OH group), trapping it in the cell. The accumulation is detected by positron emission.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'SDH and Fumarase Mutations: TCA Cycle Tumor Suppressors',x:'SDH (succinate dehydrogenase, Complex II): loss-of-function mutations cause accumulation of succinate. Succinate inhibits prolyl hydroxylases (PHDs) that normally hydroxylate HIF-1alpha for VHL-mediated degradation. Result: HIF-1alpha stabilized (pseudohypoxia), VEGF up, angiogenesis. Clinical: hereditary paraganglioma/pheochromocytoma (SDHB mutations = aggressive, metastatic; SDHD = head/neck). Also Carney-Stratakis syndrome (paraganglioma + GIST).\n\nFumarase (fumarate hydratase, FH): loss-of-function mutations accumulate fumarate. Fumarate is also an oncometabolite, inhibiting PHDs. Clinical: hereditary leiomyomatosis and renal cell carcinoma (HLRCC). Patients develop uterine leiomyomas and aggressive type 2 papillary RCC. Also severe fumarase deficiency (homozygous): infantile encephalopathy.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A 4-year-old boy has episodic hemolytic anemia triggered by eating fava beans. Blood smear shows bite cells. Which pathway is primarily deficient?',choices:['A) Glycolysis (pyruvate kinase deficiency)','B) Pentose phosphate pathway (G6PD deficiency)','C) TCA cycle (fumarase deficiency)','D) Beta-oxidation (MCAD deficiency)'],answer:1,why:'Fava beans contain oxidants (vicine, convicine) that trigger hemolysis in G6PD-deficient patients. Bite cells result from splenic removal of Heinz body-containing RBCs. G6PD is the first enzyme of the pentose phosphate pathway, generating NADPH for glutathione reduction. PK deficiency causes echinocytes, not bite cells.'},{stem:'PET scanning detects tumors using 18F-FDG. Why does FDG accumulate specifically in tumor cells?',choices:['A) Tumor mitochondria actively import FDG for oxidative phosphorylation','B) FDG is phosphorylated by hexokinase but cannot be further metabolized, trapping it in cells with high glycolytic activity','C) FDG is converted to NADH by glycolysis enzymes in tumor cells','D) FDG is stored as glycogen in tumor cells, where glycogen synthase is upregulated'],answer:1,why:'Tumors overexpress GLUT1 and hexokinase. FDG enters via GLUT1 and is phosphorylated to FDG-6-phosphate by hexokinase. Without the 2-OH group, FDG-6-phosphate cannot be isomerized by phosphoglucose isomerase and is metabolically trapped. The Warburg effect ensures high GLUT1/hexokinase expression makes the signal tumour-specific.'}]},{id:'3.9',num:'3.9',title:'3.9 Integrated Regulation and Metabolic Context',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Glycolysis and the TCA cycle are regulated at multiple levels to match ATP production to demand. The overarching logic: when [ATP]/[AMP] is high (energy replete), slow down catabolism; when [AMP] is high (energy depleted), accelerate it.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'Coordinate Regulation Across Glycolysis and TCA',x:'Key effectors and their targets:\n- AMP/ADP activates: PFK-1, isocitrate DH, citrate synthase. All three speed up under low energy.\n- ATP inhibits: PFK-1, citrate synthase, isocitrate DH, pyruvate kinase. All four slow down when ATP is abundant.\n- NADH inhibits: PDC (via PDK), alpha-KG DH, isocitrate DH, citrate synthase. High NADH signals that the ETC is backed up.\n- Acetyl-CoA: inhibits PDC (activates PDK), activates pyruvate carboxylase. Signals substrate abundance.\n- Ca2+: activates PDC (via PDP), activates isocitrate DH, activates alpha-KG DH. Muscle contraction triggers ATP demand; Ca2+ is the signal that links excitation to metabolism.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Total ATP Yield from One Glucose (Complete Oxidation)',x:'Glycolysis (cytoplasm):\n- 2 ATP (net, substrate-level)\n- 2 NADH (cytoplasmic; via malate-aspartate shuttle -> 2 x 2.5 = 5 ATP; via G3P shuttle -> 2 x 1.5 = 3 ATP)\n\nPDC (2 x pyruvate -> 2 acetyl-CoA):\n- 2 NADH (mitochondrial) -> 2 x 2.5 = 5 ATP\n\nTCA cycle (2 turns):\n- 6 NADH -> 6 x 2.5 = 15 ATP\n- 2 FADH2 -> 2 x 1.5 = 3 ATP\n- 2 GTP = 2 ATP\n\nTotal (with MAS): 2 + 5 + 5 + 15 + 3 + 2 = 32 ATP\nTotal (with G3P shuttle): 2 + 3 + 5 + 15 + 3 + 2 = 30 ATP\n\nThe textbook "36-38" figure is outdated. Modern P/O ratios (NADH = 2.5, FADH2 = 1.5) give 30-32 ATP.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'Pentose Phosphate Pathway (PPP): The Parallel Track',x:'The PPP runs parallel to glycolysis and has two phases:\n\nOxidative phase (irreversible): G6P + 2 NADP+ -> ribulose-5-P + 2 NADPH + CO2. Enzyme: G6PD (rate-limiting). Product: NADPH (for reductive biosynthesis and antioxidant defense) and ribose-5-phosphate (for nucleotide synthesis).\n\nNon-oxidative phase (reversible): interconverts sugar phosphates using transketolase (TPP-dependent) and transaldolase. Can feed back into glycolysis as F6P and G3P.\n\nKey clinical connections: G6PD deficiency = defective NADPH production in RBCs = oxidative hemolysis (discussed in 3.8). Transketolase requires TPP; thiamine deficiency impairs the non-oxidative PPP.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'During intense exercise, AMP levels rise sharply. Which combination of enzyme activities would be INCREASED?',choices:['A) PFK-1, isocitrate DH, citrate synthase','B) PDK, FBPase-1, pyruvate carboxylase','C) PFK-1 inhibited; ATP synthase inhibited','D) Citrate synthase inhibited; PK activated by alanine'],answer:0,why:'AMP is the universal low-energy signal. It activates PFK-1 (step 3, rate-limiting glycolytic step), isocitrate DH (rate-limiting TCA step), and citrate synthase (TCA entry). All three accelerate catabolism when energy is needed. PDK phosphorylates and inactivates PDC; AMP activates PDC (via PDP), so PDK would be inhibited.'},{stem:'A patient with severe malnutrition is started on IV dextrose. Transketolase activity in RBCs is markedly reduced. Which cofactor is deficient?',choices:['A) Biotin','B) Pyridoxal phosphate','C) Thiamine pyrophosphate','D) Cobalamin'],answer:2,why:'Transketolase (non-oxidative PPP) requires TPP (thiamine pyrophosphate). RBC transketolase activity is a sensitive assay for thiamine status and actually the gold-standard biochemical test for thiamine deficiency. Biotin is for carboxylases; PLP is for transaminases; B12 is for methylmalonyl-CoA mutase.'}]}],
 bottomLine:'Glycolysis converts glucose to pyruvate (net 2 ATP, 2 NADH, cytoplasm, no O2 required). Three irreversible steps (hexokinase, PFK-1, pyruvate kinase) are the regulatory valves; PFK-1 is the master switch, controlled by the energy charge and by F-2,6-BP. Under aerobic conditions, PDC (5 cofactors, TPP-lipoate-CoA-FAD-NAD+) converts pyruvate to acetyl-CoA. The TCA cycle spins twice per glucose, yielding 3 NADH + 1 FADH2 + 1 GTP per turn; isocitrate DH is rate-limiting. The reduced coenzymes carry electrons to the ETC, where ~90% of ATP is generated. Know the clinical corollaries: PK deficiency (echinocytes, high 2,3-BPG), G6PD deficiency (bite cells, Heinz bodies, X-linked), thiamine deficiency (Wernicke/Korsakoff, give B1 before glucose), arsenic (lipoic acid inhibition, dimercaprol), and the Warburg effect (aerobic glycolysis in cancer, PET scanning).',
 nextHint:'In Ch 4, the NADH and FADH2 you just produced enter the electron transport chain. You will trace electrons through Complexes I-IV, learn how the proton gradient drives ATP synthase, and calculate the final ATP yield with modern P/O ratios.',
},
{
 n:4,
 title:'Oxidative Phosphorylation and Bioenergetics',
 subtitle:'The proton gradient: how electron flow drives ATP synthesis',
 tag:'Energy Metabolism',
 foundational:'The electron transport chain oxidizes NADH and FADH2, pumping protons across the inner mitochondrial membrane. ATP synthase harnesses the resulting electrochemical gradient (proton motive force) to synthesize ATP. This oxidative phosphorylation accounts for ~90% of aerobic ATP yield.',
 buildsOn:'Ch 3, NADH and FADH2 produced by glycolysis and TCA.',
 setsUp:'Ch 5, ATP drives biosynthetic reactions including gluconeogenesis.',
 objectives:['State the thermodynamic relationship between standard free energy change, equilibrium constant, and reduction potential.','Describe the four complexes of the ETC: substrates, electron carriers, protons pumped, and specific inhibitors.','Explain the chemiosmotic hypothesis and calculate the contribution of membrane potential and pH gradient to the proton motive force.','Describe the binding change mechanism of ATP synthase and the role of the c-ring rotation.','Distinguish the effects of electron transport inhibitors, ATP synthase inhibitors, and uncouplers on O2 consumption and ATP synthesis.','Compare the malate-aspartate shuttle and glycerol-3-phosphate shuttle in terms of yield and tissue distribution.','Calculate total ATP yield per glucose under modern P/O ratios using both shuttle systems.','Identify four mitochondrial genetic diseases by mutation, clinical features, and characteristic histology.'],
 opener:'The NADH and FADH2 produced by glycolysis, PDC, and the TCA cycle are not the final product. They are electron carriers, reduced coenzymes that hold the energy released by oxidizing glucose. The electron transport chain transfers those electrons down a thermodynamically favorable gradient to the terminal acceptor, molecular oxygen. As electrons fall, four protein complexes pump protons from the mitochondrial matrix to the intermembrane space. The resulting electrochemical gradient across the inner mitochondrial membrane, the proton motive force, is the energy currency that ATP synthase converts into ATP.\n\nThis chapter covers the thermodynamic foundation, the molecular machinery of the five complexes (I-IV plus ATP synthase), the shuttles that ferry cytoplasmic NADH into the mitochondrion, the logic of coupling and uncoupling, and a cluster of mitochondrial diseases that arise when this machinery fails. By the end you will be able to calculate total ATP yield, predict the effects of specific inhibitors, and recognize the clinical syndromes of mitochondrial dysfunction.',
 pinnedDisc:{t:'COUPLING vs UNCOUPLING',x:'ETC and ATP synthase are coupled by the proton gradient: ETC pumps H+ out, ATP synthase brings H+ back in to synthesize ATP. Inhibiting ETC (rotenone, antimycin A, cyanide): proton pumping stops, gradient collapses, O2 consumption decreases, ATP synthesis decreases. Inhibiting ATP synthase (oligomycin): protons cannot re-enter through F0, gradient builds up, back-pressure halts the ETC, O2 consumption decreases, ATP synthesis decreases. Uncouplers (2,4-DNP, UCP1): provide an alternative proton leak pathway back across the IMM. Gradient collapses without passing through ATP synthase. ETC pumps frantically trying to restore gradient, O2 consumption INCREASES, ATP synthesis decreases. Net result of uncoupling: metabolic energy dissipated as heat.'},
 sections:[{id:'4.1',num:'4.1',title:'4.1 Thermodynamic Foundations',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Two equations govern the energetics of oxidative phosphorylation. First, the relationship between free energy and equilibrium: delta G = delta G degrees + RT ln Q. At equilibrium, delta G = 0 and delta G degrees = -RT ln Keq. Second, the relationship between free energy and reduction potential: delta G degrees prime = -nF delta E degrees prime, where n is the number of electrons transferred, F is the Faraday constant (96,485 C/mol), and delta E degrees prime is the difference in standard reduction potentials (E degrees prime acceptor minus E degrees prime donor).'},{t:'formula',x:'delta G = delta G degrees\' + RT ln Q'},{t:'formula',x:'delta G degrees\' = -RT ln Keq'},{t:'formula',x:'delta G degrees\' = -nF (delta E degrees\') where delta E degrees\' = E degrees\' (acceptor) - E degrees\' (donor)'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'Reduction Potentials of the ETC Carriers (most negative to most positive)',x:'NADH/NAD+ : -0.32 V (strongest reductant, highest energy electrons)\nFADH2/FAD : -0.18 V\nCoenzyme Q (ubiquinone/ubiquinol): +0.045 V\nCytochrome c (Fe3+/Fe2+): +0.235 V\nO2/H2O : +0.816 V (strongest oxidant, lowest energy)\n\nElectrons flow spontaneously from most negative to most positive potential (downhill in E degrees\', exergonic). The total delta E degrees\' from NADH to O2 = 0.816 - (-0.32) = 1.14 V. This drives delta G degrees\' = -2 x 96,485 x 1.14 / 1000 = -220 kJ/mol, more than enough energy to synthesize multiple ATP molecules (each requiring ~30.5 kJ/mol under standard conditions, more under cellular conditions).'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'ATP\'s Position in the Phosphate Transfer Hierarchy',x:'Phosphate group transfer potential (high to low):\nPEP (phosphoenolpyruvate) > 1,3-bisphosphoglycerate > creatine phosphate > ATP > glucose-6-phosphate\n\nATP sits in the MIDDLE. Compounds above ATP (PEP, 1,3-BPG, Cr-P) can donate their phosphate to ADP to make ATP (substrate-level phosphorylation). ATP can donate its phosphate to compounds below it (G6P) or drive endergonic reactions. This middleman position makes ATP the universal energy currency.'},{t:'box',kind:'why',label:'Why a Gradient Instead of Direct Burning?',x:'Cells cannot oxidize glucose and directly make ATP in one step (too exergonic: would release heat explosively, not useful work). Instead, oxidation is broken into small steps (glycolysis, TCA) that capture electrons as NADH/FADH2. The ETC then releases that electron energy in controlled increments, using the released energy to pump protons. The proton gradient is the capacitor: energy stored as an electrochemical potential, released slowly through ATP synthase on demand.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'The delta E degrees\' for a redox reaction is +0.4 V with n=2 electrons. What is the approximate delta G degrees\' (F = 96,485 C/mol)?',choices:['A) -77 kJ/mol','B) +77 kJ/mol','C) -154 kJ/mol','D) +38 kJ/mol'],answer:0,why:'delta G degrees\' = -nF(delta E degrees\') = -2 x 96,485 x 0.4 = -77,188 J/mol approximately -77 kJ/mol. Positive delta E degrees\' gives negative delta G degrees\' (spontaneous). The sign convention: when the acceptor has a more positive E degrees\' than the donor, the reaction is exergonic.'},{stem:'Why does FADH2 yield less ATP than NADH when oxidized by the ETC?',choices:['A) FADH2 enters at Complex II, bypassing Complex I, so fewer protons are pumped','B) FAD has a higher molecular weight, requiring more energy to transport','C) FADH2 cannot interact with cytochrome c','D) FADH2 is oxidized in the cytoplasm, not the matrix'],answer:0,why:'NADH is oxidized at Complex I, which pumps 4H+. FADH2 is oxidized at Complex II (or as FADH2 in other reactions feeding into CoQ), bypassing Complex I entirely. Fewer protons pumped = smaller gradient contribution = less ATP synthesized. P/O ratios: NADH = 2.5 ATP, FADH2 = 1.5 ATP.'}]},{id:'4.2',num:'4.2',title:'4.2 Mitochondrial Architecture',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Mitochondria have four compartments, and knowing what lives where is essential for mechanistic understanding.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'Four Mitochondrial Compartments',x:'Outer mitochondrial membrane (OMM): contains VDACs (voltage-dependent anion channels, also called porins). Freely permeable to molecules <5,000 Da (metabolites, ATP, ADP, ions). Impermeable to large proteins unless specific import channels are engaged.\n\nIntermembrane space (IMS): trapped between OMM and IMM. Contains cytochrome c, adenylate kinase, creatine kinase. At rest, pH of IMS is approximately equal to cytoplasmic pH (~7.2-7.4) because OMM is permeable to H+. During active ETC, H+ pumping acidifies the IMS (lowers pH).\n\nInner mitochondrial membrane (IMM): the site of oxidative phosphorylation. Highly folded into cristae (increases surface area). Contains all 5 ETC complexes (I, II, III, IV, V/ATP synthase), ANT (adenine nucleotide translocase), uncoupling proteins, and the phosphate transporter. Highly impermeable: even small ions including H+, Na+, K+, Ca2+ cannot cross without specific carriers. Rich in cardiolipin (a unique four-tail phospholipid that stabilizes IMM protein complexes and is required for ETC function).\n\nMatrix: the innermost aqueous compartment. Contains: mitochondrial DNA (mtDNA), mt-ribosomes, TCA cycle enzymes, beta-oxidation enzymes, PDC, urea cycle partial enzymes (CPS-I, OTC). pH ~7.8-8.0 (more alkaline than IMS during active respiration because H+ is pumped out).'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'Why IMM Impermeability Is Non-Negotiable',x:'The entire point of the ETC is to create a proton gradient. If H+ could leak freely across the IMM, the gradient would collapse and no ATP would be made. This is why the IMM has no simple diffusion channels for protons. Every transport of charged or polar molecules across the IMM is mediated by specific carriers (ANT for ATP/ADP, phosphate transporter for Pi, malate-aspartate shuttle carriers, etc.). Uncouplers work by providing an artificial H+ pathway that bypasses this impermeability.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'Cytochrome c is released from which mitochondrial compartment during apoptosis?',choices:['A) Matrix','B) Outer mitochondrial membrane','C) Intermembrane space','D) Inner mitochondrial membrane cristae lumen'],answer:2,why:'Cytochrome c is a soluble protein located in the IMS (where it shuttles electrons from Complex III to Complex IV). During apoptosis, MOMP (mitochondrial outer membrane permeabilization) by BAX/BAK releases cytochrome c from the IMS into the cytoplasm, where it binds APAF-1 to form the apoptosome and activates caspase-9.'}]},{id:'4.3',num:'4.3',title:'4.3 Electron Transport Chain: Complexes I-IV',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Electrons enter the ETC from two sources: NADH (at Complex I) and FADH2 (at Complex II or other FAD-linked dehydrogenases). They flow through mobile electron carriers (CoQ, cytochrome c) to Complex IV, which donates them to oxygen, forming water. The free energy released at Complexes I, III, and IV is used to pump protons from the matrix to the IMS.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'Complex I: NADH Dehydrogenase (NADH:Ubiquinone Oxidoreductase)',x:'Size: ~980 kDa, 45 subunits (7 encoded by mtDNA). L-shaped structure: horizontal arm in IMM, vertical arm in matrix.\n\nReaction: NADH -> FMN -> multiple FeS clusters -> CoQ. FMN (flavin mononucleotide, from riboflavin/B2) is the initial electron acceptor.\n\nProtons pumped: 4H+ per 2 electrons (from matrix to IMS).\n\nInhibitors: rotenone (pesticide/rodenticide, blocks FeS-CoQ junction), amytal (barbiturate), metformin (mild Complex I inhibitor, this is the antidiabetic mechanism behind reduced hepatic glucose output via AMPK activation).\n\nDisease: Complex I deficiency = most common mitochondrial disease in children; Leigh syndrome (bilateral symmetric basal ganglia lesions, mtDNA or nuclear mutations).'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'Complex II: Succinate Dehydrogenase',x:'Also known as SDH (succinate:ubiquinone oxidoreductase). Unique: it is both TCA step 6 AND an ETC complex. It is the smallest complex (4 subunits, all nuclear-encoded).\n\nReaction: FADH2 (from succinate oxidation, covalently bound FAD in SDHA) -> FeS clusters -> CoQ.\n\nProtons pumped: 0 (zero). It transfers electrons to CoQ but does not pump protons. This is why FADH2 yields less ATP than NADH.\n\nInhibitors: malonate (competitive inhibitor of succinate binding, classic teaching example). Carboxin (agricultural fungicide).\n\nDisease: SDH mutations cause paraganglioma/pheochromocytoma (SDHB = high malignant risk, SDHD = head/neck tumors). Succinate accumulates as oncometabolite.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'Coenzyme Q (Ubiquinone/CoQH2)',x:'CoQ is a lipid-soluble quinone with a long isoprenoid tail. It diffuses laterally within the hydrophobic core of the IMM. It collects electrons from both Complex I and Complex II (and from electron-transferring flavoprotein, ETF, in beta-oxidation, and glycerol-3-phosphate dehydrogenase in the G3P shuttle). CoQ is the convergence point.\n\nCoQ can exist in three forms: fully oxidized (ubiquinone, CoQ), semiquinone radical (CoQ dot minus, intermediate), and fully reduced (ubiquinol, CoQH2). The semiquinone can donate a single electron to O2, generating superoxide (O2 dot minus), a reactive oxygen species.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'Complex III: Cytochrome bc1 Complex (CoQH2:Cytochrome c Oxidoreductase)',x:'Contains cytochrome b (two heme b groups, bL and bH), the Rieske FeS protein, and cytochrome c1.\n\nReaction: transfers electrons from CoQH2 to cytochrome c via the Q cycle.\n\nQ cycle mechanism (simplified): CoQH2 binds at the Qo site, gives 1 electron to the FeS/cyt c1/cyt c chain, gives 1 electron back to reform a CoQ at the Qi site (partial reduction). The next CoQH2 completes the Qi site CoQ to CoQH2. Net: 2 CoQH2 -> 2 CoQ + 4H+ pumped to IMS + 2 cyt c reduced. Net protons pumped: 4H+ per 2e-.\n\nInhibitor: antimycin A (blocks Qi site, prevents electron recycling). Stigmatellin and myxothiazol block Qo site.\n\nDisease: mutations rare; Complex III inhibition by antimycin A markedly increases superoxide production.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'Cytochrome c: Mobile Electron Carrier in the IMS',x:'Small protein (12 kDa), single heme group (iron cycles Fe2+/Fe3+). Carries one electron at a time. Peripheral to the IMM on the IMS face. Diffuses from Complex III to Complex IV.\n\nDual role: electron carrier in respiration AND apoptosis signal. When MOMP occurs (BAX/BAK pores in OMM), cytochrome c is released into the cytoplasm. There it binds APAF-1 (apoptotic protease activating factor-1), forming the apoptosome (heptameric wheel structure), which activates procaspase-9 -> caspase cascade -> apoptosis.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'Complex IV: Cytochrome c Oxidase',x:'The terminal complex. 13 subunits, 3 large core subunits encoded by mtDNA (COX1, COX2, COX3), rest by nuclear DNA.\n\nMetal centers: CuA (binds two Cu, in COX2, accepts electrons from cyt c), heme a (passes electrons to the catalytic site), heme a3 + CuB (binds O2, reduces it to 2 H2O using 4 electrons + 4 H+).\n\nReaction: 4 Cyt c2+ + 4 H+ + O2 -> 4 Cyt c3+ + 2 H2O.\n\nProtons pumped: 4H+ per 4e- (1H+ per electron, per pair of cyt c oxidized = 2H+ pumped per cyt c pair, net effect 4H+ per O2 reduced).\n\nInhibitors: ALL block at the heme a3-CuB site by competing with O2 or locking the iron in the wrong oxidation state.\n- Cyanide (CN-): binds Fe3+ of heme a3. Most classic. Treats with hydroxocobalamin or thiosulfate.\n- Carbon monoxide (CO): binds Fe2+ of heme a3 (like hemoglobin). Treats with 100% O2 or hyperbaric O2.\n- Hydrogen sulfide (H2S): binds Fe3+ of heme a3. Source: sewer gas, volcanic emissions.\n- Azide (N3-): blocks heme a3. Used in research.\n\nDistinguish: all four cause histotoxic hypoxia (cells cannot use O2 despite adequate delivery). Venous O2 high (PvO2 elevated) because tissues cannot extract O2.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'ETC Inhibitor Summary Table',x:'Complex I: rotenone, amytal, metformin (mild)\nComplex II: malonate (competitive)\nComplex III: antimycin A (Qi site), stigmatellin/myxothiazol (Qo site)\nComplex IV: cyanide (Fe3+ heme a3), CO (Fe2+ heme a3), H2S, azide\n\nAll Complex I/III/IV inhibitors: O2 consumption decreases, NADH accumulates, cells switch to anaerobic glycolysis, lactic acidosis.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A researcher adds rotenone to isolated mitochondria supplied with NADH and succinate. Which statement is correct?',choices:['A) Electrons from NADH still reach O2 via Complex I','B) Electrons from succinate can still reach O2 via Complex II, III, and IV','C) Both NADH and succinate oxidation are completely blocked','D) Antimycin A would have the same effect as rotenone'],answer:1,why:'Rotenone blocks Complex I (between FeS clusters and CoQ). NADH cannot pass electrons to CoQ. However, succinate enters at Complex II, which feeds CoQ independently of Complex I. Electrons from succinate still flow CoQ -> Complex III -> cyt c -> Complex IV -> O2. Antimycin A would block at Complex III, stopping both NADH and succinate electrons.'},{stem:'A patient is brought to the ER after smoke inhalation. Arterial blood gas shows normal PaO2. Lactic acidosis is present. What best explains the lactic acidosis?',choices:['A) CO decreases O2 delivery by binding hemoglobin','B) CO inhibits Complex IV (heme a3), blocking mitochondrial O2 utilization despite adequate dissolved O2','C) CO activates uncoupling proteins, dissipating the proton gradient','D) CO inhibits PDC, preventing pyruvate entry into the TCA cycle'],answer:1,why:'Carbon monoxide (CO) binds the Fe2+ of heme a3 in Complex IV, blocking the terminal electron acceptor. Cells cannot use the O2 that is present (PaO2 normal). The ETC halts, NADH accumulates, and pyruvate is reduced to lactate. This is histotoxic hypoxia: adequate O2 delivery, impaired utilization. Treatment: 100% O2 (competes with CO at heme) or hyperbaric O2.'}]},{id:'4.4',num:'4.4',title:'4.4 ATP Synthase (Complex V) and the Chemiosmotic Hypothesis',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'ATP synthase (F0F1-ATPase) is the molecular turbine that converts the proton motive force into chemical energy stored in ATP. It has two functional domains: F0 (in the IMM, conducts protons) and F1 (in the matrix, synthesizes ATP).'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'ATP Synthase Structure and Mechanism',x:'F0 domain (membrane-embedded): contains the c-ring (10-15 subunits depending on species), the a subunit (contains the proton half-channels), and the b-stalk. The c-ring rotates as protons pass through the interface between the c-ring and the a subunit.\n\nF1 domain (matrix-facing): alpha3-beta3 hexameric ring (the catalytic site), gamma subunit (central rotary shaft, connects c-ring to the alpha3-beta3 ring), delta and epsilon subunits.\n\nBinding change mechanism (Paul Boyer, Nobel 1997): as the c-ring rotates, the gamma shaft rotates within the alpha3-beta3 ring, changing the conformation of each beta subunit in sequence:\n- Open (O) conformation: ADP + Pi can bind\n- Loose (L) conformation: substrates bind weakly, no catalysis yet\n- Tight (T) conformation: catalysis occurs (ATP forms spontaneously at this site)\n- Back to Open: ATP releases\n\nEach beta subunit cycles through O -> L -> T -> O. With three beta subunits offset 120 degrees, one ATP is released per 120 degrees of rotation. Approximately 3 protons pass per 120 degrees (depends on c-ring stoichiometry), so roughly 3H+ per ATP synthesized.\n\nOligomycin: blocks the a/c interface in F0, preventing proton flow. Gradient builds. ETC slows (back-pressure). O2 consumption decreases. ATP synthesis stops.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'Chemiosmotic Hypothesis: Mitchell 1961, Nobel 1978',x:'Peter Mitchell proposed that the proton electrochemical gradient (proton motive force, pmf) across the IMM drives ATP synthesis. Initially controversial; now the central dogma of bioenergetics.\n\nThe pmf has two components:\n1. Electrical gradient (membrane potential, delta psi): ~-180 mV (matrix negative, IMS positive). This alone drives proton re-entry.\n2. pH gradient (delta pH): IMS is acidic (~7.0-7.2) relative to matrix (~7.8-8.0) during active respiration. Contributes ~-40 mV equivalent.\n\npmf formula: pmf = delta psi - (2.3RT/F) x delta pH. Total pmf approximately -200 to -220 mV.\n\nOf the two components, the electrical potential (delta psi) contributes ~80% of the pmf. The pH gradient contributes ~20%. Dissipating either component with ionophores (valinomycin for K+, nigericin for H+/K+ exchange) can separate their contributions experimentally.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'Oligomycin vs Uncouplers: Key Distinction',x:'Oligomycin (ATP synthase inhibitor): blocks the F0 proton channel. Protons cannot re-enter via ATP synthase. The gradient BUILDS UP (hyperpolarization). This back-pressure slows proton pumping by ETC. O2 consumption DECREASES. ATP synthesis stops.\n\nUncouplers (2,4-DNP, UCP1, FCCP): provide an alternative proton leak pathway across the IMM. Gradient COLLAPSES. There is no back-pressure on ETC, so ETC runs at maximum rate. O2 consumption INCREASES (frantically). But since protons bypass ATP synthase, ATP synthesis stops. Energy is released as heat.\n\nMnemonic: Oligomycin = plugs the drain (gradient builds, ETC slows). Uncoupler = opens a drain hole (gradient empty, ETC revs up).'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A mitochondrial preparation is treated with oligomycin. What happens to the membrane potential (delta psi) and O2 consumption?',choices:['A) Delta psi increases; O2 consumption decreases','B) Delta psi decreases; O2 consumption increases','C) Delta psi unchanged; O2 consumption increases','D) Delta psi decreases; O2 consumption decreases'],answer:0,why:'Oligomycin blocks F0, preventing H+ re-entry via ATP synthase. Protons continue to be pumped by ETC but cannot return. The gradient (delta psi) increases (hyperpolarization). This back-pressure inhibits further proton pumping by ETC, so O2 consumption decreases. Note: this is opposite to uncouplers, which collapse delta psi and increase O2 consumption.'},{stem:'According to the binding change mechanism, in which conformation does ATP actually form from ADP + Pi?',choices:['A) Open (O)','B) Loose (L)','C) Tight (T)','D) Open-Loose transition'],answer:2,why:'In the Tight (T) conformation, ADP and Pi are bound with high affinity and ATP synthesis occurs spontaneously. The energy input from proton flow (via gamma rotation) is used not to synthesize ATP per se but to change the conformation from T to O, releasing the newly formed ATP. Boyer called this a "binding change" because the energy drives conformational changes, not the chemistry of ATP formation directly.'}]},{id:'4.5',num:'4.5',title:'4.5 Shuttle Systems for Cytoplasmic NADH',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Glycolysis produces 2 NADH per glucose in the cytoplasm. The IMM is impermeable to NADH. Two shuttle systems move the reducing equivalents into the mitochondria, but they differ in which coenzyme receives the electrons in the matrix.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'Malate-Aspartate Shuttle (MAS)',x:'Tissues: liver, heart, kidney (high energy demand, high mitochondrial density).\n\nMechanism:\n1. Cytoplasmic NADH reduces OAA to malate (malate DH, cytoplasm).\n2. Malate enters the matrix via the malate-alpha-KG antiporter.\n3. Matrix malate DH oxidizes malate back to OAA, generating NADH (matrix).\n4. Matrix OAA is transaminated to aspartate (aspartate aminotransferase).\n5. Aspartate exits via the aspartate-glutamate antiporter; glutamate enters.\n6. Cytoplasmic aspartate is transaminated back to OAA + glutamate.\n\nNet: 1 cytoplasmic NADH -> 1 matrix NADH.\nATP yield: 2.5 ATP per cytoplasmic NADH (same as matrix NADH).\n\nThis shuttle is reversible and can run in either direction. It requires the malate-alpha-KG and glutamate-aspartate transporters.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'Glycerol-3-Phosphate Shuttle (GPS)',x:'Tissues: skeletal muscle, brain (less demanding shuttle for rapid ATP production).\n\nMechanism:\n1. Cytoplasmic NADH + DHAP -> glycerol-3-phosphate (G3P) via cytoplasmic G3P dehydrogenase (NAD+-linked).\n2. G3P crosses the OMM to the IMM outer face.\n3. Mitochondrial G3P dehydrogenase (FAD-linked, embedded in IMM) oxidizes G3P back to DHAP, generating FADH2.\n4. DHAP returns to cytoplasm.\n\nNet: 1 cytoplasmic NADH -> 1 matrix FADH2.\nATP yield: 1.5 ATP per cytoplasmic NADH (FADH2 bypasses Complex I).\n\nThe GPS is irreversible and faster (no need for amino acid transamination). The trade-off is lower ATP yield. Appropriate for rapidly contracting muscle that needs rapid NAD+ regeneration over maximum ATP yield.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Shuttle Choice Determines Total ATP Yield',x:'Total ATP per glucose:\nWith MAS (liver/heart): 32 ATP\n  - Glycolysis: 2 ATP + 2 cytoplasmic NADH x 2.5 = 7 ATP\n  - PDC: 2 NADH x 2.5 = 5 ATP\n  - TCA: 6 NADH x 2.5 = 15 ATP; 2 FADH2 x 1.5 = 3 ATP; 2 GTP = 2 ATP\n  - Total: 2 + 5 + 5 + 15 + 3 + 2 = 32 ATP\n\nWith GPS (skeletal muscle/brain): 30 ATP\n  - Glycolysis cytoplasmic NADH: 2 x 1.5 = 3 ATP instead of 5 ATP\n  - All other steps same\n  - Total: 2 + 3 + 5 + 15 + 3 + 2 = 30 ATP\n\nNote: old textbook value of "36-38 ATP" used outdated P/O ratios (NADH=3, FADH2=2) and is no longer accepted.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'In skeletal muscle, cytoplasmic NADH produced during glycolysis enters the mitochondria via the glycerol-3-phosphate shuttle. The net product transferred to the matrix is:',choices:['A) NADH, yielding 2.5 ATP','B) FADH2, yielding 1.5 ATP','C) NADH, yielding 1.5 ATP','D) GTP, yielding 1 ATP'],answer:1,why:'The GPS converts cytoplasmic NADH to matrix FADH2 (via the FAD-linked mitochondrial G3P dehydrogenase). FADH2 enters at CoQ, bypassing Complex I. P/O ratio for FADH2 = 1.5 ATP. This is why skeletal muscle has a lower maximal ATP yield per glucose (30 ATP) compared to liver/heart (32 ATP, using the malate-aspartate shuttle).'}]},{id:'4.6',num:'4.6',title:'4.6 Uncouplers and Thermogenesis',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Uncoupling is not always pathological. Brown adipose tissue deliberately uncouples the ETC to generate heat. Understanding the molecular mechanism of uncoupling is also important for toxicology.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'2,4-Dinitrophenol (2,4-DNP): Pharmacological Uncoupler',x:'2,4-DNP is a weak lipophilic acid (pKa ~4.1). At physiological pH, it is mainly in the anionic form (DNP-) in the aqueous phase. In the hydrophobic IMM, however, it picks up a proton (becomes DNP-H) and diffuses across the bilayer down its electrochemical gradient (from acidic IMS to alkaline matrix). In the matrix it releases the proton (DNP- re-forms) and diffuses back. Net effect: DNP carries H+ across the IMM without going through ATP synthase.\n\nConsequences: proton gradient collapses, ETC runs maximally, O2 consumption rises, ATP synthesis falls, all energy released as heat.\n\nClinical: 2,4-DNP was sold as a weight loss drug in the 1930s (and illegally online today). Fatal hyperthermia, diaphoresis, tachycardia, metabolic acidosis (lactic acid from cells switching to glycolysis). Temperature can exceed 40 degrees C rapidly. No antidote; treatment is cooling and supportive care.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'UCP1 (Thermogenin): Physiological Uncoupling in BAT',x:'UCP1 is a proton transporter in the IMM of brown adipose tissue (BAT). When open, it provides a proton leak pathway identical in effect to 2,4-DNP.\n\nRegulation:\n- Activated by: long-chain fatty acids (released by lipolysis during cold exposure or norepinephrine signaling). Fatty acids may act as proton shuttles through UCP1 or directly activate the channel.\n- Inhibited by: GDP and ADP (bind on the matrix face and block the channel). At rest, UCP1 is mostly inhibited.\n\nSignaling: cold -> sympathetic nervous system -> norepinephrine -> beta-3-adrenergic receptors on BAT -> cAMP -> PKA -> hormone-sensitive lipase -> fatty acid release -> UCP1 activation -> proton leak -> heat.\n\nUCP1 in newborns: critical for non-shivering thermogenesis (newborns have high BAT relative to body mass, around the neck, interscapular, perirenal). Brown fat is identifiable histologically by multilocular lipid droplets and dense mitochondria.'},{t:'box',kind:'why',label:'Why Brown Fat Has So Many Mitochondria',x:'More mitochondria = more ETC complexes = more proton pumping = more substrate for UCP1-mediated heat generation. The brown color comes from the high iron content of the heme in the many ETC complexes. By contrast, white fat has few mitochondria and stores energy as unilocular lipid droplets. The metabolic purpose of BAT mitochondria is not efficient ATP synthesis but rather deliberate thermogenesis.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A patient takes an overdose of 2,4-DNP. Which combination of findings is expected?',choices:['A) Low O2 consumption, high ATP, low temperature','B) High O2 consumption, low ATP, hyperthermia','C) Low O2 consumption, low ATP, hyperthermia','D) High O2 consumption, high ATP, normal temperature'],answer:1,why:'2,4-DNP collapses the proton gradient by shuttling H+ across the IMM without going through ATP synthase. ETC pumps frantically to restore the gradient (O2 consumption high). ATP synthesis is uncoupled (ATP low). All energy is lost as heat (hyperthermia). This triad is the classic 2,4-DNP toxidrome.'},{stem:'UCP1 in brown adipose tissue is activated by which molecule during cold exposure?',choices:['A) GDP','B) ADP','C) Long-chain fatty acids','D) ATP'],answer:2,why:'Cold exposure triggers norepinephrine release, which activates lipolysis in BAT via beta-3-adrenergic receptors and PKA. Released long-chain fatty acids activate UCP1, opening the proton channel. GDP and ADP are inhibitors of UCP1. ATP is also inhibitory. Fatty acids are the physiological activators.'}]},{id:'4.7',num:'4.7',title:'4.7 Reactive Oxygen Species and Antioxidant Defenses',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Electron transport is not perfectly efficient. Partial reduction of O2 generates reactive oxygen species (ROS) that must be detoxified. Excessive ROS causes oxidative damage to proteins, lipids, and DNA.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'ROS Generation and Detoxification Cascade',x:'Sources: Complex I and Complex III are the major sites of superoxide (O2 dot minus) production. At Complex I, electrons can escape from the flavin (FMN) or FeS clusters to O2. At Complex III, the semiquinone radical (CoQ dot minus) at the Qo site can donate an electron to O2.\n\nDetoxification pathway:\n1. O2 dot minus -> H2O2: catalyzed by superoxide dismutase (SOD). Two isoforms: MnSOD (SOD2) in the mitochondrial matrix; CuZnSOD (SOD1) in the cytoplasm and IMS.\n2. H2O2 -> H2O:\n   - Catalase: in peroxisomes (and cytoplasm), direct decomposition.\n   - Glutathione peroxidase (GPx): in cytoplasm and mitochondria. Uses reduced glutathione (GSH) + H2O2 -> GSSG + H2O. Then glutathione reductase uses NADPH to regenerate GSH from GSSG. NADPH comes from G6PD (pentose phosphate pathway) and other sources.\n\nKey link: G6PD deficiency -> insufficient NADPH -> cannot regenerate GSH -> H2O2 accumulates -> oxidizes hemoglobin -> Heinz bodies -> hemolytic anemia with oxidant exposure.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'G6PD Deficiency Revisited: The NADPH Connection',x:'RBCs have no mitochondria and no TCA cycle. Their only source of NADPH is the pentose phosphate pathway (G6PD -> 6-phosphogluconate dehydrogenase). Without NADPH, GSH cannot be recycled. This makes RBCs uniquely vulnerable to oxidative stress compared to nucleated cells (which have multiple NADPH sources including mitochondrial NADP+-linked isocitrate DH and malic enzyme).\n\nG6PD deficiency is X-linked recessive, ~400 million affected worldwide, highest frequency in sub-Saharan Africa, Mediterranean, and Southeast Asia (malaria endemic areas). The A- variant (African) has near-normal enzyme activity in young RBCs; enzyme decays rapidly as cells age. Older RBCs are most vulnerable. Mediterranean variant has severely reduced activity even in young RBCs.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'Superoxide produced in the mitochondrial matrix is converted to H2O2 by which enzyme?',choices:['A) Catalase','B) Glutathione peroxidase','C) MnSOD (SOD2)','D) CuZnSOD (SOD1)'],answer:2,why:'MnSOD (SOD2, manganese-containing) is located in the mitochondrial matrix. It dismutates superoxide (O2 dot minus) to H2O2 and O2. CuZnSOD (SOD1) works in the cytoplasm and IMS. H2O2 is then detoxified by catalase (peroxisomes) or glutathione peroxidase (cytoplasm/mitochondria).'}]},{id:'4.8',num:'4.8',title:'4.8 Mitochondrial Genetics and Disease',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Mitochondrial DNA (mtDNA) is circular, 16,569 bp, maternally inherited, and encodes 13 proteins (all subunits of ETC complexes and ATP synthase), 22 tRNA, and 2 rRNA. It has no histones, no introns, and minimal non-coding sequence. It has a higher mutation rate than nuclear DNA (proximity to ROS, limited repair). Nuclear DNA encodes the remaining ~1,500 mitochondrial proteins.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'Unique Features of Mitochondrial Genetics',x:'Maternal inheritance: mtDNA is transmitted via the egg cytoplasm. Sperm mitochondria are actively degraded after fertilization (ubiquitin-mediated). Therefore, mitochondrial diseases transmitted by mtDNA mutations are maternally inherited: affected mothers pass to all children; affected fathers do not pass to any children.\n\nHeteroplasmy: cells can contain a mix of wild-type and mutant mtDNA molecules. The phenotypic severity depends on the proportion of mutant mtDNA (threshold effect). Typically >70-80% mutant mtDNA is required for biochemical deficiency. The proportion can drift during cell division (mitotic segregation).\n\nHigh copy number: each cell contains hundreds to thousands of mtDNA molecules. Mutations must reach a threshold fraction to impair function.\n\nHigh-energy tissues most affected: brain, muscle (cardiac and skeletal), kidney. These tissues have highest mitochondrial density and greatest dependence on oxidative phosphorylation. Classic histology: ragged red fibers on modified Gomori trichrome stain (subsarcolemmal accumulation of abnormal mitochondria in skeletal muscle).'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'MELAS: Mitochondrial Encephalomyopathy, Lactic Acidosis, Stroke-like Episodes',x:'Mutation: m.3243A>G in MT-TL1 (tRNA-Leu, UUR). Most common pathogenic mtDNA point mutation.\n\nMechanism: mutant tRNA-Leu impairs translation of all 13 mtDNA-encoded proteins. Complex I and IV most severely affected.\n\nClinical: onset usually before age 40. Stroke-like episodes (affecting posterior cortex, not following vascular territories), encephalopathy, lactic acidosis, hearing loss, short stature, diabetes mellitus (MIDD: maternally inherited diabetes and deafness), retinopathy.\n\nHistology: ragged red fibers (modified Gomori trichrome), COX (cytochrome c oxidase)-negative or COX-positive fibers. Subsarcolemmal mitochondrial proliferation.\n\nLabs: elevated CSF and serum lactate, lactate:pyruvate ratio elevated (>25), elevated creatine kinase.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'MERRF: Myoclonic Epilepsy with Ragged Red Fibers',x:'Mutation: m.8344A>G in MT-TK (tRNA-Lys).\n\nClinical: myoclonic epilepsy (hallmark), cerebellar ataxia, weakness, ragged red fibers on muscle biopsy. Also: sensorineural hearing loss, dementia, neuropathy.\n\nHistology: ragged red fibers, COX-negative fibers.\n\nDistinguish from MELAS: MERRF = myoclonic epilepsy + ataxia; MELAS = stroke-like episodes + lactic acidosis. Both have ragged red fibers.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'LHON: Leber Hereditary Optic Neuropathy',x:'Mutation: point mutations in mtDNA-encoded Complex I subunits (most common: m.11778G>A in MT-ND4, also MT-ND1, MT-ND6).\n\nMechanism: Complex I dysfunction -> ROS accumulation -> retinal ganglion cell apoptosis (optic nerve most vulnerable).\n\nClinical: painless bilateral sequential (often subacute) central visual loss (central scotoma). Predominantly affects young men (15-35 yr). Maternal inheritance. Many carriers never manifest (incomplete penetrance; male sex, smoking, alcohol, and specific mtDNA haplogroups increase risk).\n\nDistinguish: no ragged red fibers (affects neurons, not muscle). No lactic acidosis at baseline. Maternally inherited, but male predominance is due to modifier effects.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'Kearns-Sayre Syndrome (KSS)',x:'Mutation: large-scale mtDNA deletion (1-10 kb), usually sporadic (not maternally inherited). Deletion removes multiple tRNA and protein-coding genes.\n\nDiagnostic triad: (1) onset before age 20, (2) progressive external ophthalmoplegia (PEO), (3) pigmentary retinopathy (salt-and-pepper retinopathy).\n\nAdditional features: cardiac conduction defects (heart block, can be fatal, requires pacemaker), cerebellar ataxia, elevated CSF protein.\n\nHistology: COX-negative fibers, SDH-positive ragged red fibers (SDH is entirely nuclear-encoded so it is preserved when mtDNA-encoded subunits are deleted).\n\nDistinguish from MELAS/MERRF: KSS = deletion (sporadic), PEO + retinopathy + heart block; MELAS/MERRF = point mutations (maternal).'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'Leigh Syndrome: Nuclear and mtDNA Causes',x:'Mechanism: bilateral symmetric necrotic lesions in the basal ganglia, brainstem, and cerebellum (subacute necrotizing encephalomyelopathy). Can result from mutations in: Complex I (most common nuclear or mtDNA cause), Complex IV (SCO1, SCO2, SURF1 nuclear mutations; COX1-3 mtDNA mutations), PDH complex (X-linked PDHA1), ATP synthase (m.8993T>G in MT-ATP6).\n\nClinical: infantile-onset developmental regression, respiratory failure, failure to thrive, lactic acidosis. MRI: bilateral T2-bright lesions in basal ganglia/brainstem (putamen, caudate, subthalamic nuclei, periaqueductal gray).\n\nPrognosis: severe, death usually in early childhood without treatment. No curative treatment; supportive care, thiamine/riboflavin/CoQ10 supplementation tried empirically.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A 22-year-old woman develops stroke-like episodes not following vascular territories, with elevated serum lactate. Her mother had similar episodes. Muscle biopsy shows ragged red fibers. What is the most likely mutation?',choices:['A) m.8344A>G in MT-TK','B) m.3243A>G in MT-TL1','C) Large mtDNA deletion','D) m.11778G>A in MT-ND4'],answer:1,why:'This is the classic MELAS presentation: stroke-like episodes, lactic acidosis, ragged red fibers, maternal inheritance, young adult. The m.3243A>G mutation in MT-TL1 (tRNA-Leu) is the cause of ~80% of MELAS cases. m.8344A>G (MT-TK) causes MERRF (myoclonic epilepsy). Large deletions cause KSS (sporadic, PEO + retinopathy). m.11778A in MT-ND4 causes LHON (optic neuropathy, no ragged red fibers).'},{stem:'A patient with Kearns-Sayre syndrome undergoes muscle biopsy. Which histochemical staining result is expected?',choices:['A) COX-positive, SDH-negative ragged red fibers','B) COX-negative, SDH-positive ragged red fibers','C) COX-negative, SDH-negative fibers, no ragged red fibers','D) Normal histology'],answer:1,why:'KSS results from large mtDNA deletions removing mtDNA-encoded COX subunits (COX1-3). Cytochrome c oxidase (Complex IV) staining is negative in affected fibers. Succinate dehydrogenase (Complex II) is entirely nuclear-encoded, so SDH is preserved and stains positively. The SDH-positive, COX-negative pattern on serial sections is pathognomonic for mitochondrial myopathy from mtDNA deletion.'}]},{id:'4.9',num:'4.9',title:'4.9 ANT, Adenylate Kinase, and Integrated Transport',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'ATP produced in the matrix must be exported to the cytoplasm, and ADP must be imported for rephosphorylation. This transport is mediated by the adenine nucleotide translocase (ANT) and is itself driven by the membrane potential.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'Adenine Nucleotide Translocase (ANT)',x:'ANT (also called ADP/ATP carrier, SLC25A4) is the most abundant protein in the IMM. It exchanges one ATP4- (out) for one ADP3- (in) in a strict 1:1 antiport.\n\nThis exchange is electrogenic: net movement of 1 negative charge from matrix to IMS (ATP has 4 negative charges, ADP has 3). This is driven by the negative membrane potential in the matrix (delta psi favors export of the more negatively charged ATP4-).\n\nConsequence: ANT consumes 1H+ equivalent of the proton motive force per ATP exported (because the electrical component drives the exchange). This is why the total H+/ATP cost is actually ~3.67 (3 for synthesis at F0F1 + ~0.67 for the ATP/Pi transport system), sometimes rounded to 4 H+ per ATP.\n\nInhibitors:\n- Atractyloside (carboxyatractyloside): binds ANT on the IMS face, locks it in the cytoplasmic-facing (c-conformation). Inhibits ANT. Cardiotoxic and hepatotoxic (from Atractylis gummifera, a Mediterranean thistle).\n- Bongkrekic acid: binds ANT on the matrix face, locks it in the matrix-facing (m-conformation). Produced by Pseudomonas cocovenenans in fermented coconut. Fatal food poisonings in Indonesia (tempe bongkrek).'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'Putting It All Together: The Respiratory Chain as a Coupled System',x:'The entire respiratory chain operates as a single coupled system. Substrate availability (NADH, FADH2) drives the ETC. The ETC establishes the pmf. The pmf drives ATP synthesis via F0F1. ATP export via ANT consumes part of the pmf. Pi import also consumes a small amount.\n\nATP demand controls the whole system: when ADP is high (demand high), ANT imports ADP, ATP synthase runs fast, pmf drops, ETC senses the lower back-pressure and runs faster, O2 consumption increases, NADH is oxidized faster. When ATP is abundant (demand low), ADP is scarce, ANT stalls, ATP synthase stalls, pmf builds, ETC slows.\n\nThis is the physiological basis of respiratory control: the rate of O2 consumption is determined primarily by the ADP/ATP ratio and the availability of reducing equivalents (NADH, FADH2).'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'Atractyloside inhibits the adenine nucleotide translocase. What is the expected effect on matrix ATP and cytoplasmic ATP?',choices:['A) Matrix ATP increases; cytoplasmic ATP decreases','B) Matrix ATP decreases; cytoplasmic ATP increases','C) Both matrix and cytoplasmic ATP decrease','D) Both matrix and cytoplasmic ATP increase'],answer:0,why:'ANT exports ATP from matrix to cytoplasm in exchange for ADP. Blocking ANT traps ATP in the matrix (matrix ATP increases as ATP synthase continues briefly) while the cytoplasm is starved of mitochondrial ATP (cytoplasmic ATP decreases). As matrix ADP becomes depleted and cannot be imported, ATP synthase eventually slows, pmf builds, and ETC slows. Net effect: cellular ATP depletion.'},{stem:'Which of the following correctly states why the ADP/ATP exchange by ANT is electrogenic and favored by the membrane potential?',choices:['A) ADP3- entering and ATP4- exiting results in net export of 1 negative charge, driven by the negative matrix potential','B) ADP3- entering and ATP4- exiting results in net import of 1 negative charge, driven by the positive matrix potential','C) The exchange is electrically neutral because one nucleotide enters for each that exits','D) The membrane potential has no effect on ANT; the exchange is driven by concentration gradients alone'],answer:0,why:'ANT exchanges ADP3- (3 negative charges in) for ATP4- (4 negative charges out). The net movement of charge is 1 negative charge from matrix to IMS (equivalent to moving 1 positive charge into the matrix). The matrix is negative (delta psi approximately -180 mV). Moving a negative charge out of a negative compartment is thermodynamically favorable. Hence the membrane potential (electrical gradient) directly drives ATP export.'}]}],
 bottomLine:'Oxidative phosphorylation couples electron transport to ATP synthesis via the proton motive force. Electrons flow from NADH (Complex I) and FADH2 (Complex II) through CoQ, Complex III, cytochrome c, and Complex IV to O2. Complexes I, III, and IV pump H+; Complex II pumps none (explaining the lower ATP yield from FADH2). ATP synthase uses the electrochemical H+ gradient to rotate the c-ring, driving the binding change mechanism that synthesizes ATP. Uncouplers collapse the gradient (increase O2, decrease ATP); ATP synthase inhibitors (oligomycin) build the gradient (decrease O2, decrease ATP); ETC inhibitors (rotenone, antimycin A, CN-) directly block electron flow (decrease O2, decrease ATP). Total yield: 32 ATP with MAS, 30 ATP with GPS (modern P/O ratios). Mitochondrial diseases cluster around tissues with highest energy demand; ragged red fibers on Gomori trichrome and the pattern of COX vs SDH staining localize the defect.',
 nextHint:'In Ch 5, ATP produced here drives biosynthetic reactions. Gluconeogenesis requires 6 ATP per glucose synthesized, fatty acid synthesis requires 7 ATP + 14 NADPH per palmitate, and the cell must coordinate these demands against the catabolic pathways you have just studied.',
},
{
 n:5,
 title:'Gluconeogenesis, Glycogen Metabolism, and the Pentose Phosphate Pathway',
 subtitle:'How the body makes glucose, stores it, and diverts it for NADPH and ribose',
 tag:'Energy Metabolism',
 foundational:'Glycolysis (Chapter 3) runs in reverse conceptually, but three irreversible glycolytic steps require unique bypass enzymes. Glycogen is the glucose buffer that flattens blood-glucose swings. The pentose phosphate pathway (PPP) is the cell\'s main NADPH factory.',
 buildsOn:'Chapter 3 glycolysis enzymes and regulation; Chapter 4 pyruvate dehydrogenase and TCA cycle intermediates',
 setsUp:'Chapter 7 (integration of all fuel pathways in fed/fasted/diabetic states); lipid synthesis (Chapter 6) depends on NADPH from the PPP',
 objectives:['Name the three irreversible glycolytic steps and the enzyme that bypasses each in gluconeogenesis (GNG)','Trace the carbon path from lactate, alanine, and glycerol into glucose','Explain how fructose-2,6-bisphosphate reciprocally controls glycolysis vs. GNG','Describe glycogen synthesis and degradation including the enzymes and their co-factors','Predict the clinical phenotype of each major glycogen storage disease from the enzyme defect','Explain the two phases of the PPP and state what each phase produces','Connect G6PD deficiency to hemolysis and malaria protection','Interpret a clinical vignette distinguishing Von Gierke, Pompe, Cori, McArdle, and Tarui diseases'],
 opener:'The brain needs about 120 g of glucose per day and cannot synthesize it. Muscle burns glucose but cannot release it back into blood. The liver therefore carries the full burden of maintaining blood glucose between meals, and it does so through two complementary systems: gluconeogenesis (building glucose from non-carbohydrate precursors) and glycogen breakdown (releasing stored glucose on demand).\n\nThese two pathways are not simply the reverse of glycolysis and glycogen synthesis. They use distinct enzymes at three strategic bypass points, and they are reciprocally regulated at the level of a single small molecule, fructose-2,6-bisphosphate, whose concentration swings up in the fed state and crashes in the fasted state. The pentose phosphate pathway runs in parallel with glycolysis and diverts glucose-6-phosphate toward NADPH production and ribose synthesis, functions invisible to energy accounting but critical for reductive biosynthesis and antioxidant defense.',
 pinnedDisc:{t:'GLUCONEOGENESIS vs GLYCOGENOLYSIS',x:'Both raise blood glucose, but they are not interchangeable. Gluconeogenesis synthesizes new glucose from 3-carbon (and other) precursors; it is slow, energetically expensive (6 ATP equivalents per glucose), and operates whenever precursors are available. Glycogenolysis releases preformed glucose-1-phosphate from glycogen; it is fast, requires no ATP investment, and is the first-response system in the first 8-12 hours of fasting. After glycogen is depleted (overnight fast), GNG becomes the dominant glucose source. On Step 1, distinguish them by the enzyme defect: G6Pase deficiency (Von Gierke) blocks BOTH pathways from releasing free glucose, producing more severe hypoglycemia than a defect in glycogen degradation alone.'},
 sections:[{id:'5.1',num:'5.1',title:'5.1 Gluconeogenesis: Building Glucose From Scratch',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Gluconeogenesis (GNG) occurs mainly in the liver (~90%) and renal cortex (~10%). It is induced during fasting, prolonged exercise, and stress. The net reaction converts two pyruvate molecules into one glucose at a cost of 4 ATP, 2 GTP, and 2 NADH.'},{t:'p',x:'GNG is essentially the reverse of glycolysis except at three irreversible points. Most glycolytic enzymes are shared in both directions; only the bypass reactions are unique to GNG.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Gluconeogenic Substrates',x:'Lactate: produced by exercising muscle and red blood cells (RBCs lack mitochondria), converted to pyruvate by lactate dehydrogenase in the liver (Cori cycle).\n\nAlanine: the predominant gluconeogenic amino acid from muscle proteolysis; alanine aminotransferase converts it to pyruvate in the liver (glucose-alanine cycle, requires PLP/B6).\n\nGlycerol: released by lipolysis in adipose; phosphorylated to glycerol-3-phosphate then oxidized to DHAP, a glycolytic intermediate.\n\nGlucogenic amino acids: all amino acids EXCEPT leucine and lysine (purely ketogenic). Most glucogenic AAs enter via oxaloacetate, fumarate, succinyl-CoA, or alpha-ketoglutarate.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'Leucine and Lysine',x:'Leucine and lysine are the ONLY strictly ketogenic amino acids. They degrade exclusively to acetyl-CoA and acetoacetate, which cannot be converted to OAA or any net gluconeogenic substrate. All other amino acids are either purely glucogenic or mixed (e.g., phenylalanine, tyrosine, isoleucine, threonine, tryptophan yield both glucose and ketone precursors).'},{t:'p',x:'The Cori cycle (lactate shuttle): exercising muscle exports lactate to the liver, which reconverts it to glucose at an energy cost to the liver (6 ATP per glucose). This transfers the energetic burden from muscle to liver.'},{t:'p',x:'The glucose-alanine cycle: muscle transamination of pyruvate to alanine (using glutamate as nitrogen donor) exports both carbon and nitrogen to the liver. The liver\'s ALT reverses the transamination, yielding pyruvate for GNG and ammonium for the urea cycle.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A marathon runner has elevated lactate at mile 20. The liver converts this lactate to glucose through the Cori cycle. What is the net ATP cost to the liver per glucose synthesized from lactate?',choices:['A) 2 ATP','B) 4 ATP','C) 6 ATP','D) 8 ATP'],answer:2,why:'GNG from pyruvate (or lactate, which is converted to pyruvate at no net ATP cost since it generates NADH) costs 6 ATP equivalents per glucose (4 ATP + 2 GTP). Choice C is correct.'},{stem:'Which amino acid cannot contribute carbon to gluconeogenesis under any circumstances?',choices:['A) Phenylalanine','B) Isoleucine','C) Lysine','D) Glutamate'],answer:2,why:'Lysine (along with leucine) is purely ketogenic, degrading only to acetyl-CoA and acetoacetate. Neither can produce net oxaloacetate (net gluconeogenic carbon), because acetyl-CoA entering TCA is fully oxidized. All other listed AAs are glucogenic or mixed.'}]},{id:'5.2',num:'5.2',title:'5.2 The Three Bypass Reactions of Gluconeogenesis',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Three glycolytic steps are thermodynamically irreversible and must be bypassed by unique GNG enzymes. Memorize these as matched pairs: glycolytic enzyme → GNG bypass.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Bypass 1: Pyruvate Kinase → Pyruvate Carboxylase + PEPCK',x:'Pyruvate kinase (PK) converts PEP to pyruvate. GNG reverses this in two steps.\n\nStep A: Pyruvate carboxylase (PC): pyruvate + CO2 + ATP → oxaloacetate (OAA). Located in the mitochondrial matrix. Requires biotin as CO2 carrier and is allosterically activated by acetyl-CoA (signals that TCA is saturated and OAA should be diverted). If acetyl-CoA is low, PC is inactive and GNG stalls.\n\nStep B: PEPCK (phosphoenolpyruvate carboxykinase): OAA + GTP → PEP + CO2. Located in the cytoplasm (in humans; requires OAA to be shuttled out as malate or aspartate, regenerating NADH in the cytoplasm). Transcription is induced by glucagon and cortisol; suppressed by insulin. PEPCK is the committed step of GNG for most amino acid-derived carbons.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Bypass 2: PFK-1 → Fructose-1,6-Bisphosphatase (FBPase-1)',x:'PFK-1 converts F-6-P to F-1,6-BP in glycolysis. FBPase-1 hydrolyzes F-1,6-BP back to F-6-P + Pi in GNG. FBPase-1 is inhibited by AMP (energy-depleted state, favor glycolysis) and by fructose-2,6-bisphosphate (F-2,6-BP, the master fed-state signal). Activated by citrate.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Bypass 3: Hexokinase/Glucokinase → Glucose-6-Phosphatase (G6Pase)',x:'G6Pase hydrolyzes glucose-6-phosphate to free glucose + Pi, releasing glucose into the blood. G6Pase is located on the endoplasmic reticulum membrane and is expressed ONLY in the liver and renal cortex (not in muscle or brain). This is why muscle cannot release glucose into blood even if it has glycogen. G6Pase is deficient in Von Gierke disease (Type I GSD).'},{t:'formula',x:'Pyruvate + CO2 + ATP  →[Pyruvate Carboxylase, biotin]→  OAA + ADP + Pi\nOAA + GTP  →[PEPCK]→  PEP + CO2 + GDP\nF-1,6-BP + H2O  →[FBPase-1]→  F-6-P + Pi\nG-6-P + H2O  →[G6Pase]→  Glucose + Pi'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'Biotin Role in Carboxylations',x:'Biotin is a CO2 carrier covalently attached to the enzyme via a lysine residue (biocytin). Biotin-dependent carboxylases all require ATP to activate CO2 (as carboxyphosphate intermediate) before transferring it to the substrate. Key biotin enzymes tested on Step 1: pyruvate carboxylase (GNG), acetyl-CoA carboxylase (FA synthesis), propionyl-CoA carboxylase (odd-chain FA and some AA catabolism), methylcrotonyl-CoA carboxylase (leucine catabolism).'},{t:'box',kind:'why',label:'Why GNG Uses GTP at PEPCK',x:'GTP is used by PEPCK rather than ATP. The GTP comes from the TCA cycle: succinyl-CoA synthetase generates GTP (in liver; ATP in muscle). This creates a metabolic logic: when TCA flux is high (lots of acetyl-CoA, lots of GTP), PEPCK substrate OAA is produced and energy currency is available to push GNG forward.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A patient with pyruvate carboxylase deficiency presents with severe lactic acidosis and hypoglycemia. Which of the following would also be expected due to accumulation of pyruvate\'s metabolic fate?',choices:['A) Hyperglycemia from increased glycogenolysis','B) Elevated alanine and decreased OAA for TCA','C) Increased PEPCK activity compensating for OAA deficiency','D) Increased ketogenesis because acetyl-CoA can freely enter TCA'],answer:1,why:'Without pyruvate carboxylase, pyruvate cannot be carboxylated to OAA. Pyruvate accumulates and is shunted to lactate (causing lactic acidosis) and alanine. OAA deficiency impairs TCA (acetyl-CoA backs up into ketones to some extent, but also impairs TCA entry). PEPCK cannot compensate because it requires OAA as substrate.'},{stem:'G6Pase is absent from skeletal muscle. What is the functional consequence during a prolonged fast?',choices:['A) Muscle cannot perform glycolysis','B) Muscle glycogen can fuel muscle work but cannot raise blood glucose','C) Muscle must import glucose from blood continuously','D) Muscle preferentially oxidizes fatty acids even during intense exercise'],answer:1,why:'Without G6Pase, muscle cannot release free glucose into the bloodstream. Muscle glycogen is catabolized to glucose-6-phosphate, which enters glycolysis and fuels local muscle work only. This is why Von Gierke disease (G6Pase deficiency in the liver) prevents BOTH glycogenolysis and GNG from raising blood glucose.'}]},{id:'5.3',num:'5.3',title:'5.3 Reciprocal Regulation: Fructose-2,6-Bisphosphate as the Master Switch',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Glycolysis and GNG must not run simultaneously at full speed (futile cycling wastes ATP). Reciprocal regulation is achieved by a single allosteric regulator, fructose-2,6-bisphosphate (F-2,6-BP), whose concentration is controlled by the hormonal state.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'F-2,6-BP Actions',x:'F-2,6-BP activates PFK-1 (accelerates glycolysis) and inhibits FBPase-1 (suppresses GNG). When F-2,6-BP is high, glycolysis is on and GNG is off. When F-2,6-BP is low, glycolysis slows and GNG is active.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'PFKFB: The Bifunctional Enzyme',x:'F-2,6-BP is synthesized and degraded by a single bifunctional enzyme, PFK-2/FBPase-2 (gene name PFKFB). The enzyme has two domains: a kinase domain (makes F-2,6-BP from F-6-P + ATP) and a phosphatase domain (degrades F-2,6-BP back to F-6-P).\n\nIn the fed state: insulin signaling leads to dephosphorylation of PFKFB → kinase domain is active → F-2,6-BP rises → PFK-1 on, FBPase-1 off → glycolysis on, GNG off.\n\nIn the fasted state: glucagon → adenylyl cyclase → cAMP → PKA → phosphorylates PFKFB at Ser-32 → phosphatase domain becomes dominant → F-2,6-BP falls → PFK-1 off, FBPase-1 active → GNG on.'},{t:'formula',x:'Fasted (glucagon): PKA phosphorylates PFKFB → FBPase-2 active → F-2,6-BP ↓ → FBPase-1 active + PFK-1 inactive → GNG on\nFed (insulin): phosphatase removes PKA phosphate → PFK-2 active → F-2,6-BP ↑ → PFK-1 active + FBPase-1 inactive → glycolysis on'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'AMP vs. F-2,6-BP: Two Levels of Control',x:'FBPase-1 has two inhibitory inputs: F-2,6-BP (hormonal/fed-state signal) and AMP (energy-depletion signal). Both inhibit FBPase-1 and thereby inhibit GNG. This makes sense: if AMP is high, the cell is energy-poor and should not spend ATP on GNG. AMP simultaneously activates PFK-1, driving glycolysis. Citrate activates FBPase-1 (signals TCA abundance, GNG can proceed).'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'PEPCK Transcription vs. PFK-1 Allosterics',x:'GNG regulation occurs at two levels: allosteric (fast, FBPase-1 via F-2,6-BP and AMP; pyruvate carboxylase via acetyl-CoA) and transcriptional (slow, PEPCK gene induced by glucagon/cortisol, suppressed by insulin). Transcriptional regulation of PEPCK is the dominant long-term control; allosteric control of FBPase-1 provides minute-to-minute adjustment.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A researcher treats hepatocytes with a drug that locks PFKFB in its phosphorylated state. Which metabolic consequence is expected?',choices:['A) Increased glycolysis and suppressed GNG due to high F-2,6-BP','B) Suppressed glycolysis and active GNG due to low F-2,6-BP','C) Equal glycolysis and GNG because F-2,6-BP affects neither enzyme','D) Increased glycogen synthesis because F-2,6-BP activates glycogen synthase'],answer:1,why:'Phosphorylated PFKFB favors the FBPase-2 domain, degrading F-2,6-BP. Low F-2,6-BP removes activation of PFK-1 and removes inhibition of FBPase-1, so GNG is active and glycolysis is suppressed. This mimics the glucagon-dominant (fasted) state.'},{stem:'Metformin activates AMPK by increasing the AMP/ATP ratio. Via FBPase-1 regulation, how does this suppress hepatic GNG?',choices:['A) AMPK phosphorylates PEPCK and inactivates it directly','B) Elevated AMP inhibits FBPase-1, blocking conversion of F-1,6-BP to F-6-P','C) AMPK activates pyruvate carboxylase, diverting OAA away from GNG','D) AMPK phosphorylates PFKFB kinase domain, raising F-2,6-BP'],answer:1,why:'AMP directly inhibits FBPase-1 (allosteric inhibitor). Additionally, AMPK phosphorylates ACC (suppresses FA synthesis and raises malonyl-CoA). The primary acute anti-GNG effect is AMP inhibiting FBPase-1 and AMPK phosphorylating PFKFB to raise F-2,6-BP (which further inhibits FBPase-1). Choice B captures the direct AMP effect on FBPase-1.'}]},{id:'5.4',num:'5.4',title:'5.4 Glycogen Structure and Synthesis',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Glycogen is a branched polymer of glucose stored in the liver (~100 g) and muscle (~400 g). Liver glycogen buffers blood glucose; muscle glycogen is an exclusive local fuel.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Glycogen Structure',x:'Linear chains are linked by alpha-1,4 glycosidic bonds. Branch points are alpha-1,6 linkages, occurring every 8-12 glucose residues. Branching increases the number of non-reducing ends (sites for simultaneous addition or removal of glucose), greatly increasing the rate of synthesis and degradation.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Glycogen Synthesis Enzymes',x:'1. Glycogenin: self-glucosylating primer protein. Attaches the first 7-11 glucose residues to itself via tyrosine hydroxyl groups. Required to initiate de novo glycogen synthesis.\n\n2. Glycogen synthase (GS): elongates chains by adding UDP-glucose to the non-reducing end, forming alpha-1,4 bonds. Activated by dephosphorylation (insulin signaling activates PP1 via insulin receptor substrate cascade). RATE-LIMITING step.\n\n3. Branching enzyme (amylo-alpha-1,4→alpha-1,6 transglucosidase): transfers a terminal 6-7 glucose block from a chain end and reattaches it via an alpha-1,6 bond, creating a branch point.'},{t:'formula',x:'UDP-Glucose + Glycogen(n)  →[Glycogen Synthase]→  Glycogen(n+1) + UDP\nGlucose-1-P + UTP  →[UDP-Glucose Pyrophosphorylase]→  UDP-Glucose + PPi\n(PPi is hydrolyzed → 2 Pi, driving reaction forward)'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Regulation of Glycogen Synthase',x:'Glycogen synthase (GS) is ACTIVE when dephosphorylated and INACTIVE when phosphorylated. Multiple kinases phosphorylate GS (PKA, GSK-3, AMPK). Insulin: activates PI3K → Akt → inhibits GSK-3 → GS remains dephosphorylated → active. Glucagon/epinephrine: PKA → phosphorylates GS → inactive; simultaneously, PKA activates glycogen phosphorylase kinase → activates glycogen phosphorylase → degradation on. This is the same phosphorylation logic as glycogen phosphorylase but in the OPPOSITE activity direction: phosphorylation activates phosphorylase and inactivates synthase.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'Glucose-6-Phosphate Activates Glycogen Synthase Allosterically',x:'G-6-P is an allosteric activator of glycogen synthase (makes the phosphorylated, less active form more responsive). After a meal, rising G-6-P (from glucokinase activity) pushes GS toward active state even before full dephosphorylation. This creates a feedforward signal: abundant glucose substrate promotes its own storage.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'Insulin is administered to a fasting patient. Which molecular event directly activates glycogen synthase in liver?',choices:['A) PKA phosphorylates glycogen synthase at multiple serine residues','B) Akt phosphorylates and inactivates GSK-3, preventing GS phosphorylation','C) G-6-P covalently modifies glycogen synthase, activating it','D) Glucagon receptor activation increases cAMP, releasing GS from inhibition'],answer:1,why:'Insulin → PI3K → Akt → phosphorylates and inactivates GSK-3. Since GSK-3 phosphorylates and inactivates glycogen synthase, inhibiting GSK-3 leaves GS dephosphorylated and active. Glucagon increases cAMP and PKA, which would phosphorylate and inactivate GS, the opposite of what insulin does.'},{stem:'Branching enzyme transfers a segment of a glycogen chain to form an alpha-1,6 linkage. What is the primary metabolic benefit of branching?',choices:['A) Decreases glycogen solubility for denser storage','B) Increases the number of non-reducing ends for faster synthesis and degradation','C) Shields the inner glucose molecules from phosphorylase attack','D) Allows UDP-glucose to attach at alpha-1,6 positions directly'],answer:1,why:'Glycogen phosphorylase and glycogen synthase both act at non-reducing ends. More branch points = more non-reducing ends = more sites for simultaneous enzymatic activity = faster flux. This is the kinetic rationale for branching.'}]},{id:'5.5',num:'5.5',title:'5.5 Glycogen Degradation',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Glycogen degradation (glycogenolysis) releases glucose for immediate metabolic use. The pathway requires two enzymes working sequentially and produces different products at linear vs. branch-point residues.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Glycogen Phosphorylase',x:'Cleaves alpha-1,4 bonds by phosphorolysis (uses inorganic phosphate, not water), releasing glucose-1-phosphate. The phosphorylation spares the energy of the glycosidic bond (G-1-P directly enters glycolysis after conversion to G-6-P by phosphoglucomutase). Requires pyridoxal phosphate (PLP, vitamin B6) as covalently bound cofactor. Active in the phosphorylated form (phosphorylase a); inactive in the dephosphorylated form (phosphorylase b).\n\nPhosphorylase stops 4 residues from a branch point (sterically blocked). At that point, debranching enzyme is required.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Debranching Enzyme (Two Activities in One Protein)',x:'1. Transferase (4:4 glucan transferase) activity: moves a block of 3 glucose residues from the branch to the main chain end (extending the linear chain for phosphorylase to continue).\n\n2. Alpha-1,6-glucosidase (amylo-1,6-glucosidase) activity: hydrolyzes the single remaining alpha-1,6-linked glucose at the branch point, releasing FREE glucose (not glucose-1-phosphate). This free glucose is not phosphorylated and must cross membranes; it represents a minor fraction (~8-10%) of total glycogen glucose.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'Liver vs. Muscle Glycogenolysis',x:'Liver: G-1-P from phosphorylase → G-6-P → G6Pase → free glucose released to blood. Liver uses glycogen to maintain blood glucose.\n\nMuscle: no G6Pase. G-6-P from phosphorylase enters glycolysis directly. Muscle glycogen fuels muscle contractions only and cannot raise blood glucose.\n\nThis distinction is tested in every McArdle disease question: muscle phosphorylase deficiency means muscle cannot use glycogen during exercise, but blood glucose and liver function are normal.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Regulation of Glycogen Phosphorylase',x:'Hormonal (covalent): glucagon (liver) and epinephrine (liver + muscle) → PKA → phosphorylase kinase → phosphorylates phosphorylase b → active phosphorylase a. Insulin opposes this by activating PP1.\n\nAllosteric (muscle): AMP activates phosphorylase b (energy-depletion signal); ATP and G-6-P inhibit. Ca2+ activates phosphorylase kinase (via calmodulin subunit), linking muscle contraction to glycogenolysis.\n\nAllosteric (liver): glucose directly inhibits liver phosphorylase a (product inhibition in the fed state).'},{t:'formula',x:'Glycogen(n) + Pi  →[Phosphorylase, PLP]→  Glucose-1-P + Glycogen(n-1)\nGlucose-1-P  →[Phosphoglucomutase]→  Glucose-6-P\nGlucose-6-P  →[G6Pase, liver only]→  Glucose + Pi'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A patient with McArdle disease (muscle glycogen phosphorylase deficiency) performs an ischemic forearm exercise test. Which result is expected compared to a healthy control?',choices:['A) Forearm venous lactate rises but ammonia does not','B) Forearm venous lactate fails to rise but ammonia rises normally','C) Both lactate and ammonia fail to rise, indicating no muscle work','D) Lactate rises but muscle glycogen remains elevated at biopsy'],answer:1,why:'Without muscle phosphorylase, glycogen cannot be degraded to glucose-1-P → glycolysis → lactate. Lactate fails to rise. However, AMP deaminase from AMP catabolism still works, so ammonia rises normally (ammonia rise confirms the patient actually exercised). This pattern, no lactate rise with normal ammonia rise, is pathognomonic for McArdle (and any GSD affecting muscle glycogenolysis).'},{stem:'Debranching enzyme releases a small amount of free glucose during glycogenolysis. Which activity of the debranching enzyme produces this free glucose?',choices:['A) The 4:4 glucan transferase activity that moves residues to a linear chain','B) The alpha-1,6-glucosidase that hydrolyzes the branch-point glucose','C) Glycogen phosphorylase completing the final 4 residues before the branch point','D) G6Pase releasing glucose-6-phosphate from the branch residue'],answer:1,why:'The alpha-1,6-glucosidase (second activity of debranching enzyme) hydrolyzes the one remaining glucose at the alpha-1,6 branch position using water (not phosphate), releasing it as free glucose rather than glucose-1-phosphate. The transferase activity just repositions the 3-residue block to allow phosphorylase to continue.'}]},{id:'5.6',num:'5.6',title:'5.6 Glycogen Storage Diseases (GSDs)',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Glycogen storage diseases are autosomal recessive (with one exception: Phosphoglycerate kinase deficiency is X-linked, not covered here) enzyme defects that cause glycogen to accumulate in affected tissues. Each disease produces a distinct clinical picture that can be decoded from the enzyme\'s function.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Type I: Von Gierke Disease (G6Pase Deficiency)',x:'Enzyme: Glucose-6-phosphatase (liver, kidney, intestine). Type Ia: G6Pase catalytic subunit. Type Ib: G6P translocase (transports G-6-P into ER lumen).\n\nPathophysiology: G-6-P cannot be hydrolyzed to free glucose. Both glycogenolysis AND GNG are blocked from releasing glucose. Glucagon injection fails to raise blood glucose (diagnostic clue).\n\nClinical: severe fasting hypoglycemia (may begin at 3-4 hours post-feed), massive hepatomegaly (glycogen + fat accumulation), lactic acidosis (G-6-P diverted to glycolysis → pyruvate → lactate), hyperuricemia (G-6-P → PPP → increased purine synthesis, plus lactate competes with uric acid for renal tubular secretion), hyperlipidemia (fat accumulates because GNG substrate lactate cannot be used and FA synthesis increases from excess G-6-P).\n\nTreatment: continuous cornstarch feeds to maintain blood glucose.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Type II: Pompe Disease (Acid Maltase / Acid Alpha-Glucosidase Deficiency)',x:'Enzyme: Lysosomal acid alpha-glucosidase (acid maltase). The ONLY GSD that is a lysosomal storage disease.\n\nPathophysiology: glycogen that enters lysosomes via autophagy cannot be degraded. Lysosomal glycogen accumulates, eventually causing cell rupture.\n\nClinical: infantile form: hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, hypotonia, hepatomegaly, death by 2 years from cardiorespiratory failure. Late-onset form: progressive myopathy, no cardiac involvement.\n\nKey board fact: NORMAL blood glucose and NORMAL response to glucagon (cytoplasmic glycogenolysis is intact). Pompe is distinguished from all other GSDs by cardiac involvement and lysosomal mechanism.\n\nTreatment: enzyme replacement therapy (alglucosidase alfa, recombinant acid maltase) is approved and effective, especially in the late-onset form.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Type III: Cori Disease (Debranching Enzyme Deficiency)',x:'Enzyme: Debranching enzyme (amylo-1,6-glucosidase + 4:4 glucan transferase). Accumulates limit dextrin (truncated glycogen with short stubs).\n\nClinical: milder than Von Gierke. Fasting hypoglycemia but LESS SEVERE because GNG is intact (G6Pase works). Hepatomegaly. Some patients develop myopathy (if muscle debranching is also affected, Type IIIa vs. liver-only Type IIIb).\n\nKey discriminator from Von Gierke: glucagon works early post-meal (GNG still functions) but fails after prolonged fast once glycogen is depleted to limit dextrins.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Type V: McArdle Disease (Muscle Phosphorylase Deficiency)',x:'Enzyme: Muscle glycogen phosphorylase (PYGM gene). Liver phosphorylase is unaffected.\n\nClinical: exercise-induced muscle cramps, myoglobinuria (rhabdomyolysis from ATP depletion in muscle), no rise in lactate on ischemic forearm exercise (pathognomonic), normal ammonia rise (AMP deaminase works). Second wind phenomenon: after initial cramping, patients feel better as FFA and blood glucose become available (bypass the blocked glycolytic fuel).\n\nNo hypoglycemia. No hepatomegaly. Normal fasting glucose (liver phosphorylase intact).'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Type VII: Tarui Disease (Muscle PFK-1 Deficiency)',x:'Enzyme: Muscle phosphofructokinase-1 (M subunit). PFK-1 is a tetramer; muscle uses M subunit; RBCs use both M and L subunits.\n\nClinical: identical to McArdle in muscle (exercise intolerance, no lactate rise, myoglobinuria) PLUS hemolytic anemia (because RBCs also partially lack functional PFK-1 and have impaired glycolysis).\n\nKey discriminator from McArdle: Tarui + hemolytic anemia; McArdle blood glucose normal, no hemolysis. Glucose infusion does NOT improve symptoms in Tarui (glycolysis is blocked downstream); may worsen by diverting FFA utilization.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'GSD Board Discriminators',x:'Hypoglycemia + lactic acidosis + hepatomegaly + glucagon fails = Von Gierke (Type I)\nCardiomyopathy + lysosomal + ERT available = Pompe (Type II)\nLike Von Gierke but milder + GNG intact = Cori (Type III)\nExercise myopathy + no lactate rise + no hemolysis = McArdle (Type V)\nExercise myopathy + no lactate rise + hemolytic anemia = Tarui (Type VII)\nPompe is the only GSD with normal fasting glucose and the only lysosomal GSD.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A 4-month-old with hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, hypotonia, and a normal fasting glucose level is found to have glycogen accumulation in lysosomes on muscle biopsy. Glucagon administration raises blood glucose normally. What is the enzyme deficiency?',choices:['A) Glucose-6-phosphatase','B) Lysosomal acid alpha-glucosidase (acid maltase)','C) Debranching enzyme','D) Muscle glycogen phosphorylase'],answer:1,why:'Normal fasting glucose + normal glucagon response + lysosomal glycogen + cardiomyopathy = Pompe disease (Type II GSD). Acid maltase (lysosomal acid alpha-glucosidase) is deficient. Cytoplasmic glycogenolysis is intact, so blood glucose regulation is normal. Von Gierke (G6Pase) would cause severe hypoglycemia and no glucagon response.'},{stem:'A 16-year-old with exercise-induced cramps and dark urine is found to have elevated venous ammonia but no rise in lactate after forearm ischemic exercise. CBC shows hemolytic anemia. Which enzyme is most likely deficient?',choices:['A) Muscle glycogen phosphorylase (McArdle)','B) Liver glycogen phosphorylase (Hers)','C) Muscle phosphofructokinase-1 (Tarui)','D) Debranching enzyme (Cori)'],answer:2,why:'No lactate rise + normal ammonia rise pattern is present in both McArdle (Type V) and Tarui (Type VII). The hemolytic anemia is the discriminating feature: RBCs partially depend on the M subunit of PFK-1, so Tarui disease (PFK-1 M-subunit deficiency) causes both exercise myopathy and hemolysis. McArdle does not cause hemolysis.'}]},{id:'5.7',num:'5.7',title:'5.7 The Pentose Phosphate Pathway (PPP)',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'The pentose phosphate pathway (PPP) diverts glucose-6-phosphate from glycolysis to generate NADPH (for reductive biosynthesis and antioxidant defense) and ribose-5-phosphate (for nucleotide synthesis). It runs in the cytoplasm and does not produce ATP directly.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Oxidative Phase (Irreversible)',x:'G-6-P → 6-Phosphogluconate → Ribulose-5-P (+ 2 NADPH + CO2)\n\nRate-limiting enzyme: Glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase (G6PD). This step is strongly regulated; NADPH product-inhibits G6PD. When NADPH is low (oxidant stress), G6PD is less inhibited and PPP flux increases.\n\nProducts: 2 NADPH per glucose-6-P entering the oxidative phase (from G6PD and 6-phosphogluconate dehydrogenase reactions) and 1 CO2. Also produces ribulose-5-phosphate, which isomerizes to ribose-5-phosphate (for nucleotide synthesis) or is fed into the non-oxidative phase.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Non-Oxidative Phase (Reversible)',x:'Interconverts various sugar phosphates using transketolase (requires thiamine pyrophosphate, TPP) and transaldolase. Products are funneled back into glycolysis as fructose-6-phosphate and glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate.\n\nTransketolase transfers 2-carbon units; transaldolase transfers 3-carbon units. The reversibility means cells can adjust the ratio of NADPH:ribose-5-P depending on need:\n- High ribose-5-P needed (dividing cells): non-oxidative phase runs in reverse, converting F-6-P and G-3-P to ribose-5-P without producing NADPH\n- High NADPH needed: oxidative phase runs, ribulose-5-P recycled back via non-oxidative phase'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'NADPH Functions',x:'1. Fatty acid synthesis (FAS complex consumes 14 NADPH per palmitate)\n2. Cholesterol synthesis (HMG-CoA reductase pathway)\n3. Glutathione reductase: NADPH reduces oxidized glutathione (GSSG → 2 GSH). Reduced glutathione (GSH) quenches reactive oxygen species (ROS) and protects RBC membranes from oxidative damage\n4. Cytochrome P450 monooxygenases (drug metabolism, steroid hydroxylation)\n5. NADPH oxidase (respiratory burst in neutrophils/macrophages)\n\nNote: NADPH is NOT used for ATP generation via the electron transport chain.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'G6PD Deficiency',x:'X-linked recessive (gene on Xq28). The most common human enzymopathy worldwide (>400 million affected). High frequency in areas endemic for malaria (Mediterranean, Africa, Middle East, Southeast Asia): heterozygous advantage from impaired RBC survival when P. falciparum-infected RBCs are stressed.\n\nPathophysiology: insufficient NADPH in RBCs → insufficient reduced glutathione → oxidant stress overwhelms antioxidant capacity → denatured hemoglobin precipitates as Heinz bodies (seen on crystal violet stain) → macrophages bite out Heinz bodies → bite cells (blister cells on peripheral smear) → extravascular hemolysis.\n\nClinical: most patients asymptomatic at baseline. Hemolytic episodes triggered by oxidant stress: drugs (primaquine, dapsone, nitrofurantoin, sulfonamides), infections (most common trigger), fava beans (divicine is the oxidant).\n\nLab: Heinz bodies and bite cells on smear. Reduced G6PD enzyme activity (test after hemolytic episode resolves, because old RBCs with lowest G6PD are destroyed first; reticulocytes have relatively higher G6PD activity and can give falsely normal result during acute episode).\n\nKey distinction from pyruvate kinase deficiency: PK deficiency also causes hemolytic anemia but by an energy-depletion mechanism (not oxidant), does not cause Heinz bodies, and is autosomal recessive.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'Thiamine and Transketolase',x:'Transketolase (non-oxidative PPP) requires TPP (thiamine pyrophosphate). Thiamine (B1) deficiency impairs the non-oxidative phase. Clinically, RBC transketolase activity (with and without added TPP) is used to diagnose thiamine deficiency: a large increase in activity after adding TPP indicates cellular thiamine depletion. Other TPP-dependent enzymes: pyruvate dehydrogenase complex (PDH), alpha-ketoglutarate dehydrogenase (alpha-KGD, TCA), branched-chain alpha-ketoacid dehydrogenase (BCKD, leucine/isoleucine/valine catabolism).'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A 25-year-old man of Mediterranean descent develops jaundice, dark urine, and anemia 2 days after starting primaquine for malaria prophylaxis. Peripheral smear shows bite cells and Heinz bodies. Which enzyme is deficient?',choices:['A) Pyruvate kinase','B) Glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase','C) Glutathione reductase','D) Hexokinase'],answer:1,why:'Heinz bodies (denatured hemoglobin precipitates) + bite cells + oxidant drug trigger in a Mediterranean man = G6PD deficiency. G6PD is the rate-limiting enzyme of the oxidative PPP. Without it, RBCs cannot regenerate NADPH → cannot reduce GSSG to GSH → oxidant damage causes Hb denaturation. Pyruvate kinase deficiency causes hemolysis via energy depletion, not Heinz bodies.'},{stem:'In a cell that has abundant ATP and low NADPH, which direction should PPP flux be directed to best meet metabolic needs?',choices:['A) Oxidative phase only, producing maximum NADPH','B) Non-oxidative phase in reverse, converting glycolytic intermediates to ribose-5-P','C) Both phases, with ribulose-5-P recycled back to glycolysis via the non-oxidative phase','D) Oxidative phase halted; G6P diverted entirely to glycolysis'],answer:0,why:'When NADPH is low and ATP is sufficient, running the oxidative phase maximizes NADPH production per G-6-P. The ribulose-5-P generated can then be recycled back to glycolytic intermediates via the non-oxidative phase if ribose-5-P is not needed for nucleotide synthesis. Option A correctly states running the oxidative phase to produce NADPH.'}]},{id:'5.8',num:'5.8',title:'5.8 Integrated Glucose Homeostasis and Clinical Applications',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Glucose homeostasis integrates glycolysis, GNG, glycogen metabolism, and the PPP under hormonal control. The two major clinical contexts tested are diabetes mellitus (DM) and fasting stress physiology.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Fed State (Insulin Dominant)',x:'Blood glucose → pancreatic B-cells → insulin release. Liver: glucokinase active (low affinity, high capacity, not saturated), G-6-P rises → glycogen synthesis (GS dephosphorylated), glycolysis on (high F-2,6-BP, PFK-1 active), GNG off (PEPCK transcription suppressed). Adipose: LPL induced (clears chylomicron TAG), HSL inhibited, glucose taken up via GLUT4. Muscle: GLUT4 translocates to membrane, glucose taken up, glycogen synthesized.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Fasted State (Glucagon Dominant)',x:'Glucagon from alpha cells (low glucose). Liver: PKA activated → glycogen phosphorylase a → glycogenolysis (first 8-12 hrs); PFKFB phosphorylated → F-2,6-BP falls → FBPase-1 active → GNG on; PEPCK transcription induced. Adipose: HSL active → lipolysis → FFA + glycerol released. Kidney cortex: GNG active (uses glutamine, a major renal GNG substrate). Brain: initially uses glucose, shifts to ketones after several days of fasting (sparing muscle protein from catabolism).'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Type 1 Diabetes Mellitus (T1DM)',x:'Autoimmune destruction of B-cells → absolute insulin deficiency. Without insulin: GLUT4 does not translocate (hyperglycemia), GNG and glycogenolysis unrestrained (more hyperglycemia), lipolysis unrestrained (FFA → ketogenesis → DKA). DKA biochemistry: ketonemia (acetoacetate + beta-hydroxybutyrate) lowers serum bicarbonate → anion-gap metabolic acidosis. Osmotic diuresis from glucosuria causes dehydration and electrolyte depletion. Insulin + fluids + K+ replacement is treatment.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Type 2 Diabetes Mellitus (T2DM) and Hepatic Insulin Resistance',x:'Peripheral insulin resistance (muscle, adipose) reduces glucose uptake. Selective hepatic insulin resistance: insulin still promotes SREBP1c-driven lipogenesis (NAFLD/NASH) but fails to suppress GNG (PEPCK and G6Pase remain high) → fasting hyperglycemia. Metformin mechanism: inhibits mitochondrial Complex I → ↑ AMP/ATP ratio → AMPK activation → phosphorylates ACC (inhibits FA synthesis) + phosphorylates PFKFB (raises F-2,6-BP → inhibits FBPase-1) + inhibits GNG gene expression. Net: reduced hepatic glucose output, improved insulin sensitivity.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Counterregulatory Hormones',x:'Hierarchy from fastest to slowest: glucagon (minutes, acute glycogenolysis + GNG), epinephrine (minutes, muscle + liver glycogenolysis, lipolysis), growth hormone (hours, insulin antagonism, promotes lipolysis, reduces GLUT4 expression), cortisol (hours-days, induces PEPCK + G6Pase transcription, promotes muscle proteolysis for GNG substrates, induces GNG enzymes).\n\nCortisol is the dominant counterregulatory hormone in prolonged illness and stress; its chronic excess (Cushing syndrome) causes hyperglycemia, muscle wasting, and truncal obesity.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'Vitamin Cofactor Summary for GNG and PPP',x:'Biotin: pyruvate carboxylase (GNG bypass 1) and propionyl-CoA carboxylase (odd-chain FA catabolism → GNG via succinyl-CoA)\nThiamine (B1/TPP): transketolase (PPP non-oxidative phase), PDH, alpha-KGD\nPLP (B6): glycogen phosphorylase (covalently bound), aminotransferases (alanine cycle, all transaminations)\nUTP: UDP-glucose pyrophosphorylase (glycogen synthesis)\nNADP+: G6PD and 6-phosphogluconate dehydrogenase (PPP oxidative phase)'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A 14-year-old with T1DM presents in DKA. Serum glucose is 480 mg/dL, pH 7.18, bicarbonate 8 mEq/L. Urinalysis shows 4+ glucose and 3+ ketones. Which process is the IMMEDIATE cause of the ketoacidosis?',choices:['A) Excessive glycolysis producing pyruvate that overflows to acetyl-CoA','B) Unrestrained lipolysis providing FFA for hepatic ketogenesis in the absence of insulin','C) Glucagon-stimulated GNG producing excess OAA converted to ketones','D) Accelerated PPP producing NADPH that drives HMG-CoA to ketone bodies'],answer:1,why:'Without insulin, hormone-sensitive lipase (HSL) in adipose is unrestrained → massive FFA release → liver beta-oxidation → acetyl-CoA excess → HMG-CoA pathway → ketone bodies (acetoacetate, beta-hydroxybutyrate). The absence of insulin (not glucagon excess per se) is the permissive signal. Glucagon amplifies the effect but lipolysis is the direct ketone carbon source.'},{stem:'Metformin reduces fasting hyperglycemia in T2DM. Which downstream effect of AMPK activation accounts for its primary anti-gluconeogenic action?',choices:['A) AMPK phosphorylates and activates PEPCK, increasing carbon flux through GNG','B) AMPK phosphorylates PFKFB, raising F-2,6-BP and inhibiting FBPase-1','C) AMPK activates glycogen synthase by dephosphorylating it','D) AMPK inhibits glucagon secretion from pancreatic alpha cells'],answer:1,why:'AMPK phosphorylates PFKFB, shifting the bifunctional enzyme toward its FBPase-2 domain, which paradoxically raises F-2,6-BP (by some analyses the hepatic isoform, PFKFB3, responds differently than the muscle isoform; the net effect in liver is raised F-2,6-BP inhibiting FBPase-1). Additionally, AMPK suppresses TORC2 (a transcriptional coactivator of GNG genes including PEPCK). The AMP rise itself directly inhibits FBPase-1 allosterically.'}]},{id:'5.9',num:'5.9',title:'5.9 High-Yield Discriminators and Vignette Patterns',blocks:[{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Pyruvate Carboxylase vs. PEPCK: Which Step Is Deficient?',x:'Both enzymes are needed for GNG from pyruvate. Distinguishing them on the USMLE:\n\nPyruvate carboxylase deficiency: lactic acidosis (pyruvate accumulates → LDH → lactate), hypoglycemia, hyperammonemia (OAA needed to condense with acetyl-CoA in the urea cycle as aspartate, OAA depletion impairs N-acetylglutamate synthesis). Also impairs TCA entry (OAA depletion). May present as neonatal lactic acidosis + hyperammonemia.\n\nPEPCK deficiency (rare): milder hypoglycemia, hypoglycemia mainly from loss of GNG from amino acids, less severe lactic acidosis (pyruvate carboxylase works, OAA forms, but cannot become PEP). Anaplerosis is preserved. Rare in practice; pyruvate carboxylase deficiency is more commonly tested.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Von Gierke vs. Cori: Severity Clue',x:'Both cause hepatomegaly and fasting hypoglycemia. Von Gierke is WORSE because G6Pase deficiency blocks the FINAL COMMON STEP for both glycogenolysis and GNG: no matter how much glucose is produced, it cannot be released as free glucose. Cori disease (debranching deficiency) is milder because:\n1. GNG is fully intact (G6Pase works; PEPCK works)\n2. Phosphorylase still degrades linear chain portions, just cannot pass branch points\n3. Limit dextrins accumulate (shorter, stubby glycogen)\n\nDiagnostic distinction: glucagon after a high-carbohydrate meal raises blood glucose in Cori (GNG intact) but not in Von Gierke.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'McArdle vs. Tarui: The Hemolysis Clue',x:'Both Type V (McArdle, muscle phosphorylase) and Type VII (Tarui, muscle PFK-1) present with exercise myopathy, no lactate rise, and myoglobinuria. Hemolytic anemia appears only in Tarui because erythrocytes use the M subunit of PFK-1 in combination with L subunit; partial PFK-1 deficiency impairs RBC glycolysis and shortens RBC survival.\n\nAdditional Tarui clue: glucose infusion does not help (glycolysis is blocked at PFK-1). In McArdle, glucose administration partially helps exercise tolerance (can still use blood glucose if phosphorylase is not required).'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'Pompe vs. All Others',x:'Pompe stands apart from every other GSD in three ways:\n1. Lysosomal mechanism (acid maltase in lysosomes, not cytoplasm)\n2. Normal blood glucose and normal glucagon response (cytoplasmic glycogenolysis intact)\n3. Cardiac involvement (cardiomyopathy in infantile form)\n\nTreatment with ERT (alglucosidase alfa) is disease-modifying and unique to Pompe among the classic GSDs.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'G6PD Deficiency Test Timing',x:'Testing for G6PD deficiency during or immediately after an acute hemolytic episode will often give falsely NORMAL results. The RBCs with the lowest G6PD activity are hemolyzed first and removed from circulation. The surviving RBCs (younger reticulocytes and older RBCs that somehow survived) have relatively higher G6PD activity. Test 2-3 months after the episode when the RBC pool has normalized. Alternatively, use molecular genetic testing, which is unaffected by the acute episode.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A 6-month-old presents with fasting hypoglycemia and hepatomegaly. Glucagon injection after an overnight fast does NOT raise blood glucose, but glucagon given 2 hours after a meal DOES raise blood glucose. What does this pattern indicate?',choices:['A) Pompe disease with lysosomal glycogen accumulation','B) Von Gierke disease with G6Pase deficiency','C) Cori disease with debranching enzyme deficiency','D) McArdle disease with muscle phosphorylase deficiency'],answer:2,why:'The pattern where glucagon works post-meal but not after a prolonged fast indicates that linear glycogen (accessible to phosphorylase) is present post-meal but depleted after overnight fasting (only limit dextrins remain, which require debranching enzyme). GNG is intact (glucagon works via GNG post-meal). This is Cori disease (debranching enzyme deficiency). In Von Gierke, glucagon never works because G6Pase blocks both pathways.'}]}],
 bottomLine:'Gluconeogenesis bypasses three irreversible glycolytic steps via pyruvate carboxylase + PEPCK, FBPase-1, and G6Pase. The master fed/fasted switch is F-2,6-BP, controlled by the PFKFB bifunctional enzyme responding to PKA (glucagon) and insulin signaling. Glycogen synthesis uses UDP-glucose and glycogen synthase (active when dephosphorylated); degradation uses phosphorylase (active when phosphorylated) and debranching enzyme. Each GSD maps to a unique enzyme defect with a predictable clinical phenotype: Von Gierke (G6Pase, severe, no glucagon response), Pompe (lysosomal acid maltase, cardiac, normal glucose), Cori (debranching, mild), McArdle (muscle phosphorylase, no lactate rise), Tarui (muscle PFK-1, no lactate rise + hemolysis). The PPP produces NADPH (via G6PD) and ribose-5-P; G6PD deficiency causes oxidant-triggered hemolysis with Heinz bodies and bite cells.',
 nextHint:'Chapter 6 (Lipid Metabolism) directly depends on NADPH from the PPP (fatty acid synthesis requires 14 NADPH per palmitate), the acetyl-CoA supply chain built in this chapter (citrate shuttle exports acetyl-CoA from mitochondria), and the concept of malonyl-CoA inhibiting carnitine shuttle, which reciprocally regulates FA synthesis vs. FA oxidation.',
},
{
 n:6,
 title:'Lipid Metabolism and Lipoprotein Biology',
 subtitle:'How the body builds, burns, and transports fats, and what goes wrong in common lipid diseases',
 tag:'Other Metabolism',
 foundational:'Fatty acids are the body\'s densest fuel (9 kcal/g vs. 4 kcal/g for carbohydrates) and the primary structural material of cell membranes. Understanding lipid metabolism means tracing the same two-carbon unit (acetyl-CoA) through synthesis (building up) and oxidation (breaking down) in opposite cellular compartments, regulated by reciprocal hormonal signals. Lipoprotein biology links hepatic lipid metabolism to cardiovascular disease, the most tested clinical application of biochemistry on the MCAT.',
 buildsOn:'Chapter 3 glycolysis (produces acetyl-CoA via pyruvate dehydrogenase); Chapter 4 TCA cycle (citrate carries acetyl-CoA out of mitochondria; OAA availability controls ketogenesis); Chapter 5 pentose phosphate pathway (provides NADPH for fatty acid synthesis); Chapter 5 gluconeogenesis regulation by hormones (same PKA/insulin logic governs lipid enzyme phosphorylation)',
 setsUp:'Chapter 7 (integrated fuel selection in fed, fasted, diabetic, and exercise states); steroid hormone synthesis (Chapter 8, builds on cholesterol synthesis); bile acid biology (Chapter 9 GI biochemistry)',
 objectives:['Trace the flow of acetyl-CoA from the mitochondrial matrix to the cytoplasm via the citrate shuttle and explain why this step is required for fatty acid synthesis','Identify acetyl-CoA carboxylase as the rate-limiting enzyme of fatty acid synthesis, describe its allosteric and hormonal regulators, and explain the biotin requirement','List the 7 reactions of fatty acid synthase, name the two NADPH sources, and explain why malonyl-CoA is the 2-carbon donor rather than acetyl-CoA directly','Describe the carnitine shuttle in detail, identify which enzyme is regulated, and explain why malonyl-CoA inhibiting CAT-I creates reciprocal regulation of synthesis and oxidation','Calculate the ATP yield of beta-oxidation for a given fatty acid and adjust for odd-chain and unsaturated fatty acids','Explain ketone body synthesis and utilization, identify which tissues can and cannot use ketones and why, and distinguish DKA from starvation ketosis','Describe the HMG-CoA reductase reaction, its products and byproducts, and the SREBP feedback mechanism; explain how statins work','Trace the lifecycle of each major lipoprotein class, identify its associated apolipoproteins, and predict the phenotype of specific apolipoprotein or receptor defects','Explain reverse cholesterol transport and the roles of LCAT, ApoA-I, and CETP','Interpret a clinical vignette involving familial hypercholesterolemia, lipoprotein lipase deficiency, or Tangier disease from first principles'],
 opener:'Every cell membrane, every steroid hormone, and every fat-soluble vitamin depends on lipid chemistry. Yet lipids must be packaged and transported in water-based blood, which creates a fundamental problem: nonpolar molecules do not mix with polar solvents. The body solves this with two strategies: covalent attachment to coenzyme A (making fatty acids water-soluble in the cytoplasm) and encapsulation in lipoprotein particles (moving lipids through the bloodstream).\n\nThe metabolic logic of lipid pathways follows a single organizing principle: when energy is abundant and insulin is high, the body builds fatty acids from acetyl-CoA in the cytoplasm; when energy is scarce and glucagon is high, the body breaks fatty acids down in the mitochondrial matrix. These two processes use the same two-carbon unit, the same coenzyme A thioester chemistry, and mostly the same organelle intermediates, but they are physically and enzymatically distinct, and they cannot run at full speed simultaneously. Malonyl-CoA, the first committed product of fatty acid synthesis, directly inhibits the mitochondrial carnitine transporter to enforce this reciprocity.\n\nLipoprotein biology adds a clinical dimension. Most cardiovascular disease risk traces back to dysregulation of LDL and HDL cholesterol transport, and the molecular defects in familial hypercholesterolemia (loss of the LDL receptor) are among the most instructive case studies in receptor biology, feedback regulation, and pharmacology that biochemistry offers.',
 pinnedDisc:{t:'SYNTHESIS vs OXIDATION: COMPARTMENTS AND RECIPROCAL CONTROL',x:'Fatty acid SYNTHESIS occurs in the CYTOPLASM. It consumes acetyl-CoA, NADPH, and ATP. It is driven by insulin and citrate. Its first committed product, malonyl-CoA, is an allosteric inhibitor of carnitine acyltransferase I (CAT-I), which prevents fatty acids from entering the mitochondria for oxidation.\n\nFatty acid OXIDATION (beta-oxidation) occurs in the MITOCHONDRIAL MATRIX. It produces acetyl-CoA, NADH, FADH2, and ATP. It is driven by glucagon and epinephrine via PKA, which phosphorylates and inactivates acetyl-CoA carboxylase (ACC), dropping malonyl-CoA levels and releasing the inhibition of CAT-I.\n\nIn the fed state: insulin activates a phosphatase that dephosphorylates ACC (active), malonyl-CoA rises, CAT-I is blocked, and oxidation is suppressed.\nIn the fasted state: PKA phosphorylates ACC (inactive), malonyl-CoA falls, CAT-I is free, and oxidation is active.\n\nThis is the single most important regulatory concept in lipid metabolism for the MCAT.'},
 sections:[{id:'6.1',num:'6.1',title:'6.1 Fatty Acid Synthesis',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Fatty acid synthesis converts acetyl-CoA into long-chain saturated fatty acids, primarily palmitate (16 carbons). The process occurs in two stages: the committed regulatory step (acetyl-CoA carboxylase, ACC) and the elongation cycle (fatty acid synthase, FAS). Both enzymes reside in the cytoplasm, but their acetyl-CoA substrate is generated in the mitochondrial matrix, requiring a dedicated export mechanism.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Step 1: The Citrate Shuttle (Acetyl-CoA Export)',x:'Acetyl-CoA cannot directly cross the inner mitochondrial membrane. Instead, it condenses with oxaloacetate (OAA) to form citrate in the mitochondrial matrix (the same first reaction of the TCA cycle). Citrate is then transported into the cytoplasm by the tricarboxylate carrier.\n\nIn the cytoplasm, ATP-citrate lyase (also called citrate lyase) cleaves citrate back into acetyl-CoA and OAA: Citrate + CoA + ATP → Acetyl-CoA + OAA + ADP + Pi.\n\nThe OAA that remains in the cytoplasm must be recycled back to the mitochondria. It is first reduced to malate by cytoplasmic malate dehydrogenase (consuming NADH), then malate is oxidized to pyruvate by malic enzyme (generating NADPH), and pyruvate re-enters the mitochondria to be carboxylated back to OAA by pyruvate carboxylase.\n\nThe malic enzyme step is significant: it regenerates NADPH, one of the two NADPH sources for fatty acid synthesis. The other source is the pentose phosphate pathway (PPP). High demand for fatty acid synthesis therefore increases PPP flux and malic enzyme activity simultaneously.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Step 2: Acetyl-CoA Carboxylase (ACC): Rate-Limiting Step',x:'ACC catalyzes the committed, rate-limiting step: Acetyl-CoA + CO2 + ATP → Malonyl-CoA + ADP + Pi.\n\nMechanism: ACC uses biotin as a covalently bound CO2 carrier (attached via lysine, forming biocytin). ATP first activates CO2 as carboxyphosphate; biotin then accepts the CO2; finally, biotin donates CO2 to acetyl-CoA to form malonyl-CoA. This is identical in logic to pyruvate carboxylase and propionyl-CoA carboxylase.\n\nAllosteric activation: citrate polymerizes ACC monomers into active filaments. Citrate accumulation in the fed state signals that TCA is saturated and carbon should be redirected to fat synthesis.\n\nAllosteric inhibition: palmitoyl-CoA (the final product of FAS) inhibits ACC, providing product feedback inhibition. Palmitoyl-CoA also reverses the citrate-induced polymerization.\n\nHormonal regulation (covalent): glucagon and epinephrine activate PKA → PKA phosphorylates ACC at Ser-79 → ACC is inactive (monomeric form). Insulin activates a phosphoprotein phosphatase (via Akt) → removes the phosphate → ACC is active. AMPK also phosphorylates ACC at the same Ser-79 site during energy stress (low ATP), providing an energy-sensing brake on fatty acid synthesis.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Step 3: Fatty Acid Synthase (FAS): 7 Reactions Per Cycle',x:'FAS is a large homodimeric enzyme (each monomer ~270 kDa) with 7 catalytic domains on a single polypeptide chain. It loads substrates onto ACP (acyl carrier protein) via phosphopantetheine (a pantothenate-derived arm) and cycles through 7 reactions to add 2 carbons per cycle:\n\n1. Condensation (3-ketoacyl-ACP synthase/KS): acetyl or acyl group + malonyl-ACP → 3-ketoacyl-ACP + CO2. The CO2 that was added by ACC is released here, explaining why malonyl-CoA (not acetyl-CoA) is the 2-carbon donor: decarboxylation provides the thermodynamic driving force to push the condensation forward.\n\n2. Reduction (3-ketoacyl-ACP reductase): 3-ketoacyl-ACP + NADPH → 3-hydroxyacyl-ACP.\n\n3. Dehydration (3-hydroxyacyl-ACP dehydratase): 3-hydroxyacyl-ACP → enoyl-ACP + H2O.\n\n4. Reduction (enoyl-ACP reductase): enoyl-ACP + NADPH → acyl-ACP.\n\nReactions 2 and 4 each consume 1 NADPH, so each 2-carbon elongation cycle uses 2 NADPH.\n\nSteps 5-7 are the loading reactions: acetyl-CoA and malonyl-CoA are loaded onto the enzyme (via MAT, malonyl/acetyltransferase), and at cycle end the completed chain is transferred between enzyme domains.\n\nAfter 7 cycles starting from acetyl-CoA and adding 7 malonyl-CoA units (7 x 2 carbons = 14 carbons added to the initial 2-carbon acetyl primer), the 16-carbon palmitoyl chain is released by the thioesterase domain (TE). Total cost per palmitate: 8 acetyl-CoA, 7 ATP (for 7 malonyl-CoA syntheses), 14 NADPH.'},{t:'formula',x:'ACC: Acetyl-CoA + HCO3- + ATP  →[biotin]→  Malonyl-CoA + ADP + Pi\nFAS (net per cycle): Acyl-ACP + Malonyl-ACP  →  Acyl(+2C)-ACP + CO2 + 2 NADPH consumed\nOverall (palmitate): 8 Acetyl-CoA + 7 ATP + 14 NADPH  →  Palmitate + 8 CoA + 7 ADP + 7 Pi + 14 NADP+ + 6 H2O'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Elongation (ER) and Desaturation (SER)',x:'FAS produces palmitate (16:0). Longer chains and double bonds are added by separate enzyme systems:\n\nElongation: ER-associated elongases add 2-carbon units (from malonyl-CoA) to extend palmitate to stearate (18:0), arachidic acid (20:0), etc. NADPH is still the reductant.\n\nDesaturation: SER-associated desaturases (mixed-function oxidases, require O2 and NADH or NADPH) introduce double bonds. The key enzyme is stearoyl-CoA desaturase (SCD-1), which introduces a double bond at the delta-9 position (between carbons 9 and 10 counting from the carboxyl end), converting stearate (18:0) to oleate (18:1 delta-9).\n\nEssential fatty acids: humans cannot introduce double bonds beyond delta-9 (i.e., between C10 and the omega end). Therefore, linoleic acid (18:2 delta-9,12, an omega-6 FA) and alpha-linolenic acid (18:3 delta-9,12,15, an omega-3 FA) must come from the diet. From linoleic acid, the body can synthesize arachidonic acid (20:4 omega-6, precursor to prostaglandins and leukotrienes). From alpha-linolenic acid, the body can synthesize EPA and DHA (long-chain omega-3s), though efficiency is low.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'Why Malonyl-CoA and Not Acetyl-CoA as the 2-Carbon Donor',x:'If FAS simply condensed two acetyl-CoA units directly, the reaction would be thermodynamically unfavorable. By first carboxylating acetyl-CoA to malonyl-CoA (at the cost of 1 ATP), the subsequent decarboxylation during the FAS condensation step releases CO2 and provides the thermodynamic driving force (equivalent to about -4 kcal/mol) to push condensation forward. The CO2 added by ACC is the same CO2 released at FAS condensation, making the malonyl-CoA mechanism a thermodynamic trick rather than a net addition of CO2 to the chain. This is why carbon 1 of palmitate traces to the carbonyl of acetyl-CoA (the primer), and carbons 2-16 come from malonyl-CoA, all even-numbered except C-1.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'Biotin in Carboxylation Reactions: A Pattern',x:'Every biotin-dependent enzyme adds CO2 to a substrate using the same 3-step mechanism: (1) ATP activates bicarbonate to carboxyphosphate; (2) biotin-N1 attacks carboxyphosphate, forming carboxybiotin; (3) carboxybiotin donates CO2 to the acceptor substrate. The four biotin enzymes tested: ACC (acetyl-CoA → malonyl-CoA, FA synthesis), pyruvate carboxylase (pyruvate → OAA, GNG), propionyl-CoA carboxylase (propionyl-CoA → methylmalonyl-CoA, odd-chain FA catabolism and some AA catabolism), methylcrotonyl-CoA carboxylase (leucine catabolism). Biotin deficiency (caused by excess raw egg white consumption via avidin binding, or by deficiency of biotinidase) impairs all four enzymes simultaneously, presenting with dermatitis, alopecia, neurologic dysfunction, and lactic acidosis.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A researcher blocks ATP-citrate lyase (citrate lyase) in hepatocytes. Which of the following will directly result?',choices:['A) Increased TCA flux because citrate accumulates in the mitochondria','B) Decreased cytoplasmic acetyl-CoA availability, impairing fatty acid synthesis','C) Increased beta-oxidation because malonyl-CoA levels drop','D) Decreased NADPH because the malic enzyme reaction is accelerated'],answer:1,why:'ATP-citrate lyase cleaves cytoplasmic citrate into acetyl-CoA and OAA. Blocking it prevents mitochondrial acetyl-CoA from reaching the cytoplasm (since acetyl-CoA cannot directly cross the inner mitochondrial membrane). Without cytoplasmic acetyl-CoA, ACC cannot make malonyl-CoA and FAS cannot elongate chains: fatty acid synthesis fails. This is choice B.'},{stem:'A patient has a biotin deficiency due to excessive raw egg white intake. Which enzyme combination is impaired?',choices:['A) Acetyl-CoA carboxylase, pyruvate carboxylase, and propionyl-CoA carboxylase only','B) Acetyl-CoA carboxylase, pyruvate carboxylase, propionyl-CoA carboxylase, and methylcrotonyl-CoA carboxylase','C) Acetyl-CoA carboxylase and pyruvate carboxylase only, because these are the most biotin-dependent','D) Fatty acid synthase and HMG-CoA reductase, because both require biotin for NADPH regeneration'],answer:1,why:'All four biotin-dependent carboxylases are impaired in biotin deficiency: ACC (FA synthesis), pyruvate carboxylase (GNG), propionyl-CoA carboxylase (odd-chain FA and Ile/Val/Met catabolism), and methylcrotonyl-CoA carboxylase (leucine catabolism). FAS and HMG-CoA reductase use NADPH, not biotin. Choice B is correct.'}]},{id:'6.2',num:'6.2',title:'6.2 Beta-Oxidation of Fatty Acids',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Beta-oxidation is the primary catabolic pathway for fatty acids. It occurs in the mitochondrial matrix and systematically removes 2-carbon units as acetyl-CoA, transferring electrons to FAD and NAD+. The pathway proceeds from the carboxyl end of the fatty acid, each cycle shortening the chain by 2 carbons.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Activation: Fatty Acyl-CoA Formation',x:'Before entering any metabolic pathway, fatty acids must be activated by esterification to coenzyme A. Fatty acyl-CoA synthetase (also called acyl-CoA synthetase or fatty acid thiokinase) in the ER or outer mitochondrial membrane catalyzes: Fatty acid + CoA + ATP → Fatty acyl-CoA + AMP + PPi.\n\nThis reaction consumes 2 ATP equivalents (ATP is hydrolyzed to AMP + PPi, and pyrophosphatase then cleaves PPi to 2 Pi, making the reaction irreversible). The energy is used to form the high-energy thioester bond in fatty acyl-CoA.\n\nActivation occurs OUTSIDE the mitochondria. The resulting acyl-CoA cannot cross the inner mitochondrial membrane directly and requires the carnitine shuttle.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'The Carnitine Shuttle: Mitochondrial Import',x:'The inner mitochondrial membrane is impermeable to CoA and to long-chain acyl-CoA (>C12). Transport requires carnitine as a carrier:\n\nStep 1: Carnitine acyltransferase I (CAT-I, also called CPT-I, carnitine palmitoyltransferase I) on the OUTER face of the inner mitochondrial membrane transfers the acyl group from acyl-CoA to carnitine, forming acylcarnitine + free CoA.\n\nStep 2: The acylcarnitine/carnitine antiporter (translocase) moves acylcarnitine into the matrix in exchange for free carnitine leaving the matrix.\n\nStep 3: Carnitine acyltransferase II (CAT-II, CPT-II) on the INNER face of the inner mitochondrial membrane transfers the acyl group from carnitine back to CoA in the matrix, regenerating acyl-CoA for beta-oxidation.\n\nRegulation of the shuttle: Malonyl-CoA inhibits CAT-I (allosteric inhibition). When fatty acid synthesis is active (high malonyl-CoA), transport into the mitochondria for oxidation is blocked. When synthesis is off (glucagon/PKA phosphorylates and inactivates ACC, malonyl-CoA falls), CAT-I is released from inhibition and oxidation proceeds. This is the reciprocal regulation discussed in the Pinned Discussion.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'The 4 Reactions of Each Beta-Oxidation Cycle',x:'Once acyl-CoA is in the matrix, four reactions repeat for each cycle:\n\nReaction 1 (Oxidation, FAD-dependent): Acyl-CoA + FAD → Trans-2-enoyl-CoA + FADH2. Enzyme: Acyl-CoA dehydrogenase (several isoforms by chain length: VLCAD, LCAD, MCAD, SCAD). The double bond introduced is in the trans configuration (contrast with the cis double bonds in unsaturated dietary FAs).\n\nReaction 2 (Hydration): Trans-2-enoyl-CoA + H2O → L-3-hydroxyacyl-CoA. Enzyme: Enoyl-CoA hydratase. Water adds across the double bond to produce the L-stereospecific alcohol (only the L-isomer is a substrate for the next enzyme).\n\nReaction 3 (Oxidation, NAD+-dependent): L-3-hydroxyacyl-CoA + NAD+ → 3-ketoacyl-CoA + NADH. Enzyme: 3-hydroxyacyl-CoA dehydrogenase. This is the second oxidation step and generates 1 NADH per cycle.\n\nReaction 4 (Thiolysis): 3-ketoacyl-CoA + CoA → Acetyl-CoA + Acyl-CoA (shortened by 2C). Enzyme: Thiolase (3-ketoacyl-CoA thiolase). The acyl-CoA produced re-enters reaction 1 for the next cycle.'},{t:'formula',x:'Each cycle: Acyl-CoA(n) → FADH2 + NADH + Acetyl-CoA + Acyl-CoA(n-2)\nYield per cycle: 1 FADH2 (= ~1.5 ATP via ETC) + 1 NADH (= ~2.5 ATP via ETC) + 1 Acetyl-CoA (= ~10 ATP via TCA + ETC)\nPalmitoyl-CoA (16C): 7 cycles, 8 acetyl-CoA, 7 FADH2, 7 NADH\nGross ATP: 7(1.5) + 7(2.5) + 8(10) = 10.5 + 17.5 + 80 = 108 ATP\nNet ATP: 108 - 2 (activation cost) = 106 ATP total'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Odd-Chain Fatty Acid Oxidation',x:'Odd-chain fatty acids (found mainly in ruminant-derived foods: dairy, beef) produce propionyl-CoA (3 carbons) as the final product of the last beta-oxidation cycle instead of the usual acetyl-CoA.\n\nPropionyl-CoA cannot enter the TCA cycle directly. It is metabolized in 3 steps:\n\nStep 1: Propionyl-CoA carboxylase (requires BIOTIN): Propionyl-CoA + CO2 + ATP → D-methylmalonyl-CoA.\n\nStep 2: Methylmalonyl-CoA racemase: D-methylmalonyl-CoA → L-methylmalonyl-CoA.\n\nStep 3: Methylmalonyl-CoA mutase (requires adenosylcobalamin = vitamin B12 in its coenzyme form): L-methylmalonyl-CoA → succinyl-CoA.\n\nSuccinyl-CoA enters the TCA cycle at the succinyl-CoA step (between alpha-ketoglutarate dehydrogenase and succinyl-CoA synthetase). This makes odd-chain fatty acids (and the amino acids valine, isoleucine, threonine, and methionine, which also produce propionyl-CoA) the only lipid-derived carbons that can contribute to net gluconeogenesis (via succinyl-CoA → OAA).\n\nVitamin B12 deficiency: methylmalonyl-CoA accumulates → methylmalonic acid in urine (methylmalonic acidemia/aciduria). Also associated with neurologic deficits (myelin synthesis requires odd-chain FA metabolism), macrocytic megaloblastic anemia, and elevated homocysteine (from folate/B12 interdependence in methionine metabolism).'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Unsaturated Fatty Acid Oxidation',x:'Unsaturated fatty acids (e.g., oleate, 18:1 cis-delta-9) require extra enzymatic steps because the cis double bonds introduced by desaturases do not match the trans-2-enoyl-CoA intermediate that enoyl-CoA hydratase requires.\n\nFor monounsaturated FA (one double bond at an odd position, e.g., cis-delta-9): after 3 normal cycles bring the double bond to cis-delta-3 position, enoyl-CoA isomerase converts cis-3-enoyl-CoA to trans-2-enoyl-CoA, which then enters the normal pathway at the hydration step. Net effect: 1 fewer FADH2 per double bond (the first oxidation reaction is bypassed because the double bond already exists).\n\nFor polyunsaturated FA (multiple double bonds, e.g., linoleate 18:2 cis-delta-9,12): requires both enoyl-CoA isomerase AND 2,4-dienoyl-CoA reductase (uses 1 NADPH). Net effect: 1 fewer FADH2 per double bond at odd positions; the reductase handles double bonds at even positions.\n\nKey point for yield calculations: each double bond in the original fatty acid reduces ATP yield by approximately 1.5 ATP (the value of one FADH2).'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Peroxisomal Beta-Oxidation',x:'Very-long-chain fatty acids (VLCFAs, >C22) are too large to enter mitochondria via the carnitine shuttle and must first be shortened in peroxisomes.\n\nKey differences from mitochondrial beta-oxidation:\n1. The first oxidation step uses a FAD-containing oxidase that transfers electrons directly to O2, producing H2O2 (not FADH2). The H2O2 is detoxified by catalase. No ETC coupling; energy is released as heat.\n2. The remaining steps produce NADH and acetyl-CoA normally, and acetyl-CoA is eventually exported (as acetylcarnitine) to the mitochondria.\n3. The carnitine shuttle is NOT required for peroxisomal import (VLCFA enter peroxisomes via ABCD1 transporter in the peroxisomal membrane).\n\nZellweger syndrome (peroxisome biogenesis disorder): mutations in PEX genes prevent proper peroxisome assembly. Presents in neonates with severe hypotonia, seizures, dysmorphic facies, and early death. Elevated VLCFAs in plasma (diagnostic). Also accumulates phytanic acid (from dietary chlorophyll, which requires peroxisomal alpha-oxidation for the methyl branch). Distinguish from MCAD deficiency, which is the most common mitochondrial FA oxidation defect (presents with hypoglycemic crisis during fasting, elevated C8 acylcarnitine on newborn screen).'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'MCAD Deficiency: The Most Common FA Oxidation Defect',x:'Medium-chain acyl-CoA dehydrogenase (MCAD) deficiency is the most common inherited disorder of mitochondrial fatty acid oxidation (1:17,000 live births in the US). Without MCAD, medium-chain fatty acids (C6-C12) cannot be oxidized.\n\nClinical: hypoketotic hypoglycemia during fasting (cannot make ketones from fats, cannot maintain glucose without FA oxidation to spare glucose). Hepatomegaly, lethargy, vomiting, and encephalopathy during catabolic stress. Can present as sudden death mimicking SIDS.\n\nDiagnosis: elevated C8 (octanoylcarnitine) on newborn screening (tandem mass spectrometry). Urine organic acids show medium-chain dicarboxylic acids and acylglycines.\n\nKey discriminator: hypoketotic hypoglycemia (low ketones despite fasting) + medium-chain acylcarnitines. Contrast with ketotic hypoglycemia (where ketones are appropriately elevated), DKA (hyperglycemic, high ketones), and Jamaican vomiting sickness (hypoglycin inhibits MCAD-related enzymes, hypoketotic hypoglycemia).'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A 6-month-old presents with hypoketotic hypoglycemia after a 12-hour fast. Newborn screen shows elevated octanoylcarnitine (C8). Which enzyme is deficient and at which step of fatty acid oxidation?',choices:['A) Carnitine acyltransferase I (CAT-I), blocking mitochondrial import of long-chain fatty acids','B) Medium-chain acyl-CoA dehydrogenase (MCAD), blocking the first oxidation step for C6-C12 fatty acids','C) Enoyl-CoA hydratase, blocking the hydration step for all chain lengths','D) Thiolase, blocking the final thiolysis step and preventing acetyl-CoA release'],answer:1,why:'Elevated C8 acylcarnitine on newborn screening is the hallmark of MCAD deficiency. MCAD catalyzes the first FAD-dependent oxidation step for medium-chain (C6-C12) fatty acids. Without it, these substrates accumulate (detected as acylcarnitines) and cannot be oxidized to generate ketones or acetyl-CoA. The result is hypoketotic hypoglycemia during fasting. CAT-I deficiency would elevate long-chain acylcarnitines, not C8.'},{stem:'Malonyl-CoA is described as a reciprocal regulator of fatty acid synthesis and oxidation. Which mechanism explains its inhibitory effect on fatty acid oxidation?',choices:['A) Malonyl-CoA inhibits acetyl-CoA carboxylase by product feedback, reducing FA synthesis and liberating CoA for oxidation','B) Malonyl-CoA allosterically inhibits carnitine acyltransferase I (CAT-I), preventing fatty acyl-CoA transport into the mitochondrial matrix','C) Malonyl-CoA inhibits acyl-CoA dehydrogenase within the mitochondria, slowing all four beta-oxidation reactions','D) Malonyl-CoA activates hormone-sensitive lipase in adipose, increasing lipolysis and substrate competition'],answer:1,why:'Malonyl-CoA is an allosteric inhibitor of CAT-I (CPT-I) on the outer face of the inner mitochondrial membrane. This blocks the transfer of acyl groups from acyl-CoA to carnitine, preventing long-chain fatty acids from entering the mitochondrial matrix for oxidation. When ACC is active and malonyl-CoA is high (fed state), oxidation is off. This is the mechanistic basis of reciprocal regulation.'},{stem:'A 35-year-old man with pernicious anemia (B12 deficiency) is found to have methylmalonic acidemia. Which enzymatic step is impaired, and why does this cause neurologic symptoms?',choices:['A) Propionyl-CoA carboxylase requires B12 as its cofactor; impairment blocks succinyl-CoA from entering the TCA cycle','B) Methylmalonyl-CoA mutase requires adenosylcobalamin; impairment causes propionyl-CoA and odd-chain FA byproducts to accumulate, disrupting myelin synthesis','C) Enoyl-CoA hydratase requires methylcobalamin; impairment blocks hydration of unsaturated FA intermediates','D) Methylmalonyl-CoA racemase requires B12; impairment prevents L-methylmalonyl-CoA from forming, halting the entire TCA cycle'],answer:1,why:'Methylmalonyl-CoA mutase requires adenosylcobalamin (the coenzyme form of B12). Without it, L-methylmalonyl-CoA cannot be converted to succinyl-CoA, causing methylmalonic acid accumulation. Odd-chain fatty acids and certain amino acids (Val, Ile, Thr, Met) produce propionyl-CoA; their catabolism is blocked. Myelin synthesis in the nervous system requires normal odd-chain FA metabolism (myelin contains long-chain FAs including those derived from the propionyl-CoA pathway), explaining the neurologic phenotype. Propionyl-CoA carboxylase requires biotin, not B12.'}]},{id:'6.3',num:'6.3',title:'6.3 Ketone Body Metabolism',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Ketone bodies are water-soluble fuel molecules that allow the body to export mitochondrial acetyl-CoA equivalents from the liver to peripheral tissues during fasting and starvation. They are not metabolic waste products: they are a precisely regulated energy currency that substitutes for glucose in the brain and heart during prolonged fasting, thereby sparing muscle protein from gluconeogenic catabolism.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Ketone Body Synthesis (Ketogenesis): Hepatic Mitochondria Only',x:'Ketogenesis occurs exclusively in hepatic mitochondria and is active when acetyl-CoA supply exceeds TCA capacity.\n\nConditions that drive ketogenesis: (1) high fatty acid delivery to the liver (fasting, T1DM, prolonged exercise), which saturates the mitochondria with acetyl-CoA; (2) low OAA (oxaloacetate), because in the fasted/diabetic state, OAA is diverted to gluconeogenesis (PEPCK converts OAA to PEP). Without OAA to condense with acetyl-CoA (forming citrate), the TCA cycle stalls and acetyl-CoA is diverted to ketogenesis.\n\nSteps of ketogenesis:\n1. Two acetyl-CoA condense to form acetoacetyl-CoA via thiolase (same thiolase as beta-oxidation, running in reverse direction).\n2. HMG-CoA synthase (mitochondrial isoform) condenses acetoacetyl-CoA with a third acetyl-CoA to form HMG-CoA (3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-CoA) + free CoA.\n3. HMG-CoA lyase cleaves HMG-CoA → acetoacetate + acetyl-CoA. Acetoacetate is the primary ketone body product.\n4. 3-Hydroxybutyrate dehydrogenase reduces acetoacetate to beta-hydroxybutyrate (using NADH). In highly reduced mitochondria (lots of NADH from beta-oxidation), most acetoacetate is converted to beta-hydroxybutyrate.\n5. Acetoacetate can also spontaneously decarboxylate to acetone + CO2 (the compound responsible for the fruity breath odor in DKA).\n\nHMG-CoA lyase: key regulatory enzyme. Deficiency causes life-threatening hypoglycemia + ketoacidosis in infants because neither glucose (via GNG from acetyl-CoA) nor ketones can be made properly.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Ketone Body Utilization: Which Tissues and Why',x:'Tissues that can use ketones: brain (after 3-5 days of starvation, ketones supply up to 70% of brain energy needs), cardiac muscle (preferentially uses ketones and fatty acids at all times), renal cortex, skeletal muscle.\n\nThe utilization pathway (in the cytoplasm of consumer tissues, then in mitochondria):\n1. Beta-hydroxybutyrate is oxidized back to acetoacetate by 3-hydroxybutyrate dehydrogenase (the reverse of synthesis).\n2. Succinyl-CoA transfers its CoA to acetoacetate via succinyl-CoA:acetoacetate CoA-transferase (also called thiophorase or SCOT). This produces acetoacetyl-CoA + succinate.\n3. Thiolase cleaves acetoacetyl-CoA → 2 acetyl-CoA → TCA cycle.\n\nThe liver CANNOT use ketones: it lacks succinyl-CoA transferase (thiophorase/SCOT). This is a critical logic point for the MCAT: the liver makes ketones but cannot burn them. The liver uses a different CoA-transferase for its own acetoacetyl-CoA metabolism (in the direction of synthesis).\n\nAlso important: erythrocytes (RBCs) lack mitochondria entirely and therefore cannot oxidize either fatty acids or ketones. RBCs rely entirely on glycolysis.'},{t:'formula',x:'Synthesis (liver mitochondria):\n2 Acetyl-CoA → Acetoacetyl-CoA → (+ Acetyl-CoA) → HMG-CoA →[HMG-CoA lyase]→ Acetoacetate + Acetyl-CoA\nAcetoacetate + NADH →[3-HB dehydrogenase]→ Beta-hydroxybutyrate\nAcetoacetate (spontaneous) → Acetone + CO2\n\nUtilization (peripheral tissues):\nBeta-hydroxybutyrate → Acetoacetate →[SCOT, uses succinyl-CoA]→ Acetoacetyl-CoA →[thiolase]→ 2 Acetyl-CoA → TCA'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'DKA vs. Starvation Ketosis: Clinical Distinction',x:'Both diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA) and starvation ketosis produce elevated blood ketone bodies, but they differ in mechanism, severity, and glucose levels:\n\nStarvation ketosis: gradual, adaptive. Blood ketones reach 2-6 mM after days of fasting. Blood glucose is low but not dangerously so (GNG maintains it). Serum pH remains near normal (buffering systems compensate). The process is regulated by insulin levels that are low but not absent.\n\nDKA (typically T1DM): absolute insulin deficiency (or severe relative deficiency in sick T2DM patients). Blood glucose is markedly elevated (>250 mg/dL, often 400-600 mg/dL) because glucagon-driven GNG and glycogenolysis are unrestrained AND glucose cannot enter cells (no insulin). Ketones reach 15-25 mM (more severe than starvation). Anion-gap metabolic acidosis (normal anion gap is 8-12, in DKA often 20-30+). Osmotic diuresis from glucosuria causes hypovolemia. Life-threatening without insulin replacement.\n\nKey discriminator: blood glucose. Low in starvation ketosis; very high in DKA. Also: DKA patients often have hyperkalemia on presentation (insulin normally drives K+ into cells; without insulin, K+ accumulates in blood despite total body K+ depletion from urinary losses).'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'HMG-CoA: Mitochondrial vs. Cytoplasmic Pools',x:'HMG-CoA is produced in both compartments but for different purposes:\n\nMitochondrial HMG-CoA (via mitochondrial HMG-CoA synthase): intermediate in ketogenesis. Cleaved by HMG-CoA lyase to make acetoacetate.\n\nCytoplasmic HMG-CoA (via cytoplasmic HMG-CoA synthase): intermediate in cholesterol synthesis. Reduced by HMG-CoA reductase (the statin target) in the ER membrane to make mevalonate.\n\nThese are separate enzyme isoforms in different compartments, regulated differently. Lovastatin, atorvastatin, and other statins inhibit only the ER-bound HMG-CoA reductase (cholesterol synthesis) and do not affect mitochondrial ketogenesis.'},{t:'box',kind:'why',label:'Why Low OAA Drives Ketogenesis',x:'OAA is required to condense with acetyl-CoA (citrate synthase: acetyl-CoA + OAA → citrate) to enter the TCA cycle. In the fasted or diabetic state, glucagon-driven gluconeogenesis consumes OAA: PEPCK converts OAA to PEP. As OAA falls, TCA entry for acetyl-CoA is blocked. Acetyl-CoA cannot enter TCA and instead is diverted to ketogenesis. This is why fasting automatically generates ketones even without a genetic defect: the same gluconeogenic pathway that helps maintain blood glucose simultaneously forces hepatic acetyl-CoA into ketone production. The two processes (GNG and ketogenesis) are therefore co-induced by the same metabolic state.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'After 5 days of starvation, the brain derives the majority of its energy from ketone bodies rather than glucose. Which enzyme in the brain is required for this, and why is this enzyme absent in the liver?',choices:['A) HMG-CoA lyase converts HMG-CoA to acetoacetate; the liver lacks this enzyme and instead uses HMG-CoA for cholesterol synthesis','B) Succinyl-CoA:acetoacetate CoA-transferase (SCOT) activates acetoacetate for oxidation; the liver lacks SCOT because it synthesizes rather than consumes ketones','C) Thiolase cleaves acetoacetyl-CoA; the liver lacks thiolase and therefore cannot generate acetyl-CoA from ketones','D) 3-Hydroxybutyrate dehydrogenase oxidizes beta-hydroxybutyrate to acetoacetate; the liver lacks this enzyme because it is a synthesis-only organ'],answer:1,why:'SCOT (succinyl-CoA transferase / thiophorase) is required to activate acetoacetate to acetoacetyl-CoA by transferring CoA from succinyl-CoA. This is the committed, unique step in ketone utilization. The liver is the sole synthetic organ for ketones and specifically lacks SCOT, preventing futile cycling of making and burning ketones simultaneously. The brain, heart, and renal cortex all express SCOT and can therefore oxidize ketones.'},{stem:'A type 1 diabetic patient presents with blood glucose of 520 mg/dL, pH 7.1, and serum potassium of 5.8 mEq/L. Why is the potassium elevated despite total body potassium depletion?',choices:['A) Insulin normally suppresses aldosterone; without insulin, aldosterone rises and promotes potassium retention','B) Insulin normally drives potassium into cells via Na+/K+-ATPase stimulation; without insulin, potassium remains in the extracellular space even as total body potassium is depleted by osmotic diuresis','C) Acidosis causes potassium to shift from cells to blood in exchange for hydrogen ions buffering the intracellular space','D) Both B and C are contributing mechanisms'],answer:3,why:'Both mechanisms operate simultaneously in DKA. Insulin normally stimulates Na+/K+-ATPase and drives K+ intracellularly; its absence keeps K+ extracellular. Additionally, the metabolic acidosis causes H+ to shift into cells for buffering; to maintain electrochemical balance, K+ shifts out of cells into blood. Total body K+ is actually depleted (lost in urine via osmotic diuresis and through aldosterone activation from hypovolemia), but serum K+ is high. Insulin treatment in DKA drives K+ back into cells, causing serum K+ to plummet, which is why K+ must be repleted aggressively during treatment.'}]},{id:'6.4',num:'6.4',title:'6.4 Cholesterol Synthesis and Regulation',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Cholesterol is synthesized de novo in virtually all nucleated cells, but primarily in the liver and intestine. It is the precursor for steroid hormones, bile acids, and vitamin D, and it is an essential component of cell membranes (modulates fluidity by intercalating between phospholipids). The mevalonate pathway, named for its first committed product, generates cholesterol through a lengthy series of reactions.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'HMG-CoA Reductase: The Rate-Limiting Step',x:'HMG-CoA reductase (HMGCR) catalyzes the committed, rate-limiting step: HMG-CoA + 2 NADPH → Mevalonate + 2 NADP+ + CoA.\n\nLocation: embedded in the ER membrane (cytoplasmic face), placing it at the interface of the cytoplasm where NADPH is available.\n\nThe reaction reduces the CoA thioester to a primary alcohol (mevalonate). Two NADPH are consumed per mevalonate produced.\n\nRegulation at multiple levels:\n\n1. Transcriptional: SREBP (sterol-response element binding protein) transcription factors activate the genes for HMGCR and the LDL receptor. When intracellular cholesterol is high, the SCAP/SREBP complex is retained in the ER by INSIG proteins (insulin-induced gene proteins). When cholesterol is low, INSIG releases the complex, SCAP escorts SREBP to the Golgi where it is cleaved by S1P and S2P proteases, and the active SREBP fragment translocates to the nucleus to induce HMGCR and LDLR gene transcription.\n\n2. Post-translational: high sterol levels promote HMGCR ubiquitination and proteasomal degradation. Insulin (via phosphatase) activates HMGCR by dephosphorylation. Glucagon and AMP/AMPK phosphorylate and inactivate HMGCR.\n\n3. Allosteric: mevalonate pathway intermediates (oxysterols) inhibit SCAP, keeping SREBP in the ER.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'The Mevalonate Pathway: From Mevalonate to Cholesterol',x:'Mevalonate is phosphorylated twice and then decarboxylated to isopentenyl pyrophosphate (IPP, a 5-carbon isoprene unit). IPP is the building block for all isoprenoids.\n\nTwo IPP units condense to form geranyl-PP (10C), then one more IPP is added to form farnesyl-PP (15C). Two farnesyl-PP units condense (via squalene synthase) to form squalene (30C). Squalene is then cyclized (via squalene monooxygenase and lanosterol synthase) to form lanosterol (the first sterol intermediate), which is then modified over 19 additional steps to form cholesterol.\n\nOther important products of the mevalonate pathway (not just cholesterol):\n- Farnesyl-PP: substrate for protein farnesylation (post-translational modification of Ras, lamin A, and other signaling proteins that anchor them to membranes)\n- Geranylgeranyl-PP: substrate for geranylgeranylation (Rho GTPases, Rab proteins)\n- Dolichol: lipid carrier for N-linked glycosylation in the ER\n- Ubiquinone (CoQ10): electron carrier in the mitochondrial ETC\n\nThis explains why statins can affect not just cholesterol but also Ras signaling (relevant in cancer), prenylation of Rho-family GTPases (pleiotropic anti-inflammatory statin effects), and CoQ10 levels (rarely, statin-associated myopathy is partly attributed to reduced CoQ10 in muscle mitochondria).'},{t:'formula',x:'Acetyl-CoA (x2) → Acetoacetyl-CoA → HMG-CoA →[HMG-CoA reductase, 2 NADPH]→ Mevalonate\nMevalonate → Isopentenyl-PP (IPP, 5C)\nIPP (x2) → Geranyl-PP (10C) →[+ IPP]→ Farnesyl-PP (15C)\nFarnesyl-PP (x2) →[squalene synthase]→ Squalene (30C) → Lanosterol → Cholesterol (27C)\nSide products: Dolichol, Ubiquinone, Farnesyl groups, Geranylgeranyl groups'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'SREBP Feedback Mechanism: Sensing and Response',x:'The SREBP system is one of the most elegant feedback loops in cell biology. Its mechanism:\n\n1. In the ER membrane, SREBP is bound to SCAP (SREBP cleavage-activating protein).\n2. When cholesterol is abundant, INSIG proteins (INSIG-1 and INSIG-2) bind SCAP and retain the SCAP/SREBP complex in the ER membrane. SREBP cannot be processed and gene transcription of HMGCR and LDLR is low.\n3. When cholesterol falls below a threshold, INSIG releases SCAP. SCAP escorts SREBP to the Golgi.\n4. In the Golgi, site-1 protease (S1P) cleaves the luminal loop of SREBP, then site-2 protease (S2P, a metalloprotease) cleaves within the transmembrane domain, releasing the N-terminal transcription factor domain into the cytoplasm.\n5. The active SREBP fragment enters the nucleus, binds sterol regulatory elements (SREs) in gene promoters, and activates transcription of HMGCR (make more cholesterol) and LDLR (import more cholesterol from blood).\n\nFamilial hypercholesterolemia (FH) disrupts step 5 indirectly: LDLR is absent or dysfunctional, so LDL cholesterol cannot be imported even when SREBP is active and LDLR is transcribed. The liver continues making HMGCR and fails to sense adequate intracellular cholesterol, leading to more synthesis despite already high circulating LDL.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Statins: Mechanism, Efficacy, and Side Effects',x:'Statins (lovastatin, atorvastatin, rosuvastatin, simvastatin, etc.) are competitive inhibitors of HMG-CoA reductase. They are structural analogs of the transition state of the HMG-CoA → mevalonate reaction.\n\nMechanism of LDL lowering: statins reduce hepatic cholesterol synthesis → hepatic intracellular cholesterol falls → SREBP escapes INSIG retention → LDLR gene is transcribed → more LDL receptors appear on hepatocyte surface → more LDL is cleared from the blood.\n\nThe primary effect is therefore on receptor upregulation rather than direct synthesis inhibition (hepatic cholesterol synthesis accounts for only a portion of total body cholesterol; the LDLR upregulation effect is actually more clinically significant).\n\nSide effects: myopathy (muscle pain, elevated CK), rarely rhabdomyolysis (particularly with high-dose statins or drug-drug interactions via CYP3A4, e.g., with some macrolide antibiotics, antifungals, cyclosporine). Hepatotoxicity (rare). Teratogenic (contraindicated in pregnancy, cholesterol is essential for fetal development). Reduced CoQ10 synthesis (may contribute to myopathy).\n\nFor familial hypercholesterolemia heterozygotes: statins partially work (upregulate the one functional allele\'s LDLR). For homozygous FH (no functional LDLR): statins are largely ineffective; PCSK9 inhibitors (which prevent LDLR degradation) and lomitapide (MTP inhibitor, blocks VLDL assembly) are alternative strategies.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'Bile Acid Synthesis and Enterohepatic Circulation',x:'Cholesterol is converted to bile acids (primary: cholic acid, chenodeoxycholic acid) in the liver by a series of hydroxylation reactions, the rate-limiting step being 7-alpha-hydroxylase (CYP7A1). Bile acids are conjugated to glycine or taurine (forming bile salts), stored in the gallbladder, and released into the duodenum after meals to emulsify dietary fat.\n\nAbout 95% of bile acids are reabsorbed in the terminal ileum and returned to the liver via the portal circulation (enterohepatic circulation). The small amount lost in feces is replaced by de novo synthesis from cholesterol.\n\nBile acid sequestrants (cholestyramine, colestipol) bind bile acids in the intestinal lumen, preventing reabsorption. This forces the liver to synthesize more bile acids from cholesterol, which lowers hepatic cholesterol, induces LDLR upregulation via SREBP, and lowers serum LDL. They can be combined with statins (complementary mechanisms) for severe hypercholesterolemia.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A patient with homozygous familial hypercholesterolemia has no functional LDL receptors. Despite this, she is prescribed atorvastatin. Which aspect of statin mechanism would most likely still benefit this patient?',choices:['A) Statins directly inhibit VLDL secretion from the liver, reducing circulating LDL precursor','B) Statins reduce LDL levels primarily by activating LDLR transcription via SREBP; without any LDLR this pathway cannot lower plasma LDL','C) Statins reduce mevalonate pathway intermediates used for Ras prenylation, providing pleiotropic cardiovascular protection','D) Statins activate LPL in capillaries, increasing IDL to LDL conversion and clearing LDL faster'],answer:2,why:'In homozygous FH, there are no functional LDL receptors to upregulate; the primary mechanism by which statins lower LDL (inducing LDLR via SREBP) is therefore ineffective. However, statins still reduce the mevalonate pathway, lowering farnesylation/geranylgeranylation of Ras, Rho, and Rac GTPases, which mediates anti-inflammatory, antiproliferative, and endothelial-stabilizing effects (pleiotropic statin benefits) independent of LDL lowering. These pleiotropic effects may still provide some cardiovascular benefit.'},{stem:'INSIG proteins play a key role in cholesterol homeostasis. When intracellular cholesterol is low, INSIG releases SCAP, which escorts SREBP to the Golgi for cleavage. What is the direct consequence of INSIG releasing SCAP?',choices:['A) SREBP is immediately active as a transcription factor without requiring proteolytic cleavage','B) SCAP transports SREBP to the Golgi where S1P and S2P cleave it, releasing the active transcription factor domain','C) SCAP directly binds to sterol regulatory elements in nuclear DNA to recruit SREBP','D) INSIG release causes HMGCR to be dephosphorylated and activated in the ER membrane'],answer:1,why:'INSIG retains the SCAP/SREBP complex in the ER when cholesterol is high. When cholesterol falls, INSIG releases SCAP, which then escorts SREBP to the Golgi. In the Golgi, site-1 protease (S1P) cleaves the luminal loop and site-2 protease (S2P) cleaves the transmembrane domain, releasing the N-terminal active SREBP fragment. This fragment then translocates to the nucleus and activates HMGCR and LDLR gene transcription. SREBP requires proteolytic processing; it is not inherently active upon SCAP binding alone.'}]},{id:'6.5',num:'6.5',title:'6.5 Lipoprotein Biology',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Lipoproteins are spherical particles that transport hydrophobic lipids through the aqueous bloodstream. Each particle has a core of triglycerides (TAG) and cholesteryl esters, a surface monolayer of phospholipids and free cholesterol, and one or more apolipoproteins that determine receptor targeting and enzyme activation. The five major classes differ in size, density, lipid composition, and metabolic fate.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Chylomicrons: Dietary Fat Transport',x:'Chylomicrons are assembled in intestinal enterocytes in response to dietary fat absorption. They are the largest and least dense lipoproteins (rich in TAG, poor in protein).\n\nAssembly: free fatty acids and monoglycerides absorbed from the intestinal lumen are re-esterified to TAG in the ER. Microsomal triglyceride transfer protein (MTP) loads TAG onto the nascent ApoB-48 backbone. Chylomicrons are secreted into intestinal lymphatics (lacteals) → thoracic duct → left subclavian vein (bypassing portal circulation, which is why dietary fat does not immediately reach the liver).\n\nKey apolipoprotein: ApoB-48. This is a truncated form of ApoB-100 produced by intestinal cells via RNA editing (apobec-1 edits the mRNA at codon 2153, introducing a stop codon that truncates the protein to 48% of the full length). ApoB-48 is required for chylomicron assembly but does NOT bind the LDL receptor (because it lacks the C-terminal receptor-binding domain present in ApoB-100).\n\nIn circulation, chylomicrons acquire ApoC-II and ApoE from HDL. ApoC-II activates lipoprotein lipase (LPL) in capillary endothelium, which hydrolyzes TAG to free fatty acids (FFA) + glycerol. FFA are taken up by muscle (fuel) and adipose (storage). As TAG is depleted, the particle shrinks to a chylomicron remnant (now rich in cholesterol esters and ApoE).\n\nChylomicron remnant uptake: the liver takes up remnants via ApoE binding to hepatic LDL-receptor-related protein (LRP) and LDL receptors on hepatocytes.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'VLDL, IDL, and LDL: Endogenous Lipid Transport',x:'VLDL (very-low-density lipoprotein): assembled in hepatocytes by MTP loading TAG onto ApoB-100. The liver packages excess endogenous TAG (from de novo lipogenesis and re-esterified FFA from adipose lipolysis) into VLDL for export.\n\nKey apolipoproteins: ApoB-100 (structural, required for VLDL assembly), ApoC-II (acquired from HDL in circulation, activates LPL), ApoE (acquired from HDL, for remnant uptake).\n\nVLDL in capillaries: LPL (activated by ApoC-II) hydrolyzes VLDL-TAG, delivering FFA to muscle and adipose. VLDL progressively loses TAG and becomes denser, first forming IDL (intermediate-density lipoprotein / VLDL remnant).\n\nIDL fate: about 50% is taken up by the liver via ApoE and ApoB-100 binding to LDL receptors. The other 50% is further processed by hepatic lipase (HL) in the liver sinusoids, removing remaining TAG and phospholipids. ApoC-II and ApoE are returned to HDL. The remnant particle, now rich in cholesteryl esters and containing only ApoB-100, is LDL.\n\nLDL (low-density lipoprotein): the primary cholesterol delivery vehicle to peripheral tissues. LDL is taken up by cells via the LDL receptor (LDLR) in clathrin-coated pits (receptor-mediated endocytosis). Inside the endosome, low pH causes LDL to dissociate from LDLR; the receptor is recycled to the cell surface. Lysosomal acid lipase (LAL) hydrolyzes cholesteryl esters to free cholesterol + fatty acid.\n\nPCSK9 mechanism: the liver secretes PCSK9 (a protease), which binds LDLR on the cell surface and routes it to lysosomal degradation instead of recycling. PCSK9 inhibitors (evolocumab, alirocumab) prevent LDLR degradation, increasing surface receptor density and dramatically lowering LDL.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'HDL and Reverse Cholesterol Transport',x:'HDL (high-density lipoprotein) is the smallest and densest lipoprotein, with the highest protein-to-lipid ratio. It is synthesized as discoidal, lipid-poor nascent HDL by the liver and intestine, incorporating ApoA-I as its major structural apolipoprotein.\n\nReverse cholesterol transport: HDL collects excess cholesterol from peripheral cells and returns it to the liver.\n\nStep 1: ABC transporters (ABCA1 on macrophages and peripheral cells) actively export free cholesterol to lipid-poor ApoA-I (nascent HDL), forming discoidal pre-beta HDL.\n\nStep 2: LCAT (lecithin:cholesterol acyltransferase), activated by ApoA-I, esterifies free cholesterol on the HDL surface: phosphatidylcholine + free cholesterol → lysophosphatidylcholine + cholesteryl ester. Cholesteryl esters migrate to the hydrophobic core, converting discoidal HDL to the mature spherical HDL3, then HDL2 (larger, more lipid-rich).\n\nTangier disease: ABCA1 deficiency. Cannot export cholesterol from peripheral cells to ApoA-I. Cholesterol esters accumulate in macrophages of lymph nodes, tonsils (orange tonsils, pathognomonic), spleen, and liver. HDL is nearly absent (ApoA-I is rapidly catabolized without lipid loading). Accelerated atherosclerosis.\n\nStep 3: mature HDL delivers cholesteryl esters to the liver via two routes:\n(a) Selective uptake: SR-BI receptor on hepatocytes directly extracts cholesteryl esters from HDL without degrading the particle (HDL lipid is absorbed; the lipid-poor HDL particle is recycled).\n(b) CETP (cholesteryl ester transfer protein) transfers cholesteryl esters from HDL to VLDL and LDL in exchange for TAG. This lowers HDL cholesterol and raises VLDL/LDL cholesterol content. CETP inhibitors were developed as drugs but have had mixed clinical results.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Apolipoproteins: Functions and Associations',x:'ApoA-I: major structural protein of HDL. Activates LCAT (reverse cholesterol transport). Low ApoA-I = high cardiovascular risk. Produced by liver and intestine.\n\nApoB-48: structural protein of chylomicrons. Made only in the intestine. Does not bind LDL receptor. Identifies the particle as intestinal origin.\n\nApoB-100: structural protein of VLDL, IDL, and LDL. Made only in the liver. Binds LDL receptor (via its C-terminal domain). Familial defective ApoB-100: mutation at Arg-3500 prevents LDL receptor binding; clinically similar to familial hypercholesterolemia.\n\nApoC-I: inhibits ApoE binding to receptors (slows VLDL/remnant clearance).\n\nApoC-II: activates lipoprotein lipase (LPL) on capillary endothelium. ApoC-II deficiency: severe hypertriglyceridemia (Type I hyperlipoproteinemia), eruptive xanthomas, pancreatitis, lipemia retinalis. Cannot clear chylomicrons or VLDL TAG.\n\nApoC-III: inhibits LPL and ApoE-mediated remnant uptake (slows TAG clearance).\n\nApoE: mediates remnant uptake by LDL receptor and LRP on hepatocytes. ApoE2/E3/E4 polymorphisms: ApoE4 is a major genetic risk factor for late-onset Alzheimer disease (independent of its role in lipoprotein metabolism). ApoE2 is associated with Type III hyperlipoproteinemia (dysbetalipoproteinemia, elevated IDL, palmar xanthomas) because ApoE2 binds hepatic receptors poorly, slowing IDL clearance.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Lipoprotein Lipase (LPL): Regulation and Clinical Relevance',x:'LPL is synthesized by adipocytes, muscle cells, and other parenchymal cells but is secreted and anchored to the luminal surface of capillary endothelium by heparan sulfate proteoglycans.\n\nFunction: hydrolyzes TAG in VLDL and chylomicrons, releasing FFA and glycerol for uptake by underlying tissues.\n\nActivation: ApoC-II (required cofactor; without it, LPL has minimal activity). Insulin upregulates LPL expression in adipose (promotes fat storage in the fed state) and downregulates it in muscle. After a meal, adipose LPL rises, muscle LPL falls; during fasting, the pattern reverses.\n\nHeparin releases LPL from the endothelial surface into plasma (heparin displaces the heparan sulfate binding). This is used clinically: intravenous heparin injection followed by measurement of plasma LPL activity is used to diagnose LPL deficiency.\n\nLPL deficiency (Type I hyperlipoproteinemia): markedly elevated chylomicrons and VLDL-TAG. Serum appears milky (lipemia). Presents with recurrent pancreatitis (chylomicronemia syndrome), eruptive xanthomas over buttocks and elbows, hepatosplenomegaly, lipemia retinalis. NO increased risk of atherosclerosis (chylomicrons are too large to enter the arterial intima). Treatment: very low-fat diet (<10-15% calories from fat), medium-chain TAG supplements (MCTs bypass LPL by entering portal circulation directly).'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Familial Hypercholesterolemia (FH): LDL Receptor Defects',x:'FH is caused by loss-of-function mutations in LDLR (LDL receptor gene), less commonly by gain-of-function mutations in PCSK9, or by mutations in ApoB-100 (preventing receptor binding).\n\nMechanism: without functional LDLR, LDL cannot be removed from the blood by the liver. LDL accumulates. The liver also cannot sense adequate intracellular cholesterol, so SREBP remains active, driving more HMGCR and paradoxically more cholesterol synthesis despite high circulating LDL.\n\nHeterozygous FH (1:250-500 population): one functional LDLR allele. LDL is 2-3x normal (200-400 mg/dL). Premature coronary artery disease (MI in men by 40s-50s). Tendon xanthomas (cholesterol deposits in Achilles tendon and extensor tendons of hands), corneal arcus before age 45.\n\nHomozygous FH (1:1,000,000): no functional LDLR. LDL is 4-6x normal (>500 mg/dL). MI possible in childhood. Also tuberous xanthomas (over joints, buttocks) and xanthelasmas (periorbital).\n\nTreatment logic: statins (upregulate remaining functional LDLR, work in heterozygotes), bile acid sequestrants (synergistic: force more cholesterol into bile acid synthesis), PCSK9 inhibitors (preserve LDLR recycling, work even with one functional allele). Homozygous FH: LDL apheresis (physical removal of LDL from plasma, weekly/biweekly), lomitapide (MTP inhibitor, blocks VLDL and chylomicron assembly), evinacumab (anti-ANGPTL3 antibody, reduces VLDL and LDL via LPL-independent mechanism).'},{t:'list',x:['Chylomicrons: intestinal origin, ApoB-48, dietary TAG, removed by LPL (ApoC-II) + hepatic remnant uptake (ApoE)','VLDL: hepatic origin, ApoB-100, endogenous TAG, removed by LPL in periphery → IDL','IDL: VLDL remnant, ApoB-100 + ApoE, 50% cleared by liver (LDLR), 50% → LDL by hepatic lipase','LDL: cholesterol-rich, ApoB-100 only, cleared by LDLR on hepatocytes and peripheral cells','HDL: liver/intestine origin, ApoA-I, reverse cholesterol transport via LCAT and ABCA1, cleared by SR-BI in liver']}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A 45-year-old man presents with recurrent pancreatitis. His fasting serum appears milky. Triglycerides are 3,800 mg/dL, total cholesterol is 280 mg/dL. Intravenous heparin injection fails to raise plasma LPL activity. He has normal fasting glucose. Which diagnosis and underlying mechanism best explain these findings?',choices:['A) Familial hypercholesterolemia: absent LDLR causes chylomicron accumulation because chylomicrons carry cholesterol','B) ApoC-II deficiency: without the obligate LPL activator, chylomicrons and VLDL cannot be cleared, causing severe hypertriglyceridemia','C) LPL deficiency: absent LPL means TAG-rich lipoproteins cannot be hydrolyzed; heparin does not raise plasma LPL activity because no LPL is present to release','D) Tangier disease: ABCA1 deficiency prevents cholesterol export, and accumulated cholesterol inhibits LPL activity'],answer:2,why:'Milky serum + recurrent pancreatitis + markedly elevated TAG (>1,000 mg/dL chylomicronemia) + failure of heparin to release plasma LPL = LPL deficiency. LPL is anchored to capillary endothelium by heparan sulfate; heparin displaces it into plasma. If LPL activity is absent even after heparin, no LPL is present. ApoC-II deficiency would show some residual LPL release by heparin (LPL is present but cannot be activated). Choice C is correct. FH primarily elevates cholesterol, not TAG.'},{stem:'In Tangier disease, orange tonsils and near-absent plasma HDL are observed. What is the primary molecular defect and how does it cause the phenotype?',choices:['A) ApoA-I is absent; without the structural protein, HDL cannot be assembled, and cholesterol accumulates in peripheral tissues','B) ABCA1 transporter is deficient; cholesterol cannot be exported from macrophages to lipid-poor ApoA-I, causing ApoA-I rapid catabolism and cholesterol ester accumulation in macrophages of lymphoid organs','C) LCAT is absent; cholesterol on nascent HDL cannot be esterified, preventing HDL maturation and causing free cholesterol accumulation in tissues','D) SR-BI is overexpressed in macrophages; it extracts cholesterol from HDL into macrophages instead of delivering it to the liver'],answer:1,why:'Tangier disease is caused by ABCA1 (ATP-binding cassette transporter A1) loss-of-function mutations. ABCA1 is required to export free cholesterol from intracellular pools to lipid-poor ApoA-I in the extracellular space. Without ABCA1, ApoA-I cannot be lipidated; lipid-free ApoA-I is rapidly filtered by the kidney and catabolized, so plasma HDL is nearly absent. Cholesteryl esters accumulate in the reticuloendothelial system (macrophages in tonsils, liver, spleen, lymph nodes), producing the characteristic orange tonsils. LCAT deficiency (Fish-eye disease or LCAT deficiency) is a related disorder but presents differently.'},{stem:'A patient with Type III hyperlipoproteinemia (dysbetalipoproteinemia) is found to be homozygous for ApoE2. Which of the following best explains the pathophysiology?',choices:['A) ApoE2 binds the LDL receptor with higher affinity than ApoE3 or E4, causing excess LDL clearance and compensatory overproduction of VLDL','B) ApoE2 binds the LDL receptor and LRP with lower affinity than ApoE3 or E4, impairing IDL and chylomicron remnant clearance, causing IDL and remnant accumulation','C) ApoE2 activates LPL more effectively than ApoE3, causing excess FFA release and re-esterification into IDL','D) ApoE2 cannot associate with HDL, preventing reverse cholesterol transport and causing IDL to become cholesterol-enriched'],answer:1,why:'ApoE mediates hepatic uptake of VLDL remnants (IDL) and chylomicron remnants via binding to LDL receptors and LRP. ApoE2 has an Arg-158-Cys substitution that reduces its affinity for both receptors by approximately 50-fold compared to ApoE3. In ApoE2/E2 homozygotes, IDL and remnants accumulate in the blood, presenting as elevated IDL (broad beta band on lipoprotein electrophoresis), palmar xanthomas (pathognomonic, yellow deposits in palmar creases), and tuberous xanthomas. This requires a second hit (hypothyroidism, obesity, diabetes) to become clinically manifest in most ApoE2/E2 individuals.'}]},{id:'6.6',num:'6.6',title:'6.6 Integrated Regulation and Clinical High-Yield Patterns',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'MCAT vignettes in lipid metabolism typically test regulation (which enzymes are on or off in a given hormonal state), yield calculations (ATP from a specific fatty acid), or clinical phenotype mapping (which apolipoprotein or enzyme defect causes a specific presentation). This section integrates those patterns and provides the discriminators needed to confidently parse vignettes.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Hormonal State Summary: Lipid Metabolism',x:'Fed state (insulin dominant):\n- ACC is dephosphorylated (active) → malonyl-CoA high → CAT-I inhibited → beta-oxidation off\n- FAS is expressed (insulin upregulates FAS transcription)\n- HMG-CoA reductase is dephosphorylated (active) → cholesterol synthesis on\n- LPL in adipose is upregulated (insulin effect) → chylomicron TAG delivered to adipose for storage\n- HSL in adipose is phosphorylated by insulin-activated phosphatase (inactive) → lipolysis off\n- Glycogen synthase is dephosphorylated (active) → glycogen storage on\n\nFasted state (glucagon/epinephrine dominant):\n- PKA phosphorylates ACC → ACC inactive → malonyl-CoA falls → CAT-I free → beta-oxidation on\n- HSL in adipose is phosphorylated by PKA (active) → lipolysis on → FFA released\n- PKA phosphorylates HMG-CoA reductase → reductase less active → cholesterol synthesis reduced\n- Ketogenesis on (high acetyl-CoA, low OAA)\n- GNG on (PEPCK transcription induced by glucagon + cortisol)'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'ATP Yield Calculations: Step-by-Step',x:'For any even-chain saturated FA with n carbons:\n- Number of beta-oxidation cycles = (n/2) - 1\n- Acetyl-CoA produced = n/2\n- FADH2 produced = (n/2) - 1\n- NADH produced = (n/2) - 1\n\nUsing P/O ratios (approximate, as used on MCAT): FADH2 = 1.5 ATP; NADH = 2.5 ATP; Acetyl-CoA via TCA = 10 ATP; Activation cost = 2 ATP.\n\nFor palmitate (C16):\n- Cycles: 7; Acetyl-CoA: 8; FADH2: 7; NADH: 7\n- Gross: 7(1.5) + 7(2.5) + 8(10) = 10.5 + 17.5 + 80 = 108\n- Net: 108 - 2 = 106 ATP\n\nFor an unsaturated FA: subtract 1.5 ATP per double bond (lose one FADH2 per double bond at odd positions).\nFor odd-chain FA: the propionyl-CoA final product gives succinyl-CoA (net gain compared to if it were lost) but the calculation is usually given on the exam.\n\nFor synthesis of palmitate: costs 8 Acetyl-CoA + 7 ATP + 14 NADPH. Net ATP equivalents consumed (synthesis is energetically expensive, hence the need for high-energy fed state).'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Xanthoma Patterns and Lipoprotein Diagnosis',x:'Tendon xanthomas (especially Achilles tendon): LDL receptor defects (familial hypercholesterolemia, familial defective ApoB-100). Elevated LDL predominates.\n\nPalmar (planar) xanthomas: Type III hyperlipoproteinemia (ApoE2/E2). Yellow deposits in palmar creases. IDL elevation.\n\nTuberous xanthomas: large nodular deposits over joints (elbows, knees). Seen in homozygous FH (severe LDL elevation) and Type III.\n\nEruptive xanthomas: sudden onset, small yellow-red papules over buttocks and extensor surfaces. Severe hypertriglyceridemia (chylomicronemia syndrome from LPL or ApoC-II deficiency, or severe DM). TAG >1,000-2,000 mg/dL.\n\nXanthelasmas: periorbital yellow plaques. Less specific; associated with elevated LDL but can occur with normal lipids.\n\nCorneal arcus: white ring around the cornea. Before age 45, strongly suggests familial hypercholesterolemia. After age 50, often a normal aging finding.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'Lipoprotein Lipase Deficiency vs. ApoC-II Deficiency: How to Distinguish',x:'Both conditions cause Type I hyperlipoproteinemia (chylomicronemia, severe hypertriglyceridemia, pancreatitis, eruptive xanthomas). The distinction:\n\nLPL deficiency: heparin injection does NOT increase plasma LPL activity. Adding normal plasma to patient plasma does NOT correct LPL activity in vitro. Adding purified ApoC-II to patient plasma does NOT correct LPL activity.\n\nApoC-II deficiency: heparin injection releases patient LPL into plasma (LPL is present on endothelium), but released LPL is inactive without its cofactor. Adding normal plasma (which provides ApoC-II) to patient plasma in vitro restores LPL activity and TAG hydrolysis.\n\nThis is a classic board question: the correction experiment with normal plasma is the discriminating test.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'Abetalipoproteinemia: Connecting MTP to Lipid Transport',x:'Abetalipoproteinemia is caused by mutations in MTP (microsomal triglyceride transfer protein), the enzyme required to load TAG onto nascent ApoB-containing lipoproteins. Without MTP, neither chylomicrons (intestine) nor VLDL (liver) can be assembled.\n\nClinical: fat malabsorption (steatorrhea), fat-soluble vitamin deficiency (A, D, E, K), acanthocytosis (spiny RBCs from abnormal membrane phospholipid composition), progressive ataxia and retinitis pigmentosa (from vitamin E deficiency in neural tissue), absent ApoB-48 and ApoB-100 on lipoprotein electrophoresis, extremely low LDL and triglycerides.\n\nTreatment: massive doses of fat-soluble vitamins (especially vitamin E to prevent neurologic progression), low-fat diet to reduce symptoms.\n\nDistinguish from Familial Hypobetalipoproteinemia (mutations in the APOB gene itself, producing a truncated ApoB that is rapidly cleared; similar but milder phenotype, usually not neurologically severe).'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A fasting patient\'s hepatocytes have high glucagon signaling. Which of the following best describes the combined effect on acetyl-CoA carboxylase (ACC) and carnitine acyltransferase I (CAT-I)?',choices:['A) ACC is activated by PKA phosphorylation, malonyl-CoA rises, and CAT-I is inhibited, promoting fatty acid synthesis','B) ACC is inactivated by PKA phosphorylation, malonyl-CoA falls, and CAT-I is released from inhibition, promoting beta-oxidation','C) ACC is activated by citrate binding, malonyl-CoA rises, and CAT-I is activated by glucagon, paradoxically promoting both synthesis and oxidation','D) ACC is unaffected by glucagon; CAT-I is directly activated by glucagon binding a receptor on the mitochondrial membrane'],answer:1,why:'In the fasted, glucagon-dominant state: glucagon → cAMP → PKA → phosphorylates ACC at Ser-79 → ACC inactive → malonyl-CoA levels fall → malonyl-CoA inhibition of CAT-I is relieved → long-chain fatty acyl-CoA can enter the mitochondria via the carnitine shuttle → beta-oxidation proceeds. This is the reciprocal regulation: synthesis off, oxidation on. Choice B correctly describes this.'},{stem:'A patient with abetalipoproteinemia cannot assemble chylomicrons or VLDL. Which vitamin deficiency is most likely to cause irreversible neurologic damage if untreated?',choices:['A) Vitamin A, because the retina depends on chylomicron-delivered retinol','B) Vitamin K, because clotting factor synthesis requires chylomicron-delivered phylloquinone','C) Vitamin E, because the nervous system is particularly susceptible to lipid peroxidation and depends on chylomicron-delivered tocopherol for antioxidant protection','D) Vitamin D, because neurotransmitter synthesis depends on calcitriol-activated gene transcription'],answer:2,why:'All four fat-soluble vitamins (A, D, E, K) are deficient in abetalipoproteinemia because their chylomicron-dependent absorption is abolished. However, vitamin E deficiency causes the most severe and progressive irreversible neurologic damage: spinocerebellar ataxia and peripheral neuropathy from oxidative damage to myelin and neuronal membranes. Massive vitamin E supplementation is the primary treatment to prevent neurologic progression. Vitamin A deficiency causes night blindness and corneal damage; vitamin K deficiency causes bleeding; vitamin D deficiency causes rickets. None of these are as rapidly progressive and irreversible in the neurologic sense as vitamin E deficiency in abetalipoproteinemia.'}]}],
 bottomLine:'Fatty acid synthesis (cytoplasm, fed state, insulin) and beta-oxidation (mitochondria, fasted state, glucagon) are reciprocally regulated by malonyl-CoA inhibiting CAT-I. The rate-limiting steps are ACC (synthesis) and CAT-I transport (oxidation). Ketone bodies are made only in hepatic mitochondria (HMG-CoA lyase) when OAA is depleted by GNG, and are used by brain, heart, and renal cortex (via SCOT); the liver cannot use them. Cholesterol synthesis is rate-limited by HMG-CoA reductase (ER, requires 2 NADPH), regulated by SREBP/INSIG/SCAP, and inhibited by statins. Lipoprotein hierarchy: chylomicrons (dietary, ApoB-48) → VLDL (hepatic, ApoB-100) → IDL → LDL (cleared by LDLR). HDL performs reverse cholesterol transport via LCAT (activated by ApoA-I), ABCA1, and SR-BI. Key clinical correlates: FH = absent LDLR (tendon xanthomas, premature CAD); LPL deficiency = chylomicronemia + pancreatitis + eruptive xanthomas, no atherosclerosis; ApoC-II deficiency = same phenotype, corrected by adding normal plasma; Tangier = ABCA1 deficiency, orange tonsils, absent HDL; abetalipoproteinemia = absent MTP, fat malabsorption, vitamin E deficiency with neurologic damage.',
 nextHint:'Chapter 7 (Integrated Fuel Metabolism) applies every pathway from Chapters 3-6 simultaneously, asking what fuel each organ uses in fed, early fasted, prolonged fasted, and diabetic states. The lipid patterns from this chapter (when ketones rise, why the liver switches from glucose to FFA, why muscle never releases glucose) are the backbone of the integration chapter. Also review steroid hormone synthesis (Chapter 8), which begins at cholesterol and branches into cortisol, aldosterone, sex steroids, and vitamin D using the CYP450 enzyme family.',
},
{
 n:7,
 title:'Amino Acid Catabolism and the Urea Cycle',
 subtitle:'How the body strips nitrogen from amino acids, packages it as urea, and routes the carbon skeletons back into central metabolism',
 tag:'Other Metabolism',
 foundational:'Amino acids are not purely anabolic building blocks. In the fasted state, protein catabolism supplies both nitrogen (disposed via the urea cycle) and carbon (re-entering the TCA cycle as glucogenic or ketogenic fragments). The nitrogen-disposal machinery and the carbon-routing map are two overlapping systems that share intermediates with TCA, gluconeogenesis, and lipid metabolism.',
 buildsOn:'TCA cycle intermediates (Chapter 4): alpha-ketoglutarate, oxaloacetate, fumarate, succinyl-CoA. Gluconeogenesis substrates (Chapter 5): pyruvate and OAA as entry points. Mitochondrial transport (Chapter 4): compartment boundaries that the urea cycle straddles.',
 setsUp:'Chapter 8 (nucleotide metabolism) depends on glutamine as a nitrogen donor. Chapter 9 (vitamins) expands on PLP/B6 and B12 roles established here. Chapter 10 (metabolic integration) requires the fed/fasted nitrogen economy built in this chapter.',
 objectives:['Describe the mechanism of transamination and identify pyridoxal-5-phosphate (PLP) as the universal coenzyme','Explain how glutamate dehydrogenase funnels amino-group nitrogen into ammonium and state its allosteric regulators','Trace each step of the urea cycle, identifying the compartment, enzyme, substrate, and product at every step','Name N-acetylglutamate as the allosteric activator of CPS-I and explain why arginine indirectly controls urea cycle flux','Predict the biochemical signature of each urea cycle enzyme deficiency, distinguishing OTC from CPS-I by orotic acid','Explain the mechanism by which hyperammonemia causes cerebral edema via astrocyte glutamine accumulation','Classify amino acids as glucogenic, ketogenic, or mixed based on the TCA/gluconeogenic entry point of their carbon skeletons','Describe the key reactions in phenylalanine, tyrosine, tryptophan, methionine, and histidine metabolism and connect each to a testable clinical disorder','Distinguish the three genetic causes of homocystinuria by biochemical signature and predict appropriate vitamin therapy'],
 opener:'The body turns over roughly 300-400 g of protein per day. Most of the amino acids released are recycled into new protein, but a fraction must be fully catabolized. The nitrogen embedded in those amino groups cannot be excreted as free ammonia because free ammonium ion (NH4+) is neurotoxic at micromolar concentrations. The solution is a two-stage disposal system: first, all nitrogen is collected into a single molecule, glutamate; second, glutamate donates its nitrogen to the urea cycle, which packages two nitrogen atoms into urea for renal excretion. The carbon skeletons left behind re-enter central metabolism at specific TCA or gluconeogenic intermediates.\n\nThis chapter follows that nitrogen from protein backbone to urine urea, and traces the carbons to their metabolic destinations. The individual amino acid pathways that branch off this main story carry their own clinical weight: phenylketonuria, homocystinuria, maple syrup urine disease, and albinism are each caused by a single enzyme failure in one of the pathways covered here. The pattern throughout is the same: understand the normal reaction, identify what accumulates when it fails, and predict the clinical consequences.',
 pinnedDisc:{t:'OTC DEFICIENCY vs CPS-I DEFICIENCY',x:'Both enzyme deficiencies cause hyperammonemia with NO detectable urea cycle intermediate accumulation in blood. The diagnostic discriminator is urinary orotic acid. OTC DEFICIENCY: carbamoyl phosphate accumulates in the mitochondria and leaks into the cytoplasm, where it enters the pyrimidine synthesis pathway (carbamoyl phosphate synthetase II, OTC, and downstream enzymes convert it to orotic acid). Result: HIGH urine orotic acid. OTC deficiency is X-linked (the only urea cycle defect that is not autosomal recessive), making it more severe in hemizygous males. CPS-I DEFICIENCY: the block is upstream of carbamoyl phosphate, so nothing feeds into pyrimidine synthesis abnormally. Result: NORMAL urine orotic acid, low citrulline. The orotic acid test is the single fastest way to separate these two diagnoses at the bedside.'},
 sections:[{id:'7.1',num:'7.1',title:'7.1 Transamination: Collecting Nitrogen Into Glutamate',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Before any amino acid nitrogen reaches the urea cycle, it must be transferred to a common carrier. That carrier is glutamate. The mechanism that makes this transfer is transamination: an aminotransferase (also called a transaminase) moves the alpha-amino group from an amino acid onto alpha-ketoglutarate (alpha-KG), producing glutamate and the corresponding alpha-keto acid. Every transamination reaction follows this same pattern, which is why the amino-group collection step is uniform across virtually all amino acids.'},{t:'formula',x:'Amino acid + alpha-Ketoglutarate  →[Aminotransferase, PLP]→  alpha-Keto acid + Glutamate'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'PLP: The Universal Transaminase Coenzyme',x:'Pyridoxal-5-phosphate (PLP, the active form of vitamin B6) is covalently bound at the active site of every aminotransferase via a Schiff base (aldimine linkage) with a lysine residue of the enzyme. The mechanism works in two half-reactions. In the first half-reaction, the amino group of the substrate amino acid attacks the aldehyde carbon of PLP, displacing the enzyme lysine to form an external aldimine. This external aldimine tautomerizes to a ketimine, which is hydrolyzed to release the alpha-keto acid product and leave PLP loaded with the amino group (now as pyridoxamine-5-phosphate, PMP). In the second half-reaction, PMP reacts with alpha-ketoglutarate via the same mechanism in reverse, transferring the amino group to alpha-KG and regenerating the original PLP-enzyme. The net result is amino-group transfer with PLP cycling between its aldehyde (PLP) and amine (PMP) forms. No net consumption of PLP occurs; it is a true coenzyme.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'AST and ALT: The Clinically Tested Aminotransferases',x:'Aspartate aminotransferase (AST, also called GOT): transfers the amino group of aspartate to alpha-KG, producing oxaloacetate and glutamate. AST is found in liver, cardiac muscle, skeletal muscle, kidney, and RBCs. Because it is present in multiple tissues, an isolated AST elevation is not liver-specific.\n\nAlanine aminotransferase (ALT, also called GPT): transfers the amino group of alanine to alpha-KG, producing pyruvate and glutamate. ALT is found predominantly in the liver with much lower concentrations elsewhere. ALT elevation is more specific for hepatocellular injury than AST.\n\nClinical pattern: In viral hepatitis, both AST and ALT are elevated, with ALT typically higher than AST (ALT:AST > 1). In alcoholic hepatitis, AST:ALT ratio is typically greater than 2:1 because alcohol selectively depletes PLP (required for ALT synthesis) in hepatocytes while also directly damaging mitochondria that release AST. In myocardial infarction, AST rises (cardiac source) but ALT does not. Troponin has replaced AST in cardiac diagnosis, but the mechanistic principle remains testable.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'Why Transamination Alone Does Not Release Nitrogen',x:'Transamination does not release nitrogen from the body; it transfers it. After transamination, the nitrogen sits in glutamate. A second reaction is required to actually release nitrogen as ammonium (NH4+). That reaction is glutamate dehydrogenase. The two steps work in series: aminotransferase collects nitrogen into glutamate, then glutamate dehydrogenase releases it as NH4+. Without both steps, the nitrogen disposal is incomplete.'},{t:'p',x:'The glucose-alanine cycle illustrates how transamination integrates nitrogen disposal with gluconeogenesis. In muscle, pyruvate from glycolysis accepts an amino group (from branched-chain amino acid catabolism) via alanine aminotransferase to form alanine. Alanine is exported to the liver, where hepatic ALT reverses the reaction, releasing pyruvate for gluconeogenesis and glutamate for further nitrogen disposal. This cycle transfers both carbon (for glucose synthesis) and nitrogen (for urea synthesis) from muscle to liver without releasing free ammonia into the circulation.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'PLP-Dependent Reactions Beyond Transamination',x:'PLP supports reactions beyond aminotransfer. In each case, PLP stabilizes a carbanion intermediate at the alpha-carbon of an amino acid substrate via the electron sink of its pyridinium ring. Decarboxylation reactions: aromatic L-amino acid decarboxylase (makes dopamine from DOPA, serotonin from 5-hydroxytryptophan), histidine decarboxylase (makes histamine), glutamate decarboxylase (makes GABA). Racemization (in bacteria). Elimination and replacement reactions: cystathionine beta-synthase and cystathionine gamma-lyase in the trans-sulfuration pathway. Glycogen phosphorylase: PLP is covalently bound and stabilizes the transition state for phosphorolysis, not a transamination. ALA synthase (first step of heme synthesis). INH (isoniazid) and hydralazine form hydrazones with PLP, inactivating all PLP-dependent enzymes, which is why INH therapy is supplemented with B6.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A 52-year-old man presents with right upper quadrant pain and fatigue. Labs show AST 280 U/L and ALT 95 U/L (AST:ALT = 2.9:1). He drinks 6-8 alcoholic beverages per day. Which mechanism best explains the disproportionate AST elevation relative to ALT?',choices:['A) ALT is primarily mitochondrial, so alcohol-induced mitochondrial damage releases AST preferentially','B) Chronic alcohol use depletes hepatic PLP, impairing ALT synthesis while cardiac AST rises from subclinical myocarditis','C) Alcohol metabolism generates NADH that allosterically inhibits ALT but not AST','D) Alcohol selectively induces AST gene transcription via the nuclear receptor PXR'],answer:1,why:'ALT requires PLP as a cofactor. Chronic alcohol use depletes hepatic pyridoxal-5-phosphate (B6), impairing ALT synthesis and activity in hepatocytes. AST comes from multiple sources including mitochondria and cytoplasm of liver and other tissues; it is less dependent on the hepatic PLP pool relative to ALT activity. The classic teaching: alcoholic hepatitis has AST:ALT > 2 because ALT is selectively reduced by PLP depletion.'},{stem:'In the glucose-alanine cycle, alanine is exported from exercising muscle to the liver. Which reaction does the liver use to extract the nitrogen from alanine before using the carbon for gluconeogenesis?',choices:['A) Glutamate dehydrogenase converts alanine directly to pyruvate and NH4+','B) Alanine aminotransferase transfers the amino group to alpha-ketoglutarate, yielding pyruvate and glutamate','C) Aspartate aminotransferase transfers the amino group to oxaloacetate, yielding alanine-derived OAA','D) Carbamoyl phosphate synthetase I directly incorporates alanine nitrogen into carbamoyl phosphate'],answer:1,why:'Hepatic ALT (alanine aminotransferase) catalyzes the reverse of the muscle reaction: alanine + alpha-KG → pyruvate + glutamate. The pyruvate enters gluconeogenesis (via pyruvate carboxylase → OAA → PEPCK → PEP). The glutamate then undergoes oxidative deamination by glutamate dehydrogenase to release NH4+ for the urea cycle. This two-step sequence (ALT then Glu-DH) is the standard nitrogen extraction pathway in the liver.'}]},{id:'7.2',num:'7.2',title:'7.2 Glutamate Dehydrogenase: Releasing Nitrogen as Ammonium',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Once nitrogen is collected in glutamate, the cell must remove it as free ammonium (NH4+). Glutamate dehydrogenase (GDH) catalyzes oxidative deamination of glutamate in the mitochondrial matrix, producing alpha-ketoglutarate, NH4+, and either NADH or NADPH depending on the cofactor used. The enzyme is bidirectional: it can run in reverse (reductive amination of alpha-KG) when nitrogen must be incorporated rather than disposed. In the liver under catabolic conditions, the oxidative direction dominates, supplying NH4+ to CPS-I for urea synthesis.'},{t:'formula',x:'Glutamate + NAD+ (or NADP+)  →[GDH, mitochondrial matrix]→  alpha-Ketoglutarate + NH4+ + NADH (or NADPH)'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Allosteric Regulation of Glutamate Dehydrogenase',x:'GDH is regulated by the energy and nitrogen status of the cell. The logic is straightforward: when the cell needs energy (ADP/GDP high, ATP/GTP low), it should catabolize amino acids more aggressively, releasing NH4+ for urea synthesis and alpha-KG for the TCA cycle.\n\nActivators: ADP and GDP (signals of low energy state). Both activate GDH by binding the regulatory domain and increasing enzyme activity toward the oxidative deamination direction.\n\nInhibitors: GTP, ATP (signals of high energy state, inhibit GDH by allosteric binding). NADH also inhibits GDH (product inhibition; signals that reducing equivalents are already sufficient and further oxidation is not needed).\n\nClinical connection: Hyperinsulinism-hyperammonemia (HI/HA) syndrome. Gain-of-function mutations in GDH reduce inhibition by GTP/ATP, causing excessive GDH activity → excess NH4+ production → chronic mild hyperammonemia. Simultaneously, excess alpha-KG stimulates ATP production in pancreatic beta cells → inappropriate insulin secretion → hypoglycemia. Treatment: diazoxide (opens K-ATP channels in beta cells, reducing insulin release).'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'GDH Location Matters: Why the Mitochondrial Matrix?',x:'GDH is exclusively mitochondrial. This matters because the urea cycle begins with CPS-I, also in the mitochondrial matrix, which directly uses the NH4+ that GDH releases. The spatial coupling prevents toxic NH4+ from accumulating in the cytoplasm. The liver is the primary site of this coupling because hepatic mitochondria have high GDH and CPS-I activity. In kidney, GDH-derived NH4+ serves a different purpose: it is excreted directly into the tubular lumen as part of renal acid-base regulation (ammoniagenesis), not channeled into the urea cycle.'},{t:'p',x:'Glutamine synthetase provides an alternative nitrogen transport route. In brain, muscle, and lung, glutamine synthetase uses NH4+ and ATP to attach an amide group to glutamate, producing glutamine. Glutamine is a non-toxic, neutral amino acid that carries two nitrogen atoms per molecule (the alpha-amino group and the amide group of the side chain). It is the predominant nitrogen carrier in blood, accounting for roughly 20% of total plasma amino acid nitrogen. The liver and kidney contain glutaminase, which cleaves glutamine back to glutamate and NH4+, releasing nitrogen for urea synthesis or ammoniagenesis.'},{t:'box',kind:'why',label:'Why NH4+ Is Neurotoxic',x:'Free NH4+ disrupts brain function through several converging mechanisms. First, at physiological concentrations, NH4+ inhibits alpha-ketoglutarate dehydrogenase (alpha-KGDH), slowing TCA cycle flux and reducing ATP production in neurons. Second, the brain detoxifies NH4+ via glutamine synthetase, which consumes alpha-KG (drawing it away from the TCA cycle) and produces glutamine. Glutamine accumulation inside astrocytes raises intracellular osmolality, causing astrocyte swelling and cerebral edema. Third, excess glutamine in astrocyte mitochondria is metabolized to glutamate and NH4+ by phosphate-activated glutaminase (the Trojan horse hypothesis), generating additional mitochondrial NH4+ that directly impairs oxidative phosphorylation. The net result is energy failure, astrocyte swelling, and cerebral edema, presenting clinically as confusion, asterixis, cerebral herniation, and death in severe cases.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A patient with a gain-of-function mutation in glutamate dehydrogenase presents with episodic hypoglycemia and chronic mild hyperammonemia. Which best explains how the same enzyme mutation causes both findings?',choices:['A) Excess GDH activity raises alpha-KG, which stimulates insulin secretion; simultaneously, excess NH4+ is produced, overwhelming the urea cycle','B) GDH directly synthesizes insulin from glutamate; excess GDH therefore hypersecrets insulin','C) Excess NH4+ inhibits glucagon secretion, so blood glucose falls while NH4+ accumulates from unchecked protein catabolism','D) Gain-of-function GDH converts alpha-KG to glucose by reversing TCA, lowering blood glucose while releasing NH4+'],answer:0,why:'GDH catalyzes glutamate → alpha-KG + NH4+. Gain-of-function reduces GTP/ATP inhibition, so GDH is overactive. Excess alpha-KG enters the TCA cycle in pancreatic beta cells, raising the ATP/ADP ratio, closing K-ATP channels, and triggering insulin release (hypoglycemia). Simultaneously, excess NH4+ is released, overwhelming hepatic urea cycle capacity (chronic hyperammonemia). Diazoxide treats this by reopening K-ATP channels in beta cells.'},{stem:'Why is urinary NH4+ excretion by the kidney not sufficient to dispose of all amino acid nitrogen in a person eating 80 g of protein per day?',choices:['A) The kidney lacks glutaminase and cannot cleave glutamine to release NH4+','B) Renal NH4+ excretion is limited by tubular capacity and is primarily an acid-base buffer; at normal protein intake, urea carries the majority of nitrogen load','C) NH4+ is reabsorbed in the proximal tubule and cannot reach the collecting duct for excretion','D) The kidney converts all NH4+ to urea using a kidney-specific urea cycle'],answer:1,why:'The kidney does produce and excrete NH4+ from glutamine (via renal glutaminase), but renal ammoniagenesis is primarily regulated by acid-base status, not nitrogen load. At normal or high protein intake, the liver processes the majority of amino acid nitrogen through the urea cycle, packaging it as urea for renal filtration and excretion. Urea accounts for roughly 85% of urinary nitrogen. Renal NH4+ excretion accounts for most of the remaining nitrogen and is regulated by systemic pH rather than dietary protein load.'}]},{id:'7.3',num:'7.3',title:'7.3 The Urea Cycle: Step-by-Step',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'The urea cycle converts two nitrogen atoms (one from NH4+, one from aspartate) and one carbon atom (from bicarbonate, as CO2) into urea, at a cost of three ATP equivalents (two ATP consumed by CPS-I, one ATP consumed by ASS). The cycle is split between the mitochondrial matrix (steps 1-2) and the cytoplasm (steps 3-5). Ornithine serves as the carrier, entering the mitochondria and exiting as citrulline, then being regenerated in the cytoplasm and re-imported.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Step 1 (Mitochondria): CPS-I Fixes NH4+ Into Carbamoyl Phosphate',x:'Enzyme: Carbamoyl phosphate synthetase I (CPS-I).\nSubstrates: NH4+ + HCO3- + 2 ATP.\nProduct: Carbamoyl phosphate + 2 ADP + Pi.\n\nMechanism: CPS-I activates bicarbonate with one ATP to form carboxyphosphate, which reacts with NH4+ to form carbamic acid (carbamate), which is then phosphorylated by the second ATP to form carbamoyl phosphate. The two-ATP cost makes this the most energetically expensive single step in the cycle.\n\nKey regulatory point: CPS-I is allosterically activated by N-acetylglutamate (NAG). Without NAG, CPS-I is essentially inactive. NAG is synthesized by NAG synthase from glutamate and acetyl-CoA; NAG synthase is activated allosterically by arginine. This creates a feedforward regulatory loop: rising arginine (from protein catabolism or high protein diet) → more NAG → more CPS-I activity → more urea synthesis. When protein intake is low and arginine is scarce, urea cycle flux is damped.\n\nDo not confuse CPS-I (mitochondrial, uses NH4+, liver) with CPS-II (cytoplasmic, uses glutamine as nitrogen source, ubiquitous, for pyrimidine synthesis). Different enzyme, different location, different nitrogen source.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Step 2 (Mitochondria): OTC Loads Carbamoyl Phosphate Onto Ornithine',x:'Enzyme: Ornithine transcarbamylase (OTC).\nSubstrates: Carbamoyl phosphate + ornithine.\nProduct: Citrulline + Pi.\n\nMechanism: OTC transfers the carbamoyl group from carbamoyl phosphate to the delta-amino group of ornithine, forming citrulline. This is a transferase reaction releasing inorganic phosphate.\n\nCitrulline exits the mitochondria via the citrulline-ornithine antiporter (also called the mitochondrial citrulline carrier), exchanging citrulline (leaving the matrix) for ornithine (entering the matrix). This antiport system couples the import of recycled ornithine with the export of citrulline, maintaining cycle continuity.\n\nOTC is the most commonly deficient urea cycle enzyme (X-linked recessive). When OTC is deficient, carbamoyl phosphate accumulates in the mitochondria and leaks into the cytoplasm, feeding CPS-II (the pyrimidine synthesis enzyme), increasing orotic acid production and excretion.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Step 3 (Cytoplasm): ASS Condenses Citrulline With Aspartate',x:'Enzyme: Argininosuccinate synthetase (ASS, also called citrulline-aspartate ligase).\nSubstrates: Citrulline + aspartate + ATP.\nProduct: Argininosuccinate + AMP + PPi (pyrophosphate).\n\nMechanism: ATP activates the ureido group of citrulline, and aspartate attacks it to form argininosuccinate. The ATP is cleaved to AMP + PPi (not ADP + Pi), making this thermodynamically very favorable (PPi hydrolysis by pyrophosphatase provides additional free energy). This step introduces the SECOND nitrogen atom, contributed by the amino group of aspartate.\n\nAspartate is regenerated from fumarate (released in step 4) via the TCA cycle: fumarate → malate → OAA → aspartate (via AST). This connects the urea cycle to the TCA cycle in a linked set of reactions sometimes called the aspartate-argininosuccinate shunt.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Step 4 (Cytoplasm): ASL Releases Arginine and Fumarate',x:'Enzyme: Argininosuccinate lyase (ASL).\nSubstrate: Argininosuccinate.\nProducts: Arginine + fumarate.\n\nMechanism: ASL catalyzes an elimination reaction, cleaving argininosuccinate to release arginine (retaining the nitrogen from aspartate) and fumarate (the carbon skeleton of aspartate). Fumarate can enter the TCA cycle (fumarate → malate → OAA), coupling the urea cycle to TCA cycle anaplerosis and providing the carbon backbone for regenerating aspartate via OAA + glutamate (AST reaction). This recycling means the aspartate nitrogen donor is consumed but its carbon is returned to TCA.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Step 5 (Cytoplasm): Arginase Cleaves Arginine to Urea + Ornithine',x:'Enzyme: Arginase (arginase-1 in liver; arginase-2 in kidney, prostate, brain).\nSubstrates: Arginine + H2O.\nProducts: Urea + ornithine.\n\nMechanism: Arginase is a manganese-dependent enzyme that hydrolyzes the guanidinium group of arginine to release urea (which exits to blood and is filtered/excreted by kidneys) and regenerate ornithine. Ornithine is then imported back into the mitochondria via the citrulline-ornithine antiporter to begin the next cycle.\n\nArginase is the only enzyme that actually releases urea and regenerates the ornithine carrier. Arginase-1 deficiency causes elevated plasma arginine (argininemia) and only mild hyperammonemia (because the defect is at the last step, not at the nitrogen input steps).'},{t:'formula',x:'NET REACTION:\nNH4+ + HCO3- + 3 ATP + Aspartate  →[Urea Cycle, liver]→  Urea + Fumarate + 2 ADP + AMP + 4 Pi + PPi\n\nSimplified accounting:\n2 Nitrogen atoms in (one as NH4+, one from aspartate)\n1 Urea molecule out (contains both N atoms)\n3 ATP equivalents consumed (2 in CPS-I step, 1 in ASS step as AMP+PPi = 2 Pi energy)\nOrnithine regenerated (catalytic carrier)'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'The Urea Cycle-TCA Cycle Connection',x:'The urea cycle and TCA cycle are linked at two points. First, fumarate released in step 4 (by ASL) can enter the TCA cycle and be oxidized to malate, then OAA. OAA is transaminated (by AST) to regenerate aspartate for step 3. Second, alpha-ketoglutarate from glutamate dehydrogenase (which oxidatively deaminates glutamate to release NH4+ for step 1) can enter the TCA cycle as an anaplerotic substrate. This means that both nitrogen atoms entering the urea cycle have TCA cycle connections: the first N comes from glutamate dehydrogenase (alpha-KG product re-enters TCA), and the second N enters as aspartate whose carbon backbone is fumarate (re-enters TCA). The urea cycle and TCA cycle are therefore not isolated systems; they are metabolically coupled.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Regulation of the Urea Cycle',x:'Short-term: N-acetylglutamate (NAG) is the allosteric activator of CPS-I. NAG is synthesized from acetyl-CoA + glutamate by NAG synthase; NAG synthase is activated by arginine. After a protein-rich meal, amino acid catabolism generates glutamate (from transamination) and arginine levels rise transiently, both driving NAG synthesis and thereby activating CPS-I. This feedforward mechanism upregulates urea cycle flux in proportion to the protein load.\n\nLong-term: A high-protein diet induces transcriptional upregulation of all five urea cycle enzymes over days to weeks. The liver adapts its urea-synthesizing capacity to match chronic dietary protein intake. Starvation or a low-protein diet reduces urea cycle enzyme expression, conserving nitrogen.\n\nHepatic failure: Liver disease reduces urea cycle capacity because hepatocytes are lost. Hyperammonemia in cirrhosis results from insufficient hepatic CPS-I, OTC, and downstream enzyme activity, combined with portal-systemic shunting (blood bypasses the liver, delivering gut-derived NH4+ directly to systemic circulation).'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A liver biopsy from a patient on a very-high-protein diet shows upregulation of CPS-I, OTC, ASS, ASL, and arginase mRNA compared to baseline. A patient on a protein-restricted diet shows the reverse. What level of regulation accounts for this long-term adaptation?',choices:['A) Allosteric regulation of CPS-I by NAG adjusts enzyme activity within seconds','B) Transcriptional induction of all urea cycle enzymes adapts capacity over days to weeks','C) Post-translational phosphorylation of arginase changes its affinity for arginine','D) Substrate availability of ornithine limits the cycle rate independently of enzyme expression'],answer:1,why:'Long-term adaptation of the urea cycle to dietary protein intake is mediated by transcriptional regulation of urea cycle enzyme genes. A high-protein diet induces all five enzyme genes, increasing the liver\'s urea-synthesizing capacity over days to weeks. Short-term regulation (within minutes) is handled by the allosteric effect of NAG on CPS-I. The question specifies mRNA changes, which are transcriptional.'},{stem:'Which statement correctly describes the stoichiometry of the urea cycle?',choices:['A) One nitrogen from NH4+ and one from glutamate are incorporated into urea at a cost of 2 ATP','B) One nitrogen from NH4+ and one from aspartate are incorporated into urea at a cost of 3 ATP equivalents','C) Two nitrogens from NH4+ are incorporated into urea with ornithine as the direct nitrogen donor','D) One nitrogen from glutamine and one from glutamate are incorporated into urea at a cost of 4 ATP'],answer:1,why:'The urea cycle incorporates two nitrogen atoms: one from NH4+ (fixed by CPS-I in step 1) and one from aspartate (joined by ASS in step 3). Ornithine is the carrier, not a nitrogen donor. The cost is 3 ATP equivalents: 2 ATP consumed by CPS-I (step 1) and 1 ATP consumed by ASS (step 3, producing AMP + PPi, equivalent to 2 high-energy phosphate bonds, sometimes counted as 4 total depending on accounting convention; the most tested figure is 3 ATP).'},{stem:'Fumarate is released as a byproduct of the urea cycle. Which step produces it, and what happens to it immediately afterward in a hepatocyte?',choices:['A) CPS-I releases fumarate as a byproduct of carbamoyl phosphate synthesis; it exits the cell','B) Argininosuccinate lyase cleaves argininosuccinate to arginine + fumarate; fumarate enters the TCA cycle','C) Arginase cleaves arginine to urea + fumarate; fumarate is converted to malate for export','D) OTC releases fumarate when ornithine is loaded with the carbamoyl group'],answer:1,why:'Argininosuccinate lyase (ASL, step 4) cleaves argininosuccinate into arginine and fumarate. The fumarate is a TCA cycle intermediate and is directly converted to malate by fumarase, then to OAA by malate dehydrogenase. OAA is transaminated (by AST) back to aspartate, regenerating the nitrogen donor for step 3. This connects the urea cycle to the TCA cycle and allows the aspartate nitrogen donor to be recycled.'}]},{id:'7.4',num:'7.4',title:'7.4 Urea Cycle Defects and Hyperammonemia',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Any deficiency in a urea cycle enzyme causes hyperammonemia, because NH4+ cannot be packaged and excreted as urea. The specific pattern of accumulated intermediates and associated findings (particularly urinary orotic acid) identifies which enzyme is deficient. All urea cycle defects except OTC deficiency are autosomal recessive. OTC deficiency is X-linked recessive, affecting hemizygous males most severely; heterozygous females may be asymptomatic carriers or have partial dysfunction revealed only by protein loading.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'OTC Deficiency: The Most Common Urea Cycle Defect',x:'Enzyme: Ornithine transcarbamylase (OTC), step 2 of the urea cycle.\nInheritance: X-linked recessive.\n\nBiochemical consequence: Carbamoyl phosphate accumulates in the mitochondrial matrix. It leaks into the cytoplasm, where it enters the pyrimidine synthesis pathway via the cytoplasmic CPS-II-OTC-dihydroorotase trifunctional protein. Carbamoyl phosphate is converted through the pyrimidine pathway to orotic acid (an early pyrimidine intermediate that is excreted when downstream enzymes are not the bottleneck). Uridine is NOT produced in excess (UMP synthase converts orotic acid to UMP normally, but the increased flux overwhelms the system, and orotic acid spills into urine).\n\nKey lab finding: HIGH urine orotic acid. This is the single most important discriminator from CPS-I deficiency.\nAlso: low citrulline (because OTC cannot form it), very high NH4+, elevated glutamine (the brain\'s emergency NH4+ buffer), and low BUN (no urea being made).\n\nPresentation: Neonatal onset in hemizygous males: vomiting, lethargy, respiratory alkalosis (NH4+ stimulates the respiratory center), coma within days of birth. Late-onset forms in females or in males with partial deficiency: protein aversion, episodic hyperammonemia triggered by illness or high protein intake, behavioral changes, headache.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'CPS-I Deficiency vs OTC Deficiency: The Orotic Acid Discriminator',x:'CPS-I deficiency: enzyme produces carbamoyl phosphate (step 1). If CPS-I fails, no carbamoyl phosphate is made, so nothing feeds into the pyrimidine pathway abnormally. Orotic acid is NORMAL or LOW. Citrulline is very low (nothing to load onto ornithine in step 2). NH4+ is very high.\n\nOTC deficiency: carbamoyl phosphate IS made (CPS-I works) but cannot be transferred to ornithine (OTC fails). Carbamoyl phosphate accumulates and spills into pyrimidine synthesis, raising orotic acid. Orotic acid is HIGH.\n\nBoth: hyperammonemia, low citrulline, low BUN, elevated glutamine.\nDiscriminator: urine orotic acid. High = OTC. Normal/low = CPS-I.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'ASS Deficiency (Citrullinemia Type I) and ASL Deficiency (Argininosuccinic Aciduria)',x:'ASS deficiency (step 3, argininosuccinate synthetase): citrulline cannot condense with aspartate. Citrulline accumulates markedly in blood and urine. Called citrullinemia type I. Urine orotic acid may be elevated (carbamoyl phosphate backs up). NH4+ elevated.\n\nASL deficiency (step 4, argininosuccinate lyase): argininosuccinate cannot be cleaved. Argininosuccinate accumulates in blood, urine, and CSF. Called argininosuccinic aciduria. Unique finding: trichorrhexis nodosa (brittle hair with nodes visible on electron microscopy), thought to result from arginine deficiency in hair follicles. NH4+ elevated.\n\nArginase deficiency (step 5): arginine cannot be hydrolyzed to urea and ornithine. Plasma arginine is very high (argininemia). NH4+ is only mildly elevated (urea cycle runs but fails to recycle ornithine; some urea may still be made via alternative routes). Presents as progressive spastic diplegia and intellectual disability rather than acute hyperammonemic crisis.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Mechanism of Hyperammonemia-Induced Cerebral Edema',x:'Step 1: NH4+ enters astrocytes (high-affinity glutamine synthetase is found mainly in astrocytes, not neurons).\nStep 2: Glutamine synthetase uses NH4+ + glutamate + ATP to synthesize glutamine, reducing NH4+ concentration locally.\nStep 3: Glutamine accumulation raises intracellular osmolality in astrocytes, drawing water in (osmotic swelling).\nStep 4: Astrocyte swelling compresses the surrounding extracellular space and raises intracranial pressure.\nStep 5: Swollen astrocyte mitochondria metabolize excess glutamine back to glutamate + NH4+ (the Trojan horse), generating mitochondrial NH4+ that impairs the electron transport chain and ATP synthesis.\n\nNet: cerebral edema, energy failure, and neuronal dysfunction. Clinically: confusion, asterixis (flapping tremor from intermittent cortical inhibition), obtundation, seizures, and brain herniation in severe cases.\n\nAdditional mechanism: NH4+ inhibits alpha-KGDH (TCA cycle), reducing neuronal ATP production independently of the osmotic mechanism.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Treatment of Hyperammonemia',x:'Dietary protein restriction: reduces the nitrogen load entering the urea cycle. Essential amino acid supplements can maintain protein synthesis with minimal nitrogen waste.\n\nAlternative nitrogen sinks: sodium benzoate conjugates glycine to form hippurate (excreted by kidneys, removing one nitrogen per glycine). Sodium phenylbutyrate is converted to phenylacetate, which conjugates glutamine to form phenylacetylglutamine (excreted by kidneys, removing two nitrogens per glutamine). Both drugs bypass the urea cycle as nitrogen excretion pathways.\n\nArginine or citrulline supplementation: in most urea cycle defects, arginine becomes an essential amino acid (cannot be synthesized at normal rates). Supplementing arginine drives whatever residual cycle activity exists.\n\nDialysis: for acute hyperammonemic crises, hemodialysis removes NH4+ rapidly. Liver transplant is curative for most urea cycle defects, because the transplanted liver has normal enzyme activity.'},{t:'list',x:['CPS-I deficiency: high NH4+, low citrulline, NORMAL orotic acid, no orotic acid','OTC deficiency (X-linked): high NH4+, low citrulline, HIGH urine orotic acid','ASS deficiency (citrullinemia I): high NH4+, VERY HIGH citrulline, elevated orotic acid','ASL deficiency (argininosuccinic aciduria): high NH4+, high argininosuccinate, brittle hair (trichorrhexis nodosa)','Arginase deficiency: HIGH plasma arginine, mild or no hyperammonemia, spastic diplegia']}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A 3-day-old male infant is brought in for vomiting, poor feeding, and lethargy. Serum ammonia is 620 micromol/L. Urine orotic acid is markedly elevated. Plasma citrulline is nearly undetectable. Which enzyme is most likely deficient?',choices:['A) CPS-I, because the orotic acid signals upstream failure of carbamoyl phosphate synthesis','B) OTC, because elevated orotic acid confirms that carbamoyl phosphate is made but cannot enter the cycle','C) ASS, because citrullinemia accumulates when citrulline cannot condense with aspartate','D) Arginase, because failure to hydrolyze arginine leads to NH4+ accumulation and orotic acid excretion'],answer:1,why:'Elevated urine orotic acid means carbamoyl phosphate IS being made (CPS-I works) but cannot proceed through the urea cycle. It overflows into pyrimidine synthesis, producing orotic acid. The block at OTC is confirmed by: very low citrulline (OTC makes citrulline from carbamoyl phosphate + ornithine, so if OTC fails, no citrulline is produced) and the X-linked presentation in a male infant. CPS-I deficiency would show no orotic acid elevation.'},{stem:'A patient with hyperammonemia due to OTC deficiency is treated with sodium benzoate. Which nitrogen-containing compound is excreted in urine as a result of this treatment?',choices:['A) Urea, because benzoate re-routes the urea cycle through a bypass enzyme','B) Hippurate, because benzoate conjugates glycine and the benzoate-glycine conjugate is excreted','C) Phenylacetylglutamine, because benzoate is converted to phenylacetate in the liver','D) Orotic acid, because benzoate inhibits pyrimidine synthesis and diverts carbamoyl phosphate to urea'],answer:1,why:'Sodium benzoate is conjugated to glycine in the liver by glycine N-acyltransferase, forming hippurate (benzoylglycine). Hippurate is excreted in urine. Each mole of hippurate carries away one nitrogen atom (from glycine\'s amino group). This bypasses the urea cycle entirely. Phenylacetylglutamine excretion uses phenylbutyrate/phenylacetate (a different drug), which removes two nitrogens per glutamine.'}]},{id:'7.5',num:'7.5',title:'7.5 Glucogenic and Ketogenic Amino Acids',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'After nitrogen is stripped from an amino acid, the remaining carbon skeleton (alpha-keto acid) is routed into central metabolism. Where it enters determines whether its carbons can be used to synthesize glucose (glucogenic) or only ketone bodies and acetyl-CoA (ketogenic). The classification is entirely based on which metabolic intermediate the carbon skeleton becomes.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Glucogenic Amino Acids',x:'An amino acid is glucogenic if its carbon skeleton enters the TCA cycle or gluconeogenesis at a point that can yield net oxaloacetate and ultimately glucose. The five entry points are:\n\n1. Pyruvate (converted to OAA by pyruvate carboxylase, then to PEP by PEPCK for GNG): alanine, serine, threonine, glycine, cysteine.\n2. Oxaloacetate (directly enters GNG): aspartate, asparagine.\n3. Alpha-ketoglutarate (enters TCA, rotates to OAA): glutamate, glutamine, proline, arginine, histidine.\n4. Succinyl-CoA (enters TCA, rotates to OAA; also involves B12-dependent methylmalonyl-CoA mutase for some): valine, isoleucine (partial), methionine, threonine (partial).\n5. Fumarate (enters TCA, rotates to OAA): phenylalanine (partial), tyrosine (partial).\n\nAll of these carbon skeletons can eventually reach OAA and be directed toward gluconeogenesis.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Ketogenic Amino Acids',x:'An amino acid is ketogenic if its carbon skeleton enters metabolism only as acetyl-CoA or acetoacetate, neither of which can produce net OAA (acetyl-CoA is fully oxidized in the TCA cycle without net OAA production; acetoacetate is converted to acetyl-CoA). Therefore, ketogenic amino acids CANNOT contribute net carbon to gluconeogenesis.\n\nPurely ketogenic (ONLY leucine and lysine): both degrade exclusively to acetyl-CoA and acetoacetate.\n- Leucine: degraded via leucine transaminase and then the BCKDH complex, eventually to acetyl-CoA and acetoacetate.\n- Lysine: unique in that it does not undergo standard transamination (the alpha-amino group is removed by a different mechanism); degraded to acetyl-CoA and acetoacetate via the saccharopine pathway.\n\nMixed (both glucogenic AND ketogenic): isoleucine (makes succinyl-CoA AND acetyl-CoA), threonine (makes both), phenylalanine (makes fumarate AND acetoacetate), tyrosine (makes fumarate AND acetoacetate), tryptophan (makes alanine AND acetyl-CoA/acetoacetate).'},{t:'formula',x:'Purely ketogenic: Leucine, Lysine\nMixed (glucogenic + ketogenic): Isoleucine, Threonine, Phenylalanine, Tyrosine, Tryptophan\nPurely glucogenic: ALL other amino acids (Ala, Arg, Asn, Asp, Cys, Gln, Glu, Gly, His, Met, Pro, Ser, Val)'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'Why Leucine and Lysine Cannot Make Glucose',x:'The textbook rule is that acetyl-CoA cannot produce net glucose because both carbons entering the TCA cycle as acetyl-CoA are lost as two CO2 molecules (one at isocitrate dehydrogenase, one at alpha-KGDH) before any OAA is regenerated. While OAA is regenerated, it was consumed in the condensation step (citrate synthase), so there is no NET gain of OAA carbon from acetyl-CoA. Leucine degrades entirely to acetyl-CoA and acetoacetate, and lysine degrades entirely to acetyl-CoA and acetoacetate via the saccharopine pathway. Neither can be used by pyruvate carboxylase (which requires pyruvate, not acetyl-CoA as the 3-carbon substrate) to produce OAA for GNG.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'Maple Syrup Urine Disease (MSUD): Branched-Chain AA Catabolism Defect',x:'The three branched-chain amino acids (BCAAs) are leucine, isoleucine, and valine. Their catabolism begins with transamination (BCAT, which uses PLP) to produce branched-chain alpha-keto acids (BCKAs), then oxidative decarboxylation by the branched-chain alpha-keto acid dehydrogenase complex (BCKDH). BCKDH is analogous to pyruvate dehydrogenase and alpha-KGDH; it requires TPP (B1), lipoic acid, CoA, FAD, NAD+.\n\nMSUD: Autosomal recessive deficiency of BCKDH. BCKAs accumulate in blood, urine, and CSF. Named for the sweet, maple-syrup-like odor of urine (from alpha-ketoisocaproic acid and other keto acids). Neurological presentation: feeding difficulties, seizures, encephalopathy, cerebral edema, and death if untreated in the neonatal period.\n\nDiagnosis: elevated plasma leucine, isoleucine, and valine; elevated BCKAs in urine; alloisoleucine (a pathognomonic marker, a stereoisomer of isoleucine that forms from BCKA accumulation and is not normally present).\n\nTreatment: diet severely restricted in BCAAs (leucine, isoleucine, valine), with special medical formula supplying all other amino acids. Thiamine (B1) supplementation may help in thiamine-responsive MSUD variants (partial BCKDH activity that is thiamine-sensitive). Liver transplant corrects hepatic BCKDH deficiency.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A newborn is found on day 3 to have a sweet-smelling urine, poor feeding, and elevated plasma leucine, isoleucine, and valine. Which enzyme complex is deficient, and which vitamin would be tested first as a potential partial therapy?',choices:['A) Pyruvate dehydrogenase; biotin supplementation','B) Branched-chain alpha-keto acid dehydrogenase; thiamine (B1) supplementation','C) Alpha-ketoglutarate dehydrogenase; riboflavin (B2) supplementation','D) Glutamate dehydrogenase; pyridoxine (B6) supplementation'],answer:1,why:'MSUD results from BCKDH deficiency. BCKDH is a multi-enzyme complex analogous to PDH, with the same cofactor requirements: TPP (from thiamine/B1), lipoic acid, CoA/pantothenate, FAD (B2), and NAD+ (B3). The thiamine-responsive form of MSUD has a BCKDH mutation that retains partial activity when cofactor is in excess; high-dose thiamine may restore enough activity to reduce BCKA accumulation. Thiamine is therefore the first vitamin tested in MSUD. Alloisoleucine in plasma is pathognomonic for MSUD.'},{stem:'A patient is given a large dose of purely ketogenic amino acids. Why cannot this amino acid load contribute to gluconeogenesis despite the substantial caloric and carbon input?',choices:['A) Ketogenic amino acids are catabolized exclusively in muscle and cannot reach the liver for gluconeogenesis','B) Their carbon skeletons enter as acetyl-CoA or acetoacetate, and acetyl-CoA entering the TCA cycle loses both carbons as CO2 before OAA is regenerated, yielding no net gluconeogenic substrate','C) Ketogenic amino acids inhibit pyruvate carboxylase allosterically, preventing OAA synthesis','D) The liver lacks the enzymes to catabolize purely ketogenic amino acids and shunts them to adipose for storage'],answer:1,why:'Acetyl-CoA enters the TCA cycle by condensing with OAA to form citrate. As the cycle turns, both acetyl-CoA carbons are released as CO2 at isocitrate dehydrogenase and alpha-KGDH. The OAA regenerated at the end of the cycle is the SAME OAA consumed at the start; there is no net gain of OAA carbon from acetyl-CoA. Acetoacetate is converted to two acetyl-CoA molecules. Neither can be used for net glucose synthesis. Only carbon skeletons that can yield net OAA (or pyruvate, convertible to OAA) can fuel gluconeogenesis.'}]},{id:'7.6',num:'7.6',title:'7.6 Phenylalanine, Tyrosine, and Catecholamine Synthesis',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Phenylalanine and tyrosine share a catabolic pathway that branches into catecholamine synthesis, melanin production, and terminal oxidation. The first reaction, phenylalanine to tyrosine, is irreversible and clinically critical: it is the step blocked in phenylketonuria (PKU), the most common aminoacidopathy.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Phenylalanine Hydroxylase and Tetrahydrobiopterin (BH4)',x:'Phenylalanine hydroxylase (PAH) catalyzes the hydroxylation of phenylalanine to tyrosine. The reaction requires molecular O2 and tetrahydrobiopterin (BH4) as the hydroxyl donor. BH4 is oxidized to dihydrobiopterin (BH2) during the reaction and must be regenerated by dihydropteridine reductase (DHPR), which uses NADH. BH4 is also a cofactor for tyrosine hydroxylase (converts tyrosine to DOPA in catecholamine synthesis), tryptophan hydroxylase (converts tryptophan to 5-HTP in serotonin synthesis), and nitric oxide synthase (NOS). Therefore, BH4 deficiency causes hyperphenylalaninemia (PAH is inactive without cofactor) AND neurotransmitter deficiency (tyrosine and tryptophan hydroxylases also fail), producing a more severe neurological phenotype than PAH mutation alone.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Phenylketonuria (PKU)',x:'Cause: Autosomal recessive mutations in PAH (classic PKU) or in BH4 synthesis/recycling (atypical PKU/malignant hyperphenylalaninemia).\n\nBiochemistry: phenylalanine accumulates → transaminated to phenylpyruvate (a phenylketone, found in urine, hence phenylketonuria) → also produces phenylacetate (musty or mousy urine odor) and phenyllactate.\n\nPathophysiology: elevated phenylalanine competitively inhibits the large neutral amino acid transporter (LAT1) at the blood-brain barrier, reducing brain uptake of other large neutral AAs (tyrosine, tryptophan, leucine). This impairs neurotransmitter synthesis (dopamine from tyrosine, serotonin from tryptophan) and disrupts myelin production. Tyrosine becomes conditionally essential.\n\nClinical: intellectual disability (profound if untreated), fair hair and skin (melanin synthesis is impaired because PAH converts Phe to Tyr, the melanin precursor; without tyrosine supply, melanocytes cannot make melanin adequately), musty urine odor, eczema, seizures.\n\nScreening: newborn metabolic screen (elevated plasma phenylalanine on Guthrie test / tandem mass spectrometry on day 1-2 of life).\n\nTreatment: low-phenylalanine diet with supplemental tyrosine (making tyrosine an essential amino acid). Sapropterin (synthetic BH4) helps patients with residual PAH activity that responds to cofactor supplementation. Pegvaliase (an enzyme replacement: PEGylated phenylalanine ammonia lyase that degrades Phe) is available for adults.'},{t:'p',x:'Tyrosine is the branch point for three major pathways: catecholamine synthesis (in adrenal medulla and neurons), melanin synthesis (in melanocytes), and thyroid hormone synthesis (in thyroid follicular cells). On the MCAT, catecholamine and melanin pathways carry the most weight.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Catecholamine Synthesis From Tyrosine',x:'Tyrosine  →[Tyrosine hydroxylase (rate-limiting), BH4, Fe2+]→  DOPA (L-dihydroxyphenylalanine)\nDOPA  →[DOPA decarboxylase / aromatic L-amino acid decarboxylase, PLP/B6]→  Dopamine\nDopamine  →[Dopamine beta-hydroxylase, ascorbate (vitamin C), Cu2+]→  Norepinephrine (NE)\nNE  →[PNMT (phenylethanolamine N-methyltransferase), SAM as methyl donor]→  Epinephrine (Epi)\n\nKey points: Tyrosine hydroxylase is the committed and rate-limiting step. PNMT (in the adrenal medulla) is induced by cortisol from the adrenal cortex (high local cortisol concentration via portal circulation between cortex and medulla). This is why adrenocortical destruction (Addison disease) eventually reduces epinephrine production but not norepinephrine (NE).\n\nVitamin C (ascorbate) is required for dopamine beta-hydroxylase, explaining why scurvy causes catecholamine depletion in addition to collagen defects.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'Melanin Synthesis and Albinism',x:'In melanocytes, tyrosine is converted to DOPA by tyrosinase (a copper-containing enzyme that performs the same hydroxylation as tyrosine hydroxylase elsewhere, but uses copper rather than iron and BH4). DOPA is then oxidized by tyrosinase to dopaquinone, which polymerizes to form eumelanin (brown-black) or combines with cysteine to form pheomelanin (yellow-red).\n\nOculocutaneous albinism type 1 (OCA1): autosomal recessive tyrosinase deficiency. No melanin in skin, hair, or eyes. Features: white hair, pink skin, blue or red iris (iris vessels visible through unpigmented iris), nystagmus, photophobia, reduced visual acuity (foveal hypoplasia from lack of melanin in retinal pigment epithelium during development). Increased risk of squamous cell carcinoma from UV damage without protective melanin.\n\nOCA2: deficiency of the P protein (an anion transporter in melanosomes), not tyrosinase. Most common form globally. Some residual pigmentation may be present (yellow-tan hair, some iris color).\n\nNote: albinism in Hermansky-Pudlak syndrome (OCA with lysosomal storage and platelet dysfunction) and Chediak-Higashi syndrome (OCA with giant granule immune cells) involve organelle trafficking defects rather than tyrosinase loss.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A newborn screening panel shows elevated plasma phenylalanine and NORMAL BH4 levels. Supplementing with BH4 does not lower phenylalanine levels. Which is the most likely genetic defect?',choices:['A) Dihydropteridine reductase (DHPR) deficiency preventing BH4 regeneration','B) Loss-of-function mutation in phenylalanine hydroxylase (PAH) itself that does not respond to cofactor supplementation','C) Tyrosine hydroxylase deficiency causing phenylalanine accumulation upstream','D) Deficiency of GTP cyclohydrolase I, the first enzyme in BH4 synthesis'],answer:1,why:'If BH4 levels are normal and BH4 supplementation does not correct hyperphenylalaninemia, the defect is in PAH itself, not in BH4 synthesis or recycling. BH4-responsive PKU involves PAH mutations where the enzyme retains some residual activity that can be pushed by excess cofactor. BH4-non-responsive PKU indicates a PAH mutation that is essentially null or structurally unable to use even excess BH4. DHPR deficiency would lower BH4 levels, not leave them normal.'},{stem:'A patient with Addison disease has low adrenal cortisol production. Over time, which catecholamine shows the most selective reduction and why?',choices:['A) Dopamine, because tyrosine hydroxylase requires cortisol for maximal activity','B) Epinephrine, because PNMT (which methylates NE to Epi) is induced by local cortisol from adrenocortical blood','C) Norepinephrine, because dopamine beta-hydroxylase is cortisol-dependent in sympathetic neurons','D) All catecholamines equally, because cortisol induces tyrosine hydroxylase, the rate-limiting step'],answer:1,why:'PNMT, the enzyme that converts norepinephrine to epinephrine, is expressed almost exclusively in the adrenal medulla and is transcriptionally induced by high local cortisol delivered via the adrenocortical-medullary portal system. When Addison disease destroys the adrenal cortex, local cortisol falls, PNMT expression drops, and epinephrine synthesis is selectively reduced. Norepinephrine synthesis (via dopamine beta-hydroxylase) is less cortisol-dependent and is maintained by sympathetic neurons throughout the body.'}]},{id:'7.7',num:'7.7',title:'7.7 Tryptophan and Histidine Metabolism',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Tryptophan and histidine are both catabolized through pathways that generate physiologically important products, and both pathways are connected to clinical disorders that appear on the MCAT. Tryptophan branches into serotonin synthesis and NAD+ synthesis. Histidine is decarboxylated to histamine, the mediator of immediate hypersensitivity.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Tryptophan to Serotonin',x:'Step 1: Tryptophan  →[Tryptophan hydroxylase, BH4, O2]→  5-Hydroxytryptophan (5-HTP). Tryptophan hydroxylase is the rate-limiting step; it requires BH4 as cofactor (same as tyrosine hydroxylase). It is expressed in enterochromaffin cells of the intestinal mucosa (which produce ~95% of body serotonin) and in raphe nuclei neurons of the brainstem (which produce CNS serotonin).\n\nStep 2: 5-HTP  →[Aromatic L-amino acid decarboxylase (AAAD), PLP/B6]→  Serotonin (5-hydroxytryptamine, 5-HT) + CO2. The same AAAD enzyme also decarboxylates DOPA to dopamine.\n\nSerotonin is metabolized by MAO (monoamine oxidase) to 5-hydroxyindoleacetic acid (5-HIAA), excreted in urine. Elevated urine 5-HIAA is diagnostic for carcinoid tumor (a serotonin-secreting enterochromaffin cell tumor), which causes carcinoid syndrome: episodic flushing, diarrhea, bronchospasm, and right-sided valvular heart disease (tricuspid regurgitation, pulmonic stenosis). Right-sided heart disease predominates because serotonin is inactivated in the pulmonary circulation before reaching the left heart; hepatic metastases are required for systemic carcinoid syndrome because the liver inactivates gut-derived serotonin.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Tryptophan to NAD+ (Niacin Equivalent)',x:'Tryptophan can be converted to NAD+ via the kynurenine pathway, which requires vitamin B2 (FAD-dependent) and B6 (PLP-dependent) at key steps. The rough conversion is: 60 mg tryptophan = 1 mg niacin equivalent (NE). This conversion is the basis for the nutritional definition of niacin equivalents and explains why:\n\n1. Carcinoid syndrome causes pellagra-like symptoms: the tumor diverts tryptophan to serotonin, reducing the substrate available for NAD+ synthesis. If dietary niacin is also inadequate, NAD+ depletion (pellagra) results.\n\n2. Hartnup disease: autosomal recessive defect in the neutral amino acid transporter (SLC6A19) in the intestinal brush border and renal proximal tubule. Tryptophan cannot be absorbed from the gut (amino acid loss) and is lost in urine. The resulting tryptophan deficiency impairs NAD+ synthesis. Pellagra-like rash (photosensitive dermatitis), cerebellar ataxia, and psychiatric symptoms develop. Unlike dietary pellagra, Hartnup disease does not respond to dietary niacin alone unless tryptophan absorption is bypassed (e.g., by supplementing nicotinamide, the amide form of niacin).\n\n3. INH treatment: isoniazid inhibits PLP-dependent steps in the kynurenine pathway, reducing NAD+ synthesis from tryptophan. Combined with dietary niacin depletion, this can contribute to pellagra-like symptoms in patients on INH without B6 supplementation.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Histidine to Histamine',x:'Histidine  →[Histidine decarboxylase, PLP/B6]→  Histamine + CO2.\n\nHistidine decarboxylase (HDC) is a PLP-dependent enzyme expressed in mast cells, basophils, gastric enterochromaffin-like (ECL) cells, and neurons. The reaction is essentially irreversible and is the only known metabolic fate of histidine that produces histamine.\n\nHistamine actions (by receptor subtype): H1 (smooth muscle, endothelium, CNS): bronchoconstriction, vasodilation, increased vascular permeability, itch, pain, wakefulness. H2 (gastric parietal cells): stimulates HCl secretion (via cAMP → PKA → H+/K+-ATPase activation). H3 (presynaptic CNS): autoreceptor, reduces histamine release. H4 (immune cells): chemotaxis.\n\nMast cell activation (IgE-mediated, Type I hypersensitivity): antigen cross-links IgE on mast cell surface → mast cell degranulation → preformed histamine release → acute urticaria, angioedema, bronchospasm, anaphylaxis.\n\nClinical markers: serum tryptase (released from mast cell granules) is the most specific acute marker of mast cell activation and is used to confirm anaphylaxis. Urine methylhistamine and methylimidazoleacetic acid (histamine metabolites) can confirm histamine overproduction over longer periods.\n\nScombroid fish poisoning: bacterial histidine decarboxylase in improperly stored fish converts histidine in fish muscle to histamine. Consumption causes flushing, urticaria, headache, and GI symptoms within minutes. Treated with antihistamines.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'Carcinoid vs PKU: Urine Metabolite Pattern',x:'Carcinoid tumor: high urine 5-HIAA (serotonin metabolite), high serum serotonin. Provocation tests: flushing triggered by palpation of the liver (hepatic metastases release serotonin) or by alcohol/catecholamine stimulation.\n\nPKU: high urine phenylpyruvate, phenylacetate, phenyllactate. High plasma phenylalanine. Normal 5-HIAA.\n\nHartnup disease: aminoaciduria (neutral amino acids in urine), low plasma tryptophan, pellagra-like symptoms. Normal phenylpyruvate.\n\nMSUD: elevated BCKAs in urine, alloisoleucine in plasma, maple-syrup odor.\n\nEach disorder has a characteristic small-molecule signature that can be identified from a urine metabolomics or plasma amino acid profile.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A 35-year-old woman presents with episodic facial flushing, watery diarrhea, and wheezing. Serum serotonin is very elevated. A 24-hour urine 5-HIAA is 300 mg (normal <10 mg). CT shows a hepatic mass and an ileal mass. Which enzyme is responsible for producing the compound responsible for these symptoms in enterochromaffin cells?',choices:['A) Tyrosine hydroxylase, which converts tyrosine to DOPA in neuroendocrine cells','B) Tryptophan hydroxylase, which converts tryptophan to 5-hydroxytryptophan as the committed step in serotonin synthesis','C) Aromatic L-amino acid decarboxylase, which is the rate-limiting enzyme and the primary target for carcinoid treatment','D) MAO, which fails to degrade serotonin in the presence of hepatic metastases'],answer:1,why:'Tryptophan hydroxylase (in enterochromaffin cells and raphe neurons) catalyzes the rate-limiting committed step: tryptophan → 5-hydroxytryptophan (5-HTP), which is then decarboxylated by AAAD to serotonin. In carcinoid tumors, tryptophan hydroxylase is overexpressed, producing excess serotonin. Hepatic metastases are required for carcinoid syndrome because the liver normally inactivates gut-derived serotonin; with hepatic involvement, serotonin bypasses inactivation and reaches systemic circulation.'},{stem:'A child presents with a photosensitive rash, cerebellar ataxia, and aminoaciduria showing neutral amino acids (including tryptophan) in urine despite normal dietary tryptophan intake. Which process is disrupted at the molecular level?',choices:['A) Tryptophan hydroxylase activity is reduced due to BH4 deficiency','B) The neutral amino acid transporter (SLC6A19) in intestinal and renal brush border is non-functional, causing tryptophan malabsorption and urinary wasting','C) Histidine decarboxylase competes with tryptophan hydroxylase for the PLP cofactor, depleting serotonin synthesis','D) Aromatic L-amino acid decarboxylase is deficient, so 5-HTP accumulates and tryptophan is diverted to alternate pathways'],answer:1,why:'Hartnup disease is caused by loss-of-function mutations in SLC6A19, the apical neutral amino acid transporter in intestinal epithelium and renal proximal tubule. Without this transporter, tryptophan (a neutral amino acid) cannot be absorbed from the gut or reabsorbed from the tubular filtrate, causing aminoaciduria and dietary tryptophan deficiency. The tryptophan deficiency impairs both NAD+ synthesis (pellagra-like rash and neurological symptoms) and serotonin synthesis. The rash, ataxia, and neutral aminoaciduria together are pathognomonic for Hartnup disease.'}]},{id:'7.8',num:'7.8',title:'7.8 Methionine, SAM, and Homocysteine Metabolism',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Methionine is the only source of one-carbon methyl groups donated via S-adenosylmethionine (SAM). Every methylation reaction in the body, from DNA methylation to phosphatidylcholine synthesis to creatine synthesis, uses SAM as the methyl donor. After donating its methyl group, SAM becomes S-adenosylhomocysteine (SAH), which is hydrolyzed to homocysteine. Homocysteine sits at a metabolic crossroads: it can be remethylated back to methionine (requiring vitamin B12 and folate), or it can be converted to cysteine via the trans-sulfuration pathway (requiring vitamin B6/PLP). Defects in either route cause homocystinuria with distinct biochemical signatures.'},{t:'formula',x:'Methionine + ATP  →[Methionine adenosyltransferase]→  SAM + PPi + Pi\nSAM + Substrate  →[Methyltransferase]→  SAH + Methylated Substrate\nSAH + H2O  →[SAH hydrolase]→  Homocysteine + Adenosine\nHomocysteine + Methyl-THF  →[Methionine synthase, B12]→  Methionine + THF (remethylation)\nHomocysteine + Serine  →[CBS, PLP/B6]→  Cystathionine  →[Cystathionine gamma-lyase, PLP/B6]→  Cysteine + alpha-ketobutyrate (trans-sulfuration)'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'SAM: The Universal Methyl Donor',x:'SAM (S-adenosylmethionine) donates methyl groups to more than 100 known methyltransferase reactions. Key examples tested clinically:\n\n1. Epinephrine synthesis: PNMT transfers a methyl group from SAM to norepinephrine to make epinephrine.\n2. Creatine synthesis: guanidinoacetate methyltransferase methylates guanidinoacetate (made from arginine + glycine by AGAT in kidney) using SAM to form creatine.\n3. Phosphatidylcholine synthesis (PEMT pathway): three sequential methylation of phosphatidylethanolamine by SAM.\n4. DNA methylation: DNA methyltransferases (DNMT1, 3A, 3B) use SAM to methylate cytosines at CpG dinucleotides, controlling gene expression epigenetically.\n5. Myelin basic protein methylation and other neurological substrates.\n\nAfter methyl transfer, SAM becomes SAH. SAH is a potent competitive inhibitor of methyltransferases, so rapid hydrolysis of SAH to homocysteine is essential to maintain methylation capacity.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Three Genetic Causes of Homocystinuria',x:'TYPE 1: Cystathionine beta-synthase (CBS) deficiency. CBS catalyzes the first step of trans-sulfuration (homocysteine + serine → cystathionine). PLP/B6 is the cofactor. When CBS fails, homocysteine and methionine both accumulate (cannot be drained via trans-sulfuration).\n\nBiochemistry: high plasma homocysteine, HIGH plasma methionine, low plasma cystathionine, low cysteine.\nClinical: intellectual disability (progressive), Marfanoid habitus (tall, long limbs, arachnodactyly) but with DOWNWARD lens dislocation (ectopia lentis), osteoporosis, and thromboembolic disease (homocysteine damages endothelium, promotes platelet aggregation and thrombosis). Also: fair complexion (homocysteine may inhibit tyrosinase).\nTreatment: high-dose pyridoxine (B6) in responsive patients (those with residual CBS activity that is cofactor-limited). Betaine (trimethylglycine) provides an alternative methyl donor to remethylate homocysteine directly. Low-methionine diet + cysteine supplementation (cysteine becomes essential when CBS fails).\n\nTYPE 2: Methionine synthase deficiency or B12 deficiency. Methionine synthase (uses methylcobalamin/B12 and methyl-THF from folate) remethylates homocysteine to methionine. If B12 is absent or methionine synthase is deficient:\n\nBiochemistry: high homocysteine, LOW methionine (cannot be regenerated), elevated methylmalonic acid (MMA) if B12 is the cause (because adenosylcobalamin is also deficient, impairing methylmalonyl-CoA mutase). Methyl trap: folate is locked as 5-methyl-THF because methionine synthase cannot recycle it, depleting free THF and causing megaloblastic anemia.\nClinical: megaloblastic anemia, subacute combined degeneration of the spinal cord (B12 deficiency), no lens dislocation, no Marfanoid features.\n\nTYPE 3: MTHFR deficiency. Methylenetetrahydrofolate reductase (MTHFR) converts 5,10-methylene-THF to 5-methyl-THF (the methyl donor for methionine synthase). Without 5-methyl-THF, methionine synthase cannot remethylate homocysteine.\n\nBiochemistry: high homocysteine, LOW methionine, NORMAL MMA (adenosylcobalamin and methylmalonyl-CoA mutase are unaffected), NORMAL folate levels on blood test (folate is present but stuck in a non-functional oxidation state).\nClinical: milder presentation than CBS deficiency. Risk factor for neural tube defects (explains why MTHFR polymorphisms, especially C677T, are associated with NTD risk and why periconceptual folate supplementation is protective).'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'Distinguishing the Three Homocystinurias at a Glance',x:'CBS deficiency: homocysteine UP, methionine UP (both accumulate). Marfanoid + lens DOWN + thrombosis. Responds to B6.\n\nMethionine synthase (B12) deficiency: homocysteine UP, methionine DOWN (cannot be remethylated), MMA UP (adenosylcobalamin also deficient). Megaloblastic anemia + subacute combined degeneration.\n\nMTHFR deficiency: homocysteine UP, methionine DOWN (same as B12 deficiency). MMA NORMAL (only methylcobalamin function is lost, adenosylcobalamin is fine). Mild neurological symptoms, no anemia in mild forms. Responds to folate and betaine.\n\nBoard shortcut: Methionine HIGH = CBS deficiency. MMA HIGH = B12/methionine synthase deficiency. Both methionine LOW and MMA NORMAL = MTHFR deficiency.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'Homocysteine and Cardiovascular Disease',x:'Elevated plasma homocysteine (even mild elevation, >15 micromol/L) is associated with increased risk of atherosclerosis, coronary artery disease, stroke, and venous thromboembolism. The mechanisms include: direct endothelial toxicity (homocysteine generates reactive oxygen species, oxidizes LDL, impairs nitric oxide bioavailability), promotion of smooth muscle cell proliferation, enhanced platelet aggregation, and procoagulant state (homocysteine thiolactone modifies LDL). Mild hyperhomocysteinemia due to MTHFR C677T polymorphism (very common, ~10-15% of population) is modifiable with folate and B6/B12 supplementation, which lower homocysteine levels. However, randomized trials of B-vitamin supplementation for secondary prevention of cardiovascular events have had inconsistent results, suggesting that homocysteine is a marker rather than the direct causal agent in many patients.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A 14-year-old girl presents with intellectual disability, a tall thin build with long fingers, downward lens dislocation, and a deep vein thrombosis. Plasma homocysteine is markedly elevated and plasma methionine is also elevated. Which enzyme is most likely deficient?',choices:['A) Methionine synthase, causing failure to remethylate homocysteine with B12 cofactor','B) Cystathionine beta-synthase (CBS), causing failure to enter the trans-sulfuration pathway','C) MTHFR, causing failure to generate 5-methyl-THF for remethylation','D) Methylmalonyl-CoA mutase, causing MMA accumulation and secondary homocysteine elevation'],answer:1,why:'CBS deficiency blocks the trans-sulfuration pathway. Both homocysteine AND methionine accumulate (homocysteine cannot exit to cystathionine, and the remethylation pathway drives methionine production that cannot be drained). The clinical triad of Marfanoid habitus, DOWNWARD lens dislocation (distinguish from Marfan syndrome where lens dislocates UPWARD), and thromboembolic disease in a young person is pathognomonic for CBS deficiency homocystinuria. Methionine synthase or MTHFR deficiency would show LOW methionine (remethylation fails, so methionine cannot be regenerated).'},{stem:'A patient is found to have elevated plasma homocysteine and low plasma methionine. Serum B12 is normal. Methylmalonic acid is NORMAL. Red cell folate is normal. Which enzyme is deficient?',choices:['A) Cystathionine beta-synthase, because the elevated homocysteine means trans-sulfuration is blocked','B) Methionine synthase, because low methionine indicates remethylation failure and normal B12 rules out cofactor deficiency','C) MTHFR, because elevated homocysteine with low methionine and normal MMA and normal B12 points to failure to generate the folate-derived methyl group','D) Adenosylcobalamin-dependent methylmalonyl-CoA mutase, because normal MMA paradoxically indicates its absence'],answer:2,why:'The pattern of elevated homocysteine + low methionine + NORMAL MMA + normal B12 + normal folate is MTHFR deficiency. MTHFR converts 5,10-methylene-THF to 5-methyl-THF. Without 5-methyl-THF, methionine synthase cannot remethylate homocysteine, so homocysteine accumulates and methionine falls. Because only the methylcobalamin function of B12 is compromised (and indirectly, via reduced methionine synthase activity), adenosylcobalamin and methylmalonyl-CoA mutase are fully functional, so MMA is normal. B12 levels themselves are normal. CBS deficiency gives HIGH methionine.'}]},{id:'7.9',num:'7.9',title:'7.9 Glutamine Physiology and Integration of Nitrogen Economy',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Glutamine is not merely a conditionally essential amino acid; it is the most abundant amino acid in plasma and the predominant nitrogen transporter between tissues. Its synthesis and breakdown are regulated differently in different tissues, and understanding those differences ties together the entire chapter.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Glutamine Synthetase: The NH4+ Scavenger',x:'Glutamine synthetase (GS): Glutamate + NH4+ + ATP → Glutamine + ADP + Pi.\n\nExpression: high in brain (astrocytes: the primary cellular NH4+ detoxification site in the CNS), skeletal muscle, lung, and adipose. Low in normal hepatocytes (liver uses GDH and the urea cycle to dispose of NH4+, not GS). Perivenous hepatocytes (zone 3 of the hepatic lobule) express GS as a scavenger for NH4+ that escapes periportal urea synthesis.\n\nFunction: GS converts the neurotoxic NH4+ into the non-toxic, membrane-permeant amino acid glutamine, which exits cells and is carried in blood to the liver or kidney. In brain, astrocyte GS is the primary defense against hyperammonemia. When overwhelmed (as in urea cycle defects or hepatic encephalopathy), glutamine accumulation inside astrocytes causes osmotic swelling (the astrocyte Trojan horse mechanism).\n\nRegulation: GS is inhibited by its own product glutamine (product inhibition) and by elevated glutamate (substrate feedback). In prolonged starvation, GS activity in muscle increases, providing an alternative nitrogen sink when liver urea synthesis may be limited.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Glutaminase: The NH4+ Releaser',x:'Phosphate-activated glutaminase (PAG): Glutamine + H2O → Glutamate + NH4+.\n\nExpression: high in liver (periportal hepatocytes, releasing NH4+ for the urea cycle), kidney (proximal tubule, releasing NH4+ for urinary excretion as part of acid-base regulation), and intestinal enterocytes (rapidly dividing cells use glutamine as a major fuel via glutaminolysis).\n\nIn the kidney: renal glutaminase activity increases during metabolic acidosis. The NH4+ released from glutamine is excreted into the tubular lumen (as NH3 diffuses into the acidic lumen and is protonated to NH4+, which is trapped and cannot diffuse back). This urinary NH4+ excretion buffers acid and regenerates bicarbonate. Glutamine is therefore the primary vehicle for renal acid excretion during chronic acidosis, which is why plasma glutamine falls during prolonged metabolic acidosis as the kidney consumes it.\n\nIn the intestine: enterocytes oxidize glutamine to glutamate, then to alpha-KG, running a modified TCA cycle to generate ATP. The nitrogen is released as alanine and NH4+, which travel via the portal vein to the liver. This intestinal glutamine metabolism is why the gut contributes significantly to the portal NH4+ load and why intestinal disease or gut flora overgrowth (producing excess NH4+) can precipitate hepatic encephalopathy in cirrhotic patients.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'Glutamine as a Fuel for Rapidly Dividing Cells',x:'Cancer cells, immune cells (especially lymphocytes), and enterocytes rely heavily on glutamine as a carbon and nitrogen fuel, a phenomenon called glutamine addiction or glutaminolysis. Glutamine enters the cell and is converted to glutamate (by glutaminase), then to alpha-KG (by GDH or transaminases), which enters the TCA cycle as an anaplerotic substrate. This generates reducing equivalents and ATP without requiring glucose oxidation via pyruvate. The nitrogen from glutamine is used for nucleotide synthesis (the amide group of glutamine is the nitrogen donor for purine ring construction and for conversion of UMP to CTP via CTP synthetase). Pharmacological targeting of glutaminase (CB-839, telaglenastat) is under investigation as a cancer therapy.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'Hepatic Encephalopathy: The Clinical Integration',x:'Hepatic encephalopathy (HE) results from the liver\'s failure to clear portal NH4+. In cirrhosis, two mechanisms combine. First, functioning hepatocytes are reduced, so urea cycle capacity is low. Second, portal-systemic shunts (varices, TIPS) allow portal blood (rich in gut-derived NH4+ from bacterial urease and glutaminase) to bypass the liver entirely.\n\nPrecipitants: GI bleeding (blood protein → bacterial proteolysis → NH4+), constipation (increased colonic bacterial NH4+ production), infections (catabolism → NH4+), excess dietary protein, diuretics (alkalosis favors NH3 over NH4+, and NH3 crosses the blood-brain barrier more readily than NH4+).\n\nTreatment: Lactulose: acidifies the colon (NH4+ is trapped as the poorly absorbed ionic form, not NH3), reduces colonic transit time, alters gut flora. Rifaximin: non-absorbed antibiotic that reduces urease-producing colonic bacteria. Protein restriction: reduces the substrate for NH4+ generation. Zinc supplementation: zinc is a cofactor for ornithine transcarbamylase and may improve residual urea cycle function in cirrhotics.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'Nitrogen Flow Summary: From Protein to Urea',x:'Protein catabolism yields amino acids → transamination by aminotransferases (PLP/B6) transfers alpha-amino groups to alpha-KG → glutamate → glutamate dehydrogenase (in liver mitochondria) releases NH4+ → CPS-I (activated by NAG) fixes NH4+ into carbamoyl phosphate (2 ATP) → OTC adds carbamoyl group to ornithine → citrulline exits to cytoplasm → ASS condenses citrulline + aspartate (the second N) (1 ATP) → ASL releases arginine + fumarate → arginase cleaves arginine to urea + ornithine → urea exits liver → blood → renal filtration → urine. Net: 2 N atoms in, 1 urea out, 3 ATP consumed, ornithine regenerated.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A patient with cirrhosis is hospitalized for confusion and asterixis after a GI bleed. Serum ammonia is 190 micromol/L. Which of the following best explains why the GI bleed precipitated hepatic encephalopathy?',choices:['A) Blood in the gut is digested by intestinal proteases and bacterial urease to release ammonia, which bypasses the damaged liver via portosystemic shunts and reaches the brain','B) GI bleeding causes iron overload that directly inhibits hepatic urea cycle enzymes','C) Blood loss reduces hepatic oxygen delivery, slowing TCA cycle flux and trapping NH4+ in liver mitochondria','D) The anemia from bleeding reduces oxygen delivery to astrocytes, impairing glutamine synthetase activity and allowing NH4+ to accumulate'],answer:0,why:'Blood protein (hemoglobin, albumin) in the gut lumen is metabolized by intestinal bacteria (proteases, urease) to NH4+. Normally, this portal NH4+ is extracted by the liver and converted to urea. In cirrhosis, the combination of reduced urea cycle capacity (hepatocyte loss) and portosystemic shunting (blood bypasses the liver) allows NH4+ to reach the systemic circulation and cross the blood-brain barrier. GI bleeding dramatically increases the gut-derived NH4+ load, precipitating acute hepatic encephalopathy. Lactulose and rifaximin reduce this gut NH4+ source.'},{stem:'During chronic metabolic acidosis, the kidney increases NH4+ excretion. Which molecule serves as the primary nitrogen source for this renal NH4+ production, and which enzyme releases it?',choices:['A) Aspartate, released by aspartate aminotransferase in the proximal tubule','B) Glutamine, hydrolyzed by phosphate-activated glutaminase in the proximal tubule cells','C) Urea, hydrolyzed by renal urease to NH4+ in the collecting duct','D) Alanine, deaminated by alanine aminotransferase in the loop of Henle'],answer:1,why:'Renal ammoniagenesis during metabolic acidosis depends on glutamine as the nitrogen substrate. Phosphate-activated glutaminase in proximal tubule cells cleaves glutamine to glutamate + NH4+. The NH4+ is secreted into the tubular lumen, where the acidic pH (from H+ secretion by H+/K+-ATPase and NHE) converts NH3 to NH4+, trapping it for excretion. Glutamate undergoes further deamination to alpha-KG, releasing a second NH4+. The net result is that two NH4+ are excreted per glutamine consumed, and two bicarbonate molecules are regenerated.'}]}],
 bottomLine:'Amino acid nitrogen is collected by transamination (all aminotransferases require PLP/B6) into glutamate, then released as NH4+ by glutamate dehydrogenase (activated by ADP/GDP, inhibited by GTP/ATP/NADH, located in the mitochondrial matrix). The urea cycle disposes of two nitrogen atoms (NH4+ and aspartate) at a cost of three ATP, producing one urea and regenerating ornithine. CPS-I is activated by NAG (whose synthesis is driven by arginine), providing feedforward regulation. Urea cycle defects all cause hyperammonemia; OTC deficiency (X-linked, most common) is distinguished by high urine orotic acid; CPS-I deficiency has normal orotic acid. Hyperammonemia causes cerebral edema via astrocyte glutamine accumulation and osmotic swelling. Carbon skeletons re-enter the TCA or gluconeogenic pathway; only leucine and lysine are purely ketogenic. Key individual AA disorders: PKU (PAH deficiency, high Phe, musty urine, intellectual disability, low-Phe diet), homocystinuria type 1 (CBS deficiency, high homocysteine AND methionine, lens dislocation down, thrombosis, responds to B6), type 2 (B12/methionine synthase, high homocysteine, LOW methionine, high MMA), type 3 (MTHFR, high homocysteine, low methionine, normal MMA). MSUD is BCKDH deficiency (Leu/Ile/Val backup, sweet urine, thiamine-responsive). Carcinoid tumor overproduces serotonin (elevated urine 5-HIAA). Glutamine is the primary inter-tissue nitrogen carrier and the substrate for renal acid excretion during acidosis.',
 nextHint:'Chapter 8 (Nucleotide Metabolism) builds directly on this chapter: glutamine is the nitrogen donor for purine ring construction and for CTP synthesis from UMP. The distinction between de novo and salvage nucleotide pathways uses the same mechanistic logic as the distinction between urea cycle and alternative nitrogen-disposal routes. Folate and B12 (whose clinical integration was introduced here via homocysteine metabolism) reappear as cofactors for thymidylate synthesis and methylation in nucleotide metabolism.',
},
{
 n:8,
 title:'Nucleotide Metabolism',
 subtitle:'How the body builds, recycles, and destroys purines and pyrimidines, and why disrupting any step produces disease or becomes a drug target',
 tag:'Other Metabolism',
 foundational:'Nucleotides are the currency of genetic information and energy transfer. Every dividing cell must synthesize dNTPs for DNA replication; every metabolically active cell requires ATP, GTP, and NADH. Understanding how nucleotides are made and broken down explains gout, immunodeficiency, chemotherapy mechanisms, and antiviral drug selectivity.',
 buildsOn:'Chapter 5 (PPP produces ribose-5-phosphate, the scaffold for purine de novo synthesis); Chapter 3 (ATP as energy currency); Chapter 6 (folate as one-carbon carrier); Chapter 2 (enzyme inhibition patterns)',
 setsUp:'Molecular biology chapters (DNA replication, transcription) that assume a dNTP pool exists; pharmacology of cancer chemotherapy and antiviral drugs',
 objectives:['Trace the ten-step purine de novo synthesis pathway from ribose-5-phosphate to IMP, identifying the atoms contributed by each nitrogen and carbon donor','Identify the committed step of purine de novo synthesis and explain how AMP and GMP exert feedback inhibition','Describe the key mechanistic difference between purine and pyrimidine de novo synthesis with respect to when the ribose is attached','Explain the role of CPS-II in pyrimidine synthesis and distinguish it from CPS-I of the urea cycle','Predict the consequences of OTC deficiency and UMP synthase deficiency on orotic acid excretion','Explain how HGPRT salvages purines and why its deficiency causes Lesch-Nyhan syndrome','Trace purine catabolism to uric acid and identify the clinical consequences of uric acid overproduction or underexcretion','Explain the mechanism of allopurinol and how it differs from febuxostat and rasburicase','Connect ADA deficiency to SCID via accumulation of toxic deoxyadenosine in lymphocytes','Explain the mechanism of methotrexate, 5-FU, 6-MP, hydroxyurea, acyclovir, and NRTIs in terms of their effects on nucleotide metabolism'],
 opener:'Every time a cell divides, it must synthesize approximately 6 billion base pairs worth of dNTPs from scratch or from salvaged precursors. Every heartbeat requires ATP. Every signal transduction cascade runs on GTP. Nucleotide metabolism is therefore not a peripheral topic: it sits at the intersection of cell biology, immunology, oncology, and pharmacology.\n\nThe body builds purines and pyrimidines by two fundamentally different strategies. Purines are assembled atom by atom directly on a ribose scaffold, requiring ten enzymatic steps, two molecules of folate-derived one-carbon fragments, and several amino acids. Pyrimidines, by contrast, are ring-first: the six-membered ring is built in the cytoplasm before it is ever attached to ribose. These architectural differences explain why different drugs target the two pathways, and why folate deficiency kills both pathways simultaneously.\n\nWhen catabolism goes wrong, uric acid accumulates in joints and causes gout. When salvage pathways fail, toxic nucleotide derivatives poison lymphocytes and produce immunodeficiency. When synthetic enzymes are targeted by drugs, rapidly dividing cancer cells die. This chapter builds the mechanistic foundation to understand all of it.',
 pinnedDisc:{t:'PURINES vs PYRIMIDINES: THE KEY STRUCTURAL DIFFERENCE',x:'Purines (adenine, guanine) are bicyclic: a six-membered pyrimidine ring fused to a five-membered imidazole ring. Pyrimidines (cytosine, uracil, thymine) are monocyclic: a single six-membered ring. In de novo synthesis, the purine ring is assembled stepwise ON the ribose-5-phosphate scaffold (ring built on sugar). The pyrimidine ring is assembled first as orotate, then attached to PRPP (ring built before sugar). This means folate inhibitors (methotrexate) affect both pathways, but CPS-II inhibitors affect only pyrimidines. The end products of purine catabolism are water-insoluble uric acid (causes gout). Pyrimidine catabolism yields water-soluble beta-amino acids (no gout equivalent).'},
 sections:[{id:'8.1',num:'8.1',title:'8.1 Purine De Novo Synthesis',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'The purine de novo synthesis pathway builds the bicyclic purine ring atom by atom directly on a ribose-5-phosphate scaffold. The ribose comes from the pentose phosphate pathway as ribose-5-phosphate, which is first converted to PRPP (phosphoribosyl pyrophosphate) by PRPP synthetase. PRPP is the activated ribose donor for both purine and pyrimidine synthesis, making it one of the most strategically important intermediates in the cell.'},{t:'p',x:'The first and committed step of purine de novo synthesis is catalyzed by PRPP amidotransferase (also called glutamine phosphoribosylpyrophosphate amidotransferase). This enzyme transfers the amide nitrogen of glutamine to PRPP, displacing pyrophosphate and forming 5-phosphoribosylamine. The pyrophosphate is immediately hydrolyzed to two inorganic phosphates, making the reaction thermodynamically irreversible and truly committed. This is the regulatory bottleneck of the entire pathway.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'ATOM ORIGINS IN THE PURINE RING',x:'The purine ring is built from six different donors. N1 comes from aspartate (the amino group). N3 and N9 come from glutamine (amide nitrogen). C4, C5, and N7 come from glycine as a unit (glycine is incorporated intact into the ring). C2 and C8 each come from formyl-THF (tetrahydrofolate), a folate-derived one-carbon carrier; this is why folate deficiency and DHFR inhibitors (methotrexate) block purine synthesis. C6 comes from CO2 (bicarbonate). These origins are tested directly: folate provides C2 and C8; glycine provides C4+C5+N7 as a block; aspartate provides N1; glutamine provides N3 and N9; CO2 provides C6.'},{t:'formula',x:'PRPP + Glutamine  -[PRPP amidotransferase, committed step]->  5-phosphoribosylamine + PPi + Glutamate\n\n(10 steps total, incorporating Gly, formyl-THF x2, Gln, Asp, CO2)\n\nFirst stable product: IMP (inosine monophosphate, the common purine precursor)'},{t:'p',x:'IMP is the first stable product of de novo purine synthesis. From IMP, the pathway branches: IMP is converted to either AMP or GMP by separate enzyme sequences. The branch point reveals a beautiful cross-regulatory logic. To make AMP from IMP, adenylosuccinate synthetase uses GTP as the energy source (not ATP). To make GMP from IMP, IMP dehydrogenase and GMP synthetase use ATP as the energy source. This reciprocal arrangement means that when GTP is abundant, AMP synthesis is favored; when ATP is abundant, GMP synthesis is favored. Each nucleotide promotes synthesis of the other, preventing disproportionate accumulation of either.'},{t:'box',kind:'why',label:'WHY CROSS-REGULATION BETWEEN AMP AND GMP',x:'The cell needs both ATP and GTP in roughly equal amounts. If one were to accumulate while the other was depleted, the cross-regulatory mechanism corrects the imbalance automatically. Excess GTP accelerates the AMP branch (GTP is the cofactor for adenylosuccinate synthetase). Excess ATP accelerates the GMP branch (ATP is the cofactor for GMP synthetase). Meanwhile, both AMP and GMP feed back to inhibit PRPP amidotransferase, reducing overall purine synthesis when both end-products are adequate. The result is a self-balancing system that maintains the correct purine pool composition.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'REGULATION OF PURINE DE NOVO SYNTHESIS',x:'COMMITTED STEP: PRPP amidotransferase. INHIBITORS: AMP and GMP individually inhibit the enzyme (end-product feedback); AMP inhibits one allosteric site and GMP a separate site; both together produce synergistic inhibition. PRPP availability: PRPP synthetase itself is inhibited by AMP and GMP; reduced PRPP limits the substrate available for the committed step. ACTIVATOR: PRPP allosterically activates the committed step (substrate activation, ensures that the reaction runs only when substrate is plentiful). FOLATE DEPENDENCE: two formyl-THF molecules are incorporated at steps 3 and 9; depletion of THF (from DHFR inhibition or folate deficiency) blocks purine synthesis entirely.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'CLINICAL CONNECTION: FOLATE AND PURINE SYNTHESIS',x:'Methotrexate blocks dihydrofolate reductase (DHFR), which regenerates THF from DHF. Without THF, cells cannot form formyl-THF and cannot incorporate C2 or C8 into the growing purine ring. Purine de novo synthesis stops. This adds a second mechanism to methotrexate\'s anti-cancer action, in addition to blocking thymidylate synthesis. Rapidly dividing cells (cancer cells, gut epithelium, hair follicles) are most vulnerable because they rely heavily on de novo synthesis rather than salvage. Leucovorin (5-formyl-THF) rescue provides pre-formed folate that bypasses the DHFR block and rescues normal cells with functional folate transport.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'Which of the following correctly identifies the committed step of purine de novo synthesis and its substrate?',choices:['A) PRPP synthetase converting ribose-5-phosphate to PRPP','B) PRPP amidotransferase transferring glutamine\'s amide nitrogen to PRPP','C) Adenylosuccinate synthetase converting IMP to AMP precursor using GTP','D) IMP dehydrogenase oxidizing IMP toward GMP synthesis'],answer:1,why:'PRPP amidotransferase is the committed step. It transfers the amide nitrogen of glutamine to PRPP, forming 5-phosphoribosylamine and releasing pyrophosphate (immediately hydrolyzed). The irreversibility and the fact that it is specifically inhibited by AMP and GMP (the end products) define it as the committed, regulated step. PRPP synthetase makes PRPP but is not committed to purine synthesis specifically, since PRPP is also used for pyrimidine synthesis and other pathways.'},{stem:'A researcher discovers that GTP is the energy cofactor for converting IMP to AMP, while ATP is the energy cofactor for converting IMP to GMP. What is the physiological significance of this arrangement?',choices:['A) It wastes energy to slow the purine synthesis pathway','B) It ensures that accumulation of one purine drives synthesis of the other, balancing the AMP/GMP ratio','C) It links purine synthesis to oxidative phosphorylation through GTP production','D) It prevents AMP from being converted back to IMP under high-energy conditions'],answer:1,why:'When GTP is in excess, the GTP-requiring step (IMP to AMP via adenylosuccinate synthetase) is accelerated, consuming excess GTP and producing more AMP. When ATP is in excess, the ATP-requiring step (IMP to GMP) is accelerated, consuming excess ATP and producing more GMP. This reciprocal arrangement acts as a homeostatic buffer, keeping the ratio of purine nucleotides balanced without any separate regulatory enzyme.'}]},{id:'8.2',num:'8.2',title:'8.2 Pyrimidine De Novo Synthesis',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Pyrimidine de novo synthesis takes the opposite architectural approach from purine synthesis. Rather than building the ring on the ribose scaffold, the pyrimidine ring is assembled first as a free six-membered ring (ultimately as orotate), and only then is the completed ring attached to PRPP to form the first pyrimidine nucleotide, OMP (orotidine-5-monophosphate). This ring-first strategy has important implications: the committed step is the formation of carbamoyl phosphate by CPS-II, before any ribose is involved.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'CPS-II vs CPS-I: A CRITICAL DISTINCTION',x:'CPS-I and CPS-II are both enzymes that produce carbamoyl phosphate, but they are different enzymes in different compartments with different nitrogen sources and different physiological roles. CPS-I is in the mitochondrial matrix, uses free ammonium as the nitrogen source, requires N-acetylglutamate as an allosteric activator, and serves the urea cycle to dispose of excess nitrogen. CPS-II is in the cytoplasm, uses the amide nitrogen of glutamine as the nitrogen source, is inhibited by UTP (end-product feedback) and activated by ATP and PRPP, and serves pyrimidine synthesis. The MCAT and Step 1 frequently test this distinction. OTC deficiency (a urea cycle defect) causes carbamoyl phosphate to accumulate in mitochondria, spill into the cytoplasm, and overdrive CPS-II-mediated pyrimidine synthesis, producing orotic aciduria.'},{t:'formula',x:'CPS-II: Glutamine + 2 ATP + HCO3-  ->  Carbamoyl phosphate + Glutamate + 2 ADP + Pi  [cytoplasm]\n\nCarbamoyl phosphate + Aspartate  -[ATCase]->  Carbamoyl aspartate\nCarbamoyl aspartate  -[Dihydroorotase, ring closure]->  Dihydroorotate  [cytoplasm]\nDihydroorotate  -[Dihydroorotate dehydrogenase, DHODH]->  Orotate  [inner mitochondrial membrane]\nOrotate + PRPP  -[OPRTase]->  OMP  [cytoplasm]\nOMP  -[OMP decarboxylase]->  UMP  [cytoplasm]\nUMP  ->  UDP  ->  UTP  -[CTP synthetase, +Glutamine]->  CTP'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'THE CAD TRIFUNCTIONAL ENZYME',x:'In humans, the first three enzymatic activities of pyrimidine synthesis (CPS-II, ATCase, and dihydroorotase) are encoded by a single polypeptide called CAD. The trifunctional enzyme channels the carbamoyl phosphate intermediate directly from CPS-II to ATCase to dihydroorotase without releasing it into bulk solution, increasing efficiency. Dihydroorotate dehydrogenase (DHODH), which oxidizes dihydroorotate to orotate, is the one exception: it is located on the outer face of the inner mitochondrial membrane and uses ubiquinone (CoQ) as its electron acceptor. This means the mitochondrial electron transport chain is required for pyrimidine synthesis, a connection exploited by leflunomide (DHODH inhibitor used in rheumatoid arthritis).'},{t:'p',x:'OPRTase and OMP decarboxylase, the two enzymes that convert orotate to UMP, are encoded together as a bifunctional enzyme called UMP synthase (or UMPS). A loss-of-function mutation in UMP synthase causes hereditary orotic aciduria: orotate cannot be converted to OMP or UMP, so orotate accumulates and spills into urine. Unlike OTC deficiency, hereditary orotic aciduria does not cause hyperammonemia (the urea cycle is intact). Treatment is oral uridine supplementation, which bypasses the block: exogenous uridine is phosphorylated to UMP by uridine kinase, providing pyrimidines for nucleic acid synthesis, and the resulting feedback suppresses the de novo pathway.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'OROTIC ACIDURIA: TWO CAUSES, ONE PRESENTATION',x:'Elevated urinary orotic acid (orotic aciduria) appears in two very different metabolic disorders. In OTC deficiency (X-linked, urea cycle defect), carbamoyl phosphate accumulates in mitochondria, escapes to the cytoplasm, and is consumed by CPS-II-independent downstream enzymes (ATCase activity of CAD picks it up directly), producing excess orotate. Orotic aciduria here accompanies hyperammonemia, elevated glutamine, and low citrulline on urine organic acid/amino acid testing. In hereditary orotic aciduria (autosomal recessive, UMP synthase deficiency), orotic acid cannot be converted to OMP; orotic aciduria occurs but hyperammonemia is ABSENT (urea cycle is normal). The discriminating feature on a vignette: hyperammonemia = OTC deficiency; no hyperammonemia = hereditary orotic aciduria. Both are treated with uridine supplementation.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'THYMIDYLATE SYNTHESIS: dUMP TO dTMP',x:'Thymine nucleotides require a separate biosynthetic step not needed for other pyrimidines. Thymidylate synthase converts dUMP to dTMP using N5,N10-methylene-THF as both the carbon donor and reductant. The methylene-THF is oxidized to DHF in this reaction: both the carbon and two electrons are donated simultaneously. DHF must be regenerated to THF by dihydrofolate reductase (DHFR), which uses NADPH. The cycle is: THF -[serine hydroxymethyltransferase, uses serine]-> methylene-THF; methylene-THF -[thymidylate synthase]-> DHF + dTMP; DHF -[DHFR, NADPH]-> THF. Methotrexate blocks DHFR, depleting both the THF needed for methylene-THF regeneration AND the methylene-THF needed for C2 and C8 of purines: one drug, two metabolic blocks.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A child with hyperammonemia, elevated urinary orotate, and low plasma citrulline is most likely deficient in which enzyme?',choices:['A) UMP synthase (hereditary orotic aciduria)','B) CPS-II (pyrimidine synthesis committed step)','C) Ornithine transcarbamylase (OTC, urea cycle)','D) Dihydroorotate dehydrogenase (DHODH)'],answer:2,why:'OTC deficiency produces the combination of hyperammonemia + orotic aciduria + low citrulline. OTC normally converts ornithine + carbamoyl phosphate to citrulline in mitochondria. Without OTC, carbamoyl phosphate accumulates in mitochondria and spills into the cytoplasm, where it drives pyrimidine synthesis past dihydroorotate to orotate, which then accumulates. Hereditary orotic aciduria (UMP synthase deficiency) causes orotic aciduria WITHOUT hyperammonemia, because the urea cycle is intact.'},{stem:'Thymidylate synthase uses methylene-THF to convert dUMP to dTMP. What happens to the methylene-THF in this reaction, and why does methotrexate stop dTMP synthesis?',choices:['A) Methylene-THF is regenerated intact; methotrexate blocks thymidylate synthase directly','B) Methylene-THF is oxidized to DHF; methotrexate blocks DHFR, preventing THF regeneration and depleting the methylene-THF pool','C) Methylene-THF is reduced to formyl-THF; methotrexate blocks serine hydroxymethyltransferase','D) Methylene-THF is consumed as a carbon donor only; methotrexate blocks thymidylate synthase by competitive inhibition'],answer:1,why:'In the thymidylate synthase reaction, methylene-THF donates both a one-carbon group and two electrons (acting as a reductant). The product of the THF side is DHF, not regenerated THF. DHFR must reduce DHF back to THF using NADPH before serine hydroxymethyltransferase can regenerate methylene-THF. Methotrexate blocks DHFR, causing DHF to accumulate and methylene-THF to become depleted, halting dTMP synthesis. This is the primary anti-cancer mechanism of methotrexate for pyrimidine synthesis.'}]},{id:'8.3',num:'8.3',title:'8.3 Salvage Pathways',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'De novo synthesis is energetically expensive: each purine ring requires ten enzymatic steps and multiple ATP equivalents. Salvage pathways recover the free bases produced by nucleic acid turnover and reattach them to PRPP, regenerating nucleoside monophosphates at a fraction of the energy cost. Salvage is quantitatively dominant over de novo synthesis in most differentiated tissues; de novo synthesis is most important in rapidly dividing cells such as cancer cells and activated lymphocytes.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'PURINE SALVAGE ENZYMES',x:'HGPRT (hypoxanthine-guanine phosphoribosyl transferase): converts hypoxanthine + PRPP to IMP, and converts guanine + PRPP to GMP. Both products are nucleoside monophosphates ready for the cell. HGPRT is the major purine salvage enzyme in the body; its activity is highest in the brain and testes. APRT (adenine phosphoribosyl transferase): converts adenine + PRPP to AMP. These enzymes all use PRPP as the activated ribose donor; the pyrophosphate released is hydrolyzed, driving the reaction forward. Salvage pathways also suppress de novo synthesis by raising AMP and GMP concentrations, which feed back to inhibit PRPP amidotransferase.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'LESCH-NYHAN SYNDROME: HGPRT DEFICIENCY',x:'Lesch-Nyhan syndrome is caused by complete loss-of-function mutations in HGPRT, encoded on the X chromosome (Xq26-27). Males are affected; females are carriers with one functional copy. Without HGPRT, hypoxanthine and guanine cannot be salvaged. PRPP accumulates (because it is no longer consumed by HGPRT) and drives excessive de novo purine synthesis, ultimately producing massive uric acid overproduction. Clinical manifestations: hyperuricemia and gout (from uric acid overproduction), but also a dramatic neurological syndrome including choreoathetosis (involuntary writhing movements), intellectual disability, and pathological self-mutilation (compulsive biting of lips and fingers, not under voluntary control). The neurological features are not explained simply by uric acid and are thought to reflect loss of dopaminergic pathways in the basal ganglia that depend on purine salvage for normal function. Patients are typically resistant to 6-mercaptopurine chemotherapy because 6-MP requires HGPRT to be activated.'},{t:'p',x:'Pyrimidine salvage also occurs and is clinically exploited. Uridine kinase phosphorylates uridine to UMP, and thymidine kinase (TK) phosphorylates thymidine to TMP. Thymidine kinase 1 (TK1) is a cytoplasmic enzyme whose expression is tightly linked to the cell cycle: it is essentially absent in G0 and G1 cells and rises sharply at the G1/S boundary, becoming maximally expressed in S phase. This cell-cycle dependence reflects the sudden need for thymidine phosphorylation during DNA replication. TK1 levels in serum have been used as a proliferation marker in cancer.'},{t:'box',kind:'why',label:'WHY ANTIVIRAL NUCLEOSIDE ANALOGS ARE SELECTIVE FOR INFECTED CELLS',x:'Acyclovir and related guanosine analogs require phosphorylation to become active inhibitors of viral DNA polymerase. The first and rate-limiting phosphorylation is performed by a viral thymidine kinase, encoded by herpes simplex virus (HSV) and varicella-zoster virus (VZV) but not present in uninfected human cells. Cellular TK1 has very low affinity for acyclovir and barely phosphorylates it. Viral TK has broad substrate specificity and phosphorylates acyclovir efficiently. Once monophosphorylated, cellular kinases complete the phosphorylation to acyclo-GTP, which is a potent inhibitor of viral DNA polymerase (incorporated and acts as a chain terminator because it lacks a 3-OH group). The selectivity of acyclovir rests entirely on this viral TK-dependent first phosphorylation.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'PYRIMIDINE CATABOLISM AND BETA-AMINO ACIDS',x:'Pyrimidine catabolism produces water-soluble products, in stark contrast to purines. Uracil and cytosine both catabolize to beta-alanine (a beta-amino acid, not an alpha-amino acid) plus ammonia and CO2. Thymine catabolizes to beta-aminoisobutyrate plus ammonia and CO2. Beta-alanine enters central metabolism via conversion to malonyl-CoA and ultimately acetyl-CoA. Beta-aminoisobutyrate is mostly excreted in urine. Because pyrimidine catabolism yields these water-soluble products, there is no pyrimidine-equivalent of gout: no crystals, no joint disease. This is a direct consequence of the different end-point chemistry of purine vs. pyrimidine catabolism.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A 2-year-old boy shows self-mutilation behavior (biting his lips and fingers), choreoathetosis, and laboratory findings of hyperuricemia. Which metabolic consequence most directly explains the uric acid overproduction in this condition?',choices:['A) Increased dietary purine intake overwhelming salvage capacity','B) PRPP accumulation drives excessive de novo purine synthesis because HGPRT cannot consume it','C) Deficient xanthine oxidase converts hypoxanthine directly to uric acid without the normal intermediate steps','D) Excess AMP produced by increased de novo synthesis is directly oxidized to uric acid'],answer:1,why:'In Lesch-Nyhan syndrome, HGPRT is absent. Without HGPRT, PRPP is not consumed by salvage of hypoxanthine or guanine. PRPP accumulates and allosterically activates PRPP amidotransferase, the committed step of purine de novo synthesis. Excessive de novo synthesis floods the purine pool, leading to hyperuricemia via xanthine oxidase-mediated catabolism of the excess purines. The hypoxanthine and guanine that cannot be salvaged are also catabolized to uric acid by xanthine oxidase.'},{stem:'Acyclovir is effective against HSV infection but has minimal toxicity to uninfected human cells. Which property of acyclovir accounts for this selectivity?',choices:['A) Acyclovir is selectively taken up by cells expressing HSV surface receptors','B) Viral thymidine kinase has much higher affinity for acyclovir than human thymidine kinase 1, providing the first phosphorylation only in infected cells','C) Acyclovir is converted to the active triphosphate form only by human cellular kinases that are upregulated during viral infection','D) Acyclovir inhibits human DNA polymerase with the same potency as viral polymerase but the drug is pumped out of uninfected cells'],answer:1,why:'Acyclovir requires monophosphorylation to begin its activation to acyclo-GTP. Human TK1 has very low affinity for acyclovir and does not efficiently phosphorylate it. Viral (HSV, VZV) thymidine kinase has broad substrate specificity and readily phosphorylates acyclovir to acyclo-GMP. Only in HSV-infected cells, which express viral TK, does acyclovir get phosphorylated. Once monophosphorylated, cellular kinases complete the conversion to acyclo-GTP, which then inhibits viral DNA polymerase and terminates chain elongation.'}]},{id:'8.4',num:'8.4',title:'8.4 Purine Catabolism and Gout',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Purines are catabolized in a stepwise pathway that ends at uric acid in humans. AMP is dephosphorylated to adenosine, then deaminated to inosine by adenosine deaminase (ADA), or adenosine kinase can reuse it. Inosine is hydrolyzed to hypoxanthine + ribose-1-phosphate by purine nucleoside phosphorylase (PNP). GMP is dephosphorylated to guanosine, then converted to guanine + ribose-1-phosphate by PNP. Guanine is deaminated to xanthine by guanine deaminase. Hypoxanthine is oxidized to xanthine by xanthine oxidase. Xanthine is then oxidized to uric acid, again by xanthine oxidase. Both xanthine oxidase steps generate reactive oxygen species (superoxide and hydrogen peroxide) as byproducts, contributing to oxidative stress during states of massive purine catabolism such as tumor lysis syndrome.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'URIC ACID: ENDPOINT ONLY IN HUMANS',x:'Most mammals express uricase (urate oxidase), which converts uric acid to allantoin, a water-soluble product that is readily excreted. Humans (and other higher primates) have a non-functional URIC gene encoding uricase and therefore cannot degrade uric acid further. Uric acid is the end product of purine catabolism in humans. Uric acid\'s pKa is approximately 5.4, meaning it exists as the soluble urate anion at physiological pH (7.4), but in the distal nephron (where urine pH can fall to 5.0 to 5.5) and in avascular tissues like cartilage (lower pH, lower temperature) it approaches the protonated form, which is much less soluble. Monosodium urate crystals deposit in cooler peripheral joints (first metatarsophalangeal joint being the classic site for podagra), bursae, and tendons, and in soft tissue collections called tophi.'},{t:'formula',x:'AMP -> Adenosine -[ADA]-> Inosine -[PNP]-> Hypoxanthine\nGMP -> Guanosine -[PNP]-> Guanine -[Guanine deaminase]-> Xanthine\nHypoxanthine -[Xanthine oxidase, +O2, generates O2- and H2O2]-> Xanthine\nXanthine -[Xanthine oxidase, +O2]-> Uric acid (end product in humans)'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'GOUT: MECHANISM AND TRIGGERS',x:'Gout arises when serum urate exceeds its solubility limit (approximately 6.8 mg/dL at 37 degrees C) and monosodium urate crystals precipitate in joints and tissues. The crystals are needle-shaped and negatively birefringent under polarized light (yellow when parallel to the compensator axis). Macrophages and neutrophils phagocytose the crystals but cannot degrade them; intracellular crystal deposition activates the NLRP3 inflammasome, triggering IL-1 beta release and the acute inflammatory cascade. Colchicine treats acute gout by inhibiting microtubule polymerization, preventing neutrophil migration to the joint. METABOLIC TRIGGERS of hyperuricemia: alcohol (ethanol oxidation increases NADH/NAD+ ratio, shifting lactate from lactate dehydrogenase toward lactate, which competes with urate for proximal tubular secretion via OAT transporters; also, beer contains guanosine); fructose (fructokinase phosphorylates fructose to F-1-P consuming ATP, ADP is then dephosphorylated to AMP, which is catabolized to uric acid); thiazide diuretics (reduce renal urate excretion by volume contraction, competing with organic anion transporters); low-dose aspirin (competes with urate at proximal tubular transporters, reducing net secretion); lead nephropathy (saturne gout from lead inhibiting renal tubular urate excretion).'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'ALLOPURINOL: MECHANISM-BASED INHIBITION',x:'Allopurinol is a structural analog of hypoxanthine. It binds to xanthine oxidase and is oxidized by the enzyme to alloxanthine (also called oxypurinol), which remains tightly bound in the active site, inactivating the enzyme in a mechanism-based (suicide inhibition) fashion. Because xanthine oxidase is needed for both the hypoxanthine-to-xanthine and xanthine-to-uric acid steps, allopurinol blocks the final two steps of purine catabolism. Hypoxanthine and xanthine accumulate in the plasma, but both are more water-soluble than uric acid and are excreted renally without precipitating. Net effect: uric acid production decreases substantially. IMPORTANT DRUG INTERACTION: 6-mercaptopurine (6-MP) and azathioprine (which is metabolized to 6-MP) are catabolized by xanthine oxidase. Allopurinol inhibits their catabolism, causing 6-MP levels to rise dramatically; the dose of 6-MP or azathioprine must be reduced by approximately 75% when allopurinol is co-administered.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'FEBUXOSTAT AND RASBURICASE: ALTERNATIVE AGENTS',x:'Febuxostat is a non-purine selective inhibitor of xanthine oxidase. Unlike allopurinol, it does not need to be activated by xanthine oxidase (it is not a mechanism-based inhibitor), and it is not itself a purine analog. It has the same urate-lowering effect as allopurinol but has fewer drug interactions and does not require dose adjustment for mild to moderate renal impairment. Rasburicase is recombinant urate oxidase (uricase), the enzyme that humans lost evolutionarily. Administered intravenously, it converts uric acid to allantoin, rapidly lowering serum urate. It is used specifically for tumor lysis syndrome (TLS), in which massive cancer cell death (from chemotherapy initiation, particularly in Burkitt lymphoma and ALL) releases enormous quantities of intracellular purines. The resulting acute uric acid overload can cause acute urate nephropathy and renal failure within hours. Rasburicase converts the uric acid load to allantoin before it can precipitate. Contraindicated in G6PD deficiency because H2O2 is generated in the reaction and would cause oxidative hemolysis.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'ADA DEFICIENCY AND SCID',x:'Adenosine deaminase (ADA) converts adenosine to inosine and deoxyadenosine to deoxyinosine. In ADA deficiency (autosomal recessive), deoxyadenosine (dAdo) accumulates. Lymphocytes, particularly T cells, have high levels of deoxycytidine kinase, which phosphorylates deoxyadenosine to dAMP and then to dATP. dATP accumulates to very high concentrations specifically in T and B lymphocytes (other cell types can dephosphorylate dATP more readily). High dATP inhibits ribonucleotide reductase (RNR), depleting all other dNTPs and blocking DNA synthesis. dATP also directly activates apoptosis via cytochrome c release. The result is progressive lymphocyte depletion leading to severe combined immunodeficiency (SCID), affecting both T cell and B cell lineages. ADA-SCID was the first genetic disease treated with gene therapy (1990, replacing the ADA gene in autologous T cells). PEG-ADA enzyme replacement therapy is also available.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A patient with gout is started on allopurinol and is also taking azathioprine for an inflammatory bowel condition. Why must the azathioprine dose be reduced?',choices:['A) Allopurinol inhibits HGPRT, preventing azathioprine\'s activation to 6-MP','B) Allopurinol inhibits xanthine oxidase, which normally catabolizes 6-MP (the active metabolite of azathioprine), causing 6-MP to accumulate to toxic levels','C) Both drugs compete for the same renal tubular transporter, increasing allopurinol toxicity','D) Allopurinol activates xanthine oxidase at high doses, converting azathioprine to a toxic oxidized product'],answer:1,why:'Azathioprine is a prodrug that is converted to 6-mercaptopurine (6-MP) in vivo. 6-MP is catabolized in part by xanthine oxidase. Allopurinol inhibits xanthine oxidase (both by mechanism-based inhibition after being converted to alloxanthine, and by substrate competition). With xanthine oxidase inhibited, 6-MP is not catabolized at the normal rate, and its plasma concentration rises to potentially myelotoxic levels. The dose of azathioprine or 6-MP must typically be reduced by about 75% when allopurinol is used concurrently.'},{stem:'A young man with a history of recurrent acute joint attacks is found to have serum urate of 9.2 mg/dL. He drinks three to four beers nightly. Which mechanism best explains how alcohol raises serum urate?',choices:['A) Ethanol is converted to uric acid directly by xanthine oxidase','B) Ethanol oxidation increases NADH, shifting lactate dehydrogenase toward lactate, which competes with urate for proximal tubular secretion','C) Acetaldehyde directly activates PRPP amidotransferase, increasing de novo purine synthesis','D) Alcohol inhibits ADA, causing deoxyadenosine to accumulate and be converted to uric acid'],answer:1,why:'Ethanol is oxidized to acetaldehyde and then to acetate, with each step consuming NAD+ and producing NADH. The elevated NADH/NAD+ ratio drives lactate dehydrogenase toward lactate production (from pyruvate). Elevated serum lactate competes with urate for secretion by organic anion transporters (OAT1, OAT3) in the proximal renal tubule, reducing urate excretion and raising serum urate. Alcohol (particularly beer, which also contains guanosine) can also increase purine load, but the lactate-mediated impairment of renal urate excretion is the primary acute mechanism.'}]},{id:'8.5',num:'8.5',title:'8.5 Anticancer and Antiviral Nucleotide Analogs',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'The nucleotide synthesis pathways are among the most targeted systems in pharmacology, precisely because rapidly dividing cells (cancer cells, viruses replicating inside cells) are far more dependent on nucleotide supply than quiescent normal cells. Antimetabolites are structural analogs of normal metabolites that either inhibit the enzymes of nucleotide synthesis or are incorporated into nucleic acids and disrupt their function. Understanding the mechanism of each drug requires knowing exactly which enzyme is blocked, what intermediate accumulates, and how that disrupts cell division.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'METHOTREXATE (MTX): DHFR INHIBITOR',x:'Methotrexate is a structural analog of folate. It binds dihydrofolate reductase (DHFR) with approximately 1000-fold greater affinity than the natural substrate dihydrofolate (DHF), essentially irreversibly inhibiting the enzyme at therapeutic concentrations. Without DHFR activity, DHF accumulates and THF cannot be regenerated. The downstream consequences are twofold: (1) methylene-THF is depleted, halting thymidylate synthase (no dTMP synthesis); (2) formyl-THF is depleted, blocking incorporation of C2 and C8 into growing purine rings (halts de novo purine synthesis). Both DNA synthesis and RNA synthesis are impaired because both dTMP and purines are limiting. Leucovorin (5-formyl-THF, folinic acid) rescues normal cells from MTX toxicity by providing pre-formed, reduced folate that enters the pathway downstream of DHFR, bypassing the block. Cancer cells can develop MTX resistance via DHFR gene amplification, reduced folate transporter expression, or impaired polyglutamation (MTX must be polyglutamated intracellularly to be retained and to inhibit additional folate enzymes).'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'5-FLUOROURACIL (5-FU): THYMIDYLATE SYNTHASE INHIBITOR',x:'5-Fluorouracil is a uracil analog with a fluorine at the 5-position. 5-FU itself is a prodrug. Inside cells, it is converted to several active metabolites. The most important for its anti-tumor action is 5-FdUMP (5-fluorodeoxyuridine monophosphate), which forms a covalent ternary complex with thymidylate synthase (TS) and methylene-THF. The fluorine at C5 prevents the normal elimination step required to complete the methylation of dUMP; the enzyme cannot complete its catalytic cycle and is trapped with 5-FdUMP covalently bound. Thymidylate synthase is inactivated, dTMP synthesis stops, and cells cannot replicate DNA. A second active metabolite, FUTP (5-fluorouridine triphosphate), is incorporated into RNA and disrupts RNA processing and function. Leucovorin enhances 5-FU\'s efficacy: by flooding cells with methylene-THF, the ternary inhibitory complex between 5-FdUMP, TS, and methylene-THF is stabilized. This is why leucovorin is co-administered with 5-FU in colorectal cancer chemotherapy.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'6-MERCAPTOPURINE (6-MP): PURINE SYNTHESIS INHIBITOR',x:'6-Mercaptopurine is a purine analog (hypoxanthine with a thiol at C6 replacing the hydroxyl). It must be activated by HGPRT (the salvage enzyme) to 6-MPRP (6-mercaptopurine ribonucleoside monophosphate), making it ironically a substrate for the same enzyme whose deficiency causes Lesch-Nyhan syndrome. This is why Lesch-Nyhan patients (HGPRT deficient) are resistant to 6-MP chemotherapy. Once activated, 6-MPRP and its derivatives inhibit two key steps: (1) PRPP amidotransferase, the committed step of purine de novo synthesis (acts as a feedback analog of AMP/GMP); (2) adenylosuccinate synthetase and IMP dehydrogenase, blocking both AMP and GMP branches from IMP. 6-MP is also incorporated into DNA as a thioguanine nucleotide, causing mismatches and triggering mismatch repair-mediated cell death. 6-MP is used primarily in childhood ALL maintenance therapy and inflammatory bowel disease (as azathioprine). As noted, its dose must be reduced by 75% when allopurinol is co-administered.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'HYDROXYUREA: RIBONUCLEOTIDE REDUCTASE INHIBITOR',x:'Ribonucleotide reductase (RNR) converts ribonucleoside diphosphates (ADP, GDP, CDP, UDP) to the corresponding deoxyribonucleoside diphosphates (dADP, dGDP, dCDP, dUDP). This is the only source of the deoxyribose required for DNA synthesis; all dNTPs ultimately come from this reaction. Hydroxyurea is a radical scavenger that quenches the tyrosyl radical in the R2 subunit of RNR, inactivating it. Without RNR, dNTP pools are depleted and DNA synthesis stops. Cells in S phase are most sensitive. Clinical uses: chronic myelogenous leukemia (CML), essential thrombocythemia, polycythemia vera, and sickle cell disease. In sickle cell disease, hydroxyurea increases HbF (fetal hemoglobin) synthesis by an incompletely understood mechanism (likely involves NO generation and activation of cGMP signaling in erythroid progenitors), which dilutes HbS and reduces sickling.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'ACYCLOVIR, GANCICLOVIR, AND CHAIN TERMINATION',x:'Acyclovir is a guanosine analog in which the ribose ring is replaced by an acyclic side chain (no 3-OH group). As described in section 8.3, it requires viral thymidine kinase for the first phosphorylation (selectivity). Cellular kinases then add the second and third phosphates to form acyclo-GTP. Acyclo-GTP has two mechanisms of action: (1) it is incorporated by viral DNA polymerase at the 3-prime end of the growing chain, but because it lacks a 3-OH, no further nucleotide can be added (chain termination); (2) it binds viral DNA polymerase with much greater affinity than human DNA polymerase, giving additional selectivity. Ganciclovir has a slightly different acyclic chain that preserves a functional (but shifted) hydroxyl equivalent, making it a better substrate for viral TK and more effective against CMV, which has a different TK (UL97 kinase). CMV resistance emerges via mutations in UL97 (reducing ganciclovir activation) or in UL54 (DNA polymerase, reducing drug binding).'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'NRTIs: NUCLEOSIDE REVERSE TRANSCRIPTASE INHIBITORS FOR HIV',x:'HIV uses reverse transcriptase (RT) to convert its RNA genome into double-stranded DNA for integration. NRTIs are nucleoside analogs that are activated by cellular kinases (not viral TK) to their triphosphate forms. They lack a 3-OH group (or its equivalent) and act as chain terminators when incorporated by RT. Key NRTIs: zidovudine (AZT, thymidine analog; the first antiretroviral approved), tenofovir (adenosine analog; as tenofovir disoproxil fumarate or tenofovir alafenamide; backbone of most HIV regimens), emtricitabine (cytidine analog), lamivudine (cytidine analog, also active against HBV). Toxicities stem from mitochondrial toxicity: cellular DNA polymerase gamma (the mitochondrial polymerase) has the lowest selectivity against NRTIs, and its inhibition causes mitochondrial DNA depletion, producing lactic acidosis, hepatic steatosis, peripheral neuropathy, and lipodystrophy. AZT also causes bone marrow suppression (RBC and WBC suppression) via its action on rapidly dividing hematopoietic progenitors.'},{t:'formula',x:'Drug mechanisms summary:\n5-FU (as 5-FdUMP) -[covalent ternary complex]-> thymidylate synthase BLOCKED -> no dTMP\nMethotrexate -> DHFR BLOCKED -> no THF -> no methylene-THF -> no dTMP, no purine C2/C8\n6-MP (via HGPRT) -> 6-MPRP -> PRPP amidotransferase BLOCKED + IMP dehydrogenase BLOCKED\nHydroxyurea -> RNR radical QUENCHED -> no dNTPs\nAcyclovir (via viral TK) -> Acyclo-GTP -> viral DNA pol INHIBITED + chain termination\nNRTIs (via cellular kinases) -> Triphosphate analogs -> HIV RT INHIBITED + chain termination'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A patient with colorectal cancer is treated with 5-FU plus leucovorin. Why does leucovorin ENHANCE rather than reverse the cytotoxic effect of 5-FU in this combination?',choices:['A) Leucovorin rescues normal cells but is excluded from cancer cells, increasing the therapeutic index','B) Leucovorin provides excess methylene-THF that stabilizes the covalent ternary inhibitory complex between 5-FdUMP and thymidylate synthase','C) Leucovorin inhibits DHFR independently, adding a second mechanism of action','D) Leucovorin is converted to 5-FdUMP intracellularly, synergizing with 5-FU'],answer:1,why:'5-FdUMP, thymidylate synthase, and methylene-THF form a covalent ternary complex that inactivates the enzyme. The stability of this complex depends on the concentration of methylene-THF: higher methylene-THF levels make the complex more stable and longer-lasting. Leucovorin (5-formyl-THF) is converted intracellularly to methylene-THF, increasing its concentration and thereby stabilizing the inhibitory ternary complex. This is the opposite of the MTX situation where leucovorin is used as a rescue agent; here it is used as a potentiator of 5-FU\'s anti-tumor activity.'},{stem:'An HIV-positive patient on AZT (zidovudine) develops peripheral neuropathy and lactic acidosis. Which mechanism best explains these toxicities?',choices:['A) AZT triphosphate inhibits HIV reverse transcriptase in peripheral neurons, blocking viral replication','B) AZT triphosphate inhibits mitochondrial DNA polymerase gamma, causing mitochondrial DNA depletion and impaired oxidative phosphorylation','C) AZT is converted to a toxic metabolite by xanthine oxidase that directly poisons neuronal mitochondria','D) AZT depletes cellular dTTP pools via competitive inhibition of thymidine kinase, preventing nuclear DNA replication in neurons'],answer:1,why:'NRTIs, including AZT, are activated by cellular kinases and can inhibit not only viral reverse transcriptase but also the host\'s mitochondrial DNA polymerase (polymerase gamma), which has lower selectivity against these analogs. Inhibition of polymerase gamma causes mitochondrial DNA depletion, reducing synthesis of the mitochondrially encoded ETC subunits. Impaired oxidative phosphorylation forces cells to rely on anaerobic glycolysis, producing lactic acidosis. Peripheral nerve cells (with high energy demands met by mitochondria) are particularly vulnerable, producing peripheral neuropathy.'}]}],
 bottomLine:'Purine de novo synthesis builds the bicyclic ring in ten steps directly on ribose-5-phosphate (from PPP via PRPP); the committed step is PRPP amidotransferase, inhibited by AMP and GMP; formyl-THF contributes C2 and C8, making the pathway folate-dependent; IMP branches to AMP (needs GTP) and GMP (needs ATP) in a cross-regulatory arrangement. Pyrimidine de novo synthesis builds the ring first as orotate (via CPS-II, ATCase, dihydroorotase in the cytoplasmic CAD trifunctional enzyme, then DHODH on the inner mitochondrial membrane), attaches it to PRPP to form UMP, then makes UTP and CTP; CPS-II uses glutamine not NH4+ and is in the cytoplasm not mitochondria (unlike CPS-I of the urea cycle). OTC deficiency causes orotic aciduria with hyperammonemia; UMP synthase deficiency causes orotic aciduria without hyperammonemia, treated with uridine. Salvage: HGPRT recycles hypoxanthine to IMP and guanine to GMP; HGPRT deficiency causes Lesch-Nyhan syndrome (PRPP accumulation, excessive de novo synthesis, uric acid overproduction, self-mutilation, choreoathetosis). Purine catabolism ends at uric acid via xanthine oxidase (humans lack uricase); hyperuricemia causes gout (needle-shaped, negatively birefringent monosodium urate crystals); allopurinol is a mechanism-based xanthine oxidase inhibitor; rasburicase (uricase) rapidly clears uric acid in tumor lysis syndrome; ADA deficiency blocks deoxyadenosine catabolism, causing dATP accumulation in lymphocytes and SCID. Drug mechanisms: methotrexate blocks DHFR, depleting THF for both dTMP and purine C2/C8; 5-FU (as 5-FdUMP) forms a covalent ternary complex with thymidylate synthase and methylene-THF; leucovorin stabilizes that complex (potentiator with 5-FU) or bypasses DHFR block (rescue from MTX); 6-MP requires HGPRT activation and inhibits PRPP amidotransferase and IMP dehydrogenase; hydroxyurea quenches the RNR tyrosyl radical, depleting all dNTPs; acyclovir requires viral TK for first phosphorylation, then acts as a chain terminator lacking 3-OH; NRTIs use cellular kinases but also inhibit mitochondrial polymerase gamma, causing mitochondrial toxicity.',
 nextHint:'Chapter 9 covers integration of all metabolic pathways in the fed, fasted, and stressed states. The nucleotide pool, NADPH supply from the PPP, and one-carbon metabolism through folate all connect to the hormonal logic of fuel selection covered there. Understanding which tissues rely on which pathways, and how cancer cells reprogram nucleotide metabolism (Warburg effect, upregulated de novo synthesis), ties together everything from Chapters 3 through 8.',
},
{
 n:9,
 title:'Vitamins, Cofactors, and Specialty Pathways',
 subtitle:'The molecular toolkit: cofactors that every metabolic pathway requires, plus iron, calcium, heme, and the storage diseases',
 tag:'Integration',
 foundational:'Every enzyme-catalyzed reaction in Chapters 3-8 depends on at least one cofactor covered here. Without these molecules, metabolism stops regardless of substrate availability.',
 buildsOn:'All metabolism chapters (3-8) depend on these cofactors.',
 setsUp:'Ch 10 is the regulatory integration layer; Ch 11-13 use folate/B12 for nucleotide synthesis.',
 objectives:['Explain the mechanistic role of each B vitamin cofactor and identify the enzyme(s) that require it','Distinguish fat-soluble from water-soluble vitamins in terms of storage, toxicity, and absorption requirements','Trace heme synthesis from succinyl-CoA/glycine through all 8 steps, identifying the rate-limiting enzyme, the lead-inhibited steps, and the porphyria defects','Explain bilirubin metabolism from heme oxygenase through conjugation and excretion, and classify jaundice by lab pattern','Describe the hepcidin-ferroportin axis and distinguish iron deficiency anemia from anemia of chronic disease','Explain calcium homeostasis via PTH and calcitriol, and predict lab findings in primary hyperparathyroidism, secondary hyperparathyroidism, and hypoparathyroidism','Identify the enzyme defect, substrate that accumulates, and clinical features for each major sphingolipidosis and mucopolysaccharidosis'],
 opener:'Metabolism requires substrates and enzymes, but enzymes are only as good as their cofactors. A carboxylation reaction stalls without biotin. Transamination cannot proceed without pyridoxal phosphate. The TCA cycle stops if thiamine is absent. The vitamins and minerals covered in this chapter are not peripheral facts to memorize in isolation. They are the molecular handles that make catalysis possible.\n\nThis chapter is organized around mechanism. For each vitamin, the question is not just "what disease results from deficiency?" but "which reaction fails, and why does that reaction matter to everything downstream?" That mechanistic thread connects the biochemistry to the clinical vignette. When you understand that B6/PLP is required for ALA synthase (the first step of heme synthesis) in addition to all transamination reactions, the sideroblastic anemia of INH therapy stops being a random fact and becomes a logical consequence.',
 pinnedDisc:{t:'B12 vs FOLATE DEFICIENCY',x:'Both cause megaloblastic anemia (impaired DNA synthesis, large hypersegmented RBCs) because both are required for thymidylate synthesis. FOLATE: deficiency causes isolated megaloblastic anemia with low serum folate; NO neurological involvement; NO elevated methylmalonic acid (MMA); corrected by folate supplementation. B12: deficiency causes megaloblastic anemia PLUS subacute combined degeneration of the spinal cord (posterior and lateral column demyelination, causing loss of vibration/proprioception and spastic weakness) PLUS elevated MMA (methylmalonyl-CoA mutase fails) PLUS elevated homocysteine. KEY TRAP: giving folate to a B12-deficient patient will correct the anemia but will NOT fix neurological damage, which continues to progress. Always check B12 before treating with folate alone. Methyl trap: B12 deficiency traps folate as methylTHF (cannot donate methyl group without B12-dependent methionine synthase), depleting the THF pool needed for purine/pyrimidine synthesis.'},
 sections:[{id:'9.1',title:'Fat-Soluble vs Water-Soluble: Why the Distinction Matters',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Vitamins A, D, E, and K dissolve in lipid. They require bile acids and chylomicron packaging for intestinal absorption, travel in the lymph before entering the bloodstream, and are stored in fat tissue and liver. This storage capacity means fat-soluble vitamins accumulate with excess intake, making toxicity a real clinical problem for vitamins A and D. Deficiency develops slowly because stores must first be depleted, which takes months. Any condition that impairs fat absorption (cystic fibrosis, cholestasis, celiac disease, short bowel syndrome, orlistat use) depletes all four fat-soluble vitamins simultaneously.'},{t:'p',x:'Water-soluble vitamins (the B vitamins and vitamin C) circulate freely in plasma, are filtered by the kidney, and are not significantly stored. The body cannot buffer large fluctuations. Deficiency develops within weeks to months of inadequate intake. Toxicity from excess intake is generally rare because the kidney excretes excess efficiently, with the important exception of B6 (pyridoxine), where megadose supplementation causes sensory neuropathy.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'FAT MALABSORPTION MNEMONIC: ADEK',x:'Any patient with fat malabsorption (obstructive jaundice, CF, celiac, short gut) is at risk for deficiency of all four fat-soluble vitamins simultaneously: A (night blindness, xerophthalmia), D (osteomalacia, hypocalcemia), E (hemolytic anemia, spinocerebellar ataxia), K (coagulopathy, prolonged PT). Checking PT/INR is a quick surrogate for vitamin K status.'}]},{id:'9.2',title:'Fat-Soluble Vitamins',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Vitamin A exists in three biologically active forms. Retinol (alcohol form) is the storage and transport form. Retinal (aldehyde form) is the chromophore in photoreceptors. Retinoic acid (acid form) is the transcriptional regulator. In the rod photoreceptor, 11-cis retinal binds covalently to opsin to form rhodopsin. When a photon strikes, 11-cis retinal isomerizes to all-trans retinal, triggering a conformational change in opsin that initiates the phototransduction cascade (Gt/transducin/cGMP phosphodiesterase). All-trans retinal must be re-isomerized back to 11-cis retinal by retinal isomerase in the retinal pigment epithelium before another cycle can occur. Vitamin A deficiency depletes the rhodopsin pool, causing night blindness (nyctalopia) as the earliest and most sensitive sign. Prolonged deficiency causes xerophthalmia (dry conjunctiva), Bitot spots (foamy white plaques on the conjunctiva from keratinized epithelium), and ultimately corneal ulceration and keratomalacia.'},{t:'p',x:'Retinoic acid binds nuclear RAR/RXR heterodimers that recognize retinoic acid response elements (RAREs) in DNA. This controls differentiation of epithelial cells, immune cells, and embryonic tissues. In immune function, retinoic acid promotes IgA production and gut-homing of lymphocytes. Excess vitamin A is teratogenic because retinoic acid at supraphysiologic levels drives abnormal Hox gene expression during organogenesis, causing craniofacial, cardiac, and limb defects. Isotretinoin (13-cis retinoic acid) for acne therapy carries a mandatory pregnancy prevention program for this reason. Vitamin A toxicity (hypervitaminosis A) from excess supplementation causes increased intracranial pressure (pseudotumor cerebri, presenting as headache and papilledema), hepatotoxicity, dry skin, and alopecia. Elevated serum retinol with these symptoms is diagnostic.'},{t:'box',kind:'why',label:'WHY DOES VITAMIN A DEFICIENCY INCREASE CHILDHOOD MORTALITY?',x:'Beyond vision, retinoic acid is essential for maintaining the integrity of mucosal epithelium throughout the respiratory, GI, and genitourinary tracts. In deficiency, these surfaces undergo squamous metaplasia (columnar epithelium is replaced by keratinized squamous epithelium), which disrupts the mucus barrier and impairs ciliary clearance. Simultaneously, retinoic acid is required for the development and function of innate and adaptive immune cells, including NK cells, dendritic cells, and T cells. The result is a child who is simultaneously more susceptible to infection and less capable of mounting an adequate immune response. In regions where measles is endemic, vitamin A deficiency dramatically worsens measles mortality by impairing the immune response to the virus. WHO recommends vitamin A supplementation for measles treatment in developing countries precisely because of this biochemical link.'},{t:'p',x:'Vitamin D begins as 7-dehydrocholesterol in skin. Ultraviolet B radiation (290-315 nm) cleaves the B ring to form pre-vitamin D3, which undergoes spontaneous thermal isomerization to cholecalciferol (vitamin D3). Cholecalciferol is biologically inert and requires two sequential hydroxylations. The first occurs in the liver (25-hydroxylase, CYP2R1/CYP27A1), producing 25-hydroxyvitamin D (calcidiol, 25-OH D3), the major circulating storage form and the best marker of vitamin D status. The second occurs in the proximal tubule of the kidney (1-alpha-hydroxylase, CYP27B1), producing 1,25-dihydroxyvitamin D3 (calcitriol), the active hormone. This second step is tightly regulated: PTH upregulates renal 1-alpha-hydroxylase (when calcium is low, PTH rises and drives more calcitriol production); FGF-23 from osteocytes inhibits 1-alpha-hydroxylase and stimulates 24-hydroxylase (which inactivates calcitriol); and calcitriol itself feeds back to suppress PTH synthesis in the parathyroid gland.'},{t:'p',x:'Calcitriol binds the nuclear vitamin D receptor (VDR), which forms a heterodimer with RXR and binds vitamin D response elements (VDREs). Its primary genomic targets include TRPV6 (an apical calcium channel in the duodenum), calbindin-D (a calcium-binding protein that ferries Ca2+ across the enterocyte cytoplasm), and PMCA1b (a basolateral Ca2+ ATPase). Together these increase intestinal calcium absorption efficiency from about 10-15% in the deficient state to 30-40% in the replete state. Calcitriol also upregulates RANKL expression in osteoblasts, promoting osteoclast differentiation and bone resorption to raise serum calcium when dietary intake is insufficient. Vitamin D deficiency causes rickets in children (failure of bone matrix mineralization with open growth plates, producing the classic deformities: bowed legs, rachitic rosary, craniotabes, widened wrists) and osteomalacia in adults (painful, soft bone that fractures under normal loading). Both are characterized by low-normal calcium, low phosphate, elevated PTH, low 25-OH D, elevated alkaline phosphatase.'},{t:'p',x:'Vitamin E refers primarily to alpha-tocopherol, the most biologically potent of the eight naturally occurring tocopherols. Its primary role is as a chain-breaking antioxidant in cell membranes: it donates a hydrogen atom to lipid peroxyl radicals, terminating the chain reaction of lipid peroxidation, and the resulting tocopheroxyl radical is regenerated by vitamin C (ascorbate) or glutathione. Because vitamin E is incorporated into all cell membranes and LDL particles, deficiency leads to membrane oxidative damage. Clinical consequences are seen primarily in conditions of fat malabsorption or in premature infants with insufficient transplacental transfer. Hemolytic anemia occurs because erythrocyte membranes are particularly vulnerable to oxidative damage. Spinocerebellar ataxia and peripheral neuropathy occur from axonal membrane damage, particularly in large myelinated neurons of the dorsal root ganglia and posterior columns.'},{t:'p',x:'Vitamin K is a cofactor for gamma-glutamyl carboxylase, which converts glutamate residues to gamma-carboxyglutamate (Gla) in a CO2-dependent, oxygen-dependent reaction. During this reaction, vitamin K (reduced hydroquinone form, KH2) is oxidized to vitamin K epoxide. The epoxide is recycled back to KH2 by vitamin K epoxide reductase complex 1 (VKORC1). Warfarin blocks VKORC1, preventing regeneration of active vitamin K and depleting Gla-containing proteins. The Gla residues are essential because they chelate calcium ions, which allows the proteins to bind phosphatidylserine on platelet membranes at sites of vascular injury. Without Gla, these clotting factors (II, VII, IX, X, and the anticoagulant proteins C and S) cannot be activated. Vitamin K deficiency or warfarin effect is therefore reflected in prolonged PT (extrinsic/common pathway, Factor VII has the shortest half-life of the vitamin K-dependent factors) and prolonged PTT (intrinsic/common pathway, Factors IX and X). Protein C and S deficiency from warfarin initiation explains the transient hypercoagulable state at warfarin initiation (proteins C and S have shorter half-lives than the procoagulant factors).'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'CLINICAL BRIDGE | HEMORRHAGIC DISEASE OF THE NEWBORN',x:'Newborns have low vitamin K stores at birth because vitamin K transport across the placenta is poor and breast milk contains very little vitamin K. Gut bacteria that normally produce menaquinones (vitamin K2) have not yet colonized the neonatal intestine. The result is a transient coagulopathy that peaks at 2-5 days of life (early HDN) or at 1-6 months (late HDN, more severe, often associated with exclusively breastfed infants with fat malabsorption). IM vitamin K prophylaxis at birth reliably prevents this. Late HDN presents with intracranial hemorrhage, GI bleeding, and prolonged PT/PTT with normal platelet count.'}],quickcheck:{q:'A 4-year-old in a developing country presents with difficulty seeing at night. Examination shows bilateral conjunctival keratinization with foamy white plaques. Which reaction directly requires the deficient vitamin\'s aldehyde form?',choices:['Gamma-glutamyl carboxylation of clotting factors','Photoisomerization of 11-cis to all-trans chromophore in rods','Hydroxylation of procollagen lysine residues','Carboxylation of pyruvate to oxaloacetate'],answer:1,explanation:'Retinal (the aldehyde form of vitamin A) binds opsin to form rhodopsin. When a photon strikes, 11-cis retinal isomerizes to all-trans retinal, initiating phototransduction. Night blindness reflects depletion of the rhodopsin pool. The foamy white plaques are Bitot spots from conjunctival squamous metaplasia. Gamma-carboxylation requires vitamin K. Collagen hydroxylation requires vitamin C. Pyruvate carboxylation requires biotin.'}},{id:'9.3',title:'Water-Soluble Vitamins',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Thiamine (B1) is converted to thiamine pyrophosphate (TPP) by thiamine pyrophosphokinase. TPP is the cofactor for four enzymes: pyruvate dehydrogenase complex (PDC, bridges glycolysis to the TCA cycle), alpha-ketoglutarate dehydrogenase (alpha-KGDH, TCA cycle step 4), branched-chain alpha-keto acid dehydrogenase (BCKDH, catabolism of leucine, isoleucine, and valine), and transketolase (pentose phosphate pathway). In each case, TPP decarboxylates an alpha-keto acid by stabilizing the carbanion intermediate via its thiazolium ring. Thiamine deficiency therefore impairs the ability to generate acetyl-CoA from pyruvate (PDC failure) and to complete the TCA cycle (alpha-KGDH failure), crippling aerobic ATP production especially in tissues with high energy demand.'},{t:'p',x:'Clinical manifestations of thiamine deficiency depend on which organ system is most stressed. Wernicke encephalopathy results from thiamine deficiency in the brain, affecting structures with the highest metabolic demand: the mammillary bodies, the periventricular gray matter, and the cerebellum. The classic triad is confusion/encephalopathy, ophthalmoplegia (lateral rectus palsy from CN VI involvement), and ataxia. Untreated Wernicke encephalopathy progresses to Korsakoff syndrome (Wernicke-Korsakoff syndrome), characterized by irreversible anterograde and retrograde amnesia with confabulation, from destruction of the mammillary bodies. Wet beriberi is high-output cardiac failure from impaired myocardial energy metabolism leading to peripheral vasodilation and fluid retention. Dry beriberi is a symmetric peripheral neuropathy with distal sensorimotor deficits. In the laboratory, elevated serum pyruvate and lactate reflect PDC block, and the most specific test is reduced RBC transketolase activity with normalization after TPP addition (the TPP effect). ALWAYS give IV thiamine before glucose in any alcoholic or malnourished patient to avoid precipitating Wernicke encephalopathy by increasing metabolic demand without the cofactor.'},{t:'p',x:'Riboflavin (B2) forms two cofactors: FAD (flavin adenine dinucleotide) and FMN (flavin mononucleotide). Both serve as electron carriers in oxidation-reduction reactions because the isoalloxazine ring can accept one or two electrons (cycling between fully oxidized, semiquinone radical, and fully reduced forms). Key FAD-dependent enzymes include Complex I (NADH dehydrogenase, where FMN accepts electrons from NADH), Complex II (succinate dehydrogenase), fatty acid beta-oxidation (acyl-CoA dehydrogenase), and alpha-KGDH (the dihydrolipoamide dehydrogenase subunit uses FAD). Riboflavin deficiency presents with angular cheilosis (cracks at the corners of the mouth), glossitis (smooth beefy red tongue), seborrheic dermatitis, and corneal vascularization. Isolated riboflavin deficiency is rare because it almost always occurs alongside other B vitamin deficiencies in the context of generalized malnutrition.'},{t:'p',x:'Niacin (B3) forms two cofactors: NAD+ (nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide) and NADP+ (nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide phosphate). Both accept and donate hydride ions (two-electron transfers) and serve as the primary electron carriers in catabolic pathways. NAD+ is the major electron acceptor in glycolysis and the TCA cycle (generating NADH for the electron transport chain). NADP+ is specifically reduced to NADPH in the pentose phosphate pathway and is essential for reductive biosynthesis (fatty acid synthesis, cholesterol synthesis) and for maintaining glutathione in its reduced form (glutathione reductase uses NADPH). Niacin can be synthesized de novo from tryptophan via the kynurenine pathway, requiring vitamin B6 (60 mg tryptophan yields about 1 mg niacin). Pellagra (niacin deficiency) presents with the 4 Ds: Dermatitis (photosensitive, hyperpigmented, scaling rash in sun-exposed areas, Casal necklace around the neck), Diarrhea, Dementia (cognitive decline, psychosis), and Death if untreated. Carcinoid syndrome causes pellagra by diverting tryptophan to serotonin production, depleting the substrate for niacin synthesis. Hartnup disease (neutral amino acid transporter defect in intestine and kidney) causes pellagra by impairing tryptophan absorption. Pharmacologic niacin (1-3 g/day) lowers triglycerides and raises HDL by inhibiting VLDL secretion from the liver (via GPR109A-mediated inhibition of lipolysis in adipocytes, reducing the FFA flux to liver) and by inhibiting HDL catabolism.'},{t:'p',x:'Pantothenic acid (B5) is a structural component of coenzyme A and the acyl carrier protein (ACP) in fatty acid synthase. Every reaction that involves coenzyme A therefore requires pantothenic acid. Given the ubiquity of CoA in metabolism, isolated deficiency is vanishingly rare and seen only with severe starvation or experimental depletion. Reported symptoms include the "burning feet syndrome" (a peripheral neuropathy), fatigue, and GI complaints.'},{t:'p',x:'Pyridoxine (B6) is converted to pyridoxal-5\'-phosphate (PLP), one of the most versatile cofactors in biochemistry. PLP forms a Schiff base (aldimine) with the epsilon-amino group of a lysine residue at the active site, then exchanges this for the substrate amino acid. The resulting external aldimine is highly electrophilic and can be cleaved in three ways: transamination (alpha-C to nitrogen bond cleaved, transfers amino group), decarboxylation (alpha-carboxyl group removed, creates neurotransmitter precursors), or racemization (in bacteria). Key PLP-dependent reactions include ALL transamination reactions (AST, ALT, BCAT), neurotransmitter synthesis (DOPA decarboxylase forms dopamine, aromatic L-amino acid decarboxylase forms serotonin, histidine decarboxylase forms histamine, glutamate decarboxylase forms GABA), heme synthesis (ALA synthase, the rate-limiting step of heme synthesis that condenses succinyl-CoA with glycine), glycogen phosphorylase (allosteric stabilization of the enzyme), and cystathionine beta-synthase (CBS, converts homocysteine to cystathionine in the trans-sulfuration pathway).'},{t:'p',x:'Clinical consequences of B6 deficiency include sideroblastic anemia (ALA synthase failure impairs heme synthesis, iron accumulates in mitochondria forming ringed sideroblasts on iron stain), peripheral neuropathy, seborrheic dermatitis, glossitis, and elevated homocysteine (CBS requires PLP). Medications that inactivate PLP are a critical clinical cause: isoniazid (INH, for TB) and hydralazine form hydrazones with PLP, making it unavailable. B6 supplementation prevents these side effects in patients on INH. Oral contraceptives also impair B6 metabolism. Megadose B6 supplementation (>200 mg/day for extended periods) causes a predominantly sensory peripheral neuropathy by damaging dorsal root ganglia neurons.'},{t:'p',x:'Biotin (B7) is covalently attached to biotin-dependent carboxylases by holocarboxylase synthetase. Biotinidase recycles biotin from protein-bound biotin after proteolysis. There are four human biotin-dependent carboxylases, all of which transfer CO2 from bicarbonate to their substrates using a biotin-bound carboxyphosphate intermediate: pyruvate carboxylase (pyruvate to OAA, gluconeogenesis), acetyl-CoA carboxylase (acetyl-CoA to malonyl-CoA, first committed step of fatty acid synthesis), propionyl-CoA carboxylase (propionyl-CoA to D-methylmalonyl-CoA, odd-chain fatty acid and BCAA catabolism), and beta-methylcrotonyl-CoA carboxylase (leucine catabolism). Dietary biotin deficiency is rare because gut bacteria synthesize biotin. Biotin deficiency is classically caused by consuming large amounts of raw egg whites, because avidin (a glycoprotein in raw egg white) binds biotin with extraordinary affinity (Kd ~10^-15 M) and prevents intestinal absorption. Cooking denatures avidin. Biotinidase deficiency (autosomal recessive) causes biotin recycling failure and presents in infancy with seizures, alopecia, seborrheic dermatitis, ataxia, hearing loss, and lactic acidosis (from pyruvate carboxylase failure).'},{t:'p',x:'Folate (B9) is absorbed in the proximal small intestine and reduced to dihydrofolate (DHF), then tetrahydrofolate (THF) by dihydrofolate reductase (DHFR). THF is the universal one-carbon carrier, accepting and donating one-carbon units at various oxidation states to support the following biosynthetic reactions: thymidylate synthase uses 5,10-methylene-THF to convert dUMP to dTMP (the only step that actually consumes THF without regeneration, producing DHF that must be recycled by DHFR), and purine ring synthesis uses 10-formyl-THF at two steps. The other major form, 5-methyl-THF (the predominant circulating form), donates its methyl group to homocysteine via methionine synthase (requires B12 as cofactor) to regenerate methionine and THF. Folate deficiency causes megaloblastic anemia through impaired thymidylate synthesis: without dTMP, DNA synthesis stalls, cells cannot divide, and the result is large, hypersegmented nuclei. Unlike B12 deficiency, folate deficiency causes NO neurological disease and NO elevation of methylmalonic acid. Neural tube defects (anencephaly, spina bifida, encephalocele) result from folate deficiency in the periconceptual period (weeks 3-4 of gestation, before most women know they are pregnant), which is why folic acid supplementation (400 mcg/day) is recommended for all women of childbearing age.'},{t:'p',x:'Methotrexate and trimethoprim both inhibit DHFR. Methotrexate (at high concentrations) blocks folate recycling and depletes the THF pool, impairing both purine and thymidylate synthesis. This is the basis of its antiproliferative and anti-inflammatory effects. Leucovorin (folinic acid, 5-formyl-THF) rescues cells by providing pre-reduced folate that bypasses DHFR, and is given after high-dose methotrexate to limit toxicity. Trimethoprim (in TMP-SMX) has much higher affinity for bacterial DHFR than human DHFR, explaining its selective antimicrobial activity.'},{t:'p',x:'Cobalamin (B12) is a complex cobalt-containing molecule (corrin ring) synthesized exclusively by microorganisms. Dietary B12 requires intrinsic factor (IF, a glycoprotein secreted by gastric parietal cells) for absorption. B12 binds R-binders in the stomach, but pancreatic proteases degrade these in the duodenum, transferring B12 to IF. The IF-B12 complex is absorbed by cubilin receptors in the terminal ileum. B12 has two active forms in mammals: methylcobalamin (cofactor for methionine synthase in the cytoplasm) and adenosylcobalamin (cofactor for methylmalonyl-CoA mutase in the mitochondria). Methionine synthase: 5-methyl-THF + homocysteine to methionine + THF (requires methylcobalamin). This reaction regenerates THF from the methyl trap and regenerates methionine (SAM precursor). Methylmalonyl-CoA mutase: methylmalonyl-CoA to succinyl-CoA (requires adenosylcobalamin). This is the final step in odd-chain fatty acid catabolism and some BCAA catabolism. B12 deficiency therefore causes: (1) megaloblastic anemia (methyl trap: THF is locked as methyl-THF because methionine synthase fails, depleting the free THF pool needed for thymidylate synthesis), (2) elevated MMA in blood and urine (methylmalonyl-CoA mutase failure, specific to B12), (3) elevated homocysteine (methionine synthase failure, also seen in folate deficiency and CBS deficiency), and (4) subacute combined degeneration of the spinal cord (demyelination of dorsal columns and lateral corticospinal tracts, causing loss of vibration sense, proprioception, Romberg sign, spasticity).'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR | B12 DEFICIENCY CAUSES',x:'MEGALOBLASTIC ANEMIA (methyl trap), NEUROLOGICAL DISEASE (subacute combined degeneration), ELEVATED MMA (methylmalonyl-CoA mutase failure), ELEVATED HOMOCYSTEINE (methionine synthase failure). Folate deficiency: megaloblastic anemia + elevated homocysteine but NO neurological disease and NO elevated MMA. Measure serum B12, folate, and MMA when evaluating megaloblastic anemia. High-normal MMA is the most specific test for tissue B12 deficiency. Pernicious anemia: autoimmune destruction of parietal cells or anti-IF antibodies, the most common cause of B12 deficiency in developed countries.'},{t:'p',x:'Ascorbic acid (vitamin C) is a lactone that serves as an electron donor (reducing agent) in two critical hydroxylation reactions: prolyl hydroxylase (converts proline to hydroxyproline in procollagen, required for collagen triple helix stability and cross-linking) and lysyl hydroxylase (converts lysine to hydroxylysine in collagen, provides cross-linking sites). Without these hydroxylations, collagen is structurally weak and cannot form normal fibers. Vitamin C also donates electrons to dopamine beta-hydroxylase (converts dopamine to norepinephrine in adrenal medulla and sympathetic neurons) and to the microsomal cytochrome P450 system. In the intestine, vitamin C reduces dietary Fe3+ to Fe2+ (the absorbed form) and chelates iron, enhancing non-heme iron absorption. In plasma, vitamin C regenerates vitamin E from the tocopheroxyl radical (the antioxidant network). Scurvy from vitamin C deficiency causes failure of collagen synthesis and vessel integrity: perifollicular hemorrhages (bleeding around hair follicles), corkscrew (coiled) hairs, bleeding gums and gingival inflammation, poor wound healing, and reopening of previously healed wounds. Critically, PT and PTT are NORMAL in scurvy because the vitamin K-dependent clotting factors are unaffected. This distinguishes scurvy from coagulopathy.'}],quickcheck:{q:'A patient on long-term isoniazid (INH) therapy develops fatigue and is found to have a hypochromic microcytic anemia with ringed sideroblasts on bone marrow biopsy. Which biochemical step is impaired?',choices:['Conversion of uroporphyrinogen III to coproporphyrinogen III','Condensation of succinyl-CoA and glycine to form aminolevulinate','Insertion of Fe2+ into protoporphyrin IX by ferrochelatase','Conversion of coproporphyrinogen III to protoporphyrinogen IX'],answer:1,explanation:'INH inactivates pyridoxal-5\'-phosphate (PLP) by forming a hydrazone. ALA synthase, the rate-limiting first step of heme synthesis, requires PLP as a cofactor. It condenses succinyl-CoA and glycine to form delta-aminolevulinate (ALA). When this step is blocked, heme synthesis fails, iron accumulates in mitochondria (where ferrochelatase inserts Fe2+ into protoporphyrin), and ringed sideroblasts form on iron stain. B6 supplementation corrects this. Ferrochelatase is inhibited by lead. UPD is inhibited in PCT.'}},{id:'9.4',title:'Minerals and Trace Elements',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Iron is absorbed in the duodenum in its ferrous (Fe2+) form. Hepcidin, a 25-amino acid peptide produced by hepatocytes, is the master regulator of iron homeostasis. Hepcidin binds ferroportin (the only known iron exporter on the basolateral surface of enterocytes, macrophages, and hepatocytes) and triggers its internalization and degradation. When hepcidin is high, ferroportin is absent, iron is trapped inside cells, and systemic iron delivery falls. Hepcidin production is induced by high iron stores (detected via HFE/TfR2/hemojuvelin complex sensing of holotransferrin saturation) and by inflammation (IL-6 drives hepcidin via JAK2/STAT3). Hepcidin is suppressed by iron deficiency, anemia, hypoxia, and erythropoiesis (erythroferrone from erythroblasts inhibits hepcidin). In hereditary hemochromatosis (HFE gene, most common: C282Y homozygote), hepcidin is not appropriately upregulated despite iron loading, ferroportin stays on the surface, and iron is continuously absorbed and deposited in liver (cirrhosis), heart (dilated cardiomyopathy), pancreas (bronze diabetes), pituitary (hypogonadism), and joints (chondrocalcinosis). Anemia of chronic disease/inflammation results from hepcidin-driven iron restriction: high hepcidin traps iron in macrophages, reducing the iron available for erythropoiesis. Labs: low serum iron, LOW TIBC (opposite of iron deficiency), normal-high ferritin, low reticulocyte count.'},{t:'p',x:'Zinc is required as a structural or catalytic component of more than 300 enzymes, including carbonic anhydrase, alcohol dehydrogenase, carboxypeptidases A and B, DNA polymerase, and RNA polymerase. As a structural component it stabilizes zinc finger domains in transcription factors (Cys2His2 and Cys4 zinc fingers) that regulate gene expression throughout the genome. Zinc deficiency causes acrodermatitis enteropathica (a genetic defect in the ZIP4 intestinal zinc transporter causing perioral and acral rash, alopecia, growth retardation, and diarrhea), impaired wound healing (collagen remodeling enzymes require zinc), hypogonadism, anosmia, and dysgeusia. Zinc is also required for thymulin (a thymic hormone) and therefore for T cell maturation.'},{t:'p',x:'Copper is a cofactor for dopamine beta-hydroxylase (norepinephrine synthesis), cytochrome c oxidase (Complex IV of the electron transport chain), superoxide dismutase (SOD, Cu/Zn-SOD), lysyl oxidase (collagen and elastin cross-linking), and ceruloplasmin (the major copper-carrying protein in plasma, also a ferroxidase that converts Fe2+ to Fe3+ for loading onto transferrin). Wilson disease (autosomal recessive, ATP7B gene mutation) impairs hepatic copper transport into bile and into ceruloplasmin. Copper accumulates in the liver (hepatitis, cirrhosis), brain (dysarthria, dyskinesia, psychiatric symptoms), and eyes (Kayser-Fleischer rings in Descemet membrane). Labs: low ceruloplasmin, high 24-hour urine copper, high liver copper on biopsy. Treatment: D-penicillamine or trientine (copper chelators) or zinc (induces metallothionein to sequester copper). Menkes disease (X-linked, ATP7A gene mutation) impairs copper absorption from the intestine and transport out of most cells. Presents in infancy with kinky/steely hair (from deficient lysyl oxidase impairing cross-linking), connective tissue laxity, seizures, intellectual disability, and early death. Note: ATP7A (Menkes) = absorption defect; ATP7B (Wilson) = excretion/ceruloplasmin loading defect.'},{t:'p',x:'Selenium is incorporated as selenocysteine (the 21st amino acid) into selenoproteins. Key selenoproteins include glutathione peroxidases (GPx1-4, reduce H2O2 and lipid hydroperoxides using glutathione as the electron donor), thioredoxin reductases (antioxidant system), and iodothyronine deiodinases (convert T4 to active T3 in peripheral tissues). Selenium deficiency causes Keshan disease (endemic dilated cardiomyopathy in selenium-poor regions of China), Kashin-Beck disease (endemic osteoarthropathy), and impaired thyroid hormone activation.'},{t:'p',x:'Iodine is essential for thyroid hormone synthesis. Iodide is actively transported into thyroid follicular cells by the sodium-iodide symporter (NIS) on the basolateral membrane. Iodide is oxidized to iodine by thyroid peroxidase (TPO) and organified onto tyrosine residues of thyroglobulin (forming monoiodotyrosine, MIT, and diiodotyrosine, DIT). TPO also catalyzes the coupling reaction (MIT + DIT to form T3; DIT + DIT to form T4). Iodine deficiency impairs thyroid hormone synthesis, triggering TSH-driven thyroid hyperplasia (goiter). In fetal development, maternal and fetal iodine deficiency causes cretinism: irreversible intellectual disability, deafness, spastic diplegia, and short stature. Iodine deficiency is the most common preventable cause of intellectual disability worldwide.'}]},{id:'9.5',title:'Heme Synthesis',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Heme synthesis begins in the mitochondria and is completed in the mitochondria, with the middle steps occurring in the cytoplasm. The pathway has 8 enzymatic steps.'},{t:'formula',x:'Step 1 (mitochondria, rate-limiting): Succinyl-CoA + Glycine → delta-Aminolevulinate (ALA). Enzyme: ALA synthase (ALAS). Cofactor: PLP (B6). Regulated by: heme (feedback inhibits ALAS1 and blocks mitochondrial import of ALAS1 preprotein; ALAS2 in erythroid cells is regulated by iron via IRE/IRP).'},{t:'formula',x:'Step 2 (cytoplasm): 2 ALA → Porphobilinogen (PBG). Enzyme: ALA dehydratase (ALAD, porphobilinogen synthase). Inhibited by LEAD and succinylacetone.'},{t:'formula',x:'Step 3 (cytoplasm): 4 PBG → Hydroxymethylbilane. Enzyme: PBG deaminase (uroporphyrinogen I synthase). Deficient in ACUTE INTERMITTENT PORPHYRIA (AIP).'},{t:'formula',x:'Step 4 (cytoplasm): Hydroxymethylbilane → Uroporphyrinogen III. Enzyme: Uroporphyrinogen III cosynthase.'},{t:'formula',x:'Step 5 (cytoplasm): Uroporphyrinogen III → Coproporphyrinogen III. Enzyme: Uroporphyrinogen decarboxylase. Deficient in PORPHYRIA CUTANEA TARDA (PCT).'},{t:'formula',x:'Step 6 (mitochondria): Coproporphyrinogen III → Protoporphyrinogen IX. Enzyme: Coproporphyrinogen oxidase.'},{t:'formula',x:'Step 7 (mitochondria): Protoporphyrinogen IX → Protoporphyrin IX. Enzyme: Protoporphyrinogen oxidase.'},{t:'formula',x:'Step 8 (mitochondria): Protoporphyrin IX + Fe2+ → Heme. Enzyme: Ferrochelatase. Inhibited by LEAD.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'LEAD POISONING: TWO STEPS BLOCKED',x:'Lead inhibits ALA dehydratase (step 2) and ferrochelatase (step 8). The result: ALA accumulates in blood and urine (ALA dehydratase block) and protoporphyrin IX accumulates in RBCs (ferrochelatase block), producing elevated free erythrocyte protoporphyrin (FEP). Heme synthesis fails, causing microcytic hypochromic anemia with basophilic stippling (from ribosomal RNA aggregates, because lead also inhibits rRNA degradation). Children absorb a higher fraction of ingested lead than adults and are at greater risk for neurological toxicity. Dimercaprol (BAL) and EDTA chelate lead.'},{t:'p',x:'Acute Intermittent Porphyria (AIP): autosomal dominant deficiency of PBG deaminase (step 3). PBG and ALA accumulate. Attacks are precipitated by drugs that induce CYP450 (inducing ALAS1 via PGC-1alpha/PPAR-gamma coactivation) or by fasting or hormonal changes. Classic presentation: the 5 Ps - Pain (severe colicky abdominal pain, the most common complaint), Polyneuropathy (motor greater than sensory, can cause respiratory paralysis), Psychiatric symptoms (anxiety, psychosis, hallucinations), Pink/Port wine-colored urine (PBG oxidizes spontaneously to porphyrins in urine on standing), Precipitated by drugs (sulfa drugs, barbiturates, phenytoin, estrogens, rifampin, griseofulvin) and fasting. Treatment: IV glucose and IV hemin (both suppress ALAS1 transcription). Skin is NOT photosensitive in AIP because porphyrins (which cause photosensitivity) do not accumulate, only their precursors.'},{t:'p',x:'Porphyria Cutanea Tarda (PCT): deficiency of uroporphyrinogen decarboxylase (step 5), most commonly acquired (from hepatitis C, alcohol, iron overload, or estrogen use) rather than inherited. Uroporphyrinogen and coproporphyrinogen accumulate. These porphyrins absorb light and generate reactive oxygen species in skin, causing photosensitivity with blistering, skin fragility, hyperpigmentation, and hypertrichosis. No acute neurovisceral attacks. Urine turns tea-colored/red due to uroporphyrin excretion. Treatment: phlebotomy (reduces iron-induced enzyme inhibition) and hydroxychloroquine (mobilizes accumulated porphyrins from hepatocytes).'}],quickcheck:{q:'A 28-year-old woman on oral contraceptives presents with acute severe abdominal pain, muscle weakness in her arms and legs, and her urine darkens on standing. Urine porphobilinogen is markedly elevated. Which enzyme is deficient?',choices:['Ferrochelatase','Uroporphyrinogen decarboxylase','PBG deaminase','ALA dehydratase'],answer:2,explanation:'The presentation is Acute Intermittent Porphyria (AIP): abdominal pain, motor neuropathy, neuropsychiatric symptoms, and port-wine urine with elevated PBG. AIP results from PBG deaminase deficiency (step 3 of heme synthesis). Oral contraceptives are a classic precipitant by inducing hepatic ALAS1, increasing flux through the pathway to where the block is. Ferrochelatase deficiency causes erythropoietic protoporphyria. Uroporphyrinogen decarboxylase deficiency causes PCT (photosensitive skin, no neurovisceral attacks). ALA dehydratase deficiency (plumboporphyria) is extremely rare and also causes ALA accumulation but not PBG elevation.'}},{id:'9.6',title:'Bilirubin Metabolism and Jaundice',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Bilirubin is the end product of heme catabolism. In macrophages of the spleen, liver, and bone marrow (reticuloendothelial system), heme oxygenase cleaves the heme ring between the alpha and beta pyrrole bridges, releasing carbon monoxide (a signaling molecule) and biliverdin (a green pigment). Biliverdin reductase reduces biliverdin to bilirubin (a yellow-orange pigment). This unconjugated bilirubin is lipophilic and insoluble in water. It is transported in plasma tightly bound to albumin (two high-affinity binding sites). Albumin-bound unconjugated bilirubin cannot be filtered by the kidney, which is why unconjugated hyperbilirubinemia does not cause bilirubinuria (dark urine). However, unconjugated bilirubin can cross lipid bilayers, making it toxic to the brain (kernicterus) when concentrations are high enough to overwhelm albumin binding capacity.'},{t:'p',x:'In the liver, hepatocytes take up bilirubin from albumin via OATP transporters on the sinusoidal membrane. Intracellular bilirubin is bound by ligandin (glutathione S-transferase). UDP-glucuronosyltransferase 1A1 (UGT1A1) in the endoplasmic reticulum conjugates bilirubin with one or two molecules of glucuronic acid, producing water-soluble bilirubin monoglucuronide and diglucuronide. Conjugated bilirubin is secreted into the bile canaliculus by MRP2 (multidrug resistance protein 2, also called canalicular multispecific organic anion transporter, cMOAT). In the intestine, gut bacteria deconjugate bilirubin and reduce it to urobilinogen. Most urobilinogen is oxidized to stercobilin (the brown pigment of stool). Some urobilinogen is reabsorbed (enterohepatic circulation), re-extracted by the liver, and the rest is excreted in urine as urobilinogen (which oxidizes to urobilin, giving urine its yellow color). When bile flow to the intestine is blocked, stercobilin production falls, stools become pale/clay-colored, and urobilinogen in urine also disappears.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'JAUNDICE CLASSIFICATION BY MECHANISM',x:'PRE-HEPATIC (hemolytic): unconjugated bilirubin elevated, direct bilirubin normal, total bilirubin elevated, urine bilirubin ABSENT (conjugated not elevated, so no filtered bilirubin), urine urobilinogen HIGH (more urobilinogen from gut from more heme load), stool color normal, LFTs normal, haptoglobin LOW (bound to free Hgb), elevated LDH. Examples: hereditary spherocytosis, G6PD deficiency, sickle cell, autoimmune hemolysis, malaria. HEPATIC: both unconjugated and conjugated elevated (hepatocytes fail to conjugate and fail to secrete), urine bilirubin present (dark urine), urine urobilinogen variable, elevated AST/ALT. Examples: viral hepatitis, alcoholic hepatitis, cirrhosis. POST-HEPATIC (obstructive/cholestatic): conjugated bilirubin elevated, direct bilirubin HIGH, dark urine, pale stools (no stercobilin), elevated ALP and GGT more than AST/ALT, urine urobilinogen ABSENT (no bile reaching gut). Examples: choledocholithiasis, cholangiocarcinoma, pancreatic head cancer (Courvoisier sign: palpable gallbladder + jaundice = malignant obstruction), primary sclerosing cholangitis, biliary atresia.'},{t:'p',x:'Gilbert syndrome: autosomal recessive reduction in UGT1A1 promoter activity (TATAA box elongation: 7 TA repeats instead of the normal 6). Mildly reduced UGT1A1 expression causes mild unconjugated hyperbilirubinemia that is exacerbated by fasting, stress, illness, or exercise. Benign; no hemolysis, normal LFTs, no treatment needed. Affects about 5-10% of the population. Crigler-Najjar syndrome type I: complete absence of UGT1A1, severe unconjugated hyperbilirubinemia (often >20 mg/dL), kernicterus, requires liver transplant or continuous phototherapy to survive. Type II: partial UGT1A1 deficiency, responds to phenobarbital (induces residual UGT1A1). Dubin-Johnson syndrome: deficiency of MRP2 (conjugated bilirubin secretion into bile is impaired), causes predominantly conjugated hyperbilirubinemia, grossly black liver (melanin-like pigment deposition), elevated urine coproporphyrin I:III ratio. Benign.'},{t:'p',x:'Neonatal jaundice (physiologic): in newborns, fetal hemoglobin (HbF) is replaced by adult HbA, creating a surge of heme catabolism. UGT1A1 expression is low at birth and takes 2-4 weeks to mature. The combination of high bilirubin production and low conjugation capacity causes physiologic unconjugated hyperbilirubinemia peaking at days 3-5. Phototherapy converts unconjugated bilirubin to water-soluble photoisomers that are excreted without conjugation. At bilirubin levels above about 20-25 mg/dL (varying with gestational age and risk factors), unconjugated bilirubin crosses the blood-brain barrier and deposits in the basal ganglia, subthalamic nuclei, and hippocampus, causing kernicterus: opisthotonos, high-pitched cry, seizures, and chronic athetoid cerebral palsy.'}]},{id:'9.7',title:'Iron Metabolism in Depth',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Dietary iron exists as heme iron (from myoglobin and hemoglobin in meat, absorbed as intact heme porphyrin via HCP1/SLC46A3 transporter) and non-heme iron (Fe3+ from plant foods, reduced to Fe2+ by duodenal cytochrome b/DCYTB using ascorbate, then absorbed via DMT1). Inside the enterocyte, Fe2+ either binds ferritin (storage) or is exported across the basolateral membrane by ferroportin (the only iron exporter). Ferroportin is controlled by hepcidin as described in Section 9.4. Once in the bloodstream, Fe2+ is oxidized to Fe3+ by ceruloplasmin (or hephaestin in the intestinal epithelium), and Fe3+ binds transferrin (2 Fe3+ per transferrin molecule). Transferrin-Fe3+ binds transferrin receptor 1 (TfR1) on cells requiring iron, is endocytosed, and Fe3+ is released in the endosome after acidification by a proton pump.'},{t:'p',x:'Iron deficiency anemia (IDA): the most common nutritional deficiency worldwide. Progression: iron stores depleted first (ferritin falls) while Hgb remains normal; then iron-deficient erythropoiesis begins (serum iron falls, TIBC rises, transferrin saturation falls); finally, frank anemia develops (microcytic hypochromic anemia). Labs: low serum iron, HIGH TIBC (liver synthesizes more transferrin when iron is low), low ferritin (best single test for iron stores when not confounded by inflammation, because ferritin is an acute phase reactant), low transferrin saturation, elevated free erythrocyte protoporphyrin (cannot be metalated). On blood smear: microcytes, hypochromia, pencil cells (elliptocytes), target cells, anisocytosis, poikilocytosis. Causes: chronic blood loss (in adults, always rule out GI source), inadequate intake (infants, toddlers, pregnancy), malabsorption (celiac disease, achlorhydria, proton pump inhibitors reduce stomach acid needed to release iron from food), and increased demand (pregnancy, growth).'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR | IRON DEFICIENCY vs ANEMIA OF CHRONIC DISEASE',x:'IRON DEFICIENCY ANEMIA: serum iron LOW, TIBC HIGH (liver makes more transferrin), ferritin LOW, transferrin saturation LOW, bone marrow iron ABSENT, response to oral iron good. ANEMIA OF CHRONIC DISEASE: serum iron LOW, TIBC LOW (hepcidin traps iron in macrophages AND liver does not synthesize transferrin in inflammation), ferritin HIGH (ferritin is an acute phase reactant elevated in inflammation), transferrin saturation LOW-normal, bone marrow iron INCREASED in macrophages but unavailable for erythropoiesis. Both are initially normocytic, progressing to microcytic in severe cases. Key: TIBC and ferritin point in opposite directions. High hepcidin is the driver of ACD.'}]},{id:'9.8',title:'Calcium Homeostasis',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Serum calcium is maintained in a narrow range (8.5-10.5 mg/dL total; 4.6-5.3 mg/dL ionized) by the integrated actions of PTH, calcitriol (1,25-(OH)2 D3), and calcitonin. Roughly 50% of serum calcium is bound to albumin (inactive), 10% is complexed to anions (citrate, phosphate), and 40% is free ionized calcium (the biologically active fraction). Total calcium must be corrected for albumin: corrected Ca = measured Ca + 0.8 x (4.0 - measured albumin in g/dL).'},{t:'p',x:'Parathyroid hormone (PTH) is the primary minute-to-minute regulator of ionized calcium. The calcium-sensing receptor (CaSR) on parathyroid chief cells continuously monitors ionized calcium. When ionized calcium falls, CaSR signaling decreases, PTH is secreted. PTH acts via PTHR1 (Gs-coupled) on three targets: (1) kidney proximal tubule: activates 1-alpha-hydroxylase (CYP27B1), promoting calcitriol synthesis; inhibits NaPi-IIa (sodium-phosphate cotransporter), causing phosphaturia; increases calcium reabsorption in the distal tubule; (2) kidney: increases distal nephron calcium reabsorption (via TRPV5/6 channels); (3) bone: stimulates osteoclast activity via RANK/RANKL signaling (osteoblasts express RANKL, osteoclasts express RANK, PTH drives osteoblasts to increase RANKL expression, activating osteoclasts to resorb bone and release calcium and phosphate). Net effect of PTH: serum calcium UP, serum phosphate DOWN (phosphaturia).'},{t:'p',x:'Primary hyperparathyroidism: autonomous PTH secretion (usually from parathyroid adenoma). Labs: high Ca2+, low phosphate, HIGH PTH (inappropriate for the calcium level), elevated 1,25-(OH)2 D3, hypercalciuria, nephrolithiasis (calcium oxalate or calcium phosphate stones), bone resorption (osteitis fibrosa cystica in severe cases, brown tumors). Asymptomatic hypercalcemia is the most common presentation today. Mnemonic for hypercalcemia symptoms: "Bones, Stones, Groans, Thrones, Psychic Moans" (osteitis/fractures, nephrolithiasis, GI symptoms, polyuria/polydipsia, depression/confusion). Secondary hyperparathyroidism: high PTH is an appropriate compensatory response to chronic hypocalcemia, most commonly from chronic kidney disease (CKD: impaired 1-alpha-hydroxylase reduces calcitriol, leading to hypocalcemia and phosphate retention that both suppress calcitriol and directly stimulate PTH secretion). Labs: low Ca2+, HIGH phosphate, HIGH PTH, LOW calcitriol. Treated with phosphate binders, calcitriol analogs, and calcimimetics (cinacalcet activates CaSR, suppressing PTH secretion). Tertiary hyperparathyroidism: parathyroid gland autonomy develops after prolonged secondary hyperparathyroidism (usually in long-standing CKD or post-renal transplant); PTH secretion becomes autonomous and Ca2+ may be elevated despite restored calcitriol.'},{t:'p',x:'Hypoparathyroidism: most common cause is surgical (inadvertent removal or devascularization of parathyroid glands during thyroidectomy or parathyroidectomy). Labs: low Ca2+, HIGH phosphate (phosphaturia gone), LOW PTH, low-normal calcitriol. Symptoms of hypocalcemia: neuromuscular excitability (tetany, perioral paresthesias, Chvostek sign: facial twitching from tapping CN VII in front of the ear; Trousseau sign: carpal spasm from inflation of blood pressure cuff above systolic for 3 minutes), QT prolongation (risk of torsades), laryngospasm. Treatment: calcium supplements and calcitriol.'}]},{id:'9.9',title:'Sphingolipidoses and Mucopolysaccharidoses',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Sphingolipidoses are lysosomal storage diseases resulting from deficiency of specific lysosomal hydrolases that degrade sphingolipids. All are autosomal recessive except Fabry disease (X-linked). Because the defective enzyme normally degrades a sphingolipid, the substrate accumulates in lysosomes, enlarging cells and impairing organ function. The brain is particularly vulnerable because sphingolipids are major components of myelin and neuronal membranes.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'SPHINGOLIPIDOSIS RAPID REVIEW',x:'TAY-SACHS: beta-hexosaminidase A deficient; GM2 ganglioside accumulates; lysosomal enzyme. Presents 3-6 months: hypersensitivity to sound (hyperacusis), motor regression, cherry-red spot on macula (ganglion cells around fovea are laden with lipid, making the thinly covered fovea appear red by contrast), progressive neurodegeneration; death by age 2-5; no hepatosplenomegaly (CNS only). Ashkenazi Jewish population. NIEMANN-PICK TYPE A/B: sphingomyelinase (acid sphingomyelinase) deficient; sphingomyelin accumulates. Type A: severe neurological involvement, death by 2-3 years, foam cells in marrow. Type B: visceral disease only (hepatosplenomegaly), survival to adulthood. GAUCHER DISEASE: beta-glucocerebrosidase (glucocerebrosidase) deficient; glucocerebroside accumulates; most common lysosomal storage disease. Type 1: non-neuronopathic (most common), hepatosplenomegaly, bone marrow infiltration (Gaucher cells look like crumpled tissue paper), bone pain and avascular necrosis, thrombocytopenia. Ashkenazi Jewish. Enzyme replacement therapy (imiglucerase) effective. FABRY DISEASE: alpha-galactosidase A deficient; globotriaosylceramide (Gb3) accumulates; X-LINKED. Presents in adolescence: acroparesthesias (burning pain in extremities), angiokeratomas (dark red papules on skin), corneal opacities (cornea verticillata), renal failure, cardiac (hypertrophic cardiomyopathy) and cerebrovascular disease. KRABBE DISEASE: galactocerebrosidase (GALC) deficient; galactocerebroside AND psychosine accumulate; psychosine is directly cytotoxic to oligodendrocytes. Severe demyelination, infantile onset (by 6 months), globoid cells (multinucleated macrophages), death in infancy. METACHROMATIC LEUKODYSTROPHY (MLD): arylsulfatase A deficient; cerebroside sulfatide accumulates; demyelination of central and peripheral nervous system; late infantile, juvenile, or adult onset; metachromatic staining of accumulated sulfatide in nerve biopsies.'},{t:'p',x:'Mucopolysaccharidoses (MPS) result from deficiency of lysosomal enzymes that degrade glycosaminoglycans (GAGs: heparan sulfate, dermatan sulfate, keratan sulfate, chondroitin sulfate). GAGs accumulate progressively in connective tissue, causing progressive multiorgan dysfunction. All are autosomal recessive except Hunter syndrome (MPS II, X-linked). Clinical features common to most MPS: coarse facial features (gargoylism), short stature, dysostosis multiplex (skeletal abnormalities on X-ray), hepatosplenomegaly, corneal clouding (except Hunter), joint stiffness, and varying degrees of intellectual disability. Hurler syndrome (MPS I, alpha-L-iduronidase deficient): the prototype, severe; heparan + dermatan sulfate accumulate; corneal clouding, intellectual disability, death by childhood; responds to hematopoietic stem cell transplant if done early. Hunter syndrome (MPS II, iduronate-2-sulfatase deficient, X-linked): milder than Hurler, NO corneal clouding (distinguishing feature), aggressive behavior, "pebble skin" lesion (ivory-colored papules on upper back).'}],quickcheck:{q:'A 5-month-old infant is brought in for developmental regression and exaggerated startle to sound. Fundoscopic examination shows a cherry-red spot at the macula. Enzyme assay shows absent beta-hexosaminidase A activity. Which lipid accumulates in lysosomes?',choices:['Sphingomyelin','Glucocerebroside','Galactocerebroside','GM2 ganglioside'],answer:3,explanation:'Absent beta-hexosaminidase A is the defining defect of Tay-Sachs disease. Beta-hexosaminidase A cleaves the terminal GalNAc from GM2 ganglioside. Without this enzyme, GM2 ganglioside accumulates in lysosomes of neurons throughout the CNS. The cherry-red spot results from lipid-laden ganglion cells surrounding the fovea becoming opaque, making the thinly covered fovea appear red by contrast. Sphingomyelin accumulates in Niemann-Pick. Glucocerebroside accumulates in Gaucher. Galactocerebroside accumulates in Krabbe.'}},{id:'9.10',title:'Clinical Cheat Sheet and Vignettes',blocks:[{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'HIGH-YIELD VITAMIN DEFICIENCY TABLE',x:'B1 (thiamine): PDC/alpha-KGDH/transketolase fail; elevated pyruvate/lactate; Wernicke encephalopathy (confusion, ophthalmoplegia, ataxia), Korsakoff syndrome (amnesia, confabulation), wet beriberi (high-output CHF), dry beriberi (peripheral neuropathy). B2 (riboflavin): Complex I/II, beta-oxidation; angular cheilosis, glossitis, photophobia. B3 (niacin): NAD+/NADP+ depleted; pellagra: 4Ds (dermatitis, diarrhea, dementia, death). B5 (pantothenate): CoA depleted; "burning feet," rare. B6 (PLP): all transaminations, ALA synthase, neurotransmitter decarboxylases; sideroblastic anemia, peripheral neuropathy, elevated homocysteine; caused by INH/hydralazine. B7 (biotin): 4 carboxylases fail; alopecia, dermatitis, seizures; caused by raw egg whites (avidin). B9 (folate): THF depleted, TMP synthesis fails; megaloblastic anemia, NO neuro, NTDs; block by methotrexate, TMP. B12 (cobalamin): methionine synthase + methylmalonyl-CoA mutase fail; megaloblastic anemia + subacute combined degeneration + elevated MMA; pernicious anemia (anti-IF antibodies). Vitamin A: retinal depleted; night blindness, Bitot spots, xerophthalmia; teratogenic in excess. Vitamin C: collagen hydroxylation fails; scurvy (perifollicular hemorrhage, corkscrew hairs, bleeding gums), normal PT/PTT. Vitamin D: Ca/P absorption impaired; rickets (children), osteomalacia (adults), secondary hyperparathyroidism. Vitamin E: antioxidant network fails; hemolytic anemia, spinocerebellar ataxia in fat malabsorption. Vitamin K: gamma-carboxylation fails; coagulopathy, prolonged PT (Factor VII shortest half-life); HDN; warfarin mechanism (blocks VKORC1).'},{t:'p',x:'Vignette 1: A 52-year-old man with a history of alcohol use disorder is brought to the ED by his family for confusion, inability to walk, and abnormal eye movements. He has not eaten properly in weeks. He is afebrile, nystagmus and lateral gaze palsy on exam. Glucose is 178 mg/dL (he was given 50 mL D50 in the ambulance). Analysis: Wernicke encephalopathy from thiamine deficiency. IV glucose without thiamine can precipitate or worsen Wernicke by consuming remaining B1 in pyruvate dehydrogenase. The correct action is thiamine IV before or with glucose. Classic board trap: always give thiamine before glucose in alcoholics.'},{t:'p',x:'Vignette 2: A 2-year-old girl is brought in for failure to thrive, recurrent diarrhea, and a weeping rash around her mouth, nose, and perineum. Her mother started giving her cow\'s milk formula with rice cereal at 4 months and switched to a vegetarian diet. Zinc levels are critically low. Analysis: acrodermatitis enteropathica pattern - perioral/acral rash, alopecia, diarrhea, growth failure from zinc deficiency. Could be dietary (inadequate zinc intake on plant-based diet; phytate in cereals chelates zinc) or genetic (ZIP4 transporter defect). Zinc supplementation is diagnostic and therapeutic.'},{t:'p',x:'Vignette 3: A 45-year-old woman presents with fatigue, weight loss, nausea, and yellow discoloration of her skin and eyes. She has bronze-colored skin, elevated liver enzymes, and type 2 diabetes. Iron studies: serum iron 200 mcg/dL (high), TIBC 250 mcg/dL (low-normal), transferrin saturation 80% (markedly elevated), ferritin 3400 ng/mL (markedly elevated). Genetic testing: HFE C282Y homozygous. Analysis: hereditary hemochromatosis. Hepcidin is inadequately upregulated despite iron loading, causing continuous intestinal iron absorption and organ deposition: liver (bronze skin from hemosiderin, cirrhosis), pancreas (bronze diabetes), pituitary (hypogonadism). Treatment: phlebotomy.'}]}],
 bottomLine:'Vitamins and minerals are not optional extras. They are the catalytic infrastructure on which every metabolic pathway depends. The fat-soluble vitamins A, D, E, and K are absorbed in chylomicrons and stored; deficiency develops slowly after malabsorption but toxicity (A and D) is a clinical reality with excess. The B vitamins form the enzyme cofactors that run glycolysis, the TCA cycle, fatty acid synthesis, amino acid metabolism, and nucleotide synthesis. B1/TPP gates entry into the TCA cycle at PDC and alpha-KGDH; B2/FAD and B3/NAD+ carry the electrons; B6/PLP runs all transamination and heme synthesis; B7/biotin runs all carboxylation; B9/folate and B12/cobalamin support one-carbon transfer and methylation. Heme synthesis proceeds in 8 steps beginning with ALA synthase (PLP-dependent, rate-limiting, feedback-inhibited by heme), with lead blocking steps 2 and 8, AIP from PBG deaminase deficiency causing neurovisceral attacks, and PCT from uroporphyrinogen decarboxylase deficiency causing photosensitivity. Bilirubin metabolism converts heme to unconjugated bilirubin (toxic, albumin-bound), then conjugated bilirubin (UGT1A1, water-soluble), then excreted; the three jaundice patterns (pre-hepatic, hepatic, post-hepatic) are distinguished by direct vs indirect bilirubin, urine bilirubin, and stool color. Iron homeostasis is governed by hepcidin/ferroportin; iron deficiency and anemia of chronic disease differ by TIBC and ferritin. Calcium homeostasis is governed by PTH (raises Ca, lowers PO4 via phosphaturia, increases calcitriol synthesis) and calcitriol (increases intestinal Ca and PO4 absorption). Lysosomal storage diseases reflect the enzyme defect: Tay-Sachs (hex A, GM2), Gaucher (glucocerebrosidase, glucocerebroside), Niemann-Pick (sphingomyelinase, sphingomyelin), Fabry (alpha-galactosidase A, Gb3, X-linked), Krabbe (GALC, galactocerebroside), and the MPS group from GAG degradation enzyme defects.',
 nextHint:'Chapter 10 assembles the four master hormones (insulin, glucagon, cortisol, epinephrine) into a coordinated system that integrates all the metabolic pathways of Chapters 3-9 across fed, fasted, and starved states.',
},
{
 n:10,
 title:'Hormonal Regulation and Metabolic Integration',
 subtitle:'How insulin, glucagon, epinephrine, and cortisol coordinate every metabolic pathway across fed, fasted, and starved states',
 tag:'Integration',
 foundational:'Every metabolic pathway covered in Chapters 3 through 9 is turned on or off by hormonal signals. Without understanding hormonal integration, individual pathways are isolated facts. With it, they form a single coherent system that responds to energy state, stress, and time.',
 buildsOn:'Chapters 3-9 (glycolysis, gluconeogenesis, glycogen metabolism, fatty acid synthesis and oxidation, TCA cycle, amino acid metabolism, vitamins and cofactors); signal transduction concepts from cellular biology.',
 setsUp:'Chapter 11 (nucleotide metabolism) and Chapter 12 (molecular biology) depend on understanding how growth signals and nutrient availability regulate gene expression; the diabetic and starvation states appear throughout MCAT clinical vignettes.',
 objectives:['Trace the complete insulin signal cascade from receptor binding through Akt to each metabolic target, predicting the anabolic consequences at the enzyme level','Trace the complete glucagon signal cascade from receptor binding through PKA to each metabolic target, predicting the catabolic consequences at the enzyme level','Distinguish the four GLUT transporters by affinity, tissue distribution, and insulin dependence, and explain how each property matches its physiological role','Explain how epinephrine mobilizes fuel in skeletal muscle and adipose tissue via both Gs/cAMP/PKA and Gq/PLC/PKC/Ca2+ pathways','Explain how cortisol acts as a nuclear receptor ligand to induce gluconeogenic gene transcription and exert permissive effects on catecholamine signaling','Predict the metabolic state, dominant fuel sources, and key lab findings at each stage from the fed state through prolonged starvation','Explain the biochemical basis of DKA in Type 1 diabetes and distinguish it from hyperosmolar hyperglycemic state in Type 2 diabetes','Identify the mechanism of action of GLP-1 agonists and SGLT-2 inhibitors at the molecular level'],
 opener:'Every metabolic pathway you have studied so far has an on/off switch. Glycogen synthase is active or inactive. Hormone-sensitive lipase is phosphorylated or not. Acetyl-CoA carboxylase is dephosphorylated or inhibited. These switches are not thrown randomly. They are controlled by four hormones that continuously sample the body\'s energy state and broadcast instructions to every tissue simultaneously.\n\nInsulin says: glucose is abundant, build. Glucagon says: glucose is falling, release stores. Epinephrine says: emergency, mobilize everything now. Cortisol says: sustained stress, prioritize glucose for the brain at all costs.\n\nThe power of this chapter is not in memorizing four hormone lists. It is in seeing that the same enzyme is a downstream target of multiple signals, that cAMP/PKA and the PI3K/Akt pathways converge on the same metabolic checkpoints from opposite directions, and that the fed-to-starved transition follows a predictable biochemical logic. Once you can trace the signal cascade for each hormone to its metabolic consequences, every clinical vignette about diabetes, starvation, Cushing syndrome, or an adrenal crisis becomes a straightforward exercise in applying mechanism.',
 pinnedDisc:{t:'INSULIN vs GLUCAGON: WHICH ENZYMES ARE DIRECTLY CONTROLLED',x:'INSULIN (via Akt, net effect is dephosphorylation of targets): activates glycogen synthase (GSK-3 inhibited, so synthase NOT phosphorylated = active); activates acetyl-CoA carboxylase (ACC, dephosphorylated = active, raises malonyl-CoA, blocks CPT-I, shuts off beta-oxidation); activates pyruvate kinase and PFK-2 (glycolysis on); inhibits FOXO transcription factors (reducing PEPCK and G6Pase transcription, GNG off). GLUCAGON (via PKA, net effect is phosphorylation of targets): inhibits glycogen synthase (phosphorylated = inactive); activates phosphorylase kinase then glycogen phosphorylase (phosphorylated = active); inhibits ACC (phosphorylated = inactive, malonyl-CoA falls, CPT-I active, beta-oxidation on); activates PFK-2/FBPase-2 toward FBPase-2 activity (F-2,6-BP falls, GNG on, glycolysis slows); activates CREB (transcribes PEPCK, G6Pase, FBPASE). KEY TRAP: ACC is the master switch between FA synthesis and FA oxidation. High malonyl-CoA (insulin state) blocks CPT-I. Low malonyl-CoA (glucagon/fasting state) allows CPT-I to transfer acyl groups into mitochondria for beta-oxidation and ketogenesis.'},
 sections:[{id:'10.1',title:'Insulin Signaling and the Fed State',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Insulin is a 51-amino acid peptide hormone secreted by the beta cells of the pancreatic islets of Langerhans. Its primary stimulus for release is an elevated blood glucose concentration. The mechanism inside the beta cell is as follows: glucose enters the beta cell via GLUT2 (high Km, so glucose entry rate is proportional to blood glucose concentration); glucose is phosphorylated by glucokinase (hexokinase IV, which also has a high Km and is not saturated at normal glucose levels, making it a glucose sensor rather than a metabolic workhorse); increased glycolysis raises the ATP/ADP ratio; the high ATP closes ATP-sensitive potassium channels (KATP channels, the target of sulfonylurea drugs), depolarizing the cell membrane; voltage-gated calcium channels open; Ca2+ influx triggers exocytosis of insulin-containing secretory granules. Insulin enters the portal circulation first, where the liver extracts roughly 50% of the secreted dose, and then reaches peripheral tissues.'},{t:'p',x:'Insulin binds its receptor, a heterotetrameric receptor tyrosine kinase (RTK) consisting of two alpha subunits (extracellular, bind insulin) and two beta subunits (transmembrane, contain intrinsic tyrosine kinase domains). Insulin binding causes a conformational change that activates the intrinsic kinase in each beta subunit, which then trans-autophosphorylates tyrosine residues on the opposite beta subunit. The activated receptor phosphorylates adapter proteins IRS-1 and IRS-2 (insulin receptor substrates) on multiple tyrosine residues, creating docking sites for the SH2 domain of PI3K (phosphatidylinositol 3-kinase). Recruited PI3K phosphorylates PIP2 (phosphatidylinositol 4,5-bisphosphate) at the 3-position, generating PIP3 (phosphatidylinositol 3,4,5-trisphosphate) at the inner leaflet of the plasma membrane. PIP3 recruits PDK1 (phosphoinositide-dependent kinase 1) and Akt (protein kinase B, PKB) to the membrane via their PH domains. PDK1 phosphorylates Akt at Thr308, partially activating it; mTORC2 phosphorylates Akt at Ser473, completing full activation.'},{t:'box',kind:'why',label:'WHY DOES PTEN LOSS CAUSE INSULIN-INDEPENDENT CELL GROWTH?',x:'PTEN (phosphatase and tensin homolog) is a lipid phosphatase that removes the 3-phosphate from PIP3, converting it back to PIP2 and thereby terminating PI3K signaling. PTEN acts as the direct antagonist of PI3K. When PTEN is lost (by mutation or deletion, as in many cancers, Cowden syndrome, PTEN hamartoma syndrome), PIP3 accumulates constitutively even without insulin. Akt remains active, driving glucose uptake (GLUT4 on the surface), mTOR-mediated protein synthesis, and suppression of apoptosis (FOXO and BAD phosphorylation). This is why PI3K/Akt/mTOR is one of the most commonly mutated oncogenic pathways. The Warburg effect, in which cancer cells favor aerobic glycolysis, is partly attributable to constitutive Akt signaling driving GLUT expression and hexokinase activity.'},{t:'p',x:'Activated Akt has at least five major metabolic effects. First, GLUT4 translocation: Akt phosphorylates and inactivates AS160 (a Rab GAP); normally AS160 keeps Rab proteins in the GDP-bound inactive state, retaining GLUT4-containing storage vesicles (GSVs) intracellularly. When AS160 is phosphorylated, Rab proteins become GTP-bound and active, and GSVs fuse with the plasma membrane, inserting GLUT4. This is the primary mechanism by which insulin stimulates glucose uptake in skeletal muscle and adipose tissue. Second, GSK-3 inhibition: Akt phosphorylates and inactivates GSK-3 (glycogen synthase kinase 3); GSK-3 normally phosphorylates glycogen synthase to inactivate it, so when GSK-3 is off, glycogen synthase remains in its dephosphorylated active form, driving glycogen synthesis in both liver and muscle. Third, mTORC1 activation: Akt phosphorylates and inactivates TSC1/TSC2 (tuberous sclerosis complex), releasing inhibition of Rheb, which then activates mTORC1; mTORC1 phosphorylates S6K1 and 4EBP1 to promote ribosome biogenesis and cap-dependent translation, i.e., protein synthesis. Fourth, FOXO inhibition: Akt phosphorylates FOXO transcription factors (FOXO1, FOXO3a), causing them to be exported from the nucleus and degraded in the cytoplasm; in the nucleus, FOXO1 drives transcription of PEPCK and G6Pase (the two key gluconeogenic genes), so insulin suppresses gluconeogenesis at the transcriptional level. Fifth, ACC activation: Akt-mediated phosphorylation of PDE3B in adipocytes lowers cAMP, reducing PKA activity; in the liver, insulin-driven phosphatase activity dephosphorylates ACC (acetyl-CoA carboxylase), activating it; active ACC converts acetyl-CoA to malonyl-CoA, the first committed step of fatty acid synthesis and also a potent inhibitor of CPT-I, which blocks long-chain fatty acid entry into mitochondria and therefore blocks both beta-oxidation and ketogenesis.'},{t:'formula',x:'INSULIN SIGNAL CASCADE SUMMARY:\nInsulin binds IR (alpha subunits) → beta subunit trans-autophosphorylation → IRS-1/2 phosphorylation → PI3K activation → PIP2 → PIP3 → PDK1 + Akt recruited to membrane → Akt phosphorylated at Thr308 (PDK1) and Ser473 (mTORC2) → FULLY ACTIVE Akt → [1] AS160 off → GLUT4 to surface (muscle, adipose); [2] GSK-3 off → glycogen synthase active; [3] TSC1/2 off → mTOR on → protein synthesis; [4] FOXO out of nucleus → PEPCK/G6Pase transcription suppressed; [5] ACC dephosphorylated → malonyl-CoA rises → CPT-I blocked → FA synthesis on, beta-oxidation off'},{t:'p',x:'The four major GLUT transporters have distinct affinities, tissues, and regulatory mechanisms that match their physiological roles. GLUT1 is ubiquitous, with a Km for glucose of about 1 mmol/L, well below fasting blood glucose concentrations; it provides baseline glucose uptake to virtually all cells and is the primary transporter in erythrocytes and the blood-brain barrier. Because it operates near Vmax at all physiological glucose concentrations, it is always on and is not regulated by insulin. GLUT2 is expressed in hepatocytes, pancreatic beta cells, the small intestinal epithelium, and the kidney; it has a very high Km (15-20 mmol/L), meaning it is far from saturated at normal glucose levels and its transport rate rises steeply as blood glucose rises above normal. This low-affinity, high-capacity profile makes it a glucose sensor: in the beta cell it ensures that the rate of glucose metabolism (and thus the ATP/ADP ratio and insulin secretion) is proportional to blood glucose across a wide range. GLUT3 is expressed in neurons and has the highest affinity of the four (Km about 1 mmol/L, similar to GLUT1 but with a higher Vmax), ensuring that even when blood glucose is low, neurons can continue to extract glucose. Like GLUT1, it is constitutively expressed and not regulated by insulin. GLUT4 is expressed in skeletal muscle, cardiac muscle, and adipose tissue. Its Km is intermediate (~5 mmol/L), but its defining feature is that it is insulin-dependent: in the absence of insulin, GLUT4 resides in intracellular storage vesicles and is essentially absent from the plasma membrane. Insulin (via the PI3K/Akt/AS160/Rab pathway above) causes rapid translocation to the cell surface within minutes. Note that exercise also translocates GLUT4 by an insulin-independent mechanism involving AMPK and Ca2+/calmodulin-dependent protein kinase (CaMKII).'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'FED STATE METABOLIC SUMMARY (0-3 HOURS POST-MEAL)',x:'LIVER: glucose enters via GLUT2; glucokinase active; glycolysis on (PFK-1 active, driven by high F-2,6-BP from PFK-2 in its kinase mode); pyruvate dehydrogenase active (high ATP/NADH not limiting here because insulin effect predominates); acetyl-CoA channeled into FA synthesis (citrate exported, ATP-citrate lyase, ACC active, FAS active); glycogen synthesis on (glycogen synthase active); PEPCK and G6Pase gene expression suppressed (FOXO off). SKELETAL MUSCLE: GLUT4 on the surface; glucose enters and is either oxidized or stored as glycogen; protein synthesis activated via mTORC1. ADIPOSE TISSUE: GLUT4 on the surface; glucose enters and is converted to glycerol-3-phosphate (backbone for TAG synthesis) and to acetyl-CoA for FA synthesis; lipoprotein lipase (LPL) on capillary surface is activated by insulin, hydrolyzing VLDL-TAG and chylomicron-TAG to FFA for re-esterification into TAG; hormone-sensitive lipase (HSL) is phosphorylated by insulin\'s effects on cAMP (via PDE3B), preventing lipolysis. NET: anabolism throughout; glucose is the dominant fuel for all tissues; fat is being stored, not mobilized.'},{t:'p',x:'Insulin also exerts important non-metabolic effects. It promotes cell survival by phosphorylating and inactivating BAD (a pro-apoptotic Bcl-2 family member), increasing gene transcription via the MAPK/ERK branch of insulin signaling (a parallel pathway via Shc/Grb2/SOS/Ras/Raf/MEK/ERK), and inducing expression of sterol regulatory element-binding proteins (SREBP-1c in particular), which transcribe genes for fatty acid synthesis enzymes (ACC, FAS, SCD-1). SREBP-1c activation by insulin is the mechanism by which chronic hyperinsulinemia in obesity drives hepatic de novo lipogenesis and non-alcoholic fatty liver disease (NAFLD).'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR | GLUT TRANSPORTER PROPERTIES',x:'GLUT1: Km ~1 mM, ubiquitous (RBCs, blood-brain barrier, baseline all tissues), constitutive, NOT insulin-dependent; provides baseline glucose entry. GLUT2: Km ~15-20 mM, liver and pancreatic beta cells (also small intestine and kidney), constitutive, NOT insulin-dependent; functions as a glucose sensor because transport rate is proportional to blood glucose over the physiologic range. GLUT3: Km ~1 mM (high affinity), neurons, constitutive, NOT insulin-dependent; ensures neurons get glucose even when blood glucose is low. GLUT4: Km ~5 mM, skeletal muscle, cardiac muscle, adipose tissue, INSULIN-DEPENDENT (and exercise-dependent via AMPK); responsible for the bulk of postprandial glucose disposal. KEY TRAP: "insulin causes glucose uptake in the brain" is FALSE; brain uses GLUT1 and GLUT3, which are always active. Hypoglycemia harms the brain not because insulin is absent but because glucose substrate is gone.'},{t:'list',x:['Sulfonylureas (glipizide, glyburide): block KATP channels in beta cells, causing depolarization and insulin release regardless of glucose; risk of hypoglycemia because insulin release is not glucose-dependent','Meglitinides (repaglinide): same KATP channel target as sulfonylureas but shorter duration; taken with meals','GLP-1 agonists (liraglutide, semaglutide): mimic incretin GLP-1; stimulate insulin release only when glucose is elevated (glucose-dependent), suppress glucagon, delay gastric emptying, promote satiety; low hypoglycemia risk','SGLT-2 inhibitors (empagliflozin, dapagliflozin): block sodium-glucose cotransporter 2 in the proximal tubule, preventing renal glucose reabsorption; lower blood glucose by glucosuria; independent of insulin; also reduce cardiovascular and renal outcomes','Metformin: activates AMPK (by inhibiting Complex I of the ETC, raising AMP/ATP ratio); AMPK inhibits ACC (reducing malonyl-CoA and thereby reducing hepatic lipogenesis and gluconeogenesis); also directly inhibits PEPCK expression; reduces hepatic glucose output']},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'CLINICAL BRIDGE | INSULIN RESISTANCE MECHANISM IN TYPE 2 DIABETES',x:'In obesity, excess free fatty acids and their metabolites (diacylglycerol, ceramide) activate serine kinases (PKC isoforms, IKK-beta) that phosphorylate IRS-1 on serine residues rather than tyrosine. Serine-phosphorylated IRS-1 is a poor substrate for PI3K and is targeted for proteasomal degradation. The result: the insulin receptor fires normally but IRS-1 is impaired, so the PI3K/Akt/GLUT4 branch is blunted. Critically, the MAPK/ERK branch (which does not depend on IRS-1 to the same degree) remains intact. This selective insulin resistance explains why in early Type 2 diabetes, insulin still drives cell proliferation and atherosclerotic plaque formation via MAPK/ERK, even while glucose disposal is impaired.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A researcher blocks PI3K activity in isolated skeletal muscle cells and then adds insulin. Which of the following is most likely to be observed?',choices:['A) Decreased GLUT4 on the cell surface and decreased glycogen synthesis','B) Decreased GLUT4 on the cell surface but normal glycogen synthesis','C) Normal GLUT4 on the cell surface but decreased glycogen synthesis','D) Normal GLUT4 on the cell surface and normal glycogen synthesis'],answer:0,why:'Both GLUT4 translocation (via Akt/AS160) and glycogen synthesis (via Akt/GSK-3 inhibition) depend on the PI3K/Akt axis downstream of IRS-1. Blocking PI3K prevents PIP3 generation, so Akt cannot be recruited to the membrane and activated. Both effects fail. Glycogen synthesis requires GSK-3 inhibition (which requires Akt), and GLUT4 translocation requires AS160 phosphorylation (which also requires Akt). Both are lost when PI3K is blocked.'},{stem:'Which GLUT transporter property makes it suitable to function as a glucose sensor in pancreatic beta cells?',choices:['A) Very low Km (high affinity), ensuring saturation at all blood glucose concentrations','B) Insulin-dependent translocation, ensuring transport only occurs after insulin secretion','C) Very high Km (low affinity), ensuring transport rate rises in proportion to blood glucose over the physiologic range','D) Exclusive expression in neurons, ensuring glucose delivery to high-priority tissue'],answer:2,why:'GLUT2 has a Km of 15-20 mmol/L, much higher than normal fasting blood glucose (~5 mmol/L). This means GLUT2 operates on the steep portion of its saturation curve at physiologic glucose levels, so its transport rate increases proportionally as blood glucose rises. This allows the beta cell\'s glucose metabolism rate (and therefore ATP/ADP ratio and insulin secretion) to faithfully track blood glucose concentrations. A low-Km transporter like GLUT3 would be saturated at normal glucose and could not report changes in blood glucose to the cell.'}]},{id:'10.2',title:'Glucagon Signaling and the Fasted State',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Glucagon is a 29-amino acid peptide hormone secreted by the alpha cells of the pancreatic islets. Its primary stimulus is falling blood glucose, though amino acids (particularly alanine and arginine) also stimulate glucagon secretion during protein-rich meals when carbohydrates are absent. The physiological purpose is to restore blood glucose by mobilizing hepatic glucose stores and activating gluconeogenesis. Unlike insulin, which targets skeletal muscle and adipose tissue prominently, glucagon acts primarily on the liver (which expresses glucagon receptors at high density). Skeletal muscle lacks glucagon receptors. Adipose tissue has some glucagon receptor expression but the predominant lipolytic hormonal signal comes from epinephrine.'},{t:'p',x:'The glucagon receptor is a Gs-coupled GPCR (G protein-coupled receptor). When glucagon binds, the receptor activates the alpha subunit of Gs, which exchanges GDP for GTP and dissociates to stimulate adenylyl cyclase. Adenylyl cyclase converts ATP to cyclic AMP (cAMP). The elevated cAMP binds to the regulatory subunits of PKA (protein kinase A, also called cAMP-dependent protein kinase), releasing the catalytic subunits. Free PKA catalytic subunits phosphorylate serine and threonine residues on a wide array of targets throughout the hepatocyte, simultaneously activating the catabolic arms and inactivating the anabolic arms of metabolism.'},{t:'formula',x:'GLUCAGON SIGNAL CASCADE SUMMARY:\nGlucagon binds GPCR → Gs alpha-GTP → adenylyl cyclase active → ATP → cAMP rises → PKA regulatory subunits bind cAMP → catalytic subunits released and active → simultaneous phosphorylation targets:\n[1] Phosphorylase kinase (phosphorylated → active) → glycogen phosphorylase (phosphorylated → active) → glycogenolysis ON\n[2] Glycogen synthase (phosphorylated → inactive) → glycogen synthesis OFF\n[3] PFK-2/FBPase-2 bifunctional enzyme (phosphorylated → FBPase-2 domain active) → F-2,6-BP falls → PFK-1 less active → glycolysis slows; FBPase-1 active → GNG ON\n[4] ACC (acetyl-CoA carboxylase, phosphorylated → inactive) → malonyl-CoA falls → CPT-I active → FA enters mitochondria → beta-oxidation ON, ketogenesis ON\n[5] CREB (phosphorylated → active) → translocates to nucleus → binds CRE sequences → induces PEPCK, G6Pase, FBPASE, PGC-1alpha gene expression → sustained GNG capacity\n[6] HSL in adipose (phosphorylated → active, though epinephrine is stronger signal here) → lipolysis begins'},{t:'box',kind:'why',label:'WHY IS F-2,6-BISPHOSPHATE THE MASTER SWITCH BETWEEN GLYCOLYSIS AND GNG?',x:'Fructose-2,6-bisphosphate (F-2,6-BP) is not a glycolytic intermediate. It is a regulatory molecule whose sole role is to allosterically activate PFK-1 (the committed step of glycolysis) and allosterically inhibit FBPase-1 (the corresponding step of gluconeogenesis). The same bifunctional enzyme, PFK-2/FBPase-2, both makes and destroys F-2,6-BP, depending on its phosphorylation state. In the fed state (insulin high, cAMP low), the PFK-2 domain is active: F-2,6-BP levels are high, PFK-1 is highly active, glycolysis runs. In the fasted state (glucagon high, cAMP high), PKA phosphorylates the bifunctional enzyme, activating the FBPase-2 domain and inactivating the PFK-2 domain: F-2,6-BP levels fall, PFK-1 loses its allosteric activator, glycolysis slows, and FBPase-1 is disinhibited, driving gluconeogenesis. This reciprocal control ensures that glycolysis and gluconeogenesis are never both running at full speed simultaneously in the liver, which would waste ATP in a futile cycle.'},{t:'p',x:'The temporal sequence of glucose maintenance during fasting follows a predictable order that reflects both the capacity and rate of each fuel-mobilizing mechanism. In the first four to eight hours of fasting, hepatic glycogen is the primary source of blood glucose. The liver can export glucose directly into the bloodstream (because it expresses glucose-6-phosphatase, which hydrolyzes G6P to glucose for export; skeletal muscle does not express G6Pase and therefore cannot release glucose into the blood from glycogenolysis). By about eight to twelve hours, hepatic glycogen stores are substantially depleted (total liver glycogen is only about 80-100 g in a fasted adult), and gluconeogenesis must accelerate to maintain blood glucose. By eighteen to twenty-four hours of fasting, gluconeogenesis accounts for virtually all hepatic glucose output. The three major gluconeogenic substrates are lactate (from glycolysis in red blood cells and exercising muscle, recycled via the Cori cycle), alanine (from muscle proteolysis and transamination; the glucose-alanine cycle transfers amino groups to the liver for urea synthesis while returning glucose to muscle), and glycerol (released from TAG lipolysis in adipose tissue; glycerol-3-phosphate enters GNG at the DHAP entry point).'},{t:'p',x:'As fasting extends beyond eighteen hours, free fatty acid release from adipose tissue accelerates. Hepatic beta-oxidation of these fatty acids provides the ATP, NADH, acetyl-CoA, and propionyl-CoA that fuel and support gluconeogenesis: beta-oxidation raises the mitochondrial NADH/NAD+ ratio and acetyl-CoA concentration, both of which activate pyruvate carboxylase (which requires acetyl-CoA as an allosteric activator) and inhibit pyruvate dehydrogenase (sparing pyruvate for GNG entry). Excess acetyl-CoA that cannot enter the TCA cycle (because oxaloacetate is being diverted to GNG) is diverted to ketone body synthesis: HMG-CoA synthase (the mitochondrial rate-limiting enzyme of ketogenesis) condenses two acetyl-CoA molecules into acetoacetyl-CoA, then HMG-CoA, which is cleaved by HMG-CoA lyase to acetoacetate and acetyl-CoA. Acetoacetate is reduced to beta-hydroxybutyrate or spontaneously decarboxylated to acetone. Ketone bodies are water-soluble, freely exported from the liver, and used by the brain, heart, and skeletal muscle as alternative fuels.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'FASTING TIMELINE: WHAT IS THE DOMINANT FUEL AT EACH STAGE',x:'0-4 HOURS (fed to early post-absorptive): Insulin dominant. Liver takes up glucose and stores it. Muscle oxidizes glucose and amino acids. No net glucose output from liver. 4-8 HOURS (glycogenolysis phase): Glucagon rises. Hepatic glycogenolysis provides blood glucose. Muscle begins to shift toward FA oxidation to spare glucose. 8-18 HOURS (mixed glycogenolysis/GNG): Liver glycogen depleting. GNG from lactate and alanine begins contributing. Adipose lipolysis increasing; FFAs fuel muscle and support hepatic GNG. Brain still uses glucose exclusively. 18-72 HOURS (GNG dominant, early ketosis): Liver glycogen exhausted. GNG from lactate, alanine, glycerol is the only source of blood glucose. Ketogenesis begins; ketone levels rise to 1-3 mmol/L. Brain begins adapting to partial ketone use. Muscle proteolysis accelerating (nitrogen output as urea rises). >72 HOURS (starvation, ketone-adapted): Ketones provide 60-70% of brain fuel. Muscle proteolysis SLOWS (protein-sparing: the brain reduced its glucose demand by using ketones, so less gluconeogenic substrate is needed from protein). RBCs and renal medulla remain obligate glucose consumers (lack mitochondria or use anaerobic glycolysis exclusively). Urinary nitrogen excretion falls as adaptation occurs.'},{t:'p',x:'The Cori cycle and glucose-alanine cycle are the two main substrate recycling loops during fasting. In the Cori cycle: red blood cells and actively glycolyzing muscle produce lactate; lactate enters the bloodstream, is taken up by the liver, converted back to pyruvate by lactate dehydrogenase (LDH), and used as a gluconeogenic substrate; glucose exits the liver and returns to muscle. This cycle transfers the metabolic burden of glucose synthesis from the periphery to the liver but does not generate net new glucose from carbon (it recycles existing carbon). The glucose-alanine cycle is similar but involves muscle proteolysis: muscle amino acids undergo transamination to alanine (via alanine aminotransferase, ALT, which requires B6/PLP), alanine is exported to the liver, where ALT reverses the transamination (releasing the amino group for urea synthesis) and pyruvate enters GNG. This cycle transfers both carbon (as pyruvate) and nitrogen (as alanine) to the liver simultaneously.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'CLINICAL BRIDGE | PROLONGED FASTING AND REFEEDING SYNDROME',x:'During prolonged starvation, serum phosphate, potassium, and magnesium can fall as cells shift to using FA and ketones. When carbohydrates are reintroduced (refeeding), a surge of insulin drives massive cellular uptake of glucose, phosphate, potassium, and magnesium. If the patient is already depleted, serum levels of these electrolytes crash. The most dangerous consequence is severe hypophosphatemia: ATP synthesis requires inorganic phosphate; 2,3-BPG synthesis (which allows Hgb to release O2 to tissues) requires phosphate; phospholipid membrane synthesis requires phosphate. Refeeding syndrome presents with cardiac arrhythmias (hypokalemia, hypomagnesemia), respiratory failure, hemolytic anemia (RBC membrane instability), and rhabdomyolysis. Prevention: start nutrition slowly, supplement phosphate, potassium, and magnesium before and during refeeding.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'In the liver, PKA phosphorylates the PFK-2/FBPase-2 bifunctional enzyme during glucagon signaling. What is the direct metabolic consequence at the level of PFK-1?',choices:['A) PFK-1 is directly phosphorylated and inactivated by PKA','B) F-2,6-BP falls, removing an allosteric activator from PFK-1 and slowing glycolysis','C) F-2,6-BP rises, allosterically inhibiting PFK-1 and halting glycolysis','D) F-6-P accumulates and directly inhibits PFK-1 via substrate inhibition'],answer:1,why:'PKA phosphorylates the bifunctional PFK-2/FBPase-2 enzyme, shifting it from the PFK-2 mode (which synthesizes F-2,6-BP) to the FBPase-2 mode (which hydrolyzes F-2,6-BP). The resulting fall in F-2,6-BP removes the most potent allosteric activator of PFK-1, slowing glycolysis. PFK-1 itself is not a direct PKA substrate. This indirect allosteric mechanism allows a single phosphorylation event to simultaneously slow glycolysis and relieve FBPase-1 inhibition, coordinating two opposing pathways.'},{stem:'A patient is found unconscious after a three-day fast. Laboratory values show low blood glucose, elevated plasma beta-hydroxybutyrate, and low insulin with elevated glucagon. Which enzyme in the liver is most responsible for the elevated ketone production?',choices:['A) Beta-hydroxybutyrate dehydrogenase','B) Acetoacetyl-CoA thiolase','C) Mitochondrial HMG-CoA synthase','D) HMG-CoA reductase'],answer:2,why:'Mitochondrial HMG-CoA synthase (not to be confused with cytoplasmic HMG-CoA synthase in the cholesterol pathway) is the rate-limiting enzyme of ketogenesis. It condenses acetyl-CoA with acetoacetyl-CoA to form HMG-CoA in the mitochondrial matrix, which is then cleaved by HMG-CoA lyase to acetoacetate and acetyl-CoA. During fasting, low malonyl-CoA (ACC is inhibited by glucagon/PKA) removes CPT-I inhibition, flooding the mitochondria with acyl groups. Beta-oxidation generates abundant acetyl-CoA that exceeds the TCA cycle capacity, driving mitochondrial HMG-CoA synthase. HMG-CoA reductase is in the cytoplasm and drives cholesterol synthesis, not ketogenesis.'}]},{id:'10.3',title:'Epinephrine and the Acute Stress Response',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Epinephrine (adrenaline) is a catecholamine synthesized from tyrosine in the chromaffin cells of the adrenal medulla (which are modified sympathetic postganglionic neurons). Synthesis: tyrosine is hydroxylated by tyrosine hydroxylase (the rate-limiting step, requires BH4 as cofactor) to DOPA; DOPA is decarboxylated by aromatic L-amino acid decarboxylase (requires B6/PLP) to dopamine; dopamine is hydroxylated by dopamine beta-hydroxylase (requires vitamin C and copper) to norepinephrine; norepinephrine is methylated by PNMT (phenylamine N-methyltransferase, requires SAM as methyl donor, and cortisol as a permissive inducer of PNMT expression) to epinephrine. Epinephrine is released rapidly in response to hypoglycemia, hemorrhage, physical exertion, or psychological stress, providing an instantaneous metabolic response on a timescale of seconds to minutes.'},{t:'p',x:'Epinephrine acts through three major receptor types. Beta-1 adrenergic receptors (predominant in the heart) are Gs-coupled and increase heart rate and contractility via PKA phosphorylation of cardiac troponin I and phospholamban. Beta-2 adrenergic receptors (liver, skeletal muscle, adipose, bronchioles, blood vessels in muscle) are Gs-coupled and activate the same cAMP/PKA cascade as glucagon, producing identical effects on hepatic glucose metabolism: glycogenolysis on, GNG on, glycolysis slowed, ACC inactivated (beta-oxidation on). Alpha-1 adrenergic receptors (liver, some vascular smooth muscle) are Gq-coupled: Gq activates phospholipase C beta (PLC-beta), which cleaves PIP2 into IP3 and DAG. IP3 binds IP3 receptors on the endoplasmic reticulum, releasing stored Ca2+ into the cytoplasm. DAG and Ca2+ together activate PKC (protein kinase C). The released Ca2+ also binds calmodulin, and the Ca2+-calmodulin complex activates phosphorylase kinase (the upstream activator of glycogen phosphorylase), providing an alternative, cAMP-independent route to glycogenolysis in the liver. This alpha-1 pathway is particularly important in explaining how liver glycogenolysis can be activated even when cAMP is low.'},{t:'formula',x:'EPINEPHRINE METABOLIC EFFECTS BY RECEPTOR:\nBeta-2 in liver: Gs → cAMP → PKA → [same as glucagon] glycogenolysis on, GNG on, glycolysis off, ACC off\nBeta-2 in skeletal muscle: Gs → cAMP → PKA → phosphorylase kinase → glycogen phosphorylase → MUSCLE glycogenolysis on → muscle produces lactate (not glucose, no G6Pase) → lactate goes to liver (Cori cycle)\nAlpha-1 in liver: Gq → PLC-beta → PIP2 → IP3 + DAG → IP3 → ER Ca2+ release; DAG → PKC; Ca2+ → calmodulin → phosphorylase kinase active → glycogen phosphorylase active → glycogenolysis on (cAMP-independent)'},{t:'p',x:'In adipose tissue, epinephrine acts via beta-2 (and beta-3) receptors through the Gs/cAMP/PKA pathway to phosphorylate and activate hormone-sensitive lipase (HSL). HSL hydrolyzes the sn-1 and sn-3 ester bonds of triacylglycerol (TAG), releasing two fatty acid molecules; the remaining monoacylglycerol is hydrolyzed by monoglyceride lipase (MGL). The initial and rate-limiting step is actually performed by adipose triglyceride lipase (ATGL), which is activated by CGI-58 (a co-activator regulated by perilipin phosphorylation, also a PKA substrate). PKA also phosphorylates perilipin, causing CGI-58 to be released from perilipin and bind ATGL, activating it. So the complete PKA-driven lipolytic cascade involves perilipin phosphorylation (releases CGI-58), ATGL activation (CGI-58 now activates ATGL), and HSL phosphorylation and translocation to the lipid droplet surface. Insulin opposes this entire cascade by activating PDE3B (via Akt), lowering cAMP, and keeping PKA inactive. The released free fatty acids (FFAs) are poorly soluble in plasma and travel bound to albumin. Glycerol, the other lipolysis product, is released into the bloodstream (adipose lacks glycerol kinase, so it cannot re-phosphorylate glycerol for TAG synthesis) and taken up by the liver as a gluconeogenic substrate.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'LIVER vs MUSCLE GLYCOGENOLYSIS: A CRITICAL DISTINCTION',x:'LIVER glycogenolysis: purpose is to EXPORT glucose into the bloodstream to raise blood glucose. This is possible because liver expresses glucose-6-phosphatase (G6Pase), which cleaves the phosphate from G6P to yield free glucose that can be exported via GLUT2. Stimulated by glucagon, epinephrine (beta-2 and alpha-1), and cortisol. MUSCLE glycogenolysis: purpose is to fuel the muscle itself during exercise or stress. Muscle does NOT express G6Pase. G6P cannot be dephosphorylated, so it stays in the cell and enters glycolysis, producing lactate and pyruvate. The muscle exports LACTATE (not glucose) into the bloodstream; the liver then uses lactate for gluconeogenesis (Cori cycle). Stimulated by epinephrine (beta-2) and by local Ca2+ release during muscle contraction (Ca2+-calmodulin-phosphorylase kinase pathway, independent of hormones). TRAP: epinephrine-driven muscle glycogenolysis does not directly raise blood glucose; it contributes lactate as substrate for hepatic GNG, which then raises blood glucose indirectly.'},{t:'p',x:'The systemic effect of epinephrine during acute stress is a broad, coordinated fuel mobilization that simultaneously provides glucose (from hepatic glycogenolysis and subsequent GNG), fatty acids (from adipose lipolysis), and lactate (from muscle glycogenolysis), while also shutting down anabolic processes. Insulin secretion is acutely suppressed during epinephrine release via alpha-2 adrenergic receptors on pancreatic beta cells (Gi-coupled, inhibiting adenylyl cyclase and reducing cAMP, which opposes the KATP channel closure needed for insulin secretion). This ensures that the mobilized fuels are not re-stored. The cardiovascular effects (tachycardia, increased cardiac output, vasoconstriction in skin and viscera, vasodilation in skeletal muscle vasculature) direct blood flow to working muscles.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR | GLUCAGON vs EPINEPHRINE METABOLIC EFFECTS',x:'BOTH activate the cAMP/PKA cascade and produce the same hepatic effects: glycogenolysis on, glycogen synthesis off, GNG on, ACC off (ketogenesis on). GLUCAGON: acts primarily on liver; NO direct effect on muscle glycogenolysis (muscle lacks glucagon receptor); slower/longer-acting; used for chronic glucose maintenance during fasting; also stimulates lipolysis in adipose (weaker than epinephrine). EPINEPHRINE: acts on liver (beta-2 and alpha-1), muscle (beta-2), and adipose (beta-2/beta-3); ALSO activates muscle glycogenolysis (via beta-2 cAMP/PKA, and via local Ca2+ in exercising muscle); faster and more potent; used for acute stress/exercise response; also stimulates the Cori cycle (muscle lactate to liver for GNG). CLINICAL NOTE: in insulin-induced hypoglycemia, BOTH glucagon (first line) and epinephrine (second line) are counter-regulatory. Glucagon is given as emergency injection for severe hypoglycemia when IV access is unavailable. Patients with type 1 diabetes who have hypoglycemia unawareness have blunted glucagon and epinephrine responses, making hypoglycemia especially dangerous.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'Epinephrine stimulates glycogenolysis in the liver via both beta-2 and alpha-1 adrenergic receptors. If a patient is given a beta-adrenergic blocker (propranolol), which second messenger pathway can still activate hepatic glycogen phosphorylase?',choices:['A) cAMP produced via adenylyl cyclase downstream of the alpha-1 receptor','B) Intracellular Ca2+ released from the ER via IP3, downstream of the alpha-1 Gq pathway','C) PIP3 generated by PI3K downstream of the alpha-1 receptor','D) DAG generated by PLC activating Akt to phosphorylate glycogen phosphorylase'],answer:1,why:'The alpha-1 adrenergic receptor is Gq-coupled. Gq activates PLC-beta, which cleaves PIP2 into IP3 and DAG. IP3 binds its receptor on the ER, releasing Ca2+ into the cytoplasm. Ca2+ binds calmodulin, and the Ca2+-calmodulin complex activates phosphorylase kinase, which then phosphorylates and activates glycogen phosphorylase. This pathway is completely independent of cAMP and beta-adrenergic receptors, so propranolol does not block it. Akt does not phosphorylate glycogen phosphorylase. The alpha-1 receptor does not produce cAMP.'},{stem:'During an episode of intense exercise, skeletal muscle undergoes glycogenolysis. Why does this process NOT directly raise blood glucose?',choices:['A) Skeletal muscle glycogen phosphorylase produces glucose-1-phosphate, which inhibits GLUT4 export','B) Skeletal muscle lacks glucose-6-phosphatase, so glucose-6-phosphate cannot be dephosphorylated for export','C) Epinephrine blocks the GLUT4 transporter in muscle, preventing glucose exit','D) Insulin, released in response to exercise, rapidly re-stores the glucose as glycogen'],answer:1,why:'Glucose-6-phosphate (G6P) is the phosphorylated form of glucose produced by glycogenolysis (via the phosphoglucomutase step from G1P) and by hexokinase. Glucose-6-phosphatase (G6Pase) is the enzyme that cleaves the phosphate, producing free glucose that can be exported. The liver expresses G6Pase; skeletal muscle does not. Without G6Pase, muscle G6P is trapped in the cell and must enter glycolysis, producing pyruvate and lactate, which are exported. The lactate then travels to the liver via the Cori cycle where it is used as a gluconeogenic substrate to raise blood glucose indirectly.'}]},{id:'10.4',title:'Cortisol and the Long-Term Stress Response',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Cortisol is a glucocorticoid steroid hormone synthesized from cholesterol in the zona fasciculata of the adrenal cortex. Its synthesis and secretion are controlled by the hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal (HPA) axis: the hypothalamus releases CRH (corticotropin-releasing hormone), which stimulates the anterior pituitary to secrete ACTH (adrenocorticotropic hormone), which binds the MC2R receptor (a Gs-coupled GPCR) on adrenocortical cells, activating the steroidogenic machinery. The rate-limiting step of cortisol synthesis is the transport of cholesterol from the outer to the inner mitochondrial membrane by StAR (steroidogenic acute regulatory protein), which is induced by ACTH. Cortisol feeds back to suppress both CRH and ACTH secretion (the long-loop negative feedback), and ACTH feeds back to suppress CRH (the short-loop feedback).'},{t:'p',x:'Because cortisol is a steroid, it is lipophilic and crosses the plasma membrane by diffusion. In the cytoplasm, cortisol binds the glucocorticoid receptor (GR), a member of the nuclear receptor superfamily. Unliganded GR is held in the cytoplasm in an inactive complex with Hsp90, Hsp70, and other chaperones. Cortisol binding induces a conformational change that dissociates the chaperone complex and exposes the nuclear localization signal on GR. The cortisol-GR complex translocates to the nucleus, dimerizes, and binds glucocorticoid response elements (GREs) in the promoter regions of target genes. Depending on the gene and the co-activators or co-repressors recruited, this either activates or represses transcription. Because this mechanism requires new mRNA and protein synthesis, the effects of cortisol have an onset of 30-60 minutes and are sustained for hours to days, in contrast to the seconds-to-minutes timescale of epinephrine.'},{t:'p',x:'The principal metabolic effects of cortisol serve a single purpose: guarantee glucose supply to the brain during prolonged stress, at the expense of peripheral tissues. In the liver, cortisol induces the transcription of PEPCK (the rate-limiting enzyme of gluconeogenesis that converts OAA to PEP), fructose-1,6-bisphosphatase (removes a second phosphate barrier in GNG), G6Pase (the final step releasing glucose from the liver), and tyrosine aminotransferase (which initiates the conversion of tyrosine to fumarate and ultimately to oxaloacetate for GNG entry). In skeletal muscle, cortisol promotes proteolysis by inducing the ubiquitin-proteasome pathway and inhibiting protein synthesis (via suppression of mTOR and IGF-1 signaling). The released amino acids, primarily alanine and glutamine, travel to the liver as substrates for gluconeogenesis. In adipose tissue, cortisol promotes lipolysis, releasing FFAs and glycerol. The FFAs support hepatic gluconeogenesis indirectly (by providing the acetyl-CoA that allosterically activates pyruvate carboxylase) and the glycerol enters GNG directly.'},{t:'box',kind:'why',label:'WHY DOES CORTISOL CAUSE CENTRAL OBESITY BUT PERIPHERAL WASTING?',x:'In Cushing syndrome, excess cortisol produces a distinctive fat redistribution pattern: central (visceral) fat accumulates (moon face, buffalo hump, truncal obesity) while peripheral (extremity) fat and muscle are wasted. The reason lies in regional differences in glucocorticoid receptor density and local cortisol activation. Visceral adipocytes have higher glucocorticoid receptor density than subcutaneous adipocytes and higher expression of 11-beta-HSD1 (the enzyme that converts inactive cortisone to active cortisol locally), making them more sensitive to cortisol\'s lipogenic effects in the fed state. At the same time, cortisol-driven insulin resistance shifts nutrient storage toward visceral fat. In peripheral fat and muscle, the catabolic effects (lipolysis, proteolysis, anti-insulin signaling via IRS-1 serine phosphorylation) predominate. The net result is central accumulation and peripheral wasting. This fat distribution pattern (high waist-to-hip ratio) is itself independently associated with cardiovascular risk because visceral fat is more metabolically active and inflammatory.'},{t:'p',x:'Cortisol has critical permissive effects on catecholamine signaling. It induces the expression of beta-adrenergic receptors and components of the Gs/adenylyl cyclase signaling machinery in multiple tissues. It also induces PNMT (phenylethanolamine N-methyltransferase) in the adrenal medulla, the enzyme that converts norepinephrine to epinephrine. Without adequate cortisol, epinephrine responses are severely blunted, which is why patients with adrenal insufficiency (Addison disease) are at risk for hemodynamic collapse during surgical or physiological stress: they cannot mount the catecholamine surge that maintains blood pressure and fuel mobilization. This is the biochemical basis for stress-dosing glucocorticoids in patients with known adrenal insufficiency before procedures or illness.'},{t:'p',x:'Cortisol also exerts potent anti-inflammatory effects through two main mechanisms. First, it induces the synthesis of annexin-1 (lipocortin), a protein that inhibits phospholipase A2. Phospholipase A2 cleaves arachidonic acid from membrane phospholipids, generating the substrate for both the cyclooxygenase pathway (prostaglandins, thromboxanes) and the lipoxygenase pathway (leukotrienes). By suppressing phospholipase A2, cortisol blocks arachidonic acid release and therefore inhibits both pathways simultaneously. This is why glucocorticoids are more potent anti-inflammatory agents than NSAIDs (which only block COX). Second, activated GR directly represses the transcription of pro-inflammatory cytokines (TNF-alpha, IL-1, IL-6) and COX-2 by binding and antagonizing the transcription factors NF-kappaB and AP-1. These mechanisms underlie the clinical use of prednisone and dexamethasone in autoimmune disease, asthma, and transplant rejection.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'CUSHING SYNDROME vs ADDISON DISEASE: COMPLETE COMPARISON',x:'CUSHING SYNDROME (cortisol excess): central obesity (moon face, buffalo hump, truncal obesity), peripheral muscle wasting, skin thinning and easy bruising (collagen loss), abdominal striae (purple striae from rapid fat deposition with skin atrophy), hyperglycemia (insulin resistance from cortisol-driven GNG and anti-insulin signaling), hypertension (cortisol activates mineralocorticoid receptors at high concentrations, causing Na+/water retention), hypokalemia (mineralocorticoid effect), immunosuppression (lymphopenia, opportunistic infections), osteoporosis (cortisol inhibits osteoblast activity and Ca2+ absorption). Causes: pituitary adenoma (Cushing disease, 70%, ACTH high), adrenal adenoma/carcinoma (ACTH low, suppressed by excess cortisol), ectopic ACTH (small cell lung cancer, ACTH very high, bilateral adrenal hyperplasia). Diagnosis: elevated 24h urine free cortisol, elevated late-night salivary cortisol, failed low-dose dexamethasone suppression test (1 mg overnight). High-dose dexamethasone (8 mg) suppresses pituitary ACTH (Cushing disease) but NOT ectopic ACTH. ADDISON DISEASE (primary adrenal insufficiency, cortisol deficiency): hypoglycemia (GNG fails), hypotension and hyponatremia (no aldosterone: Na+ wasting, K+ retention), hyperkalemia (hypoaldosteronism), hyperpigmentation (skin and mucosal), because ACTH and MSH (melanocyte-stimulating hormone) share the same precursor POMC and are both elevated when cortisol feedback is absent; ACTH cross-reacts with MC1R. Precipitating crisis: stressful illness or surgery; must stress-dose with hydrocortisone.'},{t:'list',x:['Cortisol is a steroid (lipophilic): diffuses across cell membrane, binds intracellular GR, GR-cortisol translocates to nucleus, binds GREs, alters transcription','Insulin, glucagon, and epinephrine are peptides or catecholamines (hydrophilic): cannot cross cell membrane, bind surface receptors, transduce signal via second messengers (cAMP, PIP3, IP3/DAG)','This distinction explains why steroid effects take 30-60 minutes (require new mRNA/protein) while epinephrine effects occur within seconds (phosphorylation cascade is already assembled)','Synthetic glucocorticoids: prednisone (inactive prodrug, activated to prednisolone by 11-beta-HSD); dexamethasone (potent, long-acting, used for dexamethasone suppression test and anti-inflammatory); fludrocortisone (has mineralocorticoid activity, used in Addison disease alongside hydrocortisone)','HPA axis suppression: prolonged glucocorticoid therapy suppresses CRH and ACTH; abrupt discontinuation causes secondary adrenal insufficiency because the adrenal cortex has atrophied; must taper slowly']}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A patient with a pituitary ACTH-secreting adenoma (Cushing disease) undergoes an 8 mg overnight dexamethasone suppression test. Cortisol is appropriately suppressed to less than 50% of baseline. What is the mechanism of this suppression?',choices:['A) Dexamethasone directly inhibits adrenal cortisol synthesis by blocking StAR protein','B) Dexamethasone binds GR in pituitary corticotrophs and suppresses ACTH transcription via the HPA feedback axis','C) Dexamethasone activates mineralocorticoid receptors in the hypothalamus, suppressing CRH release','D) Dexamethasone inhibits 11-beta-HSD1, preventing conversion of cortisone to cortisol in the adrenal cortex'],answer:1,why:'Dexamethasone is a potent synthetic glucocorticoid that binds the glucocorticoid receptor (GR). In pituitary corticotrophs, the activated GR complex suppresses POMC gene transcription (the precursor of ACTH) via negative GRE binding and NF-kappaB antagonism. In Cushing disease, the pituitary adenoma is still partially sensitive to glucocorticoid feedback; the high dose (8 mg) overrides the slightly elevated set point and suppresses ACTH, which in turn lowers adrenal cortisol output. In ectopic ACTH-producing tumors, the tumor cells typically lack functional GR-mediated feedback, so dexamethasone does NOT suppress cortisol. This is the basis of the high-dose dexamethasone suppression test for distinguishing pituitary from ectopic causes of ACTH-dependent Cushing syndrome.'},{stem:'A patient with Addison disease presents to the emergency department in adrenal crisis after developing a severe infection. Which lab finding is most characteristic of primary adrenal insufficiency?',choices:['A) Hyperglycemia, hypokalemia, and suppressed ACTH','B) Hypoglycemia, hyperkalemia, hyponatremia, and elevated ACTH','C) Hyperglycemia, hyponatremia, and elevated ACTH','D) Hypoglycemia, hypokalemia, and suppressed ACTH'],answer:1,why:'In primary adrenal insufficiency (Addison disease), both the glucocorticoid (cortisol) and mineralocorticoid (aldosterone) outputs of the adrenal cortex are lost. Absent cortisol means gluconeogenesis cannot be maintained, causing hypoglycemia. Absent aldosterone means the principal cells of the collecting duct do not retain Na+ or excrete K+, causing hyponatremia and hyperkalemia. ACTH is markedly elevated because the negative feedback from cortisol on the pituitary is absent (the POMC precursor is cleaved into both ACTH and MSH, explaining the hyperpigmentation). The combination of hypoglycemia, hyperkalemia, hyponatremia, and elevated ACTH is the hallmark laboratory profile.'}]},{id:'10.5',title:'Integration: Fed, Fasted, and Starvation States',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'The four hormones studied in this chapter do not act in isolation. At any given moment, their relative concentrations and the sensitivity of target tissues determine the metabolic phenotype of the body. The most useful framework is to examine each major metabolic transition and identify the dominant hormones, the dominant fuel, and the dominant metabolic pathways at each stage.'},{t:'p',x:'In the fully fed state (the first two to three hours after a carbohydrate-containing meal), insulin is the dominant hormone and the insulin-to-glucagon ratio is high. Glucose is being absorbed from the gut. The liver takes up glucose via GLUT2 and runs glycolysis (high F-2,6-BP from active PFK-2 drives PFK-1). Excess glucose is stored as glycogen (glycogen synthase active). Acetyl-CoA from glycolysis runs the TCA cycle, and additional acetyl-CoA is used for fatty acid synthesis (ACC active, FAS active, malonyl-CoA high). The liver packages newly synthesized fatty acids as VLDL and exports them to peripheral tissues. In adipose tissue, GLUT4 is on the surface (insulin-dependent); incoming glucose provides glycerol-3-phosphate (G3P) for TAG synthesis; lipoprotein lipase (LPL) on the capillary endothelium (activated by insulin via ApoCII presentation) hydrolyzes VLDL-TAG and chylomicron-TAG, delivering FFAs to adipocytes for re-esterification; HSL is inactive (insulin-driven cAMP suppression). In skeletal muscle, GLUT4 is on the surface; glucose is stored as glycogen and oxidized for energy; mTOR activates protein synthesis. The brain uses glucose via GLUT1 and GLUT3 continuously throughout.'},{t:'formula',x:'DOMINANT FUEL FLOWS BY METABOLIC STATE:\n\nFED: Gut glucose → liver (glycogen + VLDL) and muscle (glycogen + oxidation) and adipose (TAG storage). FA synthesis on. GNG off. Ketogenesis off. Proteolysis minimal.\n\nEARLY FASTING (4-18h): Liver glycogen → blood glucose. Adipose TAG → FFA + glycerol → muscle (FA oxidation) + liver (GNG substrate). Brain: glucose only. Muscle: glucose + FA.\n\nPROLONGED FASTING (18-72h): Liver GNG (from lactate via Cori cycle, alanine via glucose-alanine cycle, glycerol from lipolysis). Ketogenesis beginning. Brain: glucose + early ketone use. Muscle: FA + early ketones.\n\nSTARVATION (>72h): Liver GNG continues but at reduced rate (protein-sparing). Ketones 60-70% of brain fuel. Muscle: ketones + FA. RBCs: glycolysis only (obligate). Renal medulla: glycolysis only (obligate). Urinary nitrogen excretion falls as protein catabolism slows.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'CLINICAL BRIDGE | DIABETIC KETOACIDOSIS (DKA)',x:'DKA occurs primarily in Type 1 diabetes (absolute insulin deficiency) but can rarely occur in severe Type 2. The biochemistry follows directly from the absence of insulin. Without insulin: GLUT4 does not translocate, so muscle and adipose cannot take up glucose (hyperglycemia). HSL is uninhibited by insulin, so lipolysis in adipose is maximal (massively elevated FFA release). FFAs flood the liver. ACC is not activated (no insulin), so malonyl-CoA is low and CPT-I is fully active: all incoming FFAs are oxidized by beta-oxidation. The resulting overwhelming acetyl-CoA cannot enter the TCA cycle (OAA is being used for GNG, which is also maximal because glucagon is high and unopposed). Acetyl-CoA floods the ketogenic pathway: acetoacetate and beta-hydroxybutyrate accumulate. Both are organic acids. At concentrations above 7-10 mmol/L, they overwhelm the bicarbonate buffering system. DIAGNOSTIC CRITERIA: glucose >250 mg/dL, pH <7.3, bicarbonate <18 mEq/L, anion gap elevated (unmeasured ketoacid anions), serum/urine ketones positive. Acetone (from spontaneous decarboxylation of acetoacetate) is volatile and produces the characteristic fruity breath. Potassium: total body K+ is depleted (osmotic diuresis, transcellular shifts), but serum K+ may be normal or elevated initially because acidosis drives K+ out of cells (H+/K+ exchange). Treatment includes insulin, IV fluids, and careful K+ replacement (as insulin is given, K+ returns intracellularly and hypokalemia can develop rapidly).'},{t:'p',x:'Type 2 diabetes presents a different metabolic picture. The fundamental defect is insulin resistance in skeletal muscle and adipose tissue (the PI3K/Akt/GLUT4 axis is impaired, as described in Section 10.1). To compensate, the pancreatic beta cells secrete more and more insulin (hyperinsulinemia). Blood glucose remains near-normal for years. Eventually, beta cell exhaustion occurs (from chronic ER stress, lipotoxicity from elevated FFAs, and glucotoxicity from chronic high glucose). At that point, insulin secretion falls and frank hyperglycemia develops. Because some insulin is still present (unlike Type 1), lipolysis and ketogenesis are partially suppressed; DKA is uncommon in Type 2. Instead, the more common acute complication is hyperosmolar hyperglycemic state (HHS): extreme hyperglycemia (>600 mg/dL) with severe dehydration, altered mental status, and no significant acidosis (some insulin is present, blunting ketogenesis). Mortality of HHS is higher than DKA.'},{t:'p',x:'The pharmacological management of Type 2 diabetes can be understood mechanistically. Metformin activates AMPK in the liver by inhibiting Complex I of the ETC (raising AMP/ATP ratio); activated AMPK phosphorylates and inactivates ACC (lowering malonyl-CoA), which primarily reduces hepatic FA synthesis and indirectly reduces the energy available to drive GNG; additionally, metformin may directly suppress mitochondrial glycerophosphate dehydrogenase, impairing the mitochondrial reducing equivalents that fuel GNG. GLP-1 agonists (liraglutide, semaglutide, exenatide) mimic incretin GLP-1: they bind the GLP-1 receptor (a Gs-coupled GPCR) on beta cells and stimulate insulin release in a glucose-dependent manner (only when glucose is elevated, via the same ATP/KATP/Ca2+ mechanism potentiated by cAMP/PKA), suppress glucagon release from alpha cells, slow gastric emptying, and act centrally to increase satiety. Because insulin release is glucose-dependent, the risk of hypoglycemia is low compared to sulfonylureas. SGLT-2 inhibitors (empagliflozin, dapagliflozin, canagliflozin) block the sodium-glucose cotransporter 2 (SGLT-2) in the S1 and S2 segments of the proximal renal tubule, where 90% of filtered glucose is normally reabsorbed. By blocking reabsorption, these drugs force glucosuria (glucose loss in urine), lowering blood glucose independent of insulin signaling. They also reduce cardiovascular mortality and slow progression of diabetic kidney disease by mechanisms that include reduction of glomerular hyperfiltration (via tubuloglomerular feedback, because the blocked tubular glucose cotransport also blocks Na+ reabsorption, increasing distal Na+ delivery to the macula densa, causing afferent arteriole constriction).'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR | TYPE 1 vs TYPE 2 DIABETES METABOLIC FEATURES',x:'TYPE 1 (absolute insulin deficiency, autoimmune beta cell destruction, anti-islet/anti-GAD/anti-insulin antibodies): age of onset typically childhood/adolescence; thin body habitus typical; C-peptide absent or very low (C-peptide is co-secreted with insulin and reflects endogenous insulin production; exogenous insulin does not contain C-peptide); DKA is common and may be the presenting event; requires exogenous insulin; GLUT4 tissues cannot take up glucose even when blood glucose is high; lipolysis and ketogenesis are maximal when insulin is absent. TYPE 2 (relative insulin deficiency on a background of insulin resistance; genetic predisposition plus obesity, physical inactivity): age of onset typically middle age but rising in youth; obesity, particularly central/visceral; C-peptide initially elevated (hyperinsulinemia), later falls; DKA uncommon; HHS is the more typical acute complication; initial treatment with lifestyle modification, metformin, and other oral/injectable agents before insulin is required. SHARED LONG-TERM COMPLICATIONS (from chronic hyperglycemia): non-enzymatic glycation of proteins (AGE formation, damages blood vessels, nerves, kidneys, retina); RAAS activation in the kidney; polyol pathway activation (aldose reductase converts glucose to sorbitol, depleting NADPH and causing osmotic damage); microvascular disease (retinopathy, nephropathy, neuropathy); macrovascular disease (atherosclerosis, CAD, stroke, PVD).'},{t:'p',x:'The obligate glucose-consuming tissues are those that either lack mitochondria or are functionally committed to anaerobic glycolysis. Red blood cells lack mitochondria entirely and therefore cannot perform oxidative phosphorylation; they are entirely dependent on glycolysis for ATP. The renal medulla experiences a state of relative hypoxia due to its countercurrent architecture and sparse capillary supply in the outer medulla; the medullary cells therefore rely primarily on glycolysis. Both tissues require glucose regardless of the hormonal milieu. In prolonged starvation, these tissues impose a minimum glucose requirement on the body, setting a floor below which gluconeogenesis cannot fall. This is one reason why the body cannot fully eliminate gluconeogenesis even in deep starvation: some glucose must always be produced for RBCs (which cannot use ketones) and for the renal medulla. The brain also retains a partial glucose requirement even when adapted to ketones (covering the remaining 30-40% of brain fuel needs during deep starvation), partly because the blood-brain barrier has lower permeability to some ketone body species and partly because certain brain regions maintain obligate glucose use.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A 19-year-old woman with Type 1 diabetes presents with nausea, vomiting, rapid deep breathing, and fruity-smelling breath. Blood glucose is 380 mg/dL, pH 7.20, bicarbonate 12 mEq/L, and anion gap is 24 mEq/L. Which mechanism directly explains the elevated anion gap?',choices:['A) Accumulation of lactic acid from impaired mitochondrial oxidation due to insulin deficiency','B) Accumulation of acetoacetate and beta-hydroxybutyrate as unmeasured anions from maximal ketogenesis','C) Accumulation of urea from maximal hepatic proteolysis and GNG','D) Accumulation of free fatty acids in the bloodstream from uninhibited lipolysis'],answer:1,why:'DKA produces an elevated anion gap metabolic acidosis because the ketone bodies acetoacetate and beta-hydroxybutyrate are organic acids; at physiologic pH they are fully dissociated and exist as their conjugate base anions (acetoacetate(-) and beta-hydroxybutyrate(-)). These anions are not measured by the standard Na+/K+/Cl-/HCO3- panel. Anion gap = Na+ - (Cl- + HCO3-); when unmeasured anions (ketoacids) rise, HCO3- falls as it buffers the acid, but the Na+ and Cl- values do not change proportionally, causing the gap to widen. Urea is not an acid and does not contribute to the anion gap. FFA concentrations in plasma are elevated but FFAs are largely albumin-bound and do not dominate the anion gap. Lactic acidosis can coexist but is not the primary mechanism in DKA.'},{stem:'After 5 days of total starvation, which tissue continues to require glucose as its sole metabolic fuel and cannot use ketone bodies?',choices:['A) Cardiac muscle','B) Hepatocytes','C) Red blood cells','D) Neurons of the cerebral cortex'],answer:2,why:'Red blood cells (RBCs) lack mitochondria. All ATP production in RBCs occurs via anaerobic glycolysis (Embden-Meyerhof pathway). Since ketone body utilization requires mitochondrial enzymes (succinyl-CoA:3-ketoacid CoA transferase, acetoacetyl-CoA thiolase, and subsequently the TCA cycle and oxidative phosphorylation), RBCs cannot use ketones at all. They are absolutely dependent on glucose throughout starvation. Cardiac muscle, hepatocytes, and neurons all possess mitochondria and can use ketone bodies. During prolonged starvation, the brain adapts to use ketones for 60-70% of its fuel, though it retains a partial glucose requirement. Cardiac muscle actually preferentially uses fatty acids and ketones and adapts very efficiently to starvation.'}]},{id:'10.6',title:'AMPK: The Cellular Energy Sensor',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'AMP-activated protein kinase (AMPK) is a serine/threonine kinase that operates as a cellular fuel gauge. It is activated when cellular AMP/ATP or ADP/ATP ratios rise, which occurs during energy depletion: exercise, hypoxia, fasting, or metformin treatment. AMPK consists of a catalytic alpha subunit and regulatory beta and gamma subunits; the gamma subunit has four CBS domains that bind adenine nucleotides. AMP binding to the gamma subunit causes a conformational change that exposes the Thr172 phosphorylation site on the alpha subunit, allowing upstream kinases (LKB1, the tumor suppressor kinase; and CaMKK2, activated by Ca2+) to phosphorylate and fully activate AMPK. ADP (unlike ATP) also activates AMPK by the same conformational mechanism and protects Thr172 from dephosphorylation, making AMPK responsive not only to AMP but to any fall in the adenylate energy charge.'},{t:'p',x:'Once activated, AMPK simultaneously suppresses anabolic (ATP-consuming) pathways and activates catabolic (ATP-producing) pathways. Its key metabolic targets are: ACC (phosphorylated at Ser79, inactivated, malonyl-CoA falls, CPT-I active, beta-oxidation on), HMG-CoA reductase (phosphorylated, inactivated, cholesterol synthesis off), glycogen synthase (phosphorylated, inactivated, glycogen synthesis off), PFKFB3 (in heart and some tissues, phosphorylated, PFK-2 activity up, glycolysis on), and mTORC1 (inhibited via TSC1/2 activation and Raptor phosphorylation, protein synthesis off). Additionally, AMPK promotes GLUT4 translocation by an insulin-independent mechanism (important during exercise), and promotes mitochondrial biogenesis via PGC-1alpha. The net effect of AMPK activation is a cell-autonomous response to low energy that is qualitatively similar to the systemic fasting response driven by glucagon: both turn off FA synthesis, cholesterol synthesis, glycogen synthesis, and protein synthesis, and both turn on beta-oxidation.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'CLINICAL BRIDGE | LKB1, AMPK, AND PEUTZ-JEGHERS SYNDROME',x:'LKB1 (STK11) is the primary upstream kinase that activates AMPK by phosphorylating Thr172. LKB1 is a tumor suppressor. Loss-of-function mutations in LKB1 cause Peutz-Jeghers syndrome: hamartomatous GI polyps throughout the intestinal tract (particularly small bowel), mucocutaneous melanin pigmentation (lips, buccal mucosa, fingers), and dramatically elevated lifetime risk of GI, breast, pancreatic, and other cancers. The cancer risk results partly from loss of AMPK activation (which normally suppresses mTOR and cell growth in low-nutrient environments) and partly from loss of other LKB1-dependent substrates involved in cell polarity and mitosis. This connection between cellular energy sensing (AMPK/LKB1) and tumor suppression illustrates why cancer cells must reprogram their energy metabolism (the Warburg effect) to proliferate despite nutrient limitation.'},{t:'p',x:'AMPK serves as a unifying link between exercise physiology and the hormonal fasting response. During aerobic exercise, repeated cycles of actomyosin ATP hydrolysis rapidly lower the muscle cell\'s energy charge, activating AMPK. AMPK then activates beta-oxidation (via ACC inhibition) and promotes GLUT4 translocation to the muscle plasma membrane (via a TBC1D1 phosphorylation pathway parallel to insulin\'s TBC1D4/AS160 pathway). This explains why exercise lowers blood glucose and improves insulin sensitivity: the muscle is taking up glucose and oxidizing both glucose and fatty acids via an insulin-independent mechanism. In Type 2 diabetes, where insulin signaling to GLUT4 is impaired, exercise-driven AMPK activation can partially compensate by providing an alternate route to GLUT4 membrane insertion.'},{t:'list',x:['AMPK is activated by: rising AMP/ADP ratios (energy depletion), LKB1 (tumor suppressor kinase), CaMKK2 (Ca2+ signaling, during muscle contraction), metformin (via Complex I inhibition raising AMP/ATP), resveratrol and AICAR (experimental activators), and leptin (via hypothalamic and peripheral pathways)','AMPK is inactivated by: rising ATP ratios (energy replete state), protein phosphatase 2A (PP2A) and PP2C which dephosphorylate Thr172, and insulin signaling (Akt phosphorylates and partially inactivates AMPK in some contexts)','AMPK targets in ANABOLISM (turned off): ACC (FA synthesis off), HMG-CoA reductase (cholesterol synthesis off), glycogen synthase (glycogen synthesis off), mTORC1 via TSC2 phosphorylation (protein synthesis off), SREBP-1c reduced (lipogenic gene transcription off)','AMPK targets in CATABOLISM (turned on): CPT-I active (malonyl-CoA falls from ACC inhibition), GLUT4 translocation (via TBC1D1), PGC-1alpha gene expression (mitochondrial biogenesis), autophagy induction (via ULK1 phosphorylation)']}],quickcheck:[{stem:'Metformin activates AMPK in hepatocytes. Which of the following best explains how AMPK activation reduces hepatic glucose output?',choices:['A) AMPK directly phosphorylates and inhibits PEPCK, the rate-limiting enzyme of gluconeogenesis','B) AMPK activates ACC, raising malonyl-CoA and allosterically inhibiting PEPCK','C) AMPK inhibits ACC (lowering malonyl-CoA and reducing FA synthesis) and suppresses mTOR and SREBP-1c, collectively reducing hepatic lipid accumulation and VLDL production, and inhibits CREB-mediated transcription of PEPCK and G6Pase','D) AMPK directly phosphorylates glucagon receptors, preventing glucagon from activating adenylyl cyclase'],answer:2,why:'AMPK does not directly phosphorylate PEPCK. Its effects on gluconeogenesis are indirect. AMPK inhibits TORC2 (a transcriptional coactivator of CREB that drives PEPCK and G6Pase transcription) and reduces SREBP-1c-mediated lipogenic gene expression, lowering hepatic lipid content that would otherwise fuel GNG. The reduction in malonyl-CoA (from ACC inhibition) reduces FA synthesis energy demand. Additionally, by activating SIRT1 (via raising NAD+) and by direct phosphorylation of HDAC5, AMPK suppresses the transcriptional program that drives GNG gene expression. The net result is reduced PEPCK and G6Pase expression and reduced hepatic glucose output, which is the primary mechanism by which metformin lowers fasting blood glucose.'},{stem:'A patient undergoes vigorous aerobic exercise. Skeletal muscle GLUT4 translocates to the plasma membrane during the exercise session. Which statement best describes the signal mediating this translocation?',choices:['A) Insulin released in response to exercise activates PI3K/Akt/AS160 to insert GLUT4','B) Glucagon released during exercise activates PKA, which phosphorylates AS160 to insert GLUT4','C) AMPK activated by falling ATP/AMP ratios phosphorylates TBC1D1 (not AS160), triggering GLUT4 translocation independently of insulin','D) Epinephrine released during exercise activates Akt via beta-2 receptor signaling to insert GLUT4'],answer:2,why:'Exercise-induced GLUT4 translocation is insulin-independent. During exercise, repeated ATP hydrolysis by myosin raises AMP/ATP, activating AMPK. AMPK phosphorylates TBC1D1 (a Rab GAP closely related to AS160/TBC1D4 but the predominant isoform in skeletal muscle during exercise). Phospho-TBC1D1 has reduced Rab-GAP activity, allowing Rab-GTP to accumulate and GLUT4 vesicles to fuse with the plasma membrane. This pathway is entirely distinct from the insulin/PI3K/Akt/AS160 axis. This is clinically important: in insulin-resistant patients (Type 2 diabetes), where the Akt/AS160 pathway is impaired, the AMPK/TBC1D1 exercise pathway remains functional, explaining why exercise is therapeutic for glucose control even when insulin signaling is defective.'}]},{id:'10.7',title:'High-Yield Clinical Vignettes and Integration Problems',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'This section walks through six high-yield clinical scenarios that require integrating the signaling and metabolic content of the entire chapter. For each scenario, the goal is to identify the primary hormonal disturbance, trace its consequences to specific enzymatic steps, and predict the clinical and laboratory findings.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'VIGNETTE 1: INSULINOMA',x:'A 44-year-old woman has repeated episodes of sweating, confusion, and palpitations that occur after overnight fasting and are relieved by eating. Blood glucose at the time of an episode is 42 mg/dL. Insulin level: 28 uU/mL (elevated, should be near zero with glucose this low). C-peptide: elevated (confirms endogenous insulin production, not exogenous injection). The mechanism: autonomous insulin secretion from a beta cell tumor. Even during fasting, when blood glucose has fallen to 42 mg/dL, the insulinoma continues secreting insulin. The inappropriately high insulin activates the PI3K/Akt axis in liver, muscle, and adipose: hepatic glucose output is suppressed (FOXO remains in the cytoplasm, PEPCK and G6Pase not transcribed; glycogen synthase active, consuming hepatic glucose reserves), muscle and adipose GLUT4 remain on the surface (consuming blood glucose), lipolysis is suppressed (HSL remains phosphorylated off by PDE3B). The result: blood glucose continues to fall despite fasting. Neuroglycopenic symptoms (confusion) and sympathoadrenal symptoms (sweating, palpitations from epinephrine release in response to hypoglycemia) result. KEY LABS: low glucose, high insulin, high C-peptide, low beta-hydroxybutyrate (ketogenesis is suppressed by insulin), low FFA. Treatment: surgical resection; diazoxide (opens KATP channels, preventing beta cell depolarization and insulin secretion) as a bridge.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'VIGNETTE 2: GLUCAGONOMA',x:'A 58-year-old man presents with a characteristic migratory skin rash (necrolytic migratory erythema), weight loss, glucose of 240 mg/dL, low serum amino acids (hypoaminoacidemia), and anemia. Glucagon level is dramatically elevated. The mechanism: autonomous glucagon secretion from an alpha cell tumor drives maximal hepatic gluconeogenesis (CREB-mediated transcription of PEPCK, G6Pase, FBPASE is constitutively on; GNG consumes amino acid substrates, depleting serum amino acids). Simultaneously, glucagon drives lipolysis (ACC off, beta-oxidation on) and glycogenolysis. The hyperglycemia results from both increased hepatic glucose output and glucagon\'s opposition of insulin\'s effects. The skin rash (necrolytic migratory erythema) results from amino acid deficiency (the skin requires amino acids for keratinocyte proliferation; hypoaminoacidemia causes epidermal breakdown). The anemia is normocytic from amino acid depletion impairing erythropoiesis and reduced protein synthesis. KEY LAB: very high plasma glucagon (>500 pg/mL, normal <100). Treatment: octreotide (somatostatin analog that suppresses glucagon secretion via Gi-coupled SSTR receptors); surgical resection.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'VIGNETTE 3: PHEOCHROMOCYTOMA',x:'A 35-year-old woman with episodic severe hypertension, headache, diaphoresis, and palpitations. Between episodes: normal blood pressure and glucose. During an episode: BP 220/130 mmHg, heart rate 130, glucose 320 mg/dL. Urine metanephrines and vanillylmandelic acid (VMA) are markedly elevated. The mechanism: a tumor of adrenal medulla chromaffin cells secreting excess epinephrine and norepinephrine. Cardiovascular effects: epinephrine beta-1 receptor activation (tachycardia, increased cardiac output), norepinephrine alpha-1 receptor activation (peripheral vasoconstriction, hypertension). Metabolic effects: beta-2 activation in liver (cAMP/PKA/glycogenolysis and GNG) and in adipose (HSL activation, massive lipolysis, FFA release); alpha-1 in liver (Gq/IP3/Ca2+/phosphorylase kinase/glycogenolysis). Alpha-2 receptors on beta cells are Gi-coupled and suppress insulin secretion. The combination of maximal glucose mobilization plus minimal insulin secretion produces hyperglycemia. Paradoxically, treatment with a beta-blocker alone could worsen hypertension (by removing beta-2 vasodilatory effects in muscle vasculature, leaving alpha-1 vasoconstriction unopposed); alpha-blockade (phenoxybenzamine, phentolamine) must precede beta-blockade. Diagnosis: 24h urine metanephrines or plasma free metanephrines; CT/MRI of abdomen; MIBG scan for extra-adrenal lesions.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'VIGNETTE 4: FATTY ACID OXIDATION DEFECT (MCAD DEFICIENCY)',x:'A 14-month-old boy is brought to the ED after a 24-hour febrile illness during which he ate poorly. He has lethargy, vomiting, and hypoglycemia (glucose 28 mg/dL). Labs: hypoketotic hypoglycemia (low glucose, low or absent ketones), elevated medium-chain acylcarnitines in plasma, elevated medium-chain dicarboxylic acids in urine. The diagnosis is medium-chain acyl-CoA dehydrogenase (MCAD) deficiency, the most common inherited fatty acid oxidation disorder. The biochemistry: during fasting, when glycogen is depleted, the body must rely on (1) hepatic GNG fueled by beta-oxidation-derived acetyl-CoA and NADH, and (2) ketogenesis to provide fuel for the brain. Both require functional beta-oxidation. In MCAD deficiency, medium-chain acyl-CoAs (C6-C12) accumulate in the mitochondrial matrix and cannot be processed; they are transferred to carnitine (forming acylcarnitines) and exported, or undergo omega-oxidation to dicarboxylic acids (alternative pathway in ER, hence urinary dicarboxylic acids). GNG fails because its mitochondrial support (acetyl-CoA for pyruvate carboxylase allosteric activation, NADH to drive the redox balance) is unavailable. Ketogenesis fails because the acetyl-CoA cannot be generated from medium-chain substrates. The brain runs out of glucose and ketones simultaneously: hypoketotic hypoglycemia. Treatment: frequent feeds (avoid prolonged fasting), carnitine supplementation, IV glucose during illness. Newborn screening by tandem mass spectrometry detects characteristic acylcarnitine profiles.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'VIGNETTE 5: GLYCOGEN STORAGE DISEASE TYPE I (VON GIERKE DISEASE)',x:'A 6-month-old infant with a protuberant abdomen, hepatomegaly, and hypoglycemia after even brief fasting. Labs: severely low blood glucose despite 4-hour fast; elevated lactic acid (4.8 mmol/L); elevated uric acid; elevated triglycerides. The enzyme defect: glucose-6-phosphatase (G6Pase) deficiency. The mechanism: G6P cannot be dephosphorylated to free glucose for export. Hepatic glycogenolysis (driven by glucagon/epinephrine/PKA/phosphorylase) produces G1P, then G6P, but G6P cannot exit the liver. The G6P instead feeds back into glycolysis (producing lactate, causing lactic acidosis) and into the pentose phosphate pathway (producing NADPH, which fuels FA synthesis from excess acetyl-CoA, explaining hypertriglyceridemia). Uric acid rises because the purine salvage pathway is overwhelmed by the increased flux through the pentose phosphate pathway and because lactic acid competes with urate for renal excretion. Hypoglycemia occurs because neither glycogenolysis nor GNG (which produces G6P that also cannot be dephosphorylated) can release glucose into the blood. Treatment: continuous cornstarch feeds (slowly released glucose), avoidance of fasting, and management of lipids and uric acid. GSD Type Ia: G6Pase catalytic subunit deficient. GSD Type Ib: G6P translocase (transport of G6P into the ER lumen for G6Pase access) deficient, also causes neutropenia and inflammatory bowel disease.'},{t:'p',x:'The key to integrating hormonal regulation with metabolic pathways on the MCAT is to always ask three questions when reading a clinical vignette: What is the hormonal state (which hormone is dominant)? What is the target tissue and receptor type? What enzymatic targets are up-regulated or down-regulated as a result? Most MCAT questions about metabolism are disguised versions of these three questions. A patient who cannot produce ketones during fasting despite high glucagon has an enzymatic defect somewhere in the beta-oxidation or ketogenic pathway. A patient with hyperglycemia despite high insulin has a defect in insulin signaling (receptor, IRS-1, PI3K, Akt, or GLUT4). A patient with unexplained hypoglycemia has either too much insulin (insulinoma, exogenous insulin, sulfonylurea overdose) or too little glucagon/cortisol/epinephrine (adrenal insufficiency, panhypopituitarism). Working backward from the metabolic phenotype to the molecular defect is the skill the MCAT tests most heavily.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A 2-year-old child with Von Gierke disease (glucose-6-phosphatase deficiency) is given glucagon IM to treat hypoglycemia. Which of the following best predicts the response?',choices:['A) Blood glucose rises normally because glucagon activates glycogen phosphorylase, releasing glucose from glycogen','B) Blood glucose does not rise because glycogen phosphorylase is absent in Von Gierke disease','C) Blood glucose does not rise because glucagon\'s effect produces glucose-6-phosphate that cannot be dephosphorylated for export, while lactic acid rises further','D) Blood glucose rises and then falls rapidly because G6Pase is only transiently bypassed by glucagon'],answer:2,why:'Glucagon will still activate glycogen phosphorylase via the PKA cascade, and glycogenolysis will proceed normally up to glucose-6-phosphate (G6P). However, G6Pase is the enzyme that converts G6P to free glucose for export. Without G6Pase, G6P cannot be dephosphorylated. It accumulates in the liver, re-enters glycolysis, and is converted to lactate and pyruvate, causing a rise in serum lactate (lactic acidosis worsens). No free glucose is released into the bloodstream. Glucagon injection is therefore ineffective in Von Gierke disease and may worsen the lactic acidosis. This is a clinical test: failure to respond to glucagon with a blood glucose rise, combined with a rise in lactic acid, is diagnostic of a GNG/glycogenolysis export defect at the G6Pase step.'},{stem:'Which finding would best distinguish an insulinoma from factitious hypoglycemia caused by surreptitious exogenous insulin injection?',choices:['A) Blood glucose level during a hypoglycemic episode','B) Plasma insulin level during a hypoglycemic episode','C) Serum C-peptide level during a hypoglycemic episode','D) Urine ketone level during a hypoglycemic episode'],answer:2,why:'C-peptide (connecting peptide) is the fragment cleaved from proinsulin during the processing of endogenous insulin in beta cell secretory granules. It is co-secreted with insulin in equimolar amounts by the beta cell. Exogenous (pharmaceutical) insulin does not contain C-peptide. Therefore: in insulinoma (endogenous autonomous insulin secretion), both insulin AND C-peptide are elevated during hypoglycemia. In factitious hypoglycemia from injected insulin, insulin is elevated but C-peptide is suppressed (the high exogenous insulin feeds back to suppress normal beta cell secretion, lowering endogenous C-peptide). Both conditions have low blood glucose and elevated insulin during episodes, so neither glucose nor insulin alone distinguishes them. Urine ketones would be suppressed in both cases (because insulin is high in both).'}]}],
 bottomLine:'Hormonal regulation is not a separate topic from metabolism: it is the control layer that sits above every metabolic pathway in the book. Insulin acts via a receptor tyrosine kinase (IR/IRS-1/PI3K/PIP3/PDK1/Akt) to drive anabolism: GLUT4 translocation to muscle and adipose, glycogen synthesis (GSK-3 inhibited), protein synthesis (mTOR activated), gluconeogenesis suppressed (FOXO expelled from nucleus), and fatty acid synthesis on with beta-oxidation off (ACC active, malonyl-CoA high, CPT-I blocked). Glucagon and epinephrine both act via Gs-coupled GPCRs to raise cAMP and activate PKA, reversing every insulin effect: glycogenolysis on (phosphorylase kinase and phosphorylase phosphorylated active), glycogen synthesis off (synthase phosphorylated inactive), gluconeogenesis on (F-2,6-BP falls from PFK-2 inactivation, CREB drives PEPCK and G6Pase transcription), beta-oxidation and ketogenesis on (ACC phosphorylated inactive, malonyl-CoA falls, CPT-I active). Epinephrine additionally acts via alpha-1/Gq/PLC/IP3/Ca2+/calmodulin on liver and skeletal muscle to activate glycogenolysis by a cAMP-independent route. Cortisol acts as a nuclear receptor ligand (GR), inducing gluconeogenic gene transcription and muscle proteolysis over hours to days, and provides permissive support for catecholamine signaling by upregulating beta-adrenergic receptors and PNMT. AMPK is the cellular energy sensor that mirrors the fasting hormone response at the cell-autonomous level, activated by rising AMP/ADP, and turned on by exercise and metformin. The fed-to-starved transition follows a predictable order: hepatic glycogenolysis first (0-18 hours), then GNG from lactate, alanine, and glycerol (18-72 hours), then ketone-adapted starvation (>72 hours, ketones cover 60-70% of brain fuel, muscle proteolysis slows). RBCs and renal medulla are obligate glycolytic tissues that always require glucose. DKA (Type 1 diabetes, absent insulin) produces high anion gap metabolic acidosis from ketoacid accumulation; HHS (Type 2, some residual insulin) produces extreme hyperglycemia with hyperosmolarity but minimal ketosis. Every clinical vignette about fuel metabolism resolves to: identify the hormonal imbalance, trace its signal cascade, identify the enzymatic consequences, and predict the lab findings.',
 nextHint:'Chapter 11 applies these regulatory principles to nucleotide metabolism: the synthesis of purines and pyrimidines is controlled by the same energy-sensing mechanisms (AMPK, mTOR) and depends on the folate/B12 one-carbon chemistry from Chapter 9.',
},
{
 n:11,
 title:'DNA Structure, Replication, and Repair',
 subtitle:'How genetic information is stored in the double helix, copied with extraordinary fidelity, and defended against a constant assault of chemical damage',
 tag:'Information',
 foundational:'Every downstream process in molecular biology, transcription, translation, epigenetic regulation, and cancer biology, depends on the physical properties of the DNA molecule established here. Understand the helix architecture, the replication machinery, and the repair pathways at the mechanism level, and drug mechanisms from fluoroquinolones to temozolomide become logical consequences rather than isolated facts.',
 buildsOn:'Ch 8 (nucleotides and nucleotide synthesis) for base structures and the purine/pyrimidine chemistry; Ch 1 (protein structure) for histone modification logic and polymerase active-site geometry.',
 setsUp:'Ch 12 (RNA synthesis and processing) and Ch 13 (translation) depend on the replicated, intact genome established here. Cancer biology throughout clinical medicine depends on the mutation and repair mechanisms covered in Section 11.4 and 11.5.',
 objectives:['Describe the geometry of B-DNA including helix handedness, base pairs per turn, rise per base pair, and the functional differences between the major and minor grooves','Apply Chargaff rules and anti-parallel strand polarity to predict base composition and strand orientation','Trace the hierarchy of DNA compaction from naked DNA through nucleosome, 30 nm fiber, loop domains, and metaphase chromosome','Explain how histone acetylation, methylation, phosphorylation, and ubiquitination alter chromatin structure and gene expression','Distinguish Type I from Type II topoisomerases by mechanism, ATP requirement, and drug targets including camptothecin, etoposide, and fluoroquinolones','Explain the Meselson-Stahl experiment and what it proved about replication mode','Compare prokaryotic and eukaryotic replication initiation, identifying the key proteins at each stage from origin recognition through primer synthesis','Describe the roles of Pol epsilon, Pol delta, PCNA, RFC, and primase at the replication fork, distinguishing leading from lagging strand synthesis','Explain the end-replication problem and how telomerase solves it, and connect telomerase activity to cell senescence and cancer','Compare DNA polymerases alpha, beta, delta, epsilon, gamma, and the translesion polymerases by function, fidelity, and proofreading capacity','Trace the sequential steps of base excision repair, nucleotide excision repair, mismatch repair, homologous recombination, and NHEJ, identifying the key proteins and the lesions each pathway handles','Connect repair pathway defects to clinical disease: xeroderma pigmentosum, Lynch syndrome, BRCA1/2-associated cancers, and glioblastoma response to temozolomide','Classify mutations as transitions, transversions, silent, missense, nonsense, frameshift, or chromosomal, and predict the consequence of each type','Explain the molecular mechanism of trinucleotide repeat expansion diseases including Huntington disease, Fragile X syndrome, and myotonic dystrophy'],
 opener:'Every time a cell divides, it must copy approximately 3 billion base pairs of DNA with an error rate that averages less than one mistake per cell division. That achievement is not passive. It requires a molecular machine that recognizes a specific starting point, unwinds a tightly packaged helix, synthesizes two new strands simultaneously from two templates, removes the RNA primers it used to start synthesis, and proofreads every base it just added. It requires a second layer of quality control that scans the freshly replicated DNA for mismatches the polymerase missed. And it requires a constant, ongoing repair operation that fixes damage inflicted by ultraviolet light, oxidative stress, alkylating chemicals, and the chemistry of water itself.\n\nThis chapter covers the physical structure of the double helix, the machinery of DNA replication, and the five major repair pathways that keep the genome intact. It also connects these mechanisms to the clinical consequences of their failure: the UV hypersensitivity of xeroderma pigmentosum, the microsatellite instability of Lynch syndrome, the homologous recombination defect in BRCA1/2-mutant cancers, and the Philadelphia chromosome translocation that drives chronic myeloid leukemia.\n\nThe same thread runs through all of it: the structure of DNA is not merely a fact to memorize. It is the physical basis that makes every mechanism in this chapter either possible or necessary. Learn the geometry first, then every protein, every pathway, and every disease follows from it.',
 pinnedDisc:{t:'LEADING STRAND vs LAGGING STRAND',x:'At the replication fork, both new strands are synthesized 5 prime to 3 prime by DNA polymerase. The leading strand is synthesized continuously in the same direction the fork moves, using Pol epsilon and only a single primer. The lagging strand is synthesized in fragments (Okazaki fragments, each 150-200 nt in eukaryotes) in the direction opposite fork movement, so each fragment needs its own RNA primer. Pol alpha synthesizes the primer; Pol delta then extends it. FEN1 and RNaseH1 remove the RNA primer; Pol delta fills the gap; DNA ligase seals the nick. PCNA (the sliding clamp) tethers both Pol delta and Pol epsilon to the template to maintain processivity. On the MCAT: the lagging strand requires more enzymatic steps, uses Pol delta, and has multiple primers. The leading strand uses Pol epsilon and one primer.'},
 sections:[{id:'11.1',num:'11.1',title:'11.1 DNA Structure: The Double Helix',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'The Watson-Crick B-form double helix is the predominant conformation of DNA in cells. It is a right-handed helix: if you hold the helix with your right thumb pointing upward, your fingers curl in the direction of the turn. Each complete turn of the helix spans 3.4 nanometers along the helical axis (the rise per turn) and contains 10 base pairs, so each base pair contributes 0.34 nanometers (3.4 angstroms) of rise. The helix diameter is approximately 2 nanometers. These numbers appear directly on the MCAT and should be automatic: 10 bp/turn, 3.4 nm/turn, 0.34 nm/bp.'},{t:'p',x:'The sugar-phosphate backbone of each strand runs along the outside of the helix, where it is exposed to the aqueous environment. The negatively charged phosphate groups at physiological pH are why DNA is a polyanion, why histones (rich in lysine and arginine) bind it electrostatically, and why divalent cations like Mg2+ are required as cofactors for many nucleic acid enzymes. The bases stack on the interior, shielded from water by both the sugar-phosphate walls and by pi-pi stacking interactions between adjacent bases that contribute significantly to helix stability.'},{t:'box',kind:'why',label:'WHY STACKING IS AS IMPORTANT AS HYDROGEN BONDING FOR HELIX STABILITY',x:'Students often assume the Watson-Crick hydrogen bonds between complementary bases are the primary stabilizing force for the double helix. Thermodynamic analyses show otherwise. Base stacking, the van der Waals and electrostatic interactions between the flat aromatic rings of adjacent bases along the same strand, contributes roughly as much to overall helix stability as the hydrogen bonds between strands. This is why GC-rich regions are more stable than AT-rich regions: not just because GC pairs form three hydrogen bonds instead of two, but also because the purine-pyrimidine stacking geometry in GC-rich sequences is more favorable. The implication: melting temperature (Tm) increases with GC content for both reasons simultaneously, and denaturation treatments must overcome stacking as well as hydrogen bonding.'},{t:'p',x:'The two grooves of the double helix arise from the geometry of base stacking. The major groove is wide (approximately 22 angstroms) and deep, exposing the edges of the base pairs to the solvent. The chemical information encoded in the major groove, the distinctive pattern of hydrogen bond donors, acceptors, and hydrophobic methyl groups presented by each base pair, is rich enough that transcription factors, restriction enzymes, and many DNA-binding drugs can read the DNA sequence without unwinding the helix. The minor groove is narrow (approximately 12 angstroms) and shallow. It also contains sequence-specific information, though less than the major groove. Several important molecules bind preferentially in the minor groove: netropsin and distamycin (AT-rich minor groove binders used in research), DAPI and Hoechst dyes (fluorescent AT-minor groove binders), and some transcription repressors. The minor groove also narrows further at AT-rich sequences, enhancing binding selectivity for minor groove ligands.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'MAJOR vs MINOR GROOVE',x:'MAJOR GROOVE: wide (~22 angstroms), deep, accessible to transcription factors, restriction enzymes, zinc fingers, helix-turn-helix proteins, and some drugs; contains more chemical information for sequence-specific recognition. MINOR GROOVE: narrow (~12 angstroms), shallow; binding site for netropsin, distamycin (AT-specific minor groove binders that inhibit transcription), DAPI and Hoechst dyes (AT-selective, used in microscopy), and some gene-silencing repressors. Clinical note: several anthracycline antibiotics (doxorubicin) intercalate between base pairs, fitting into the helix and distorting both grooves, which inhibits topoisomerase II and blocks transcription.'},{t:'p',x:'Base pairing follows strict Watson-Crick complementarity. Adenine pairs with thymine via two hydrogen bonds; the donor-acceptor pattern from A to T is N6(H)...O4 and N1...N3(H). Guanine pairs with cytosine via three hydrogen bonds; the donor-acceptor pattern is N1(H)...N3, O6...N4(H), and N2(H)...O2. Three hydrogen bonds versus two: this is the mechanistic basis for why GC-rich DNA requires higher temperature to denature (higher Tm) and why the G + C fraction of a genome is one measure of its thermal stability. Chargaff rules state that in any double-stranded DNA, the molar amount of adenine equals that of thymine (%A = %T) and the molar amount of guanine equals that of cytosine (%G = %C). Chargaff rules follow directly from complementary base pairing and are violated only in single-stranded nucleic acids. An MCAT question may give you the %A and ask for %C: use %A + %T + %G + %C = 100% and %A = %T, %G = %C to solve.'},{t:'formula',x:'Chargaff rules: %A = %T, %G = %C, therefore %A + %G = %T + %C = 50% of any double-stranded DNA. Melting temperature (Tm) approximation for short oligonucleotides: Tm = 2(A+T) + 4(G+C) in degrees C.'},{t:'p',x:'The two strands of the double helix are antiparallel: one strand runs 5 prime to 3 prime in one direction while the complementary strand runs 5 prime to 3 prime in the opposite direction. This polarity is defined by the phosphodiester backbone: the 5 prime carbon of one deoxyribose is connected to the phosphate group, and the phosphate connects to the 3 prime oxygen of the next deoxyribose. Antiparallel orientation means that the 5 prime end of one strand is at the same end of the helix as the 3 prime end of the other. This matters fundamentally for DNA replication: both new strands must be synthesized 5 prime to 3 prime, but they extend in opposite directions relative to the fork, which is why the lagging strand must be made in discontinuous fragments.'},{t:'p',x:'Besides B-DNA, two other helical forms are encountered on the MCAT. A-DNA is a right-handed helix with 11 base pairs per turn and a shorter, wider appearance than B-DNA; it is the predominant form in DNA-RNA hybrids (as formed during transcription) and in dehydrated DNA. Z-DNA is a left-handed helix with 12 base pairs per turn, forming a characteristic zigzag backbone; it arises in GC-rich sequences under high salt or supercoiling stress and may play a role in transcriptional regulation. For the MCAT, the key distinctions are: B-DNA (right-handed, 10 bp/turn, most common), A-DNA (right-handed, 11 bp/turn, DNA-RNA hybrids), Z-DNA (left-handed, 12 bp/turn, GC-rich sequences).'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'B-DNA HIGH-YIELD NUMBERS',x:'10 base pairs per turn. 3.4 nm (34 angstroms) rise per complete turn. 0.34 nm (3.4 angstroms) per base pair. 2 nm helix diameter. Right-handed helix. Major groove: wide (~22 angstroms), protein recognition. Minor groove: narrow (~12 angstroms), netropsin binding. A=T: 2 hydrogen bonds. G=C: 3 hydrogen bonds. Chargaff: %A=%T, %G=%C. Antiparallel strands: 5 prime to 3 prime convention.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A researcher analyzes a double-stranded DNA sample and finds that adenine constitutes 32% of the bases. What percentage of the total bases is cytosine?',choices:['A) 18%','B) 32%','C) 36%','D) 64%'],answer:0,why:'By Chargaff rules, in double-stranded DNA %A = %T and %G = %C. If %A = 32%, then %T = 32%. Together A + T = 64%, leaving G + C = 36%. Since %G = %C, each is 18%. Cytosine = 18%. This is a direct application of the complementary base pairing logic: the total must be 100%, and G-C pairs make up the remainder after accounting for A-T.'},{stem:'A transcription factor protein recognizes and binds a specific 8-base-pair DNA sequence to activate a target gene. Without unwinding the helix, which feature of the double helix does it most likely use to read the sequence?',choices:['A) The minor groove, because it presents hydrogen bond donors and acceptors specific to each base pair','B) The major groove, because it is wide and exposes chemical information unique to each base pair','C) The sugar-phosphate backbone, because each base pair has a distinctive phosphate spacing','D) The minor groove, because it is the binding site for all sequence-specific transcription factors'],answer:1,why:'The major groove is wide and deep, exposing the edges of the base pairs to solvent. Each of the four Watson-Crick base pairs (AT, TA, GC, CG) presents a unique pattern of hydrogen bond donors, acceptors, and hydrophobic contacts (such as the 5-methyl group of thymine) in the major groove. Transcription factors, restriction enzymes, and most sequence-specific DNA-binding proteins read this pattern in the major groove. The minor groove is narrower and presents less chemical diversity, though it is the site for netropsin and DAPI binding.'}]},{id:'11.2',num:'11.2',title:'11.2 DNA Compaction: Nucleosomes, Chromatin, and Histone Modifications',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'The human genome contains approximately 3.2 billion base pairs, which as naked B-DNA would extend roughly 2 meters end to end. This must be packaged into a nucleus approximately 6 micrometers in diameter, a compaction ratio of more than 10,000-fold. The solution is hierarchical packaging that operates on at least four structural scales: the nucleosome (the basic repeating unit), the 30 nm fiber, loop domains anchored to the nuclear scaffold, and the fully condensed metaphase chromosome.'},{t:'p',x:'The nucleosome is the fundamental unit of chromatin. Its core consists of an octamer of histone proteins: two copies each of H2A, H2B, H3, and H4. Around this protein spool, 147 base pairs of DNA are wrapped 1.65 times in a left-handed superhelical path. This wrapping compacts DNA approximately 6-fold at the nucleosome level. Between adjacent nucleosome cores runs the linker DNA (approximately 10 to 80 bp depending on cell type and species), giving chromatin the appearance of beads on a string in electron micrographs when nucleosomes are not further compacted. Histone H1 (the linker histone) binds at the points where DNA enters and exits the nucleosome core, sealing the wrapped DNA and facilitating higher-order compaction. H1 is not part of the octamer core and is not present in the same stoichiometry as the core histones.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'NUCLEOSOME COMPOSITION',x:'Core octamer: (H2A-H2B)-(H3-H4)2-(H2A-H2B), meaning one H3-H4 tetramer flanked by two H2A-H2B dimers. Each core histone contributes one copy to the octamer, giving two copies of each. H1 (linker histone): NOT part of the octamer; binds the exit/entry DNA; stabilizes the 30 nm fiber. Memory aid: the four core histones are H2A, H2B, H3, H4 (no H1, no H5). DNA wrapped: 147 bp per nucleosome core, 1.65 turns, left-handed. MCAT trap: students confuse H1 as part of the octamer. It is NOT. The octamer has 8 proteins, two of each core histone.'},{t:'p',x:'The N-terminal tails of each core histone project out from the nucleosome surface and are the targets of an elaborate system of post-translational modifications that govern chromatin accessibility and gene expression. The most important modifications for the MCAT are acetylation and methylation, but phosphorylation and ubiquitination are also high-yield.'},{t:'p',x:'Histone acetylation is placed on lysine residues (primarily in H3 and H4 tails) by histone acetyltransferases (HATs) and removed by histone deacetylases (HDACs). Mechanistically, acetylation adds an acetyl group to the epsilon-amino group of lysine, converting the positively charged side chain (pKa ~10.5, essentially always +1 at physiological pH) to a neutral acetamide. This charge neutralization reduces the electrostatic attraction between the histone tail and the negatively charged DNA phosphate backbone. The result is a more open chromatin structure (euchromatin) that is accessible to transcription machinery. Hyperacetylation of histones is generally associated with active transcription. HDAC inhibitors (vorinostat, romidepsin) are used clinically in certain T-cell lymphomas because blocking deacetylation leaves histones in the acetylated state, re-activating tumor suppressor genes that had been silenced.'},{t:'p',x:'Histone methylation is placed on lysine or arginine residues by histone methyltransferases (HMTs) and removed by histone demethylases. Unlike acetylation, methylation does not change the charge of the lysine residue (methylated lysine retains its positive charge). Instead, methylation creates a docking surface recognized by specific reader proteins that either activate or repress transcription depending on which residue is methylated and how many methyl groups are added (mono, di, or trimethyl). H3K4me3 (trimethylation of histone H3 at lysine 4) marks active gene promoters. H3K27me3 (trimethylation of histone H3 at lysine 27) is placed by the Polycomb repressor complex and marks transcriptionally silenced genes. H3K9me3 marks constitutive heterochromatin (permanently silenced repetitive sequences and centromeric DNA). EZH2, the HMT subunit of PRC2 that places H3K27me3, is overexpressed in several cancers and is a therapeutic target.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'EPIGENETIC INHERITANCE AND HISTONE CODE',x:'Histone modifications are heritable through cell division because histone-modifying enzymes recognize existing marks on the parental nucleosome and re-establish those marks on newly deposited histones after replication. This epigenetic inheritance allows a cell to pass its gene expression pattern to daughter cells without any change in the DNA sequence itself. HDAC inhibitors are used in cancer because tumor suppressor genes are frequently silenced by aberrant histone deacetylation and promoter hypermethylation. Restoring acetylation reactivates these genes. DNA methylation (of cytosine in CpG dinucleotides by DNMT enzymes) works in parallel with histone modifications: promoter CpG island methylation recruits methyl-CpG binding proteins that recruit HDACs, coupling DNA methylation to histone deacetylation and creating a stable, heritable silenced state. This is distinct from histone methylation, which acts via reader proteins, not methyl-binding proteins.'},{t:'p',x:'Histone H3 phosphorylation at serine 10 (H3S10ph) is catalyzed by Aurora B kinase during mitosis and is a marker of mitotic chromatin condensation. It is used as a laboratory marker for cells in mitosis. Histone H2A ubiquitination at K119 is placed by PRC1 and contributes to Polycomb-mediated gene silencing. H2B monoubiquitination at K120 is placed by RNF20/40 and promotes transcription elongation. Ubiquitination of histones affects their interactions with other chromatin-associated proteins and can signal for nucleosome remodeling.'},{t:'p',x:'Above the nucleosome level, the 30 nm fiber forms when H1-stabilized nucleosomes fold into a compact helical arrangement. The exact structure of the 30 nm fiber is still debated, but it provides a further ~6-fold compaction. Loop domains are large loops of 30 nm fiber (each containing approximately 40,000 to 100,000 bp) anchored at their bases to a protein scaffold composed of topoisomerase II and SMC proteins (structural maintenance of chromosomes, including cohesin and condensin). These loops give the interphase nucleus its territorial organization and allow local regulation of large chromosomal domains. Further compaction during cell division involves condensin-driven helical coiling of the loop-scaffold structure into the 300 nm fiber and ultimately the 700 nm condensed metaphase chromosome, where the DNA is packaged too tightly for transcription.'},{t:'p',x:'Topoisomerases are enzymes that solve the topological problems created by the double helix. Because DNA is a covalently closed, double-stranded circle in bacteria (or a very long constrained loop in eukaryotes), unwinding the helix at one point for replication or transcription over-winds (positive supercoiling) the DNA ahead of the moving machinery. Without relief, this supercoiling builds until it physically blocks further unwinding. Type I topoisomerases relieve supercoiling by transiently cutting one strand, allowing the other strand to rotate around the remaining backbone, and resealing the nick. They require no ATP (the energy of the broken phosphodiester bond is conserved as a covalent enzyme-DNA intermediate via a tyrosine residue). Type II topoisomerases relieve supercoiling by transiently cutting both strands simultaneously, passing another double-stranded DNA segment through the break, and resealing. They use ATP and can both relax supercoils and decatenate (disentangle) two circular DNA molecules that have been interlocked during replication.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'TYPE I vs TYPE II TOPOISOMERASE',x:'TYPE I: cuts ONE strand; no ATP required; changes linking number by 1 per catalytic cycle; relieves supercoiling; cannot decatenate; inhibitors: camptothecin (CPT), topotecan, irinotecan (stabilize the cleavage complex, trapping Topo I covalently attached to nicked DNA, which becomes a lethal DSB when the replication fork collides with it; used as anticancer drugs). TYPE II: cuts BOTH strands simultaneously; requires ATP; changes linking number by 2 per catalytic cycle; relieves supercoiling AND decatenates interlocked circles; inhibitors: etoposide, teniposide (stabilize eukaryotic Topo II cleavage complex, used in cancer therapy); fluoroquinolones (ciprofloxacin, levofloxacin) specifically inhibit bacterial DNA gyrase and Topo IV (both Type II enzymes) with much higher affinity than human Topo II. Bacterial DNA gyrase introduces negative supercoils (unique to bacteria), relieving tension ahead of the replication fork.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'Histone acetylation by HAT enzymes promotes transcription primarily by which mechanism?',choices:['A) Adding bulky acetyl groups that physically separate DNA strands and expose the template','B) Neutralizing the positive charge on lysine residues, reducing DNA-histone electrostatic attraction and opening chromatin','C) Creating methylation marks recognized by reader proteins that recruit RNA polymerase','D) Phosphorylating H3 at serine 10, triggering nucleosome eviction'],answer:1,why:'Histone acetyltransferases add acetyl groups to the epsilon-amino group of lysine residues on histone tails. Lysine at physiological pH carries a positive charge (+1), which attracts the negatively charged DNA phosphate backbone. Acetylation converts -NH3+ to -NH-CO-CH3, neutralizing the charge. This weakens the electrostatic histone-DNA interaction, loosening chromatin into a more accessible euchromatic state where transcription factors and RNA polymerase can bind. Methylation of histones does not change the charge; it creates reader protein docking sites. H3S10 phosphorylation is associated with mitosis, not transcription activation.'},{stem:'Camptothecin (CPT) is an anticancer drug that traps topoisomerase I in a covalent complex with nicked DNA. What is the mechanism by which this kills rapidly dividing cancer cells preferentially?',choices:['A) It prevents negative supercoil introduction ahead of the replication fork, stalling helicase','B) When the replication fork collides with the trapped cleavage complex, the nick becomes a double-strand break, triggering lethal DNA damage','C) It blocks both strands simultaneously, preventing decatenation of sister chromatids after replication','D) It hyperacetylates histones near the replication fork, causing premature chromatin condensation'],answer:1,why:'Topoisomerase I normally cuts one strand, allows rotation, and reseals the nick. Camptothecin traps the enzyme covalently attached to the 3 prime end of the cut strand. In non-replicating DNA, this is tolerated if repair occurs before the drug dissociates. However, when a replication fork encounters the stalled, covalently trapped Topo I-DNA complex, the collision converts the single-strand nick into a double-strand break, which triggers apoptosis if unrepaired. Rapidly dividing cells (cancer cells) replicate DNA more frequently, so they collide with trapped complexes more often, explaining the preferential toxicity. Fluoroquinolones target bacterial gyrase (a Type II enzyme that introduces negative supercoils), not Topo I.'}]},{id:'11.3',num:'11.3',title:'11.3 DNA Replication: Initiation and Fork Assembly',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'DNA replication is semi-conservative: each daughter cell receives one parental strand and one newly synthesized strand. The Meselson-Stahl experiment (1958) proved this by growing E. coli in medium containing the heavy nitrogen isotope 15N until all DNA was heavy-labeled (15N/15N), then switching to 14N medium and collecting DNA at each subsequent generation. DNA was separated by density-gradient ultracentrifugation in cesium chloride (CsCl). After one generation, all DNA appeared at an intermediate density (hybrid 15N/14N). After two generations, DNA appeared in two bands: one at hybrid density and one at light density (14N/14N). This result is consistent only with semi-conservative replication. Conservative replication would have produced one heavy and one light band after generation one. Dispersive replication would have produced one band of increasingly lighter intermediate density at every generation.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'MESELSON-STAHL: THE THREE MODELS',x:'SEMI-CONSERVATIVE (actual): each strand serves as template; daughter molecules each contain one old + one new strand. After 1 gen: all hybrid (15N/14N). After 2 gen: 50% hybrid + 50% light. CONSERVATIVE (rejected): the original double helix remains intact; an entirely new double helix is made. After 1 gen: 50% heavy + 50% light. After 2 gen: 25% heavy + 75% light. DISPERSIVE (rejected): both strands of both daughters contain fragments of old and new interspersed. After 1 gen: all intermediate (but lighter than hybrid). After 2 gen: all intermediate (even lighter). The experiment definitively ruled out conservative (which would show two bands after one generation) and dispersive (which would never show the sharp band separation seen in the actual data).'},{t:'p',x:'In prokaryotes (using E. coli as the model), replication initiates at a single origin of replication called oriC (approximately 245 bp). The initiator protein DnaA (an AAA-ATPase) binds specific 9-mer repeats (DnaA boxes) within oriC and also binds an AT-rich DNA unwinding element. The energy from DnaA-ATP binding drives local strand separation at the AT-rich region (A-T pairs are easier to separate because they form only 2 hydrogen bonds rather than 3). The DnaB helicase (the actual ring-shaped motor that unwinds the helix) is then loaded onto the exposed single-stranded DNA by the loader protein DnaC (also an AAA-ATPase). DnaB uses ATP hydrolysis to translocate in the 5 prime to 3 prime direction along the lagging-strand template, unwinding the helix at approximately 1,000 base pairs per second. Two DnaB helicases load at oriC, one on each strand, establishing bidirectional replication.'},{t:'p',x:'Single-stranded DNA-binding proteins (SSB in prokaryotes, RPA in eukaryotes) coat the exposed single-stranded template behind the helicase. SSB/RPA serve two functions: they prevent the single-stranded regions from re-annealing, and they prevent single-stranded DNA from adopting secondary structures (hairpins) that would block the polymerase. SSB binding is cooperative: once a few SSB tetramers bind, additional tetramers bind adjacent single-stranded DNA with higher affinity. Primase (DnaG in E. coli) then synthesizes a short RNA primer (approximately 10 to 12 nucleotides) by base-pairing with the template and extending from the first nucleotide without requiring a free 3 prime hydroxyl. This primer provides the 3 prime-OH that DNA polymerase III (the main replicative polymerase in E. coli) needs to begin DNA synthesis.'},{t:'p',x:'In eukaryotes, replication initiates at multiple origins simultaneously. Human cells have approximately 30,000 to 50,000 replication origins, clustered in replication timing domains that fire at different points during S phase (early-replicating domains tend to be euchromatic and gene-rich; late-replicating domains tend to be heterochromatic). Origins are defined by ARS (autonomously replicating sequence) elements in yeast (the model system). Origins are licensed for replication in G1 phase by loading the pre-replication complex. The origin recognition complex (ORC, six subunits) binds the origin throughout the cell cycle and recruits Cdc6 and Cdt1, which load the MCM2-7 hexameric helicase (the eukaryotic equivalent of DnaB) onto double-stranded DNA in an inactive, double-hexamer form.'},{t:'p',x:'Origin firing, the activation of a pre-replication complex to begin synthesis, requires two kinases: CDC7-Dbf4 (DDK, Dbf4-dependent kinase) phosphorylates MCM subunits, and S-phase CDK (cyclin E-CDK2 in early S phase, cyclin A-CDK2 in late S phase) phosphorylates the firing factors Sld2 and Sld3, which recruit GINS and Cdc45 to the MCM helicase. The CMG complex (Cdc45-MCM-GINS) is the active eukaryotic helicase that unwinds the double helix. RPA (replication protein A, the eukaryotic SSB) then coats the single strands. Primase activity in eukaryotes is supplied by Pol alpha, which carries both a primase subunit (synthesizes an ~8-10 nt RNA primer) and a DNA polymerase subunit (extends the primer by about 20 additional deoxyribonucleotides before being displaced).'},{t:'p',x:'After Pol alpha has synthesized the initial primer-template, the clamp loader RFC (replication factor C) loads the sliding clamp PCNA (proliferating cell nuclear antigen) onto the primer-template junction. PCNA is a homotrimeric ring that encircles the DNA double helix and tethers the replicative polymerases to the template, increasing their processivity from tens of nucleotides (without the clamp) to thousands or tens of thousands. Pol epsilon is then recruited to the leading strand template, where it synthesizes continuously in the direction of fork movement. Pol delta is recruited to the lagging strand template, where it synthesizes each Okazaki fragment (approximately 150-200 nucleotides in eukaryotes) starting from each new primer laid down by Pol alpha. The leading strand therefore needs only a single primer (or one per origin), while the lagging strand needs one primer per Okazaki fragment.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'EUKARYOTIC REPLICATION FORK PROTEINS',x:'ORC (origin recognition complex): marks origins, recruits licensing factors throughout cell cycle. MCM2-7: the eukaryotic helicase motor (AAA-ATPase); loaded as a double hexamer; activated by DDK + CDK. GINS + Cdc45: activate MCM and form the CMG (Cdc45-MCM-GINS) active helicase complex. RPA: coats ssDNA to prevent reannealing (eukaryotic SSB equivalent). Pol alpha-primase: synthesizes the RNA primer and extends it ~20 nt; no proofreading. RFC (clamp loader): loads PCNA onto primer-template junctions using ATP hydrolysis. PCNA (sliding clamp): homotrimeric ring that encircles DNA; tethers Pol epsilon and Pol delta; increases processivity; ubiquitinated at K164 to recruit translesion polymerases when a lesion is encountered. Pol epsilon: leading strand synthesis; high fidelity; 3 prime to 5 prime proofreading exonuclease. Pol delta: lagging strand Okazaki fragment synthesis; 3 prime to 5 prime proofreading exonuclease; also fills in gaps after primer removal and participates in repair synthesis.'},{t:'p',x:'The end-replication problem arises from an inherent limitation of DNA polymerase: it cannot synthesize DNA in the 3 prime to 5 prime direction and cannot initiate a new chain without a primer. On the lagging strand, the RNA primer for the most terminal Okazaki fragment is positioned at the very 5 prime end of the linear chromosome. When this primer is removed, no upstream sequence exists from which a new primer can be placed to fill the gap. The result is progressive shortening of the lagging strand with each round of replication, which translates to progressive shortening of both chromosome ends. In human somatic cells, telomeres (the repetitive TTAGGG hexanucleotide sequences at chromosome ends, typically 5-15 kb in length) serve as a sacrificial buffer, being shortened with each division rather than coding sequences. When telomeres reach a critical minimum length (~3-5 kb), the cell undergoes either permanent cell cycle arrest (replicative senescence) or apoptosis. This Hayflick limit of approximately 50 to 70 divisions in primary human cells is partly explained by telomere shortening.'},{t:'p',x:'Telomerase is the enzyme that counteracts the end-replication problem. It is a specialized reverse transcriptase consisting of TERT (telomerase reverse transcriptase, the catalytic protein subunit) and TERC (telomerase RNA component, which contains an 11-nucleotide template sequence 3 prime-AAUCCC-5 prime that is complementary to the TTAGGG telomeric repeat). Telomerase extends the 3 prime overhang of the G-rich lagging strand template by using TERC as an internal RNA template: TERC hybridizes to the single-stranded 3 prime overhang, TERT synthesizes new TTAGGG repeats, then telomerase translocates and repeats. After TERT has extended the 3 prime end, conventional primase-polymerase synthesis fills in the complementary strand (leaving the terminal 3 prime overhang as a T-loop structure that protects the end from being recognized as a double-strand break). Telomerase is active in germ cells and adult stem cells, maintaining telomere length through many divisions. In most somatic cells, TERT expression is repressed, and telomeres shorten with each division. In approximately 85-90% of cancer cells, TERT is reactivated (by TERT promoter mutations, chromosomal rearrangements, or amplification), granting replicative immortality. Telomerase activity is a marker of cancer and a potential therapeutic target.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'In the Meselson-Stahl experiment, E. coli grown for many generations in 15N medium are transferred to 14N medium. After TWO generations of growth in 14N medium, how many distinct DNA density bands would be visible on a CsCl gradient?',choices:['A) One band at heavy density (15N/15N)','B) One band at intermediate density (hybrid)','C) Two bands: one at intermediate density and one at light density (14N/14N)','D) Three bands: heavy, intermediate, and light'],answer:2,why:'After one generation in 14N, every DNA molecule has one 15N strand (old) and one 14N strand (new), yielding a single hybrid density band. After two generations, each original 15N/14N hybrid molecule replicates: the 15N strand templates one new 14N strand (producing one more hybrid molecule), and the 14N strand templates one new 14N strand (producing one all-light 14N/14N molecule). The result is 50% hybrid and 50% light DNA, giving two bands. Conservative replication would show only heavy and light bands after generation one, which is not what was observed. Dispersive replication would give one intermediate band of decreasing density at every generation.'},{stem:'PCNA is described as a processivity factor for DNA polymerase. What is the molecular basis of this function?',choices:['A) PCNA provides the 3 prime-OH primer end required to initiate DNA synthesis','B) PCNA is a homotrimeric ring that encircles the DNA duplex and tethers the polymerase, preventing its dissociation from the template','C) PCNA unwinds the double helix ahead of the polymerase using ATP hydrolysis','D) PCNA recruits primase to synthesize RNA primers at each Okazaki fragment'],answer:1,why:'PCNA is a homotrimeric ring-shaped protein that forms a closed circle around the DNA double helix. The polymerase (Pol epsilon or Pol delta) binds to the back face of this ring through a short hydrophobic PCNA-interacting protein (PIP) motif. Because PCNA is topologically linked to the DNA, the polymerase cannot diffuse away from the template without threading through the ring, increasing processivity from tens to thousands of nucleotides per binding event. PCNA is loaded onto the primer-template junction by RFC (the clamp loader), which uses ATP hydrolysis to open the ring and close it around the DNA. Providing the primer 3 prime-OH is the function of primase and Pol alpha. Helicase activity is performed by MCM.'}]},{id:'11.4',num:'11.4',title:'11.4 DNA Polymerase Properties and Replication Fidelity',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'All DNA polymerases share three fundamental properties that follow directly from the chemistry of template-directed synthesis. First, every DNA polymerase requires a primer: a pre-existing oligonucleotide (RNA or DNA) with a free 3 prime hydroxyl group, onto which the polymerase adds new deoxyribonucleotides. Polymerases cannot begin synthesis de novo on a bare template. This is why primase (which CAN initiate de novo) must lay down a short RNA primer before the replicative polymerase takes over. Second, all DNA polymerases synthesize exclusively in the 5 prime to 3 prime direction, adding dNTPs to the growing 3 prime end. The incoming dNTP is attacked by the 3 prime-OH of the last nucleotide in the chain, displacing pyrophosphate (PPi), which is then hydrolyzed by pyrophosphatase to drive the reaction forward thermodynamically. Third, DNA polymerases cannot synthesize in the 3 prime to 5 prime direction; the template is read 3 prime to 5 prime, but synthesis always proceeds 5 prime to 3 prime.'},{t:'p',x:'The eukaryotic DNA polymerases are named by Greek letters, and their functions are distinct. Pol alpha carries a primase subunit and synthesizes the initial RNA primer extended by a short stretch of DNA at every new Okazaki fragment origin and at the leading strand origin. Pol alpha has no proofreading (3 prime to 5 prime exonuclease) activity. Pol delta is the lagging strand polymerase in eukaryotes, extending Okazaki fragments after Pol alpha lays down the primer; it possesses 3 prime to 5 prime proofreading exonuclease activity. Pol epsilon is the leading strand polymerase; it is highly processive with PCNA and has 3 prime to 5 prime proofreading exonuclease activity. Pol delta also participates in DNA repair synthesis (long-patch BER, NER, MMR). Pol gamma is located in mitochondria and replicates the 16.5 kb mitochondrial genome; it has proofreading activity and is inhibited by nucleoside reverse transcriptase inhibitors (NRTIs like zidovudine, stavudine) used in HIV therapy, which is the mechanistic basis of NRTI-associated mitochondrial toxicity. Pol beta is the main short-patch base excision repair polymerase and has NO proofreading exonuclease. Translesion synthesis polymerases (Pol eta, Pol iota, Pol kappa, Rev1) are recruited by ubiquitinated PCNA when the replicative polymerase stalls at a lesion; they can incorporate nucleotides across from damaged bases but are highly error-prone and have no proofreading.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'EUKARYOTIC DNA POLYMERASES',x:'Pol alpha: primase + DNA pol; starts replication at origins and each Okazaki fragment; NO proofreading; low fidelity. Pol delta: lagging strand; proofreading (3 prime to 5 prime exo); PCNA-dependent; also used in repair. Pol epsilon: leading strand; proofreading; PCNA-dependent; highest fidelity among replicative pols. Pol gamma: mitochondrial; proofreading; target of NRTI-related mitochondrial toxicity. Pol beta: short-patch BER; NO proofreading; fills single nucleotide gap. Translesion pols (eta, iota, kappa): bypass DNA lesions; no proofreading; error-prone; recruited by monoubiquitinated PCNA at K164.'},{t:'p',x:'The accuracy of DNA replication is achieved in three successive stages, each reducing the error rate by roughly two orders of magnitude. At the nucleotide selection stage, the geometry of the polymerase active site provides an initial discrimination of approximately 10,000-fold against incorrect base pairing: the active site closes around a correct Watson-Crick base pair but remains partially open with a mismatched pair, slowing the chemical step of phosphodiester bond formation. This intrinsic fidelity yields approximately one error per 100,000 nucleotides incorporated (10^-5). The 3 prime to 5 prime exonuclease (proofreading) activity of the replicative polymerases then monitors the last incorporated base; a mismatched 3 prime terminus activates the exonuclease by causing the 3 prime end to transfer from the polymerase active site to the exonuclease active site, where the mismatched nucleotide is excised and the polymerase can try again. Proofreading reduces the error rate by an additional 100-fold, to approximately 10^-7. Mismatch repair (see Section 11.5) then catches the remaining errors during or shortly after replication, reducing the overall error rate to approximately 10^-9 to 10^-10, equivalent to about one error per cell division in the human genome.'},{t:'formula',x:'Error rates: Before proofreading: ~1 per 10^5 (intrinsic polymerase selectivity). After 3 prime to 5 prime proofreading: ~1 per 10^7. After mismatch repair: ~1 per 10^9 to 10^10.'},{t:'p',x:'In prokaryotes, Pol I (DNA polymerase I of E. coli) performs a function not needed in eukaryotes: the 5 prime to 3 prime exonuclease activity that removes the RNA primer of each Okazaki fragment while simultaneously filling in with new DNA (nick translation). The 5 prime to 3 prime exonuclease of Pol I is distinct from the 3 prime to 5 prime proofreading exonuclease. It cleaves nucleotides from the 5 prime end of the RNA primer while extending from the upstream 3 prime end, effectively translating the nick 5 prime to 3 prime along the lagging strand. DNA ligase then seals the final nick. In eukaryotes, the RNA primer of each Okazaki fragment is removed by the combined action of RNaseH1 (degrades the RNA of RNA-DNA hybrids) and FEN1 (a flap endonuclease that cleaves the displaced RNA flap structure after Pol delta has displaced it). Pol delta then fills any remaining gap, and DNA ligase I seals the nick using ATP (bacterial DNA ligase uses NAD+).'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'PCNA UBIQUITINATION AND TRANSLESION SYNTHESIS',x:'When Pol delta or Pol epsilon encounters a lesion that blocks normal synthesis (for example, a pyrimidine dimer or an AP site), it stalls. Stalling activates the RAD6-RAD18 ubiquitin ligase complex, which monoubiquitinates PCNA at lysine 164 (K164). Monoubiquitinated PCNA at K164 acts as a recruiting signal for translesion synthesis (TLS) polymerases: Pol eta, Pol iota, Pol kappa, and Rev1. These polymerases have spacious, flexible active sites that accommodate damaged templates but lack the tight geometric constraints that provide selectivity, so they are error-prone. Pol eta (mutated in the variant form of xeroderma pigmentosum, XPV) is the most clinically relevant TLS polymerase: it efficiently and accurately inserts two adenines across from a cis-syn cyclobutane pyrimidine dimer (CPD), the most common UV-induced lesion. Patients with XPV lack functional Pol eta, so another TLS polymerase (less accurate) handles CPDs, causing elevated UV-induced mutagenesis.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A newly developed antiviral drug inhibits the mitochondrial DNA polymerase gamma (Pol gamma) as a side effect. Which clinical finding would most likely develop with long-term use?',choices:['A) Megaloblastic anemia from impaired thymidylate synthesis','B) Myopathy with ragged-red fibers from mitochondrial DNA depletion','C) Increased UV-induced skin cancers from impaired translesion synthesis','D) Microsatellite instability in tumor cells from impaired mismatch repair'],answer:1,why:'Pol gamma is the only DNA polymerase that replicates mitochondrial DNA. Inhibition of Pol gamma leads to mitochondrial DNA depletion, impairing synthesis of the 13 mitochondrial-encoded subunits of the electron transport chain and ATP synthase. This manifests as mitochondrial myopathy: muscle weakness, lactic acidosis, and ragged-red fibers on Gomori trichrome stain of muscle biopsy (ragged-red fibers represent mitochondrial accumulations at the subsarcolemmal rim, seen in electron microscopy as abnormal mitochondrial proliferations). This mechanism underlies NRTI-associated myopathy from drugs like stavudine and zidovudine. Megaloblastic anemia is from folate or B12 deficiency. UV cancers result from NER defects. MSI is from mismatch repair defects.'},{stem:'Why must DNA polymerase always use a primer, but RNA polymerase can initiate de novo?',choices:['A) DNA polymerase lacks the 5 prime to 3 prime exonuclease activity needed to remove the first mismatched nucleotide','B) The initiation step (first phosphodiester bond) is thermodynamically unfavorable unless a 3 prime-OH is already present to provide the attacking nucleophile','C) DNA polymerase requires RNA polymerase to first open the double helix before it can begin','D) The proofreading exonuclease of DNA polymerase would immediately excise any single-nucleotide 5 prime terminus formed de novo'],answer:1,why:'The fundamental reason is chemical: forming the very first internucleotide phosphodiester bond of a new chain (the initiation step) is thermodynamically unfavorable compared to extending an existing chain. RNA polymerase active sites are structured to stabilize the pppNpN dinucleotide initiation complex, tolerating the energetic cost. DNA polymerase active sites are optimized for the elongation mode, which has a pre-existing 3 prime-OH as the nucleophile. Without that 3 prime-OH, the transition state geometry for catalysis is not achievable. Evolution has preserved this constraint in DNA polymerases while allowing primases (RNA polymerases) to initiate de novo, because the short RNA primer is later removed and replaced, so the lack of proofreading at initiation is acceptable for the temporary primer.'}]},{id:'11.5',num:'11.5',title:'11.5 DNA Repair Pathways',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'DNA damage is not a rare event. Each human cell sustains approximately 10,000 to 100,000 lesions per day from sources including oxidative damage (superoxide, hydrogen peroxide, hydroxyl radical from mitochondrial electron leak and inflammation), spontaneous hydrolysis (deamination of cytosine to uracil occurs approximately 70-500 times per cell per day; depurination at approximately 5,000-10,000 sites per cell per day), UV radiation (pyrimidine dimers), ionizing radiation (double-strand breaks), and endogenous alkylating reactions (S-adenosylmethionine can spontaneously methylate DNA). Each of the five major repair pathways targets a specific class of lesion.'},{t:'p',x:'Base excision repair (BER) handles small, chemically modified bases that do not significantly distort the helix. The paradigmatic substrate is uracil in DNA, arising from cytosine deamination (which would cause a C to T transition if not repaired) or from misincorporation of dUTP. Step 1: a DNA glycosylase recognizes and removes the damaged base by hydrolyzing the N-glycosidic bond between the base and the deoxyribose, creating an AP site (apurinic/apyrimidinic site, also called an abasic site). Different glycosylases handle different lesions: uracil-DNA glycosylase (UNG) removes uracil; OGG1 removes 8-oxoguanine (a common oxidative lesion that pairs with adenine and causes G to T transversions if unremedied); MYH glycosylase removes adenine mispaired with 8-oxoG. Step 2: AP endonuclease (APE1) nicks the phosphodiester backbone 5 prime to the AP site, creating a one-nucleotide gap with a 3 prime-OH and a 5 prime deoxyribose-phosphate (dRP) residue. Step 3: in short-patch BER (the predominant pathway), Pol beta fills the single nucleotide gap and also uses its intrinsic 5 prime-dRP lyase activity to remove the dRP residue. Step 4: DNA ligase III/XRCC1 seals the nick. In long-patch BER (2 to 10 nucleotides), Pol delta or epsilon displaces the existing strand to create a flap, FEN1 removes the flap, and ligase I seals.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'BASE EXCISION REPAIR STEPS',x:'STEP 1: DNA glycosylase recognizes damaged base, cleaves N-glycosidic bond, leaves AP site. Key glycosylases: UNG (uracil), OGG1 (8-oxoG), MYH (A opposite 8-oxoG), SMUG1 (single-strand uracil). STEP 2: APE1 (AP endonuclease 1) nicks 5 prime to AP site. STEP 3A (short-patch, 1 nt): Pol beta fills gap + uses dRP lyase to remove ribose flap. STEP 4A: Ligase III-XRCC1 seals nick. STEP 3B (long-patch, 2-10 nt): Pol delta/epsilon displaces downstream DNA; FEN1 removes flap. STEP 4B: Ligase I seals nick. KEY CLINICAL NOTE: Pol beta has no proofreading. Methoxyamine (a BER inhibitor) traps the AP site by reacting with the aldehyde form of the AP site, blocking APE1 and sensitizing tumor cells to alkylating agents in clinical trials.'},{t:'p',x:'Nucleotide excision repair (NER) handles bulky lesions that distort the double helix, above all the UV-induced pyrimidine dimers. Two types of pyrimidine dimers form: the cis-syn cyclobutane pyrimidine dimer (CPD), which forms between adjacent thymines (or TC, CC, CT pairs) and is the most abundant UV photoproduct; and the 6-4 photoproduct (6-4PP), which is less abundant but more helix-distorting and more efficiently recognized by NER. Both lesions block RNA polymerase II during transcription and stall DNA polymerase during replication. NER operates in two sub-pathways: global genome NER (GG-NER), which surveys the entire genome, and transcription-coupled NER (TC-NER), which specifically repairs lesions blocking RNA Pol II.'},{t:'p',x:'In GG-NER, the XPC-RAD23B complex (sometimes with DDB1-DDB2 for CPD recognition, which is less helix-distorting and harder to detect) recognizes the helix distortion. In TC-NER, stalled RNA Pol II is detected by CSB (Cockayne syndrome B protein) and CSA (Cockayne syndrome A protein, a DDB1-containing E3 ubiquitin ligase complex), which then recruit the downstream NER machinery. Both pathways converge at the verification and unwinding steps: TFIIH (a multifunctional complex that includes the helicases XPB and XPD, which unwind the helix around the lesion) and XPA (which verifies the presence of the lesion and coordinates assembly) open approximately 25 to 30 base pairs around the lesion. RPA coats the undamaged strand. XPF-ERCC1 makes an incision approximately 15 to 24 nucleotides 5 prime to the lesion; XPG makes an incision approximately 2 to 8 nucleotides 3 prime to the lesion. The 25 to 30 nucleotide oligonucleotide fragment containing the lesion is released. Pol delta or Pol epsilon fills in the gap using the undamaged strand as template (with RFC and PCNA), and ligase seals the nick.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'XERODERMA PIGMENTOSUM AND COCKAYNE SYNDROME',x:'Xeroderma pigmentosum (XP) results from autosomal recessive loss-of-function mutations in any of eight XP genes (XPA through XPG, plus XPV). XPA-G encode NER proteins; mutations cause failure to repair UV-induced pyrimidine dimers in either GG-NER or TC-NER. XPV encodes Pol eta (the TLS polymerase that accurately bypasses CPDs); loss of Pol eta means other error-prone TLS polymerases handle CPDs, causing mutagenesis. Clinical features: extreme photosensitivity (severe sunburn from minimal UV exposure), progressive freckling and pigmentation changes in sun-exposed skin, dramatically elevated incidence of skin cancers (squamous cell, basal cell, and melanoma) with onset in the first decade of life (1,000-fold increased risk), neurological degeneration in some subtypes (XPA, XPB, XPD, XPG). Cockayne syndrome (CS) results from mutations in CSB (most common) or CSA, which are required specifically for TC-NER. CS presents with photosensitivity, progeria-like aging (growth failure, cachexia, dental caries, bird-like facies), severe neurological deterioration (demyelination), but remarkably, NOT an elevated cancer risk, because GG-NER is intact. This distinguishes CS from XP: CS patients age prematurely without a dramatic cancer predisposition.'},{t:'p',x:'Mismatch repair (MMR) corrects errors made by the replicative polymerases that escaped proofreading: single-base mismatches and small insertion-deletion loops (IDLs) that arise when polymerase slips on repetitive sequences (microsatellites). In E. coli, the MutS protein recognizes the mismatch and recruits MutL, which activates the MutH endonuclease. MutH discriminates the newly synthesized (error-containing) strand from the parental template strand by recognizing hemimethylated GATC sites: in E. coli, adenine in GATC is methylated by Dam methylase shortly after replication, so the parental strand is fully methylated and the newly synthesized strand is transiently unmethylated. MutH nicks the unmethylated (new) strand, and an exonuclease degrades from the nick back past the mismatch; Pol III resynthesizes, and ligase seals.'},{t:'p',x:'In eukaryotes, the Dam/MutH system does not exist. Strand discrimination relies instead on the proximity of PCNA (the sliding clamp) and single-strand nicks present in newly replicated lagging-strand DNA. MutS homologs (MSH) recognize mismatches: MSH2-MSH6 (MutSalpha) recognizes single-base mismatches and small IDLs; MSH2-MSH3 (MutSbeta) recognizes larger IDLs. Recruitment of MutL homologs (MLH1-PMS2, the principal MutL complex) activates the latent endonuclease activity of PMS2, which nicks the mismatch-containing strand. Exonuclease 1 (EXO1) then degrades from the nick through the mismatch; RPA coats the single-stranded gap; Pol delta fills in the gap; ligase seals.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'LYNCH SYNDROME AND MICROSATELLITE INSTABILITY',x:'Lynch syndrome (hereditary nonpolyposis colorectal cancer, HNPCC) is the most common inherited predisposition to colorectal cancer, accounting for approximately 3% of all colorectal cancers. It is caused by germline loss-of-function mutations in MMR genes: MLH1 (~40% of cases), MSH2 (~30%), MSH6 (~10%), PMS2 (~5%). Lynch syndrome follows an autosomal dominant pattern with high but incomplete penetrance. The second allele is somatically inactivated in tumor cells (Knudson two-hit model). Loss of MMR dramatically increases the rate of slippage mutations at microsatellites (short tandem repeats throughout the genome), producing a distinctive tumor phenotype called microsatellite instability (MSI-high, or MSI-H). MSI-H tumors: colorectal, endometrial (~60% of endometrial cancers in Lynch syndrome), ovarian, gastric, urinary tract. Testing: Bethesda criteria trigger tumor MSI testing by PCR or MMR immunohistochemistry; MLH1 promoter hypermethylation (in sporadic MSI tumors) versus germline MMR mutation (Lynch syndrome) must be distinguished. MSI-H is predictive of response to immune checkpoint inhibitors (pembrolizumab, nivolumab), because the hypermutator phenotype generates neoantigens that prime cytotoxic T cells.'},{t:'p',x:'Double-strand break (DSB) repair uses two mechanistically distinct pathways. Homologous recombination (HR) is the high-fidelity pathway. It uses the intact sister chromatid (available in S and G2 phases, after DNA replication) as a template. Step 1: the MRN complex (MRE11-RAD50-NBS1) recognizes the DSB and begins 5 prime resection, creating 3 prime single-stranded overhangs. Step 2: RPA coats the 3 prime overhangs. Step 3: BRCA2 loads RAD51 onto the RPA-coated single-stranded DNA, displacing RPA and forming a RAD51 nucleoprotein filament. Step 4: the RAD51 filament performs strand invasion, searching the sister chromatid for homologous sequence and invading the duplex to form a displacement loop (D-loop). Step 5: DNA synthesis extends from the 3 prime end of the invading strand, using the sister chromatid as template. Step 6: resolution of the Holliday junction (or dissolution by the BLM-Topo III alpha complex) restores two intact duplex molecules without mutation. BRCA1 promotes HR by inhibiting the competing NHEJ pathway and by facilitating 5 prime end resection. BRCA1 and BRCA2 mutations therefore impair HR, forcing reliance on the error-prone NHEJ pathway and causing genomic instability, a hallmark of BRCA1/2-mutant cancers.'},{t:'p',x:'Non-homologous end joining (NHEJ) is the faster but more error-prone DSB repair pathway, dominant in G1 phase (when no sister chromatid is available). Ku70/Ku80 heterodimer binds directly to each DSB end, protecting the ends from extensive degradation and serving as a scaffold. The DNA-dependent protein kinase catalytic subunit (DNA-PKcs) is recruited by Ku70/80, forming the DNA-PK holoenzyme. DNA-PKcs autophosphorylates and phosphorylates downstream effectors. The Artemis nuclease (activated by DNA-PKcs) trims the DNA ends to make them compatible for ligation. DNA polymerases mu and lambda perform limited fill-in synthesis across the break. The XRCC4-DNA ligase IV complex seals the joined ends, often with small insertions or deletions at the junction (NHEJ is inherently error-prone). NHEJ is essential not only for repairing radiation-induced DSBs but also for V(D)J recombination (somatic diversification of immunoglobulin and T-cell receptor genes in developing lymphocytes), which requires Ku70/80, DNA-PKcs, Artemis, and XRCC4-ligase IV.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'HR vs NHEJ',x:'HOMOLOGOUS RECOMBINATION: high fidelity; requires sister chromatid (S/G2 phases only); slow; uses RAD51, BRCA1/2, MRN; templates from sister chromatid; no mutations introduced. NHEJ: error-prone (small indels at junction); no template required; dominant in G1 phase; fast; uses Ku70/80, DNA-PKcs, Artemis, XRCC4-Ligase IV; essential for V(D)J recombination. BRCA1 promotes HR and inhibits NHEJ; BRCA1/2 mutations shift cells toward NHEJ. PARP inhibitors (olaparib, rucaparib): PARP1 repairs single-strand breaks; inhibiting PARP traps PARP on DNA, converting SSBs to DSBs; in BRCA1/2-mutant cells (deficient HR), these DSBs cannot be repaired by HR and must use error-prone NHEJ, causing lethal genomic instability (synthetic lethality concept). This is why PARP inhibitors are specifically effective in BRCA-mutant ovarian and breast cancers.'},{t:'p',x:'A clinically important single-step repair mechanism is the direct reversal of O6-methylguanine by MGMT (O6-methylguanine-DNA methyltransferase). Alkylating agents (temozolomide, nitrosoureas, nitrogen mustards) and endogenous S-adenosylmethionine can methylate guanine at the O6 position. O6-methylguanine pairs with thymine rather than cytosine during replication, causing G:C to A:T transitions. MGMT directly transfers the alkyl group from the O6 position of guanine to a cysteine residue in its own active site, restoring the guanine and simultaneously inactivating the MGMT protein (it is a suicidal repair enzyme, consumed in each reaction). MGMT promoter methylation (silencing MGMT expression by epigenetic means) sensitizes tumors to alkylating agents because the tumor cells cannot repair O6-methylguanine. In glioblastoma (GBM), MGMT promoter methylation status is the single most predictive biomarker for response to temozolomide (TMZ) chemotherapy; methylated GBM patients have significantly longer survival with TMZ than unmethylated GBM patients.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A patient is found to carry a germline mutation in MSH2. Over time, a colorectal tumor develops in which the second MSH2 allele is somatically inactivated. Which molecular phenotype would most likely be observed in this tumor?',choices:['A) Large deletions at the TP53 locus due to impaired homologous recombination','B) Microsatellite instability (MSI-high) due to accumulated slippage mutations at short tandem repeats','C) Pyrimidine dimer accumulation at CPD sites due to impaired nucleotide excision repair','D) Loss of H3K27me3 at tumor suppressor promoters due to impaired EZH2 activity'],answer:1,why:'MSH2 encodes a core component of the mismatch repair system (MSH2-MSH6 recognizes single-base mismatches and small IDLs; MSH2-MSH3 recognizes larger IDLs). When MMR is lost, slippage mutations at microsatellite sequences accumulate uncorrected. Microsatellites are short tandem repeats throughout the genome where polymerase slippage is frequent. MMR normally corrects these insertion-deletion loops. Without MMR, microsatellite lengths vary between tumor and normal tissue (microsatellite instability, MSI-high). This MSH2-germline scenario is the classic Lynch syndrome presentation. HR defects affect BRCA1/2 and cause large chromosomal abnormalities. Pyrimidine dimer accumulation is an NER defect (XP). H3K27me3 is an epigenetic mark placed by EZH2, unrelated to MMR.'},{stem:'A BRCA2-mutant ovarian cancer cell line is treated with a PARP inhibitor. The rationale for synthetic lethality in this context is that PARP inhibition causes which type of DNA lesion to accumulate in a cell already deficient in BRCA2-dependent homologous recombination?',choices:['A) Unrepaired pyrimidine dimers that block RNA polymerase','B) Unrepaired double-strand breaks arising from conversion of stalled replication forks at trapped PARP-SSB complexes','C) Extensive microsatellite instability from loss of mismatch repair','D) Accumulated 8-oxoguanine lesions that cause G to T transversions'],answer:1,why:'PARP1 normally detects single-strand breaks (SSBs) and coordinates BER. PARP inhibitors trap PARP1 in a covalent complex at SSBs (similar to how topotecan traps Topo I). When a replication fork encounters this trapped PARP-DNA complex, the SSB is converted to a double-strand break (DSB). In cells with functional BRCA2, these DSBs are repaired by high-fidelity homologous recombination using RAD51. In BRCA2-mutant cells, HR is impaired because BRCA2 is required to load RAD51 onto resected DSB ends. The cells must rely on error-prone NHEJ, leading to accumulating genomic instability and ultimately cell death. This synthetic lethality (two non-lethal defects combining for a lethal outcome) is the basis for the FDA approval of olaparib, rucaparib, and niraparib in BRCA-mutant cancers.'}]},{id:'11.6',num:'11.6',title:'11.6 Mutations: Types, Causes, and Clinical Consequences',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'A mutation is a heritable change in the DNA sequence. Mutations are classified first by their scope (point mutations affecting a single base pair versus gross chromosomal changes affecting large segments) and then, for point mutations, by the nature of the base change and its effect on the encoded protein. Understanding mutation types at the mechanistic level allows prediction of clinical consequences and is heavily tested on both the MCAT and Step 1.'},{t:'p',x:'Point mutations are changes in a single base pair. Transitions are substitutions of one purine for another purine (A to G or G to A) or one pyrimidine for another pyrimidine (C to T or T to C). Because the shape of the base pair is preserved in a transition (purine-pyrimidine geometry), transitions are generally better tolerated by the DNA helix and are more likely to arise from spontaneous deamination (C deaminates to U, causing C to T transitions; 5-methylcytosine deaminates to thymine, a particularly mutagenic event because thymine is a normal base and not recognized by UNG). Transversions are substitutions of a purine for a pyrimidine or vice versa (A or G to C or T, and vice versa). Transversions alter the geometry of the base pair and tend to arise from chemical lesions: oxidative damage (8-oxoG causes G to T transversion), UV light in some contexts, and polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons from tobacco smoke (causing G to T transversions in TP53 in lung cancers). Aflatoxin B1 (a mycotoxin from Aspergillus on stored grains) causes a specific G to T transversion at codon 249 of TP53 (Arg249Ser), which is a mutational signature of hepatocellular carcinoma in aflatoxin-exposed populations.'},{t:'p',x:'The effect of a point mutation on protein function depends on the codon change. A silent (synonymous) mutation changes a codon to a different codon that encodes the same amino acid (due to the degeneracy of the genetic code). Silent mutations have no effect on the protein sequence, though they can affect splicing if they alter splice sites, and can affect translational efficiency if they alter codon usage bias. A missense mutation changes a codon to one encoding a different amino acid (for example, Glu6Val in sickle cell anemia: GAG to GTG, or Gly380Arg in achondroplasia, the most common cause of short-limb dwarfism, caused by a constitutively activating mutation in FGFR3). A conservative missense mutation changes an amino acid to one with similar biochemical properties (for example, one hydrophobic residue to another) and often has a mild phenotype. A nonconservative missense mutation changes an amino acid to one with very different properties and tends to have larger functional effects. A nonsense mutation changes a codon to a premature stop codon (UAA, UAG, or UGA), truncating the protein. Premature stop codons often trigger nonsense-mediated mRNA decay (NMD), destabilizing the mRNA and effectively reducing protein expression to near zero (loss of function).'},{t:'p',x:'A frameshift mutation arises from insertion or deletion of a number of base pairs that is not a multiple of three (since codons are read in triplets, the reading frame is established from the start codon and any non-triplet insertion or deletion shifts all downstream codons). Frameshifts almost always generate a premature stop codon within a short distance downstream of the mutation (because one in three codons in a random sequence is a stop codon when the reading frame is shifted). The resulting truncated protein typically has no normal function and may be degraded by NMD or proteasomal pathways. Frameshift mutations are the most frequent molecular basis of alpha-1 antitrypsin deficiency of the null class, some BRCA1 mutations, and many other loss-of-function diseases. In-frame insertions or deletions (multiples of three) add or remove one or more amino acids without shifting the reading frame and can have phenotypes ranging from mild to severe.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'MUTATION TYPES',x:'TRANSITION: purine to purine (A<>G) or pyrimidine to pyrimidine (C<>T). Most common spontaneous mutation; caused by deamination (C to T), alkylation of G (O6-MeG pairs with T, G:C to A:T), APOBEC enzyme activity. TRANSVERSION: purine to pyrimidine or vice versa. Less common spontaneous; caused by oxidative damage (8-oxoG causes G:C to T:A), aflatoxin B1 (G:C to T:A at TP53 codon 249), tobacco carcinogens (benzo[a]pyrene causes G:C to T:A in lung). UV SIGNATURE: C to T transitions at dipyrimidine sites; CC to TT dinucleotide substitutions (CC>TT) are the most specific UV signature, seen in melanoma. SILENT: same amino acid, no protein change. MISSENSE: different amino acid, variable phenotype. NONSENSE: premature stop, truncated protein + NMD. FRAMESHIFT (insertion/deletion, not multiple of 3): shifts reading frame, almost always produces premature stop downstream; usually null allele. IN-FRAME INDEL (multiple of 3): adds/removes amino acids without frame shift.'},{t:'p',x:'Chromosomal mutations involve large-scale rearrangements. Deletions remove a chromosomal segment (for example, the 22q11.2 deletion causes DiGeorge syndrome; the 15q11-q13 deletion causes Prader-Willi or Angelman syndrome depending on parent of origin). Inversions reverse the orientation of a chromosomal segment. Translocations exchange segments between non-homologous chromosomes. The Philadelphia chromosome, t(9;22)(q34;q11), is the best-known translocation in medicine: the breakpoint on chromosome 9 disrupts the ABL1 proto-oncogene (encoding a tyrosine kinase) and the breakpoint on chromosome 22 disrupts BCR (breakpoint cluster region). The resulting BCR-ABL1 fusion gene encodes a constitutively active tyrosine kinase that drives unregulated cell proliferation, causing chronic myeloid leukemia (CML) in the chronic phase and eventually blast crisis. Imatinib (Gleevec) was the first targeted kinase inhibitor specifically designed against BCR-ABL1, occupying the ATP-binding pocket in the inactive conformation and blocking kinase activity. Second-generation inhibitors (dasatinib, nilotinib) and third-generation (ponatinib) were developed to overcome resistance mutations (most commonly T315I, the gatekeeper mutation).'},{t:'p',x:'Trinucleotide repeat expansion disorders occur when unstable tandem repeats of three nucleotides expand above a threshold during DNA replication or repair. The mechanism involves slippage of the nascent or template strand at the repeats during replication, creating stable hairpin structures that are not corrected by MMR. Above a pathogenic threshold, the repeat expansion silences the gene (if in the 5 prime UTR, causing Fragile X syndrome), produces a polyglutamine-expanded protein (if in the coding region, causing Huntington disease), or disrupts splicing and sequestrates RNA-binding proteins (if in the 3 prime UTR or intron, causing myotonic dystrophy). Anticipation describes the phenomenon by which the repeat expansion tends to increase with successive generations and the disease presents at an earlier age and with greater severity in children than in parents.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'TRINUCLEOTIDE REPEAT DISEASES',x:'HUNTINGTON DISEASE: CAG repeat in exon 1 of HTT (huntingtin gene) on chromosome 4p; normal <35 repeats; pathogenic >40 repeats; encodes polyglutamine (polyQ) tract; expanded polyQ huntingtin misfolds, forms aggregates in striatal neurons, and causes neuronal death; autosomal dominant (gain of toxic function); anticipation occurs predominantly through paternal transmission (male meiosis expands repeats more than female meiosis). FRAGILE X SYNDROME: CGG repeat in the 5 prime UTR of FMR1 (fragile X mental retardation protein) on chromosome Xq27.3; normal <55 repeats; premutation 55-200 repeats (risk for fragile X-associated tremor/ataxia syndrome, FXTAS, and premature ovarian insufficiency); full mutation >200 repeats; CpG methylation of the repeat region and FMR1 promoter silences the gene; X-linked; most common inherited cause of intellectual disability; anticipation through maternal transmission (female premutation carriers expand to full mutation in offspring). MYOTONIC DYSTROPHY type 1 (DM1): CTG repeat in 3 prime UTR of DMPK gene on chromosome 19; normal <37 repeats; pathogenic from ~50 repeats; expanded DMPK mRNA accumulates and sequesters MBNL1 (a splicing regulator) in nuclear foci, causing widespread splicing defects; autosomal dominant; affects muscle (myotonia, progressive weakness), heart (conduction defects), endocrine (insulin resistance, hypogonadism), eye (cataracts), brain; anticipation through maternal transmission (congenital DM1, the most severe form, is almost always inherited from the mother).'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A patient with chronic myeloid leukemia (CML) is started on imatinib but develops resistance after 18 months. Sequencing reveals a T315I mutation in the BCR-ABL1 kinase domain. Why does this specific mutation confer resistance?',choices:['A) T315I activates a second oncogene that drives CML independently of BCR-ABL1 activity','B) Threonine 315 forms a hydrogen bond with imatinib; substitution to isoleucine eliminates this contact and creates a steric clash, preventing imatinib binding while allowing ATP to bind normally','C) T315I causes BCR-ABL1 to adopt the active conformation permanently, but imatinib binds the inactive conformation only','D) Isoleucine at position 315 activates a pro-apoptotic pathway that makes the cells resistant to treatment'],answer:1,why:'Imatinib binds the inactive (closed) conformation of the BCR-ABL1 kinase and forms a critical hydrogen bond with the threonine at position 315 (the gatekeeper residue). Substitution of threonine with isoleucine (T315I) eliminates this hydrogen bond and creates a steric clash with imatinib\'s pyridine ring, preventing binding of the drug while preserving the ATP-binding capacity of the kinase. The kinase remains constitutively active and drives continued proliferation. This is the most common resistance mutation to imatinib. Ponatinib (a third-generation BCR-ABL1 inhibitor) was specifically designed to accommodate the T315I mutation and is used for T315I-positive CML.'},{stem:'A boy has intellectual disability and is found to have more than 200 CGG repeats in the 5 prime UTR of FMR1. The FMR1 promoter CpG island is heavily methylated. What is the most direct consequence of this methylation?',choices:['A) The FMR1 mRNA is produced normally but contains an expanded CGG sequence that is translated into an abnormal polyglycine protein','B) Transcription of FMR1 is silenced, leading to absence of FMRP protein, which is required for normal synaptic pruning and plasticity','C) The expanded CGG repeats in the mRNA sequester MBNL1, disrupting splicing of multiple target genes','D) The CGG repeat expansion causes a frameshift in the FMR1 open reading frame, producing a truncated protein'],answer:1,why:'In Fragile X syndrome with more than 200 CGG repeats in the 5 prime UTR of FMR1, the repeat expansion triggers de novo DNA methylation at the adjacent CpG island promoter by DNMT3A/3B. Methylated CpG islands recruit methyl-CpG binding proteins (such as MeCP2) that in turn recruit histone deacetylases (HDACs), producing a compact, transcriptionally inactive chromatin state. The result is silencing of FMR1 transcription and absence of FMRP (fragile X mental retardation protein). FMRP is an mRNA-binding protein that regulates translation of a large set of synaptic mRNAs; its loss causes excessive synaptic protein synthesis, impaired long-term depression, and intellectual disability. Sequestering MBNL1 by CUG/CCUG repeats is the mechanism of myotonic dystrophy type 1/2, not Fragile X. PolyGln expansion is the mechanism of Huntington disease.'}]}],
 bottomLine:'DNA structure, replication, and repair form the molecular foundation of all information transfer in biology and medicine. B-DNA is a right-handed double helix with 10 base pairs per turn, 0.34 nm per base pair, antiparallel strands, and a major groove wide enough for transcription factor recognition. Chargaff rules (%A=%T, %G=%C) follow directly from base pairing. Compaction proceeds from the 147 bp nucleosome core (histone octamer H2A/H2B/H3/H4) through the 30 nm fiber and loop domains to the metaphase chromosome. Histone acetylation (charge neutralization of Lys by HAT) opens chromatin and activates transcription; HDAC inhibitors exploit this clinically. H3K4me3 marks active genes; H3K27me3 (placed by EZH2/PRC2) marks silenced genes. Topoisomerase I (no ATP, one-strand nick) is targeted by camptothecin; Topo II (ATP, two-strand break) is targeted by etoposide and by fluoroquinolones against bacterial gyrase. Semi-conservative replication was proved by the Meselson-Stahl CsCl density gradient experiment. Eukaryotic replication requires ORC, MCM helicase, PCNA sliding clamp, RFC loader, RPA, primase-Pol alpha, Pol epsilon (leading strand), and Pol delta (lagging strand). Pol epsilon and delta both have 3 prime to 5 prime proofreading; Pol beta does not. Error rate falls from 10^-5 to 10^-7 after proofreading to 10^-9 after mismatch repair. The end-replication problem is solved by telomerase (TERT + TERC RNA template), active in stem cells and cancer but not somatic cells. Five repair pathways match specific lesions: BER (glycosylase removes damaged base, APE1 nicks AP site, Pol beta fills) handles small non-distorting lesions such as uracil and 8-oxoG; NER (25-30 nt dual incision by XPF-ERCC1 and XPG) handles bulky UV dimers; XP and Cockayne syndrome are NER disorders; MMR (MSH2-MSH6 recognizes mismatches, MLH1-PMS2 coordinates removal) corrects replication errors; Lynch syndrome is an MMR defect with MSI-H as its hallmark and sensitivity to checkpoint immunotherapy. HR (RAD51 nucleofilament, uses sister chromatid, S/G2 phase, high fidelity) and NHEJ (Ku70/80, DNA-PKcs, Artemis, XRCC4-Ligase IV, G1 phase, error-prone) repair double-strand breaks; BRCA1/2 mutations impair HR and confer synthetic lethality with PARP inhibitors. MGMT promoter methylation sensitizes glioblastoma to temozolomide. Mutations are classified as transitions (purine for purine, most common), transversions (purine for pyrimidine, caused by oxidative and chemical damage), silent, missense, nonsense, frameshift, or chromosomal. BCR-ABL1 translocation causes CML and is treated with imatinib. Trinucleotide repeats expand across generations (anticipation): Huntington (CAG/polyQ, paternal), Fragile X (CGG/methylation silencing, maternal), and myotonic dystrophy (CTG/MBNL1 sequestration, maternal for congenital form).',
 nextHint:'Chapter 12, RNA Synthesis and Processing, builds directly on the DNA template established here: RNA polymerase must access the major groove to read the template strand, the topoisomerase logic of transcription elongation parallels replication fork management, and the pre-mRNA splicing and processing steps transform the nascent transcript into the mature mRNA that Chapter 13 will translate into protein.',
},
{
 n:12,
 title:'Transcription and Gene Regulation',
 subtitle:'How the cell reads its genome: RNA polymerases, promoters, processing machinery, and the regulatory circuits that decide which genes are on or off',
 tag:'Information',
 foundational:'Transcription is the first committed step of gene expression. Every protein discussed in Chapters 1 through 11 was produced by a transcriptional decision. Understanding how that decision is made, and how drugs, mutations, and epigenetic marks alter it, connects biochemistry to genetics, cell biology, and disease.',
 buildsOn:'Ch 11 (DNA replication and repair builds the template); Ch 1 (proteins are the output); Ch 10 (signaling pathways control many transcription factors).',
 setsUp:'Ch 13, translation: mRNA produced here is decoded there. The central dogma is complete across Chapters 11, 12, and 13.',
 objectives:['Describe the subunit composition of prokaryotic RNA polymerase holoenzyme, identify the role of sigma factor, and trace the three stages of bacterial transcription','Compare rho-independent and rho-dependent termination mechanisms at the molecular level','Explain the mechanism of rifampin and predict resistance mutations','Identify the three eukaryotic nuclear RNA polymerases, their products, and the promoter elements recognized by Pol II','Trace the assembly of the Pol II pre-initiation complex from TFIID binding through TFIIH-mediated promoter opening and CTD phosphorylation','Explain the mechanism of 5-prime capping, 3-prime polyadenylation, and pre-mRNA splicing by the spliceosome','Analyze the lac operon: negative control by the repressor, positive control by CAP-cAMP, and the logic of catabolite repression','Explain the trp operon: repressible control plus the attenuation mechanism at the molecular level','Classify eukaryotic transcription factor DNA-binding domains and describe how enhancers communicate with promoters via DNA looping','Describe chromatin remodeling by SWI/SNF, histone acetylation/deacetylation, histone methylation marks, and CpG DNA methylation','Explain miRNA and siRNA biogenesis, loading into RISC, and the downstream silencing mechanism','Analyze alternative splicing, RNA editing by ADAR and APOBEC1, and nonsense-mediated decay as post-transcriptional regulatory layers','Apply splicing defects to clinical examples including Duchenne muscular dystrophy exon skipping and spinal muscular atrophy'],
 opener:'The human genome encodes roughly 20,000 protein-coding genes and approximately 25,000 additional non-coding RNA genes, yet any given cell type expresses only a fraction of them at any moment. A pancreatic beta cell transcribes insulin; a neuron does not. A hepatocyte turns on gluconeogenic enzymes when blood glucose falls; adipocytes do not. The decision about which genes to transcribe, at what level, and in response to which signals, is made at the transcription initiation step, and it is this decision that separates one cell type from another despite their sharing an identical DNA sequence.\n\nThis chapter traces the mechanism of transcription from the first contact between RNA polymerase and a promoter through the synthesis of a complete RNA, the processing modifications that convert a nascent transcript into a functional molecule, and the regulatory circuits that adjust gene output to the needs of the cell. The logic starts with the simplest systems: bacterial operons, where a single repressor protein binding to a short DNA sequence can silence an entire gene cluster. It then scales up to the eukaryotic nucleus, where dozens of transcription factors, multisubunit mediator complexes, chromatin remodelers, and small RNA surveillance pathways collectively determine whether a gene fires or stays silent.\n\nThe clinical relevance is immediate. Rifampin kills tuberculosis by targeting bacterial RNA polymerase. Exon-skipping antisense oligonucleotides restore the reading frame in Duchenne muscular dystrophy by manipulating the spliceosome. Nusinersen rescues spinal muscular atrophy patients by redirecting splicing of an exon. CpG hypermethylation silences tumor suppressor genes in cancer. Every one of these interventions exploits a mechanism covered in this chapter.',
 pinnedDisc:{t:'PROKARYOTIC vs EUKARYOTIC TRANSCRIPTION: THE ESSENTIAL DIFFERENCES',x:'PROKARYOTES: Single RNA polymerase (alpha2-beta-beta-prime-omega core + sigma = holoenzyme) transcribes all RNA types. No nuclear compartment: ribosomes attach to mRNA while transcription is still in progress (coupled transcription-translation). No 5-prime cap or poly-A tail on mRNA. mRNAs are often polycistronic (multiple ORFs per transcript). Termination uses stem-loops or rho helicase. Rifampin blocks the beta subunit. EUKARYOTES: Three nuclear RNA polymerases: Pol I (rRNA in nucleolus), Pol II (mRNA and most snRNA), Pol III (tRNA, 5S rRNA). mRNA processing is extensive and co-transcriptional: 5-prime 7-methylguanosine cap, splicing by spliceosome, 3-prime polyadenylation. mRNAs are monocistronic. Transcription and translation are physically and temporally separated by the nuclear envelope. Chromatin structure adds a regulatory layer absent in prokaryotes. KEY MCAT TRAP: Prokaryotic mRNA has NO cap and NO poly-A tail; eukaryotic mRNA has BOTH; mitochondrial mRNA lacks a cap (bacteria-like).'},
 sections:[{id:'12.1',num:'12.1',title:'12.1 Prokaryotic Transcription: The Bacterial RNA Polymerase and Its Cycle',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Bacterial RNA polymerase (RNAP) synthesizes all cellular RNA species from a DNA template. The core enzyme consists of five subunits: two alpha subunits (each ~36 kDa, form the assembly platform and interact with regulatory factors), one beta subunit (~150 kDa, contains the catalytic center for phosphodiester bond formation and is the target of rifampin), one beta-prime subunit (~155 kDa, the largest subunit, binds DNA non-specifically through a positively charged cleft), and one omega subunit (~10 kDa, assists beta-prime folding and assembly). The core enzyme can elongate RNA chains but cannot initiate transcription at a specific promoter without the sigma factor. The sigma factor is a dissociable subunit that associates transiently with the core to form the holoenzyme (alpha2-beta-beta-prime-omega + sigma). The predominant sigma factor in E. coli under normal growth conditions is sigma-70 (sigma^70), named for its molecular weight of 70 kDa. The sigma factor contains four conserved regions: region 2.4 recognizes the -10 element of the promoter, and region 4.2 recognizes the -35 element.'},{t:'p',x:'Promoter recognition is the first step of initiation. The consensus sequence of the sigma-70 promoter has two key elements upstream of the transcription start site (+1): the -10 element (also called the Pribnow box), with consensus TATAAT centered approximately 10 bp upstream of +1, and the -35 element, with consensus TTGACA centered approximately 35 bp upstream. These are consensus sequences derived from statistical analysis of many promoters; strong promoters match the consensus closely, weak promoters deviate from it, and the spacing between elements matters. The holoenzyme first contacts these elements in the closed complex, where the DNA duplex is intact. The enzyme then melts approximately 12 to 17 bp of DNA centered at the -10 element to form the open complex (also called the transcription bubble), in which the template strand is accessible to the catalytic center. Open complex formation is rate-limiting for transcription initiation at most promoters.'},{t:'p',x:'During initiation, the polymerase begins synthesizing short RNA oligonucleotides while remaining anchored to the promoter, a phase called abortive initiation. These short products (typically 2 to 9 nt) are released, and the polymerase resets. Eventually, an RNA of sufficient length (approximately 9 to 11 nt) forms a stable RNA-DNA hybrid in the active-site cleft; at this point the sigma factor dissociates and the core enzyme transitions to the elongation mode, a process called promoter clearance or escape. Sigma release is critical: because sigma stabilizes the interaction between RNAP and the promoter, retaining sigma would tether the polymerase at the promoter and prevent movement along the template.'},{t:'box',kind:'why',label:'WHY SIGMA DISSOCIATES AFTER INITIATION',x:'Sigma factor increases the affinity of the core enzyme for the promoter by more than a million-fold, which is essential for locating the promoter among the 4 million base pairs of the E. coli chromosome. Once the polymerase has initiated transcription, however, that tight promoter affinity becomes a liability: it would prevent the polymerase from moving away from the promoter along the template. The structural transition from open complex to the elongation-competent conformation involves a rearrangement of the clamp domain that simultaneously destabilizes sigma binding and tightens the grip on the downstream DNA. Thus the same conformational change that triggers elongation also evicts sigma. Free sigma then re-associates with another core enzyme, initiating a new round of transcription. The sigma recycling mechanism allows a limited pool of sigma-70 to support many simultaneous rounds of initiation.'},{t:'p',x:'Elongation proceeds continuously in the 5-prime to 3-prime direction at approximately 50 to 90 nucleotides per second in bacteria. RNA polymerase does not require a primer: it can initiate de novo because the active site stabilizes the first two nucleotides through base-pairing with the template and through protein contacts. The incoming substrate is an NTP (not a dNTP); RNA polymerase catalyzes formation of a 3-prime,5-prime phosphodiester bond by attacking the alpha-phosphate of the incoming NTP with the 3-prime hydroxyl of the growing RNA, releasing pyrophosphate (PPi). PPi is rapidly hydrolyzed by pyrophosphatase, driving the reaction forward thermodynamically. The polymerase unwinds approximately 12 to 17 bp of duplex DNA ahead of the active site to expose the template strand, while simultaneously re-annealing the double helix behind the bubble as the RNA-DNA hybrid peels apart and the single-stranded RNA exits through the RNA exit channel. The RNA-DNA hybrid within the active site is approximately 8 to 9 bp long.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'PROKARYOTIC TRANSCRIPTION STAGES AT A GLANCE',x:'INITIATION: sigma factor binds core RNAP to form holoenzyme; holoenzyme contacts -35 element (region 4.2) and -10 element (region 2.4) of the promoter; closed complex forms; approximately 12-17 bp of DNA melts to open complex; abortive initiation produces short RNAs; sigma dissociates after approximately 9-11 nt RNA is made; polymerase escapes the promoter. ELONGATION: core enzyme moves 5-prime to 3-prime; template strand read 3-prime to 5-prime; NTPs incorporated; RNA-DNA hybrid of approximately 8-9 bp; approximately 17 bp transcription bubble; re-annealing occurs behind the polymerase; approximately 50-90 nt/sec; no primer required. TERMINATION: two mechanisms (below). No 5-prime cap or poly-A tail added; prokaryotic mRNA is often polycistronic and immediately accessible to ribosomes.'},{t:'p',x:'Transcription termination occurs by two distinct mechanisms in bacteria. Rho-independent (intrinsic) termination depends on the sequence of the nascent RNA itself. As the polymerase transcribes through the terminator region, the RNA folds into a GC-rich stem-loop hairpin immediately followed by a run of approximately 6 to 8 uridine residues (the poly-U tract). The stem-loop hairpin causes the polymerase to pause, and the weak rU-dA base pairs in the RNA-DNA hybrid behind the hairpin are insufficient to maintain the hybrid during the pause. The hybrid destabilizes, the RNA falls off the template, and the polymerase dissociates. The stem-loop is the energy source driving termination: more stable hairpins cause more efficient termination. Rho-dependent termination requires the rho protein, a hexameric ATP-dependent RNA helicase. Rho loads onto a rho utilization site (rut site) on the 5-prime portion of the nascent RNA, a region that is unstructured and not occupied by ribosomes. Using ATP hydrolysis, rho translocates along the RNA in the 5-prime to 3-prime direction, pursuing the RNA polymerase. When the polymerase pauses at a pause site, rho catches up and uses its helicase activity to unwind the RNA-DNA hybrid, releasing the RNA and dissociating the polymerase. Rho-dependent termination is the mechanism used when a protein requires that a gene be off unless the mRNA is being actively translated.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'RIFAMPIN: MECHANISM AND CLINICAL USE',x:'Rifampin (rifampicin) is a bactericidal antibiotic that inhibits prokaryotic RNA polymerase by binding deep within a pocket of the beta subunit adjacent to the active site. The drug makes extensive hydrophobic and hydrogen-bond contacts with beta subunit residues. When rifampin is bound, the growing RNA chain cannot extend beyond 2 to 3 nucleotides because the drug physically blocks the RNA exit channel near the active site. Rifampin thus blocks initiation and very early elongation; it does not inhibit RNAP that has already begun elongating (because the drug can only access the binding pocket when the enzyme is in the open-complex configuration). Rifampin does NOT inhibit eukaryotic RNA polymerase II because the beta-equivalent subunit (RPB1) in eukaryotes has a structurally different pocket. Clinical uses: first-line agent for tuberculosis (Mycobacterium tuberculosis, always used in combination to prevent resistance); meningococcal prophylaxis (eradicates nasopharyngeal carriage of Neisseria meningitidis); chemoprophylaxis for Haemophilus influenzae type b contacts; leprosy. Resistance: single-base substitutions in the rpoB gene (encoding beta subunit) at key rifampin-contact residues (most commonly S531L, H526Y, or D516V in E. coli numbering equivalents) disrupt drug binding without significantly impairing catalytic activity. RpoB mutation testing is now used clinically to rapidly detect rifampin-resistant TB (Xpert MTB/RIF).'},{t:'p',x:'A critical feature of prokaryotic gene expression that has no counterpart in eukaryotes is coupled transcription-translation. Because bacteria lack a nuclear envelope, the 5-prime end of an mRNA is accessible to ribosomes as soon as it emerges from the RNA polymerase. Ribosomes begin translating the 5-prime end of the mRNA while the 3-prime end is still being synthesized. This physical coupling serves two purposes: it increases the efficiency of protein production by minimizing the delay between gene transcription and protein production, and it plays a direct role in gene regulation (as in the attenuation mechanism of the trp operon, described in Section 12.3). In electron micrographs of E. coli, actively transcribed genes appear decorated with polysomes arranged in the pattern of a Christmas tree, each successive ribosome starting translation slightly behind the previous one.'},{t:'list',x:['Holoenzyme composition: alpha2 + beta + beta-prime + omega (core) + sigma factor; sigma recognizes promoter elements','Sigma-70 promoter: -10 element (TATAAT, Pribnow box) and -35 element (TTGACA); spacing of ~17 bp between them','Open complex: ~12-17 bp of DNA melted; transition from closed to open complex is rate-limiting','Sigma dissociates after ~9-11 nt RNA formed; core enzyme proceeds to elongation','Elongation: 5-prime to 3-prime; no primer; NTPs used; PPi released and hydrolyzed; ~50-90 nt/sec','Rho-independent termination: GC hairpin + poly-U tract in RNA; RNA-DNA hybrid destabilizes; RNA falls off','Rho-dependent termination: rho helicase loads on rut site; translocates 5-prime to 3-prime; catches paused pol; unwinds hybrid','No cap, no poly-A in prokaryotes; mRNA often polycistronic; coupled transcription-translation possible','Rifampin: blocks beta subunit RNA exit channel; prevents extension beyond 2-3 nt; resistance via rpoB mutation']},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'HIGH-YIELD: PROKARYOTIC TRANSCRIPTION FOR THE MCAT',x:'The MCAT tests the following prokaryotic transcription facts at high frequency: (1) sigma factor role: recognizes promoter, dissociates after initiation. (2) -10 (TATAAT) and -35 (TTGACA) promoter elements. (3) RNA polymerase needs no primer; uses NTPs (not dNTPs); synthesizes 5-prime to 3-prime. (4) Rifampin blocks beta subunit: used for TB, meningococcal prophylaxis; resistance from rpoB mutation. (5) Rho-independent termination: stem-loop hairpin + poly-U; rho-dependent: rho helicase pursues paused polymerase. (6) No 5-prime cap, no poly-A tail on prokaryotic mRNA. (7) Coupled transcription-translation: ribosomes bind mRNA before transcription is complete.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A researcher finds a mutation in the rpoB gene of Mycobacterium tuberculosis that changes a serine to leucine in the rifampin-binding pocket. What is the expected functional consequence?',choices:['A) The RNA polymerase can no longer bind promoter DNA because rpoB encodes sigma factor','B) The bacterium will be resistant to rifampin because drug binding is disrupted, but RNA polymerase activity is retained','C) The bacterium will be hypersensitive to rifampin because the mutation increases drug binding affinity','D) The bacterium cannot perform rho-dependent termination because rho cannot recognize the mutant beta subunit'],answer:1,why:'The rpoB gene encodes the beta subunit of RNA polymerase. Rifampin binds deep within a pocket in the beta subunit, blocking the RNA exit channel. A missense mutation at a rifampin-contact residue (such as Ser531Leu) disrupts drug binding through steric or electrostatic changes while preserving the catalytic function of the polymerase. The result is rifampin resistance. rpoB does not encode sigma factor (encoded by rpoD in E. coli) and is unrelated to rho-dependent termination.'},{stem:'Which of the following best describes the mechanism of rho-independent transcription termination in bacteria?',choices:['A) Rho helicase binds the rut site on the mRNA and uses ATP to unwind the RNA-DNA hybrid when the polymerase pauses','B) The nascent RNA forms a GC-rich stem-loop hairpin followed by a poly-U stretch, destabilizing the RNA-DNA hybrid and releasing the RNA','C) The sigma factor re-associates with the polymerase and dissociates from the template, pulling the RNA off','D) A specific termination protein binds the -35 element of the promoter and dislodges the polymerase'],answer:1,why:'Rho-independent (intrinsic) termination depends entirely on the sequence of the nascent RNA. A GC-rich inverted repeat folds into a stable hairpin stem-loop, causing polymerase pausing. The poly-U sequence immediately downstream of the hairpin forms weak rU-dA base pairs with the template DNA in the transcription bubble. These weak pairs cannot maintain the hybrid while the polymerase is paused, and the RNA dissociates. Choice A describes rho-dependent termination.'}]},{id:'12.2',num:'12.2',title:'12.2 Eukaryotic Transcription: Three RNA Polymerases and the Pol II Pre-initiation Complex',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Eukaryotic cells compartmentalize transcription in the nucleus and employ three distinct nuclear RNA polymerases, each responsible for a different category of RNA product. RNA Polymerase I operates exclusively in the nucleolus and transcribes the 45S pre-rRNA precursor, which is processed by a series of endonucleolytic cleavages to yield the 28S, 18S, and 5.8S rRNAs that make up the large and small ribosomal subunit cores. Because ribosome biogenesis is the single largest consumer of cellular transcriptional resources, Pol I accounts for roughly 60% of total cellular RNA synthesis in rapidly dividing cells. RNA Polymerase II transcribes all protein-coding genes (producing pre-mRNAs that are processed into mature mRNAs), most snRNAs (which are components of the spliceosome), snoRNAs, and many long non-coding RNAs. It is the most extensively regulated of the three polymerases and the primary target of general and gene-specific transcriptional regulation. RNA Polymerase III transcribes small, structured RNAs with housekeeping roles: tRNAs, 5S rRNA (which joins the large ribosomal subunit alongside the 28S and 5.8S rRNAs from Pol I), the 7SL RNA component of the SRP, and several other small cytoplasmic and nuclear RNAs. All three polymerases are large, multi-subunit complexes structurally related to the bacterial core enzyme, and all use a two-metal-ion (Mg2+) catalytic mechanism for phosphodiester bond formation.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'THREE EUKARYOTIC RNA POLYMERASES: LOCATION, PRODUCTS, AND ALPHA-AMANITIN SENSITIVITY',x:'RNA POL I: located in nucleolus; products are 28S, 18S, and 5.8S rRNA (from 45S precursor); not inhibited by alpha-amanitin; promoter elements recognized by species-specific transcription factors (UBF, SL1/TIF-IB). RNA POL II: located in nucleoplasm; products are pre-mRNA (all protein-coding genes), most snRNAs, snoRNAs, many lncRNAs; inhibited by low concentrations of alpha-amanitin (~0.02 microg/mL); the most regulated polymerase; the target of most transcriptional control. RNA POL III: located in cytoplasm and nucleoplasm; products are tRNA, 5S rRNA, 7SL RNA, U6 snRNA, other small RNAs; inhibited by high concentrations of alpha-amanitin (~20 microg/mL). ALPHA-AMANITIN (from Amanita phalloides, the death cap mushroom) is the canonical tool for distinguishing the three polymerases experimentally: Pol I is alpha-amanitin resistant; Pol II is highly sensitive; Pol III requires high concentrations. Clinical: Amanita phalloides poisoning causes fulminant hepatic failure (Pol II inhibition in hepatocytes). RNA-DEPENDENT RNA POLYMERASE: viruses encode this enzyme, which copies RNA from an RNA template; it has no counterpart in uninfected mammalian cells and is a target for antiviral drugs (e.g., sofosbuvir targets the HCV NS5B polymerase).'},{t:'p',x:'The RNA Pol II promoter is structurally more complex than a bacterial promoter because it must integrate signals from many transcription factors simultaneously. The core promoter is the minimal DNA sequence sufficient to direct accurate transcription initiation by Pol II; it typically spans approximately -40 to +40 relative to the transcription start site (TSS) at +1. Four elements are found in subsets of Pol II core promoters: (1) the TATA box (consensus TATAAA, centered approximately 25 to 30 bp upstream of the TSS; present in approximately 20-30% of human promoters, enriched at tissue-specific and developmentally regulated genes, absent from many constitutively expressed housekeeping gene promoters); (2) the BRE (TFIIB recognition element, located immediately upstream of the TATA box, recognized by the TFIIB general transcription factor); (3) the Inr (initiator element, spans the TSS at approximately -3 to +5, consensus YYANWYY; present in both TATA-containing and TATA-less promoters); and (4) the DPE (downstream promoter element, approximately +28 to +34, functional in TATA-less promoters, recognized by TAF6 and TAF9 subunits of TFIID).'},{t:'p',x:'The general transcription factors (GTFs) assemble onto the core promoter in a defined order to build the pre-initiation complex (PIC). The order of assembly, which has been worked out by biochemical depletion and add-back experiments, begins with TFIID, proceeds through TFIIA and TFIIB, then recruits the Pol II-TFIIF complex, followed by TFIIE and finally TFIIH. TFIID is a large complex of TBP (TATA-binding protein) and approximately 13 to 14 TBP-associated factors (TAFs). TBP makes direct contact with the minor groove of the TATA box and introduces a dramatic structural distortion: TBP bends the TATA box DNA by approximately 90 degrees and partially unwinds it by intercalating its beta-sheet surface between the T-A base pairs. This distortion serves as the primary architectural element of the PIC, positioning the flanking TAFs and the downstream DNA template. In TATA-less promoters, TAF subunits of TFIID contact the Inr and DPE elements directly, providing the structural equivalent of TBP-TATA interaction. TFIIA stabilizes TBP binding and counteracts negative factors that compete with TBP for promoter occupancy. TFIIB makes contacts with both the BRE and TBP, and also makes the first contact with Pol II, positioning the enzyme over the TSS.'},{t:'p',x:'TFIIF is a heterodimer that associates constitutively with Pol II and escorts it to the promoter when Pol II joins the assembling PIC after TFIIB. TFIIF reduces the affinity of Pol II for non-specific DNA sequences, helping the enzyme find its target. TFIIE joins the growing PIC and recruits TFIIH. TFIIH is the most enzymatically active GTF: it is a ten-subunit complex containing two enzymatic activities that are indispensable for transcription initiation. The XPB helicase subunit (also called ERCC3) uses ATP hydrolysis to unwind approximately 11 bp of DNA around the TSS, forming the open complex necessary for RNA synthesis to begin. The CDK7 kinase subunit phosphorylates serine 5 (Ser5) of the heptapeptide repeat (consensus YSPTSPS) in the C-terminal domain (CTD) of the largest Pol II subunit (RPB1). This Ser5 phosphorylation is the trigger for promoter escape: it weakens the interaction between the Pol II CTD and the Mediator complex, which has been holding the PIC together at the promoter, allowing the polymerase to break free and begin elongation.'},{t:'box',kind:'why',label:'WHY THE Pol II CTD IS PHOSPHORYLATED IN TWO WAVES',x:'The RPB1 subunit of Pol II carries a unique C-terminal domain (CTD) consisting of tandemly repeated heptapeptide sequences (YSPTSPS in humans, approximately 52 repeats). The CTD functions as a landing platform for RNA processing factors; its phosphorylation state changes dynamically during the transcription cycle and determines which factors are recruited at each stage. At a promoter, the CTD is hypophosphorylated (unmodified), allowing it to interact with the Mediator complex that holds the assembled PIC at the promoter. TFIIH kinase (CDK7) phosphorylates Ser5 during initiation and early elongation; Ser5-phosphorylated CTD recruits the capping enzyme (which adds the 7-methylguanosine cap to the 5-prime end of the nascent RNA within the first approximately 20-30 nt of synthesis) and the RNA 5-prime triphosphatase that processes the 5-prime end. As elongation proceeds, CDK9 (part of the P-TEFb complex) phosphorylates Ser2 of the CTD; Ser2 phosphorylation recruits the splicing machinery and the cleavage/polyadenylation machinery (which adds the poly-A tail at the 3-prime end). Thus the CTD code uses sequential phosphorylation events to coordinate the co-transcriptional addition of the 5-prime cap (Ser5-CTD), splicing (Ser2-CTD), and 3-prime processing (Ser2-CTD) with the transcription elongation process itself.'},{t:'p',x:'The Mediator complex is a large (~1.2 MDa, approximately 25-30 subunits in humans) protein bridge that connects gene-specific transcriptional activators bound at enhancers and promoter-proximal regions to the Pol II PIC assembled at the core promoter. Mediator has no intrinsic enzymatic activity; it is a conformational relay. Specific Mediator submodules (head, middle, tail, and kinase modules) contact different activator domains and different components of the PIC, particularly Pol II and TFIID. Activated transcription (above the basal level achievable by GTFs alone) requires Mediator at essentially every regulated Pol II gene. Mediator subunit mutations are found in many human cancers and developmental disorders, reflecting its central role in transcriptional amplification.'},{t:'p',x:'Enhancers and silencers are cis-regulatory DNA sequences that can regulate transcription from distances of tens to hundreds of kilobases from the genes they control, and that can act in either orientation and upstream or downstream of their target genes. These properties distinguish enhancers from promoters (which are position-dependent and orientation-sensitive). The mechanism by which an enhancer controls a distant promoter involves chromatin looping: proteins bound at the enhancer physically contact proteins assembled at the promoter when the intervening DNA loops out, bringing the two elements into proximity. Cohesin (a ring-shaped SMC protein complex) and CTCF (an eleven-zinc-finger insulator-binding protein) stabilize chromatin loops at topologically associating domain (TAD) boundaries, restricting enhancer-promoter interactions to within the same TAD. Insulators are DNA sequences that, when bound by CTCF, block enhancer-promoter communication across a domain boundary, thereby restricting regulatory interactions to the correct genes.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'CLINICAL BRIDGE: WHEN ENHANCER HIJACKING CAUSES CANCER',x:'In many hematologic malignancies, chromosomal translocations place a powerful enhancer from one chromosomal location next to a proto-oncogene at another location, driving its aberrant overexpression. In Burkitt lymphoma, the t(8;14) translocation places the MYC oncogene on chromosome 8 under the control of the immunoglobulin heavy chain enhancer on chromosome 14, which is constitutively active in B cells. The MYC gene is now driven to extreme levels. MYC encodes a basic helix-loop-helix transcription factor that activates hundreds of growth and proliferation genes; its overexpression drives rapid B cell proliferation and lymphomagenesis. In multiple myeloma, translocations involving chromosome 14q32 (the IgH locus) frequently bring strong enhancers into proximity with FGFR3, MMSET, cyclin D1, MAF, and other oncogenes. Enhancer hijacking is now recognized as a general mechanism of cancer gene activation, and high-resolution chromatin conformation capture (Hi-C) is used in research to detect these aberrant loops.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'Which general transcription factor contains both a helicase that opens the transcription bubble at the start site and a kinase that phosphorylates the Pol II CTD to trigger promoter escape?',choices:['A) TFIID','B) TFIIB','C) TFIIH','D) TFIIF'],answer:2,why:'TFIIH contains XPB helicase (unwinds approximately 11 bp of DNA at the TSS to form the open complex) and CDK7 kinase (phosphorylates Ser5 of the Pol II CTD heptapeptide repeat). Ser5 phosphorylation weakens the CTD-Mediator interaction and triggers promoter escape. TFIID contains TBP (binds TATA box). TFIIB contacts BRE and TBP. TFIIF escorts Pol II to the promoter and suppresses non-specific binding.'},{stem:'A researcher treats cells with alpha-amanitin at a concentration of 1 microgram/mL. Which RNA species would be most severely depleted after several hours?',choices:['A) 28S rRNA','B) 5S rRNA','C) tRNA','D) mRNA from protein-coding genes'],answer:3,why:'At 1 microgram/mL, alpha-amanitin specifically and potently inhibits RNA Polymerase II, which transcribes all protein-coding genes to produce pre-mRNAs (processed into mature mRNAs). RNA Pol I (28S, 18S, 5.8S rRNA synthesis) is resistant to alpha-amanitin. RNA Pol III (5S rRNA and tRNA synthesis) requires much higher concentrations (approximately 20 microg/mL) for inhibition. Therefore, mRNA from protein-coding genes would be most depleted at the given concentration.'}]},{id:'12.3',num:'12.3',title:'12.3 mRNA Processing in Eukaryotes: Cap, Splice, and Tail',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'After the bacterial model of transcription was established, it was assumed that eukaryotic mRNA would be similarly simple: a transcript of the coding sequence with minimal modification. The discovery of split genes (1977, Sharp and Roberts, Nobel Prize 1993) and the subsequent characterization of the spliceosome revealed that eukaryotic gene expression is far more elaborate. Virtually every eukaryotic mRNA undergoes three categories of co-transcriptional processing before it is exported from the nucleus: 5-prime capping, splicing of introns, and 3-prime polyadenylation. All three processes are mechanistically coupled to the elongating Pol II through the CTD code (Ser5 phosphorylation recruits capping factors; Ser2 phosphorylation recruits splicing and 3-prime processing factors).'},{t:'p',x:'The 5-prime 7-methylguanosine (m7G) cap is added to the nascent transcript when it is only approximately 20 to 30 nucleotides long, making it the first processing event. The reaction has three enzymatic steps carried out by enzymes recruited to the Ser5-phosphorylated CTD. First, RNA 5-prime triphosphatase removes the gamma-phosphate from the 5-prime-triphosphate end of the nascent RNA, generating a 5-prime diphosphate terminus. Second, guanylyltransferase adds a GMP from GTP via an unusual 5-prime to 5-prime triphosphate linkage (not the standard 3-prime to 5-prime linkage used in the RNA backbone), creating the GpppN cap. Third, guanine N-7 methyltransferase methylates the N-7 position of the added guanosine using S-adenosylmethionine (SAM) as the methyl donor, yielding the m7GpppN cap. This cap structure performs multiple essential functions: it protects the 5-prime end of the mRNA from degradation by 5-prime exonucleases, it is recognized by the nuclear cap-binding complex (CBC) to facilitate nuclear export and pre-mRNA splicing, it is recognized by eIF4E to initiate cap-dependent translation in the cytoplasm, and it is involved in pioneer translation (the first round of translation that links translation to mRNA surveillance by nonsense-mediated decay).'},{t:'p',x:'Pre-mRNA splicing removes introns and joins exons to produce the mature mRNA. The core splicing machinery is the spliceosome, a dynamic ribonucleoprotein (RNP) complex assembled anew on each intron from five small nuclear ribonucleoprotein particles: U1, U2, U4, U5, and U6 snRNPs. Each snRNP consists of one or two small nuclear RNAs (snRNAs) bound by a set of proteins. Three conserved sequence elements in the pre-mRNA define each intron: the 5-prime splice site (consensus GU at the intron start), the 3-prime splice site (consensus AG at the intron end), and the branch point sequence (approximately 20 to 50 nt upstream of the 3-prime splice site; contains the invariant branch-point adenosine, consensus YNYURAY in humans).'},{t:'p',x:'Spliceosome assembly and catalysis proceed through a defined order. U1 snRNA base-pairs with the 5-prime splice site by complementarity. U2 snRNA base-pairs with the branch point sequence such that the branch-point adenosine is looped out (bulged), leaving its 2-prime hydroxyl group accessible and oriented for nucleophilic attack. The U4/U6 di-snRNP and U5 snRNP join as a preformed tri-snRNP to complete the B complex. A major rearrangement then occurs: U1 and U4 snRNAs are displaced from their base-paired positions (an RNA unwinding event), bringing U6 snRNA into contact with both the 5-prime splice site (replacing U1) and U2 snRNA. This activated spliceosome (Bact complex, then B* complex after additional remodeling) then catalyzes the two transesterification reactions of splicing. In the first step, the 2-prime hydroxyl of the branch-point adenosine attacks the phosphodiester bond at the 5-prime splice site, cleaving the exon-intron junction and forming a lariat intermediate in which the 5-prime end of the intron is covalently connected to the branch-point adenosine via a 2-prime to 5-prime phosphodiester bond. In the second step, the free 3-prime hydroxyl of the upstream exon attacks the 3-prime splice site, joining the two exons and releasing the lariat intron. The lariat is subsequently debranched by a 2-prime to 5-prime phosphodiesterase and degraded.'},{t:'box',kind:'why',label:'WHY SPLICING USES A LARIAT RATHER THAN SIMPLE HYDROLYSIS',x:'The two-step transesterification mechanism of splicing (via lariat intermediate) is thermodynamically neutral: one phosphodiester bond is broken and one new bond is formed in each step, with no net change in the number of phosphodiester bonds. This is in contrast to hydrolytic cleavage, which would require energy input (or subsequent ligation with ATP expenditure) to rejoin the exons. The lariat mechanism allows the spliceosome to join exons without net energy expenditure because the transesterification steps are isoenergetic. The lariat also physically tethers the intron, keeping both splice sites in proximity for the second step and reducing the probability of aberrant reactions. The 2-prime,5-prime branch is unique in cellular RNA chemistry; the invariant branch-point adenosine at the apex is selected precisely because adenosine-2-prime-OH is a good nucleophile, and the lariat geometry positions it optimally for the first step attack.'},{t:'p',x:'3-prime polyadenylation adds a poly(A) tail of approximately 200 adenosine residues to the 3-prime end of the pre-mRNA. The process is coupled to transcription elongation through the Ser2-phosphorylated CTD, which recruits the cleavage and polyadenylation machinery. Two key sequence elements in the pre-mRNA coordinate the reaction: the polyadenylation signal AAUAAA, located approximately 10 to 30 nt upstream of the cleavage site, and a GU-rich or U-rich downstream sequence element (DSE). CPSF (cleavage and polyadenylation specificity factor) recognizes and binds AAUAAA; CstF (cleavage stimulation factor) binds the DSE; additional cleavage factors (CF Im and CF IIm) assist in complex assembly. Endonucleolytic cleavage of the pre-mRNA occurs approximately 10 to 30 nt downstream of the AAUAAA signal, between the AAUAAA and the DSE. Poly(A) polymerase (PAP), which requires CPSF for processive activity, then adds approximately 200 non-templated adenosine residues to the newly generated 3-prime hydroxyl, using ATP as substrate. The poly(A) tail is immediately bound by poly(A)-binding protein (PABPN1) in the nucleus, which stimulates PAP processivity and helps define the final poly-A length. The poly(A) tail promotes mRNA stability, nuclear export, and in the cytoplasm, translation stimulation (cytoplasmic PABPC1 interacts with eIF4G to circularize the mRNA, stimulating reinitiation).'},{t:'formula',x:'Splicing reaction 1: 2-prime-OH of branch-point A attacks 5-prime splice site GU = lariat intermediate formed; exon 1 free 3-prime-OH generated. Splicing reaction 2: 3-prime-OH of exon 1 attacks 3-prime splice site AG = exons joined; lariat intron released.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'HIGH-YIELD: mRNA PROCESSING SUMMARY',x:'5-PRIME CAP: 7-methylguanosine added co-transcriptionally when transcript is ~20-30 nt long; unusual 5-prime to 5-prime triphosphate linkage; protects from 5-prime exonucleases; recognized by eIF4E for cap-dependent translation; added at Ser5-phosphorylated CTD. SPLICING: spliceosome = U1, U2, U4/U6, U5 snRNPs; U1 binds 5-prime splice site (GU); U2 binds branch point A; two transesterification reactions via lariat intermediate; result: introns removed, exons joined. 3-PRIME POLY-A TAIL: ~200 A residues added non-templated by poly(A) polymerase; CPSF recognizes AAUAAA signal; endonucleolytic cleavage ~10-30 nt downstream of AAUAAA; promotes mRNA stability, export, translation; added at Ser2-phosphorylated CTD. All three modifications are co-transcriptional and coupled to the Pol II CTD phosphorylation code.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'The branch-point adenosine in a pre-mRNA intron performs which function during splicing?',choices:['A) Its 5-prime hydroxyl attacks the 5-prime splice site to begin the first transesterification','B) Its 2-prime hydroxyl attacks the 5-prime splice site to form the lariat intermediate','C) It base-pairs with U1 snRNA to position the 5-prime splice site','D) It is methylated by SAM-dependent methyltransferase to mark the intron for degradation'],answer:1,why:'The branch-point adenosine, which is looped out when U2 snRNA base-pairs with the branch-point sequence, contributes its 2-prime hydroxyl group as the nucleophile for the first transesterification reaction of splicing. This 2-prime-OH attacks the phosphodiester bond at the 5-prime splice site, releasing the upstream exon and forming the 2-prime,5-prime phosphodiester bond of the lariat. U1 snRNA base-pairs with the 5-prime splice site, not the branch point.'},{stem:'Which combination of sequence elements is recognized by the polyadenylation machinery to direct cleavage and poly-A addition at the 3-prime end of pre-mRNA?',choices:['A) GU at the 5-prime splice site and AG at the 3-prime splice site','B) AAUAAA approximately 10-30 nt upstream of the cleavage site and a GU-rich downstream sequence element','C) TATAAT at -10 and TTGACA at -35 relative to the transcription start site','D) The 7-methylguanosine cap structure and the Kozak consensus sequence'],answer:1,why:'Polyadenylation requires the AAUAAA hexamer (recognized by CPSF) approximately 10-30 nucleotides upstream of the cleavage site, and a GU-rich/U-rich downstream sequence element (recognized by CstF). Cleavage occurs between these two elements, and poly(A) polymerase adds approximately 200 A residues to the upstream cleavage product. The GU/AG sequences are splice site elements, TATAAT/-35 are bacterial promoter elements, and the cap/Kozak are translation initiation elements.'}]},{id:'12.4',num:'12.4',title:'12.4 Prokaryotic Gene Regulation: The Lac and Trp Operons',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Prokaryotic gene regulation is dominated by the operon model: a cluster of functionally related genes transcribed as a single polycistronic mRNA from a shared promoter, with expression controlled by regulatory proteins that bind to specific DNA sequences near the promoter. The lac operon of E. coli is the paradigm for inducible operons regulated by both negative and positive control mechanisms, and the trp operon is the paradigm for repressible operons with an additional post-initiation attenuation mechanism.'},{t:'p',x:'The lac operon encodes three structural genes in a single transcriptional unit: lacZ (encoding beta-galactosidase, which hydrolyzes lactose to glucose and galactose), lacY (encoding lactose permease, a membrane protein that transports lactose into the cell), and lacA (encoding thiogalactoside transacetylase, which acetylates beta-galactosides and whose physiological function in the operon context is less clear but likely aids in removal of nonspecific beta-galactosides). These structural genes are transcribed from the lac promoter (Plac), which overlaps with the operator (a specific DNA sequence recognized by the lac repressor). Upstream of the structural genes and promoter is a separate constitutively expressed gene, lacI, which encodes the lac repressor protein.'},{t:'p',x:'Negative control of the lac operon: when lactose is absent from the growth medium, the lac repressor (a homotetramer of lacI gene product) is in its active conformation and binds tightly to the lac operator (a 21-bp palindromic sequence that overlaps with the Plac promoter and the +1 transcription start). Repressor binding physically blocks RNA polymerase from binding to or clearing the Plac promoter, preventing elongation into the structural genes. When lactose is present, a small fraction is converted by basal levels of beta-galactosidase to allolactose (a structural isomer of lactose in which galactose is linked via a 1-6 rather than 1-4 bond). Allolactose is the inducer that binds to the repressor, causing a conformational change that greatly reduces the repressor\'s affinity for the operator DNA. The repressor dissociates from the operator, allowing RNA polymerase access to Plac and transcription of lacZ, lacY, and lacA. The structural consequence is an inducible system: the operon is off in the absence of lactose and on in its presence.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'LAC OPERON LOGIC TABLE',x:'Lactose absent + Glucose present: repressor ON (no allolactose), CAP-cAMP low (glucose high suppresses cAMP). Result: transcription essentially off. Lactose absent + Glucose absent: repressor ON, CAP-cAMP high. Result: transcription essentially off (no inducer to remove repressor). Lactose present + Glucose present: repressor OFF (allolactose present), CAP-cAMP low (glucose still present). Result: transcription low/basal (polymerase can bind promoter but without CAP activation the rate is low). Lactose present + Glucose absent: repressor OFF, CAP-cAMP HIGH. Result: transcription MAXIMUM (both repressor removed and CAP-cAMP activates). KEY PRINCIPLE: FULL lac induction requires lactose present (to remove repressor) AND glucose absent (to maximize cAMP-CAP activation). The cell only maximally expresses lac genes when the preferred carbon source (glucose) is absent and the alternative carbon source (lactose) is available.'},{t:'p',x:'Positive control of the lac operon via catabolite repression: glucose is the preferred carbon source for E. coli, and when glucose is abundant, expression of genes for metabolizing alternative carbon sources (lactose, arabinose, maltose, etc.) is kept low regardless of whether those alternative substrates are present. The molecular mechanism operates through intracellular cAMP levels. When glucose is abundant, the phosphotransferase system (PTS) enzyme IIA-Glc is predominantly dephosphorylated, and in this state it inhibits adenylyl cyclase (also through interactions with other membrane transport proteins). Low adenylyl cyclase activity means low intracellular cAMP. When glucose is absent, enzyme IIA-Glc accumulates in its phosphorylated form, which activates adenylyl cyclase, raising intracellular cAMP. The elevated cAMP binds to the catabolite activator protein (CAP, also called CRP, the cAMP receptor protein), inducing a conformational change that allows CAP-cAMP to bind specifically to the CAP site, a DNA sequence approximately 61 bp upstream of the lacZ transcription start site. CAP-cAMP acts as a transcriptional activator: it makes direct contacts with the alpha subunit of RNA polymerase (specifically the C-terminal domain of the alpha subunit), recruiting the enzyme to Plac and stimulating open complex formation by approximately 50-fold. Without CAP-cAMP, RNAP binds the lac promoter poorly because the lac promoter has a suboptimal -35 element; CAP-cAMP compensates for this weakness by providing the recruitment energy.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'BRIDGE: CATABOLITE REPRESSION AND THE HIERARCHY OF CARBON SOURCE UTILIZATION',x:'Catabolite repression is how bacteria prioritize glucose use over all other carbon sources. The term "repression" is historically confusing because the mechanism is actually positive regulation by CAP-cAMP acting on non-glucose carbon source operons, combined with the consequence that these operons are expressed at low rates when glucose is present (and cAMP is therefore low). When bacteria are grown on glucose + lactose, they first consume all available glucose (during which lac genes are expressed only at low basal levels, because cAMP is low and CAP is inactive even though the repressor is partially off). After glucose is exhausted, cAMP rises, CAP-cAMP activates, and lac expression shoots up: this creates the classic diauxic growth curve (two phases of exponential growth separated by a lag). The cAMP-CAP system is therefore a metabolic sensor: cAMP reports the absence of glucose, and CAP-cAMP translates that report into transcriptional activation of the alternative carbon source operon. The underlying logic is elegant economy: why pay the metabolic cost of producing enzymes to metabolize a less efficient fuel when the preferred fuel is available?'},{t:'p',x:'The trp operon encodes five structural genes for tryptophan biosynthesis: trpE, trpD, trpC, trpB, and trpA (encoding the sequential enzymes of the tryptophan biosynthetic pathway). The regulatory logic is the mirror image of the lac operon: rather than being induced by the substrate (as lacZ is induced by lactose), the trp operon is repressed by the product (tryptophan). The trpR gene encodes the trp repressor, which in its apo form (without tryptophan) is an inactive, unfolded protein that cannot bind DNA. When cellular tryptophan concentrations rise, tryptophan acts as a corepressor: it binds to the apo-repressor and induces a conformational change that activates the trp repressor by enabling it to fold and position its helix-turn-helix DNA-binding motif correctly. The active repressor binds the trp operator (which overlaps the trp promoter, analogous to the lac operator) and blocks transcription. When tryptophan is scarce, the repressor is in the inactive apo form, and the trp genes are transcribed.'},{t:'p',x:'Attenuation provides a second, independent layer of regulation of the trp operon that responds more rapidly and sensitively to tryptophan levels than the repressor-operator mechanism. Between the trp operator and the first structural gene (trpE), there is a 162-nt leader sequence that contains an open reading frame encoding a 14-amino acid leader peptide with two consecutive tryptophan codons (Trp codons 10 and 11). This leader sequence can fold into two alternative RNA secondary structures: an antiterminator (hairpin formed by regions 2:3 of the leader RNA) and a terminator (hairpin formed by regions 3:4, a typical rho-independent terminator followed by a poly-U stretch). Which hairpin forms depends on the position of the ribosome translating the leader peptide, which in turn depends on whether tryptophan-charged tRNATrp is available.'},{t:'p',x:'When tryptophan is abundant: ribosomes translate the leader peptide efficiently, incorporating both Trp residues without stalling. The ribosome translates through region 1 and into region 2 of the leader RNA, physically blocking region 2 from participating in hairpin formation. Without region 2 available, regions 3 and 4 fold into the terminator hairpin. Transcription of the remainder of the operon terminates in the leader region, and little full-length trp mRNA is produced. When tryptophan is scarce: the ribosome stalls at the consecutive Trp codons in the leader peptide because charged tRNATrp is depleted. The stalled ribosome occupies only region 1 of the leader RNA, leaving region 2 free. Region 2 base-pairs with region 3 to form the antiterminator hairpin, which prevents region 3 from participating in the terminator hairpin. With the terminator hairpin unable to form, RNA polymerase reads through the leader region and transcribes the full operon. Attenuation thus directly couples the translational status of the ribosome (a real-time sensor of the available charged tRNATrp pool) to the transcriptional output of the trp operon, and it can reduce trp operon expression by approximately 8 to 10-fold relative to the derepressed state.'},{t:'formula',x:'Trp abundant: ribosome reads leader = region 2 blocked = regions 3:4 form terminator hairpin = transcription stops in leader. Trp scarce: ribosome stalls at Trp codons = region 2 free = regions 2:3 form antiterminator = regions 3:4 CANNOT form = transcription reads through into structural genes.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'E. coli cells are grown in a medium containing glucose and lactose. Which statement best describes lac operon expression?',choices:['A) Maximum transcription because both lactose and glucose are present','B) Low transcription because glucose keeps cAMP low and CAP-cAMP activation is absent','C) Maximum transcription because the lac repressor is inactive in the presence of lactose','D) No transcription because glucose activates the lac repressor directly'],answer:1,why:'When glucose is present, the PTS system keeps adenylyl cyclase inhibited, resulting in low intracellular cAMP. Without cAMP, CAP (CRP) cannot bind the CAP site and the RNA polymerase recruitment effect is lost. Although allolactose from the lactose present will partially inactivate the repressor, RNA polymerase binds the lac promoter poorly without CAP-cAMP activation (the -35 element is suboptimal). The result is low basal transcription, not maximum. Maximum transcription requires both allolactose (to remove repressor) AND high cAMP-CAP (requires glucose to be absent).'},{stem:'In the trp operon attenuation mechanism, what occurs when tryptophan is scarce?',choices:['A) The trp repressor binds tryptophan and blocks the operator','B) The ribosome stalls at consecutive Trp codons in the leader peptide, allowing the antiterminator hairpin to form so transcription continues','C) High cAMP levels activate CAP, which recruits RNA polymerase to the trp promoter','D) Rho helicase is recruited to the leader region and terminates transcription of the leader peptide only'],answer:1,why:'Attenuation operates through the availability of charged tRNATrp. When tryptophan is scarce, charged tRNATrp is depleted, and the ribosome stalls at the two consecutive Trp codons in the leader peptide. The stalled ribosome covers only region 1 of the leader RNA, leaving region 2 free to base-pair with region 3, forming the antiterminator hairpin (2:3). This prevents region 3 from pairing with region 4 to form the terminator hairpin, so transcription continues through the leader into the structural genes. Choice A describes repressor-mediated control, which is a separate mechanism.'}]},{id:'12.5',num:'12.5',title:'12.5 Eukaryotic Gene Regulation: Transcription Factors, Chromatin, and Epigenetics',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'In eukaryotes, the decision to transcribe a gene is made at multiple levels simultaneously. Gene-specific transcription factors bind enhancer and promoter-proximal sequences to recruit or repel the Pol II PIC. The chromatin environment determines whether those sequences are accessible to transcription factors at all. Epigenetic modifications (histone marks and DNA methylation) create heritable patterns of gene expression that can be maintained through cell division without changes in the underlying DNA sequence. All three levels are integrated at every regulated gene.'},{t:'p',x:'Transcription factors are proteins with at least two distinct functional domains: a DNA-binding domain (DBD) that recognizes specific DNA sequences, and an activation domain (AD) or repression domain that contacts the Mediator complex, GTFs, or chromatin remodeling enzymes to modulate Pol II activity. The modular nature of transcription factors was established by the domain-swap experiments of Ptashne and colleagues in the 1980s, which showed that the DBD and AD are independently functional modules that can be exchanged between proteins to create chimeric activators. Several structurally distinct DBD families are recurrently tested because they appear in a wide range of human transcription factors and in clinical vignettes.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DNA-BINDING DOMAIN FAMILIES IN TRANSCRIPTION FACTORS',x:'HELIX-TURN-HELIX (HTH): the oldest and most widespread DBD architecture; two alpha helices connected by a short turn; the recognition helix inserts into the major groove; present in homeodomain proteins (Hox proteins, Pax proteins) and many bacterial repressors (lac repressor uses a modified HTH). HOMEODOMAIN: a specialized 60-aa HTH variant found in developmental transcription factors encoded by Hox genes; homeodomain proteins establish the anterior-posterior body axis in development; mutation in HOXD13 causes synpolydactyly. ZINC FINGER (Cys2-His2): most common DBD in the human genome (approximately 700 human proteins); each finger is a ~28-aa module coordinating a Zn2+ ion between two Cys and two His residues; the C-terminal alpha helix inserts into the major groove; transcription factors with multiple zinc fingers (SP1, WT1, Kruppel-like factors) can contact extensive stretches of DNA; Cys4 zinc finger (or nuclear receptor zinc finger): found in steroid hormone receptors (see below); four cysteines coordinate Zn2+. LEUCINE ZIPPER (bZIP): two helices from two protein subunits interdigitate via leucines at every seventh residue to form a coiled-coil dimerization interface; the basic region N-terminal to the zipper contacts DNA; leucine zipper proteins always function as dimers (homo- or hetero-); key examples: GCN4 (yeast AP-1), c-Fos/c-Jun (AP-1 in mammals), C/EBP family, CREB (activated by PKA-mediated phosphorylation). HELIX-LOOP-HELIX (HLH): dimerization domain of loop-helix architecture; examples: Myc/Max/Mad family; Myc-Max activates growth genes; Mad-Max competes with Myc-Max and represses the same targets; HER2/ErbB2 signaling activates Myc expression; HLH proteins E2A, Id; MyoD (master regulator of muscle differentiation).'},{t:'p',x:'Nuclear receptors form a superfamily of ligand-activated transcription factors that respond to lipophilic signaling molecules: steroid hormones (glucocorticoids, mineralocorticoids, sex steroids), thyroid hormone, retinoic acid, vitamin D, and fatty acid derivatives (PPARs). The glucocorticoid receptor (GR) is the paradigmatic example of a cytoplasmic nuclear receptor. In the absence of cortisol, GR is held in the cytoplasm in an inactive, chaperone-bound complex with Hsp90, Hsp70, and other co-chaperones; this complex maintains GR in a conformation with high ligand-binding affinity but prevents DNA binding. Cortisol (a small, lipophilic steroid) diffuses freely across the plasma membrane, binds to the ligand-binding domain of GR in the cytoplasm, and induces a conformational change in the C-terminal helix (helix 12, the activation function-2 helix or AF-2 helix) that repositions it to create a surface compatible with coactivator binding and simultaneously displaces Hsp90. The ligand-bound GR dimerizes, exposes its nuclear localization signal, is imported into the nucleus, and binds glucocorticoid response elements (GREs): palindromic half-sites (TGTTCT separated by 3 bp on each strand). Thyroid hormone receptor (TR) and retinoic acid receptor (RAR) differ from GR in that they reside in the nucleus even without ligand, bound to response elements in complex with corepressors (NCoR, SMRT); ligand binding causes exchange of corepressor for coactivator (SRC-1, p300, PCAF).'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'CLINICAL BRIDGE: GLUCOCORTICOID RECEPTOR AND ANTI-INFLAMMATORY THERAPY',x:'Synthetic glucocorticoids (prednisone, dexamethasone, budesonide) bind GR with high affinity and act in the nucleus by two mechanisms. Transactivation: GR-GRE binding activates anti-inflammatory genes including annexin-1 (inhibits phospholipase A2, reducing prostaglandin synthesis) and the DUSP1 phosphatase (inactivates p38 MAPK). Transrepression: ligand-bound GR monomers interact directly with AP-1 (Fos-Jun) and NF-kB to inhibit their transcriptional activity without GRE binding, suppressing pro-inflammatory cytokine genes (IL-1beta, IL-6, TNF-alpha, COX-2). The adverse effects of systemic glucocorticoids map directly onto the physiological gene programs they activate: hyperglycemia (gluconeogenic gene induction), osteoporosis (decreased RANK-L and osteoblast gene expression, increased osteoclast survival), immunosuppression (lymphocyte apoptosis, reduced cytokine transcription), HPA axis suppression (suppression of CRH and ACTH genes), cataracts (lens epithelium), and skin thinning (reduced collagen gene transcription in fibroblasts).'},{t:'p',x:'Chromatin remodeling is the enzymatic alteration of nucleosome position, composition, or density to modulate DNA accessibility for transcription factors and the transcription machinery. The nucleosome core particle consists of approximately 147 bp of DNA wrapped approximately 1.65 times around an octamer of histone proteins (two copies each of H2A, H2B, H3, and H4). This wrapping compacts DNA and sterically occludes many protein-binding sites. Two major classes of enzyme control chromatin accessibility. ATP-dependent chromatin remodelers use the energy of ATP hydrolysis to slide nucleosomes along DNA (changing position), evict nucleosomes from DNA (increasing accessibility at specific loci), insert histone variants (H2A.Z, macroH2A, H3.3), or restructure nucleosome composition. The SWI/SNF complex (mammalian BAF/PBAF) is the most studied ATP-dependent remodeler; it is recruited by transcriptional activators to promoters and enhancers and generates nucleosome-free regions that allow GTF binding. SWI/SNF subunit mutations (SMARCA4, ARID1A, SMARCB1) are among the most common driver mutations in human cancer, particularly in ovarian clear cell carcinoma, renal rhabdoid tumor, lung adenocarcinoma, and others.'},{t:'p',x:'Histone-modifying enzymes write, read, and erase chemical marks on the histone tail domains (disordered N-terminal extensions of each core histone that project outward from the nucleosome surface) and occasionally on the histone globular domains. Histone acetyltransferases (HATs, also called KATs) add acetyl groups from acetyl-CoA to lysine side chains on histone tails. Acetylation neutralizes the positive charge of lysine, weakening the electrostatic interaction between the histone and the negatively charged DNA phosphate backbone; acetylated nucleosomes are less tightly packed and more accessible. Histone deacetylases (HDACs) remove acetyl groups, restoring the positive charge and promoting chromatin compaction. Key HAT complexes: SAGA/PCAF (HAT is GCN5/PCAF, activated at regulated genes by transcriptional activators), CBP/p300 (coactivators with intrinsic HAT activity, phospho-CREB binding protein and its paralog). Key HDAC complexes: NuRD, Sin3A, CoREST (all recruit class I/II HDACs to repressed genes and silenced developmental programs).'},{t:'p',x:'Histone methylation is catalyzed by histone methyltransferases (HMTs, also called KMTs) using SAM as the methyl donor; methylation can be mono-, di-, or trimethylation (me1, me2, me3). Unlike acetylation, methylation does not neutralize charge; instead, it creates a docking platform recognized by specific methyl-binding domains. The biological outcome depends entirely on which residue is methylated. H3K4me3 (trimethylation of lysine 4 on histone H3) marks the promoters and 5-prime regions of actively transcribed genes and is recognized by PHD finger domains in TFIID subunits and other coactivators, linking H3K4me3 to active transcription initiation. H3K27me3 (trimethylation of lysine 27 on H3) is deposited by the Polycomb Repressive Complex 2 (PRC2, containing the EZH2 methyltransferase) and marks genes silenced by Polycomb repression; H3K27me3 is recognized by the PRC1 chromodomain, which compacts chromatin. Overactivating mutations in EZH2 are found in diffuse large B-cell lymphoma and other hematologic malignancies. H3K36me3 (deposited over gene bodies by SETD2) marks active transcription elongation. H3K9me3 marks constitutive heterochromatin (pericentromeric and telomeric repeats) and is the mark that recruits HP1 (heterochromatin protein 1) to compact silent regions.'},{t:'p',x:'DNA methylation at CpG dinucleotides provides an additional layer of epigenetic silencing. DNA methyltransferases (DNMT3A and DNMT3B establish de novo methylation; DNMT1 maintains methylation through DNA replication by methylating the newly synthesized strand using the parental methylated strand as template, via its preference for hemi-methylated DNA) add a methyl group to the carbon-5 position of cytosine (5-methylcytosine, 5mC) within CpG dinucleotides. The mechanism of transcriptional silencing by CpG methylation involves two pathways: methyl-CpG-binding proteins (MeCP2, MBD1, MBD2) recruit HDAC complexes to methylated regions, promoting chromatin compaction; and methylated CpGs directly inhibit the binding of some transcription factors (those whose DBD contacts unmethylated cytosine). In cancer, CpG island hypermethylation at the promoters of tumor suppressor genes silences them: MLH1 (in sporadic microsatellite instability-positive colorectal cancer), CDKN2A/p16 (in many solid tumors), VHL (in renal cell carcinoma), BRCA1 (in a subset of sporadic breast and ovarian cancers), and CDH1 (E-cadherin, in lobular breast cancer and gastric cancer). Simultaneously, global DNA hypomethylation at repetitive elements (LINE-1, SINE elements) occurs in cancer, permitting transposon expression and genomic instability.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'HISTONE MARKS HIGH-YIELD TABLE',x:'H3K4me3: active promoters; deposited by MLL/SET1 complexes; recognized by TFIID subunit PHD fingers; found at TSS of expressed genes. H3K27me3: Polycomb repression; deposited by PRC2 (EZH2 is the methyltransferase); recognized by PRC1 chromodomain; silences developmental genes; EZH2 mutations drive lymphoma. H3K9me3: constitutive heterochromatin; deposited by SUV39H; recognized by HP1; pericentromeric/telomeric. H3K36me3: active gene bodies; deposited by SETD2; linked to mRNA processing; SETD2 mutation causes clear cell renal cell carcinoma. H3K27Ac: active enhancers and promoters (enhancers have H3K4me1 + H3K27Ac); deposited by CBP/p300. H3K4me1: primed or active enhancers. Histone acetylation overall: open chromatin, active; deposited by HATs (p300, CBP, GCN5); removed by HDACs; HDAC inhibitors (vorinostat, romidepsin) used in cancer treatment. CpG methylation: silencing; DNMT3A/B (de novo), DNMT1 (maintenance); promoter CpG hypermethylation silences tumor suppressors in cancer; 5mC can be oxidized to 5hmC by TET enzymes (active demethylation).'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'The glucocorticoid receptor (GR) is held in the cytoplasm in an inactive state by which protein complex, and what event triggers its release and nuclear translocation?',choices:['A) NCoR/SMRT corepressor complex; cortisol binding releases the corepressor','B) Hsp90 chaperone complex; cortisol binding causes conformational change that displaces Hsp90 and exposes the nuclear localization signal','C) Importin-alpha; cortisol binding to the NLS allows importin recognition','D) The SWI/SNF complex; cortisol binding triggers chromatin remodeling at GREs'],answer:1,why:'In the absence of ligand, GR is held in the cytoplasm in a large complex with Hsp90, Hsp70, and other co-chaperones. This complex maintains GR in a high-ligand-affinity but transcriptionally inactive state. When cortisol binds the GR ligand-binding domain, it induces a conformational change that repositions the AF-2 helix, destabilizes the Hsp90 interaction, and exposes the GR nuclear localization signal. GR dimerizes, is imported via importin-alpha, and binds GREs. NCoR/SMRT corepressors are relevant to TR and RAR (which reside in the nucleus even without ligand), not to GR.'},{stem:'Which histone modification mark is characteristically found at the promoters of actively transcribed genes and is deposited by MLL/SET1 family methyltransferases?',choices:['A) H3K27me3','B) H3K9me3','C) H3K4me3','D) H3K36me3'],answer:2,why:'H3K4me3 is the mark of active gene promoters. It is deposited by MLL/SET1 family histone methyltransferases at the 5-prime regions and promoters of actively expressed genes. TFIID subunits contain PHD finger domains that directly read H3K4me3, linking this mark to transcription initiation. H3K27me3 marks Polycomb-repressed genes (EZH2). H3K9me3 marks constitutive heterochromatin (SUV39H). H3K36me3 marks active gene bodies during elongation (SETD2).'}]},{id:'12.6',num:'12.6',title:'12.6 Small RNAs: miRNA, siRNA, and piRNA Pathways',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Post-transcriptional gene silencing by small RNAs is a conserved mechanism present in essentially all eukaryotes. The three major classes of small RNAs differ in their biogenesis, the proteins they associate with, and the biological processes they regulate, but all three use a common principle: a short guide RNA strand loaded into an Argonaute family protein directs sequence-specific silencing of complementary RNA targets.'},{t:'p',x:'MicroRNAs (miRNAs) are approximately 22-nucleotide non-coding RNAs encoded in the genome, typically within introns of protein-coding genes or in dedicated miRNA gene clusters, and transcribed by RNA Pol II as long primary transcripts (pri-miRNAs). Processing begins in the nucleus: the Microprocessor complex, composed of the RNase III enzyme Drosha and its obligate cofactor DGCR8 (DiGeorge Critical Region 8, also called Pasha), cleaves the pri-miRNA approximately 11 bp below the base of the characteristic stem-loop hairpin structure, generating a ~65-nt precursor miRNA (pre-miRNA) with a 2-nt 3-prime overhang. The pre-miRNA is exported to the cytoplasm by Exportin-5 in a RanGTP-dependent manner. In the cytoplasm, the RNase III enzyme Dicer (in complex with TRBP or PACT) cleaves the pre-miRNA loop approximately 22 bp from the base, generating a ~22-bp miRNA duplex with 2-nt 3-prime overhangs on both ends. This duplex is loaded into the Argonaute (AGO) protein complex. One strand (the guide strand or mature miRNA) is selectively retained in the AGO complex based on thermodynamic asymmetry (the strand whose 5-prime end is less stably base-paired is preferentially loaded as the guide strand), while the other strand (the passenger strand or miRNA*) is ejected and degraded. The AGO-miRNA complex constitutes the core of the RISC (RNA-induced silencing complex).'},{t:'p',x:'RISC with a loaded miRNA guide searches for target mRNAs using the miRNA seed region (approximately nucleotides 2 through 8 at the 5-prime end of the miRNA), which provides the primary determinant of target recognition. Target recognition occurs predominantly in the 3-prime untranslated region (3-prime UTR) of mRNAs. In animals, miRNA-target interactions are typically imperfect (mismatches and bulges are common outside the seed region), which allows a single miRNA to target hundreds of different mRNAs. The downstream silencing mechanisms depend on AGO protein identity and on the degree of complementarity. For partial complementarity (the norm in animals): the RISC complex recruits the GW182 protein (TNRC6 family), which in turn recruits deadenylase complexes (CCR4-NOT) to remove the poly(A) tail of the target mRNA; this promotes target mRNA decapping and degradation in P-bodies (cytoplasmic RNA processing bodies), or alternatively promotes translational repression without immediate mRNA destabilization. For near-perfect complementarity (more common in plants, and in the case of siRNAs): AGO2 (the only human Argonaute with slicer/endonuclease activity) cleaves the mRNA between nucleotide positions 10 and 11 of the guide RNA. miRNA pathways are clinically relevant: miR-21 is one of the most frequently upregulated miRNAs in cancer (it targets multiple tumor suppressors); let-7 is a tumor suppressor miRNA that targets RAS; miR-122 is required for hepatitis C virus RNA replication in hepatocytes (the LNA-antisense drug miravirsen targets miR-122).'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'miRNA vs siRNA: BIOGENESIS AND MECHANISM COMPARISON',x:'miRNA: encoded in the genome; transcribed by Pol II as pri-miRNA; processed by Drosha/DGCR8 in nucleus to pre-miRNA; Exportin-5 nuclear export; Dicer in cytoplasm generates ~22 bp duplex; guide strand loaded into AGO1/2/3/4; targets mRNA 3-prime UTR with imperfect complementarity; causes translational repression and mRNA deadenylation/degradation; one miRNA can target hundreds of mRNAs; used by the cell to fine-tune gene expression programs. siRNA: exogenous double-stranded RNA (from viruses, transposons, or introduced artificially for RNAi experiments); processed by Dicer into ~21 bp duplexes with 2-nt 3-prime overhangs; loaded into AGO2 in RISC; targets mRNA with near-perfect complementarity; AGO2 cleaves target between positions 10-11; single target specificity; used experimentally as a gene knockdown tool (RNAi); therapeutic application: patisiran (siRNA targeting TTR for hereditary transthyretin amyloidosis), givosiran (targets ALAS1 for acute hepatic porphyria). KEY DIFFERENCE: miRNAs are endogenous, target imperfect matches, cause translational repression plus mRNA decay; siRNAs are typically exogenous, require near-perfect matching, cause mRNA cleavage.'},{t:'p',x:'PIWI-interacting RNAs (piRNAs) are a distinct class of small RNAs (24 to 31 nt, somewhat larger than miRNAs) expressed predominantly in the germline (spermatocytes, oocytes) and associated with Argonaute proteins of the PIWI clade (MILI, MIWI, MIWI2 in mice; HIWI/PIWIL1/2/3/4 in humans) rather than the AGO clade. The primary biological function of piRNAs is to suppress transposons in the germline, protecting genome integrity across generations. piRNAs are generated from long, single-stranded precursor transcripts from piRNA clusters in the genome, in a Dicer-independent process; the primary piRNA biogenesis involves endonucleolytic cleavage by MIWI2, and an amplification loop (the ping-pong cycle) in which antisense piRNAs loaded in MILI guide cleavage of sense transposon transcripts, which themselves become new sense piRNAs; the sense piRNAs then guide MILI to cleave antisense transcripts, generating new antisense piRNAs. Defective piRNA pathways cause transposon mobilization in the germline, leading to insertional mutagenesis and male infertility.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'HIGH-YIELD: SMALL RNA PATHWAYS FOR THE MCAT',x:'miRNA biogenesis: Pol II transcribes pri-miRNA; Drosha/DGCR8 cleave to pre-miRNA in nucleus; Exportin-5 exports to cytoplasm; Dicer cleaves to ~22 nt mature miRNA duplex; guide strand loaded into AGO-RISC; binds 3-prime UTR of target mRNA; imperfect complementarity leads to translational repression and mRNA deadenylation; AGO2 can also cleave targets with perfect match. siRNA: exogenous dsRNA; Dicer processing; RISC-AGO2 loaded; near-perfect match; mRNA cleavage; RNAi knockdown tool; therapeutic: patisiran (TTR silencing). piRNA: germline-specific; PIWI proteins; Dicer-independent; suppresses transposons; ping-pong amplification cycle. Clinical: miR-21 oncomiR (targets tumor suppressors); let-7 tumor suppressor miRNA; miR-122 required for HCV replication.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'During miRNA biogenesis, which enzyme cleaves the pre-miRNA in the cytoplasm to generate the mature miRNA duplex?',choices:['A) Drosha','B) Exportin-5','C) Dicer','D) AGO2 (Argonaute-2)'],answer:2,why:'Dicer is the cytoplasmic RNase III enzyme that cleaves the pre-miRNA (the ~65-nt hairpin exported from the nucleus) approximately 22 bp from its base, generating the ~22 bp miRNA duplex. Drosha (with DGCR8) performs the first cleavage in the nucleus to generate the pre-miRNA from the pri-miRNA. Exportin-5 exports the pre-miRNA from the nucleus to the cytoplasm. AGO2 is the slicer Argonaute protein that is loaded with the guide strand after Dicer processing.'},{stem:'An siRNA targeting the mRNA of a disease-causing gene is introduced into human cells. The mRNA is cleaved between positions 10 and 11 of the siRNA guide strand. Which protein executes this cleavage?',choices:['A) Dicer','B) Drosha','C) PIWI','D) AGO2 (Argonaute-2)'],answer:3,why:'AGO2 is the only human Argonaute family member with endonuclease (slicer) activity. When RISC containing AGO2 and a fully complementary guide siRNA recognizes its target mRNA, AGO2 cleaves the mRNA strand between the nucleotides complementary to positions 10 and 11 of the guide. Dicer generates the siRNA duplex but does not cleave target mRNAs. Drosha processes pri-miRNA in the nucleus. PIWI proteins are associated with piRNAs in the germline.'}]},{id:'12.7',num:'12.7',title:'12.7 RNA Processing: Alternative Splicing, RNA Editing, and Nonsense-Mediated Decay',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'After the spliceosome assembles and carries out the two transesterification reactions of splicing, the result is not always the same. The spliceosome can be directed by regulatory factors to include or exclude specific exons, to use alternative 5-prime or 3-prime splice sites, or to retain introns, generating distinct mRNA isoforms from the same pre-mRNA template. This process, called alternative splicing, is pervasive in multicellular eukaryotes: approximately 95% of human multi-exon genes undergo alternative splicing, and the estimated number of distinct protein isoforms encoded by the approximately 20,000 human protein-coding genes is well over 100,000. Alternative splicing is the primary mechanism by which functional diversity vastly exceeds gene number in complex organisms.'},{t:'p',x:'The choice between alternative splice site pairs is controlled by splicing regulatory sequences and the proteins that bind them. Exonic splicing enhancers (ESEs) and intronic splicing enhancers (ISEs) promote usage of nearby splice sites; exonic splicing silencers (ESSs) and intronic splicing silencers (ISSs) repress splice site usage. The principal activating proteins are SR proteins (named for their Ser-Arg-rich domain), which bind ESE sequences and recruit spliceosomal components to nearby splice sites. The principal repressive proteins are hnRNPs (heterogeneous nuclear ribonucleoproteins), which bind ESS and ISS sequences and block SR protein binding or directly compete with spliceosomal factors. The relative concentrations of SR proteins and hnRNPs vary between cell types and in response to signaling events, allowing the same pre-mRNA to be spliced differently in different tissues or under different physiological states. A well-studied example is the Drosophila sex-determination gene dsx: a female-specific SR protein (Tra) promotes inclusion of a female-specific exon; in males, Tra is absent, and the default splicing pattern produces a male-specific isoform.'},{t:'p',x:'Three clinical examples of alternative splicing are tested at the MCAT and Step 1 level. First, Duchenne muscular dystrophy (DMD): the dystrophin gene (DMD) is the largest gene in the human genome at 2.4 Mb, and its 79 exons are subject to many types of mutation. Most DMD-causing mutations are out-of-frame deletions that disrupt the reading frame and introduce a premature stop codon, resulting in complete absence of dystrophin protein. Exon-skipping therapy uses antisense oligonucleotides (ASOs) that base-pair with specific exonic regions to sterically block SR protein binding and spliceosomal recognition of the targeted exon, causing the spliceosome to skip that exon entirely. For patients with exon 51 deletion causing a frameshift, skipping exon 51 (already deleted in some patients) or skipping exon 51 in patients with adjacent out-of-frame deletions can restore the reading frame to produce a truncated but partially functional protein similar to Becker muscular dystrophy. Eteplirsen and casimersen are FDA-approved exon-skipping ASOs for specific DMD exon 51 and 45 deletion mutations.'},{t:'p',x:'Second, spinal muscular atrophy (SMA): SMA is caused by biallelic loss-of-function mutations or deletions of the SMN1 gene (Survival Motor Neuron 1) on chromosome 5q13. A nearly identical paralogous gene, SMN2, is present in the same chromosomal region and differs from SMN1 by only a few nucleotides, the most critical being a C-to-T transition in exon 7 at position +6 (relative to the exon 7 start). This C-to-T change creates an exonic splicing silencer and disrupts an exonic splicing enhancer, causing approximately 80 to 90% of SMN2 transcripts to skip exon 7 during splicing. The exon 7-skipped protein product (SMN-delta7) is unstable and degraded, and the SMN2 gene produces only approximately 10 to 20% of full-length SMN protein, insufficient to compensate for SMN1 loss. SMN protein is required for snRNP biogenesis (assembly of the Sm proteins onto snRNAs) and therefore for spliceosome function. Nusinersen (Spinraza) is an ASO that masks the ISS-N1 intronic splicing silencer just downstream of exon 7 in SMN2 pre-mRNA, forcing inclusion of exon 7 and producing more full-length SMN protein. Risdiplam is a small-molecule splicing modifier with the same goal: it stabilizes the 5-prime splice site of SMN2 exon 7 and modulates SR protein binding to promote inclusion. Both drugs transform SMA from a rapidly fatal infant disease to a manageable condition.'},{t:'p',x:'Third, BRCA1 and deep intronic mutations: BRCA1 is a DNA damage response protein; germline mutations in BRCA1 cause hereditary breast and ovarian cancer syndrome. A subset of pathogenic BRCA1 mutations lie deep within introns and create new 5-prime or 3-prime splice sites (cryptic splice sites), causing inclusion of a pseudoexon (a segment of intronic sequence normally excluded from the mRNA) in the mature BRCA1 mRNA. The pseudoexon introduces a frameshift or premature stop codon. These mutations are invisible to standard exon-focused sequencing and illustrate why full-gene sequencing and RNA-level analysis are needed for complete BRCA1 diagnosis.'},{t:'p',x:'RNA editing refers to post-transcriptional changes to the nucleotide sequence of an RNA molecule, altering its coding information without changing the underlying DNA. Two major types of RNA editing operate in mammals. Adenosine-to-inosine (A-to-I) editing is catalyzed by ADAR (adenosine deaminase acting on RNA) enzymes, which convert adenosine to inosine by deamination of the C6-amino group. Inosine is decoded by the ribosome and reverse-transcribed by retroviral reverse transcriptases as guanosine (G), so A-to-I editing is functionally equivalent to an A-to-G change. The most clinically important ADAR editing event is at the GluA2 subunit (GRIA2) of the AMPA-type glutamate receptor: ADAR2 edits the codon encoding glutamine at position 607 in the channel pore-forming loop from CAG (Gln) to CIG (read as CGG, Arg). This Gln607Arg change converts the AMPA receptor from Ca2+-permeable to Ca2+-impermeable, which is critical for the health of hippocampal neurons. ALS (amyotrophic lateral sclerosis) patients show dramatically reduced GluA2 Q/R editing in motor neurons; the resulting Ca2+-permeable AMPA receptors are thought to contribute to motor neuron excitotoxic death.'},{t:'p',x:'Cytidine-to-uridine (C-to-U) RNA editing is exemplified by the editing of the apolipoprotein B (ApoB) mRNA by APOBEC1 (apolipoprotein B mRNA-editing enzyme, catalytic polypeptide 1). In the liver, the full-length ApoB-100 protein (4,536 amino acids) is synthesized from the unedited mRNA; ApoB-100 is the structural protein of LDL particles and binds the LDL receptor. In intestinal enterocytes, APOBEC1 deaminates cytosine at position 6666 of the ApoB mRNA to uridine, converting the codon CAA (Gln) to UAA (stop codon). The resulting truncated protein, ApoB-48, contains only the N-terminal 2,152 amino acids of ApoB-100; it lacks the C-terminal LDL receptor-binding domain and is instead used for chylomicron assembly in the intestine. Thus a single enzyme creates two functionally distinct proteins from one gene, using tissue-specific RNA editing as the molecular switch.'},{t:'p',x:'Nonsense-mediated decay (NMD) is a eukaryotic mRNA surveillance mechanism that detects and rapidly degrades mRNAs containing premature termination codons (PTCs), preventing the production of truncated proteins that might act as dominant negatives or otherwise be toxic to the cell. The molecular rule: a stop codon located more than approximately 50 to 55 nucleotides upstream of the last exon-exon junction is recognized as premature. The exon junction complex (EJC) is a protein complex deposited ~20 to 25 nt upstream of each exon-exon junction by the spliceosome during splicing. During the pioneer round of translation (the first translation of a newly exported mRNA, in which the cap-binding complex CBC rather than eIF4E initiates translation), the ribosome normally removes EJCs as it translocates along the mRNA. If the ribosome encounters a stop codon while EJCs remain downstream (i.e., more than ~50-55 nt upstream of a downstream EJC), it pauses with UPF1 (an ATP-dependent RNA helicase and master NMD factor) recruited to the stalled ribosome. UPF1 is then phosphorylated by SMG1 kinase and interacts with UPF2 and UPF3, which are associated with downstream EJCs; this UPF1-UPF2-UPF3 complex triggers NMD through a combination of decapping (DCP1/2), deadenylation (CCR4-NOT), and endonucleolytic cleavage (SMG6). NMD is clinically relevant: approximately 30% of all known disease-causing genetic variants are nonsense mutations or frameshift mutations that generate PTCs; whether a PTC-containing mRNA is subject to NMD determines whether the patient has a complete loss-of-function phenotype or a partial one.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'CLINICAL BRIDGE: NMD AND DISEASE SEVERITY',x:'Whether a PTC-containing mutant mRNA escapes or undergoes NMD can determine the clinical severity of a genetic disease. In beta-thalassemia, mutations that introduce PTCs within exons 1 or 2 (far from the last exon-exon junction) trigger NMD; the mutant mRNA is degraded, no truncated globin is produced, and the disease phenotype is a pure loss-of-function (beta-thalassemia major or intermedia depending on the other allele). In contrast, PTCs within the last exon (or within 50-55 nt of the last junction) escape NMD and produce truncated proteins; these truncated beta-globin proteins can be incorporated into hemoglobin tetramers and act as dominant negatives, potentially altering the clinical presentation. In Duchenne vs Becker muscular dystrophy: DMD out-of-frame mutations lead to a PTC; whether NMD degrades the mRNA affects whether any residual short dystrophin protein is made. Understanding NMD in specific mutations guides predictions about disease outcome and response to read-through therapies (e.g., ataluren promotes ribosome read-through of PTCs in some DMD patients whose NMD has not fully eliminated the mutant mRNA).'},{t:'p',x:'tRNA processing involves several maturation steps. The pre-tRNA transcript is first cleaved at its 5-prime end by RNase P, a ribozyme (the RNA component, called M1 RNA in bacteria, is the catalytic subunit; protein is required in eukaryotes for activity under physiological conditions but is not itself the catalyst). RNase P cleaves the 5-prime leader sequence of the pre-tRNA to generate the mature 5-prime end. The 3-prime trailer is removed by a series of endonucleases and exonucleases. The universal CCA-3-prime terminus (present on all mature tRNAs) is added post-transcriptionally by CCA-adding enzyme (a template-independent nucleotidyltransferase), since the CCA is not encoded in most eukaryotic tRNA genes. Introns in tRNA are removed by a tRNA splicing endonuclease (not the spliceosome). Various base modifications occur: pseudouridine (Psi, isomerization of uridine), dihydrouridine (D, reduction of the 5,6 double bond), ribothymidine (T, methylation of uridine), and inosine at the wobble position (by ADAT, as described in Section 12.1 context). Pre-rRNA (45S in humans) is transcribed by Pol I in the nucleolus as a single precursor and processed by a series of endonucleolytic cleavages, guided by small nucleolar RNAs (snoRNAs), to produce the mature 28S, 18S, and 5.8S rRNAs. The 5S rRNA is transcribed separately by Pol III.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'Nusinersen (Spinraza) treats spinal muscular atrophy by which molecular mechanism?',choices:['A) Replacing the missing SMN1 gene by viral vector gene therapy','B) Blocking the ISS-N1 intronic splicing silencer in SMN2 pre-mRNA to force inclusion of exon 7 and increase full-length SMN protein','C) Inhibiting the nonsense-mediated decay of SMN2 mRNA so more truncated protein can be made','D) Activating ADAR to edit the C-to-U change in SMN2 exon 7 back to the wild-type sequence'],answer:1,why:'Nusinersen is an antisense oligonucleotide that base-pairs with the ISS-N1 (intronic splicing silencer N1) sequence just downstream of exon 7 in SMN2 pre-mRNA. By blocking this silencer element, nusinersen prevents the hnRNP proteins that normally bind ISS-N1 from repressing exon 7 inclusion. The spliceosome then includes exon 7 in approximately 80-90% of SMN2 transcripts (versus the untreated 10-20%), producing full-length SMN protein from the SMN2 gene and compensating for SMN1 loss.'},{stem:'APOBEC1-mediated RNA editing of ApoB mRNA in intestinal enterocytes converts a CAA codon at position 6666 to UAA. What is the direct molecular consequence?',choices:['A) The ApoB mRNA is exported from the nucleus more efficiently','B) A premature stop codon is introduced, producing ApoB-48, which lacks the LDL receptor-binding domain and is used for chylomicron assembly','C) The edited codon is recognized by a specialized tRNA, producing an unusual amino acid at position 2222 of the protein','D) The mRNA undergoes nonsense-mediated decay, eliminating ApoB expression in the intestine'],answer:1,why:'APOBEC1 deaminates cytidine to uridine at position 6666 of the ApoB mRNA in intestinal enterocytes, converting the glutamine codon CAA to the stop codon UAA. Translation terminates at this site, producing ApoB-48 (the first 2152 amino acids of ApoB-100). ApoB-48 lacks the C-terminal LDL receptor-binding domain of ApoB-100 and instead functions as the structural apolipoprotein of chylomicrons for dietary fat absorption. NMD does not degrade the transcript because the editing-introduced stop codon is near the 3-prime end of the coding sequence and downstream EJCs are absent at that position.'}]}],
 bottomLine:'Transcription converts information stored in DNA into functional RNA molecules. In bacteria, a single RNA polymerase holoenzyme (alpha2-beta-beta-prime-omega + sigma) recognizes the -10 (TATAAT) and -35 (TTGACA) promoter elements, melts the DNA, initiates RNA synthesis de novo, and sigma dissociates after approximately 9 to 11 nt to allow elongation. Termination uses either a stem-loop plus poly-U tract (rho-independent) or the rho helicase chasing a paused polymerase (rho-dependent). Rifampin blocks the beta subunit RNA exit channel and is used for tuberculosis and meningococcal prophylaxis; resistance comes from rpoB point mutations. Coupled transcription-translation is possible because bacteria lack a nuclear compartment. In eukaryotes, three nuclear RNA polymerases divide the workload: Pol I makes rRNA in the nucleolus; Pol II makes mRNA and most snRNAs; Pol III makes tRNA and 5S rRNA. Pol II requires assembly of general transcription factors (TFIID binds the TATA box via TBP, TFIIB anchors the promoter, TFIIH opens the bubble via XPB helicase and triggers promoter escape via CDK7-Ser5-CTD phosphorylation). Mediator bridges gene-specific activators at enhancers to the Pol II PIC. mRNA is extensively processed co-transcriptionally: 5-prime m7G cap (added at Ser5-CTD, required for translation initiation), splicing by the spliceosome (U1/U2/U4/U6/U5 snRNPs, two transesterification reactions via a lariat intermediate), and 3-prime polyadenylation (AAUAAA signal recognized by CPSF, approximately 200 A residues added). Gene regulation in prokaryotes uses the operon model: the lac operon is off when the repressor binds operator and on when allolactose (inducer) removes the repressor plus cAMP-CAP provides positive activation absent when glucose is present. The trp operon is repressible (tryptophan-bound repressor blocks transcription) and additionally controlled by attenuation (ribosome stalling at Trp codons in the leader peptide controls whether an antiterminator or terminator hairpin forms, adjusting transcriptional output to the available tRNATrp pool). In eukaryotes, transcription factors with helix-turn-helix, zinc finger, leucine zipper, or HLH DBDs recruit coactivators or corepressors to promoters and enhancers; chromatin remodeling by SWI/SNF (ATP-dependent), HATs/HDACs (acetylation/deacetylation), and histone methylation (H3K4me3 marks active promoters; H3K27me3 marks Polycomb-silenced genes) controls DNA accessibility; CpG methylation silences genes including tumor suppressors in cancer. Small RNAs fine-tune gene expression post-transcriptionally: miRNAs (Drosha/Dicer biogenesis, RISC-AGO silencing of mRNA 3-prime UTR targets) and siRNAs (exogenous dsRNA processed by Dicer, perfect-match mRNA cleavage by AGO2) represent two major pathways. Alternative splicing generates protein diversity from limited gene number; its misregulation causes DMD (correctable by exon-skipping ASOs), SMA (correctable by nusinersen/risdiplam promoting SMN2 exon 7 inclusion), and other diseases. RNA editing (ADAR A-to-I editing controls AMPA receptor Ca2+ permeability; APOBEC1 C-to-U editing generates ApoB-48 in the intestine) and nonsense-mediated decay (EJC-based surveillance destroys PTC-containing mRNAs) add further layers of post-transcriptional control. Together these mechanisms allow the same genomic information to produce vastly different gene expression profiles in different cell types, developmental stages, and physiological states.',
 nextHint:'Chapter 13, Translation, Post-Translational Modification, and Protein Targeting, takes the mature mRNA produced in Chapter 12 and traces it through ribosomal decoding, the elongation cycle, antibiotic targets, and the full downstream machinery of modification and compartmental routing. The central dogma of Book 6 is complete across Chapters 11, 12, and 13.',
},
{
 n:13,
 title:'Translation, Post-Translational Modification, and Protein Targeting',
 subtitle:'From codon to folded, modified, and correctly localized protein',
 tag:'Information',
 foundational:'The ribosome is a ribozyme. The genetic code is decoded by aminoacyl-tRNA synthetases, not by the ribosome itself. Every protein carries a sequence-encoded address that routes it to the correct cellular compartment.',
 buildsOn:'Ch 12, mRNA is produced; Ch 1, protein structure is the product.',
 setsUp:'End of Book 6. This is the complete central dogma.',
 objectives:['Decode the genetic code: degeneracy, wobble, universality, and mitochondrial exceptions','Explain aminoacyl-tRNA synthetase two-step reaction, proofreading, and energy cost','Compare prokaryotic and eukaryotic ribosome subunits, sites, and initiation mechanisms','Trace the GTP-driven cycle of elongation and the role of release factors in termination','Identify the mechanism and clinical toxicities of antibiotics that target the ribosome','Describe the major post-translational modifications: phosphorylation, glycosylation, ubiquitination, hydroxylation, gamma-carboxylation, and proteolytic cleavage','Explain the signal hypothesis and co-translational insertion into the ER, including SRP, translocon, BiP, calnexin, ERAD, and the UPR','Trace protein sorting through the Golgi: COPII/COPI/clathrin vesicles, mannose-6-phosphate targeting, and I-cell disease','Describe nuclear import (NLS/importin/RanGTP), mitochondrial import (MTS/TOM/TIM), and peroxisomal targeting (PTS1/PTS2/PEX)'],
 opener:'A cell builds roughly two million protein molecules every minute. Every one of them starts life as a codon sequence on an mRNA, gets translated by a ribosome that is itself a ribozyme, and then must be chemically modified, quality-checked, folded, and shipped to exactly the right address. The remarkable fact is not that this process occasionally goes wrong. The remarkable fact is that it goes right the overwhelming majority of the time, and that when it fails in specific, predictable ways, we get diseases specific enough to diagnose from a blood test.\n\nTranslation itself is a precision machinery problem: sixty-one sense codons must be decoded by a community of transfer RNAs whose identities are enforced by twenty aminoacyl-tRNA synthetases, each with its own proofreading mechanism, all supervised by a ribosome that is itself largely composed of catalytic RNA. Once the polypeptide emerges, it enters a second world of enzymatic rewriting, including phosphorylations, glycosylations, ubiquitinations, hydroxylations, and proteolytic cleavages that collectively determine whether a protein is active, stable, targeted to the correct compartment, or scheduled for destruction.\n\nThe machinery of protein targeting routes each protein to its destination using sequence-encoded address labels: signal peptides for co-translational ER insertion, nuclear localization signals for importin-mediated nuclear import, mitochondrial targeting sequences for TOM/TIM-dependent matrix delivery, and mannose-6-phosphate tags for lysosomal hydrolases. When any step in this post-translational world fails, a missing phosphotransferase, a defective peroxin, a misfolded CFTR, the clinical consequences are stark. Chapter 13 closes the biochemistry curriculum of Book 6 by integrating the molecular logic of translation with the full downstream proteome.',
 pinnedDisc:{t:'PROKARYOTIC vs EUKARYOTIC TRANSLATION',x:'Key MCAT differences: (1) Ribosomes: 70S (30S + 50S) vs 80S (40S + 60S). (2) Initiation: Shine-Dalgarno sequence in mRNA pairs with 16S rRNA anti-SD; fMet-tRNAfMet (formylated) enters P site directly; IF2 is the GTPase that delivers the initiator tRNA; no 5\' cap; polycistronic mRNAs common in prokaryotes. Eukaryotic: 40S subunit; 43S preinitiation complex scans from 5\' cap; Met-tRNAi (NOT formylated) enters P site directly; eIF2 delivers initiator tRNA (eIF2-GTP-Met-tRNAi ternary complex); 5\' cap recognized by eIF4E; Kozak context determines AUG selection; eIF5B is the final GTPase that triggers 60S joining; monocistronic mRNAs the rule. (3) Translation and transcription are coupled in prokaryotes, separate in eukaryotes. (4) Antibiotic sensitivity: clinically exploited because most antibiotics targeting translation are specific to 70S ribosomes, sparing eukaryotic cells; selectivity is not absolute since mitochondrial ribosomes (55S) are structurally closer to bacterial ribosomes.'},
 sections:[{id:'13.1',num:'13.1',title:'13.1 The Genetic Code',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'The genetic code is the set of rules by which each nucleotide triplet (a codon) in an mRNA is matched to a specific amino acid or to a signal to stop. The code consists of 64 possible codons (4 nucleotide choices at each of 3 positions = 4^3 = 64). Of these, 61 are sense codons that specify amino acids, and 3 are stop codons: UAA (ochre), UAG (amber), and UGA (opal, also called umber). A single codon, AUG, plays a dual role: it specifies methionine in the interior of a coding sequence, and it serves as the universal start codon when placed in the appropriate context. In bacteria, the initiating AUG is decoded by a specialized initiator tRNA carrying formylmethionine (fMet), a chemically blocked amino group that cannot serve as a nucleophile except at the start of a chain. In eukaryotes, the initiating AUG is decoded by a distinct Met-tRNAi (also called the initiator Met-tRNA), which is not formylated but is otherwise functionally segregated from the elongator Met-tRNA.'},{t:'p',x:'Because there are 61 sense codons but only 20 amino acids, the code is degenerate: multiple codons encode the same amino acid. The redundancy is not random. Related codons cluster: amino acids with two codons typically differ only at the third (3\') position of the codon, and amino acids with four or six codons differ at the third position across a broader range. This is the basis of Francis Crick\'s wobble hypothesis, proposed in 1966. The wobble position is the third nucleotide of the codon, which corresponds to the fifth position of the anticodon (the 5\' end of the anticodon). The pairing at the first two codon positions follows strict Watson-Crick geometry. The wobble position, however, allows non-standard pairings: a U at the 5\' position of the anticodon (wobble position of the anticodon) can base-pair with either A or G at the third position of the codon. Inosine (I), a modified nucleoside derived from adenosine by deamination, is the most permissive wobble base: I in the anticodon can pair with U, C, or A in the third codon position. The minimum number of tRNAs needed to read all 61 codons, given optimal wobble pairings, is 31.'},{t:'box',kind:'why',label:'WHY DEGENERACY IS PROTECTIVE',x:'Degeneracy is often called redundancy, but a more precise framing is protection against point mutations. Synonymous substitutions (single-nucleotide changes that do not alter the encoded amino acid) are far more common at the third codon position than at the first or second, precisely because the wobble position is tolerant of variation. A transition at the third position of many codons (e.g., GCU to GCC to GCA to GCG, all encoding alanine) causes no change in the amino acid sequence. The proteome is partially buffered against the steady accumulation of single-nucleotide polymorphisms. The protection is partial, not complete, since first and second position mutations almost always change the amino acid, but degeneracy provides a measurable fitness advantage.'},{t:'p',x:'The genetic code is nearly universal: the same 61 codons specify the same amino acids in bacteria, archaea, plants, fungi, and animals. This universality is evidence that all living organisms share a common ancestor in which the code was already fixed before the last universal common ancestor diverged. The universality is also what makes recombinant DNA technology possible: a human insulin gene expressed in Escherichia coli produces human insulin because the code is shared. A small number of exceptions exist in mitochondria and in a few ciliate organisms. The human mitochondrial genetic code uses UGA to encode tryptophan rather than as a stop codon; AUA encodes methionine rather than isoleucine; and AGA and AGG, which normally encode arginine, instead function as stop codons. These mitochondrial deviations are possible because the mitochondrial genome encodes only 13 proteins and uses a streamlined set of 22 tRNAs (compared with the ~45 cytoplasmic tRNAs in mammals), with highly permissive wobble pairing allowing a single tRNA to read entire codon families.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'HIGH-YIELD: CODON TABLE ESSENTIALS',x:'AUG = methionine and universal start codon. Stop codons: UAA (ochre), UAG (amber), UGA (opal). 64 total codons = 61 sense + 3 stop. Degeneracy concentrated at third (wobble) position. Inosine (I) in anticodon can pair with U, C, or A. Mitochondrial exceptions: UGA = Trp; AUA = Met; AGA/AGG = stop.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A mutation changes the third position of a codon from C to A. Which outcome is most likely?',choices:['A) The amino acid sequence is unchanged (synonymous substitution)','B) The mutation is always lethal','C) The protein gains a new disulfide bond','D) The reading frame shifts by one nucleotide'],answer:0,why:'Third-position (wobble) changes are most often synonymous because multiple codons differing only at the third position encode the same amino acid. Frame shifts result from insertions or deletions, not substitutions.'}]},{id:'13.2',num:'13.2',title:'13.2 tRNA Structure and Aminoacylation',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Transfer RNA molecules are the physical adaptors that solve the decoding problem: they carry an amino acid on one end and display the corresponding anticodon on the other. Each tRNA is 73 to 93 nucleotides in length and folds into a characteristic cloverleaf secondary structure held together by intrastrand base-pairing. The four arms of the cloverleaf are the acceptor stem (where the amino acid is attached), the D-loop (named for dihydrouridine modifications within it), the anticodon loop (containing the three-nucleotide anticodon), and the TpsiC loop (named for ribothymidine, pseudouridine, and cytidine). In three dimensions the cloverleaf folds into an L-shaped structure: the acceptor stem and T-loop stack to form one arm of the L, and the D-loop and anticodon loop stack to form the other arm. The anticodon and the amino acid attachment site are thus located at opposite ends of the L, approximately 7.5 nm apart. This separation is essential: the ribosome positions the anticodon in the decoding center (small subunit) and the amino acid in the peptidyl transferase center (large subunit) simultaneously. The universal 3\'-CCA-OH terminus of all tRNAs is the attachment site for the amino acid.'},{t:'p',x:'The anticodon is a three-nucleotide sequence located at the apex of the anticodon loop. It reads the codon in an antiparallel, 3\'-to-5\' direction relative to the mRNA. The wobble base (the base that participates in the permissive pairing described by Crick) is the 5\'-most nucleotide of the anticodon and pairs with the 3\'-most nucleotide of the codon. When U occupies the wobble position of the anticodon, it can hydrogen-bond with either A or G in the codon. When inosine (I) is present at the wobble position, it pairs with U, C, or A, allowing a single tRNA to read three codons in the same codon family. Inosine is generated post-transcriptionally by adenosine deaminase acting on tRNA (ADAT), which deaminates adenosine at position 34 of the tRNA to produce inosine.'},{t:'p',x:'The accuracy of translation ultimately depends on the correct charging of each tRNA with its cognate amino acid. This is the job of the aminoacyl-tRNA synthetases (AARS), a family of 20 enzymes (one per amino acid) that together constitute what is sometimes called the second genetic code because their identity-recognition decisions implement the correspondence between nucleotide sequence and amino acid identity. Each AARS must solve two problems: recognize the correct amino acid among the 20, and recognize the correct tRNA among the dozens present in the cell.'},{t:'p',x:'The aminoacylation reaction proceeds in two chemical steps. In the first step, the AARS activates the amino acid: amino acid + ATP yields aminoacyl-adenylate (aminoacyl-AMP) + pyrophosphate (PPi). The amino acid is linked via its carboxyl group to the alpha-phosphate of AMP in a high-energy mixed anhydride bond. Pyrophosphate is simultaneously released and is rapidly hydrolyzed by pyrophosphatase (PPi yields 2 Pi), which drives the reaction forward thermodynamically. In the second step, the activated amino acid is transferred from the aminoacyl-AMP intermediate to the 3\' terminal adenosine of the tRNA: aminoacyl-AMP + tRNA yields aminoacyl-tRNA + AMP. The amino acid forms an ester linkage to either the 2\'- or 3\'-hydroxyl of the terminal adenosine. The overall energetic cost of aminoacylation is equivalent to two ATP equivalents: one ATP is consumed (ATP yields AMP + PPi), and the hydrolysis of PPi releases a further ~7 kcal/mol, meaning the cell commits two phosphate bond equivalents to ensure that each aminoacyl-tRNA is correctly charged. A third ATP equivalent is consumed during the elongation step when EF-Tu-GTP delivers the aminoacyl-tRNA to the ribosome.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR | AMINOACYLATION ENERGY COST',x:'The aminoacylation reaction consumes ATP and converts it to AMP + PPi (not ADP + Pi). This is the equivalent of two high-energy phosphate bonds: the ATP to AMP step releases one bond worth of energy stored in the aminoacyl-AMP intermediate, and PPi hydrolysis releases another. The result is that the energetic cost of charging one tRNA is TWO ATP equivalents, not one. Do not confuse this with kinase reactions (ATP to ADP + Pi, one equivalent) or with the GTP consumed during ribosomal elongation (each peptide bond costs 1 GTP for EF-Tu delivery and 1 GTP for EF-G-driven translocation, but those are charged separately to the elongation cycle). Total cost per amino acid incorporated: 2 ATP (charging) + 2 GTP (elongation) = 4 high-energy phosphate bonds.'},{t:'p',x:'A critical feature of the AARS is the editing (proofreading) active site. Because the chemical similarity of some amino acids (e.g., isoleucine and valine, which differ by a single methylene group) means the synthetic site occasionally activates the wrong amino acid, most AARS possess a separate hydrolytic editing site that specifically destroys mischarged tRNAs. Isoleucyl-tRNA synthetase, for example, occasionally activates valine; the editing site of IleRS hydrolyzes val-tRNA-Ile before it can be used. This double-sieve mechanism (the synthetic site excludes large amino acids, the editing site destroys small ones) achieves error rates of approximately one mischarged tRNA per 10,000 to 100,000 correctly charged tRNAs.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'Aminoacyl-tRNA synthetase charges a tRNA by consuming ATP. What are the direct products of this reaction?',choices:['A) ADP + Pi','B) AMP + PPi (equivalent to 2 ATP)','C) AMP + Pi','D) GDP + Pi'],answer:1,why:'The AARS reaction produces AMP + PPi from ATP. PPi is then hydrolyzed to 2 Pi by pyrophosphatase, driving the reaction forward. This costs 2 ATP equivalents total, not 1.'}]},{id:'13.3',num:'13.3',title:'13.3 Ribosome Structure and the Three tRNA-Binding Sites',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'The ribosome is the macromolecular machine that translates mRNA codons into a polypeptide chain. It is a ribonucleoprotein complex (RNA and protein in roughly equal mass), but the catalytic heart of the ribosome, the peptidyl transferase center (PTC), is composed of ribosomal RNA (rRNA), not protein. The ribosome is therefore a ribozyme: an RNA molecule with catalytic activity. This is among the most important principles in molecular biology, with profound implications for the origin of life (RNA world hypothesis) and for the mechanism of action of antibiotics.'},{t:'p',x:'The bacterial ribosome sediments at 70S and is composed of two subunits. The small subunit (30S) contains 16S rRNA and approximately 21 ribosomal proteins. The large subunit (50S) contains 23S rRNA, 5S rRNA, and approximately 31 ribosomal proteins. The 16S rRNA of the small subunit contains the anti-Shine-Dalgarno sequence near its 3\' end, which base-pairs with the Shine-Dalgarno sequence in the mRNA to position the start codon. The 23S rRNA of the large subunit contains the peptidyl transferase center; specific nucleotides within the 23S rRNA (particularly A2451 and A2602 in E. coli 23S numbering) form the active site geometry that catalyzes peptide bond formation.'},{t:'p',x:'The eukaryotic cytoplasmic ribosome sediments at 80S. The small subunit (40S) contains 18S rRNA and approximately 33 proteins. The large subunit (60S) contains 28S rRNA, 5.8S rRNA, 5S rRNA, and approximately 49 proteins. The larger size of eukaryotic ribosomes reflects additional rRNA expansion segments and the extra proteins associated with them; the core catalytic architecture, including the PTC (now in 28S rRNA) and the decoding center (in 18S rRNA), is conserved from bacteria. The mitochondrial ribosome (mitoribosomes) in humans sediments at 55S, more similar in structure to bacterial ribosomes than to cytoplasmic eukaryotic ribosomes, consistent with the endosymbiotic origin of mitochondria. This has clinically important consequences: some antibiotics that target bacterial ribosomes can partially inhibit mitochondrial translation.'},{t:'p',x:'The ribosome contains three tRNA-binding sites, all of which span the interface between the large and small subunits. The A site (aminoacyl site) receives the incoming aminoacyl-tRNA during elongation; it is where codon-anticodon recognition occurs in the small subunit decoding center. The P site (peptidyl site) holds the tRNA carrying the growing polypeptide chain; during peptide bond formation, the peptide is transferred from the P-site tRNA to the A-site aminoacyl group. The E site (exit site) transiently holds the deacylated tRNA after it has donated its amino acid; tRNA leaves the ribosome from the E site. Translocation moves the tRNAs from A to P and P to E simultaneously.'},{t:'box',kind:'why',label:'WHY THE RIBOSOME IS AN ANTIBIOTIC TARGET',x:'The differences in composition and structure between prokaryotic 70S ribosomes and eukaryotic 80S ribosomes are large enough to allow selective pharmacological targeting. Aminoglycosides, tetracyclines, chloramphenicol, macrolides, linezolid, and clindamycin all bind to specific rRNA or protein elements in the bacterial ribosome that are either absent or structurally different in the human 80S ribosome. This selectivity is the principle underlying all translation-targeting antibiotics. The selectivity is not absolute: mitochondrial ribosomes (55S) are structurally closer to bacterial ribosomes, which explains chloramphenicol-mediated bone marrow suppression (mitochondria in rapidly dividing precursor cells) and aminoglycoside ototoxicity (cochlear hair cell mitochondria).'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A peptidyl-tRNA currently occupies the P site of a ribosome. Where does the incoming aminoacyl-tRNA bind?',choices:['A) E site','B) A site','C) P site','D) Decoding center of the 50S subunit'],answer:1,why:'The A (aminoacyl) site receives the incoming aminoacyl-tRNA. The P (peptidyl) site holds the growing chain. The E (exit) site holds the spent deacylated tRNA before it leaves.'}]},{id:'13.4',num:'13.4',title:'13.4 Prokaryotic Translation: Initiation, Elongation, and Termination',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Prokaryotic translation initiation begins when the 30S subunit, free from the 50S subunit, is available to bind mRNA. Initiation factor 3 (IF3) binds to the 30S subunit and prevents premature reassociation with the 50S subunit, keeping the small subunit available for new initiation events. The mRNA is positioned on the 30S subunit through the Shine-Dalgarno interaction: a purine-rich sequence approximately 5 to 10 nucleotides upstream of the AUG start codon (the Shine-Dalgarno sequence, consensus AGGAGG) base-pairs with the complementary anti-Shine-Dalgarno sequence at the 3\' end of the 16S rRNA (3\'-UCCUCC-5\'). This base-pairing positions the AUG start codon directly at the P site of the 30S subunit. The initiator tRNA, fMet-tRNAfMet, is brought to the P site by initiation factor 2 (IF2), which is a GTPase. The ternary complex of 30S subunit, mRNA, and fMet-tRNAfMet at the P site constitutes the 30S initiation complex. The 50S subunit then joins, IF1, IF2, and IF3 are released, GTP on IF2 is hydrolyzed, and the 70S initiation complex is formed with fMet-tRNAfMet in the P site and an empty A site awaiting the second codon.'},{t:'p',x:'A key feature of prokaryotic initiation is that the initiator tRNA (fMet-tRNAfMet) enters directly into the P site, bypassing the A site entirely. This distinguishes the initiator tRNA from all elongator tRNAs, which enter at the A site during elongation. The N-formyl group on the methionine of fMet-tRNAfMet blocks the alpha-amino group from acting as a nucleophile toward a preceding peptide, a chemical feature that enforces the identity of fMet as a start, never as an elongation amino acid. Many bacterial proteins are subsequently cleaved by methionine aminopeptidase to remove the initial fMet residue, so the mature bacterial protein often does not begin with methionine.'},{t:'p',x:'The elongation cycle repeats for each amino acid added to the growing chain. Delivery of the aminoacyl-tRNA to the A site is mediated by elongation factor Tu (EF-Tu), a GTPase that forms a ternary complex with GTP and any aminoacyl-tRNA (except the initiator fMet-tRNAfMet). EF-Tu-GTP escorts the aminoacyl-tRNA to the A site; codon-anticodon recognition in the decoding center of the 30S subunit triggers a conformational change in the ribosome (accommodation) that positions the aminoacyl end of the tRNA in the peptidyl transferase center of the 50S subunit. GTP hydrolysis by EF-Tu then releases EF-Tu-GDP from the ribosome; EF-Tu-GDP is inactive and must be reactivated by the guanine nucleotide exchange factor EF-Ts (EF-Ts displaces GDP, allows GTP to rebind, regenerating active EF-Tu-GTP). The codon-anticodon matching step is a kinetic proofreading step: a cognate codon-anticodon pair triggers fast GTP hydrolysis, whereas near-cognate or non-cognate tRNAs dissociate before accommodation, providing an additional layer of fidelity beyond simple base-pairing.'},{t:'p',x:'Peptide bond formation is catalyzed by the PTC in the 23S rRNA. The reaction is a nucleophilic attack: the alpha-amino group of the A-site aminoacyl-tRNA attacks the carbonyl carbon of the ester bond linking the peptide chain to the 3\'-OH of the P-site tRNA. The peptide is transferred to the A-site tRNA in a single step, generating a peptidyl-tRNA in the A site (one amino acid longer than before) and a deacylated tRNA in the P site. The rate of peptide bond formation is extremely fast (~50 per second per ribosome in bacteria) and does not require GTP hydrolysis: the PTC is a pure ribozyme-catalyzed reaction.'},{t:'p',x:'Translocation is the step in which the ribosome advances three nucleotides along the mRNA, moving the tRNAs from A to P to E positions. This is catalyzed by elongation factor G (EF-G), which is a GTPase. EF-G-GTP binds the ribosome in a conformation that mimics a tRNA:EF-Tu:GTP ternary complex (molecular mimicry). GTP hydrolysis drives a large conformational change in the ribosome (the ratchet-like rotation of the two subunits relative to each other) which moves the mRNA and the two tRNAs by exactly one codon. After translocation: the new peptidyl-tRNA is in the P site, the deacylated tRNA is in the E site (where it soon leaves), the A site is empty and presenting the next codon, and the mRNA has advanced by three nucleotides. EF-G-GDP then dissociates, and the cycle begins again.'},{t:'p',x:'The elongation cycle continues until one of the three stop codons (UAA, UAG, UGA) enters the A site. Stop codons are not recognized by tRNAs; instead they are recognized by protein release factors (RFs) that enter the A site and mimic the shape of a tRNA (molecular mimicry, analogous to EF-G mimicking the tRNA:EF-Tu complex). In bacteria, RF1 recognizes UAA and UAG; RF2 recognizes UAA and UGA; RF3 is a GTPase that stimulates the dissociation of RF1 or RF2 after peptide release. When a release factor occupies the A site, it triggers the PTC to catalyze hydrolysis rather than peptide transfer: water acts as the nucleophile, hydrolyzing the ester bond between the polypeptide and the P-site tRNA, releasing the completed polypeptide into the solvent. After release, the ribosome recycling factor (RRF) and EF-G together disassemble the 70S post-termination complex, releasing the mRNA and the deacylated tRNA so that the subunits can be reused.'},{t:'formula',x:'Elongation cycle per amino acid: (1) EF-Tu-GTP + aa-tRNA -> A site delivery; GTP hydrolysis on codon recognition; (2) PTC catalyzes peptide bond (no GTP); (3) EF-G-GTP drives translocation; GTP hydrolysis. Cost: 1 GTP (EF-Tu) + 1 GTP (EF-G) = 2 GTP per residue, plus 2 ATP for charging = 4 high-energy bonds total per amino acid incorporated.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'Which elongation factor delivers aminoacyl-tRNA to the A site of the prokaryotic ribosome and uses GTP hydrolysis to confirm correct codon-anticodon pairing?',choices:['A) EF-G','B) EF-Ts','C) EF-Tu','D) RF3'],answer:2,why:'EF-Tu-GTP forms a ternary complex with aminoacyl-tRNA and delivers it to the A site. GTP hydrolysis occurs rapidly when the correct codon-anticodon match is made, confirming the pairing and allowing accommodation. EF-G drives translocation, not delivery.'}]},{id:'13.5',num:'13.5',title:'13.5 Eukaryotic Translation: Key Differences and Regulatory Mechanisms',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Eukaryotic translation shares the same fundamental chemistry as prokaryotic translation but differs in initiation mechanism, factor nomenclature, mRNA recognition, and the regulatory circuitry that controls global and gene-specific translation rates.'},{t:'p',x:'Eukaryotic mRNAs are distinguished from bacterial mRNAs by their 5\' 7-methylguanosine cap and 3\' poly(A) tail, both of which contribute to translational efficiency. Cap-dependent initiation begins when eIF4E (the cap-binding protein) recognizes and binds the 5\' cap structure. eIF4E is part of the eIF4F complex, which also includes eIF4G (a large scaffold protein that bridges the cap-binding machinery to the ribosome) and eIF4A (an ATP-dependent RNA helicase that unwinds secondary structures in the 5\' untranslated region to allow ribosome scanning). eIF4G also binds PABP (poly(A)-binding protein), which circularizes the mRNA and stimulates reinitiation.'},{t:'p',x:'Meanwhile, the 43S preinitiation complex (PIC) assembles separately. The 43S PIC consists of the 40S small subunit associated with a ternary complex of eIF2-GTP-Met-tRNAi plus eIF1, eIF1A, eIF3, and eIF5. The 43S PIC is recruited to the 5\' cap region of the mRNA through interactions between eIF3 and the eIF4F complex (particularly eIF4G). Once loaded onto the 5\' end, the 43S PIC scans downstream in the 5\' to 3\' direction, unwinding secondary structures as it goes. Scanning pauses when the Met-tRNAi anticodon (CAU) encounters an AUG codon in a favorable Kozak consensus context (the human consensus is GCC(A/G)CCAUGG, where the purine at position -3 and the G immediately after AUG are most important). Base-pairing between the AUG and the Met-tRNAi anticodon in the P site stabilizes the complex; eIF5 stimulates GTP hydrolysis on eIF2; and the 60S subunit joins, aided by eIF5B-GTP, displacing and releasing all initiation factors. The 80S initiation complex is now ready for elongation.'},{t:'p',x:'The master regulator of global translation in eukaryotes is mTOR (mechanistic target of rapamycin), a serine-threonine kinase that integrates nutrient, energy, and growth factor signals to control the rate of protein synthesis. mTOR Complex 1 (mTORC1) is activated downstream of PI3K/Akt signaling (growth factors, insulin) and inhibited by AMPK (energy depletion), rapamycin, and amino acid starvation. When active, mTORC1 phosphorylates two key targets. First, 4E-BP1 (eIF4E-binding protein 1): in its unphosphorylated (hypophosphorylated) state, 4E-BP1 sequesters eIF4E, preventing it from joining the eIF4F complex and blocking cap-dependent initiation. mTORC1-mediated hyperphosphorylation of 4E-BP1 releases eIF4E, which is then free to assemble eIF4F and drive translation. Second, S6 kinase 1 (S6K1), whose activation promotes ribosome biogenesis and increased translation of mRNAs containing 5\' terminal oligopyrimidine (5\'-TOP) tracts.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR | PROKARYOTIC vs EUKARYOTIC TRANSLATION INITIATION',x:'PROKARYOTIC: 30S subunit; Shine-Dalgarno sequence in mRNA pairs with 16S rRNA anti-SD; fMet-tRNAfMet (formylated) enters P site directly; IF2 is the GTPase that delivers the initiator tRNA; no 5\' cap; polycistronic mRNAs common. EUKARYOTIC: 40S subunit; 43S preinitiation complex scans from 5\' cap; Met-tRNAi (NOT formylated) enters P site directly; eIF2 delivers initiator tRNA (eIF2-GTP-Met-tRNAi ternary complex); 5\' cap recognized by eIF4E; Kozak context determines AUG selection; eIF5B is the final GTPase that triggers 60S joining; monocistronic mRNAs the rule. The structural analogy is: SD/16S rRNA base-pairing in bacteria is functionally replaced by cap/eIF4E/scanning in eukaryotes. Both mechanisms position the start codon in the P site.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'In eukaryotes, which protein directly binds the 5\' 7-methylguanosine cap of mRNA as the first step of cap-dependent initiation?',choices:['A) eIF2','B) eIF4G','C) eIF4E','D) eIF5B'],answer:2,why:'eIF4E is the cap-binding protein. It is part of the eIF4F complex. eIF4G is a scaffold, eIF2 delivers the initiator tRNA, and eIF5B is the GTPase that joins the 60S subunit.'}]},{id:'13.6',num:'13.6',title:'13.6 Antibiotics That Target Translation',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Because the bacterial ribosome is structurally distinct from the eukaryotic cytoplasmic ribosome, it is one of the most productive antibiotic targets in medicine. Translation inhibitors fall into two structural groups based on which subunit they target, and within each group they act at specific steps in the translation cycle. Understanding the mechanism of each antibiotic class explains its spectrum of activity, its adverse effect profile, and the mechanisms of resistance that bacteria have evolved.'},{t:'p',x:'30S subunit inhibitors. Tetracyclines (doxycycline, minocycline): block the A site by binding 16S rRNA near the decoding center, preventing aminoacyl-tRNA entry. Key toxicities include GI upset, tooth discoloration and bone growth inhibition in children (due to chelation of calcium), photosensitivity, and they are NOT used in pregnancy (Fanconi syndrome of renal tubule, but more to the point the teeth and bone effect in the fetus). Aminoglycosides (streptomycin, gentamicin, tobramycin, amikacin): bind 16S rRNA near A site (helix 44); cause conformational change that leads to codon misreading (accepting near-cognate tRNAs); streptomycin also inhibits initiation. Key toxicities: nephrotoxicity (proximal tubule accumulation via megalin) and ototoxicity (irreversible destruction of cochlear outer hair cells and vestibular hair cells, high-frequency hearing loss that progresses to lower frequencies). A mitochondrial 12S rRNA variant (m.1555A>G) dramatically increases cochlear sensitivity to aminoglycosides.'},{t:'p',x:'50S subunit inhibitors. Chloramphenicol: binds 23S rRNA at the PTC A-site cleft; blocks peptidyl transferase by preventing the aminoacyl end of A-site tRNA from binding. Two distinct toxicities: (1) aplastic anemia, an idiosyncratic, dose-independent, immune-mediated reaction occurring in approximately 1 in 20,000 to 40,000 patients exposed to systemic chloramphenicol, believed to result from a toxic nitroso metabolite that damages hematopoietic stem cells, and (2) gray baby syndrome, a dose-dependent toxicity in neonates and premature infants due to immature hepatic UDP-glucuronosyltransferase activity and reduced renal filtration, causing chloramphenicol accumulation, inhibition of mitochondrial translation in cardiomyocytes, and cardiovascular collapse with ashen gray color. Macrolides (erythromycin, azithromycin, clarithromycin): bind 23S rRNA at the peptide exit tunnel (near A2058); block translocation and force premature peptide release for short peptides; do not block PTC directly. GI motility (motilin agonist), QT prolongation (azithromycin), CYP3A4 inhibition (erythromycin, clarithromycin). Linezolid: binds 23S rRNA at PTC; prevents formation of the 70S initiation complex (prevents fMet-tRNAfMet positioning). Toxicities include myelosuppression (thrombocytopenia), serotonin syndrome with SSRIs (weak MAO-A inhibition), and peripheral/optic neuropathy with prolonged use. Clindamycin: binds 23S rRNA near peptide exit tunnel (overlapping with macrolide site); blocks peptide elongation early. Most notable association with C. difficile colitis. Fusidic acid: NOT a ribosome binder; binds EF-G and stabilizes EF-G:GDP on ribosome post-GTP hydrolysis, blocking recycling of EF-G and preventing translocation.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'CLINICAL BRIDGE | CHLORAMPHENICOL TOXICITY',x:'Chloramphenicol has two distinct high-yield toxicities. Aplastic anemia: idiosyncratic, dose-independent, immune-mediated; occurs in ~1/20,000 to 40,000 patients; results from a toxic nitroso metabolite damaging hematopoietic stem cells; can occur after oral therapy; high mortality; not predictable from blood levels. Gray baby syndrome: dose-dependent; neonates have immature hepatic glucuronidation (UDP-glucuronosyltransferase activity is minimal) and reduced renal filtration; chloramphenicol accumulates to toxic levels; inhibits mitochondrial translation in cardiomyocytes and other cells; cardiovascular collapse, ashen gray color, abdominal distension, and death. Prevention requires appropriate dosing and blood level monitoring in neonates.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'CLINICAL BRIDGE | AMINOGLYCOSIDE TOXICITY',x:'Aminoglycosides cause two predictable, concentration-dependent toxicities. Nephrotoxicity results from accumulation in proximal tubular cells (which have megalin-mediated uptake); the drugs accumulate in lysosomes and inhibit phospholipase, leading to phospholipidosis, cell necrosis, and acute tubular injury. Monitoring serum creatinine and trough levels (or area under the curve in once-daily dosing) is standard of care. Ototoxicity results from irreversible destruction of cochlear outer hair cells and vestibular hair cells; cochlear toxicity causes high-frequency hearing loss that progresses to lower frequencies with prolonged exposure. Hair cells do not regenerate in mammals. A specific mitochondrial 12S rRNA variant (m.1555A>G) dramatically increases cochlear sensitivity to aminoglycosides, and patients with this variant may develop profound deafness after even a single dose, an important pharmacogenomic consideration.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'Which antibiotic blocks the peptidyl transferase center by preventing binding of the aminoacyl end of the A-site tRNA, and is classically associated with aplastic anemia?',choices:['A) Erythromycin','B) Tetracycline','C) Chloramphenicol','D) Streptomycin'],answer:2,why:'Chloramphenicol binds the 23S rRNA at the PTC A-site cleft and blocks peptidyl transferase. Its signature toxicities are aplastic anemia (idiosyncratic, immune-mediated) and gray baby syndrome (dose-dependent, neonates).'}]},{id:'13.7',num:'13.7',title:'13.7 Post-Translational Modifications',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'The polypeptide chain released from the ribosome is rarely in its final functional form. A large fraction of all proteins undergo one or more post-translational modifications (PTMs) that alter their chemical properties, localization, stability, or activity.'},{t:'p',x:'Phosphorylation is the reversible addition of a phosphate group from ATP to the hydroxyl group of serine, threonine, or tyrosine residues, catalyzed by protein kinases. The reverse reaction is catalyzed by protein phosphatases. Phosphorylation introduces a bulky, negatively charged group (-PO4^2- at physiological pH) that profoundly alters local electrostatics and can switch a protein between active and inactive conformations, create or destroy docking sites for other proteins, or target a protein for degradation. Serine and threonine kinases (e.g., protein kinase A, CaM kinase, CDKs) are the most numerous; tyrosine kinases (e.g., the receptor tyrosine kinases EGFR, PDGFR, insulin receptor) are less abundant but critical in growth factor signaling.'},{t:'p',x:'Glycosylation is the attachment of carbohydrate moieties to proteins. Two major types exist: N-linked and O-linked. N-linked glycosylation occurs in the endoplasmic reticulum and begins co-translationally. The consensus sequence for N-linked glycosylation is Asn-X-Ser/Thr (where X is any amino acid except proline; proline introduces a rigid kink that prevents the oligosaccharyltransferase from accessing the asparagine). The core oligosaccharide (Glc3-Man9-GlcNAc2, 14 sugars total) is assembled en bloc on a lipid carrier (dolichol pyrophosphate) on the cytoplasmic face of the ER membrane, then flipped to the luminal face and transferred as a complete unit onto the asparagine by the oligosaccharyltransferase complex. Within the ER, the three terminal glucose residues are trimmed sequentially by glucosidases I and II; the resulting monoglucosylated intermediate is the substrate recognized by calnexin and calreticulin, lectin chaperones that retain the glycoprotein in the ER until it is correctly folded (the calnexin/calreticulin cycle). O-linked glycosylation occurs mainly in the Golgi; sugars are added sequentially (one at a time, not en bloc) to the hydroxyl groups of serine or threonine residues; there is no consensus sequence analogous to Asn-X-Ser/Thr.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR | N-LINKED vs O-LINKED GLYCOSYLATION',x:'N-LINKED: target is Asn in Asn-X-Ser/Thr; occurs in ER (initiation) and Golgi (maturation); sugars added as a preformed 14-sugar block from dolichol carrier (en bloc transfer by oligosaccharyltransferase); initial product is high-mannose type; complex and hybrid types generated in Golgi; glycan assists protein folding via calnexin/calreticulin cycle; dolichol is a polyisoprenoid lipid anchor. O-LINKED: target is Ser or Thr; occurs mainly in Golgi; sugars added sequentially (one at a time, not en bloc); no dolichol carrier; simpler oligosaccharides generally; no chaperone cycle; nuclear/cytoplasmic O-GlcNAc modification by OGT is a metabolic sensor (substrate UDP-GlcNAc reflects hexosamine pathway flux/nutrient status).'},{t:'p',x:'Ubiquitin is a 76-amino-acid protein found in all eukaryotic cells, so highly conserved that yeast and human ubiquitin differ by only three amino acids. It is covalently attached to lysine residues of substrate proteins through an isopeptide bond between the C-terminal glycine of ubiquitin and the epsilon-amino group of the substrate lysine. The attachment reaction requires three enzymes acting in sequence: E1 (ubiquitin-activating enzyme) first activates ubiquitin using ATP, forming a high-energy thioester between ubiquitin\'s C-terminus and the E1 active-site cysteine; E2 (ubiquitin-conjugating enzyme) receives ubiquitin from E1 via transthioesterification; E3 (ubiquitin ligase) recruits the substrate protein and facilitates transfer of ubiquitin from E2 to the substrate lysine. There is one E1 in most organisms, approximately 30 to 40 E2s, and hundreds of E3s. The E3 diversity provides substrate specificity, making the E3 ligases the key regulatory enzymes in the ubiquitin system.'},{t:'p',x:'The biological outcome of ubiquitination depends on the type of modification. Polyubiquitin chains in which successive ubiquitins are linked through lysine-48 (K48) of ubiquitin form a compact, proteasome-recognized structure that targets the substrate for degradation by the 26S proteasome, the primary pathway for regulated proteolysis in the cytoplasm and nucleus. Polyubiquitin chains linked through lysine-63 (K63) adopt a more extended, non-degradative conformation and function as scaffolds for signaling: K63-linked chains on PCNA (proliferating cell nuclear antigen) activate damage-tolerant DNA synthesis pathways; K63-linked chains on TRAF6 activate NF-kB signaling. Key discriminator: when a question says ubiquitin, think proteasome for K48; think signaling/DNA repair for K63.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR | K48-LINKED vs K63-LINKED POLYUBIQUITIN',x:'K48-LINKED (proteasomal degradation): compact beta-sheet conformation recognized by the 19S regulatory particle of the 26S proteasome; substrate is unfolded and threaded into the 20S catalytic core; ubiquitin is recycled by deubiquitylases (DUBs); clinical relevance: bortezomib (proteasome inhibitor used in multiple myeloma) blocks this pathway, causing accumulation of misfolded and proapoptotic proteins in malignant plasma cells. K63-LINKED (signaling scaffold): extended conformation not recognized by proteasome; recruits signaling proteins with K63-specific ubiquitin-binding domains (e.g., RAP80 for DNA damage, TAB2 for NF-kB). Key discriminator: when a question says ubiquitin going to proteasome, think K48. When it says ubiquitin for signaling/DNA repair, think K63.'},{t:'p',x:'Hydroxylation of proline and lysine residues in collagen is catalyzed post-translationally by prolyl hydroxylase and lysyl hydroxylase, respectively. These enzymes are iron-dependent, alpha-ketoglutarate-dependent dioxygenases that require molecular oxygen and vitamin C (ascorbic acid) as a cofactor. Vitamin C is required to keep the active-site iron in the ferrous (Fe2+) state; without it, the iron is oxidized to Fe3+ and the enzyme is inactivated. Hydroxyproline provides conformational stability of the collagen triple helix by participating in hydrogen bonds through its hydroxyl group; hydroxylysine serves as the attachment point for O-linked galactose and glucosylgalactose, and also participates in crosslinking by lysyl oxidase. Vitamin C deficiency (scurvy) thus directly impairs collagen maturation: un-hydroxylated collagen triple helices are unstable, leading to fragile blood vessels, poor wound healing, perifollicular hemorrhage, gum disease, and corkscrew hairs.'},{t:'p',x:'Gamma-carboxylation of glutamate residues in the coagulation factors II (prothrombin), VII, IX, X, and the anticoagulant proteins C and S generates gamma-carboxyglutamate (Gla). The carboxylase responsible requires vitamin K (specifically reduced vitamin K, vitamin KH2, as the active cofactor) and carbon dioxide. Gamma-carboxyglutamate residues have two negative charges at physiological pH and chelate calcium ions with high affinity. Calcium binding induces a conformational change in the Gla domain of coagulation factors that allows them to anchor to phosphatidylserine on the surface of activated platelets or damaged endothelium, the phospholipid surface assembly essential for the coagulation cascade. Warfarin inhibits vitamin K epoxide reductase (VKORC1), blocking regeneration of active vitamin KH2 from its oxidized epoxide form; the result is depletion of functional Gla residues in coagulation factors and anticoagulation. The anticoagulant proteins C and S are ALSO vitamin K-dependent, which is why warfarin initially causes a paradoxical hypercoagulable state (proteins C and S have shorter half-lives than prothrombin and factor X, and are depleted first).'},{t:'p',x:'Proteolytic cleavage is an irreversible PTM that activates or localizes proteins by cleaving specific peptide bonds. Signal peptide removal: proteins that enter the ER have a cleavable N-terminal signal peptide (typically 16 to 30 residues, with a hydrophobic core) that is removed co-translationally by signal peptidase on the luminal face of the ER membrane; this cleavage converts the nascent polypeptide to its mature ER-lumenal form. Zymogen activation: many proteases, particularly digestive enzymes and coagulation factors, are synthesized as inactive precursors (zymogens or proenzymes) that require proteolytic cleavage to become active. Trypsinogen is converted to trypsin by enteropeptidase in the duodenal lumen, and subsequently autocatalytically; chymotrypsinogen becomes chymotrypsin; pepsinogen becomes pepsin (by gastric acid). Proinsulin is converted to insulin: the connecting C-peptide (35 aa) is removed in the secretory granule by convertase 1/3 (PC1/3) and carboxypeptidase E, releasing mature insulin (A + B chains held by disulfide bonds) and an equimolar amount of C-peptide. C-peptide measurement is clinically valuable as an endogenous indicator of pancreatic beta-cell insulin secretion.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'HIGH-YIELD: POST-TRANSLATIONAL MODIFICATIONS',x:'Phosphorylation (kinase/phosphatase): Ser, Thr, Tyr; reversible switch; most common PTM in signal transduction. N-linked glycosylation: Asn (Asn-X-Ser/Thr); ER + Golgi; en bloc from dolichol; calnexin/calreticulin quality control. O-linked glycosylation: Ser or Thr; mainly Golgi; sequential; no consensus sequence; O-GlcNAc in cytoplasm. K48 polyubiquitin leads to 26S proteasome degradation; K63 polyubiquitin leads to signaling scaffold (NF-kB, DNA repair). Gamma-carboxylation: Glu to Gla; vitamin K cofactor; coagulation factors II, VII, IX, X, protein C, protein S. Prolyl/lysyl hydroxylation: collagen; Fe2+ + vitamin C required; scurvy = collagen instability. Prenylation: CAAX cysteine; farnesyl (Ras) or geranylgeranyl (Rab); membrane anchoring. Zymogen cleavage: trypsinogen to trypsin; proinsulin to insulin + C-peptide; irreversible activation.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A patient develops easy bruising, perifollicular hemorrhages, and corkscrew hairs. The defect is in which post-translational modification?',choices:['A) N-linked glycosylation in the ER','B) Gamma-carboxylation of coagulation factors','C) Prolyl and lysyl hydroxylation of collagen','D) K48-linked ubiquitination'],answer:2,why:'Scurvy (vitamin C deficiency) impairs prolyl and lysyl hydroxylase, which require vitamin C to maintain the active-site iron in the Fe2+ state. Without hydroxylation, procollagen triple helices are unstable. The classic features are corkscrew hairs, perifollicular hemorrhages, bleeding gums, and poor wound healing.'}]},{id:'13.8',num:'13.8',title:'13.8 Protein Targeting and Trafficking',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Eukaryotic cells must route thousands of distinct protein types to their correct destinations: the cytoplasm, nucleus, mitochondria, peroxisomes, ER lumen, Golgi, lysosomes, plasma membrane, or extracellular space. Proteins are targeted by sequence-encoded address labels: short peptide signals (or post-translational modifications like mannose-6-phosphate) that are recognized by specific receptors and import/export machineries. The general principle, established by Gunter Blobel and colleagues in the signal hypothesis (Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine, 1999), is that the information for protein localization is encoded in the protein sequence itself.'},{t:'p',x:'Proteins destined for the secretory pathway (ER lumen, Golgi, lysosomes, plasma membrane, extracellular space) begin with a signal sequence: an N-terminal peptide of approximately 16 to 30 residues with a hydrophobic core of 8 to 12 consecutive hydrophobic amino acids. The signal sequence is recognized by the signal recognition particle (SRP), a ribonucleoprotein complex composed of a 7SL RNA scaffold and six proteins (SRP9, SRP14, SRP19, SRP54, SRP68, SRP72). SRP54, the core subunit, contains a methionine-rich M domain that forms a hydrophobic groove accommodating the signal sequence. When the signal sequence emerges from the ribosome exit tunnel during translation, SRP54 recognizes and binds it. SRP binding slows translation (elongation pause), tethering the ribosome-nascent chain complex to SRP until it docks at the ER membrane.'},{t:'p',x:'At the ER membrane, SRP binds to the SRP receptor (SR), a heterodimeric GTPase (SRalpha and SRbeta subunits) embedded in the ER membrane. Both SRP and SR are GTPases, and their interaction stimulates mutual GTP hydrolysis, releasing the ribosome-nascent chain from SRP and transferring it to the translocon. The translocon is the Sec61 complex, a protein-conducting channel in the ER membrane through which the growing polypeptide is threaded co-translationally into the ER lumen. For soluble secreted proteins, the chain threads completely through the translocon into the lumen. For integral membrane proteins, hydrophobic transmembrane segments are laterally released from the Sec61 channel into the lipid bilayer. Signal peptidase, an enzyme complex on the luminal face of the ER membrane, cleaves the signal peptide from the translocating chain, generating the mature N-terminus of the protein.'},{t:'p',x:'The ER lumen is an oxidizing environment (unlike the reducing cytoplasm), which supports the formation of disulfide bonds, a modification essential for the stability of most secreted and membrane proteins. Protein disulfide isomerase (PDI) catalyzes the formation, isomerization, and reduction of disulfide bonds; it oxidizes the substrate cysteines while reducing its own active-site disulfides, which are subsequently reoxidized by Ero1 (ER oxidase 1) using molecular oxygen as the final electron acceptor. BiP (also called GRP78 or HSPA5) is the major ER-resident Hsp70 chaperone; it binds exposed hydrophobic stretches in unfolded or partially folded proteins, preventing aggregation and holding substrates for refolding attempts. Calnexin (a transmembrane protein) and calreticulin (a soluble luminal protein) are lectin chaperones that bind specifically to monoglucosylated N-linked glycans on glycoproteins, retaining them in the ER while folding is completed (the calnexin/calreticulin cycle). If folding is successful, the final glucose is removed, and the protein is released for onward transport. If folding fails repeatedly, the protein is retained and eventually targeted for ERAD.'},{t:'p',x:'ER-associated degradation (ERAD) is the quality control pathway that removes terminally misfolded proteins from the ER. Misfolded proteins are first recognized by ER chaperones, then retrotranslocated (threaded back through the Sec61 complex or the ERAD-specific Hrd1/Derlins complex) into the cytoplasm. In the cytoplasm, they are ubiquitinated by ER-associated E3 ligases (Hrd1, gp78) and delivered to the 26S proteasome for degradation. ERAD is the physiological fate of the deltaF508 CFTR mutant in cystic fibrosis: the deletion of phenylalanine-508 in CFTR causes the protein to misfold in the ER, be recognized as aberrant by BiP and calnexin, fail the quality control cycle, and get retrotranslocated and degraded by the proteasome before any functional CFTR reaches the apical membrane. This is why some CF therapies target the folding problem directly: correctors such as lumacaftor improve deltaF508 CFTR folding; potentiators such as ivacaftor keep the gate open once CFTR reaches the membrane.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'CLINICAL BRIDGE | CYSTIC FIBROSIS AS A PROTEIN TRAFFICKING DISEASE',x:'Cystic fibrosis (CF) is caused by mutations in the CFTR gene, which encodes a chloride channel at the apical surface of airway, intestinal, and exocrine epithelial cells. The most common mutation, deltaF508 (deletion of phenylalanine at position 508), does not destroy chloride channel function per se: patch-clamp studies show that deltaF508 CFTR that has been rescued from ERAD and inserted into membranes can conduct chloride, though with reduced gating. The primary defect is protein trafficking: deltaF508 CFTR misfolds in the ER, is recognized by BiP and calnexin, fails the quality control cycle, and is ERAD-targeted before it can reach the apical membrane. The therapeutic insight from understanding ERAD is direct: lumacaftor (a corrector, improves deltaF508 CFTR folding in the ER, allowing more protein to escape ERAD and traffic to the membrane) and ivacaftor (a potentiator, increases the open probability of CFTR channels at the membrane) are the basis of the elexacaftor/tezacaftor/ivacaftor triple combination therapy.'},{t:'p',x:'Proteins that correctly fold in the ER are packaged into COPII-coated vesicles and transported to the Golgi. COPII coat proteins (Sar1, Sec23/24, Sec13/31) are recruited to ER exit sites (ERES) when Sar1-GTP is activated; COPII vesicles carry anterograde cargo from the ER to the cis face of the Golgi. The return trip, retrieval of ER resident proteins that have escaped to the Golgi, is mediated by COPI-coated vesicles. Soluble ER-resident proteins (e.g., BiP, PDI, protein disulfide isomerase) carry a C-terminal KDEL tetrapeptide (Lys-Asp-Glu-Leu) that is recognized by KDEL receptors on the cis Golgi membrane. Binding triggers packaging into COPI vesicles for retrograde transport back to the ER. COPI also mediates intra-Golgi retrograde transport (Golgi stack maintenance). Transmembrane ER-resident proteins use a cytoplasmic KKXX motif for COPI-mediated retrieval.'},{t:'p',x:'Lysosomal hydrolases are sorted in the trans Golgi network by the mannose-6-phosphate (M6P) targeting pathway. In the cis Golgi, GlcNAc-1-phosphotransferase adds GlcNAc-1-phosphate to specific mannose residues on lysosomal hydrolases (the enzyme recognizes a 3D patch signal on the hydrolase surface, not a simple linear sequence). A second enzyme, uncovering enzyme, removes the GlcNAc to expose mannose-6-phosphate. M6P residues are recognized by M6P receptors (MPR, specifically cation-dependent and cation-independent forms) in the trans Golgi network; receptor-hydrolase complexes bud off in clathrin-coated vesicles and are delivered to late endosomes, where the low pH causes dissociation of the hydrolase from the receptor. The hydrolase is released into the forming lysosome; the receptor is recycled back to the Golgi.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'CLINICAL BRIDGE | I-CELL DISEASE (MUCOLIPIDOSIS II)',x:'I-cell disease (mucolipidosis type II) is caused by a deficiency of GlcNAc-1-phosphotransferase, the enzyme that initiates mannose-6-phosphate tagging of lysosomal enzymes. Without M6P tags, newly synthesized lysosomal hydrolases cannot be recognized by MPRs in the trans Golgi network. Instead of being sorted to lysosomes, they are default-secreted into the extracellular space. Lysosomes lack their hydrolytic enzymes and accumulate undigested macromolecules (glycosaminoglycans, lipids, glycolipids) in large dense inclusion bodies within cells, hence the name I-cell (inclusion cell). Clinical features include coarse facies, gingival hyperplasia, skeletal dysplasia (dysostosis multiplex), restricted joint mobility, hepatosplenomegaly, corneal clouding, and progressive neurological deterioration. Plasma levels of lysosomal enzymes are markedly elevated (secreted rather than retained). The high plasma lysosomal enzyme levels are diagnostically distinctive, distinguishing I-cell disease from Hurler syndrome (where lysosomal enzymes are deficient in serum because they are retained but nonfunctional).'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR | COPII vs COPI vs CLATHRIN VESICLES',x:'COPII: ER to Golgi (anterograde); coat recruited by Sar1-GTP; sorts ER-exit signals; cargo includes newly synthesized secretory and membrane proteins. COPI: Golgi to ER (retrograde); also intra-Golgi retrograde; coat recruited by ARF-GTP; retrieves KDEL proteins and KKXX membrane proteins that escaped to Golgi. CLATHRIN: TGN to late endosome/lysosome (with AP1 adaptor, M6P cargo); plasma membrane to early endosome (receptor-mediated endocytosis, with AP2 adaptor); coat is triskelion; requires dynamin for pinching. Memory: COPII goes Forward (ER to Golgi); COPI goes Reverse (Golgi to ER); Clathrin goes Down (TGN to lysosome, surface to endosome). All three require GTPases (Sar1, ARF, dynamin) for budding.'},{t:'p',x:'The nucleus is bounded by the nuclear envelope (two lipid bilayer membranes) pierced by nuclear pore complexes (NPCs), large protein assemblies (~120 MDa) composed of about 30 different nucleoporins. Small molecules (<40 kDa) passively diffuse through the NPC; larger proteins and RNAs require active, signal-mediated transport. Nuclear proteins carry nuclear localization signals (NLS): classical NLS sequences are rich in basic amino acids (Lys and Arg), either as a monopartite cluster (e.g., PKKKRKV, from SV40 large T antigen) or as a bipartite sequence (two basic clusters separated by ~10 aa). Import begins when importin-alpha (an adaptor that binds the classical NLS directly) forms a complex with the NLS-bearing protein. Importin-beta then binds importin-alpha and mediates translocation of the entire complex through the NPC by making successive contacts with FG-repeat nucleoporins that line the central channel. Inside the nucleus, RanGEF (Ran guanine nucleotide exchange factor, also called RCC1) catalyzes exchange of GDP for GTP on Ran, generating the high nuclear RanGTP concentration. RanGTP binds importin-beta, causing it to release its cargo (the importin-alpha/protein complex). The importin-alpha is then stripped of the NLS protein by CAS (exportin for importin-alpha) in a RanGTP-dependent manner. The RanGTP gradient (high in nucleus, low in cytoplasm) is the thermodynamic driver of unidirectional nuclear import. Key distinction: the NLS is NOT cleaved after import; it remains part of the mature nuclear protein, allowing re-import after cell division.'},{t:'p',x:'More than 99% of mitochondrial proteins are encoded by the nuclear genome, translated on cytoplasmic ribosomes, and post-translationally imported into mitochondria. Nuclear-encoded mitochondrial proteins carry a mitochondrial targeting sequence (MTS), also called a presequence, at their N-terminus. The MTS is typically 20 to 40 residues long and forms an amphipathic helix with positively charged residues on one face and hydrophobic residues on the other. The positive charges are attracted to the highly negative mitochondrial matrix, driven by the mitochondrial membrane potential (Psi-m, approximately -150 to -180 mV negative inside). Import into the matrix proceeds through the TOM complex (translocase of the outer mitochondrial membrane), which recognizes the MTS and imports the precursor protein across the outer membrane, and then through the TIM23 complex (translocase of the inner mitochondrial membrane), which uses the membrane potential and the mitochondrial Hsp70 (mtHsp70) ATPase to drive import into the matrix. After import, the MTS is cleaved by mitochondrial processing peptidase (MPP) in the matrix, and the mature protein folds with the assistance of mitochondrial chaperones (Hsp60/Hsp10). Key distinction from NLS: MTS IS CLEAVED after import.'},{t:'box',kind:'disc',label:'DISCRIMINATOR | NLS vs MTS',x:'NLS (nuclear localization signal): rich in basic amino acids (Lys, Arg); recognized by importin-alpha (adaptor) which recruits importin-beta; transport through nuclear pore complex; driven by RanGTP gradient; NLS NOT cleaved after import (it remains part of the mature nuclear protein, which allows re-import after cell division). MTS (mitochondrial targeting sequence): N-terminal amphipathic helix; positively charged residues on one face, hydrophobic on the other; recognized by TOM complex on outer mitochondrial membrane; translocated through TOM then TIM23 into matrix; driven by Psi-m (membrane potential, approximately -180 mV); MTS IS CLEAVED by MPP in the matrix after import. Key distinction: NLS is retained; MTS is cleaved. Both signals are necessary and sufficient to redirect heterologous proteins to the correct compartment when experimentally grafted.'},{t:'p',x:'Peroxisomes are single-membrane organelles that house oxidative reactions, particularly fatty acid alpha-oxidation and very-long-chain fatty acid beta-oxidation. Unlike mitochondria and the ER, peroxisomes import folded proteins (not unfolded), and they import the membrane-associated ATP-binding cassette transporters ABCD1 and ABCD2 via dedicated membrane insertion pathways. Matrix protein import uses two types of peroxisomal targeting signal. PTS1 (peroxisomal targeting signal 1) is a C-terminal tripeptide SKL (or closely related Ser-Lys/Arg-Leu/Met) that is recognized by the PEX5 receptor in the cytoplasm; the PEX5-cargo complex docks at the peroxisomal membrane and the cargo is translocated into the matrix (the PEX5 receptor cycles in and out of the membrane as a transient pore, the extended shuttle model). PTS2 is an N-terminal signal peptide recognized by PEX7. More than 95% of peroxisomal matrix proteins use PTS1. The import and membrane machinery is composed of PEX (peroxin) proteins; at least 16 PEX genes are known in humans.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'CLINICAL BRIDGE | ZELLWEGER SPECTRUM DISORDERS',x:'Zellweger syndrome (cerebrohepatorenal syndrome) is the most severe disorder of peroxisome biogenesis, caused by mutations in PEX1, PEX6, PEX10, PEX12, or PEX26 (among others), all of which are required for peroxisomal matrix protein import or membrane assembly. Without functional peroxisomes, very-long-chain fatty acids (VLCFAs, carbon chain length >=24) cannot be beta-oxidized and accumulate in plasma and tissues. Phytanic acid (from dietary phytol, requires alpha-oxidation in peroxisomes) also accumulates. Clinical features are severe and apparent at birth: profound hypotonia, neonatal seizures, craniofacial dysmorphisms (large fontanelle, flat occiput, epicanthal folds), neuronal migration defects (pachygyria, polymicrogyria), hepatomegaly, cholestasis, and stippled epiphyses on X-ray. Laboratory diagnosis shows elevated plasma VLCFAs and reduced erythrocyte plasmalogen levels (plasmalogen synthesis requires peroxisomes). Most children with classic Zellweger syndrome do not survive beyond the first year of life.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A newly synthesized lysosomal hydrolase is secreted into the plasma instead of being routed to the lysosome. Which enzyme deficiency best explains this?',choices:['A) Mannose-6-phosphate receptor deficiency','B) GlcNAc-1-phosphotransferase deficiency','C) Signal peptidase deficiency','D) Calnexin deficiency'],answer:1,why:'GlcNAc-1-phosphotransferase in the cis Golgi adds the first step of the M6P tag to lysosomal hydrolases. Without this enzyme (I-cell disease), hydrolases lack M6P and cannot be recognized by M6P receptors; they are default-secreted. The M6P receptor itself is intact in I-cell disease; the tag is simply missing.'}]},{id:'13.9',num:'13.9',title:'13.9 Toxins That Exploit Translation Machinery',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'Several clinically important bacterial toxins work by targeting the eukaryotic translation elongation cycle, providing vivid examples of how precisely translation machinery can be exploited.'},{t:'p',x:'Diphtheria toxin is produced by Corynebacterium diphtheriae strains lysogenized by the corynephage beta carrying the tox gene. The toxin is an A-B toxin: the B subunit (a receptor-binding and membrane-insertion domain) delivers the A subunit into the cytoplasm via receptor-mediated endocytosis and acid-induced membrane insertion. The A subunit is an ADP-ribosyltransferase that catalyzes the transfer of an ADP-ribose group from NAD+ to a modified histidine residue (diphthamide) on elongation factor 2 (EF-2, also called eEF2 in eukaryotes, the functional homolog of bacterial EF-G). ADP-ribosylation of EF-2 irreversibly inactivates it, blocking the translocation step of eukaryotic elongation. Because a single molecule of the A subunit can ADP-ribosylate all the EF-2 molecules in a cell, the toxin is extremely potent: a single molecule is theoretically sufficient to kill a cell. Pseudomonas exotoxin A has a mechanistically identical target (EF-2 diphthamide) and is the basis of immunotoxin cancer therapeutics. Note that EF-Tu and EF-Ts, the bacterial elongation factors, are not ADP-ribosylated by diphtheria toxin because the toxin targets the eukaryotic EF-G equivalent (EF-2) exclusively.'},{t:'p',x:'Ricin is a plant toxin from Ricinus communis (castor bean) composed of two chains linked by a disulfide bond. The B chain is a lectin that binds galactose residues on cell surface glycoproteins and glycolipids, mediating endocytosis. The A chain is a ribosome-inactivating protein (RIP): specifically, an N-glycosidase (also called a rRNA N-glycosidase) that depurinates a single conserved adenosine (A4324 in rat 28S rRNA) in the alpha-sarcin/ricin loop (SRL) of the 28S rRNA in the 60S large subunit. This single depurination inactivates the ribosome because the SRL is the binding site for EF-1 (EF-Tu equivalent) and EF-2 during elongation; without an intact SRL, neither GTPase can bind and protein synthesis halts completely. Like diphtheria toxin A chain, ricin A chain is a catalytic enzyme, so a single molecule can inactivate thousands of ribosomes. There is no antidote; the only treatment is supportive.'},{t:'box',kind:'hl',label:'HIGH-YIELD: TOXINS TARGETING TRANSLATION',x:'Diphtheria toxin: A-B toxin; A subunit is ADP-ribosyltransferase; target is diphthamide on EF-2 (eEF2, eukaryotic EF-G equivalent); blocks translocation; irreversible; one molecule kills cell; antitoxin must be given early. Pseudomonas exotoxin A: same target (EF-2 diphthamide); used in immunotoxins. Ricin: B chain binds galactose (cell entry); A chain depurinates A4324 of 28S rRNA in alpha-sarcin/ricin loop; blocks EF-1 and EF-2 binding; no antidote. Shiga toxin / Shiga-like toxin (STEC): same mechanism as ricin (depurinates 28S rRNA SRL); produced by Shigella dysenteriae and enterohemorrhagic E. coli (O157:H7); HUS (hemolytic uremic syndrome) results from toxin reaching renal endothelium. Botulinum toxin: NOT a translation inhibitor; cleaves SNAREs (VAMP/synaptobrevin, SNAP-25, syntaxin) at neuromuscular junctions, blocking ACh vesicle fusion.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'Diphtheria toxin ADP-ribosylates which specific target to block eukaryotic translation?',choices:['A) EF-Tu (EF-1A), blocking aa-tRNA delivery to A site','B) 28S rRNA, depurinating the alpha-sarcin/ricin loop','C) EF-2 (eEF2) at diphthamide residue, blocking translocation','D) eIF4E, blocking cap-dependent initiation'],answer:2,why:'Diphtheria toxin A subunit ADP-ribosylates the unusual amino acid diphthamide on EF-2 (eEF2, the eukaryotic homolog of bacterial EF-G). This modification irreversibly inactivates EF-2, blocking the translocation step. Ricin (not diphtheria toxin) depurinates 28S rRNA.'}]},{id:'13.10',num:'13.10',title:'13.10 Step 1 Clinical Correlations',blocks:[{t:'p',x:'The following clinical vignettes integrate the translation, post-translational modification, and protein targeting mechanisms from this chapter with Step 1 presentation-level knowledge.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'VIGNETTE 1: I-CELL DISEASE (MUCOLIPIDOSIS II)',x:'A 6-month-old presents with coarse facial features, gingival hyperplasia, restricted joint mobility, hepatosplenomegaly, and developmental delay. Radiographs show dysostosis multiplex. Plasma lysosomal enzyme activity is markedly elevated. Leukocyte lysosomal enzyme activity is markedly reduced, and cells on electron microscopy show large dense inclusion granules. The molecular defect is loss-of-function mutation in GNPTAB, encoding GlcNAc-1-phosphotransferase. Without M6P tagging, all lysosomal hydrolases are secreted into plasma instead of being retained in lysosomes. Distinguishing features: elevated plasma lysosomal enzymes (opposite of most lysosomal storage diseases, where plasma enzymes are normal or only mildly elevated); inclusion bodies in fibroblasts; onset in infancy.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'VIGNETTE 2: ZELLWEGER SYNDROME',x:'A neonate has severe hypotonia, seizures from day 2 of life, a large anterior fontanelle, subtle dysmorphic features (flat occiput, shallow orbital ridges), profound jaundice, and hepatomegaly. Brain MRI shows gyral abnormalities (pachygyria, simplified gyral pattern). Plasma VLCFA panel shows markedly elevated C24:0, C25:0, and C26:0 fatty acids with elevated C26:0/C22:0 ratio. Erythrocyte plasmalogen levels are reduced. Genetic testing identifies biallelic mutations in PEX1. The defect is peroxisome biogenesis failure: PEX1 is an AAA+ ATPase required for recycling PEX5 receptor, so peroxisomal matrix protein import fails globally. Elevated VLCFAs result from the inability to import and use the beta-oxidation enzymes normally resident in the peroxisomal matrix.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'VIGNETTE 3: CYSTIC FIBROSIS AS A PROTEIN TRAFFICKING DEFECT',x:'A 2-year-old with recurrent Pseudomonas aeruginosa pulmonary infections, failure to thrive, and a sweat chloride of 85 mEq/L is found to be homozygous for the deltaF508 CFTR mutation. The pathophysiology at the molecular level is protein misfolding and ERAD: the deltaF508 mutation causes CFTR to misfold in the ER, be retained by BiP and calnexin, retrotranslocated by ERAD machinery, polyubiquitinated, and degraded by the proteasome before it can reach the apical membrane. The defect is therefore a failure of protein trafficking, not an absent gene. This explains why CFTR modulators (elexacaftor/tezacaftor/ivacaftor) that rescue deltaF508 CFTR folding and gating are effective: the gene is present, transcribed, and translated, but the protein needs pharmacological assistance to escape ERAD and function at the membrane.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'VIGNETTE 4: DIPHTHERIA',x:'A child with inadequate vaccination develops a gray, adherent pseudomembrane on the posterior oropharynx, cervical lymphadenopathy (bull-neck appearance), and a low-grade fever. Several days later, cardiac monitoring reveals new-onset heart block with prolonged PR interval. The organism is Corynebacterium diphtheriae, and its toxicity stems from the ADP-ribosylation of EF-2 in cardiac myocytes, halting protein synthesis and causing cell death. Myocarditis is the leading cause of death in diphtheria. Antitoxin must be administered empirically based on clinical diagnosis; culture confirmation is too slow. The toxin is only produced by strains carrying the tox gene on the corynephage beta; it exerts no toxicity on the bacterium itself because the modification target is diphthamide, a eukaryote-specific modified histidine residue absent in EF-G of bacteria.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'VIGNETTE 5: GRAY BABY SYNDROME',x:'A 10-day-old premature infant being treated with chloramphenicol for gram-negative meningitis develops progressive abdominal distension, pallor, an ashen gray skin color, vomiting, and cardiovascular collapse over 48 hours. The cause is chloramphenicol accumulation due to immature hepatic glucuronidation (UDP-glucuronosyltransferase activity is minimal in premature and full-term neonates). Elevated free chloramphenicol inhibits mitochondrial translation (targeting the 55S mitoribosomes), reducing oxidative phosphorylation in cardiac and other mitochondria-rich tissues. Treatment is discontinuation of chloramphenicol and supportive care.'},{t:'box',kind:'bridge',label:'VIGNETTE 6: SCURVY',x:'A 45-year-old with alcoholism and limited dietary variety presents with perifollicular hemorrhages around curled (corkscrew) hairs, easy bruising, bleeding gums, and poor wound healing. Gum examination shows swollen, spongy, bleeding gingiva. The cause is vitamin C deficiency impairing prolyl and lysyl hydroxylase activity in collagen synthesis. Without hydroxylation, procollagen chains do not form stable triple helices (hydroxyproline hydrogen bonds are required for triple-helix stability at body temperature). Unstable procollagen cannot be properly secreted; blood vessels, skin, and connective tissues lose structural integrity. Treatment is dietary vitamin C supplementation with rapid clinical improvement.'}],quickcheck:[{stem:'A child with repeated lysosomal storage disease features has markedly elevated plasma levels of multiple lysosomal enzymes. Which diagnosis is most consistent with this laboratory finding?',choices:['A) Hurler syndrome (MPS I)','B) Gaucher disease','C) I-cell disease (Mucolipidosis II)','D) Niemann-Pick disease type A'],answer:2,why:'I-cell disease (GlcNAc-1-phosphotransferase deficiency) is the only lysosomal storage disease where plasma lysosomal enzyme levels are markedly elevated, because the hydrolases lack M6P tags and are default-secreted. In other lysosomal storage diseases, the enzyme deficiency causes reduced activity in plasma or near-normal levels.'}]}],
 bottomLine:'Translation converts the four-letter nucleotide code into the twenty-letter amino acid alphabet using a degenerate, near-universal genetic code (64 codons, 61 sense, 3 stop), read by aminoacyl-tRNAs whose fidelity is enforced by 20 AARS enzymes with proofreading (cost: 2 ATP equivalents per amino acid). The ribosome (70S in prokaryotes, 80S in eukaryotes) catalyzes peptide bond formation via its 23S/28S rRNA ribozyme PTC, and cycles through GTPase-driven delivery (EF-Tu/eEF1A), peptide transfer, and translocation (EF-G/eEF2) at each codon. Prokaryotic and eukaryotic ribosomes differ sufficiently to allow selective antibiotic targeting; key toxicities include chloramphenicol-induced aplastic anemia and gray baby syndrome, and aminoglycoside nephrotoxicity/ototoxicity. Post-translational modifications (phosphorylation, N- and O-linked glycosylation, K48/K63 ubiquitination, acetylation, vitamin-K-dependent gamma-carboxylation, vitamin-C-dependent hydroxylation, lipid anchoring, and proteolytic cleavage) collectively rewrite the protein\'s identity, stability, and localization after synthesis. Protein targeting uses sequence-encoded address labels: signal peptides for co-translational ER insertion (SRP/Sec61 pathway), NLS for nuclear import (importin/RanGTP), MTS for mitochondrial matrix import (TOM/TIM23, Psi-m-driven), and PTS1/PTS2 for peroxisomes (PEX5/PEX7). Golgi sorting routes lysosomal enzymes via mannose-6-phosphate tagging (GlcNAc-phosphotransferase/MPR); its deficiency causes I-cell disease. ER quality control relies on BiP, calnexin, and ERAD; chronic ER stress triggers the UPR and, terminally, CHOP-mediated apoptosis. The trafficking defect in deltaF508 CFTR, the peroxisome failure in Zellweger syndrome, and the M6P sorting failure in I-cell disease are paradigmatic molecular medicine examples of protein targeting gone wrong.',
 nextHint:'Chapter 13 is the final chapter of Book 6: Biochemistry. The complete central dogma is now in place. The thirteen chapters of Book 6 cover the full biochemistry tested on the MCAT and USMLE Step 1. Return to Chapter 1 for a second pass with the full mechanistic context that every later chapter has built.',
}
];;
